1. e4
{ Welcome to this course − the second and final part of my Lifetime Repertoire devoted to how to play  1.e4  with White. Let me introduce myself, offer a bit of background on my experience as an author, and explain my motivation behind creating this course.  I am a 24-year-old International Master who has spent the last 6-7 years teaching club players full-time, alongside getting my Bachelor's and Master's degrees. I also played for the United States' number one chess college team, Webster University, where I met and worked with multiple top-100 players. So, I have a lot of experience when it comes to opening preparation at all levels.  However, in my experience, what players of all levels NEED is more understanding of the arising positions, not exact specific knowledge of particular lines. According to my observations, everyone who moved on from memorizing to understanding more, from GMs to club players, made a lot of progress. So, all my courses  (and this is my 8th @@StartBracket@@!@@EndBracket@@ Chessable course)  are aimed at EXPLAINING things, not focusing on showing a lot of lines that need to be memorized. It looks like this approach worked so far since my courses have been praised exactly for this − for having plenty of explanations. I also really like focusing on model games, and in my last courses, a full White 1.Nf3 repertoire and the French Defense for Black, I've offered an innovative approach with a chapter on typical pawn structures that arise in the course.  However, this course is a bit special, because it's the first Lifetime Repertoire I've created. Or, rather, the second part of a Lifetime Repertoire. The fact that it's an LTR didn't make me change my philosophy, so to speak − I still focus on understanding. In fact, I went further down this rabbit hole by replacing the praised chapter on typical pawn structures and ideas at the beginning of the course with such a chapter after every @@StartBracket@@!@@EndBracket@@ theoretical part on each opening. Each theoretical part is also supplemented by a chapter on model games in the corresponding opening.  What is different is that this time I am not messing around. What I mean by that is that I really love experimenting with the less-known lines, such as the Evans Gambit, or the Accelerated Queen's Indian. I truly believe those are interesting, promising, and sound lines. But, they are obviously on the riskier end of things. So, in this regard, the approach for this course was completely different: risk-averse, as sound as possible! My main criteria for choosing the lines were:  ♟ Rarity: If there are a few equally strong moves, I always like choosing the less-known one. Remember, the position is equal until one of the players goes wrong, which means giving your opponent a position one likely hasn't seen leads to better winning chances! That's why you will often see novelties or very rare suggestions on moves 7-8.  ♟ Restrictiveness: I made this repertoire as positional and as restrictive as possible. In most lines, my goal was to get pleasant positions with long-term pressure based on superior pawn structure, better minor pieces, space, and things like that. So, the goal was to never enter sharp lines which require memorization, unless it's needed. That's how I wrote most of my courses, and that's the position I like best.  ♟ Endgame: if possible, I want to trade queens! That's what we do in several key lines of the Sicilian with  2...e6  and with  2...g6  , as well as in the Caro-Kann and the Rubinstein French. Learn to play the endgame, ladies and gentlemen! However, this part is a bit different from the first one. In the first part, I was able to get endgame positions and simplified positions a lot more often. But this part deal with the more combative openings, such as the Sicilian. It's not easy to always trade the queens in the Sicilian. So, I decided to take a slightly different route.  If it was possible to trade the queens beneficially, I would gladly do that. But in many cases, it wasn't. So, in a number of variations in this part, you will see complex middlegame positions. But, those positions still fit our criteria: we are fighting for space and other long-term advantages, trying to restrict the opponent as much as possible.  There are no positions here that are tactically messy, chaotic, or absurd. I do not ever, unless absolutely necessary, sacrifice long-term chances for an attack, for example. On a serious note, I feel this approach could prove really beneficial for a few reasons:  Your opponents won't have much experience in these restrictive positional variations. Your ability to play strategic middlegame positions with clear plans will improve. Soundness: no sacrifices, gambits, and dubious experiments unless necessary. Lack of forced play. We rely on ideas, not on exact lines! Theoretical challenges for Black. Don't get me wrong − it's not a 'timid' or 'toothless' repertoire. It's one based on the most principled lines of the best engines and best human minds! It's just positional, but it's aimed at giving you an edge − every time they go wrong!  
So, I challenged all the major existing books and courses − more on that in the Repertoire Clashes. So, most of the lines you will see in the course are aimed at not allowing counterplay. I don't want a mess, and I don't want to be lost with White by move 15 if I forget something. I want a reliable repertoire based on ideas and plans that you can use  (truly!)  for a lifetime, and that's what I am presenting to you here. Now, the last thing. What are the lines I chose and why?  ➢ The French with @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/3PP3/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq d6 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Nc3  . This might be a somewhat surprising choice to many of you, given that I am known for looking for practical variations, and  3.Nc3  is rightfully known as the most principled way for White to play. Well, here is my reasoning. I wanted a theoretically challenging repertoire, and I wanted us to be making the choices, not the opponent! After  3.Nd2  , Black has too many choices, from the solid  3...c5  4.exd5  Qxd5  lines, or the IQP positions with  4...exd5  , to the classical pawn chain positions after  3...Nf6  .  After @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/3PP3/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq d6 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.e5  , Black also has a lot of choices, and it's not easy to offer new theoretical ideas there. After @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/3PP3/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq d6 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.exd5  , it's too easy to equalize in many ways. However, playing  3.Nc3  (the main move)  does not mean we must play the sharpest, most theoretical lines! in the Winawer @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/3PP3/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq d6 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Nc3  Bb4  , instead of the crazy  4.e5  , I choose the restrictive  4.Nge2  . A lot of people wouldn't know much already on move 4, and we won't ever allow the opponent to ruin our structure. Positional play? Yes! Surprise effect? Yes!  In the Classical French @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/3PP3/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq d6 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Nc3  Nf6  , I went for the very positional  4.Bg5  as well. There will be no complications, and the setups I recommend are very logical and easy to play.  In the Rubinstein French, I have recommended the non-trendy, yet very poisonous @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/ppp2ppp/4pn2/8/3P4/5N2/PPP2PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7.g3  , which offers White risk-free pressure. As you can see, all these lines were a perfect fit!  ➢ In the Caro-Kann I chose the Advance Variation: again, the seemingly  (and truthfully)  White's most ambitious choice. The thing is that many other trendy lines, such as the Two Knights @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c6  2.Nf3  d5  3.Nc3  , offer Black many choices. But in the Advance, Black only has two moves: @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp2pppp/2p5/3pP3/3P4/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Bf5  and  3...c5  , and White dictates the way the game goes in both cases.  After  3...Bf5  , I recommend the positionally ambitious  4.c4  . White fights for space in the center, and the game is totally idea-based. After @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp2pppp/2p5/3pP3/3P4/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3...c5  , I went with the restrictive  4.Nf3  , which gives Black only one or two decent responses and many ways to go wrong. Again, play is totally idea-based, and White can always choose between the more known and the more unexplored variations later on.  ➢ The Sicilian: This was a hard one! I always knew I didn't want to cover the main lines, as then the repertoire would take ages to not just write, but also learn. I wanted a practical weapon! So, after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq c6 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.Nf3  d6  , I went with the  3.d4  cxd4  4.Qxd4  variation − a pretty unexplored, yet very promising path. Most often, we want to get a Maroczy pawn structure, sidestepping the complex Najdorf or Dragon systems. This is a great idea because we can rely on the familiar pawn structures, while also avoiding the long theoretical sequences.  After @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq c6 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.Nf3  e6  , I suggest the rare but very interesting  3.c4  , which is also aimed at getting a Maroczy Bind type of position. I couldn't be more excited about this choice! Again, White is mostly playing risk-free.  After @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq c6 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.Nf3  g6  , I actually decided to surprise Black − instead of offering the direct Maroczy setup, I went with  3.d4  cxd4  4.Qxd4  . This line might seem messy at first, but it actually leads to simplifications, and in most cases, to endgames with a very pleasant advantage for White. I chose to not suggest the direct Maroczy lines because most Black players are very well-prepared to meet them. I want the structure, not the forcing 20-move-long lines!  Finally, after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq c6 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.Nf3  Nc6  , I, of course, recommend the Rossolimo. It's a bit cliché at this point to do so, but there was no choice since  3.d4  would get us move-ordered of our repertoire. However, the Rossolimo is a very rich and interesting opening, and I am very glad to present a ton of new ideas that really challenge the opponent.  This was a long intro about the opening choices! The best part − 30 model games and 35 examples of how to play different pawn structures, and what ideas we can use in most of these positions! The course became a bit too huge, which was unexpected for me − over 220  000  words! However, I think this is a great thing, it was clearly a labor of love. I couldn't be more thrilled to have you study this repertoire, and I am absolutely certain that it would truly serve you for a lifetime, without taking a lifetime to learn − mostly, due to the very reasonable amount of trainable variations, one of the most generous word count per line, and a ton of games and structures that will help you understand the arising positions very deeply. Enjoy! }
