1. e4
{ One of the most important questions about any course or repertoire is: how does it challenge the other, already existing courses? Does it offer any new ideas? So, this small chapter is exactly about this − how I challenged the existing books and Chessable courses in search of an opening advantage or fresh ways to pose problems. Below you'll find clickable variations for all the lines I mention here. Here are some, but not all, courses and books I've used:  1. Lifetime Repertoires: Giri's French Defense: Giri, of course, is a brilliant theoretician. He wrote a very good course on how to play the French for Black, and a rather extensive one. However, he did not cover my suggested improvement, namely 7.Bf4, after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/3PP3/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq d6 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Nc3  Bb4  4.Nge2  Nc6  5.a3  Bxc3  6.Nxc3  dxe4  7.Bf4!   2. Lifetime Repertoires: Plichtas's French Defense coincides with our repertoire. In the McCutcheon Variation, after @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/ppp2ppp/4pn2/3p2B1/1b1PP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R2QKBNR w KQkq - 4 5@@EndFEN@@  5.Ne2  dxe4  6.a3  Be7  7.Bxf6  Bxf6  8.Nxe4  Nc6  9.c3  O-O  , Kamil does not cover  10.N2g3  , which is our suggestion.  3. The French Defense: A Complete Black Repertoire by GM Nikita Vitiugov: Vitiugov is another super GM − and, of course, a strong theoretician. Instead of building a streamlined repertoire, in his book, he tried to cover nearly all the possible lines for Black, including the solid Rubinstein, the sharp Winawer, and the ambitious McCutcheon. After @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/3PP3/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq d6 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Nc3  Bb4  4.Nge2  Nc6  5.a3  Bxc3  6.Nxc3  dxe4  , the same line as Giri gives, he also fails to cover  7.Bf4!   4. Vitiugov's line in the Rubinstein: he recommends the solid, but passive endgame. I just disagree that Black easily builds a fortress − see the clickable.  5. Vitiugov's line in the Classical French: after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/3PP3/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq d6 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Nc3  Nf6  4.Bg5  , he mentions that  4...dxe4  is a transposition to the 'good Rubinstein', but that's not correct, as we haven't yet committed to Nf3, so he fails to cover our move order.  6. My course on the French Defense. I analyze the @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/3PP3/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq d6 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Nc3  Be7  4.Bd3  c5  lines, suggesting Black goes for an IQP position, which is between a slight advantage for White and equality. However, these positions have hardly been researched, with only a few dozen games in the database. So, I figured it wasn't worth going into a tremendous amount of detail. But, in the White course, I have gone into more detail, exploring the plans and ideas White can try, and the potential pitfalls Black has to be careful about.  7. The Solid Rubinstein by Hannes Langrock: He recommends the endgame variation, where Black is passively hoping to hold a draw. Again, it might be a fortress, but White is pushing risk-free, so I don't consider this a challenging choice.  8. Bryan Tillis’s variations in the French Defense coincide with some of our lines.  ♟ In the Rubinstein, after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/3PP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq - 1 3@@EndFEN@@  3...dxe4  4.Nxe4  Nd7  5.Nf3  Ngf6  6.Nxf6  Nxf6  , he does not cover  7.g3  .  ♟ Classical − after  3...Nf6  4.Bg5  Be7  5.e5  Nfd7  6.Bxe7  Qxe7  , Tillis does not cover  7.Qd2  .  ♟ Winawer − after  3...Bb4  4.Ne2  Nc6  5.a3  Ba5  6.b4  Bb6  7.Bb2  Nge7  , Tillis does not cover  8.Qd3  .  9. Lifetime Repertoires: Caro-Kann by GM Erwin L'Ami: the @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp2pppp/2p5/3p4/3PP3/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq d6 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.e5  Bf5  lines − Erwin really did an incredible job. His course is not a course, but a Caro-Kann Bible! He recommends two lines: @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp2pppp/2p5/3p4/3PP3/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq d6 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.e5  Bf5  , and @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp2pppp/2p5/3p4/3PP3/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq d6 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.e5  c5  . After @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp2pppp/2p5/3p4/3PP3/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq d6 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.e5  Bf5  4.c4  e6  5.Nc3  , he recommends the rare  5...Bb4  , but doesn't go into enough detail about the recently discovered ambitious kingside plan. I think White is definitely pressing in those positions.  10. L'Ami's suggestion in the  3.e5  c5  Caro-Kann lines: After @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp2pppp/2p5/3p4/3PP3/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq d6 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.e5  c5  , I recommend the most challenging variation with  4.Nf3  . Following  4...cxd4  5.Nxd4  Nc6  , there is a pretty straightforward variation, where White forces an endgame with the bishop pair. Objectively, those positions are equal, and I agree with L'Ami's evaluation. However, I analyzed them in quite a bit more detail, and believe we can pose practical problems!  11. Keep It Simple for Black by IM Christof Sielecki: Just like L'Ami, he suggests the best line after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp2pppp/2p5/3p4/3PP3/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq d6 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.e5  c5  4.Nf3  . Again, we get the same endgame − the position is theoretically equal, but practically, I think we are posing problems.  12. Beating the Anti-Sicilians by GM Vasilios Kotronias: After @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq c6 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.Nf3  Nc6  3.Bb5  , he recommends  3...d6  − one of the most sound sidelines. However, after  4.Bxc6  bxc6  5.e5  , he fails to consider my move order and fails to equalize.  13. Lifetime Repertoires: Accelerated Dragon by FM Kamil Plichta: Plichta is one of Chessable's most favorite authors, and his reputation is deserved. He writes passionately and detailed courses! In his course, after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq c6 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.Nf3  Nc6  3.Bb5  , he helps bring to attention and glory the variation that was considered silly just a few years ago:  3...e5  .  However, in the last few years, this variation's reputation has changed considerably, and now it's believed to be a perfectly decent way of playing. In the main line, I go in a bit more depth, claiming that White's position is a bit better due to the better pawn structure, while Kamil stops a bit earlier and claims equality.  Objectively, it's a bit of both: easier to play with White, but objectively holdable for Black. Still, this is a good outcome! Of course, these are not the only sources I have used, but hopefully, this gives you a good idea about how deep and challenging this repertoire is, and how it tries to improve on the existing theory! }
1... e6
{ ➢  1...c5  2.Nf3  Nc6  3.Bb5  e5  is Kamil Plichta's line.   3...d6  4.Bxc6+  bxc6  5.e5  dxe5  6.Nxe5  Qd5  7.Nf3  Qe4+  8.Kf1  .  In this position, we want to develop the dark-squared bishop to b2, to the long diagonal. Most players went ...Nf6, allowing that to happen. But Kotronias claims to solve this issue with  8...g6  .  However, he overlooks the simple idea  9.Nc3  Qf5  10.b3!  We still manage to play Bb2, reaching the typical favorable positions that he thought he could avoid. White is better.   10.d3  Bg7!  is his point. Now, b2-b3 is no longer possible!  4.O-O  Bd6  5.c3  a6  6.Ba4  b5  7.Bc2  Nge7  8.a4  b4  9.d4  cxd4  10.cxd4  Nxd4  11.Nxd4  exd4  12.Nd2  Qc7  13.Nf3  O-O  14.Bg5Ν  Ng6  15.Rc1  Bb7  .  Kamil stops here, claiming full equality. However, I do not fully agree.  16.Bb1  Bc6  17.Qxd4⩲  .  I would still definitely pick White, as we have no weaknesses, but the opponent does. Next, I'd probably want to play g2-g3, blocking the diagonal the black queen and bishop are on, and follow up with Rfd1.  Then, we can consider moving the queen away to d2 to keep an eye on the b4-pawn and follow with Nd4, activating the knight, looking to threaten the pinned bishop, or coming to f5.  See the main chapter for more details!   ➢  1...c6  2.d4  d5  3.e5  c5   3...Bf5  4.c4  e6  5.Nc3  Bb4  6.cxd5  cxd5  7.h4  h6  8.g4  Bh7  9.h5  is is another line that L'Ami gives for Black. Objectively, I again agree that the 5...Bb4 variation is a very good one, but I think this position needs to be analyzed in more detail. It's understandable that Erwin chose to be brief since it's only been seen in 2 games, but this variation is definitely starting to become more popular, so more analysis is needed − and I offer that in the main chapter!  4.Nf3  cxd4  5.Nxd4  Nc6  6.c4  e6  7.Nc3  Bb4  8.Nxc6  bxc6  9.Qa4  a5  10.cxd5  Qxd5  11.Qxb4  axb4  12.Nxd5  exd5  13.Be3  is the endgame in question, which both L'Ami and Sielecki reach with Black in  their @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp2pppp/2p5/3p4/3PP3/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq d6 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.e5  c5  Caro-Kann variations. Objectively, it is equal. But, there are a few problems:  In many thousands of games, Black only got here 47 times, and most games are either top-GM level or correspondence. So, there is a very low chance your opponents would know this variation. Objectively it's equal, but I think White can keep posing practical problems − see the relevant chapter for more information! }
2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Bb4
{ ➢  3...dxe4  4.Nxe4  Nd7  5.Nf3  Ngf6  6.Nxf6+  Nxf6  7.g3  b6  8.Bb5+  Bd7  9.a4  a6  10.Be2  Bc6  11.O-O  Bd6  12.Ne5  Bxe5  13.dxe5  Qd5  14.Qxd5  Nxd5  15.a5  b5  16.Bd2  .  Both Vitiugov and Langrock suggest going for this position, where we have the bishop pair and all the ability and time in the world to try to make progress. For example, by trading the rooks and then advancing on the kingside with f2-f4, g3-g4, f4-f5, etc. Sure, it might be objectively a draw, but White keeps pressing indefinitely and scored 67% in this position, so I do not believe this is a good solution to Black's problems.   ➢  3...Nf6  4.Bg5  dxe4  5.Nxe4  Nbd7  .  Vitiugov claims  6.Nf3  transposes into a good Rubinstein line for Black, but I won't touch that knight yet!  6.Bd3!  See the chapter for more details, but I do not believe Black has easy life here. }
4. Ne2 dxe4 5. a3 Bxc3+ 6. Nxc3 Nc6
{ This is the position that both Giri and Vitiugov reach − Black's best line after @@StartFEN@@rnbqk1nr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/1b1PP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 2 4@@EndFEN@@  4.Nge2  . However, they only analyze the most popular moves like @@StartFEN@@r1bqk1nr/ppp2ppp/2n1p3/8/3Pp3/P1N5/1PP2PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 1 7@@EndFEN@@  7.Bb5  and  7.d5  , failing to consider a new and powerful idea. }
7. Bf4 { See the dedicated chapter for the full overview. } *

