1. e4
{ Hi and welcome to this Quickstarter Guide! Here, we will be discussing the Sicilian, the French, and the Caro-Kann. Instead of looking at the very main lines, I preferred focusing on the most popular ones at the club level or the most instructive ones. As a result, after studying this chapter, you will be able to get a very good grasp of all the ideas and start playing this repertoire in no time! }
1... e6
{ This move, followed by ...d7-d5, defines something called the French Defense. This opening is about fighting for the center rather ambitiously while avoiding direct piece play. As you will see, the first two moves only feature pawn play. The downside for Black is the locked-up light-squared bishop, and very often, this piece tends to be a large issue for quite a long time. }
2. d4 d5
{ Here, we arrive at massive crossroads. White can lock up the center with e4-e5, take Black's pawn and open up the position, or defend the pawn with some knight move − either to c3 or to d2. }
3. Nc3
{ After a long thought, I decided to suggest this move, which is the most critical and ambitious one. Why did I do that and what's the point of this move? As we can see, we are simply protecting the e4-pawn while keeping the center flexible for now. It's important to do so for the following practical reason: most Black players who play the French @@StartBracket@@and I am one of them; I just wrote a course on the French that I'm in love with!@@EndBracket@@ love positions with pawn chains. Our goal is to try to avoid creating one!  However, don't worry: while the move  3.Nc3  is known for being a very principled and theoretically heavy one, we won't need loads of theory − instead, I am opting for practical, easy-to-learn sidelines, which still carry quite a bit of punch, as always!  In this position, we'll need to consider quite a lot of moves. Black can try to pin the knight with  3...Bb4  , which is known as the Winawer Variation − the most forcing and sharp one. Black can also try to force us to lock up the center with the move  3...Nf6  , which is another major theoretical move. The passive yet solid decision is to play  3...dxe4  − the Rubinstein Variation. Black is hoping to avoid the pawn chain situation and trade down, liquidating White's hopes to get a spatial advantage or long-term pressure.  And, of course, there are quite a few sidelines, such as  3...Nc6  ,  3...Be7  − the move I suggested in my Black French course,  3...h6  ,  3...a6  , and so on. We tackle them all in the main course! }
3... dxe4
{ This move defines what we know as the Rubinstein Variation of the French. Black immediately opens up the center, avoiding the standard positions with pawn chains. The upside for our opponent is that this variation avoids risking a standard outcome where Black ends up squeezed, lacking space and counterplay, and then slowly but surely losing on the kingside.   However, the bad news for Black is that we get a position with a noticeable steady advantage because our pawn on d4 is controlling more space/center than the one on e6 and because the c8-bishop is still a bad piece. Nevertheless, the Rubinstein Variation is a very solid way to play, and many strong GMs, such as the German player Georg Meier demonstrated this by using it to draw numerous top-10 level players. }
4. Nxe4
{ Here, Black is also at a bit of a crossroads. The main move is  4...Nd7  ,  the point being to play ...Ngf6 next, offering a knight trade, being able to recapture back with the knight to avoid doubling the pawns or having to get the queen out early.  However, due to the effort of the ever-creative Georgian GM Baadur Jobava, the odd-looking move  4...Bd7  came to life and started enjoying quite a lot of popularity. Black is trying to solve the standard problem of the bad bishop by  deploying it to c6 very fast, and likely trading it off on e4. But, in this Quickstarter, we will only focus on the main line  4...Nd7  . }
4... Nd7
{ This is the classic way of playing the Rubinstein, preparing ...Ngf6, looking to trade down and simplify the position, reducing the spatial disadvantage. }
5. Nf3 { For now, we just keep developing. } 5... Ngf6 6. Nxf6+ Nxf6
{ This is the critical position where White has to make a choice. There are a plethora of moves, but essentially, here is what's happening. Black has two issues to resolve:  Black needs to activate the light-squared bishop, which is normally accomplished with ...b7-b6. Black needs to challenge our spatial advantage, created by the d4-pawn. That is typically done by means of ...c7-c5. Sometimes ...e6-e5 could be considered, but realistically, that pawn break is hardly ever possible.  
So, White can choose a very aggressive strategy, such as playing Be3, Qd2, and castling queenside, trying to get a position with opposite-side castles and attack the black king. White can also develop with Bd3, Qe2, and so on, castling kingside and centralizing the pieces.  However, I want to go for a completely different approach. It hasn't ever been considered the most critical one, but I believe that in most lines we get an incredibly easy-to-play position with a noticeable advantage. In the best lines available to the knowledgeable opponents, Black might approach equality, but I do not believe the positions will ever fully get there. }
7. g3
{ We want to deploy the bishop to the long diagonal, which serves several crucial purposes. As we know, one of Black's big ideas is ...b7-b6 and ...Bb7. If our opponent doesn't do that fast enough, the bishop won't ever get out that way due to pressure on the long diagonal.  Secondly, the other plan is to push ...c7-c5. But doing so also empowers the g2-bishop and prevents Black from ever blocking the diagonal with ...c7-c6! This move also scores better than the main lines with a whopping 64.7% win rate for White.   And, it's rare enough for your opponents to not know how to handle it well − just 270 games in the master database compared to 5000 in the main line with  7.Bd3! }
7... Be7
{ This is also a really bad idea. Again, it's ABSOLUTELY URGENT for Black to get the queenside out and solve the upcoming threat of White dominating the long diagonal, so simple development won't cut it. }
8. Bg2
{ We, however, can just continue developing. This g2-bishop is looking forward to enjoying itself on the long diagonal! }
8... O-O 9. O-O c5
{ Most Black players who got to this position, which included several 2500-level players, tried undermining White's center, looking to get rid of the d4-pawn. Just like in the line with @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/ppp2ppp/4pn2/8/3P4/5NP1/PPP2P1P/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7...c5  , it only helps White! }
10. dxc5 Bxc5 11. Qe2
{ A lot of other moves are also good, but I like this one because it helps White connect the rooks and take the e5-square under better control, which helps to not only discourage ...e6-e5 but also prepare Ne5!, activating the knight and opening the light-squared bishop. Black's queenside has a very hard time getting out. }
11... Qb6
{ Let's say Black tries to get the queen out and protect the b7-pawn in advance. @@StartBracket@@Also, of course, developing it to c7 wasn't tempting at all as Bf4 would inevitably win another tempo soon enough@@EndBracket@@.   11...Bd7?  12.Ne5±  doesn't help Black at all:  the b7-pawn is hanging, and at best, Black will just lose the bishop pair. }
12. Ne5
{ We open up the g2-bishop and prepare ideas like a4-a5, or maybe a2-a4 and Qb5!?, offering a transposition to a winning endgame. }
12... Rd8 13. a4
{ We are about to play a4-a5 and grab more space, possibly followed up with a5-a6. Alternatively, this Qb5!? idea, swapping the queens and paralyzing the queenside, could also be really attractive. }
13... a5
{ Let's say Black prevents our a-pawn from advancing further. Of course, it also weakens the b5-square, making it an outpost for our pieces, while also making the a5-pawn a long-term target. }
14. b3
{ The bishop will be perfectly placed on b2. Black's queenside is still stuck − at best, Black will go ...Bd7 and surrender the bishop pair, and we don't even need to hurry to take on d7, as the bishop isn't going anywhere. The plan is very simple: we'll just play Bb2 and Rd1 @@StartBracket@@any rook should do@@EndBracket@@.  It's worth remembering the following simple principle: trade the opponent's ACTIVE pieces and leave Black with the passive ones. The a8-rook and c8-bishop are passive, so we will gladly offer to trade the other pair of rooks, the queens, and the dark-squared bishops! White is just dominating.   14.Qb5  , offering a queen trade, is not a bad idea either. However, I think it is better to first get the rest of the pieces out. The black queen is not threatening us in any way, and we can always trade it off later. }
*

