[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Classical French 4.Bg5 Be7 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ Hi and welcome to this Quickstarter Guide! Here, we will be discussing the Sicilian, the French, and the Caro-Kann. Instead of looking at the very main lines, I preferred focusing on the most popular ones at the club level or the most instructive ones. As a result, after studying this chapter, you will be able to get a very good grasp of all the ideas and start playing this repertoire in no time! }
1... e6
{ This move, followed by ...d7-d5, defines something called the French Defense. This opening is about fighting for the center rather ambitiously while avoiding direct piece play. As you will see, the first two moves only feature pawn play. The downside for Black is the locked-up light-squared bishop, and very often, this piece tends to be a large issue for quite a long time. }
2. d4 d5
{ Here, we arrive at massive crossroads. White can lock up the center with e4-e5, take Black's pawn and open up the position, or defend the pawn with some knight move − either to c3 or to d2. }
3. Nc3
{ After a long thought, I decided to suggest this move, which is the most critical and ambitious one. Why did I do that and what's the point of this move? As we can see, we are simply protecting the e4-pawn while keeping the center flexible for now. It's important to do so for the following practical reason: most Black players who play the French @@StartBracket@@and I am one of them; I just wrote a course on the French that I'm in love with!@@EndBracket@@ love positions with pawn chains. Our goal is to try to avoid creating one!  However, don't worry: while the move  3.Nc3  is known for being a very principled and theoretically heavy one, we won't need loads of theory − instead, I am opting for practical, easy-to-learn sidelines, which still carry quite a bit of punch, as always!  In this position, we'll need to consider quite a lot of moves. Black can try to pin the knight with  3...Bb4  , which is known as the Winawer Variation − the most forcing and sharp one. Black can also try to force us to lock up the center with the move  3...Nf6  , which is another major theoretical move. The passive yet solid decision is to play  3...dxe4  − the Rubinstein Variation. Black is hoping to avoid the pawn chain situation and trade down, liquidating White's hopes to get a spatial advantage or long-term pressure.  And, of course, there are quite a few sidelines, such as  3...Nc6  ,  3...Be7  − the move I suggested in my Black French course,  3...h6  ,  3...a6  , and so on. We tackle them all in the main course! }
3... Nf6
{ The Classical Variation − one of the two best theoretical ways for Black to continue. Black is putting pressure on the e4-pawn, seeking to provoke the move e4-e5, which would lock up the center and create a position with pawn chains. This is exactly what most French Defense players live for! }
4. Bg5
{ This, along with e4-e5, is one of White's two most popular moves. I prefer it because it seems to be giving us more choices than the opponent. Instead, after  4.e5  , Black can choose among a dozen decent lines, which means it's not only difficult to analyze all of them and try to get an advantage of any kind, but also, you will be at a losing practical position, since the opponent is the one dictating how the game will go.  Here, we need to investigate 4 moves. The most popular continuation is @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp2ppp/4pn2/3p2B1/3PP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R2QKBNR b KQkq - 3 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Be7  , which is a quiet way to play and the one we study in the Quickstarter. A rather passive continuation, which is also quite frequent, is  4...dxe4  − we can call it a slightly improved version of the Rubinstein Variation, and that is because  we had already committed to playing Bg5, which somewhat narrowed down our options.   Then, there is, of course, a pretty sharp move  4...Bb4  . It can, if both parties are willing, very rapidly result in really murky positions. However, it doesn't have to, as we will see − we will politely decline the invitation for a carnage. Finally, the move  4...h6  , which people hadn't thought was possible in the past, is starting to gain some traction, and is not nearly as bad as one might think, so we will also investigate that one in the main course! }
4... Be7
{ This is Black's most popular and quiet way to play. We were intending to go e4-e5 and cause the opponent problems, as his knight was pinned. So, Black just unpins it, while also developing a piece.   The McCutcheon Variation,  4...Bb4  , transposes to the Winawer positions after  5.Nge2  and the ideas are the same.   The Burn Variation,  4...dxe4  , results in similar positions to the Rubinstein @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/3PP3/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq d6 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Nc3  dxe4  . For the purpose of the Quickstarter, we focus on ideas, and those variations don’t offer any particularly new plans we need to worry about. }
5. e5
{ Given the pawn was hanging, we couldn't wait much longer. We lock up the center and create a position with pawn chains, but with a slight difference compared to the @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp2ppp/4pn2/3p4/3PP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 2 4@@EndFEN@@  4.e5  lines. What is that difference? We will trade the dark-squared bishops! This exchange has, of course, both advantages and cons.   On one hand, we are glad to trade those bishops, since we have already placed our central pawns on the dark squares d4 and e5, and plan on placing another one on f4. With so many pawns on the dark squares, the dark-squared bishop, naturally, tends to be rather bad.  However, there is also a downside to that trade. Specifically, Black has less space, so trades of almost any kind tend to benefit the opponent for that reason. Of course, I still like what we are doing, or else we wouldn't be going in this direction! But, it's important you are aware that almost any decision, including this one, might have some downsides to it. }
5... Nfd7 6. Bxe7
{ 6.h4  initiates what is known as the Alekhine Gambit − an interesting variation, which is supposed to promise White a lovely initiative for the pawn. I dug deeper into it, both for the purpose of this course and overall, and I couldn't make it work well enough, Black has too many good defenses. In the course, you can go through the most critical continuation and form a better opinion. }
6... Qxe7 7. Qd2
{ We are continuing the natural development. It might seem as though White is only interested in castling queenside next, but actually, there is one more very cool idea coming up. As you hopefully remember, a typical fear of any White player while facing the French, is that their big beautiful center will get destroyed with ...c7-c5 or ...f7-f6. We are able to meet the latter with f2-f4, but what about the former?  For now, as we'll see, Black is unable to play this move. But in the future, Black will! That's why our mini-plan is to go Nd1!, rerouting the knight to e3, where it is likely to prove useful in the upcoming kingside play, while also preparing to meet ...c7-c5 with c2-c3! Even in the opening, it's crucial to think of prophylaxis. }
7... a6
{ This move, which takes the b5-square under control, is the most popular one, and for a good reason. As far as I can see, it achieves two purposes: it prevents Nb5, which makes the ...c7-c5 break possible, and it prepares ...b7-b5, grabbing more space on the queenside. }
8. Nd1
{ However, our little idea arrives just on time: we are about to meet ...c7-c5 with c2-c3. }
8... c5
{ Of course, Black starts challenging our center, but we aren't worried about that at all! }
9. c3 { This move has become possible just on time. } 9... Nc6
{ Black continues with logical development − the knight comes out to a good square, from where it's putting pressure on our center. }
10. f4
{ After several very natural and easy-to-make moves, Black arrives at crossroads, where has to make a large decision. Here is how I would describe this position: if nothing happens, White seems to be comfortably better because of the spatial advantage.  Sure enough, the d1-knight doesn't look pretty at the moment and all that, but since the position is very closed, it's not a concern right now. In the near future, White will easily be able to play Nf3, Ne3, Bd3, O-O and finish development.  Once that happens, Black's position will look sad − bad bishop, no space, no counterplay. At that point, it seems as though White should be pretty easily able to start building up kingside expansion − a slow, yet powerful attack. So, Black needs to do something. Ignoring specific moves, the choices are:  Trade the queens. Close up the kingside with ...f7-f5. Open up some files with ...f7-f6 and try to get counterplay fast, while our development is still not that amazing. These are the continuations we will now analyze. }
10... cxd4
{ This is the path Black would choose for a passive but safe position. On the next turn, Black will trade queens. This will eliminate the risk of running into a kingside attack, and partially  (very slightly so)  decrease the space disadvantage problems. Why partially? I had never thought of this concept until I was a titled player  (a FIDE Master)  and I read the words in Gelfand's excellent book Positional Decision Making in Chess, which were along these lines:   @@StartBlockQuote@@Spatial advantage is only for minor pieces. Major pieces might be affected by it, but very slightly so. It's the minor pieces that are always restrained by lack of space, hardly ever the queen or the rooks.@@EndBlockQuote@@I thought of it a lot in the following years, and I think this observation of Gelfand is just spot-on, which isn't surprising, of course. :@@EndBracket@@ }
11. cxd4 Qb4
{ This was the whole point behind exchanging on d4. White cannot avoid a queen trade @@StartBracket@@not that we want to avoid one, either@@EndBracket@@. }
12. Nf3 Qxd2+ 13. Kxd2
{ We are in no hurry. The bishop on c8 is bad. Very importantly, our center is super safe, the f4-pawn is really making sure of that. Next, we'll likely play something like Ne3, Bd3, and Rac1. Then maybe g2-g3 to reinforce the pawn chain, or maybe even g2-g4 and f4-f5, making progress on the kingside. It's also possible to instead try to make progress on the queenside by means of Nc3-a4-c5, then a2-a3 and b2-b4, for example. }
13... Nb6
{ Black often played this move, trying to come to c4 with the knight, but this is an easy one to take care of. }
14. b3
{ White will continue with the aforementioned plan, and it looks like Black does not have any counterplay whatsoever. Also, Black has a bad bishop and no space, which is no fun at all! }
