{ Of course, Black starts challenging our center, but we aren't worried about that at all! }
9. c3 { This move has become possible just on time. } 9... Nc6
{ Black continues with logical development − the knight comes out to a good square, from where it's putting pressure on our center. }
10. f4
{ After several very natural and easy-to-make moves, Black arrives at crossroads, where has to make a large decision. Here is how I would describe this position: if nothing happens, White seems to be comfortably better because of the spatial advantage.  Sure enough, the d1-knight doesn't look pretty at the moment and all that, but since the position is very closed, it's not a concern right now. In the near future, White will easily be able to play Nf3, Ne3, Bd3, O-O and finish development.  Once that happens, Black's position will look sad − bad bishop, no space, no counterplay. At that point, it seems as though White should be pretty easily able to start building up kingside expansion − a slow, yet powerful attack. So, Black needs to do something. Ignoring specific moves, the choices are:  Trade the queens. Close up the kingside with ...f7-f5. Open up some files with ...f7-f6 and try to get counterplay fast, while our development is still not that amazing. These are the continuations we will now analyze. }
10... f6
{ This seems to be Black's best shot at equality @@StartBracket@@and even counterplay!@@EndBracket@@ in the entire @@StartFEN@@rnb1k2r/1ppnqppp/p3p3/3pP3/3P4/2N5/PPPQ1PPP/R3KBNR w KQkq - 0 8@@EndFEN@@  8.Nd1!?  variation. }
11. Nf3
{ We just keep getting our pieces out. Remember, we have a long-term advantage because of our space, while Black has the dynamic one because Black can quickly castle and start putting pressure on the d4-pawn, the f3-knight, and so on. All we need is to stabilize our position. If we manage to do so, our spatial advantage will give the opponent a very hard time. }
11... cxd4
{ Black is trading this pair of pawns first to make the d4-pawn weaker. We'll see in a moment why that matters. }
12. cxd4 fxe5 { Now, Black is opening up the f-file. } 13. fxe5 O-O
{ And here, we need to be very careful. But wait, careful about what? Doesn't the center look very solid? The problem is that Black is about to take on f3. By sacrificing an exchange, Black will ruin our kingside structure and weaken the d4-pawn, and then win it with ...Qh4+! }
14. Nf2
{ By activating the knight, we also block the e1-h4 diagonal, preventing the idea of ...Rxf3 and ...Qh4+. Subtle prophylaxis!   14.Bd3?!  is an example of careless play. Now, after  14...Rxf3!  15.gxf3  Qh4+  16.Qf2  Qxd4  , Black gets wonderful compensation for the missing exchange due to:  having a pawn for it; the e5-pawn being very weak; the f-pawn being backward; the rooks having no open files to take advantage of. This is ABSOLUTELY something to avoid! }
14... Nb6
{ Black needs to activate the knight, threatening to come to the active c4-square with it. By doing so, Black also enables the bishop to come out to d7, which is really important, since it facilitates:  the standard ...Bd7-e8-h5! idea, getting rid of Black's bad bishop; the ...Rc8 move, starting to fight for the open c-file, and connecting the rooks. }
15. b3 { We prevent ...Nc4, of course, leaving the knight out of work. } 15...
Bd7
{ Black is starting to improve the bad bishop, which is a very natural and good plan. }
16. Be2 Be8
{ The bishop is about to come to h5. If Black does that, will likely want to swap it with ...Bxf3, decreasing the spatial advantage. }
17. O-O
{ But, we can still continue developing. There are no threats yet that we should be reacting to. }
17... Bh5 18. Rac1 { Now, it's time to start fighting for the c-file. } 18...
a5 { Black is looking to get counterplay by opening up the a-file. } 19. Qe3
{ This position was achieved in a game between two low-rated players, but it was a correspondence game, so no wonder they played nearly perfectly. ½-½ Gubo-Reede, LSS email 2014. I believe this variation is the best one for Black in the entire @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp2ppp/4pn2/3p4/3PP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 2 4@@EndFEN@@  4.Bg5  Be7  system, as it enables Black to avoid a typical passive position with a lack of space. Later on, the game was drawn.   I think Black is quite close to achieving equality here, but the position is not exactly there yet. Why did White make the last move? It is for a few reasons:  To enable the Nd3-c5 idea. Previously, it wasn't possible, since playing Nd3 would prevent our queen from protecting the d4-pawn and allow for ...Bxf3 followed by ...Nxd4. To overprotect the e5-pawn and the c5-square. That is important because if you ever play Rc5, you don't want to run into ...Nxe5, when dxe5 leaves the c5-rook unprotected.  
Later, we'd like to play Nd3-c5, or maybe Rc5 and Rfc1. Potentially, the move a2-a4 might be not a bad one. It would create an outpost on b4 for the black pieces but prevent ...a5-a4. If Black wants to play ...a5-a4 and ...axb3 right now, Black will get some activity down the a-file, but nothing for us to worry about, as there are no targets/weaknesses in our position.  Another thing worth mentioning is that while opening up the f-file was a great idea for our opponent since it activated the rook and enabled the ...Bd7-e8-h5 maneuver, it also had a major downside. What downside? Now the e6-pawn is weak! That's why, if we ever play Nd3-c5, Black would always have to babysit that pawn. Not exactly a pleasant thing to have to do!  So, all in all, this is a position where Black almost equalized, but we are still enjoying some pressure due to all the aforementioned factors. But, in the other lines, Black seems to be doing even worse, so this is the best choice, I believe. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Winawer 3.Nc3 Bb4 4.Nge2 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ Hi and welcome to this Quickstarter Guide! Here, we will be discussing the Sicilian, the French, and the Caro-Kann. Instead of looking at the very main lines, I preferred focusing on the most popular ones at the club level or the most instructive ones. As a result, after studying this chapter, you will be able to get a very good grasp of all the ideas and start playing this repertoire in no time! }
1... e6
{ This move, followed by ...d7-d5, defines something called the French Defense. This opening is about fighting for the center rather ambitiously while avoiding direct piece play. As you will see, the first two moves only feature pawn play. The downside for Black is the locked-up light-squared bishop, and very often, this piece tends to be a large issue for quite a long time. }
2. d4 d5
{ Here, we arrive at massive crossroads. White can lock up the center with e4-e5, take Black's pawn and open up the position, or defend the pawn with some knight move − either to c3 or to d2. }
3. Nc3
{ After a long thought, I decided to suggest this move, which is the most critical and ambitious one. Why did I do that and what's the point of this move? As we can see, we are simply protecting the e4-pawn while keeping the center flexible for now. It's important to do so for the following practical reason: most Black players who play the French @@StartBracket@@and I am one of them; I just wrote a course on the French that I'm in love with!@@EndBracket@@ love positions with pawn chains. Our goal is to try to avoid creating one!  However, don't worry: while the move  3.Nc3  is known for being a very principled and theoretically heavy one, we won't need loads of theory − instead, I am opting for practical, easy-to-learn sidelines, which still carry quite a bit of punch, as always!  In this position, we'll need to consider quite a lot of moves. Black can try to pin the knight with  3...Bb4  , which is known as the Winawer Variation − the most forcing and sharp one. Black can also try to force us to lock up the center with the move  3...Nf6  , which is another major theoretical move. The passive yet solid decision is to play  3...dxe4  − the Rubinstein Variation. Black is hoping to avoid the pawn chain situation and trade down, liquidating White's hopes to get a spatial advantage or long-term pressure.  And, of course, there are quite a few sidelines, such as  3...Nc6  ,  3...Be7  − the move I suggested in my Black French course,  3...h6  ,  3...a6  , and so on. We tackle them all in the main course! }
3... Bb4
{ The famous Winawer Variation. Black develops in the most active way possible, immediately pinning the knight and threatening the e4-pawn. The downside of this move is that it weakens the g7-pawn. Plus, if Black ever goes ...Ne7, the bishop often ends up short on squares and unable to return to the kingside. }
4. Ne2
{ I like this rare, played 13! times less often than the main move  4.e5!  But, when I say 'sideline', don't worry − this is not a bad move! It's a variation that has been tried by such outstanding players as MVL, Firouzja, Ivanchuk, Xiong, and many others when they were looking to avoid the mainstream theory and get a bit more creative.    We make sure the structure remains very flexible by overprotecting the c3-knight with our knight, so that if Black ever takes it, we can take back with the knight, avoiding doubled pawns. On the next turn, we are planning on continuing with a2-a3, kicking out the annoying bishop and neutralizing the pin. Once we do that, Black will have a hard time finding a good square for the bishop, and we'll continue the flexible nice development. But, of course, just as any line  (especially a sideline)  , this move has a few downsides, namely:  It blocks the development of our kingside, even if just temporarily. It leaves the e4-pawn hanging.   Black mostly captures the hanging pawn with @@StartFEN@@rnbqk1nr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/1b1PP3/2N5/PPP1NPPP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 3 4@@EndFEN@@  4...dxe4  , however, some players have tried such moves as  4...Nf6  ,  4...Nc6  , and  4...Ne7  . Here, we'll focus on the main line  4...dxe4  . Of course, the sidelines are considered in great detail in the corresponding chapter.   4.e5  is the one and only main line. But, I'm not a fan of deeply researched chess, where it's hard to come up with anything new. So, we won't do this! Here is a sample line that shows how the game typically develops in this variation.  4...c5  5.a3  Bxc3+  6.bxc3  , Black ruins  the queenside structure, hoping to attack the pawns in the future with ...Qa5, ...Rc8, and so on.  6...Ne7  7.Qg4  ,  White attacks the g7-pawn, weakened by the absence of Black's dark-squared bishop. Here, Black has a ton of interesting lines, but the main one goes  7...Qc7  . Black ignores the threat, instead counterattacking on the c-file.  After  8.Qxg7  Rg8  9.Qxh7  , White gladly scoops up two kingside pawns.  9...cxd4  and  now, ...Qxc3+ is a huge threat, winning the rook on a1.  10.Ne2  Nbc6  , Black is focusing on the overexpanded  weak e5-pawn.  11.f4  , we protect it.  11...Bd7  Black just continues development.  Please note it's very difficult to develop the kingside!  12.Qd3  , White typically brings the queen back to defend the queenside and consolidate the position.  12...dxc3  13.Nxc3  a6  and the arising position is just the beginning of sharp theoretical play.   As we can see, we are a pawn up here, but it's very difficult to develop the f1-bishop, as the g2-pawn would hang. It's also not obvious where to castle − queenside is weak, kingside is suspicious since Black's rooks have a lot of open files, and staying in the center doesn't sound appealing either. Of course, White isn't doing poorly here, but such sharp complex play is not to my taste at all. }
4... dxe4
{ Black is just capturing the free pawn. Later on, Black might return it and focus on rapid comfortable development, or instead try to hold on to it with ...f7-f5. }
5. a3
{ We, of course, follow up with our plan of kicking out the opponent's bishop and breaking the pin. At this point, Black needs to decide whether to hold on to the pawn by taking the knight and then doing something about the hanging pawn or to retreat, returning it right away. }
5... Be7
{ The more popular move, but, due to the recent discoveries I've made in this line, I don't have much faith in it. }
6. Nxe4
{ We get the pawn back. Because of the extra space and more active pieces, it seems obvious White should be better. However, there is one problem: the knight on e2 is really passive! That's the only thing that gives Black hope for equality, I believe. }
6... Nf6
{ Black offers a knight trade, which is a logical thing to do, as it decreases the spatial disadvantage: the fewer pieces left, the less it matters that you don't have much space. }
7. Nxf6+
{ This move is quite rare, but it's been used in recent years by such strong young players as Xiong, Abdusattorov, Niemann, and others, and White scored really well: 58%. We are happy to force the bishop to go to f6 without having to determine or commit to placing our pieces on weird squares, such as after  7.Qd3  . }
7... Bxf6 8. Be3
{ Now, the goal is obviously to get the queen out and castle. In most cases, we will probably settle for Qd2, followed by queenside castling. However, in many positions, the queen can come to g4 after we play Nf4 and create a lot of threats on the kingside! }
8... O-O
{ This, of course, has been the most popular continuation − for now, Black just castles. }
9. Qd2
{ And we also continue to develop. The plan is to castle and then play Nf4, intending to either open the center with d4-d5! and install the knight on d5, when the time is right, or play g2-g3 and Bg2, increasing pressure on the long diagonal. Of course, the plan of Nf4, O-O-O and g2-g4, h2-h4, etc, can also be very strong and logical! }
9... c5
{ An attempt to simplify the position and liquidate some pawns in the center. It seems logical, but as we've seen in many other chapters by now, it hardly ever works! Of course, we don't want to take the c5-pawn before castling, as that would leave the one on b2 hanging. }
10. O-O-O
{ We get the d4-square under better control and also protect the b2-pawn, creating a simple threat of winning the c5-pawn on the next turn. }
10... cxd4 11. Nxd4
{ Black's main issues involve:  the undeveloped queenside; the fact the d6-square is weak and easily accessible to our pieces − for example, after Nb5-d6, our knight will obviously put a ton of pressure on the position; the fact we can easily develop a kingside attack, both because the bishop is going to run into tempi-winning moves like g4-g5! soon, and because the kingside lacks defenders. }
11... Bd7
{ Black needs this move to be able to develop the knight to c6 and recapture back with the bishop, avoiding the situation where the pawn structure gets ruined. }
12. g4
{ While Black is trying to crawl out of bed, we are instead building the kingside attack without any obstacles. }
12... Nc6 13. Nb5
{ The knight is about to land on d6, and the kingside attack is developing rather easily. Plus, of course, at this very moment, we are threatening to win the bishop on d7. This position isn't nice for Black! }
*

