5... Be7
{ The more popular move, but, due to the recent discoveries I've made in this line, I don't have much faith in it. }
6. Nxe4
{ We get the pawn back. Because of the extra space and more active pieces, it seems obvious White should be better. However, there is one problem: the knight on e2 is really passive! That's the only thing that gives Black hope for equality, I believe. }
6... Nf6
{ Black offers a knight trade, which is a logical thing to do, as it decreases the spatial disadvantage: the fewer pieces left, the less it matters that you don't have much space. }
7. Nxf6+
{ This move is quite rare, but it's been used in recent years by such strong young players as Xiong, Abdusattorov, Niemann, and others, and White scored really well: 58%. We are happy to force the bishop to go to f6 without having to determine or commit to placing our pieces on weird squares, such as after  7.Qd3  . }
7... Bxf6 8. Be3
{ Now, the goal is obviously to get the queen out and castle. In most cases, we will probably settle for Qd2, followed by queenside castling. However, in many positions, the queen can come to g4 after we play Nf4 and create a lot of threats on the kingside! }
8... O-O
{ This, of course, has been the most popular continuation − for now, Black just castles. }
9. Qd2
{ And we also continue to develop. The plan is to castle and then play Nf4, intending to either open the center with d4-d5! and install the knight on d5, when the time is right, or play g2-g3 and Bg2, increasing pressure on the long diagonal. Of course, the plan of Nf4, O-O-O and g2-g4, h2-h4, etc, can also be very strong and logical! }
9... b6
{ Black wants to develop the bishop to the long diagonal, where it will be rather active. Fair enough! }
10. O-O-O { We also just continue our development for now. } 10... Bb7 11. Nf4
{ This move is a very important one for us. Why so?  The knight can jump to h5, disturbing the bishop, helping us seek the bishop pair advantage, and helping us build up the kingside attack. It can support the d4-d5 break, which can at times @@StartBracket@@provided our pieces are more active@@EndBracket@@ help us favorably open up the center. It gets out of the bishop's way, which enables us to finish development easily. }
11... Nd7
{ Black keeps developing too. And this is when we need to make a decision about the direction of the game from now on. Do we attack on the kingside? Do we open the center? }
12. d5
{ The decision to open up the center is justified by the awkward placement of two of Black's minor pieces:  the bishop on f6 − we can easily hit it and hope to get the bishop pair; the knight on d7 − the pin on the d-file can prove really awkward for Black to deal with. }
12... exd5 { This leads to a very difficult endgame after a natural sequence. }
13. Nxd5 { Now, we'd like to take the f6-bishop. } 13... Bxd5 14. Qxd5
{ Black gave up the bishop pair and now struggles because of the pinned d7-knight. }
14... Ne5
{ It's logical to activate the pinned knight, but this move enables a queen trade, which is, of course, good for us. Why so? Easy! The bishop pair is a long-term advantage that manifests itself best in endgames with no major pieces, so swapping the queens and rooks is typically good for the side that has the bishop pair − in this case, it's us! }
15. Be2
{ But instead of begging for a trade  (taking the queen and helping Black activate the rook)  , we just keep developing. Let Black take instead! }
15... Qxd5 16. Rxd5
{ The upcoming endgame is going to be extremely difficult for Black. Why so? Isn't the pawn structure symmetrical?   The position is open enough for the bishop pair to prove very strong. The move ...b7-b6 has weakened the a6-square, the c6-square, and the h1-a8 diagonal. Our bishops can easily target the queenside pawns. For example, imagine if we trade rooks and play Bf4-b8. Wouldn't all the pawns just fall? The weakened queenside makes it easy for our king, once we trade the rooks, to invade and help us win their pawns. All in all, Black is nearly lost. }
