{ We, of course, follow up with our plan of kicking out the opponent's bishop and breaking the pin. At this point, Black needs to decide whether to hold on to the pawn by taking the knight and then doing something about the hanging pawn or to retreat, returning it right away. }
5... Bxc3+ 6. Nxc3
{ If we just get to take the e4-pawn without consequences, we should have a considerable advantage due to the extra space in the center, created by our d4-pawn, the bishop pair, and the fact Black's c8-bishop is inactive, as almost always in the French. Black should hurry to accomplish something right now! }
6... f5
{ An attempt to hold on to the extra pawn. As it often happens, it's not a good idea for Black to be greedy in this opening, just like in many other openings. This move doesn't help develop any pieces, and it weakens a lot of dark squares, such as the h1-b8 diagonal, the e5-square, and the a1-h8 diagonal, of course. Since we have a unique and unmatched dark-squared bishop, that's gonna be a huge problem for our opponent. }
7. Qh5+
{ Our goal is to make Black weaken the dark squares as much as possible, so we dream of forcing ...g7-g6 − and we make the dream come true! }
7... g6 8. Qh3
{ From here, the queen is watching the h7-pawn and the one on e6, potentially. The goal is to quickly develop the dark-squared bishop, likely to f4, castle queenside, and blow up the center with f2-f3! Once that happens, we'll have easy access to all the weaknesses, such as the e6-pawn after Bc4, Rhe1, and so on. How does Black plan on surviving? And why is Black agreeing to go through all these issues? Is it just to be a pawn up?! }
8... Nf6
{ Black should try to castle as soon as possible to be relatively safe when the center opens after the inevitable f2-f3. }
9. Bg5
{ The bishop could have also gone to h6, preventing castling. But pinning the loose knight also looks great! }
9... O-O
{ Black finally manages to castle. It seems the worst is over, right? } 10.
O-O-O
{ But we are just getting started! Now, the idea is to play f2-f3, then take with the g-pawn and achieve several important things, such as:  open up the e-file to attack the e6-pawn; get easier access to the e5-square; control the e4 and g4-squares better; open up the g-file. }
10... Nbd7
{ Black should keep getting the pieces out. What else is there to do since there is no active play? }
11. f3 { We are continuing with the logical plan of tearing the center open. }
11... exf3 12. gxf3
{ Now, the e6-pawn is finally a target. Another idea could be to play h2-h4-h5 at some point, opening up Black's king a lot more. As we can see, we have tremendous compensation for the pawn: the much more active pieces and lots of threats in the center. Additionally, Black's queenside pieces are beyond very passive. }
12... Nb6
{ It seems like this move, which prepares ...Nbd5 and enables the c8-bishop to protect the weak e6-pawn, is logical. Regardless, Black is lost by the way. :@@EndBracket@@ }
13. Qh4
{ We put more pressure on the knight. Potentially, there could even be such a funny idea as Ne4!, attacking the knight another time, meeting ...fxe4 with fxe4, opening up the f-file, and preparing e4-e5! }
13... Rf7
{ For example, Black can try this move, which prepares ...Qf8 to defend the knight, while also breaking the pin and bringing the queen closer to the defense of the kingside. What else can to do? }
14. Ne2
{ We are just completely winning. The threat is Nf4, not only putting more pressure on the e6-pawn, which I had already mentioned a dozen times, but also preparing the little regrouping Nd3-e5!, taking full advantage of this gorgeous outpost in the center.  Once this is done, the f7-rook will be under pressure and we'll start considering ideas of sacrificing on g6 to open up Black's king. For example, with the knight on e5, after Rg1 and Qh6, it seems the sacrifice could be deadly. Black doesn't have a single active move and is lost, of course. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Winawer 3.Nc3 Bb4 4.Nge2 #4"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ Hi and welcome to this Quickstarter Guide! Here, we will be discussing the Sicilian, the French, and the Caro-Kann. Instead of looking at the very main lines, I preferred focusing on the most popular ones at the club level or the most instructive ones. As a result, after studying this chapter, you will be able to get a very good grasp of all the ideas and start playing this repertoire in no time! }
1... e6
{ This move, followed by ...d7-d5, defines something called the French Defense. This opening is about fighting for the center rather ambitiously while avoiding direct piece play. As you will see, the first two moves only feature pawn play. The downside for Black is the locked-up light-squared bishop, and very often, this piece tends to be a large issue for quite a long time. }
2. d4 d5
{ Here, we arrive at massive crossroads. White can lock up the center with e4-e5, take Black's pawn and open up the position, or defend the pawn with some knight move − either to c3 or to d2. }
3. Nc3
{ After a long thought, I decided to suggest this move, which is the most critical and ambitious one. Why did I do that and what's the point of this move? As we can see, we are simply protecting the e4-pawn while keeping the center flexible for now. It's important to do so for the following practical reason: most Black players who play the French @@StartBracket@@and I am one of them; I just wrote a course on the French that I'm in love with!@@EndBracket@@ love positions with pawn chains. Our goal is to try to avoid creating one!  However, don't worry: while the move  3.Nc3  is known for being a very principled and theoretically heavy one, we won't need loads of theory − instead, I am opting for practical, easy-to-learn sidelines, which still carry quite a bit of punch, as always!  In this position, we'll need to consider quite a lot of moves. Black can try to pin the knight with  3...Bb4  , which is known as the Winawer Variation − the most forcing and sharp one. Black can also try to force us to lock up the center with the move  3...Nf6  , which is another major theoretical move. The passive yet solid decision is to play  3...dxe4  − the Rubinstein Variation. Black is hoping to avoid the pawn chain situation and trade down, liquidating White's hopes to get a spatial advantage or long-term pressure.  And, of course, there are quite a few sidelines, such as  3...Nc6  ,  3...Be7  − the move I suggested in my Black French course,  3...h6  ,  3...a6  , and so on. We tackle them all in the main course! }
3... Bb4
{ The famous Winawer Variation. Black develops in the most active way possible, immediately pinning the knight and threatening the e4-pawn. The downside of this move is that it weakens the g7-pawn. Plus, if Black ever goes ...Ne7, the bishop often ends up short on squares and unable to return to the kingside. }
4. Ne2
{ I like this rare, played 13! times less often than the main move  4.e5!  But, when I say 'sideline', don't worry − this is not a bad move! It's a variation that has been tried by such outstanding players as MVL, Firouzja, Ivanchuk, Xiong, and many others when they were looking to avoid the mainstream theory and get a bit more creative.    We make sure the structure remains very flexible by overprotecting the c3-knight with our knight, so that if Black ever takes it, we can take back with the knight, avoiding doubled pawns. On the next turn, we are planning on continuing with a2-a3, kicking out the annoying bishop and neutralizing the pin. Once we do that, Black will have a hard time finding a good square for the bishop, and we'll continue the flexible nice development. But, of course, just as any line  (especially a sideline)  , this move has a few downsides, namely:  It blocks the development of our kingside, even if just temporarily. It leaves the e4-pawn hanging.   Black mostly captures the hanging pawn with @@StartFEN@@rnbqk1nr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/1b1PP3/2N5/PPP1NPPP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 3 4@@EndFEN@@  4...dxe4  , however, some players have tried such moves as  4...Nf6  ,  4...Nc6  , and  4...Ne7  . Here, we'll focus on the main line  4...dxe4  . Of course, the sidelines are considered in great detail in the corresponding chapter.   4.e5  is the one and only main line. But, I'm not a fan of deeply researched chess, where it's hard to come up with anything new. So, we won't do this! Here is a sample line that shows how the game typically develops in this variation.  4...c5  5.a3  Bxc3+  6.bxc3  , Black ruins  the queenside structure, hoping to attack the pawns in the future with ...Qa5, ...Rc8, and so on.  6...Ne7  7.Qg4  ,  White attacks the g7-pawn, weakened by the absence of Black's dark-squared bishop. Here, Black has a ton of interesting lines, but the main one goes  7...Qc7  . Black ignores the threat, instead counterattacking on the c-file.  After  8.Qxg7  Rg8  9.Qxh7  , White gladly scoops up two kingside pawns.  9...cxd4  and  now, ...Qxc3+ is a huge threat, winning the rook on a1.  10.Ne2  Nbc6  , Black is focusing on the overexpanded  weak e5-pawn.  11.f4  , we protect it.  11...Bd7  Black just continues development.  Please note it's very difficult to develop the kingside!  12.Qd3  , White typically brings the queen back to defend the queenside and consolidate the position.  12...dxc3  13.Nxc3  a6  and the arising position is just the beginning of sharp theoretical play.   As we can see, we are a pawn up here, but it's very difficult to develop the f1-bishop, as the g2-pawn would hang. It's also not obvious where to castle − queenside is weak, kingside is suspicious since Black's rooks have a lot of open files, and staying in the center doesn't sound appealing either. Of course, White isn't doing poorly here, but such sharp complex play is not to my taste at all. }
4... dxe4
{ Black is just capturing the free pawn. Later on, Black might return it and focus on rapid comfortable development, or instead try to hold on to it with ...f7-f5. }
5. a3
{ We, of course, follow up with our plan of kicking out the opponent's bishop and breaking the pin. At this point, Black needs to decide whether to hold on to the pawn by taking the knight and then doing something about the hanging pawn or to retreat, returning it right away. }
5... Bxc3+ 6. Nxc3
{ If we just get to take the e4-pawn without consequences, we should have a considerable advantage due to the extra space in the center, created by our d4-pawn, the bishop pair, and the fact Black's c8-bishop is inactive, as almost always in the French. Black should hurry to accomplish something right now! }
6... Nc6
{ Black's most principled and sound choice, immediately counterattacking the d4-pawn and making us react. }
7. Bf4
{ This rare move has been seen in just 3% of the games or so, but it's been mostly used in very recent years by top players. There are several ideas:  Potentially, we are looking to harass the c7-pawn with Nb5. We are looking to discourage the ...e6-e5 break. At some point, say if Black takes the d4-pawn, ideas like Be5! become possible, attacking whatever piece is on d4 and the g7-pawn. It's just a developing move. If we reach the consensus there's no need to defend the d4-pawn, then why go to the passive e3-square and not here? Next, we'd like to play Qd2 and castle queenside.   Black can consider accepting the d4-pawn, but the overwhelming majority of players who reached this position with the Black pieces tried  7...Nf6  or  7...Nge7  , looking to castle quickly instead of being greedy. }
7... Nge7
{ Developing the knight to this square has, of course, certain upsides and downsides.  The bad: The e4-pawn isn't defended. The h5 and g4-squares are not controlled, so our queen could jump there.   The good: Bg5 won't be a pin on the knight. In the event of Bb5-Bxc6 at any moment, Black can take back with the knight and keep the pawn structure intact. }
8. Qd2
{ We ignore the seemingly hanging d4-pawn and continue developing while preparing queenside castling. We've already seen in several lines of this chapter that holding on to the extra e4-pawn with ...f7-f5 is typically a poor idea, so we're in no hurry to win back the pawn, as we're not afraid of Black trying that.   This, by the way, is pretty much a new move − everyone takes the e4-pawn instead, but the correspondence players, who know better, keep developing with  8.Qd2  . Let's follow their ideas! }
8... O-O { Black should just ignore the pawn and castle. } 9. O-O-O
{ So should we. Now, we're ready to win back the e4-pawn without ever wondering if the one on d4 can be recaptured. Of course, if we do get to peacefully win the e4-pawn back, we will be clearly better due to our bishop pair, central control, space advantage, and the fact Black's pieces are pretty passive, especially the c8-bishop.  Then, we'll start building pressure on the kingside with Bd3, h2-h4, g2-g4, Ng5, and so on. I think Black should accept that uncomfortable scenario. However, most people would prefer to at least keep the extra pawn if they have to deal with an uncomfortable position. }
9... f5 { That's the move we should really investigate. } 10. f3
{ However, just as in some other lines with the same structure, we can blow up the center, open up the g-file, and prepare to start taking advantage of the weak backward e6-pawn and the outpost on e5. }
10... exf3 11. gxf3
{ Now, the g-file is open, and we are about to execute a very simple plan. What plan, exactly?  We'll develop the bishop to c4 to put more pressure on the e6-pawn so that our opponent is stuck defending it. We'll double the rooks on the g-file, and maybe bring the queen in there too. We'll advance the h-pawn to help us open up the king's shelter. At some point, the d4-d5! break might prove very powerful as well. }
11... Nd5 { Perhaps Black should try to trade down. } 12. Nxd5
{ We'll gladly do so. } 12... Qxd5
{ Now, we need to be paying some attention to the queen, which could suddenly jump on a2. It's not a big deal, just don't miss Qa1 with checkmate. That's something that can be easily stopped with, say, Qc3, making room for the king on a2. }
13. Rg1
{ We start putting more pressure on Black's kingside. Ideas like Bh6 and Qg5 are right around the corner! }
13... Rf7
{ It's logical for Black to stop that threat, while also defending the c7-pawn, which we could have easily won a move ago. We just choose to focus on developing an even more powerful initiative. }
14. c4
{ It's time to blow up the center, making full use of the bishop pair and our major pieces on the d-file, which are ready to dominate it once it's open! }
14... Qd8 15. d5
{ The poor black pieces are being pushed all the way back. Let me show you one fascinating and gorgeous way the game can go. }
15... Ne7
{ Of course, taking on d5 only helps White, so Black wisely chooses to retreat. }
16. Kb1
{ The point of this move is to avoid running into any checks on the c-file, and to prevent ...Qxd2 from being a check! Once this is no longer a problem, we can start considering forcing ideas like Bxc7 followed by d5-d6, and things of that sort. And, of course, we're creating a huge threat of dxe6, because then we'll take the f7-rook with check!   16.dxe6  doesn't work as well as a move later since after  16...Qxd2+  , Black gives a check, so we cannot take the rook! }
16... exd5 { Black has to capture in order to stop the dxe6 threat. } 17. cxd5
{ Now, d5-d6 is on the agenda, followed by Bc4! Or, of course, we can play Bc4 first and threaten d5-d6! later on. }
17... Ng6
{ For example, Black can try to block the g-file to stop all sorts of dangers. We are already going way above and beyond what's necessary, but I can't help myself. I NEED to show you this beautiful idea! }
18. Rxg6
{ We have such a dominant position that we can easily afford to sacrifice an exchange to just win a tempo and completely stop Black from being able to control any of the dark squares. }
18... hxg6 19. Bc4
{ With d5-d6 coming, as well as Rg1, or Be5 and f3-f4!, reinforcing the bishop on a gorgeous outpost, and Black's queenside pieces completely undeveloped and stuck, it's obvious our position is completely winning. What an example of domination! }
*

