{ This is the move Black overwhelmingly chooses, reinforcing the d5-pawn and starting to prepare kingside development − now the bishop can come out, the knight gets the e7-square, and so on. }
5. Nc3 Nd7
{ This is Black's second most popular move. It is fairly natural, isn't it? Black is just developing a knight, for now, keeping the tension in the center alive. However, even though a number of very strong GMs, such as Esipenko, Kobalia, and many others have used this move order, I believe it is suspicious and hardly correct!  Why would I make such a claim? See, this move creates a problem, which is more typical of openings like the Slav or London: often, one side can open up the c-file @@StartBracket@@in this case, we can do that by playing cxd5@@EndBracket@@, but doesn't want to, because doing so surrenders the spatial advantage @@StartBracket@@our pawn on c4 is more useful than the Black one on c6@@EndBracket@@.  However, the idea of opening up that file becomes A LOT more tempting after ...Nd7, because now the Black knight cannot go to c6 anymore to block it! Of course, Black could try to play ...Ne7-c6, but in that case, the knight on d7 would be extremely passive. It seems to me that this variation's popularity has been declining, and that is exactly because of the c-file opening up fast, and only in White's favor. }
6. cxd5 { We are very glad to be able to immediately open up the c-file! } 6...
cxd5 7. h4
{ We are threatening to trap the black bishop with g2-g4 and h4-h5, of course. }
7... h6
{ Black must make room for this bishop exactly this way since  7...h5?  would weaken the kingside too much. }
8. g4
{ But now, we can grab even more space, while also continuing to win time! }
8... Bh7 9. Bd3
{ Now, we force Black to trade and help us develop the queen, which wins another tempo. }
9... Bxd3 10. Qxd3
{ Black's main problem is that it seems very difficult to find good squares for all the pieces. A few setups that come to mind include ...Bb4 and ...Ne7, or ...Ne7-c6 followed by ...Be7. It's also not obvious if it's safe to castle kingside. Logically, you'd think it shouldn't be! }
10... Bb4
{ A possible way of playing, but it allows us to comfortably finish our development while keeping all that lovely extra space on the kingside at no cost. }
11. Ne2 Ne7 12. Bd2
{ For now, we unpin the knight and get a step closer to connecting the rooks. We aren't yet making a commitment of any kind regarding our king's position. But, likely, we'd love to castle queenside. }
12... O-O
{ It's not obvious to me if Black should castle kingside, but it's also not clear what to do with the king and the h8-rook otherwise. It's a brand-new position, so let's assume Black does castle. }
13. O-O-O
{ Our king is perfectly safe here. In order to not be annoyed by any pins, we'd love to go Kb1, after which the kingside attack would unfold extremely fast: we just need to go h4-h5, Ng3, Rdg1, g4-g5, and Black will be done! I fail to see much counterplay for Black, so let's stop here.  Our position looks very promising to me since Black has created a hook for our kingside attack by playing ...h7-h6. Black's pieces are fairly passive and, of course, our next moves look very logical. }
*

