[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Caro-Kann 3.e5 c5 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ Hi and welcome to this Quickstarter Guide! Here, we will be discussing the Sicilian, the French, and the Caro-Kann. Instead of looking at the very main lines, I preferred focusing on the most popular ones at the club level or the most instructive ones. As a result, after studying this chapter, you will be able to get a very good grasp of all the ideas and start playing this repertoire in no time! }
1... c6
{ This move, followed by  2.--  d5  , defines the Caro-Kann Defense − one of the most solid openings for Black out there. Black is preparing to fight for the  center with ...d7-d5, just like in the French Defense. So, these two openings are sort of siblings, if you would like a bit of a figure of speech.  The main difference is that in the French, Black blocks the light-squared bishop, but gets to attack White's center with ...c7-c5 in one move − rather fast! On the other hand, in the Caro, Black cannot attack the center nearly as fast, since ...c7-c6, followed by ...c7-c5, would cost an extra tempo. But on the bright side, Black doesn't block the light-squared bishop! So, the Caro-Kann players want a solid game without a typical bad bishop. They hope to develop it or trade it off and then still eventually undermine the center with ...c6-c5, hoping the tempo won't make much of a difference. }
2. d4
{ This, of course, is White's most ambitious move.  2.Nf3  d5  3.d3!?  is another variation, which is a recent discovery − it's been actively played at the top level only since 2018. It's one of my all-time favorites, and I had written about it in the past.  Unfortunately, even though it would have been a good fit for this course, and I know many people were hoping I'd cover exactly this variation, I decided to go for something else, and that's for a few reasons.   The theory isn't changing very fast in this Nf3-d3 system, so I didn't feel as though I had a lot of new ideas to offer.  In the main system, the Advance Variation, which is what I'm recommending, the game is much more complex. I thought we'd get a nice mix of the ability to discover more about interesting strategic chess and a relatively simple line to learn too!    3...dxe4  4.dxe4  Qxd1+  5.Kxd1  . If you like endgames, and variations that don't require much theory, make sure to pay attention to this one as well! }
2... d5
{ Black follows up in the most logical way, fighting for the center with the d-pawn. Now, we arrive at massive crossroads. In the second part of the 20th century, everyone used to play  3.Nd2  or  3.Nc3  − these two moves are just a transposition. No one used to believe  3.e5  was dangerous.  However, nowadays, the opinion most players hold is exactly the opposite:  3.Nd2  and  3.Nc3  have been neutralized in numerous ways, while  3.e5  is known to offer the most interesting complex play! }
3. e5
{ Sorry, I couldn't help myself with the exclamation mark. While there are many other interesting variations that White can choose, this one is the most strategically interesting one. You won't ever run out of new ideas to explore, or alternative ways to play. We are closing the center, preventing Black from exchanging the central pawns, and are grabbing a lot of space while doing so.  Here, Black has two main moves:  3...Bf5  , developing the light-squared bishop, which has been the most popular move historically, and  3...c5  , which is an attempt to play the French a tempo down, but without blocking the  bishop on c8.  The  3...c5  line has become very popular in 2010-2015, and its popularity has only been increasing. It leads to more forcing play. }
3... c5
{ This variation has started to become fairly popular @@StartBracket@@and then extremely popular!@@EndBracket@@ in the last decade. Since Black is immediately provoking conflict in the center, it is only natural that play here is quickly becoming pretty forcing, unlike after  3...Bf5  , where the strategic understanding and knowledge of plans can often nearly completely eliminate one's need to know the forcing lines.   3...Bf5  is the historical main line. It is still the most popular continuation nowadays, but the difference is that back in the day, only  3...Bf5  was considered reputable, while now  3...c5  gets a fair share of respect as well. }
4. Nf3
{ We just protect the d4-pawn, getting ready to blow up the center with our favorite move c2-c4! This move might be 4 times less common than the main line  4.dxc5  , but it is the most critical theoretical attempt to challenge Black's setup.  Here, Black has three main continuations. The most popular move is @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp2pppp/8/2ppP3/3P4/5N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Nc6  , which is not as good as  4...cxd4  unless it is played with the intention of transposing to the 4...cxd4 lines with  4...Nc6  5.c4  cxd4!  6.Nxd4  .  Also, very importantly, @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp2pppp/8/2ppP3/3P4/5N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Nc6  gives White the additional option of  5.dxc5  , which is not the same as the @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp2pppp/8/2ppP3/3P4/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.dxc5  lines. This is because when the  black knight is on c6, it can run into the Bb5 pin, and can no longer go to d7, attacking the c5-pawn. So, the move  order @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp2pppp/8/2ppP3/3P4/5N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Nc6  has several drawbacks, no upside, and at best just transposes to the correct  4...cxd4  5.Nxd4  Nc6  lines.  Finally, there is @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp2pppp/8/2ppP3/3P4/5N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Bg4  , after which play can get really sharp.  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp2pppp/8/2ppP3/3P4/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.dxc5  is the main line. I don't mind the arising positions, but I am afraid the theoretical workload will be a bit too large here. Typically, what you get is a position like this one.  4...e6   4...Nc6  is also a fairly popular move, but I actually don't have much faith in this one! And that's an important piece of knowledge for our theoretical variations, as in some lines, we might try to transpose here!  5.a3  ,  White isn't holding on to the c5-pawn, as that's not really possible yet. Instead, White wants to meet ...Bxc5 with b2-b4, grabbing space on the queenside and gaining time.  5...Bxc5  6.b4  Bb6  7.Nf3  Ne7  8.Bd3  a5  9.b5  Nd7  10.O-O  Ng6  11.Bb2  O-O  .   A position like this is really interesting to play, without a doubt. Black would try to undermine our e5-pawn with ...f7-f6, and take advantage of the weakened c5-square by playing ...Nc5, ...a5-a4, etc. We, instead, often try to push c2-c4, looking to recapture on c4 with the knight and then install it on d6. Interesting play, without a doubt, but not something I'd prefer. }
4... cxd4
{ Releasing the tension immediately is Black's best, safest, and easiest choice, since it prevents us from being able to capture on c5. }
5. Nxd4 e6
{ This is an inferior move order. Since Black isn't attacking the d4-knight, we are able to take advantage of that and get the b1-knight out in the most flexible way possible. }
6. Nd2 { Now, this knight would be able to come to f3 very easily. } 6... Nc6
{ Of course, it makes sense for Black to finally play this move, attacking the e5-pawn and offering a trade. }
7. Nxc6
{ Just like in the main lines, we are happy with this pawn structure. Our plan is fairly simple: use the mighty e5-pawn, which prevents ...Nf6 and ...Bd6, to develop the standard kingside attack with moves such as Bd3, Qg4/h5, and Nf3-g5. And, of course, we'd love to see Black struggle to finish the kingside development since the pieces on that part of the board really lack space. }
7... bxc6 8. Bd3 Ne7
{ The knight typically goes here, and then to g6, making way for the bishop to go to e7. If instead ...Be7 is played, the knight has no squares; on another note, if Black places the bishop on c5, that runs into Qg4, as the g7-pawn is a very typical target in this structure. }
9. O-O Ng6
{ Black can also just focus on development, foregoing any ...a7-a5 related ideas, which we see in another line. }
10. Nf3
{ We, of course, protect the e5-pawn. Unfortunately, we couldn't get the queen out to g4 before playing Nf3, but that's okay. }
10... Be7
{ After  10...a5  , looking to trade the light-squared bishops quickly, we can react in a standard way:  11.c4!  Ba6  12.Qa4  , getting a similar position to the one here. }
11. c3
{ This move is not only helping us control the d4-square better. There is one more wonderful idea! }
11... O-O 12. Qa4
{ The queen is finding its way to the kingside, after all! The c6-pawn is under attack too, of course. }
12... c5 13. Qg4
{ White has many annoying threats and ideas, such as:  h2-h4-h5, kicking out the knight @@StartBracket@@where would it go?!@@EndBracket@@ and grabbing space on the kingside; Bxg6!, followed by Bg5, Qh4, and hopefully Nxg5 and Qh7 with checkmate; Qh5, Ng5 and f2-f4, maybe followed by Rf3-h3. All in all, we seem to have a very easy kingside attack and no weaknesses. }
