{ We just protect the d4-pawn, getting ready to blow up the center with our favorite move c2-c4! This move might be 4 times less common than the main line  4.dxc5  , but it is the most critical theoretical attempt to challenge Black's setup.  Here, Black has three main continuations. The most popular move is @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp2pppp/8/2ppP3/3P4/5N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Nc6  , which is not as good as  4...cxd4  unless it is played with the intention of transposing to the 4...cxd4 lines with  4...Nc6  5.c4  cxd4!  6.Nxd4  .  Also, very importantly, @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp2pppp/8/2ppP3/3P4/5N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Nc6  gives White the additional option of  5.dxc5  , which is not the same as the @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp2pppp/8/2ppP3/3P4/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.dxc5  lines. This is because when the  black knight is on c6, it can run into the Bb5 pin, and can no longer go to d7, attacking the c5-pawn. So, the move  order @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp2pppp/8/2ppP3/3P4/5N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Nc6  has several drawbacks, no upside, and at best just transposes to the correct  4...cxd4  5.Nxd4  Nc6  lines.  Finally, there is @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp2pppp/8/2ppP3/3P4/5N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Bg4  , after which play can get really sharp.  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp2pppp/8/2ppP3/3P4/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.dxc5  is the main line. I don't mind the arising positions, but I am afraid the theoretical workload will be a bit too large here. Typically, what you get is a position like this one.  4...e6   4...Nc6  is also a fairly popular move, but I actually don't have much faith in this one! And that's an important piece of knowledge for our theoretical variations, as in some lines, we might try to transpose here!  5.a3  ,  White isn't holding on to the c5-pawn, as that's not really possible yet. Instead, White wants to meet ...Bxc5 with b2-b4, grabbing space on the queenside and gaining time.  5...Bxc5  6.b4  Bb6  7.Nf3  Ne7  8.Bd3  a5  9.b5  Nd7  10.O-O  Ng6  11.Bb2  O-O  .   A position like this is really interesting to play, without a doubt. Black would try to undermine our e5-pawn with ...f7-f6, and take advantage of the weakened c5-square by playing ...Nc5, ...a5-a4, etc. We, instead, often try to push c2-c4, looking to recapture on c4 with the knight and then install it on d6. Interesting play, without a doubt, but not something I'd prefer. }
4... cxd4
{ Releasing the tension immediately is Black's best, safest, and easiest choice, since it prevents us from being able to capture on c5. }
5. Nxd4 Nc6
{ Now, the e5-pawn seems to be hanging. But, as we will soon find out, it's not true. So, we continue our plan of blowing up Black's center in order to open up the position and tremendously activate our pieces. }
6. c4 { Everything according to the plan. } 6... e6
{ Black must protect the d5-pawn. } 7. Nc3 Bb4
{ Black's best choice, pinning the knight. This way Black also decreases pressure on the d5-pawn. Then, Black just wants to go ...Nge7 and castle, finishing development. }
8. Nxc6
{ This knight trade isn't just a trade − it's an introduction to a forcing line, which leads to... an endgame! }
8... bxc6 9. Qa4
{ The black bishop is hanging, and so is the c6-pawn.   9.Bd3  is the less forcing move, which leads to more complex positions. If you don't like the objective equality of the main line, give it a shot! For example, after  9...Ne7  10.cxd5  Qxd5  11.O-O!?  is an interesting pawn sacrifice. The queen is now hanging, of course. But if Black were to retreat,  say with ...Qa5, we'd keep a large advantage by playing Qe2, f2-f4, Ne4, and so on. We'd have a much better pawn structure, and our pieces would be more active too. So, Black has to bite the bullet.    11...Qxe5  12.Re1  Qd6!  It's important for Black to retreat exactly here. Why so? Because White wants to attack with  moves like Qg4 or Qh5, and by retreating to d6, Black prevents that since the d3-bishop would be left hanging.  13.Qf3  O-O  14.Bf4  .  White's pieces are much more active. Next, we can play Be4, Qe4, maybe Rad1, Re3-g3/h3, and so on. We have a lot of compensation for the missing pawn, without a doubt! So, if you prefer messy positions, where the game cannot dry up too fast, explore this gambit! }
9... a5
{ Black hopes to keep the pin alive, which is why the bishop gets protected. Fair enough! }
10. cxd5
{ We immediately trade, taking advantage of the pinned c3-pawn. Black is forced to enter a pretty forcing line.   10.Qxc6+?  is a bad idea since after  10...Bd7  11.Qb7  d4!  , we run into a lot of threats. White isn't losing, by sheer miracle, but I don't want to be a part of this! }
10... Qxd5
{ A bit of tactical equilibristics. Black is taking advantage of the fact our knight is pinned, making a bold move. The queen not only ensures the safety of the c6-pawn, but it's also attacking the one on d5! Now, our queen looks a bit silly on a4, and we certainly don't want to feel forced to start defending.   10...exd5?  This time, we can just win a pawn!  11.Qxc6+  Bd7  −  the difference is that the d5-pawn is hanging too!  12.Qxd5±  and Black just lost material for no reason.   Black can also give up the bishop pair with  10...Bxc3+  , but after the simple  11.bxc3  Qxd5  12.Be3±  , we follow  up with f2-f4, Rd1, and get a dominant position without much effort. }
11. Qxb4
{ The queen is not that safe on d5, after all! By capturing the bishop, we unpin the knight and get ready to take the queen. }
11... axb4
{ 11...Qxe5+??  isn't a good intermediate move, as after  12.Qe4  , we keep the extra piece. }
12. Nxd5 exd5
{ Black must take this way in order to keep the queenside pawns connected. If we try Bd2, Black will simply protect the b4-pawn with ...c6-c5. This is the variation that GM Erwin L'Ami and IM Christof Sielecki recommended for Black in their Caro-Kann courses. Both courses are great, and the line is objectively very sound. I do believe Black should be doing okay here, but the problems certainly aren't over yet. And, this position has been seen in only 48 games so far, so it's not as though this 'solution' is well-known. }
13. Be3
{ The bishop is going to c5. This way, we achieve several things:  Get ready to attack the b4-pawn. Prevent Black from connecting the pawns with ...c6-c5. Prevent Black from castling. If Black blocks the a3-f8 diagonal with ...Ne7, Black won't be able to castle anyway since the knight would be left hanging. A very useful move, as you can see! }
13... f6
{ Black should immediately undermine the e5-pawn. This way, Black will either get rid of our main space-grabbing asset or will force us to play f2-f4, when Black can exchange a pair of pawns and claim the isolated e-pawn could wind up weak.   13...Ne7  is not as good since the knight loses the option of coming out to f6 after exf6 Nxf6.  14.f4  with a much better version of the positions in the main line in the text. }
14. f4 { We protect the pawn, of course. } 14... Bf5
{ Typically, Black would keep the tension and develop the bishop. This is the move Sielecki and L'Ami propose in their courses. }
15. Bc5 { Of course, we continue with our plan of attacking the b4-pawn. }
15... Kd7
{ Black gives it up, hoping to activate the kingside pieces quickly and get counterplay against the weak e5-pawn and on the a and b-files. As we saw in many other lines, the natural reaction of playing ...b4-b3 hardly ever turns out good in these positions, since White just plays a2-a4 and goes after the b3-pawn with Ra3 later on. }
16. Bxb4 fxe5 17. fxe5 Nh6
{ We cannot hold on to the e5-pawn, Black will get that one back. However, that's fine! }
18. a3
{ We are not only protecting the bishop, avoiding ...Rb8 with a tempo in the future, but we are also enabling the a-rook to move freely since it will be no longer tied up protecting the a2-pawn. }
18... Rhe8 { Black attacks the e5-pawn. It cannot be saved. } 19. Kd2
{ Time to get the king in action! Of course, there is no point in castling. In the endgame, the king can often safely be in the center. Here, it's certainly the case, since the d-file is closed. }
19... Rxe5 20. Be2
{ Objectively speaking, Black has enough activity to hold equality. However, I would still pick White for a very simple reason. We have the bishop pair and outside passed pawn! What does this mean? Typically, in positions with the bishop pair, you want to trade all the rooks.  Why so? Because the bishops are better at cutting off the opponent's king and controlling the entire board, than other minor pieces. As a result, once the rooks are gone, it's much easier for the side with the bishop pair to use their king as an active piece. Combine that with an outside passed a-pawn, and you will quickly see that if all the rooks come off, Black could easily land in a lost endgame!   So, while Black is okay, has to be careful, and we have a very clear plan − just trade the rooks off! But, objectively, this is Black's very best theoretical defense in the @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp2pppp/2p5/3pP3/3P4/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3...c5  4.Nf3  system. If Black knows this far, the positions should be okay − that's a fair outcome. But, very few games saw these variations, and those were mostly GM games or correspondence chess games. I wouldn't worry about your opponents being aware of this way of defending Black's position! }
