1. e4
{ Hi and welcome to this Quickstarter Guide! Here, we will be discussing the Sicilian, the French, and the Caro-Kann. Instead of looking at the very main lines, I preferred focusing on the most popular ones at the club level or the most instructive ones. As a result, after studying this chapter, you will be able to get a very good grasp of all the ideas and start playing this repertoire in no time! }
1... c5
{ This move initiates what we know as the Sicilian Defense, the queen of the @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  Black openings. Alongside  1.e4  e5  , it's one of the two most sound ways of meeting 1.e4  from the theoretical standpoint. Black is fighting for the center, the d4-square, without creating a symmetrical position. This opening is extremely popular with players who want sharp, creative and fighting chess, and those who don't want to settle for symmetry, less space, or any other concessions. }
2. Nf3
{ In this Lifetime Repertoire, I have decided to go for the most ambitious way of playing versus the Sicilian Defense − the so-called Open Sicilian. Why would I do that? Isn't this a positional repertoire, and isn't the Open Sicilian known to be sharp and principled? Well, here is the deal.  It's a Lifetime Repertoire. I want this course to carry a theoretical punch, which most sidelines cannot offer. I was considering the Alapin, 2.c3, as well, but decided to not go down that route, because the isolated pawn positions, which often arise there, aren't to everyone's taste.  Interestingly enough, in many sharp-looking positions, there is a path to simplifications, which means that with sufficient theoretical knowledge, we are playing risk-free. It's not possible to get an advantage in every single theoretical variation of the Sicilian as White, and maybe not even in most.  
What we are doing instead is something different. We are striving to test our opponent's knowledge of typical ideas and forcing lines, and if Black is prepared brilliantly, we accept the fact Black should be able to defend. However, we want to play risk-free, looking to get the better endgames or positions with pleasant positional pressure in the middlegame! }
2... g6
{ The so-called Hyper Accelerated Dragon. Black wants to keep the pawn on d7 for the time being, which is an important nuance: the option of playing ...d7-d5 remains open, thus discouraging White from ever going for the sharpest lines with queenside castling.   Another detail is that Black avoids the Rossolimo Variation, which arises after  2...Nc6  3.Bb5  ,  but allows for the Maroczy Bind @@StartBracket@@where White plays c2-c4@@EndBracket@@, and for the variation that I have chosen to suggest. }
3. d4 cxd4 4. Qxd4
{ This is one of the most principled lines versus the Hyper Accelerated Dragon, which requires Black to be knowledgeable and precise. Now, you might be surprised: am I not known for sidelines and practical choices? Why go for the main line, or one of those?  Well, here is what's interesting about chess. To people who are seeing some complex-looking line for the first time in their life, it might seem as though the positions are messy and unclear. However, especially as theory has gotten more advanced in recent years, people have understood that often forcing lines are simply a way to kill all the counterplay and get a pleasant endgame, for example.  Here, we would need to know a couple of specific sequences, sure. But the reward is endgames a pawn up or endgames with the bishop pair. These positions are NOT complex if we just know a few ideas, including the ones that allow us to simplify the game! Now, of course, Black's rook is hanging.   4.Nxd4  Nc6  5.c4  results in what is known as the  Maroczy Bind − a system with the pawns on c4 and e4.  For more details, see the relevant Informational. }
4... Nf6 5. Nc3
{ We just keep developing. The knight protects the e4-pawn now, and we are getting ready to play e4-e5.   After  5.e5?!  Nc6  6.Qa4  Nd5  ,  Black's knight can easily retreat to c7 if needed. Unfortunately, the e5-pawn will be attacked with ...Bg7 and undermined with ...d7-d6. It's currently restricting Black's pieces quite considerably, so it would be very advantageous for Black to undermine it and get rid of it. We shouldn't be allowing this to happen! }
5... Bg7 { An ignorant move order since it neglects our big threat. } 6. e5
{ Of course, we are immediately harassing the knight. } 6... Nc6 7. Qa4
{ The knight hardly has any squares. If it goes to h5, the move g2-g4 will trap and win it. There is no choice but to retreat all the way back to g8. }
7... Ng8 { The e5-pawn is hanging, but that's an easy problem to solve. } 8.
Bf4
{ White's task is very simple. As you can see, this gorgeous e5-pawn is restricting Black considerably. All we need to do is keep it safe and protected, thus preventing Black from unraveling and getting the pieces out to good squares.  Next, we'd love to castle queenside, maybe play h2-h3 to restrict the opponent even more and prevent any ...Ng4 or ...Bg4 ideas. Then, we'll develop the bishop to c4; maybe the queen can come over to the kingside, and eventually, our centralized pieces will find a way to break through. Here, Black would typically either try to prepare kingside castling with the awkward move ...Nh6, or undermine the powerful e5-pawn with ...f7-f6. }
8... Nh6
{ This move is the more popular one, but I consider it very suspicious on account of a lovely positional idea. }
9. h3
{ The knight can no longer go to g4. This is a huge problem because, at some point, a simple move like Qd2 or Qe3 would nearly trap it. Going to f5 isn't a solution due to g2-g4! }
9... O-O
{ The strongest Black player who ever got here is IM Padmini, who authored a book on the Hyper Accelerated Dragon. That must have been an experiment because Black's position is nearly lost. }
10. O-O-O
{ As you can see, the opponent cannot afford to play ...d7-d6 without dropping a pawn. The plan is to bring the queen back to the center with Qe4, then go g2-g4 to restrict the opponent's knight and threaten to trap with it Qe3. We can also develop the bishop to c4. Finally, perhaps the way to break through would be simply h3-h4-h5, obtaining a decisive initiative on the kingside, while the opponent is just watching. }
10... a6
{ It's logical to make this move, hoping to prepare ...b7-b5. But, Black still cannot go ...b7-b5, since the a6-pawn is pinned! We will just capture that pawn, since the a8-rook would be hanging at the end. }
11. g4
{ Time to restrict the black knight even more. Now, if we manage to play Qe4-e3, we will trap the h6-knight. }
11... Rb8 { Black is preparing ...b7-b5. } 12. Qe4 Kh8
{ Black needs to make room for the knight on g8.  12...b5  is a huge blunder, as after  13.Qe3!+-  ,  we win the h6-knight and the game. }
13. Qe3 Ng8 14. h4
{ With h4-h5 coming next, we obviously have not only a dominating position but also, a decisive kingside attack. Black still hasn't made a single active move and hasn't created a single threat! }
*

