1. e4
{ Hi and welcome to this Quickstarter Guide! Here, we will be discussing the Sicilian, the French, and the Caro-Kann. Instead of looking at the very main lines, I preferred focusing on the most popular ones at the club level or the most instructive ones. As a result, after studying this chapter, you will be able to get a very good grasp of all the ideas and start playing this repertoire in no time! }
1... c5
{ This move initiates what we know as the Sicilian Defense, the queen of the @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  Black openings. Alongside  1.e4  e5  , it's one of the two most sound ways of meeting 1.e4  from the theoretical standpoint. Black is fighting for the center, the d4-square, without creating a symmetrical position. This opening is extremely popular with players who want sharp, creative and fighting chess, and those who don't want to settle for symmetry, less space, or any other concessions. }
2. Nf3
{ In this Lifetime Repertoire, I have decided to go for the most ambitious way of playing versus the Sicilian Defense − the so-called Open Sicilian. Why would I do that? Isn't this a positional repertoire, and isn't the Open Sicilian known to be sharp and principled? Well, here is the deal.  It's a Lifetime Repertoire. I want this course to carry a theoretical punch, which most sidelines cannot offer. I was considering the Alapin, 2.c3, as well, but decided to not go down that route, because the isolated pawn positions, which often arise there, aren't to everyone's taste.  Interestingly enough, in many sharp-looking positions, there is a path to simplifications, which means that with sufficient theoretical knowledge, we are playing risk-free. It's not possible to get an advantage in every single theoretical variation of the Sicilian as White, and maybe not even in most.  
What we are doing instead is something different. We are striving to test our opponent's knowledge of typical ideas and forcing lines, and if Black is prepared brilliantly, we accept the fact Black should be able to defend. However, we want to play risk-free, looking to get the better endgames or positions with pleasant positional pressure in the middlegame! }
2... e6
{ This move is a very flexible one. Black is getting ready to develop the light-squared bishop. Later, Black can choose to set up the Hedgehog-style setup with ...a7-a6, ...b7-b6, ...d7-d6, etc, or play more ambitiously on the queenside with ...a7-a6 and ...b7-b5.  Black could consider meeting d2-d4 with ...cxd4 and then ...Bc5 or ...Bb4, trying to deploy the dark-squared bishop actively. In terms of variations, this move is used by people who play the Taimanov Variation, the Kan Variation, the Scheveningen Variation, and some others. But, we have a different idea in mind this time, instead of the Open Sicilian! }
3. c4
{ With this move, we are grabbing space in the center, looking to play d2-d4 at some point, and setting up the so-called Maroczy Bind structure, which we also encounter in the 2...d6 positions. In particular, we'd like to delay d2-d4 in order to wait for Black to play ...Be7, or ...d7-d6, so that once the center opens up, Black can never pin our c3-knight with ...Bb4, or at least would need to do that at a loss of a tempo.   At this point, Black can make more than one move. The main one by far is  3...Nc6  . Some players also went for  3...a6  or  3...d6  , but we'll cover those on move 4 − it will be the same thing! }
3... Nc6
{ Now, we are facing a choice: we can play d2-d4 right now, which isn't a bad move, but it sort of ignores the point I had just made in the comments to our third move, or keep delaying that pawn push. }
4. Nc3
{ This is our main choice. We are waiting for Black to commit to ...Be7 or ...d7-d6, which would motivate us to push d2-d4, getting a wonderful Maroczy Bind or Hedgehog-type position.   Here, Black mostly goes  4...Nf6  . However, a bunch of other moves have been tried as well, such as  4...a6  and  4...d6  , keeping the tension and getting ready for the Hedgehog-type play, or  4...Nd4  , which prevents  the d2-d4 ideas completely, or even  4...e5  , which does the same thing. We'll look at all those moves except  4...e5  , which we'll cover on the next turn − that'd be the same thing.   4.d4  is the alternative. Frankly, this move, especially when associated with the somewhat simplifying plan that we are about to see, is fairly interesting as well. For more information, see the relevant section. }
4... d6 { This move gets us a Hedgehog pawn structure. } 5. d4
{ Of course, we immediately open up the center, as Black can no longer go ...Bb4. }
5... cxd4 6. Nxd4
{ We are happy Black can no longer pin us. This means we can easily focus on developing our pieces and preserving our powerful center. }
6... Nf6 7. Be2
{ First, we'll finish development, and so will the opponent. In a few moves, once all the pieces came out, we'd discuss the plans. }
7... Be7 8. O-O O-O 9. Be3
{ Now that some basic development moves have been played, let's discuss the plans. White has a lot more space. Black, in the Hedgehog positions, typically strives to play ...a7-a6, ...b7-b6, ...Bb7, ...Nbd7, ...Qc7, ...Rac8 and ...Rfd8, harmoniously setting all the pieces on the last two files, and controlling the 5th rank with the pawns − that's why the opening is called this way, referring to the pawns on the 6th rank as the hedgehog's needles.  However, there is a problem, Black's knight is already on c6. This is bad, because of several reasons:  the b7-bishop would be blocked; the knight on d7 could protect the b6-pawn and the f6-knight, and on c6, it cannot; if Black places the queen on c7, with the knight on c6 would often run into the typical Rc1-Nd5! temporary knight sacrifice.   Black can make several moves here, such as  9...a6  ,  9...Bd7  , or  9...Nxd4  . I suggest we focus on the plans instead of worrying too much about the specific move orders. Another issue Black has is  that ...b7-b6 can't be played now or anytime soon, as that'd hang the knight. We can try to advance on the kingside with f2-f4, Qd2, Kh1, Rg1, g2-g4.  The more positional plan would be playing f2-f3, reinforcing the e4-pawn, and then a2-a3, b2-b4, and Nb3 obtaining a dominant position on the queenside. That's the plan I like better, as this repertoire is not about going crazy. :@@EndBracket@@ }
9... Nxd4 { It's logical for Black to trade a pair of knights. } 10. Bxd4 b6
{ Finally, Black can develop the bishop to the long diagonal. } 11. Qd3
{ The queen belongs here, as it helps defend the e-pawn, coordinate the rooks, and from d3, it is ready to slide to g3 or h3 at some point. }
11... Bb7 12. Rad1
{ We keep centralizing the pieces, of course. Next, we'd love to play f2-f4, grabbing space on the kingside, and then f4-f5, hoping to provoke ...e6-e5, which would create a hole on d5. }
12... a6
{ Black takes the b5-square under control, hoping to prepare ...b6-b5 at some point. }
13. Qg3 { The e4-pawn isn't hanging due to the threat of checkmate on g7. }
13... Rc8
{ Let's imagine the opponent keeps the tension, continuing to develop.  13...e5??  14.Bxe5  just loses Black a pawn. }
14. b3
{ We overprotect the c4-pawn. There is no rush! The kingside play will start when we want! Black is in a very passive and difficult situation, and cannot make any pawn break work. So, it's logical to go ...Qc7 and ...Rfd8, isn't it? }
14... Qc7
{ Now, we could start the aforementioned kingside play with f2-f4, or instead open up the center. }
15. e5
{ Black, surprisingly, cannot at all afford a situation when the center opens up. }
15... dxe5
{ 15...Ne8  16.Na4±  and, finally, the material gains  (the b6-pawn)  follow. We are already winning, a pawn up, and with the more active pieces. }
16. Bxe5 { The queen cannot go to c6 due to Bf3! winning a piece. } 16... Qc5
17. Na4 Qa5 18. Bc3
{ There is nothing better than  18...Qf5  and after  19.Rd7  , Black loses a piece and the game. Amazing! }
*

