6. exd5 exd5
{ Black is threatening to push ...d5-d4. Of course, we don't want to capture the pawn, getting an isolated d-pawn and helping Black activate the knight. }
7. d4
{ So, we need to push the central pawn. However, we are very happy to do so. Now, we have an absolutely symmetrical position, except we have an extra move Be2, which means we should have some initiative. Of course, we are ready to castle on the next turn. If the position starts opening up, the extra tempo will make a world of difference. Especially if we can play Re1+ quickly at some point, starting to harass the black king! }
7... Be7
{ Black can also choose to develop and keep the tension, maintaining symmetry in the center for the time being. }
8. Be3
{ We are threatening to capture the c5-pawn since now we control the d4-square, which means Black won't be able to meet dxc5 with ...d5-d4. }
8... cxd4 { So, Black needs to release the tension in the center. } 9. Nxd4
{ Black can choose between trading a pair of knights on d4 right away, or castling first. Likely, one variation will transpose into the other. }
9... O-O
{ 9...dxc4?  is, of course, bad, as now Black gets a bad pawn structure for no reason.  10.Nxc6  bxc6  11.Qxd8+  Bxd8  12.Bxc4⩲  with a long-lasting advantage due to Black's weak pawns. }
10. O-O
{ Both parties have made quite a few logical developing moves. Now, we'd like to capture on c6 and then on d5, creating an isolated pawn in Black's position. For that reason, Black needs to unload the center. }
10... Nxd4 11. Bxd4
{ We have a threat of capturing on d5, luring the knight on that square, and then winning a pawn with the familiar tactic Bxg7, taking advantage of the d5-knight's loose position. That's why an overwhelming majority of the Black players chose to capture on c4 right away, activating our other bishop but stopping that threat. }
11... dxc4 12. Bxc4
{ This position is extremely uncomfortable for Black, in my opinion. Next, we'd love to go Qa4, activating the queen. Don't worry, we are not hanging the d4-bishop − Black cannot take it due to a discovered attack on the queen with Bxf7+.  Then, we'll install the rooks on d1 and e1, and maybe will reroute our light-squared bishop to the h1-a8 diagonal with Be2-f3, putting pressure on the b7-pawn. As you can see, although the position is very symmetrical, we are clearly enjoying a pretty strong initiative because all of our pieces are a lot more active. }
12... Bg4
{ The vast majority of players have chosen this ambitious move, which immediately activates the bishop, trying to provoke a weakening move like f2-f3. }
13. Qa4
{ With this cute move, we not only activate the queen, potentially preparing ideas like Rfe1, maybe h2-h3, and Be2-f3, but we also create a tactical threat! See, that g4-bishop is loose? A bit loose − defended just by the f6-knight. See where I am going with this? We are threatening to play Bxf6, eliminating its defender, then Bxf7+, and then Qxg4, winning a pawn!   13.f3  has also been tried, but it weakens  the g1-a7 diagonal. The d4-bishop would be taken with check, for example. So I don't like this move. }
13... Bd7
{ Black can also try to place the bishop on c6, but it seems too slow and passive. }
14. Qb3
{ Now, the b7 and f7-pawns are under pressure, which means the bishop would be stuck on c6 and the f8-rook won't be able to move. We plan on getting the rooks on d1 and e1, making the e7-bishop and the d8-queen loose and uncomfortable. }
14... Bc6 15. Rad1 { Now, the x-ray with Bxf6 is about to win a piece. } 15...
Qa5 { Black should avoid that threat, of course. } 16. Rfe1
{ The bishop is loose, and Black cannot defend it with either rook from e8. Why so? ...Rfe8, obviously, is a blunder of the f7-pawn. The other rook move looks awkward, and also is a bad one for tactical reasons, but it's a bit less obvious why. }
16... Qb4
{ Seeking a queen trade is not illogical but doesn't exactly help Black reach full equality.  16...Rae8?  is bad due to  17.Bxf6!  Taking with the pawn is obviously horrible, so Black needs to take with the bishop.  17...Bxf6  18.Rxe8  .  Now, Black cannot take with the rook due to Bxf7+.  18...Bxe8  19.Qxb7  , Black lost a pawn, but seems to be doing fine, as another one can be regained right away, correct?   19...Bxc3  20.bxc3  Qxc3  21.Qa6!±  . I don't think so! With our last move,  we stop the a7-pawn from running away. Next, we'll play Bb3, placing the bishop on a safe and protected square, then h2-h3 to get an escape square, and will win the a7-pawn. Please note that all of Black's pieces are very passive. Not only the f8-rook but also the e8-bishop literally doesn't have a single move at the moment, so Black is nearly lost! }
17. Qxb4 Bxb4 18. a3
{ The bishop cannot go to e7, as we'd win it; the d6-square isn't available either due to Bxf6 followed by Rxd6. It doesn't make sense to go to a5 due to b2-b4 and b4-b5 winning a ton of time and space. So, Black seems forced to trade on c3. }
18... Bxc3
{ 18...Ba5?  19.b4!  Bb6  20.b5!  Bxd4  21.Rxd4±  is a disaster for Black as well. }
19. Bxc3
{ We have a large advantage due to the bishop pair in a very open position. Next, we'll go f2-f3, taking the e4 and g4-squares away from Black's minor pieces, and Kf2, improving the king. We'd love to swap off all the rooks, centralize the king, and get a winning minor piece endgame in no time! }
