{ This is Black's most popular move, and one of the best moves among the well-known ones. I am saying this because no one seems to know about the brilliant idea  5...f6!  While it looks really ugly, since Black voluntarily accepts a very bad pawn structure, Black can justify this decision with the next move, which happens to be very concrete. This move was recommended by GM Kotronias in his book on Anti-Sicilians published by Quality Chess in 2016. }
6. Nxe5 Qd5
{ This was the entire point of Black's last move. Having ruined the pawn structure, Black is winning a tempo by double-attacking the knight and the g2-pawn. }
7. Nf3 Qe4+
{ Fortunately for Black, another very precise and specific move is available. We still haven't had the time to castle, and Black takes advantage of that. We need to either give up castling rights or block the check with Qe2, losing the c2-pawn. }
8. Kf1
{ It's totally fine to give up the castling rights. Next, we'll play d2-d3, then Nbd2-c4, taking advantage of the outpost. Then, we'll develop the bishop to the long diagonal with b2-b3 and Bb2. After that, we'd love to play Qe2 and offer a queen trade. If we do trade the queens, the uncastled king won't be a problem. It could just sit on e2, or walk to h1-h2. If the queens don't get traded, then we can just walk the king to a safe spot, while also connecting the rooks with h2-h3 and Kg1-h2. }
8... Nf6
{ 8...Bg4  would just result in identical positions to the ones after 7...Bg4.  9.d3  Bxf3  10.Qxf3  Qxf3  11.gxf3⩲  with the same ideas. }
9. d3
{ We are happy to prepare Nbd2-c4, while also kicking out the queen with a tempo. }
9... Qf5 10. Nbd2 g6
{ It makes sense for Black to deploy the bishop on the long diagonal, as opposed to going ...e7-e6 and ...Be7. If Black chooses that path, the bishop on e7 would be passive, and the c8-bishop would end up locked in. }
11. b3
{ I think it's very useful to place the bishop on the long diagonal. Especially now, so that Black is not in time to go ...Bg7, move the knight and start harassing us on the a1-h8 diagonal before our bishop gets to b2. }
11... Bg7 12. Bb2 O-O 13. Qe2
{ This move is aimed at controlling the e4 and e5-squares, helping the a1-rook get in the game via e1... and something else! }
13... Re8
{ The e7-pawn was under attack, so it makes sense for Black to defend it. } 14.
Qe5
{ With this move, we are forcing a queen trade, because retreating would lose the c5-pawn. Once the queens are gone, our king's position is no longer a concern. We'll install the knight on c4, then go Ke2, or h2-h3, Kg1-h2, then Rfe1, and will start trading down, while also trying to attack Black's weak pawns with moves like Ba3, or Ne5, or Nc4-a5. Black has no counterplay, no active ideas, and weak pawns, so the position is very unpleasant. }
