[White "1) French − Sidelines"]
[Black "French Sidelines 3...Nc6 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6
{ This move, followed by ...d7-d5, defines something called the French Defense. This opening is about fighting for the center rather ambitiously while avoiding direct piece play. As you will see, the first two moves only feature pawn play. The downside for Black is the locked-up light-squared bishop, and very often, this piece tends to be a large issue for quite a long time. }
2. d4 d5
{ Here, we arrive at massive crossroads. White can lock up the center with e4-e5, take Black's pawn and open up the position, or defend the pawn with some knight move − either to c3 or to d2. }
3. Nc3
{ After a long thought, I decided to suggest this move, which is the most critical and ambitious one. Why did I do that and what's the point of this move? As we can see, we are simply protecting the e4-pawn while keeping the center flexible for now. It's important to do so for the following practical reason: most Black players who play the French @@StartBracket@@and I am one of them, I just wrote a course on French that I'm in love with!@@EndBracket@@ love positions with pawn chains. Our goal is to try to avoid creating one!  However, don't worry: while the move  3.Nc3  is known for being a very principled and theoretically heavy one, we won't need loads of theory − instead, I am opting for practical, easy-to-learn sidelines, which still carry quite a bit of punch, as always!  In this position, we'll need to consider quite a lot of moves. Black can try to pin the knight with  3...Bb4  , which is known as the Winawer Variation − the most forcing and sharp one. Black can also try to force us to lock up the center with the move  3...Nf6  , which is another major theoretical move. The passive yet solid decision is to play  3...dxe4  − the Rubinstein Variation. Black is hoping to avoid the pawn chain situation and trade down, liquidating White's hopes to get a spatial advantage or long-term pressure.  And, of course, there are quite a few sidelines, such as  3...Nc6  ,  3...Be7  − the move I suggested in my Black French course,  3...h6  ,  3...a6  , and so on. Let's tackle them all one by one! }
3... Nc6
{ This move is aimed at keeping tension in the center. Black wants to potentially prepare ...e6-e5. If we ever play e4-e5, Black would like to undermine that pawn with ...f7-f6, when the knight would help apply pressure on our center.   Perhaps the best move here is  4.e5  , but it leads to unnecessary complications. Instead, I think we should be happy to get a lovely and easy edge without memorizing anything. }
4. Nf3 { We keep developing, while also keeping the central tension. } 4... Bb4
{ This is an inferior version of both the Winawer @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/3PP3/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq d6 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Nc3  Bb4  and of this line after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/3PP3/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq d6 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Nc3  Nc6  4.e5  .   4...dxe4?!  5.Nxe4  just leads to an inferior version of the Rubinstein System with @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/3PP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq - 1 3@@EndFEN@@  3...dxe4  since Black's knight is misplaced  on c6 for multiple reasons.  Black cannot play ...c7-c5 anymore. Black cannot go ...Nbd7 to prepare ...Ngf6 and then recapture with the other knight. If Black ever goes ...b7-b6 and ...Bb7, the knight on c6 would be blocking that bishop on b7. }
5. e5
{ Typically, I'd rather not lock up the center. However, here it makes perfect sense to do so: the bishop on b4 would only be helpful if Black could try to ruin our queenside with ...c7-c5, ...Qa5, etc. But, since the c6-knight is blocking all of those plans and ideas, Black has no counterplay. Not having the bishop on the kingside means that part of the board has been weakened.  Of course, in this structure, when our central pawn chain  (the d4 and e5-pawns)  are aimed at Black's kingside, we'd love to develop an initiative there. We plan on doing so with moves like h2-h4 and Ng5 followed by Qh5, maybe Rh1-h3-g3. If you'd like to act in a more civilized and peaceful way, you could also proceed with Bd3, then maybe Qd2-f4. I don't think much analysis is needed here. }
5... Nge7 6. Bd3 Nf5
{ In most games, Black chose to play this way, looking to put pressure on the d4-pawn. No worries!   6...O-O??  was played in many games, but of course, it's a terrible blunder due to the standard tactical theme: the Greek Gift.  7.Bxh7+  Kxh7  8.Ng5+  Kg8  @@StartBracket@@  8...Kg6  9.h4  isn't better for Black,  as h4-h5 and Qg4 will guarantee a quick checkmate  too@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/ppp1npp1/2n1p3/3pP1N1/1b1P4/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQK2R w KQ - 2 9@@EndFEN@@  9.Qh5  and Qh7 is coming with checkmate. }
7. a3
{ I want to push the bishop away or force the opponent to give up the bishop pair. }
7... Be7 8. Ne2
{ Black's hopes to destroy or harass our center have totally failed. Next, we just build a kingside attack with h2-h4-h5, Rh3, g2-g4, Nf4, maybe Ng5-Qh5, and so on. Remember: in these structures, White dominates the kingside!  The only bad thing that can typically happen is that Black gets counterplay on the queenside. But here, Black does not have even the slightest bit of that, so you can easily concentrate laser-sharp focus on building your kingside play without having to get distracted on defense. This position is strategically winning for us because of these reasons. }
