2. d4 d5
{ Here, we arrive at massive crossroads. White can lock up the center with e4-e5, take Black's pawn and open up the position, or defend the pawn with some knight move − either to c3 or to d2. }
3. Nc3
{ After a long thought, I decided to suggest this move, which is the most critical and ambitious one. Why did I do that and what's the point of this move? As we can see, we are simply protecting the e4-pawn while keeping the center flexible for now. It's important to do so for the following practical reason: most Black players who play the French @@StartBracket@@and I am one of them, I just wrote a course on French that I'm in love with!@@EndBracket@@ love positions with pawn chains. Our goal is to try to avoid creating one!  However, don't worry: while the move  3.Nc3  is known for being a very principled and theoretically heavy one, we won't need loads of theory − instead, I am opting for practical, easy-to-learn sidelines, which still carry quite a bit of punch, as always!  In this position, we'll need to consider quite a lot of moves. Black can try to pin the knight with  3...Bb4  , which is known as the Winawer Variation − the most forcing and sharp one. Black can also try to force us to lock up the center with the move  3...Nf6  , which is another major theoretical move. The passive yet solid decision is to play  3...dxe4  − the Rubinstein Variation. Black is hoping to avoid the pawn chain situation and trade down, liquidating White's hopes to get a spatial advantage or long-term pressure.  And, of course, there are quite a few sidelines, such as  3...Nc6  ,  3...Be7  − the move I suggested in my Black French course,  3...h6  ,  3...a6  , and so on. Let's tackle them all one by one! }
3... Nc6
{ This move is aimed at keeping tension in the center. Black wants to potentially prepare ...e6-e5. If we ever play e4-e5, Black would like to undermine that pawn with ...f7-f6, when the knight would help apply pressure on our center.   Perhaps the best move here is  4.e5  , but it leads to unnecessary complications. Instead, I think we should be happy to get a lovely and easy edge without memorizing anything. }
4. Nf3 { We keep developing, while also keeping the central tension. } 4... Nf6
{ This is Black's main follow-up to 3...Nc6 by putting more pressure on the e4-pawn.   4...dxe4?!  5.Nxe4  just leads to an inferior version of the Rubinstein System with @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/3PP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq - 1 3@@EndFEN@@  3...dxe4  since Black's knight is misplaced  on c6 for multiple reasons.  Black cannot play ...c7-c5 anymore. Black cannot go ...Nbd7 to prepare ...Ngf6 and then recapture with the other knight. 3@@EndBracket@@If Black ever goes ...b7-b6 and ...Bb7, the knight on c6 would be blocking that bishop on b7. }
5. e5
{ Now, we lock up the center, taking advantage of the fact we won a tempo by attacking Black's knight, which makes the opponent too busy to undermine our pawns or create any counterplay. The knight typically retreats to the center, but it could also go back. }
5... Nd7
{ While it's a typical way to retreat in many French positions, here it does not make sense: the knight isn't supporting any counterplay, and since Black fails to trade pieces, will just end up in a very passive situation. }
6. Ne2
{ Please remember this absolutely crucial idea. We no longer need the knight on c3 − it only went there to protect the e4-pawn in the past, but that's no longer a responsibility. Now, it's coming over to f4 or g3 to help us build the kingside attack... plus, we are making the idea of c2-c3, protecting the d4-pawn even more, possible. The only hope for counterplay that Black could ever have here is based on undermining our center with ...f7-f6 so Black should try to make this work right away. }
6... f6
{ In this position, which occurred in only 16 games so far, for some reason, most players captured Black's pawn, giving up the center and helping develop the queen rapidly. Instead, it's much better to keep our knight journey, which is what the strongest player who faced this line  (the Russian young talent Volodar Murzin)  went on to play. }
7. Nf4 { The e6-pawn is under attack and it's unaffordable to lose it. } 7...
Qe7
{ The queen is placed fairly awkwardly here − how will the f8-bishop come out? }
8. exf6
{ Now, if the queen captures on f6, Black would be a tempo down compared to the situation when we'd take on f6 immediately instead of our last knight move. }
8... Qxf6
{ But, that's exactly what Black @@StartBracket@@a strong Ukrainian GM from the world top 100!@@EndBracket@@ did. White played a logical developing move  9.Bd3  ,  was better, but eventually lost. However, I'd like to recommend a different  (brand-new!)  way of developing our pieces. 0-1 Murzin-Kuzubov, chess.com 2020. }
9. g3
{ The bishop can come either to g2, in order to make our king even safer, or even to h3, in order to attack the e6-pawn. In this position, Black has long-term static problems: a weak e6-pawn, a bad c8-bishop, and we enjoy the outpost on e5. If that's the case, we don't need to rush, try to checkmate, or feel pressured in any way. Instead, all we need to do is develop comfortably and enjoy the better middlegame.  Please note they cannot easily free up the position with the ...e6-e5 break, as our f4-knight is placed very conveniently, attacking the d5-pawn as well, which means ...e6-e5 would blunder the d5-pawn. }
9... Bd6 10. Bg2 O-O 11. O-O
{ Black has no counterplay. Next, we'd like to play c2-c3 to overprotect the d4-pawn, then Re1 to attack the e6-pawn and discourage the ...e6-e5 break even more, then Nd3 to grab the e5-square under more control, and then Bf4 to trade Black's good bishop. The position is just awful for our opponent. }
