3. Nc3
{ After a long thought, I decided to suggest this move, which is the most critical and ambitious one. Why did I do that and what's the point of this move? As we can see, we are simply protecting the e4-pawn while keeping the center flexible for now. It's important to do so for the following practical reason: most Black players who play the French @@StartBracket@@and I am one of them, I just wrote a course on French that I'm in love with!@@EndBracket@@ love positions with pawn chains. Our goal is to try to avoid creating one!  However, don't worry: while the move  3.Nc3  is known for being a very principled and theoretically heavy one, we won't need loads of theory − instead, I am opting for practical, easy-to-learn sidelines, which still carry quite a bit of punch, as always!  In this position, we'll need to consider quite a lot of moves. Black can try to pin the knight with  3...Bb4  , which is known as the Winawer Variation − the most forcing and sharp one. Black can also try to force us to lock up the center with the move  3...Nf6  , which is another major theoretical move. The passive yet solid decision is to play  3...dxe4  − the Rubinstein Variation. Black is hoping to avoid the pawn chain situation and trade down, liquidating White's hopes to get a spatial advantage or long-term pressure.  And, of course, there are quite a few sidelines, such as  3...Nc6  ,  3...Be7  − the move I suggested in my Black French course,  3...h6  ,  3...a6  , and so on. Let's tackle them all one by one! }
3... Nc6
{ This move is aimed at keeping tension in the center. Black wants to potentially prepare ...e6-e5. If we ever play e4-e5, Black would like to undermine that pawn with ...f7-f6, when the knight would help apply pressure on our center.   Perhaps the best move here is  4.e5  , but it leads to unnecessary complications. Instead, I think we should be happy to get a lovely and easy edge without memorizing anything. }
4. Nf3 { We keep developing, while also keeping the central tension. } 4... Nf6
{ This is Black's main follow-up to 3...Nc6 by putting more pressure on the e4-pawn.   4...dxe4?!  5.Nxe4  just leads to an inferior version of the Rubinstein System with @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/3PP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq - 1 3@@EndFEN@@  3...dxe4  since Black's knight is misplaced  on c6 for multiple reasons.  Black cannot play ...c7-c5 anymore. Black cannot go ...Nbd7 to prepare ...Ngf6 and then recapture with the other knight. 3@@EndBracket@@If Black ever goes ...b7-b6 and ...Bb7, the knight on c6 would be blocking that bishop on b7. }
5. e5
{ Now, we lock up the center, taking advantage of the fact we won a tempo by attacking Black's knight, which makes the opponent too busy to undermine our pawns or create any counterplay. The knight typically retreats to the center, but it could also go back. }
5... Ne4
{ Black is hoping to trade a pair of knights, which would considerably simplify life, as the main problem is lack of space and trading would solve that. }
6. Ne2
{ This is an important idea to remember! We have no desire whatsoever to trade pieces here. The knight is going to f4 to pressure the e6-pawn, discouraging the ...f7-f6 pawn break, or maybe to jump to h5 and help us get an attack on the black king. At some point, we could consider ignoring what I said earlier by playing Ng3 − yes, we don't want to trade, but that trade would open the h-file for our rook and thus be favorable. }
6... f6
{ Black absolutely must try to break up our center right away, taking advantage of the fact the knight on e2 is kind of clumsy − our development isn't the best at the moment, so we cannot punish Black directly. }
7. Ng3
{ Okay, now we offer a trade. Again, it would be a huge mistake for Black to take, as our h1-rook would be so happy that the opponent would get overwhelmed enough by that happiness to just resign. }
7... fxe5
{ Black would almost always take this pawn, getting rid at least of a part of our center.   7...Nxg3?  8.hxg3  fxe5  9.dxe5  .  Next, we play Bd3, Ng5, Qh5 and soon the game ends in a checkmate − Black's kingside/king has no defenders whatsoever. }
8. dxe5
{ Now, however, Black has an issue: we are about to take the knight on e4 and spoil the structure, creating weak doubled e-pawns. Taking on g3 is bad, as it opens the h-file for our rook, but the knight doesn't have too many places to retreat, either. }
8... Nc5
{ This does solve the problem of Nxe4 coming up, but misplaces the knight even more. }
9. Bb5
{ Of course, it was the most active and logical square to place the bishop − the regular d3 wasn't available as Black's knight would have taken it. We can play Nd4 at some point, putting more pressure on the c6-knight. }
9... Bd7 { Black chooses to unpin the knight. } 10. O-O Be7
{ For now, both parties continue developing. } 11. Bxc6
{ We don't need the bishop. We're happy to give it up to either double Black's pawns or distract the bishops. }
11... Bxc6 12. Nd4
{ Winning more time. Now, there is a threat of grabbing the e6-pawn with b2-b4!, distracting the only defender. Also, the kingside is weak, which means there are ideas coming like Qg4-h5, f2-f4-f5, etc. }
12... Bd7 13. Qf3
{ Castling is not possible − it's not obvious at all what Black should be doing, while we can threaten the kingside with Nh5 on the next turn, provoke a weakening move like ...g7-g6, then follow up with Bh6 at some point, maybe Qg4, and so on. White is just running a free attack at no cost; no sacrifices were required, and no positional concessions. This is awful for the opponent. }
