{ Black absolutely must try to break up our center right away, taking advantage of the fact the knight on e2 is kind of clumsy − our development isn't the best at the moment, so we cannot punish Black directly. }
7. Ng3
{ Okay, now we offer a trade. Again, it would be a huge mistake for Black to take, as our h1-rook would be so happy that the opponent would get overwhelmed enough by that happiness to just resign. }
7... fxe5
{ Black would almost always take this pawn, getting rid at least of a part of our center.   7...Nxg3?  8.hxg3  fxe5  9.dxe5  .  Next, we play Bd3, Ng5, Qh5 and soon the game ends in a checkmate − Black's kingside/king has no defenders whatsoever. }
8. dxe5
{ Now, however, Black has an issue: we are about to take the knight on e4 and spoil the structure, creating weak doubled e-pawns. Taking on g3 is bad, as it opens the h-file for our rook, but the knight doesn't have too many places to retreat, either. }
8... Be7
{ After this move, we won't take the knight. As tempting as it is to spoil Black's pawn structure, our knight would love to retreat to g5, but it's hard at the moment. }
9. c3
{ I like this little move − we take the d4-square under more control. There is another, much more subtle idea: to play Bd3 and meet ...Nc5 with Bc2!, keeping the bishop on the best diagonal it could possibly be  (b1-h7)  to keep the options of attacking the opponent's king. }
9... O-O 10. Bd3
{ The knight is under pressure, it doesn't have too many options! Of course, taking on g3, opening up the h-file for the rook, is suicide. }
10... Nc5 11. Bc2
{ We enjoy a spatial advantage, perfect control over the center, a semi-outpost on d4, and chances to build a kingside attack, while Black has no counterplay. I use the weird term I just made up, 'semi-outpost', because technically speaking, Black could kick our knight out from d4 with ...c7-c5, but practically, the c7-pawn is blocked, so that doesn't seem to be a real possibility.  Next, we'll castle, play Nd4, f2-f4, Qg4, f4-f5, and will take over the kingside, while Black just watches − where is the counterplay? }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1) French − Sidelines"]
[Black "French Sidelines 3...a6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6
{ This move, followed by ...d7-d5, defines something called the French Defense. This opening is about fighting for the center rather ambitiously while avoiding direct piece play. As you will see, the first two moves only feature pawn play. The downside for Black is the locked-up light-squared bishop, and very often, this piece tends to be a large issue for quite a long time. }
2. d4 d5
{ Here, we arrive at massive crossroads. White can lock up the center with e4-e5, take Black's pawn and open up the position, or defend the pawn with some knight move − either to c3 or to d2. }
3. Nc3
{ After a long thought, I decided to suggest this move, which is the most critical and ambitious one. Why did I do that and what's the point of this move? As we can see, we are simply protecting the e4-pawn while keeping the center flexible for now. It's important to do so for the following practical reason: most Black players who play the French @@StartBracket@@and I am one of them, I just wrote a course on French that I'm in love with!@@EndBracket@@ love positions with pawn chains. Our goal is to try to avoid creating one!  However, don't worry: while the move  3.Nc3  is known for being a very principled and theoretically heavy one, we won't need loads of theory − instead, I am opting for practical, easy-to-learn sidelines, which still carry quite a bit of punch, as always!  In this position, we'll need to consider quite a lot of moves. Black can try to pin the knight with  3...Bb4  , which is known as the Winawer Variation − the most forcing and sharp one. Black can also try to force us to lock up the center with the move  3...Nf6  , which is another major theoretical move. The passive yet solid decision is to play  3...dxe4  − the Rubinstein Variation. Black is hoping to avoid the pawn chain situation and trade down, liquidating White's hopes to get a spatial advantage or long-term pressure.  And, of course, there are quite a few sidelines, such as  3...Nc6  ,  3...Be7  − the move I suggested in my Black French course,  3...h6  ,  3...a6  , and so on. Let's tackle them all one by one! }
3... a6
{ This is a fairly popular way to play versus @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/3PP3/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq d6 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Nd2  , but I don't see it making much sense versus  3.Nc3  . Black is trying to make a waiting move, hoping we commit to some decision like @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/1pp2ppp/p3p3/3p4/3PP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.e5  , locking up the center and letting Black try to destroy it with  4...c5  , or to @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/1pp2ppp/p3p3/3p4/3PP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.Nf3  ,  when f2-f4 is no longer possible and it could be hard to reinforce the center at times.  However, we can just continue our development. I don't mind playing the most popular continuation  4.Nf3  , but it seems even more beneficial to hold off with that move and keep the option of developing  the horsey to e2 open. }
4. Bd3 Nf6 { This is a classic positional mistake. } 5. e5 Nfd7 6. Nce2
{ We achieve an absolute dream scenario, where ...c7-c5 can be easily met with c2-c3, while ...f7-f6 can be dealt with by means of f2-f4. Next, we'll proceed with f2-f4, Nf3, O-O, and just crush Black on the kingside with f4-f5, Ng5, Qh5, etc. Easy and effective! }
