3. Nc3
{ After a long thought, I decided to suggest this move, which is the most critical and ambitious one. Why did I do that and what's the point of this move? As we can see, we are simply protecting the e4-pawn while keeping the center flexible for now. It's important to do so for the following practical reason: most Black players who play the French @@StartBracket@@and I am one of them, I just wrote a course on French that I'm in love with!@@EndBracket@@ love positions with pawn chains. Our goal is to try to avoid creating one!  However, don't worry: while the move  3.Nc3  is known for being a very principled and theoretically heavy one, we won't need loads of theory − instead, I am opting for practical, easy-to-learn sidelines, which still carry quite a bit of punch, as always!  In this position, we'll need to consider quite a lot of moves. Black can try to pin the knight with  3...Bb4  , which is known as the Winawer Variation − the most forcing and sharp one. Black can also try to force us to lock up the center with the move  3...Nf6  , which is another major theoretical move. The passive yet solid decision is to play  3...dxe4  − the Rubinstein Variation. Black is hoping to avoid the pawn chain situation and trade down, liquidating White's hopes to get a spatial advantage or long-term pressure.  And, of course, there are quite a few sidelines, such as  3...Nc6  ,  3...Be7  − the move I suggested in my Black French course,  3...h6  ,  3...a6  , and so on. Let's tackle them all one by one! }
3... a6
{ This is a fairly popular way to play versus @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/3PP3/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq d6 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Nd2  , but I don't see it making much sense versus  3.Nc3  . Black is trying to make a waiting move, hoping we commit to some decision like @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/1pp2ppp/p3p3/3p4/3PP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.e5  , locking up the center and letting Black try to destroy it with  4...c5  , or to @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/1pp2ppp/p3p3/3p4/3PP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.Nf3  ,  when f2-f4 is no longer possible and it could be hard to reinforce the center at times.  However, we can just continue our development. I don't mind playing the most popular continuation  4.Nf3  , but it seems even more beneficial to hold off with that move and keep the option of developing  the horsey to e2 open. }
4. Bd3 c5
{ This leads to positions similar to @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/3PP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq - 1 3@@EndFEN@@  3...c5  . In other words, it doesn't work. }
5. dxc5 Bxc5 6. exd5 exd5 7. Nxd5
{ An uncomfortable nuance: Black doesn't get to play a standard IQP position. }
7... Bxf2+
{ Black is forced to play this way in order to be able to control the b5-square with the queen.  7...Qxd5??  8.Bb5+  axb5  9.Qxd5  isn't acceptable, of course. }
8. Kxf2 Qxd5 9. Qf3
{ I love this move. It's not the most aggressive one, but it's simple and really good. We force an endgame where we have the bishop pair and superior development. }
9... Qxf3+ 10. Nxf3
{ We have a huge advantage in the endgame due to the bishop pair and superior development. It looks like no further investigation is needed − just play Re1+, maybe Ng5 or Nd4, Bf4 or b2-b3, and Bb2 and destroy the opponent! }
