3... Be7
{ This is a very rare move that I am really passionate about − passionate enough to recommend it in my Black course! The idea is to wait for White to commit to playing e4-e5 and then blow up the center with ...c7-c5, claiming the opponent won't have the time to back it up on time with f2-f4 and Nf3.   I have a lot of faith in this line, especially considering it cuts the amount of theory Black needs to learn but about 10-20 times less compared to the main lines with  3...Bb4  and  3...Nf6  . However, White does have a way to cause problems without learning a ton of @@StartFEN@@rnbqk1nr/ppp1bppp/4p3/3p4/3PP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 2 4@@EndFEN@@  4.e5  related theory here. Let's explore how! }
4. Bd3
{ I think this move is a lot more practical. Why dive into complications versus a sideline? For now, we are just developing pieces. }
4... Nc6
{ This move has been played most often, but in my opinion, it doesn't align at all with the philosophy behind 3...Be7, which is to blow up White's center with ...c7-c5. }
5. Nf3
{ Since there are no threats, we just keep developing. It's worth mentioning we are interested in being a little careful to make sure ...e6-e5  (one of the few good things the move ...Nc6 might enable)  doesn't happen, which is why the knight always belongs on f3, never on e2. }
5... Nf6 { A bad version of any French position. } 6. e5 Nd7 7. a3
{ Black fails to get counterplay versus our center. With our last move, we've prevented ...Nb4, which would harass and misplace our precious light-squared bishop, and now we are ready to proceed with the standard Ne2 idea, rerouting the knight somewhere to the kingside after Nf4-h5, or Ng3-h5, and so on.  It's always worth remembering that Ne2! is very appealing as it unblocks the c-pawn, which means ...c7-c5 at any moment in the future can be met with c2-c3!, reinforcing the center. Since Black failed to trade pieces, improve the light-squared bishop, or put any pressure on our center, the opening play can be clearly deemed a failure. }
