3... Be7
{ This is a very rare move that I am really passionate about − passionate enough to recommend it in my Black course! The idea is to wait for White to commit to playing e4-e5 and then blow up the center with ...c7-c5, claiming the opponent won't have the time to back it up on time with f2-f4 and Nf3.   I have a lot of faith in this line, especially considering it cuts the amount of theory Black needs to learn but about 10-20 times less compared to the main lines with  3...Bb4  and  3...Nf6  . However, White does have a way to cause problems without learning a ton of @@StartFEN@@rnbqk1nr/ppp1bppp/4p3/3p4/3PP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 2 4@@EndFEN@@  4.e5  related theory here. Let's explore how! }
4. Bd3
{ I think this move is a lot more practical. Why dive into complications versus a sideline? For now, we are just developing pieces. }
4... Nc6
{ This move has been played most often, but in my opinion, it doesn't align at all with the philosophy behind 3...Be7, which is to blow up White's center with ...c7-c5. }
5. Nf3
{ Since there are no threats, we just keep developing. It's worth mentioning we are interested in being a little careful to make sure ...e6-e5  (one of the few good things the move ...Nc6 might enable)  doesn't happen, which is why the knight always belongs on f3, never on e2. }
5... Nb4
{ If you ever play this line with Black, this is the way to go. Why so? Well, at least Black is distracting our bishop from its current active position on the b1-h7 diagonal, where it was hoping to make itself useful for the kingside attack after the upcoming e4-e5. }
6. Be2
{ No worries, we just retreat. And it turns out the line doesn't have much of an independent meaning: you either play ...Nf6 as Black, getting an extremely poor version of a standard French position where ...c7-c5 hasn't arrived on time, or take on e4 and get a poor version of the Rubinstein. }
6... dxe4 7. Nxe4 Nf6
{ Black tries to trade a pair of pieces to decrease the number of problems related to lack of space. }
8. Nxf6+
{ That's fine, we are happy to trade. It's worth knowing that in the Rubinstein positions, the black KNIGHT wants to land on f6, not the bishop. That's why you usually see Black play ...Nbd7, and only then ...Ngf6, to recapture on f6 with the queenside knight. Why is that the case? A few reasons:  The knight on f6 helps prevent the potential kingside attack by safeguarding the h7-pawn and taking the h5 and g4-squares away from the white queen and other pieces.  The bishop is needed on e7, or at least on d6 in order to support the typical ...c7-c5 break, which is something really important for Black to carry out in order to decrease the spatial disadvantage and get rid of White's impressive center. }
8... Bxf6 9. c3 { It's nice to kick the knight out. } 9... Nd5
{ It feels odd to award this obvious move with an exclamation mark, but that was kind of a point of Black's ...Nb4 idea. Black wanted the knight to eventually end up in the center. }
10. O-O O-O 11. Bd3
{ However, Black still ends up in a very passive position, in my opinion. Black failed to play ...e6-e5 or ...c7-c5, the light-squared bishop is still a problem, there is still no counterplay, and we have the standard spatial advantage. Next, we'll proceed with Qe2-e4, trying to provoke weaknesses on the kingside. }
