[White "1) French − Sidelines"]
[Black "French Sidelines 3...Be7 #5"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6
{ This move, followed by ...d7-d5, defines something called the French Defense. This opening is about fighting for the center rather ambitiously while avoiding direct piece play. As you will see, the first two moves only feature pawn play. The downside for Black is the locked-up light-squared bishop, and very often, this piece tends to be a large issue for quite a long time. }
2. d4 d5
{ Here, we arrive at massive crossroads. White can lock up the center with e4-e5, take Black's pawn and open up the position, or defend the pawn with some knight move − either to c3 or to d2. }
3. Nc3
{ After a long thought, I decided to suggest this move, which is the most critical and ambitious one. Why did I do that and what's the point of this move? As we can see, we are simply protecting the e4-pawn while keeping the center flexible for now. It's important to do so for the following practical reason: most Black players who play the French @@StartBracket@@and I am one of them, I just wrote a course on French that I'm in love with!@@EndBracket@@ love positions with pawn chains. Our goal is to try to avoid creating one!  However, don't worry: while the move  3.Nc3  is known for being a very principled and theoretically heavy one, we won't need loads of theory − instead, I am opting for practical, easy-to-learn sidelines, which still carry quite a bit of punch, as always!  In this position, we'll need to consider quite a lot of moves. Black can try to pin the knight with  3...Bb4  , which is known as the Winawer Variation − the most forcing and sharp one. Black can also try to force us to lock up the center with the move  3...Nf6  , which is another major theoretical move. The passive yet solid decision is to play  3...dxe4  − the Rubinstein Variation. Black is hoping to avoid the pawn chain situation and trade down, liquidating White's hopes to get a spatial advantage or long-term pressure.  And, of course, there are quite a few sidelines, such as  3...Nc6  ,  3...Be7  − the move I suggested in my Black French course,  3...h6  ,  3...a6  , and so on. Let's tackle them all one by one! }
3... Be7
{ This is a very rare move that I am really passionate about − passionate enough to recommend it in my Black course! The idea is to wait for White to commit to playing e4-e5 and then blow up the center with ...c7-c5, claiming the opponent won't have the time to back it up on time with f2-f4 and Nf3.   I have a lot of faith in this line, especially considering it cuts the amount of theory Black needs to learn but about 10-20 times less compared to the main lines with  3...Bb4  and  3...Nf6  . However, White does have a way to cause problems without learning a ton of @@StartFEN@@rnbqk1nr/ppp1bppp/4p3/3p4/3PP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 2 4@@EndFEN@@  4.e5  related theory here. Let's explore how! }
4. Bd3
{ I think this move is a lot more practical. Why dive into complications versus a sideline? For now, we are just developing pieces. }
4... c5
{ I think this continuation is the only one that is in the spirit of the 3...Be7 line. Black is looking to ruin the center, showing the willingness to play with an isolated queen's pawn. This position is already rare enough, only 36 games have been ever played. }
5. exd5 exd5
{ 5...cxd4?  is a bad idea, as after  6.Bb5+  Bd7  7.Qxd4+-  , White just ends up a pawn up for no compensation whatsoever. }
6. dxc5
{ We are creating a guaranteed isolated queen's pawn for the opponent − a structure known for offering active play in the middlegame as long as pieces stay on the board. But if they don't, Black gets a very bad endgame where the pawn will be weak, as it cannot be protected by any other pawns, so our goal is to trade down! }
6... Nf6
{ Black just keeps developing by protecting the d5-pawn and getting ready to take on c5 soon.  6...Bxc5?  7.Bb5+  Bd7  8.Qxd5  just wins us a pawn and gives us a completely winning position. }
7. Nf3
{ This is the first subtle point, which I explain from Black's perspective in the French course. Black is getting an IQP and should be interested in keeping a lot of pieces on the board. That's why taking on c5 with the bishop isn't a great idea: you run into trades or tactics. }
7... Bxc5 { A bad idea. } 8. Qe2+
{ Now, Black has to either passively retreat with  8...Be7  , which is certainly going against the goals in an IQP position, or self-pin on the e-file with  8...Be6  and give up the bishop pair after Ng5.  Instead,  8...Qe7  is bad, because once the queens are gone, so is all the dynamic play, and Black just gets a very passive endgame. }
8... Be6 9. Ng5 Qe7
{ The only game that reached this position saw Black defend the bishop this way, and White just castled. That was a decent decision, but instead, I'd like to recommend a different continuation. }
10. Nxe6 { We immediately grab the bishop pair. } 10... fxe6
{ Of course, Black wants to keep the queens on the board. } 11. Bd2
{ We are getting ready to castle queenside! } 11... O-O 12. O-O-O
{ Both parties have gotten their kings to safety. } 12... Nc6
{ This is a great spot for the knight. From here, it can control the d4 and e5-squares, and possibly assist Black with some active pawn pushes like ...e6-e5 in the future. }
13. Rhe1
{ Black cannot play ...e6-e5, and next, we'll proceed with f2-f4, fixing the weak e6-pawn in its place. }
13... Rae8
{ 13...e5?  looks natural, but loses to  14.Nxd5!  Nxd5  15.Bc4  . The pinned knight won't have a good destiny. Following  15...Rad8  16.Qe4  , the knight falls and White gets a winning position because of the bishop pair, better structure, and the fact the black king's shelter got weakened. }
14. f4
{ The e5-square is now under control. We have the bishop pair and can prepare slow but certain advancement on the kingside with h2-h3 and g2-g4. It's not going to turn into a mating attack or anything like that anytime soon, but we just have a clear positional advantage due to the bishop pair and weakness on e6.  The fact that kings are castled on opposite sides is not very relevant here in a known way. What I mean by that is that, typically, people think opposite-side castling positions tend to be very sharp. But here, there won't be much of an attack. Instead, we just castled queenside in order to easily advance the kingside pawns and push Black further back. }
