4. Bd3
{ I think this move is a lot more practical. Why dive into complications versus a sideline? For now, we are just developing pieces. }
4... c5
{ I think this continuation is the only one that is in the spirit of the 3...Be7 line. Black is looking to ruin the center, showing the willingness to play with an isolated queen's pawn. This position is already rare enough, only 36 games have been ever played. }
5. exd5 exd5
{ 5...cxd4?  is a bad idea, as after  6.Bb5+  Bd7  7.Qxd4+-  , White just ends up a pawn up for no compensation whatsoever. }
6. dxc5
{ We are creating a guaranteed isolated queen's pawn for the opponent − a structure known for offering active play in the middlegame as long as pieces stay on the board. But if they don't, Black gets a very bad endgame where the pawn will be weak, as it cannot be protected by any other pawns, so our goal is to trade down! }
6... Nf6
{ Black just keeps developing by protecting the d5-pawn and getting ready to take on c5 soon.  6...Bxc5?  7.Bb5+  Bd7  8.Qxd5  just wins us a pawn and gives us a completely winning position. }
7. Nf3
{ This is the first subtle point, which I explain from Black's perspective in the French course. Black is getting an IQP and should be interested in keeping a lot of pieces on the board. That's why taking on c5 with the bishop isn't a great idea: you run into trades or tactics. }
7... O-O 8. O-O
{ Now, Black has two options, which are equally popular: either recapture on c5 with the bishop or play ...Nbd7 and take the pawn with the knight a move later. In my opinion, it's more reasonable to do the latter, which is exactly the recommendation I am going for in my Black course. What's the reasoning?  Well, I think the knight is very active on c5 as it controls the d3 and e4-squares. The bishop could be really active on c5 as well, especially in conjugation with ...Qb6 and ...Ne4, since the f2-pawn could be pressured rather easily. But I prefer the knight recapture because it discourages the Bg5-pin-related ideas. Also, once we have played ...Nbd7-c5-e4, the ...Bc5 move can still always come. So that's the reasoning for Black.  But we are White! So, what are we doing? For one, we still want to simply trade all the pieces. Also, it's not a typical IQP position, because most IQP positions see White have a pawn on e3 instead of c2. That means the f2-square is a lot weaker, so you need to be paying attention. However, the upside for us is that the e-file is open, which means a few things.  It's easier to trade pieces on it. There could be tactical issues related to the Rxe7! idea at some point when the bishop is on g5 because then Nxd5 might follow. But we'll see more of that later, don't worry yet! }
8... Bxc5
{ I like this move less for Black, as I explained above, but it's been very frequently used by the main proponent of the 3...Be7 variation, the Russian GM Demidov, who used it to draw Caruana, among others. }
9. Bg5
{ It seems very logical to develop the bishop to the most active square possible, pinning the knight and creating ideas of taking it, and then winning the d5-pawn. }
9... Be6
{ Black would normally defend the pawn, while also developing the pieces. } 10.
Qd2
{ Caruana chose  10.h3  instead, but I like this move better. We are connecting the rooks,  preparing to play Rad1 or maybe even Rae1, in order to not only control the e-file but also keep the f-rook on f1 to protect the f2-pawn! Then, Re2-Rfe1 could be a reasonable improvement plan. @@StartBracket@@Naturally, if that's what you want, then either rook's move to e1 should be fine@@EndBracket@@.  Another plan here would incude a2-a3 and b2-b4, grabbing space on the queenside while also pushing the bishop away, and Ne2-d4, starting to enjoy the outpost and blocking the c5-bishop. It's also worth pointing out another idea. It likely won't matter for a while but is good to keep in mind. Having a queen on d2 is good because at some point  (not yet!)  the move ...h7-h6 can be met with Bxh6!, when we'd get a decisive mating attack. }
10... Nc6
{ Most people developed the knight here, instead of c6, hoping to keep it placed more actively. From c6, the knight controls the d4-square and the one on b4 as well, potentially also allowing Black to push ...d5-d4 if that is beneficial. }
11. Rad1
{ We get another piece in the game, pointing out the d5-pawn might end up under some noticeable pressure. }
11... Be7
{ Normally, Black would play this move to unpin, which seems fairly logical. However, that wouldn't yield a lot of counterplay, which is exactly what you should be striving for with an IQP: a long-term weakness. }
12. Rfe1 { The last piece comes in the game. } 12... Re8
{ Black also places the rook on the open e-file. } 13. Nb5
{ Next, the knight will come to d4. I would love to trade a pair of knights and then restrict Black even further with the moves c2-c3 and f2-f3! − pay particular attention to the latter move, which takes away the e4 and g4-squares. While our advantage is by no means large, it was pretty easy to get here without memorizing anything, and White is definitely pressing in a typical position without incurring any risk. }
