{ Now, Black has two options, which are equally popular: either recapture on c5 with the bishop or play ...Nbd7 and take the pawn with the knight a move later. In my opinion, it's more reasonable to do the latter, which is exactly the recommendation I am going for in my Black course. What's the reasoning?  Well, I think the knight is very active on c5 as it controls the d3 and e4-squares. The bishop could be really active on c5 as well, especially in conjugation with ...Qb6 and ...Ne4, since the f2-pawn could be pressured rather easily. But I prefer the knight recapture because it discourages the Bg5-pin-related ideas. Also, once we have played ...Nbd7-c5-e4, the ...Bc5 move can still always come. So that's the reasoning for Black.  But we are White! So, what are we doing? For one, we still want to simply trade all the pieces. Also, it's not a typical IQP position, because most IQP positions see White have a pawn on e3 instead of c2. That means the f2-square is a lot weaker, so you need to be paying attention. However, the upside for us is that the e-file is open, which means a few things.  It's easier to trade pieces on it. There could be tactical issues related to the Rxe7! idea at some point when the bishop is on g5 because then Nxd5 might follow. But we'll see more of that later, don't worry yet! }
8... Nbd7
{ Black is getting ready to capture on c5. This position is very rare − it's just move 8, and it's been seen in only 33 games. Naturally, when I was writing my Black course, I couldn't afford to go into tremendous detail explaining nuances of forests of variations in each such line, and I stopped here. Let me quote what I said about this position there:  'Since we are not afraid of White trying to hold on to the pawn, as we had seen in many variations above, we have all the time in the world to recapture the pawn. We would prefer to do so with the knight, because the knight is very active on c5, from where it can come to e4 if needed. Also, ideas like ...Bg4, ...Re8, ...Bc5 look great. And, once the knight moves from d7 to c5 and e4, the e7-bishop can move over to c5 as well, putting pressure on the f2-pawn. I believe it is better to investigate these positions on the level of ideas, so we'll be looking at them in more detail in the chapter on model games.' So, here are some ideas for Black. What about White? We will try to trade pieces! }
9. Be3
{ I like this move better than Bg5 in this case − the bishop is on e7 already, so the pin won't accomplish much. Instead, we get better control of the d4-square and are hoping to trade a pair of pieces when the time is right. }
9... Nxc5
{ 9...Bxc5?  doesn't make any sense, it only helps us achieve more trades.  10.Re1  Bxe3  11.Rxe3⩲  with a standard structural advantage and no counterplay for Black. }
10. h3
{ We prevent Black from pinning us with ...Bg4. It seems like the position is somewhere between equality and a slight edge for White, which is a normal opening outcome. However, there are plenty of opportunities to go wrong for Black. First of all, we are not afraid of ...Nxd3 − we would only welcome this trade, as we are now interested not in some miraculous kingside attack with the help of our light-squared bishop, but in winning the d5-pawn!   Instead, how should they develop?  10...Be6  is more logical but often runs into Nd4, looking for a trade. Instead,  10...Bd7  is a passive way of playing. }
10... Re8
{ The highest-level game that saw this position featured a logical move where Black got the rook on the open file. }
11. Bd4
{ I really like this unusual move, the bishop is positioned very well here! ½-½ Belov-Nikolenko, Moscow 2009. }
11... Be6 12. Re1
{ We can proceed with the regular moves like Qd2 and Rad1, or try to harass Black with Ng5, so it seems logical for Black to prevent that. }
12... h6 13. Bb5
{ But now we get to chase the rook away from its active position or trade more pieces if Black goes  13...Bd7! }
13... Rf8 14. Re3
{ We could proceed either with Qd2 and Rad1, but watch out for ...Ne4 at some point if you choose this setup, or with an unusual idea: Qe1!? and Rad1. It seems as though playing with White is pretty easy and comfortable, and of course, we'll be seeing some examples in the chapter on model games. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2) Classical Rubinstein 3...dxe4"]
[Black "Rubinstein Variation 3...dxe4 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6
{ This move, followed by ...d7-d5, defines something called the French Defense. This opening is about fighting for the center rather ambitiously while avoiding direct piece play. As you will see, the first two moves only feature pawn play. The downside for Black is the locked-up light-squared bishop, and very often, this piece tends to be a large issue for quite a long time. }
2. d4 d5
{ Here, we arrive at massive crossroads. White can lock up the center with e4-e5, take Black's pawn and open up the position, or defend the pawn with some knight move − either to c3 or to d2. }
3. Nc3
{ After a long thought, I decided to suggest this move, which is the most critical and ambitious one. Why did I do that and what's the point of this move? As we can see, we are simply protecting the e4-pawn while keeping the center flexible for now. It's important to do so for the following practical reason: most Black players who play the French @@StartBracket@@and I am one of them, I just wrote a course on French that I'm in love with!@@EndBracket@@ love positions with pawn chains. Our goal is to try to avoid creating one!  However, don't worry: while the move  3.Nc3  is known for being a very principled and theoretically heavy one, we won't need loads of theory − instead, I am opting for practical, easy-to-learn sidelines, which still carry quite a bit of punch, as always!  In this position, we'll need to consider quite a lot of moves. Black can try to pin the knight with  3...Bb4  , which is known as the Winawer Variation − the most forcing and sharp one. Black can also try to force us to lock up the center with the move  3...Nf6  , which is another major theoretical move. The passive yet solid decision is to play  3...dxe4  − the Rubinstein Variation. Black is hoping to avoid the pawn chain situation and trade down, liquidating White's hopes to get a spatial advantage or long-term pressure.  And, of course, there are quite a few sidelines, such as  3...Nc6  ,  3...Be7  − the move I suggested in my Black French course,  3...h6  ,  3...a6  , and so on. Let's tackle them all one by one! }
3... dxe4
{ This move defines what we know as the Rubinstein Variation of the French. Black immediately opens up the center, avoiding the standard positions with pawn chains. The upside for our opponent is that this variation avoids risking a standard outcome where Black ends up squeezed, lacking space and counterplay, and then slowly but surely losing on the kingside.   However, the bad news for Black is that we get a position with a noticeable steady advantage because our pawn on d4 is controlling more space/center than the one on e6 and because the c8-bishop is still a bad piece. Nevertheless, the Rubinstein Variation is a very solid way to play, and many strong GMs, such as the German player Georg Meier demonstrated this by using it to draw numerous top-10 level players. }
4. Nxe4
{ Here, Black is also at a bit of a crossroads. The main move is  4...Nd7  ,  the point being to play ...Ngf6 next, offering a knight trade, being able to recapture back with the knight to avoid doubling the pawns or having to get the queen out early.  However, due to the effort of the ever-creative Georgian GM Baadur Jobava, the odd-looking move  4...Bd7  came to life and started enjoying quite a lot of popularity. Black is trying to solve the standard problem of the bad bishop by  deploying it to c6 very fast, and likely trading it off on e4. }
4... Nd7
{ This is the classic way of playing the Rubinstein, preparing ...Ngf6, looking to trade down and simplify the position, reducing the spatial disadvantage. }
5. Nf3 { For now, we just keep developing. } 5... Ngf6 6. Nxf6+ Nxf6
{ This is the critical position where White has to make a choice. There are a plethora of moves, but essentially, here is what's happening. Black has two issues to resolve:  Black needs to activate the light-squared bishop, which is normally accomplished with ...b7-b6. Black needs to challenge our spatial advantage, created by the d4-pawn. That is typically done by means of ...c7-c5. Sometimes ...e6-e5 could be considered, but realistically, that pawn break is hardly ever possible.  
So, White can choose a very aggressive strategy, such as playing Be3, Qd2, and castling queenside, trying to get a position with opposite-side castles and attack the black king. White can also develop with Bd3, Qe2, and so on, castling kingside and centralizing the pieces.  However, I want to go for a completely different approach. It hasn't ever been considered the most critical one, but I believe that in most lines we get an incredibly easy-to-play position with a noticeable advantage. In the best lines available to the knowledgeable opponents, Black might approach equality, but I do not believe the positions will ever fully get there. }
7. g3
{ We want to deploy the bishop to the long diagonal, which serves several crucial purposes. As we know, one of Black's big ideas is ...b7-b6 and ...Bb7. If our opponent doesn't do that fast enough, the bishop won't ever get out that way due to pressure on the long diagonal.  Secondly, the other plan is to push ...c7-c5. But doing so also empowers the g2-bishop and prevents Black from ever blocking the diagonal with ...c7-c6! This move also scores better than the main lines with a whopping 64.7% win rate for White.   And, it's rare enough for your opponents to not know how to handle it well − just 270 games in the master database compared to 5000 in the main line with  7.Bd3! }
7... c5
{ A perfect example of how easy it is to misplay this position. Black challenges the d4-pawn but makes our light-squared bishop an absolute beast. }
8. Bg2 { White scored over 77% in this position! } 8... cxd4 9. Qxd4
{ This is an absolutely crucial idea to remember. In many variations of the 7.g3 system, we desperately crave the queen trade. Why so? Because as a result, we get a very pleasant endgame where our g2-bishop is exerting powerful pressure on the b7-pawn, and as a result, the queenside is absolutely stuck! Remember: no queens = a lot less counterplay. We are in control, we are dominating, so we dearly welcome that scenario! }
9... Qxd4 10. Nxd4 Bc5
{ The most popular continuation. Black is trying to develop the bishop actively, which seems rather logical. However, it also comes at a loss of tempo. }
11. Nb3
{ The knight retreats with tempo, which is always a pleasant piece of news. From here, it can help us accomplish several things, such as:  Landing on a5 in the future to pressure Black's b7-pawn − a typical idea worth knowing. Supporting the a4-a5 push. If the black pawn ends up on a5, pressuring it, keeping the opponent's pieces stuck. Supporting the c4-c5 push. Controlling the d4-square. I shall stop this list here, because how much more could you demand of one piece?    11.Nb5  doesn't make that much sense this time. We are still better after  11...O-O  ,  but there are no benefits from the Nc7-related ideas. }
11... Bb6
{ Most strong players chose to retreat this way, which is logical, as this way Black keeps the bishop on a long g1-a7 diagonal. It also prevents us from developing our bishop to e3, from where it could put serious pressure on the queenside. }
12. O-O { For now, we just castle, connecting the rooks. } 12... O-O 13. a4
{ I would like to recommend this rare move, which has been tried in only one game so far. What's happening in this position? Well, as you can see, the c8-bishop is still stuck. The opponent has no counterplay, so we can do whatever we want.  The idea is to grab space on the queenside. Next, once we play a4-a5, we kick the bishop away from its active position. After that, a5-a6 could always be an attractive idea to consider. It looks as though Black should stop this pawn push! }
13... a5
{ I think Black should stop the a-pawn run-up. However, now the a5-pawn is another weakness the opponent should be always keeping an eye on!   13...Re8?  was played in that game but after  14.a5!  Bc7  15.Be3!  Nd5  16.Bc5  a6  17.Rfd1+-  ,  White was, naturally, completely winning. As you can see, Black hardly has any moves, and c2-c4 is on the way. It didn't take much longer to convert the advantage in Rindlisbacher-Abdulla, Kocaeli 2011. }
14. Bf4
{ The bishop might run into ...Nd5 at some point, but we don't mind that anymore. }
14... Nd5 15. Be5
{ Black's queenside pieces can't ever come out: for example, ...Bd7 would always fail on the spot as c2-c4! would kick out the knight and allow us to pick up the b7-pawn. }
15... f6 16. Bd4 Bxd4 17. Nxd4
{ We get a position where Black still cannot develop any queenside pieces, and we managed to get rid of Black's only active piece. Next, we'll keep increasing pressure with Rfd1, Nb5, c2-c4-c5, and so on. What can our opponent even do? Well, it looks like nothing... }
*

