9... Qxd4 10. Nxd4 a6
{ The second most popular move in this position, which has been chosen by several 2500+ rated players. Black is trying to prevent us from landing our knight on b5, which severely distresses the queenside. However, that doesn't really help Black alleviate any pressure − we still keep building it up, as the opponent is wasting time. }
11. Bd2
{ We are just developing the pieces, ready to castle long, which would keep the king active and enable the a1-rook to immediately get in the game − the d-file is open, isn't it? It might appear more active to develop the bishop to e3 or f4 instead; however, that doesn't work out that well because then the black knight can come to d5 with tempo. }
11... Be7
{ ½-½ Roseneck-Al Huwar, Warsaw 2019. In this position, a strong IM-level player just castled with White, which still left him in a great spot, even though he failed to convert the advantage into a full point. Instead, I'd like to recommend a gorgeous-looking @@StartBracket@@and a very logical!@@EndBracket@@ novelty. }
12. Nc6
{ Funky move, ain't it? Of course, if Black takes, will end up forked, losing the rook. But it's not a one-move blunder that we're hoping for. Instead, we are planning to position the knight on a5, from where it would be putting endless enormous pressure on the b7-pawn! }
12... Bc5
{ For example, let's say Black tries to avoid losing the bishop pair. } 13. Na5
Ra7 { 13...Rb8  would run into  14.Bf4  , so Black has to continue this way. }
14. b4 { We grab more space, while also winning a tempo. } 14... Be7 15. c4
{ Now, White is dominating the entire board. The black knight no longer has access to the d5-square and the c8-bishop is still stuck. There is an immediate threat of Be3, winning on the spot. All in all, this is just a disaster for the poor Black player, who completely lacks any coordination whatsoever. }
