7... Bd7
{ This move has been played in just 24 games out of nearly 300, but it's not that bad, surprisingly! Black is trying to go ...Bc6 on the next turn, activating the bishop. }
8. Ne5
{ We, of course, want to prevent that, going after the bishop pair at the same time. }
8... Bc6 { Wait, what is this? Isn't Black also ruining the structure? } 9.
Nxc6 Qd5
{ No! Due to this pretty double attack, Black is able to force us to give up the kingside castling rights. }
10. Rg1 Qxc6 11. Bg2
{ But we still get the bishop pair and aim to take advantage of the long diagonal. }
11... Qb6 { The queen has to stick around the b7-pawn, of course. } 12. c3
{ We overprotect the d4-pawn and want to offer a queen trade with Qb3 on the next turn. }
12... Bd6 13. Qb3
{ Black cannot avoid the trade, as moving the queen away would hang the b7-pawn. }
13... c6
{ It's natural that in all games that reached this position, Black chose to block the diagonal. }
14. Bd2
{ Typically, White would trade queens, but I think there is no need to rush. Instead, we can just develop and potentially prepare queenside castling. If Black wants to take, that is welcome! }
14... Qxb3 15. axb3 { Now, the a-file opens up. } 15... a6
{ Black should make this move for a few reasons: this way, the rook is no longer stuck defending the a7-pawn, while b3-b4-b5 is much more difficult to carry out. We would have loved to make that happen to open up the g2-bishop! }
16. b4
{ However, the arising position is still not very pleasant for Black. At some point, the c3-c4 and b4-b5 plan could be on White's agenda. Also, it's possible to grab more space on the kingside with f2-f4, Bf3, g3-g4, and so on. Black is fairly solid, but during the next several dozen moves, will be stuck defending passively, which is by no means a pleasant scenario. This is certainly something we should celebrate!   However, honestly, given the nature of the positions Black gets in the main line with @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/ppp2ppp/4pn2/8/3P4/5NP1/PPP2P1P/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7...b6  , this might be a better outcome. }
