8... Bd7 9. a4
{ We are not avoiding the bishop trade, but we aren't forcing it, either. The aspiration is that if Black captures, we take back and open up the a-file for our rook, while also creating a backward weak pawn on a7 in the opponent camp, as well as the weak square on c6, which can  (and likely will!)  serve as an outpost for the knight after Ne5-c6. }
9... Bxb5 10. axb5
{ This creates a fantastic position for White, where the a7-pawn is weak, the a8-rook is stuck defending it, and the c6-square is a huge problem. Black cannot allow for Ne5-c6. }
10... Bd6 11. Bg5 { A new problem arises: a fairly awkward pin. } 11... O-O 12.
O-O h6 { We are going to gladly and readily part with the bishop. } 13. Bxf6
Qxf6 14. Qe2
{ Black is absolutely restricted. There are no pawn breaks: ...c7-c5 isn't happening, and ...e6-e5 is really easy to prevent with Rfe1, for example. We can keep improving the position with c2-c4, Ra4, Rfa1, and so on. Likely, the a7-pawn will soon be lost. }
