{ This unexpected check  (why isn't the bishop going to g2, one might ask)  is aimed at preventing its black counterpart from getting developed to b7, thus causing coordination problems.   8.Bg2!?  Bb7  is a line that is believed to be harmless. However, I don't necessarily agree with this conclusion! First of all, it's undoubtedly a very playable position with the potential to outplay the opponent; for example, Harikrishna used this line to beat Giri, and many other top players, such as Nakamura, Topalov, Svidler, and others gave it a shot as well.  Secondly, Black doesn't have a direct immediate path to equality. So, if you want to avoid theory and just play chess, or just switch things up every now and then, consider giving this a shot as well.  9.O-O  Bd6  10.Qe2  O-O  11.Rd1  h6  12.c4  Qe7  13.Ne5  Bxg2  14.Kxg2  Bxe5  15.Qxe5⩲  and White kept a comfortable pressure and eventually won in Harikrishna-Giri, Wijk aan Zee 2013. }
8... Bd7 9. a4
{ We are not avoiding the bishop trade, but we aren't forcing it, either. The aspiration is that if Black captures, we take back and open up the a-file for our rook, while also creating a backward weak pawn on a7 in the opponent camp, as well as the weak square on c6, which can  (and likely will!)  serve as an outpost for the knight after Ne5-c6. }
9... a6
{ Black forces us to make a decision regarding the bishop trade. Do we retreat or trade? }
10. Be2
{ I think it's much more principled to keep them on the board because our intention is to attack Black's bishop with Ne5 and try to get the bishop pair. But this isn't just my opinion − 49/51 games in this position saw this move.   One big point behind including a2-a4 and ...a7-a6 is that we are hoping that Black's move could be a weakening one. We are hoping it would either keep the rook stuck on a8, or that Black will need to play ...a6-a5 at some point, weakening the b5-square, and making ...c7-c5 less desirable. }
10... Be7 { This is possible but very passive, to my mind. } 11. Ne5
{ Of course, we are always happy to play this move, not just to go after the bishop but also to try to activate our light-squared bishop and take advantage of the weak c6-square by means of Bf3, followed by bringing some piece to c6. }
11... O-O 12. Bf3
{ Now, Black has to waste even more time making ugly moves. Of course, ...Nd5 won't cut it, as after c2-c4!, White is winning material. }
12... Rb8 13. O-O
{ Now, we'd love to follow up with c2-c4, grabbing even more space in the center and preventing Black from being able to access the d5-square. Then, we'll keep improving the position with simple moves like Qe2, Rfd1, Be3, or maybe b2-b3 and Bb2. Black has absolutely no active moves whatsoever! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2) Classical Rubinstein 3...dxe4"]
[Black "Rubinstein Variation 3...dxe4 #8"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6
{ This move, followed by ...d7-d5, defines something called the French Defense. This opening is about fighting for the center rather ambitiously while avoiding direct piece play. As you will see, the first two moves only feature pawn play. The downside for Black is the locked-up light-squared bishop, and very often, this piece tends to be a large issue for quite a long time. }
2. d4 d5
{ Here, we arrive at massive crossroads. White can lock up the center with e4-e5, take Black's pawn and open up the position, or defend the pawn with some knight move − either to c3 or to d2. }
3. Nc3
{ After a long thought, I decided to suggest this move, which is the most critical and ambitious one. Why did I do that and what's the point of this move? As we can see, we are simply protecting the e4-pawn while keeping the center flexible for now. It's important to do so for the following practical reason: most Black players who play the French @@StartBracket@@and I am one of them, I just wrote a course on French that I'm in love with!@@EndBracket@@ love positions with pawn chains. Our goal is to try to avoid creating one!  However, don't worry: while the move  3.Nc3  is known for being a very principled and theoretically heavy one, we won't need loads of theory − instead, I am opting for practical, easy-to-learn sidelines, which still carry quite a bit of punch, as always!  In this position, we'll need to consider quite a lot of moves. Black can try to pin the knight with  3...Bb4  , which is known as the Winawer Variation − the most forcing and sharp one. Black can also try to force us to lock up the center with the move  3...Nf6  , which is another major theoretical move. The passive yet solid decision is to play  3...dxe4  − the Rubinstein Variation. Black is hoping to avoid the pawn chain situation and trade down, liquidating White's hopes to get a spatial advantage or long-term pressure.  And, of course, there are quite a few sidelines, such as  3...Nc6  ,  3...Be7  − the move I suggested in my Black French course,  3...h6  ,  3...a6  , and so on. Let's tackle them all one by one! }
3... dxe4
{ This move defines what we know as the Rubinstein Variation of the French. Black immediately opens up the center, avoiding the standard positions with pawn chains. The upside for our opponent is that this variation avoids risking a standard outcome where Black ends up squeezed, lacking space and counterplay, and then slowly but surely losing on the kingside.   However, the bad news for Black is that we get a position with a noticeable steady advantage because our pawn on d4 is controlling more space/center than the one on e6 and because the c8-bishop is still a bad piece. Nevertheless, the Rubinstein Variation is a very solid way to play, and many strong GMs, such as the German player Georg Meier demonstrated this by using it to draw numerous top-10 level players. }
4. Nxe4
{ Here, Black is also at a bit of a crossroads. The main move is  4...Nd7  ,  the point being to play ...Ngf6 next, offering a knight trade, being able to recapture back with the knight to avoid doubling the pawns or having to get the queen out early.  However, due to the effort of the ever-creative Georgian GM Baadur Jobava, the odd-looking move  4...Bd7  came to life and started enjoying quite a lot of popularity. Black is trying to solve the standard problem of the bad bishop by  deploying it to c6 very fast, and likely trading it off on e4. }
4... Nd7
{ This is the classic way of playing the Rubinstein, preparing ...Ngf6, looking to trade down and simplify the position, reducing the spatial disadvantage. }
5. Nf3 { For now, we just keep developing. } 5... Ngf6 6. Nxf6+ Nxf6
{ This is the critical position where White has to make a choice. There are a plethora of moves, but essentially, here is what's happening. Black has two issues to resolve:  Black needs to activate the light-squared bishop, which is normally accomplished with ...b7-b6. Black needs to challenge our spatial advantage, created by the d4-pawn. That is typically done by means of ...c7-c5. Sometimes ...e6-e5 could be considered, but realistically, that pawn break is hardly ever possible.  
So, White can choose a very aggressive strategy, such as playing Be3, Qd2, and castling queenside, trying to get a position with opposite-side castles and attack the black king. White can also develop with Bd3, Qe2, and so on, castling kingside and centralizing the pieces.  However, I want to go for a completely different approach. It hasn't ever been considered the most critical one, but I believe that in most lines we get an incredibly easy-to-play position with a noticeable advantage. In the best lines available to the knowledgeable opponents, Black might approach equality, but I do not believe the positions will ever fully get there. }
7. g3
{ We want to deploy the bishop to the long diagonal, which serves several crucial purposes. As we know, one of Black's big ideas is ...b7-b6 and ...Bb7. If our opponent doesn't do that fast enough, the bishop won't ever get out that way due to pressure on the long diagonal.  Secondly, the other plan is to push ...c7-c5. But doing so also empowers the g2-bishop and prevents Black from ever blocking the diagonal with ...c7-c6! This move also scores better than the main lines with a whopping 64.7% win rate for White.   And, it's rare enough for your opponents to not know how to handle it well − just 270 games in the master database compared to 5000 in the main line with  7.Bd3! }
7... b6
{ If Black is hoping to equalize in this variation, this is undoubtedly the way to go! The bishop is trying to immediately come to the long diagonal. It's absolutely imperative Black accomplishes this before White does, since if our bishop had been on g2, we could go Ne5!, opening it up, and probably winning on the spot because of the problems with the h1-a8 diagonal and the c6-square in particular. }
8. Bb5+
{ This unexpected check  (why isn't the bishop going to g2, one might ask)  is aimed at preventing its black counterpart from getting developed to b7, thus causing coordination problems.   8.Bg2!?  Bb7  is a line that is believed to be harmless. However, I don't necessarily agree with this conclusion! First of all, it's undoubtedly a very playable position with the potential to outplay the opponent; for example, Harikrishna used this line to beat Giri, and many other top players, such as Nakamura, Topalov, Svidler, and others gave it a shot as well.  Secondly, Black doesn't have a direct immediate path to equality. So, if you want to avoid theory and just play chess, or just switch things up every now and then, consider giving this a shot as well.  9.O-O  Bd6  10.Qe2  O-O  11.Rd1  h6  12.c4  Qe7  13.Ne5  Bxg2  14.Kxg2  Bxe5  15.Qxe5⩲  and White kept a comfortable pressure and eventually won in Harikrishna-Giri, Wijk aan Zee 2013. }
8... Bd7 9. a4
{ We are not avoiding the bishop trade, but we aren't forcing it, either. The aspiration is that if Black captures, we take back and open up the a-file for our rook, while also creating a backward weak pawn on a7 in the opponent camp, as well as the weak square on c6, which can  (and likely will!)  serve as an outpost for the knight after Ne5-c6. }
9... a6
{ Black forces us to make a decision regarding the bishop trade. Do we retreat or trade? }
10. Be2
{ I think it's much more principled to keep them on the board because our intention is to attack Black's bishop with Ne5 and try to get the bishop pair. But this isn't just my opinion − 49/51 games in this position saw this move.   One big point behind including a2-a4 and ...a7-a6 is that we are hoping that Black's move could be a weakening one. We are hoping it would either keep the rook stuck on a8, or that Black will need to play ...a6-a5 at some point, weakening the b5-square, and making ...c7-c5 less desirable. }
10... Bc6
{ It's imperative that Black activates the bishop before we can play Ne5 and sort of trap it. }
11. O-O
{ By castling, we not only make a logical move that connects the rooks but also unpin the f3-knight, preparing Ne5 next. This position was reached in nearly 50 games, mostly very high-level ones, with Nepo, Jones, Deac, and many others representing White, and Meier, Ivanchuk, and many other strong players trying to defend Black's case.   At this point, since White is about to jump with the knight to e5, Black needs to make a choice about where to develop the bishop: to d6 or e7. The former move seems more active as it enables Black to capture the knight. However, doing so concedes the bishop pair, which doesn't necessarily seem so obviously fantastic.  On the other hand, ...Be7 makes the position more bulletproof against the pin Bg5, and if Black has no intention of giving up the bishop pair, going there seems more logical.  Generally, both moves are very logical and have been played equally often. We'll now discuss how the game can develop, but the position isn't particularly forcing, so don't worry too much about memorizing theory. }
11... Be7
{ Meier tried this move in several games, but lost to Nepo and Moskalenko. Overall, White is doing really well, scoring 62% here. }
12. Ne5
{ Of course, this is a logical way of continuing, activating the knight, and winning a tempo. }
12... Bb7 13. c4
{ White's grabbing even more space. Next, we'd like to play Bf3!, trade the light-squared bishops, and take advantage of the fact the c6-square is really weak. }
13... Nd7 { Naturally, Black tries to trade off the active knight. } 14. Bf3
{ White continues with the plan, as planned. } 14... Bxf3 15. Qxf3
{ The c6-square seems very loose, with ideas like Nc6 around the corner. Of course, the f7-pawn is also hanging. So, Black has no choice but to trade the knights. }
15... Nxe5 16. dxe5
{ This position has been reached in 5 games, with White scoring 4/5 − three wins and two draws. We are better because of the spatial advantage and the weak c6-square, primarily. The pawn on a6 also gives us an opportunity to at some point harass the queenside with the idea a4-a5, looking to create a weakness on a6. }
16... O-O 17. Rd1
{ And White went on to win a lovely positional game. We'll stop the analysis and the trainable line here but will certainly discuss this position in more detail in the chapter on model games.  Next, we can try to build the queenside initiative with a4-a5, or even some kingside play with h4-h5, Rd4-g4, and so on! Of course, controlling the d-file and the h1-a8 diagonal and having ideas like Qc6 and Rd7 doesn't hurt either. 1-0 Nepomniachtchi-Meier, Heraklion 2017. }
*

