11... Bd6
{ ...Bd6 enables Black to achieve a passive endgame, but the whole idea of playing this line doesn't look appealing at all. }
12. Ne5 Bb7
{ This move is less popular, but I think it's a less unpleasant way to play. I didn't say 'more pleasant' on purpose, because it seems Black's position is somewhat disgusting no matter what. }
13. Bf3 { As usual, we're readily taking advantage of the weak c6-square. }
13... Qc8
{ Whenever this position arose, Black would always protect the bishop, hoping to not yet have to surrender control over the long diagonal. }
14. Bg5
{ Now, we're threatening to take on f6 and ruin Black's pawn structure. That's a threat to reckon with, so all Black players always removed the knight away in response. }
14... Ne4 15. Bf4
{ The bishop retreats − simple and natural. Now, we're about to disturb the knight with Qe2. }
15... O-O 16. Qe2
{ It seems very silly to have to retreat. If Black did that, we'd just go c2-c4, grabbing even more space and reaching a very pleasant position where they have no counterplay. }
16... f5 17. Rfd1
{ We just keep improving our pieces. This move also looks very logical, since Black seems willing to at some point play ...c7-c5. In that case, the d-file will inevitably open up and the rook would be placed just perfectly. }
17... c5
{ Of course, Black has to try to finally play at least one active move, challenging our space superiority. }
18. Bg2
{ Next, we'll play c2-c3, reinforcing the center, and maybe f2-f3, kicking the active knight out. The e6-pawn is backward, the black king is somewhat unsafe and our pieces are more active. This is by no means the end of the world, but we enjoy a rather large advantage! }
