3... dxe4
{ This move defines what we know as the Rubinstein Variation of the French. Black immediately opens up the center, avoiding the standard positions with pawn chains. The upside for our opponent is that this variation avoids risking a standard outcome where Black ends up squeezed, lacking space and counterplay, and then slowly but surely losing on the kingside.   However, the bad news for Black is that we get a position with a noticeable steady advantage because our pawn on d4 is controlling more space/center than the one on e6 and because the c8-bishop is still a bad piece. Nevertheless, the Rubinstein Variation is a very solid way to play, and many strong GMs, such as the German player Georg Meier demonstrated this by using it to draw numerous top-10 level players. }
4. Nxe4
{ Here, Black is also at a bit of a crossroads. The main move is  4...Nd7  ,  the point being to play ...Ngf6 next, offering a knight trade, being able to recapture back with the knight to avoid doubling the pawns or having to get the queen out early.  However, due to the effort of the ever-creative Georgian GM Baadur Jobava, the odd-looking move  4...Bd7  came to life and started enjoying quite a lot of popularity. Black is trying to solve the standard problem of the bad bishop by  deploying it to c6 very fast, and likely trading it off on e4. }
4... Nf6
{ This move, without the inclusion of ...Nbd7 first, almost never works out particularly well for Black in the French Defense. Why so? Because after we take the opponent's knight, Black is forced to either take with the queen, which misplaces and exposes it, or with the pawn, which weakens the kingside. }
5. Nxf6+ { We are VERY glad to capture in this case! } 5... gxf6
{ About one-quarter of all the games after 5.Nxf6+ saw this recapture, but it doesn't lead to anything good. However, it was tried recently  (even if mostly in blitz and rapid)  by Rapport, Sanal, Pacitan, and other strong players, so we need to learn how to handle it. Black will likely try to castle queenside and use the g-file to try to attack the white king with ...Rg8 and things like that. Would this plan work? Not really, as long as we are careful. }
6. Nf3 b6
{ Black tries to fianchetto the bad light-squared bishop. This is a very reasonable idea, and we should do our best to prevent the opponent from accomplishing that plan. }
7. Bb5+
{ Our goal is to provoke ...c7-c6 because this move, once played, will block Black's b7-bishop − if not forever, then at least for a very long time. }
7... c6 8. Bc4
{ I like this somewhat surprising retreat, instead of the more common and logical-looking  8.Bd3  . What is the point of this move, and what are we doing overall in this position?  Well, the bishop on d3 could be easily blocked by ...f6-f5.  However, one huge downside of this structure  (this is a really important theme to know of!)  is that lacking the g-pawn means the h5-square is very weak. That's why a typical idea in these positions is to play Nh4 and Qh5! Once the queen lands there, the f7-pawn finds itself under constant pressure. It makes it very difficult for Black to castle long without losing it!  On top of that, there will be threats like Bxe6. And, if we play Nh4, castle kingside, and install the rook on e1, ideas like Nf5! will always be around the corner too. }
8... Bb7 9. O-O Nd7
{ This move might seem pretty logical, but I wanted to show you why it's bad. The problem is that it's blocking the 7th rank, making it very difficult for Black to defend the f7-pawn with the queen from, say, c7. }
10. Nh4
{ The knight is making room for our queen, which would love to land on h5. From there, it would threaten the f7-pawn. That pawn is pinned, so there will be threats like Bxe6! }
10... Qc7 11. Qh5
{ Now, not only is there an immediate threat of Bxe6, but also Black simply cannot castle, as the f7-pawn would hang. Given that ideas like Re1 and Nf5 are also around the corner, I am afraid Black should soon start thinking about how to resign − by gracefully offering the hand to the opponent, or by running away from the tournament hall. On a serious note, it's kind of amazing HOW quickly you can get a lost position. }
