{ Here, we arrive at massive crossroads. White can lock up the center with e4-e5, take Black's pawn and open up the position, or defend the pawn with some knight move − either to c3 or to d2. }
3. Nc3
{ After a long thought, I decided to suggest this move, which is the most critical and ambitious one. Why did I do that and what's the point of this move? As we can see, we are simply protecting the e4-pawn while keeping the center flexible for now. It's important to do so for the following practical reason: most Black players who play the French @@StartBracket@@and I am one of them, I just wrote a course on French that I'm in love with!@@EndBracket@@ love positions with pawn chains. Our goal is to try to avoid creating one!  However, don't worry: while the move  3.Nc3  is known for being a very principled and theoretically heavy one, we won't need loads of theory − instead, I am opting for practical, easy-to-learn sidelines, which still carry quite a bit of punch, as always!  In this position, we'll need to consider quite a lot of moves. Black can try to pin the knight with  3...Bb4  , which is known as the Winawer Variation − the most forcing and sharp one. Black can also try to force us to lock up the center with the move  3...Nf6  , which is another major theoretical move. The passive yet solid decision is to play  3...dxe4  − the Rubinstein Variation. Black is hoping to avoid the pawn chain situation and trade down, liquidating White's hopes to get a spatial advantage or long-term pressure.  And, of course, there are quite a few sidelines, such as  3...Nc6  ,  3...Be7  − the move I suggested in my Black French course,  3...h6  ,  3...a6  , and so on. Let's tackle them all one by one! }
3... dxe4
{ This move defines what we know as the Rubinstein Variation of the French. Black immediately opens up the center, avoiding the standard positions with pawn chains. The upside for our opponent is that this variation avoids risking a standard outcome where Black ends up squeezed, lacking space and counterplay, and then slowly but surely losing on the kingside.   However, the bad news for Black is that we get a position with a noticeable steady advantage because our pawn on d4 is controlling more space/center than the one on e6 and because the c8-bishop is still a bad piece. Nevertheless, the Rubinstein Variation is a very solid way to play, and many strong GMs, such as the German player Georg Meier demonstrated this by using it to draw numerous top-10 level players. }
4. Nxe4
{ Here, Black is also at a bit of a crossroads. The main move is  4...Nd7  ,  the point being to play ...Ngf6 next, offering a knight trade, being able to recapture back with the knight to avoid doubling the pawns or having to get the queen out early.  However, due to the effort of the ever-creative Georgian GM Baadur Jobava, the odd-looking move  4...Bd7  came to life and started enjoying quite a lot of popularity. Black is trying to solve the standard problem of the bad bishop by  deploying it to c6 very fast, and likely trading it off on e4. }
4... Nf6
{ This move, without the inclusion of ...Nbd7 first, almost never works out particularly well for Black in the French Defense. Why so? Because after we take the opponent's knight, Black is forced to either take with the queen, which misplaces and exposes it, or with the pawn, which weakens the kingside. }
5. Nxf6+ { We are VERY glad to capture in this case! } 5... gxf6
{ About one-quarter of all the games after 5.Nxf6+ saw this recapture, but it doesn't lead to anything good. However, it was tried recently  (even if mostly in blitz and rapid)  by Rapport, Sanal, Pacitan, and other strong players, so we need to learn how to handle it. Black will likely try to castle queenside and use the g-file to try to attack the white king with ...Rg8 and things like that. Would this plan work? Not really, as long as we are careful. }
6. Nf3 b6
{ Black tries to fianchetto the bad light-squared bishop. This is a very reasonable idea, and we should do our best to prevent the opponent from accomplishing that plan. }
7. Bb5+
{ Our goal is to provoke ...c7-c6 because this move, once played, will block Black's b7-bishop − if not forever, then at least for a very long time. }
7... c6 8. Bc4
{ I like this somewhat surprising retreat, instead of the more common and logical-looking  8.Bd3  . What is the point of this move, and what are we doing overall in this position?  Well, the bishop on d3 could be easily blocked by ...f6-f5.  However, one huge downside of this structure  (this is a really important theme to know of!)  is that lacking the g-pawn means the h5-square is very weak. That's why a typical idea in these positions is to play Nh4 and Qh5! Once the queen lands there, the f7-pawn finds itself under constant pressure. It makes it very difficult for Black to castle long without losing it!  On top of that, there will be threats like Bxe6. And, if we play Nh4, castle kingside, and install the rook on e1, ideas like Nf5! will always be around the corner too. }
8... Bb7 9. O-O Qc7
{ A better idea because the queen is able to guard the f7-pawn. However, since we now know the black knight cannot go to d7, the question is, where would it go?! }
10. Nh4
{ We continue with the same plan anyway. Not only, remember, can the queen land on h5, but also, there is this idea of Re1 and Nf5! }
10... Na6 { The knight has no choice but to go there. } 11. Qe2
{ Now, the knight is under attack, which means Black has no choice but to weaken the queenside. However, in that event, it'd be very dangerous to castle there. }
11... b5 12. Bd3
{ Now, a2-a4! seems to be a huge threat. And if Black somehow manages to address the immediate threat of this move, it would still remain an ever-present problem, hanging upon Black's queenside like a sword of Damocles. }
12... Nb4
{ Black's only chance is to remove the knight from its vulnerable position by winning a tempo. }
13. Be4 { Of course, we won't let Black trade off our gorgeous bishop. } 13...
O-O-O
{ Black did manage to castle, but it doesn't mean getting out of the woods yet! }
14. c3 { First, we kick out the knight. } 14... Nd5 15. g3
{ And then we restrict it even more. Our knight can go back to f3 if needed. Or, it can find its way elsewhere via g2 to e3, or maybe f4. And, of course, the a2-a4 idea is still hanging in the air. Black cannot attack our king at all − in no small part, thanks to the wonderful h4-knight that is stalling the advance of the black h-pawn. However, we're ready to blow up the queenside and should be, frankly, just winning, or at least very close to that. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3) Rubinstein − Sidelines"]
[Black "Rubinstein Sidelines 4...Nf6 #4"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6
{ This move, followed by ...d7-d5, defines something called the French Defense. This opening is about fighting for the center rather ambitiously while avoiding direct piece play. As you will see, the first two moves only feature pawn play. The downside for Black is the locked-up light-squared bishop, and very often, this piece tends to be a large issue for quite a long time. }
2. d4 d5
{ Here, we arrive at massive crossroads. White can lock up the center with e4-e5, take Black's pawn and open up the position, or defend the pawn with some knight move − either to c3 or to d2. }
3. Nc3
{ After a long thought, I decided to suggest this move, which is the most critical and ambitious one. Why did I do that and what's the point of this move? As we can see, we are simply protecting the e4-pawn while keeping the center flexible for now. It's important to do so for the following practical reason: most Black players who play the French @@StartBracket@@and I am one of them, I just wrote a course on French that I'm in love with!@@EndBracket@@ love positions with pawn chains. Our goal is to try to avoid creating one!  However, don't worry: while the move  3.Nc3  is known for being a very principled and theoretically heavy one, we won't need loads of theory − instead, I am opting for practical, easy-to-learn sidelines, which still carry quite a bit of punch, as always!  In this position, we'll need to consider quite a lot of moves. Black can try to pin the knight with  3...Bb4  , which is known as the Winawer Variation − the most forcing and sharp one. Black can also try to force us to lock up the center with the move  3...Nf6  , which is another major theoretical move. The passive yet solid decision is to play  3...dxe4  − the Rubinstein Variation. Black is hoping to avoid the pawn chain situation and trade down, liquidating White's hopes to get a spatial advantage or long-term pressure.  And, of course, there are quite a few sidelines, such as  3...Nc6  ,  3...Be7  − the move I suggested in my Black French course,  3...h6  ,  3...a6  , and so on. Let's tackle them all one by one! }
3... dxe4
{ This move defines what we know as the Rubinstein Variation of the French. Black immediately opens up the center, avoiding the standard positions with pawn chains. The upside for our opponent is that this variation avoids risking a standard outcome where Black ends up squeezed, lacking space and counterplay, and then slowly but surely losing on the kingside.   However, the bad news for Black is that we get a position with a noticeable steady advantage because our pawn on d4 is controlling more space/center than the one on e6 and because the c8-bishop is still a bad piece. Nevertheless, the Rubinstein Variation is a very solid way to play, and many strong GMs, such as the German player Georg Meier demonstrated this by using it to draw numerous top-10 level players. }
4. Nxe4
{ Here, Black is also at a bit of a crossroads. The main move is  4...Nd7  ,  the point being to play ...Ngf6 next, offering a knight trade, being able to recapture back with the knight to avoid doubling the pawns or having to get the queen out early.  However, due to the effort of the ever-creative Georgian GM Baadur Jobava, the odd-looking move  4...Bd7  came to life and started enjoying quite a lot of popularity. Black is trying to solve the standard problem of the bad bishop by  deploying it to c6 very fast, and likely trading it off on e4. }
4... Nf6
{ This move, without the inclusion of ...Nbd7 first, almost never works out particularly well for Black in the French Defense. Why so? Because after we take the opponent's knight, Black is forced to either take with the queen, which misplaces and exposes it, or with the pawn, which weakens the kingside. }
5. Nxf6+ { We are VERY glad to capture in this case! } 5... Qxf6
{ Now, the black queen will find itself at risk. } 6. Nf3
{ If White was allowed to play Bd3 and Bg5, the queen would all of a sudden get trapped! The queen certainly should have stayed home. }
6... h6 { So, Black needs to take the g5-square under control. } 7. Bd3
{ We just keep developing our pieces to the most logical squares. As Black is about to find out, it won't be very easy to castle kingside! }
7... Bd6
{ It's more logical to develop the bishop here than to e7 for a few reasons. It is placed more actively here and had it been on e7, Black's queen would be sort of stuck − it won't have any room for retreating back home. }
8. Qe2
{ We are potentially preparing queenside castling. On top of that, there is of course a very common idea Qe2-e4, setting up a powerful battery aimed at mating the black king. }
8... Nc6
{ Black has to try queenside castling, but this is a horrible idea too. } 9. c3
{ We just overprotect the center for now, while also preparing b2-b4. } 9...
Bd7 { Black is getting ready to castle queenside. } 10. O-O
{ We don't care. We need to finish development no matter what. Also, of course, connecting the rooks is a good thing. Once Black castles, we'll go for a rapid queenside pawn storm! }
10... O-O-O
{ This move is logical but optimistic to the point of being naive. Black's king won't be safe there... at all. }
11. b4
{ With b4-b4, a2-a4-a5, etc, coming next, Black's days are counted. Of course, Black still has no counterplay on the kingside. Pay close attention! It's NOT ONLY BECAUSE THE PAWNS HAVE NOT ADVANCED, but also because Black has no pieces there besides the queen! }
