{ We are potentially preparing queenside castling. On top of that, there is of course a very common idea Qe2-e4, setting up a powerful battery aimed at mating the black king. }
8... O-O
{ Surprisingly, this natural move just loses − all because of that pawn on h6! }
9. Qe4
{ We are threatening checkmate, and not leaving Black with too many defensive options. }
9... g6
{ This move loses, but  9...Qf5  won't help either, as after  10.Qh4  , the black queen has to move far away from the action. For example,  10...Qa5+  11.Bd2  Qb6  12.Bxh6+-  and checkmate is around the corner. }
10. Bxh6
{ White scoops up a crucial pawn, while also getting ready to either convert calmly, or mount up a decisive attack with h2-h4-h5, Bg5 or Ng5, and so on. }
