{ Some people retreat with the knight to g3, but most just defend it while developing the bishop, and that's what I recommend doing as well.   Now, Black would normally play  6...Nd7  , continuing development and  preparing ...Ngf6 − this happened in nearly 90% of the games. However, some people also tried other moves, such as immediately capturing on e4. }
6... Nf6 7. Nxf6+
{ This just results in positions similar to the ones after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/8/3PN3/8/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Nf6  5.Nxf6+  ,  but even worse for Black because the bishop has already occupied the c6-square, taking it away from the knight. One funny pattern worth pointing out is that taking with the queen loses on the spot. }
7... Qxf6 8. Bg5 Bxf3
{ It seems as though White is in trouble − now, our queen and bishop are both hanging! }
9. Qd2
{ The smoke fades away and it becomes obvious Black has gotten the queen trapped. This is good news for us! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3) Rubinstein − Sidelines"]
[Black "Jobava Rubinstein 4...Bd7 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6
{ This move, followed by ...d7-d5, defines something called the French Defense. This opening is about fighting for the center rather ambitiously while avoiding direct piece play. As you will see, the first two moves only feature pawn play. The downside for Black is the locked-up light-squared bishop, and very often, this piece tends to be a large issue for quite a long time. }
2. d4 d5
{ Here, we arrive at massive crossroads. White can lock up the center with e4-e5, take Black's pawn and open up the position, or defend the pawn with some knight move − either to c3 or to d2. }
3. Nc3
{ After a long thought, I decided to suggest this move, which is the most critical and ambitious one. Why did I do that and what's the point of this move? As we can see, we are simply protecting the e4-pawn while keeping the center flexible for now. It's important to do so for the following practical reason: most Black players who play the French @@StartBracket@@and I am one of them, I just wrote a course on French that I'm in love with!@@EndBracket@@ love positions with pawn chains. Our goal is to try to avoid creating one!  However, don't worry: while the move  3.Nc3  is known for being a very principled and theoretically heavy one, we won't need loads of theory − instead, I am opting for practical, easy-to-learn sidelines, which still carry quite a bit of punch, as always!  In this position, we'll need to consider quite a lot of moves. Black can try to pin the knight with  3...Bb4  , which is known as the Winawer Variation − the most forcing and sharp one. Black can also try to force us to lock up the center with the move  3...Nf6  , which is another major theoretical move. The passive yet solid decision is to play  3...dxe4  − the Rubinstein Variation. Black is hoping to avoid the pawn chain situation and trade down, liquidating White's hopes to get a spatial advantage or long-term pressure.  And, of course, there are quite a few sidelines, such as  3...Nc6  ,  3...Be7  − the move I suggested in my Black French course,  3...h6  ,  3...a6  , and so on. Let's tackle them all one by one! }
3... dxe4
{ This move defines what we know as the Rubinstein Variation of the French. Black immediately opens up the center, avoiding the standard positions with pawn chains. The upside for our opponent is that this variation avoids risking a standard outcome where Black ends up squeezed, lacking space and counterplay, and then slowly but surely losing on the kingside.   However, the bad news for Black is that we get a position with a noticeable steady advantage because our pawn on d4 is controlling more space/center than the one on e6 and because the c8-bishop is still a bad piece. Nevertheless, the Rubinstein Variation is a very solid way to play, and many strong GMs, such as the German player Georg Meier demonstrated this by using it to draw numerous top-10 level players. }
4. Nxe4
{ Here, Black is also at a bit of a crossroads. The main move is  4...Nd7  ,  the point being to play ...Ngf6 next, offering a knight trade, being able to recapture back with the knight to avoid doubling the pawns or having to get the queen out early.  However, due to the effort of the ever-creative Georgian GM Baadur Jobava, the odd-looking move  4...Bd7  came to life and started enjoying quite a lot of popularity. Black is trying to solve the standard problem of the bad bishop by  deploying it to c6 very fast, and likely trading it off on e4. }
4... Bd7
{ This odd move initiates what we know as the Jobava Variation of the Rubinstein system. It has been played before but caught up in popularity only in the last decade due to the effort of the ever-creative Georgian GM. What's the idea? Black knows the bishop is bad in the French positions because it's restricted by the e6-pawn, so Black tries to resolve this problem right away by placing it on c6 and then trading it off.  Overall, there is nothing 'wrong' either with the idea of this variation or with the execution. But, of course, executing this plan costs Black a lot of time and yields a very passive position. On a small personal note, when I was looking for an additional solid weapon for my Black French repertoire here on Chessable, I was considering writing a small chapter on this variation.  However, upon further investigation, I couldn't bring myself to do it: in many lines, the weaker/lazy White players can easily force a repetition/draw/a very dry position, but at the same time, the ambitious, strong, and knowledgeable White players can keep posing problems in front of Black nearly indefinitely.  So, I didn't see what would be the practical use case of this line and abandoned it. What you will see in this chapter is, actually, the line I got very scared of while trying to make this variation work for Black! }
5. Nf3 { We just keep developing. } 5... Bc6
{ And so does Black; nothing unexpected so far. } 6. Bd3
{ Some people retreat with the knight to g3, but most just defend it while developing the bishop, and that's what I recommend doing as well.   Now, Black would normally play  6...Nd7  , continuing development and  preparing ...Ngf6 − this happened in nearly 90% of the games. However, some people also tried other moves, such as immediately capturing on e4. }
6... Nd7
{ Black is preparing the standard idea: ...Nf6, and if White takes, take back with the knight, centralizing it, but avoiding having to deploy the queen early on. }
7. O-O Ngf6
{ This is the very critical tabiya of the Jobava system. White has tried a ton of moves here, from the natural  8.Qe2  to the elegant  8.Ng3  or even the odd  8.Ned2  ,  looking to preserve as many pieces on the board as possible. But, I found a move that has been hardly ever seen  (in just 278 games out of 5000+!)  , and it seems to cause a ton of problems for Black. }
8. Re1
{ You'd think, what's the difference between this move and the more popular way of protecting the knight, which is  8.Qe2?  Hold on for a moment! }
8... Nxe4 { Black has to execute this trading idea; what else could be done? }
9. Bxe4 Bxe4 10. Rxe4
{ Here, we arrive at a crossroads: most people developed with  10...Nf6  , which is very logical; however, some tried  10...Be7  , keeping the knight on its original square. Bigger picture-wise, it seems as though Black has traded two pairs of pieces, so shouldn't have too many issues playing against our extra space, right? Well, it's not that simple, because there is also the factor of piece activity. Watch our rook, it's about to do something really cool. }
10... Be7
{ The idea seems to be preventing  (or at least not allowing yet!)  the move Rh4. However, this seems fairly dubious, and that is because of two reasons. Now, as the game showed, the rook can enjoy itself on another equally good square − g4. Okay, so you wait with ...Nf6 to prevent Rh4. But at some point you have to play ...Nf6 anyway, don't you? And once you do, the rook still goes there, so what exactly is the accomplishment? }
11. Rg4
{ Black has to make some sort of concession.  11...g6  weakens the dark squares and allows  our bishop to land on h6, so it can hardly be recommended. However,  11...Bf6  , which was played in the game, takes the square away from the knight and is difficult to suggest, either. }
11... Bf6
{ Black defends the hanging pawn, trying to avoid having to make any pawn moves on the kingside, as doing that might prove fairly weakening.   11...g6  12.Bh6  leaves Black wondering what exactly to do next. For example, after  12...Nf6  13.Rf4  Nd5  14.Re4  Nf6  15.Re1±  , we might not have achieved much with our rook, but we did provoke a large concession on the kingside. Now, Black will have a very hard time castling. Even if castling is achieved, the dark squares will be very weak for the rest of the game. }
12. h4
{ White is immediately adding more kingside pressure. The last pawn move can be useful in a few ways, namely:  it creates support for White's pieces by controlling g5, so it's easy to jump there; it can advance to h5, restricting the g-pawn's ability to move; it can try to provoke either ...h7-h5, which makes Black's h-pawn a target and weakens the g5-square, or ...h7-h6, which would make our dark-squared bishop the happiest chess piece in the world, as prospects of a sacrifice on h6 become very real. }
12... c6
{ Black prevents any d4-d5 ideas, and more importantly, prepares a queen sortie. }
13. Qe2 { White improves the queen position and connects the rooks. } 13... Qa5
14. c4
{ And now White is able to take even more space in the center, controlling the b5 and d5-squares. }
14... O-O { Black castles, which was at some point necessary, of course. } 15.
Bd2
{ The Serbian GM just keeps making logical moves, winning another tempo by attacking the queen. The bishop will be placed perfectly on c3, from where it can eye down the g7-square. }
15... Qf5 16. Re4
{ Now, g2-g4!, trapping the queen, is a huge threat all of a sudden! } 16... h5
{ Black had to stop that. } 17. Rd1
{ But now, White just has a dominant position. Why so?  central domination; a lot more space; the h5-pawn can prove rather weak in the future; the g5-square is a hole White can try to use; the black queen is in a rather vulnerable and inactive position.  
Later on, White went on to win a wonderful game, which we should absolutely use as a model example of how to handle these positions, and as our theoretical guide. 1-0 Ivic-Ragger, Belgrade 2022. }
*

