7. O-O Ngf6
{ This is the very critical tabiya of the Jobava system. White has tried a ton of moves here, from the natural  8.Qe2  to the elegant  8.Ng3  or even the odd  8.Ned2  ,  looking to preserve as many pieces on the board as possible. But, I found a move that has been hardly ever seen  (in just 278 games out of 5000+!)  , and it seems to cause a ton of problems for Black. }
8. Re1
{ You'd think, what's the difference between this move and the more popular way of protecting the knight, which is  8.Qe2?  Hold on for a moment! }
8... Nxe4 { Black has to execute this trading idea; what else could be done? }
9. Bxe4 Bxe4 10. Rxe4
{ Here, we arrive at a crossroads: most people developed with  10...Nf6  , which is very logical; however, some tried  10...Be7  , keeping the knight on its original square. Bigger picture-wise, it seems as though Black has traded two pairs of pieces, so shouldn't have too many issues playing against our extra space, right? Well, it's not that simple, because there is also the factor of piece activity. Watch our rook, it's about to do something really cool. }
10... Nf6
{ And this is the position where I discovered a truly fascinating idea. Most people went  11.Re1  , while some tried to pin the knight with  11.Bg5  . But... why go back if we can go forward? }
11. Rh4
{ Yes! Exactly here! While it might seem as though we don't have that many pieces on the board and the attack won't be strong enough, I actually disagree. We can easily play Qd3, or Qc2 after moving the c-pawn, and put pressure on the h7-pawn. If Black goes ...h7-h6, there are always ideas related to the bishop sacrifice on h6.  Of course, it's also possible to use the knight for the attack, specifically by means of Ne5-g4. At the same time, it's crucial to remember we haven't by any means committed to attacking 'all-in', as we haven't sacrificed any material or made any positional concessions.  The only weird thing about our position is that if the rook on h4 won't find any use for itself, it'd be misplaced. Sure enough, that's true. However, if Black ever goes ...c7-c5 to challenge our central superiority, and then takes on d4, then our rook can easily get back in the center by just recapturing on d4! Amazingly, this very logical and principled move has never been played yet, which I think is a great chance for you to surprise your opponent! }
11... Be7
{ Black just keeps developing, which is very logical. Placing the bishop on e7 seems to make the most sense because now the move Bg5 won't result in a very annoying pin. }
12. c4
{ We take more space in the center, while also depriving the black knight of the d5-square and preparing to place our queen either on c2, putting more pressure on the h7-pawn and kingside overall, or maybe keeping in mind the option of jumping to b3 or a4! }
12... O-O
{ It's also possible to castle immediately, but now the kingside definitely becomes something Black should be worried about. }
13. Qc2
{ If the f6-knight disappears, Black would get mated on h7. That's why our next moves will be Bd2-c3 or Bg5. }
13... c6
{ Let's see what happens if Black adopts a passive waiting strategy and, rather than challenging our center, tries to restrict our ability to play d4-d5 while making room for the queen. }
14. Be3
{ Now, even this way of developing the bishop can make a lot of sense. What's the point of having it here? We simply overprotect the d4-pawn, preparing Ne5! on the next turn. }
14... Qa5 15. Ne5
{ Black seems to be in rough shape since we can attack on the kingside with moves like Ng4, or g2-g4, and Black has failed to obtain any counterplay whatsoever. Funnily enough, there could even be such unexpected threats as Nd7!, trying to distract the knight from defending the h7-pawn! This position is as bad as it looks for our opponent! }
*

