12... c5
{ It's imperative for Black to challenge and destroy some of our center. } 13.
Qc2
{ We continue as planned. The bishop would like to come to g5, especially if Black castles. However, it would also be really strong on c3 because then it's able to create a ton of pressure on the a1-h8 diagonal, which means threats like d4-d5 or dxc5, followed by taking the f6-knight and checkmating Black on h7, would always be in the air. }
13... cxd4
{ So, Black continues to unload the center, getting rid of our powerful d4-pawn. }
14. Rxd4
{ However, now the rook swings back into the center! Generally, it's hard to attack a flank when the center is open, so we are somewhat abandoning our kingside ambitions, focusing on central play instead. Now, Black has to make a very precise move because we're threatening to play Qa4+ and deprive Black of castling rights. The best reply to our threat is to maneuver the queen towards the c6-square  (via b6, c7, or c8)  in order to block the check. However, this results in a damaged pawn structure for Black. }
14... Qc7 15. Qa4+ Qc6 16. Qxc6+
{ This results in an endgame where Black's queenside pawns will be vulnerable in the long run. For example, we can consider harassing them with Rd3-a3, Be3, Ne5, and so on. }
