{ Here, we arrive at massive crossroads. White can lock up the center with e4-e5, take Black's pawn and open up the position, or defend the pawn with some knight move − either to c3 or to d2. }
3. Nc3
{ After a long thought, I decided to suggest this move, which is the most critical and ambitious one. Why did I do that and what's the point of this move? As we can see, we are simply protecting the e4-pawn while keeping the center flexible for now. It's important to do so for the following practical reason: most Black players who play the French @@StartBracket@@and I am one of them, I just wrote a course on French that I'm in love with!@@EndBracket@@ love positions with pawn chains. Our goal is to try to avoid creating one!  However, don't worry: while the move  3.Nc3  is known for being a very principled and theoretically heavy one, we won't need loads of theory − instead, I am opting for practical, easy-to-learn sidelines, which still carry quite a bit of punch, as always!  In this position, we'll need to consider quite a lot of moves. Black can try to pin the knight with  3...Bb4  , which is known as the Winawer Variation − the most forcing and sharp one. Black can also try to force us to lock up the center with the move  3...Nf6  , which is another major theoretical move. The passive yet solid decision is to play  3...dxe4  − the Rubinstein Variation. Black is hoping to avoid the pawn chain situation and trade down, liquidating White's hopes to get a spatial advantage or long-term pressure.  And, of course, there are quite a few sidelines, such as  3...Nc6  ,  3...Be7  − the move I suggested in my Black French course,  3...h6  ,  3...a6  , and so on. Let's tackle them all one by one! }
3... dxe4
{ This move defines what we know as the Rubinstein Variation of the French. Black immediately opens up the center, avoiding the standard positions with pawn chains. The upside for our opponent is that this variation avoids risking a standard outcome where Black ends up squeezed, lacking space and counterplay, and then slowly but surely losing on the kingside.   However, the bad news for Black is that we get a position with a noticeable steady advantage because our pawn on d4 is controlling more space/center than the one on e6 and because the c8-bishop is still a bad piece. Nevertheless, the Rubinstein Variation is a very solid way to play, and many strong GMs, such as the German player Georg Meier demonstrated this by using it to draw numerous top-10 level players. }
4. Nxe4
{ Here, Black is also at a bit of a crossroads. The main move is  4...Nd7  ,  the point being to play ...Ngf6 next, offering a knight trade, being able to recapture back with the knight to avoid doubling the pawns or having to get the queen out early.  However, due to the effort of the ever-creative Georgian GM Baadur Jobava, the odd-looking move  4...Bd7  came to life and started enjoying quite a lot of popularity. Black is trying to solve the standard problem of the bad bishop by  deploying it to c6 very fast, and likely trading it off on e4. }
4... Bd7
{ This odd move initiates what we know as the Jobava Variation of the Rubinstein system. It has been played before but caught up in popularity only in the last decade due to the effort of the ever-creative Georgian GM. What's the idea? Black knows the bishop is bad in the French positions because it's restricted by the e6-pawn, so Black tries to resolve this problem right away by placing it on c6 and then trading it off.  Overall, there is nothing 'wrong' either with the idea of this variation or with the execution. But, of course, executing this plan costs Black a lot of time and yields a very passive position. On a small personal note, when I was looking for an additional solid weapon for my Black French repertoire here on Chessable, I was considering writing a small chapter on this variation.  However, upon further investigation, I couldn't bring myself to do it: in many lines, the weaker/lazy White players can easily force a repetition/draw/a very dry position, but at the same time, the ambitious, strong, and knowledgeable White players can keep posing problems in front of Black nearly indefinitely.  So, I didn't see what would be the practical use case of this line and abandoned it. What you will see in this chapter is, actually, the line I got very scared of while trying to make this variation work for Black! }
5. Nf3 { We just keep developing. } 5... Bc6
{ And so does Black; nothing unexpected so far. } 6. Bd3
{ Some people retreat with the knight to g3, but most just defend it while developing the bishop, and that's what I recommend doing as well.   Now, Black would normally play  6...Nd7  , continuing development and  preparing ...Ngf6 − this happened in nearly 90% of the games. However, some people also tried other moves, such as immediately capturing on e4. }
6... Nd7
{ Black is preparing the standard idea: ...Nf6, and if White takes, take back with the knight, centralizing it, but avoiding having to deploy the queen early on. }
7. O-O Ngf6
{ This is the very critical tabiya of the Jobava system. White has tried a ton of moves here, from the natural  8.Qe2  to the elegant  8.Ng3  or even the odd  8.Ned2  ,  looking to preserve as many pieces on the board as possible. But, I found a move that has been hardly ever seen  (in just 278 games out of 5000+!)  , and it seems to cause a ton of problems for Black. }
8. Re1
{ You'd think, what's the difference between this move and the more popular way of protecting the knight, which is  8.Qe2?  Hold on for a moment! }
8... Nxe4 { Black has to execute this trading idea; what else could be done? }
9. Bxe4 Bxe4 10. Rxe4
{ Here, we arrive at a crossroads: most people developed with  10...Nf6  , which is very logical; however, some tried  10...Be7  , keeping the knight on its original square. Bigger picture-wise, it seems as though Black has traded two pairs of pieces, so shouldn't have too many issues playing against our extra space, right? Well, it's not that simple, because there is also the factor of piece activity. Watch our rook, it's about to do something really cool. }
10... Nf6
{ And this is the position where I discovered a truly fascinating idea. Most people went  11.Re1  , while some tried to pin the knight with  11.Bg5  . But... why go back if we can go forward? }
11. Rh4
{ Yes! Exactly here! While it might seem as though we don't have that many pieces on the board and the attack won't be strong enough, I actually disagree. We can easily play Qd3, or Qc2 after moving the c-pawn, and put pressure on the h7-pawn. If Black goes ...h7-h6, there are always ideas related to the bishop sacrifice on h6.  Of course, it's also possible to use the knight for the attack, specifically by means of Ne5-g4. At the same time, it's crucial to remember we haven't by any means committed to attacking 'all-in', as we haven't sacrificed any material or made any positional concessions.  The only weird thing about our position is that if the rook on h4 won't find any use for itself, it'd be misplaced. Sure enough, that's true. However, if Black ever goes ...c7-c5 to challenge our central superiority, and then takes on d4, then our rook can easily get back in the center by just recapturing on d4! Amazingly, this very logical and principled move has never been played yet, which I think is a great chance for you to surprise your opponent! }
11... Be7
{ Black just keeps developing, which is very logical. Placing the bishop on e7 seems to make the most sense because now the move Bg5 won't result in a very annoying pin. }
12. c4
{ We take more space in the center, while also depriving the black knight of the d5-square and preparing to place our queen either on c2, putting more pressure on the h7-pawn and kingside overall, or maybe keeping in mind the option of jumping to b3 or a4! }
12... c5
{ It's imperative for Black to challenge and destroy some of our center. } 13.
Qc2
{ We continue as planned. The bishop would like to come to g5, especially if Black castles. However, it would also be really strong on c3 because then it's able to create a ton of pressure on the a1-h8 diagonal, which means threats like d4-d5 or dxc5, followed by taking the f6-knight and checkmating Black on h7, would always be in the air. }
13... cxd4
{ So, Black continues to unload the center, getting rid of our powerful d4-pawn. }
14. Rxd4
{ However, now the rook swings back into the center! Generally, it's hard to attack a flank when the center is open, so we are somewhat abandoning our kingside ambitions, focusing on central play instead. Now, Black has to make a very precise move because we're threatening to play Qa4+ and deprive Black of castling rights. The best reply to our threat is to maneuver the queen towards the c6-square  (via b6, c7, or c8)  in order to block the check. However, this results in a damaged pawn structure for Black. }
14... Qa5 { Black has to prevent the aforementioned check. } 15. Bd2
{ But, now we get to develop even more pieces with tempi. } 15... Qa6
{ The queen has to keep controlling the a4-square. } 16. b4
{ Now, we're gladly taking a lot of space on the queenside. } 16... O-O 17. c5
{ We keep restricting Black even further. Next, a2-a4 and b4-b5 are on the agenda. Please note that the black queen is completely out of the game! Also, it's not a concern at all that we are giving up the d5-square, and that is for a few reasons.  The knight on d5, while beautifully placed, won't be attacking anything. If the knight walks away from the kingside, suddenly the kingside attack ideas, like Rg4, Bh6, etc, start becoming scary again! }
17... Nd5 18. a4
{ We are threatening to trap the queen with b4-b5 on the very next turn. And, even though that can be avoided, there is not much to argue about when it comes to the evaluation of this position.  Black has no counterplay whatsoever; all the pieces are a lot less active than ours. Of course, our tremendously impressive spatial advantage on the queenside and ability to develop the initiative on both parts of the board doesn't hurt, either. White is nearly winning. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4) Classical French 4.Bg5 Be7"]
[Black "Classical French 4.Bg5 Be7 5.e5 Ne4"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6
{ This move, followed by ...d7-d5, defines something called the French Defense. This opening is about fighting for the center rather ambitiously while avoiding direct piece play. As you will see, the first two moves only feature pawn play. The downside for Black is the locked-up light-squared bishop, and very often, this piece tends to be a large issue for quite a long time. }
2. d4 d5
{ Here, we arrive at massive crossroads. White can lock up the center with e4-e5, take Black's pawn and open up the position, or defend the pawn with some knight move − either to c3 or to d2. }
3. Nc3
{ After a long thought, I decided to suggest this move, which is the most critical and ambitious one. Why did I do that and what's the point of this move? As we can see, we are simply protecting the e4-pawn while keeping the center flexible for now. It's important to do so for the following practical reason: most Black players who play the French @@StartBracket@@and I am one of them, I just wrote a course on French that I'm in love with!@@EndBracket@@ love positions with pawn chains. Our goal is to try to avoid creating one!  However, don't worry: while the move  3.Nc3  is known for being a very principled and theoretically heavy one, we won't need loads of theory − instead, I am opting for practical, easy-to-learn sidelines, which still carry quite a bit of punch, as always!  In this position, we'll need to consider quite a lot of moves. Black can try to pin the knight with  3...Bb4  , which is known as the Winawer Variation − the most forcing and sharp one. Black can also try to force us to lock up the center with the move  3...Nf6  , which is another major theoretical move. The passive yet solid decision is to play  3...dxe4  − the Rubinstein Variation. Black is hoping to avoid the pawn chain situation and trade down, liquidating White's hopes to get a spatial advantage or long-term pressure.  And, of course, there are quite a few sidelines, such as  3...Nc6  ,  3...Be7  − the move I suggested in my Black French course,  3...h6  ,  3...a6  , and so on. Let's tackle them all one by one! }
3... Nf6
{ The Classical Variation − one of the two best theoretical ways for Black to continue. Black is putting pressure on the e4-pawn, seeking to provoke the move e4-e5, which would lock up the center and create a position with pawn chains. This is exactly what most French Defense players live for! }
4. Bg5
{ This, along with e4-e5, is one of White's two most popular moves. I prefer it because it seems to be giving us more choices than the opponent. Instead, after  4.e5  , Black can choose among a dozen decent lines, which means it's not only difficult to analyze all of them and try to get an advantage of any kind. You will also be at a practical disadvantage since the opponent is the one dictating how the game will go.  Here, we need to investigate 4 moves. The most popular continuation is @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp2ppp/4pn2/3p2B1/3PP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R2QKBNR b KQkq - 3 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Be7  , which is a quiet way to play. A rather passive continuation, which is also quite frequent, is  4...dxe4  − we can call it a slightly improved version of the Rubinstein Variation, and that is because  we have already committed to playing Bg5, which somewhat narrows down our options.   Then, there is, of course, a pretty sharp move:  4...Bb4  . It can, if both parties are willing, very rapidly result in really murky positions. However, it doesn't have to, as we will see − we will politely decline the invitation for a carnage. Finally, the move  4...h6  , which people hadn't thought was possible in the past, is starting to gain some traction, and is not nearly as bad as one might think, so we will also investigate that one! }
4... Be7
{ This is Black's most popular and quiet way to play. We were intending to go e4-e5 and cause the opponent problems, as the knight was pinned. So, Black just unpins it, while also developing a piece. }
5. e5
{ Given the pawn was hanging, we couldn't wait much longer. We lock up the center and create a position with pawn chains, but with a slight difference compared to the @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp2ppp/4pn2/3p4/3PP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 2 4@@EndFEN@@  4.e5  lines. What is that difference? We will trade the dark-squared bishops! This exchange has, of course, both advantages and cons.   On one hand, we are glad to trade those bishops, since we have already placed our central pawns on the dark squares d4 and e5, and plan on placing another one on f4. With so many pawns on the dark squares, the dark-squared bishop, naturally, tends to be rather bad.  However, there is also a downside to that trade. Specifically, Black has less space, so trades of almost any kind tend to benefit the opponent for that reason. Of course, I still like what we are doing, or else we wouldn't be going in this direction! But, it's important you are aware that almost any decision, including this one, might have some downsides to it. }
5... Ne4
{ This has been tried on a few occasions, but it's a pretty bad move: Black will just get a weak pawn on e4. }
6. Bxe7 { First, we trade the bishops. } 6... Qxe7 7. Nxe4 { And the knights! }
7... dxe4
{ Now, the e4-pawn appears terminally ill. However, you need to be a little careful to make sure the move ...Qb4+ doesn't end up forking our king and the b2-pawn. }
8. Qe2
{ We attack the pawn, while also getting ready to meet ...Qb4+ with c2-c3. I don't believe it's worth going in tremendous detail analyzing this line, so we'll look at Black's most popular move only. }
8... b6
{ Black is trying to develop the bishop to b7 to protect the pawn, taking advantage of the fact we cannot yet win it because of that nasty ...Qb4+. }
9. O-O-O { Now, the pawn is threatened. } 9... Bb7 10. g3
{ We are about to go Bg2 and get the pawn very shortly. Of course, moves like ...e4-e3 won't do anything, since we'll just reply f2-f3, blocking the diagonal, and will win the pawn shortly after. Frankly, I think stopping looking at this variation right here isn't a bad idea at all. However, I would like to show you a few more moves, just in case, as it looks as though Black can actually get some counterplay. }
10... c5
{ If Black wants to avoid just losing a pawn for nothing, Black absolutely needs to counterattack our center right away, trying to ruin it. }
11. Bg2 { We keep developing, getting ready to win the e4-pawn. } 11... Nc6
{ The center is under a bit too much pressure, which means we have to do something about that. }
12. dxc5 { We are going to win the e4-pawn. } 12... Qg5+
{ Trying to get the e5-pawn with the queen. } 13. Kb1 Qxe5 14. cxb6
{ We avoid losing the c5-pawn and are about to just be a pawn up. } 14... f5
{ Seems forced, as otherwise Black loses the e4-pawn and allows us to dramatically activate the light-squared bishop. }
15. f3
{ The e4-pawn is about to fall. If that happens, Black will just be lost. }
15... e3
{ However, trying to avoid that scenario doesn't work, as we'll easily pick up the weak e3-pawn. }
16. f4
{ We activate the bishop first and win a tempo, and then take the pawn on e3 with Rd3-e3 at any moment of our choosing. The pawn is dead, so we don't have to hurry. In fact, it's even better to not hurry and simply develop the kingside knight first, and then pick the pawn up naturally with Rhe1! and Qxe3.  Black's pieces are passive, the structure is bad, and the pressure on the e6-pawn, down the h1-a8 diagonal, and on the d-file is rather noticeable... Plus, Black is about to be a pawn down. The game is over, boys and girls! }
*

