{ This is Black's most popular and quiet way to play. We were intending to go e4-e5 and cause the opponent problems, as the knight was pinned. So, Black just unpins it, while also developing a piece. }
5. e5
{ Given the pawn was hanging, we couldn't wait much longer. We lock up the center and create a position with pawn chains, but with a slight difference compared to the @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp2ppp/4pn2/3p4/3PP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 2 4@@EndFEN@@  4.e5  lines. What is that difference? We will trade the dark-squared bishops! This exchange has, of course, both advantages and cons.   On one hand, we are glad to trade those bishops, since we have already placed our central pawns on the dark squares d4 and e5, and plan on placing another one on f4. With so many pawns on the dark squares, the dark-squared bishop, naturally, tends to be rather bad.  However, there is also a downside to that trade. Specifically, Black has less space, so trades of almost any kind tend to benefit the opponent for that reason. Of course, I still like what we are doing, or else we wouldn't be going in this direction! But, it's important you are aware that almost any decision, including this one, might have some downsides to it. }
5... Nfd7 6. Bxe7 Qxe7 7. Qd2
{ We are continuing the natural development. It might seem as though White is only interested in castling queenside next, but actually, there is one more very cool idea coming up. As you hopefully remember, a typical fear of any White player while facing the French, is that their big beautiful center will get destroyed with ...c7-c5 or ...f7-f6. We are able to meet the latter with f2-f4, but what about the former?  For now, as we'll see, Black is unable to play this move. But in the future, Black will! That's why our mini-plan is to go Nd1!, rerouting the knight to e3, where it is likely to prove useful in the upcoming kingside play, while also preparing to meet ...c7-c5 with c2-c3! Even in the opening, it's crucial to think of prophylaxis. }
7... c5 { A tempting, but a really bad move. } 8. Nb5
{ Black cannot prevent us from landing the knight on d6 with check; an attempt to do so will blunder the rook to Nc7. Once the knight lands on d6, Black is clearly going to regret being so hasty and careless. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4) Classical French 4.Bg5 Be7"]
[Black "Classical French 4.Bg5 Be7 5.e5 Nfd7 #3 − Informational 8.Nd1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6
{ This move, followed by ...d7-d5, defines something called the French Defense. This opening is about fighting for the center rather ambitiously while avoiding direct piece play. As you will see, the first two moves only feature pawn play. The downside for Black is the locked-up light-squared bishop, and very often, this piece tends to be a large issue for quite a long time. }
2. d4 d5
{ Here, we arrive at massive crossroads. White can lock up the center with e4-e5, take Black's pawn and open up the position, or defend the pawn with some knight move − either to c3 or to d2. }
3. Nc3
{ After a long thought, I decided to suggest this move, which is the most critical and ambitious one. Why did I do that and what's the point of this move? As we can see, we are simply protecting the e4-pawn while keeping the center flexible for now. It's important to do so for the following practical reason: most Black players who play the French @@StartBracket@@and I am one of them, I just wrote a course on French that I'm in love with!@@EndBracket@@ love positions with pawn chains. Our goal is to try to avoid creating one!  However, don't worry: while the move  3.Nc3  is known for being a very principled and theoretically heavy one, we won't need loads of theory − instead, I am opting for practical, easy-to-learn sidelines, which still carry quite a bit of punch, as always!  In this position, we'll need to consider quite a lot of moves. Black can try to pin the knight with  3...Bb4  , which is known as the Winawer Variation − the most forcing and sharp one. Black can also try to force us to lock up the center with the move  3...Nf6  , which is another major theoretical move. The passive yet solid decision is to play  3...dxe4  − the Rubinstein Variation. Black is hoping to avoid the pawn chain situation and trade down, liquidating White's hopes to get a spatial advantage or long-term pressure.  And, of course, there are quite a few sidelines, such as  3...Nc6  ,  3...Be7  − the move I suggested in my Black French course,  3...h6  ,  3...a6  , and so on. Let's tackle them all one by one! }
3... Nf6
{ The Classical Variation − one of the two best theoretical ways for Black to continue. Black is putting pressure on the e4-pawn, seeking to provoke the move e4-e5, which would lock up the center and create a position with pawn chains. This is exactly what most French Defense players live for! }
4. Bg5
{ This, along with e4-e5, is one of White's two most popular moves. I prefer it because it seems to be giving us more choices than the opponent. Instead, after  4.e5  , Black can choose among a dozen decent lines, which means it's not only difficult to analyze all of them and try to get an advantage of any kind. You will also be at a practical disadvantage since the opponent is the one dictating how the game will go.  Here, we need to investigate 4 moves. The most popular continuation is @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp2ppp/4pn2/3p2B1/3PP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R2QKBNR b KQkq - 3 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Be7  , which is a quiet way to play. A rather passive continuation, which is also quite frequent, is  4...dxe4  − we can call it a slightly improved version of the Rubinstein Variation, and that is because  we have already committed to playing Bg5, which somewhat narrows down our options.   Then, there is, of course, a pretty sharp move:  4...Bb4  . It can, if both parties are willing, very rapidly result in really murky positions. However, it doesn't have to, as we will see − we will politely decline the invitation for a carnage. Finally, the move  4...h6  , which people hadn't thought was possible in the past, is starting to gain some traction, and is not nearly as bad as one might think, so we will also investigate that one! }
4... Be7
{ This is Black's most popular and quiet way to play. We were intending to go e4-e5 and cause the opponent problems, as the knight was pinned. So, Black just unpins it, while also developing a piece. }
5. e5
{ Given the pawn was hanging, we couldn't wait much longer. We lock up the center and create a position with pawn chains, but with a slight difference compared to the @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp2ppp/4pn2/3p4/3PP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 2 4@@EndFEN@@  4.e5  lines. What is that difference? We will trade the dark-squared bishops! This exchange has, of course, both advantages and cons.   On one hand, we are glad to trade those bishops, since we have already placed our central pawns on the dark squares d4 and e5, and plan on placing another one on f4. With so many pawns on the dark squares, the dark-squared bishop, naturally, tends to be rather bad.  However, there is also a downside to that trade. Specifically, Black has less space, so trades of almost any kind tend to benefit the opponent for that reason. Of course, I still like what we are doing, or else we wouldn't be going in this direction! But, it's important you are aware that almost any decision, including this one, might have some downsides to it. }
5... Nfd7 6. Bxe7 Qxe7 7. Qd2
{ We are continuing the natural development. It might seem as though White is only interested in castling queenside next, but actually, there is one more very cool idea coming up. As you hopefully remember, a typical fear of any White player while facing the French, is that their big beautiful center will get destroyed with ...c7-c5 or ...f7-f6. We are able to meet the latter with f2-f4, but what about the former?  For now, as we'll see, Black is unable to play this move. But in the future, Black will! That's why our mini-plan is to go Nd1!, rerouting the knight to e3, where it is likely to prove useful in the upcoming kingside play, while also preparing to meet ...c7-c5 with c2-c3! Even in the opening, it's crucial to think of prophylaxis. }
7... O-O
{ This is also a popular and logical way to play. However, after deep analysis, I have doubts about the reliability of Black's position. }
8. Nd1
{ Nd1 does not look like a great idea now that we are sort of a tempo down compared to the ...a7-a6 line, because castling is a much more useful move. But, it's worth seeing why this move is no longer appealing. }
8... c5 { Black starts by undermining the center in this standard way. } 9. c3
Nc6 10. f4 { So far so good, right? } 10... f6
{ Of course, this move is the one causing us problems. Why so? This position is a classic example of a battle between two advantages: static and dynamic. In the long run, our center is fabulous. It's restricting the opponent's pieces tremendously, while also offering our pieces endless opportunities for maneuvering.  However, in the short run, we have development issues. So, if Black wants to get an enjoyable game, has to challenge us very fast, before we're done developing. And the way to do so is known: open up as many files and diagonals as possible! }
11. Nf3
{ Looks like we're peacefully continuing development, right? Not exactly... }
11... cxd4
{ First, Black captures this pawn. As we are about to discover, it's not as much to open up the c-file as it is to make the d4-pawn more vulnerable. }
12. cxd4 fxe5 { Now, the f-file is opening up. } 13. fxe5 Rxf3
{ And now we see the actual problem. With this fairly standard exchange sacrifice, Black ruins our pawn structure, weakens our king, and wins the d4-pawn. }
14. gxf3 Qh4+
{ The d4-pawn is going to fall, and likely so will the one on e5. Our pieces aren't very developed and the rooks don't have an opportunity to use any open files to a great benefit. Naturally, we can conclude Black is taking over, so this should be avoided by all means! }
