9. Nf3
{ That's alright. We just keep developing, reinforcing the d4-pawn with a piece instead. }
9... Nc6 10. dxc5
{ Now, we are ready to release the tension. Generally, there are two main ways to play the arising position:  Try to attack Black on the kingside by means of such ideas as Bd3, h2-h4-h5, Ng5, Rh3-g3, etc. Try to play for positional advantage due to the d4-square being an outpost and the c8-bishop being inactive. That typically involves trying to trade down everything, but leaving the knight on d4 versus Black's light-squared bishop.  
Sometimes, interestingly enough, these absolutely opposite-looking plans end up... combined. How can that happen, you would ask? Typically, that's because we are launching a kingside attack, and Black manages to neutralize it by trading pieces, which results in the aforementioned endgame that is rather attractive for us. }
10... Nxc5
{ This is the more popular and more logical recapture. The knight gets out of the way, so the queenside pieces can start getting out. }
11. O-O-O
{ We continue with our plan. Next, we'd love to play Bd3, Ne2, h2-h4-h5, etc, as discussed earlier. }
11... a6
{ Black is trying to prepare queenside counterplay by looking to expand with ...b7-b5-b4. That makes perfect sense in this position with kings tucked away on opposite sides of the board. }
12. Qe3
{ I like this little move, which accomplishes various things:  It puts pressure on the knight, making it harder for the queen to move; for example, it cannot go to c7-a5, or to f6 after a potential ...f7-f6 break. It frees up the rook's ability to control the d4-square. It discourages the ...f7-f6 break because, after exf6, the e6-pawn becomes weak, and there are tactical ideas of exploiting the pin on the e-file with Nxd5!? at some point. }
12... b5 { Black follows up with the logical plan of queenside expansion. } 13.
Bd3
{ We are developing the bishop to the most active square, starting to point at the potential Greek Gift sacrifice ideas. }
13... Nxd3+
{ It seems logical for Black to get rid of our most powerful attacking piece as soon as possible. }
14. Rxd3 b4 { Black keeps advancing the queenside pawns. } 15. Ne2
{ But the knight wanted to go here anyway. The point is that on the next turn, it can go to d4, starting to enjoy the lovely outpost. }
15... a5 16. Nfd4
{ While it really shouldn't matter which knight to install here, since after Black takes and we take back, it's just a transposition, I want to point out one extra opportunity this specific move allows: now, the 3rd rank is open, which means ideas like Qh3 and Rg3 are becoming available! }
16... Nxd4 17. Nxd4 Ba6
{ It's crucial for Black to play this active move now. If Black were to wait, the rook would be able to move away to g3 or h3, which would be much worse for our opponent. }
18. Rd2 { But now, a bit unfortunately, it has to go back. } 18... a4
{ This was seen in the game 1-0 Horvath-Karthikeyan, Canberra 2012. Black keeps advancing the queenside pawns. There are no real threats yet, but we do need to be paying some attention. }
19. f5
{ And here, instead of the prophylactical move  19.Kb1  White made in the game,  I'd like to offer a novelty. We are also starting to create a lot of tension on the kingside! The opponent always has to be careful about f5-f6! coming up at some point. For example, if we could play Rf1, then f5-f6, Black took and we took back with the e-pawn, then the f6-pawn would create a wonderful mating net, and Qh6-g7 would likely become an unstoppable threat. }
19... Rfc8
{ Black moves the rook away to make room for defensive moves like ...Qf8 or ...Kf8, as well as to create more pressure on our king. }
20. Kb1 { And we gladly remove the king from the c-file. } 20... b3
{ This doesn't make much sense, as the 'attack' gets shut down forever. } 21.
cxb3 axb3 22. a3
{ The only bad thing that could ever happen would be if Black could move the bishop away, then sacrifice the rook on a3, and then somehow checkmate us, say, with ...Qxa3, ...b3-b2 and ...Qa1+, but that won't ever happen, as there aren't enough pieces left on the board for an attack after a rook sacrifice.  Just keep your rook around and meet the sacrifice with Rb2! at the end, or Qc3!, and you're safe. On the other hand, our attack will develop flawlessly after g2-g4-g5-g6, or f5-f6. White should be winning at this point. }
