10... f6
{ This seems to be Black's best shot at equality @@StartBracket@@and even counterplay!@@EndBracket@@ in the entire @@StartFEN@@rnb1k2r/1ppnqppp/p3p3/3pP3/3P4/2N5/PPPQ1PPP/R3KBNR w KQkq - 0 8@@EndFEN@@  8.Nd1!?  variation. }
11. Nf3
{ We just keep getting our pieces out. Remember, we have a long-term advantage because of our space, while Black has the dynamic one because Black can quickly castle and start putting pressure on the d4-pawn, the f3-knight, and so on. All we need is to stabilize our position. If we manage to do so, our spatial advantage will give the opponent a very hard time. }
11... cxd4
{ Black is trading this pair of pawns first to make the d4-pawn weaker. We'll see in a moment why that matters. }
12. cxd4 fxe5 { Now, Black is opening up the f-file. } 13. fxe5 O-O
{ And here, we need to be very careful. But wait, careful about what? Doesn't the center look very solid? The problem is that Black is about to take on f3. By sacrificing an exchange, Black will ruin our kingside structure and weaken the d4-pawn, and then win it with ...Qh4+! }
14. Nf2
{ By activating the knight, we also block the e1-h4 diagonal, preventing the idea of ...Rxf3 and ...Qh4+. Subtle prophylaxis!   14.Bd3?!  is an example of careless play. Now, after  14...Rxf3!  15.gxf3  Qh4+  16.Qf2  Qxd4  , Black gets wonderful compensation for the missing exchange due to:  having a pawn for it; the e5-pawn being very weak; the f-pawn being backward; the rooks having no open files to take advantage of. This is ABSOLUTELY something to avoid! }
14... Nb6
{ Black needs to activate the knight, threatening to come to the active c4-square with it. By doing so, Black also enables the bishop to come out to d7, which is really important, since it facilitates:  the standard ...Bd7-e8-h5! idea, getting rid of Black's bad bishop; the ...Rc8 move, starting to fight for the open c-file, and connecting the rooks. }
15. b3 { We prevent ...Nc4, of course, leaving the knight out of work. } 15...
Bd7
{ Black is starting to improve the bad bishop, which is a very natural and good plan. }
16. Be2 Be8
{ The bishop is about to come to h5. If Black does that, will likely want to swap it with ...Bxf3, decreasing the spatial advantage. }
17. O-O
{ But, we can still continue developing. There are no threats yet that we should be reacting to. }
17... Bh5 18. Rac1 { Now, it's time to start fighting for the c-file. } 18...
a5 { Black is looking to get counterplay by opening up the a-file. } 19. Qe3
{ This position was achieved in a game between two low-rated players, but it was a correspondence game, so no wonder they played nearly perfectly. ½-½ Gubo-Reede, LSS email 2014. I believe this variation is the best one for Black in the entire @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp2ppp/4pn2/3p4/3PP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 2 4@@EndFEN@@  4.Bg5  Be7  system, as it enables Black to avoid a typical passive position with a lack of space. Later on, the game was drawn.   I think Black is quite close to achieving equality here, but the position is not exactly there yet. Why did White make the last move? It is for a few reasons:  To enable the Nd3-c5 idea. Previously, it wasn't possible, since playing Nd3 would prevent our queen from protecting the d4-pawn and allow for ...Bxf3 followed by ...Nxd4. To overprotect the e5-pawn and the c5-square. That is important because if you ever play Rc5, you don't want to run into ...Nxe5, when dxe5 leaves the c5-rook unprotected.  
Later, we'd like to play Nd3-c5, or maybe Rc5 and Rfc1. Potentially, the move a2-a4 might be not a bad one. It would create an outpost on b4 for the black pieces but prevent ...a5-a4. If Black wants to play ...a5-a4 and ...axb3 right now, Black will get some activity down the a-file, but nothing for us to worry about, as there are no targets/weaknesses in our position.  Another thing worth mentioning is that while opening up the f-file was a great idea for our opponent since it activated the rook and enabled the ...Bd7-e8-h5 maneuver, it also had a major downside. What downside? Now the e6-pawn is weak! That's why, if we ever play Nd3-c5, Black would always have to babysit that pawn. Not exactly a pleasant thing to have to do!  So, all in all, this is a position where Black almost equalized, but we are still enjoying some pressure due to all the aforementioned factors. But, in the other lines, Black seems to be doing even worse, so this is the best choice, I believe. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5) Classical French 4.Bg5 h6"]
[Black "Classical French 4.Bg5 h6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6
{ This move, followed by ...d7-d5, defines something called the French Defense. This opening is about fighting for the center rather ambitiously while avoiding direct piece play. As you will see, the first two moves only feature pawn play. The downside for Black is the locked-up light-squared bishop, and very often, this piece tends to be a large issue for quite a long time. }
2. d4 d5
{ Here, we arrive at massive crossroads. White can lock up the center with e4-e5, take Black's pawn and open up the position, or defend the pawn with some knight move − either to c3 or to d2. }
3. Nc3
{ After a long thought, I decided to suggest this move, which is the most critical and ambitious one. Why did I do that and what's the point of this move? As we can see, we are simply protecting the e4-pawn while keeping the center flexible for now. It's important to do so for the following practical reason: most Black players who play the French @@StartBracket@@and I am one of them, I just wrote a course on French that I'm in love with!@@EndBracket@@ love positions with pawn chains. Our goal is to try to avoid creating one!  However, don't worry: while the move  3.Nc3  is known for being a very principled and theoretically heavy one, we won't need loads of theory − instead, I am opting for practical, easy-to-learn sidelines, which still carry quite a bit of punch, as always!  In this position, we'll need to consider quite a lot of moves. Black can try to pin the knight with  3...Bb4  , which is known as the Winawer Variation − the most forcing and sharp one. Black can also try to force us to lock up the center with the move  3...Nf6  , which is another major theoretical move. The passive yet solid decision is to play  3...dxe4  − the Rubinstein Variation. Black is hoping to avoid the pawn chain situation and trade down, liquidating White's hopes to get a spatial advantage or long-term pressure.  And, of course, there are quite a few sidelines, such as  3...Nc6  ,  3...Be7  − the move I suggested in my Black French course,  3...h6  ,  3...a6  , and so on. Let's tackle them all one by one! }
3... Nf6
{ The Classical Variation − one of the two best theoretical ways for Black to continue. Black is putting pressure on the e4-pawn, seeking to provoke the move e4-e5, which would lock up the center and create a position with pawn chains. This is exactly what most French Defense players live for! }
4. Bg5
{ This, along with e4-e5, is one of White's two most popular moves. I prefer it because it seems to be giving us more choices than the opponent. Instead, after  4.e5  , Black can choose among a dozen decent lines, which means it's not only difficult to analyze all of them and try to get an advantage of any kind. You will also be at a practical disadvantage since the opponent is the one dictating how the game will go.  Here, we need to investigate 4 moves. The most popular continuation is @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp2ppp/4pn2/3p2B1/3PP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R2QKBNR b KQkq - 3 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Be7  , which is a quiet way to play. A rather passive continuation, which is also quite frequent, is  4...dxe4  − we can call it a slightly improved version of the Rubinstein Variation, and that is because  we have already committed to playing Bg5, which somewhat narrows down our options.   Then, there is, of course, a pretty sharp move:  4...Bb4  . It can, if both parties are willing, very rapidly result in really murky positions. However, it doesn't have to, as we will see − we will politely decline the invitation for a carnage. Finally, the move  4...h6  , which people hadn't thought was possible in the past, is starting to gain some traction, and is not nearly as bad as one might think, so we will also investigate that one! }
4... h6
{ This weird move, which seems to be just losing a pawn, has been only seen in 300 games or so. Compare it to  4...Be7  ,  which has been played nearly 30 000 times! However, this rare unexpected idea  (a real pawn sacrifice)  is quickly gaining in popularity and is not a bad way to play. In fact, I consider it to be one of the best lines against 4.Bg5, and if anything, the most practical line by far. Black can cut the workload by 90% by using it, as Black only needs to know a couple of ideas. }
5. Bxf6
{ We have to take, of course, or else we'd lose a pawn.  5.Bh4?  just loses a pawn after  5...g5  6.Bg3  Nxe4  7.Nxe4  dxe4∓  . }
5... Qxf6 6. a3
{ That's right, instead of accepting a seemingly free pawn, my main recommendation would be this unexpected prophylactic move, which has been only seen in 5 games so far − 3 of them played last year. We prevent the annoying ...Bb4 pin and threaten to capture the d5-pawn on the next turn. Black, of course, can avoid losing it, but our idea is to force play into the Rubinstein-style structure, where Black is very passive, despite the recently-acquired bishop pair.   Nevertheless,  6.exd5  offers a risk-free way of playing, so I would also give you this option as an alternative. }
6... c6
{ Tried in two games by GM-level Black players. The point of Black's move is to defend the d5-pawn and avoid having to release the tension.  6...Qd8  7.f4Ν  results in a similar position as the one after @@StartFEN@@rnb1kb1r/ppp2pp1/4pq1p/3p4/3PP3/P1N5/1PP2PPP/R2QKBNR b KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6...c6  7.Qd2  . }
7. Qd2
{ I like this unexpected move. The idea is to potentially prepare queenside castling, it seems. That's not a wrong observation, but the most important idea behind our last move is a slightly different one. We are not developing the g1-knight yet, and that's because we want to take as much space as possible with f2-f4!, and only then go Nf3. What would Black do about this plan? We don't know, because it's a brand-new position, but we can make some logical assumptions. }
7... Qd8
{ It seems fairly reasonable to remove the queen off the weird f6-square in advance, so that, for example, after ...Be7, the queen isn't oddly stuck in the middle of a board. }
8. f4 Be7
{ Black can also keep the tension for now. That's fine, we just keep developing. }
9. Nf3 O-O 10. Bd3 Nd7
{ At this point, I think it's worth starting the kingside attack. } 11. e5
{ First, we lock up the center. It's easy enough to make sure it doesn't fall apart since the f4-pawn is greatly helping when it comes to stabilizing the center. Why is this move instrumental when it comes to starting the kingside attack? That's an easy one, guys! That's because every flank attack is much more powerful when the center is closed. And, of course, the opposite holds true: if your opponent attacks on a flank, the right thing to do is to look for a pawn break in the center. }
11... c5 12. h4
{ With g2-g4-g5 coming next, I would be really scared to be Black in this fresh and unexplored position. }
*

