{ However, Black's position here doesn't seem all that great. Sure enough, Black has the bishop pair, but the board isn't open yet. On the other hand, we enjoy spatial advantage thanks to our d4-pawn, and better development − we already have a piece in the center, another one is coming in, and Black hasn't made a single developing move yet because time was wasted moving the queen around. }
8. Nf3
{ Surprisingly, no one has ever tried this natural move. We just develop a knight for now, not yet making a decision regarding what to do with the rest of the pieces. }
8... Be7 9. Bd3 O-O 10. Qe2
{ I think this position is extremely dangerous for Black because the kingside has no defenders; for example, the f6-knight is gone. Additionally, Black had already created a hook for our upcoming attack by playing ...h7-h6, which means ideas like g2-g4-g5 are much easier to carry out and are much more effective too. }
10... Nd7 11. O-O-O
{ With g2-g4, h2-h4, and g4-g5 coming next, it seems Black will just get mated. And, as you can observe, Black hasn't yet created any counterplay. At all! So, we should be nearly winning. }
