5. Nxe4 Be7
{ Black breaks the pin, looking to trade pieces, and, of course, threatening to win our knight on e4 on the next turn. }
6. Nxf6+
{ For the purpose of this repertoire, which was meant to be positional, restrictive, and simple to learn, I chose this move, because it forces positions that are symmetrical, or nearly so, with slight pressure on Black's position, and where Black doesn't have much counterplay if any.  This move also has another advantage, which is a considerable one in my eyes: it's 7@@StartBracket@@!@@EndBracket@@ times less popular than taking on f6 with the bishop, which means Black is much less likely to know well what to do here.   6.Bxf6  is the more complex line, because after  6...gxf6  , we get a position where Black has the open g-file and a bishop pair, while we have more space in the center and a better structure. Imbalance at its finest! There is nothing wrong with this line, I just don't want to dive into it, as it's too complex. }
6... gxf6
{ This is not nearly as good here because while Black does spoil the structure and opens up the g-file, Black does not get the bishop pair, which tends to be one of the backbones in this variation. As a result, Black will find it difficult to get counterplay, which will likely lead to a passive position. }
7. Be3
{ We retreat and protect the d4-pawn, so that if Black ever goes ...Nc6, we don't need to waste time defending it. Also, if Black ever wants to play ...c7-c5, having a bishop on e3 makes it much more difficult, since we can just take and try to hold on to the pawn! }
7... b6
{ Whenever this position arose, in most cases, Black would try to fianchetto the light-squared bishop. Here, I feel White has a very tempting idea, which hasn't yet caught up in popularity, but which absolutely deserves to do so. }
8. Qf3
{ Black is forced to either block the diagonal with ...c7-c6 or offer a queen trade. This move forces matters and prevents Black from managing to develop and get a slow, unforced kind of game. Instead, Black will have to either accept a sad endgame or weaken the pawn structure even more, while also killing the light-squared bishop in the process. }
8... Qd5
{ This results in a sad passive endgame for Black due to the bad pawn structure. }
9. Qxd5 exd5 10. Ne2
{ The knight will love the f4-outpost. We'll place it there, then we'll castle queenside or place our king on d2, then the bishop will come out to e2-f3, pressuring the d5-pawn. I wouldn't want to be Black here! In fact, because of the weak kingside pawns, pressure on the d5-pawn, a pretty bad light-squared bishop, and the outposts on the f-file, Black seems nearly lost. }
