9... O-O
{ Before looking into any pawn breaks, Black should castle.   9...e5??  is, of course, very premature. It would lose the game after  10.dxe5  Nxe5??  11.Qe3+-  and Black loses a piece.   9...c5?  works poorly, just as in many other lines. For instance, after  10.O-O-O  cxd4  11.Qxd4  Qxd4  12.Nxd4±  we follow up with f2-f4 to grab more space, as well as g2-g3 and Bg2 to put more pressure on the b7-pawn. Black gets a typical bad endgame that we'll see in many more lines of this chapter. }
10. O-O-O
{ Now, the plan is to continue with Bd3 and then maybe h2-h4, Ng5, etc, developing initiative on the kingside. Black can consider two plans with ...c7-c5 or ...e6-e5. }
10... c5
{ As usual in this variation, this pawn break tends to work out very poorly for Black. I am sure many moves look tempting, but the easiest and most forcing solution is the text move. }
11. Bb5
{ We are putting pressure on the knight, threatening to capture it and then win the c5-pawn. This way, we force Black to release the tension. }
11... cxd4 12. Qxd4 Qxd4 13. Rxd4
{ The resulting endgame is winning for White because of the lead in development and difference in piece activity. Yes, I said it − WINNING, not slightly better. Black won't be able to get the queenside pieces out or challenge us on the d-file without incurring material losses. Let's see a sample line. }
13... Nf6 14. Ne5
{ We prevent the bishop from ever coming to d7 − not that it could, but it's nice to take this square under even more control! }
14... b6
{ In the only game that reached this position, Black tried getting out of the bind this way, but failed. }
15. Bc6 Rb8
{ 1-0 Schmitt-Bauer, Wuerttemberg 1997. At this point, many moves look tempting, but I like the following novelty: }
16. b4
{ The point is to grab space on the queenside, and if needed, play b4-b5!, which would shut down/force back the black bishop if it ever comes to a6, or support ours on c6. }
16... Bb7 17. a4
{ Next, we'll play c2-c4, Kb2-b3, b4-b5, Rhd1, etc. The opponent literally has no moves. }
