8... b6
{ A logical move since Black wants to develop the light-squared bishop on the long diagonal, where it would be rather active. Unfortunately, it doesn't work out that great, and for a fairly typical reason. }
9. Bb5+
{ In these Rubinstein-style positions, playing ...b7-b6 before castling is usually a bad idea exactly because of this check. Now, the move ...c6-c5 would just block the h1-a8 diagonal, rendering the entire idea of ...b7-b6 and ...Bb7 kind of pointless. }
9... Bd7 10. a4
{ We make it hard for Black to develop the queenside and install the bishop on the long diagonal. Taking on b5 is something we'd greatly encourage, as it would open up the a-file for our rook and create a backward weak pawn on a7. }
10... a6 11. Be2
{ Now, Black gets a weak-ish pawn on a6, which will require constant babysitting. }
11... Bc6
{ Black tries to activate the bishop, but that doesn't seem to solve all the problems. }
12. O-O
{ Having protected the g2-pawn, we are ready to harass the bishop with Ne5! }
12... Nd7 { Black should stop that. } 13. a5
{ Now, we harass the queenside pawns, looking to provoke the move ...b6-b5, which will create a lot of weak dark squares. Of course, Black needs to play that move, since we are threatening to capture on b6 and then win the a6-pawn. }
13... b5 14. b4
{ The ...c7-c5 break won't ever happen. Next, we can activate the rook with Ra3, play Qd2, maybe Rfe1, or Re3 and Ne5. The queenside pawns, which are fixed on a6 and b5, can end up vulnerable in various scenarios: for example, what if our knight lands on c5? Or what if we push c2-c4 at some point, force ...bxc4 Bxc4 and start attacking the a6-pawn?   The position is by no means a disaster, but Black has those vulnerable queenside pawns, lacks space and pawn breaks, and any kind of productive ideas, while we dominate the dark squares and can keep improving our position in many ways. }
