{ We continue developing in the most natural way possible. Now the b2-pawn is protected, which means we are threatening to take the c5-pawn and hold on to it. Additionally, of course, the rook is able to help on the d-file, which is about to open up. This is something we find very beneficial!  While this position hasn't been seen a lot  (in just 20 games so far)  , all of those games have been played at 2300+ level and within the last 5 years, which means the line is really challenging for the opponent. }
10... cxd4
{ Simply exchanging everything in the center might be a natural desire, but it doesn't help Black solve any of the current problems. }
11. Qxd4 Qxd4 12. Nxd4
{ Now, the goal is to install the bishop on the h1-a8 diagonal and put pressure on the b7-pawn, while also discouraging the c8-bishop from coming out. }
12... Bd7
{ Black needs to make this move because developing the knight to c6 right away would allow us to ruin the pawn structure, making the queenside pawns easy targets for the rooks, bishop, and even the king. }
13. g3 { However, the bishop is coming to the long diagonal. } 13... Nc6 14.
Bg2
{ If Black exchanges on d4, there will be a huge problem since both the d7-bishop and the b7-pawn will end up hanging. Otherwise, there is a positional threat of capturing on c6 twice, creating weak queenside pawns, which will then be targeted with our rooks − for instance by means of Rd3-c3/a3 or Rhe1-e4-a4/c4, as well as the king after c2-c3, Kc2-b3-c4-c5.  It does not look like there is a good solution to the opponent's problems, so Black seems to be in a really difficult situation, where the best outcome would be a bad endgame. }
