{ After a long thought, I decided to suggest this move, which is the most critical and ambitious one. Why did I do that and what's the point of this move? As we can see, we are simply protecting the e4-pawn while keeping the center flexible for now. It's important to do so for the following practical reason: most Black players who play the French @@StartBracket@@and I am one of them, I just wrote a course on French that I'm in love with!@@EndBracket@@ love positions with pawn chains. Our goal is to try to avoid creating one!  However, don't worry: while the move  3.Nc3  is known for being a very principled and theoretically heavy one, we won't need loads of theory − instead, I am opting for practical, easy-to-learn sidelines, which still carry quite a bit of punch, as always!  In this position, we'll need to consider quite a lot of moves. Black can try to pin the knight with  3...Bb4  , which is known as the Winawer Variation − the most forcing and sharp one. Black can also try to force us to lock up the center with the move  3...Nf6  , which is another major theoretical move. The passive yet solid decision is to play  3...dxe4  − the Rubinstein Variation. Black is hoping to avoid the pawn chain situation and trade down, liquidating White's hopes to get a spatial advantage or long-term pressure.  And, of course, there are quite a few sidelines, such as  3...Nc6  ,  3...Be7  − the move I suggested in my Black French course,  3...h6  ,  3...a6  , and so on. Let's tackle them all one by one! }
3... Nf6
{ The Classical Variation − one of the two best theoretical ways for Black to continue. Black is putting pressure on the e4-pawn, seeking to provoke the move e4-e5, which would lock up the center and create a position with pawn chains. This is exactly what most French Defense players live for! }
4. Bg5
{ This, along with e4-e5, is one of White's two most popular moves. I prefer it because it seems to be giving us more choices than the opponent. Instead, after  4.e5  , Black can choose among a dozen decent lines, which means it's not only difficult to analyze all of them and try to get an advantage of any kind. You will also be at a practical disadvantage since the opponent is the one dictating how the game will go.  Here, we need to investigate 4 moves. The most popular continuation is @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp2ppp/4pn2/3p2B1/3PP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R2QKBNR b KQkq - 3 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Be7  , which is a quiet way to play. A rather passive continuation, which is also quite frequent, is  4...dxe4  − we can call it a slightly improved version of the Rubinstein Variation, and that is because  we have already committed to playing Bg5, which somewhat narrows down our options.   Then, there is, of course, a pretty sharp move:  4...Bb4  . It can, if both parties are willing, very rapidly result in really murky positions. However, it doesn't have to, as we will see − we will politely decline the invitation for a carnage. Finally, the move  4...h6  , which people hadn't thought was possible in the past, is starting to gain some traction, and is not nearly as bad as one might think, so we will also investigate that one! }
4... dxe4
{ This variation is very similar to the Rubinstein Variation − the one after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/3PP3/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq d6 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Nc3  dxe4  , which we had already seen in a different chapter. However, here we had already committed to playing @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp2ppp/4pn2/3p4/3PP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 2 4@@EndFEN@@  4.Bg5  , which is a bit unfortunate since our bishop's position makes it easier for Black to insist on  trades after ...Be7. So, this line is somewhat safer/more reliable for Black than the Rubinstein, it seems.  At the same time, Black can try to play this position in a more aggressive way as well, mostly by looking to change the structure by meeting Nxf6 or Bxf6 with ...gxf6, opening up the g-file. That's what Black often does in this line... But with a neat idea, we'll do our best to make this plan very illogical if not impossible! }
5. Nxe4 Be7
{ Black breaks the pin, looking to trade pieces, and, of course, threatening to win our knight on e4 on the next turn. }
6. Nxf6+
{ For the purpose of this repertoire, which was meant to be positional, restrictive, and simple to learn, I chose this move, because it forces positions that are symmetrical, or nearly so, with slight pressure on Black's position, and where Black doesn't have much counterplay if any.  This move also has another advantage, which is a considerable one in my eyes: it's 7@@StartBracket@@!@@EndBracket@@ times less popular than taking on f6 with the bishop, which means Black is much less likely to know well what to do here.   6.Bxf6  is the more complex line, because after  6...gxf6  , we get a position where Black has the open g-file and a bishop pair, while we have more space in the center and a better structure. Imbalance at its finest! There is nothing wrong with this line, I just don't want to dive into it, as it's too complex. }
6... Bxf6 7. Bxf6 { We trade more pieces in order to not waste time. } 7...
Qxf6 8. Nf3
{ It might look like this position should be easier to defend because Black had already gotten rid of two pairs of pieces. On the one hand, this is a reasonable observation: after all, it's a good idea to trade when you have less space, right?  However, there is another consideration, which contradicts the first one a bit. Namely, the c8-bishop is still bad. Unless Black finds a way to improve it, the position will be passive with a bad piece. And when the opponent has a bad piece, trading other pieces is often a good idea, because, in the end, we are sort of a piece up − the more advanced version of 'trade while material up', which is what all beginners learn when they start studying chess.  Black should better hurry to improve that bishop! That can be done by ...b7-b6 and ...Bb7, or maybe by ...e6-e5, even though accomplishing the latter seems a bit unlikely. Another thing Black needs to remember is that the d4-pawn provides more space than any other pawn, so challenging it sooner or later with ...c7-c5 or ...e6-e5 would be rather important.   At this point, the most popular move by far is  8...O-O  , played in nearly 1100 games at a master level. There are also  8...Nd7  @@StartBracket@@150 games@@EndBracket@@,  8...c5  @@StartBracket@@115 games@@EndBracket@@ and  8...b6  @@StartBracket@@75 games@@EndBracket@@ to consider. }
8... O-O 9. Qd3
{ I really like this rare move. First of all, it considerably decreases the opponent's chances to be prepared, as it's been seen in just 60 games out of 1200 that reached this position. But more importantly, it prepares queenside castling, as well as the kingside pressure-related idea of Qe4-Bd3! }
9... c5
{ Black should try to challenge the d4-pawn now, to take advantage of the fact that White cannot take, as the b2-pawn would hang.   9...Rd8  10.O-O-O  c5  will transpose to @@StartFEN@@rnb2rk1/ppp2ppp/4pq2/8/3P4/3Q1N2/PPP2PPP/R3KB1R b KQ - 3 9@@EndFEN@@  9...c5  10.O-O-O  Rd8  . }
10. O-O-O
{ We continue developing in the most natural way possible. Now the b2-pawn is protected, which means we are threatening to take the c5-pawn and hold on to it. Additionally, of course, the rook is able to help on the d-file, which is about to open up. This is something we find very beneficial!  While this position hasn't been seen a lot  (in just 20 games so far)  , all of those games have been played at 2300+ level and within the last 5 years, which means the line is really challenging for the opponent. }
10... Rd8
{ Black should try to put pressure on the d4-pawn, or else we can continue building the initiative without feeling disturbed at all. Black MUST look for counterplay right now! }
11. Qe4
{ The queen steps away from the awkward pinned position on the d-file to the best central square. From here, it's able to:  Create threats to the black king after Bd3. Prevent ...b7-b6 by pinning the b7-pawn. Prevent ...Bd7 by attacking the b7-pawn. Help control the e5-square, just in case, making any attempts to play ...e6-e5 much less realistic. }
11... cxd4
{ This results in a passive endgame after the obviously forced sequence: } 12.
Rxd4 Rxd4 13. Qxd4 Qxd4 14. Nxd4
{ With g2-g3 and Bg2, or Be2-f3 coming, it looks like Black cannot solve the queenside development problems easily, which means facing unpleasant defense for many more moves. }
14... Bd7 { Trying to prepare ...Nc6 without ruining the pawn structure. } 15.
Be2 Nc6 16. Rd1 { We take the d-file under control. } 16... Nxd4 17. Rxd4 Bc6
{ It seems as though everything is fine since Black was first to install the bishop on the long diagonal, which prevented Bf3, but this turns out to be an optical illusion since we have a wonderful idea. }
18. Bf3 Bxf3 19. gxf3
{ Despite the ugly-looking kingside pawns, White is dominating since our rook is about to invade on the 7th rank. }
19... Kf8 20. Rd7 Rb8 21. b4
{ Black is absolutely paralyzed. Sure enough, ...Ke8 can be played and chase the rook away to c7, but then what? The king is stuck protecting the kingside pawns, while the rook has to defend the ones on the queenside. Next, we'll improve the king with Kb2-b3, will play c2-c4, a2-a4, c4-c5, Kc4, b4-b5, get a passed pawn on the c-file and win the game. This is absolutely inevitable! }
*

