{ Black is trying to break the pin, taking advantage of the fact we cannot retreat without dropping the e4-pawn. This move has been suggested by the super GM Vitiugov in a chapter on the @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp2ppp/4pn2/3p4/3PP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 2 4@@EndFEN@@  4.Bg5  Bb4  variation of his book. }
6. Bxf6 { Unfortunately, the bishop pair needs to go. } 6... Qxf6 7. a3
{ Now, we kick out the bishop. To a player who isn't very familiar with the position, it would seem as though the d5-pawn would hang if the bishop walks away, so Black seems forced to take on c3. Actually, this is not true. But many people would still take it for that reason! }
7... Ba5
{ This seems wrong at a first glance, but actually, it's a decent move. } 8. b4
{ We unpin, forcing the opponent's bishop to a passive position, while also gaining an opportunity to win the d5-pawn. }
8... Bb6 9. e5
{ However, having an opportunity to do something doesn't mean we want to do it. Instead, we grab more space in the center and close the position.   9.exd5?!  seems tempting, but doesn't work out that well, since after  9...O-O  , we can see that our development is rather poor.  The knight on e2 is paralyzing the kingside pieces and we are not close to being ready to castle. That's why opening up the files, which is exactly what's happening right now, is not a good idea − it's not worth winning this pawn! }
9... Qe7 10. Na4
{ We take advantage of the fact the bishop cannot retreat. The point of our move is that at some point we might be interested in depriving the opponent of the bishop pair. Or maybe the knight will just go to c5. We will see. But we are making sure that if we want to, we can take the bishop. And, we are making it possible to protect the d4-pawn with c2-c3, just in case. }
10... Bd7
{ Typically, Black would make this developing move, which threatens the knight and asks White to clarify matters a little bit.  10...O-O  11.Nf4  results in the same positions as in @@StartFEN@@rnb1k2r/ppp1qpp1/1b2p2p/3pP3/NP1P4/P7/2P1NPPP/R2QKB1R b KQkq - 2 10@@EndFEN@@  10...Bd7  . }
11. c3
{ We protect the knight with our queen, while also reinforcing the center.  11.Nxb6?!  isn't a good idea, since after  11...axb6  ,  Black gets a semi-open file for the rook and a backward pawn on a3 to attack. }
11... O-O
{ Black just castles, which is a natural developing move, before committing to any active action. At this point, we need to keep in mind two possible active ideas the opponent can try, which are ...a7-a5 and ...f7-f6. However, ...a7-a5 seems difficult and undesirable because we can take on b6, and Black won't be able to recapture with the a-pawn, which would spoil the pawn structure. But, ...f7-f6 is also difficult to carry about because that move weakens the g6-square. How can we try to take advantage of that? }
12. Nf4
{ Of course! This move not only prepares the development of our kingside pieces, but it also prevents ...f7-f6, since Ng6! would be a fork, which would win us an exchange. Vitiugov mentions this position briefly in his book as a decent way to play, but I am fairly convinced it's not comfortable for Black at all. }
12... Bxa4
{ In most games that featured this position, Black chose to trade off this knight. It's an understandable decision: the bishop wasn't doing much on d7. Plus, now Black no longer needs to consider Nxb6 on every single move and can try to push ...a7-a5, hopefully getting some counterplay on the queenside. }
13. Qxa4 Nd7
{ Black gets the last piece in the game while also connecting the rooks. } 14.
Qc2
{ There is no need for our queen to sit on the a-file, where it would inevitably end up harassed after ...a7-a5. }
14... c6
{ Black could try many moves, but it seems logical to make room for the passive b6-bishop. For example, Black can try to retreat to c7 and then prepare ...b7-b6 and ...c6-c5, or maybe ...f7-f6, since the bishop is helping control the e5-pawn and the h2-b8 diagonal overall. }
15. Be2 { We are just finishing development and getting ready to castle. }
15... a5
{ The most logical idea for Black here is to immediately do something on the a-file. }
16. O-O
{ We castle and connect the rooks. Black can double on the a-file, but we will just remove our rook from there, for example with Rab1, so that if Black ever trades on b4 and invades with ...Ra2, we can respond with Rb2. Black's queenside play isn't going to result in anything meaningful. It can only help reduce the number of pawns and maybe swap some rooks, but it's not a way to create threats.  It's not entirely obvious what our winning plan is. But, we are certainly considerably better because of the tremendous spatial advantage. Also, look at the difference in the bishops' abilities! The b6-bishop is absolutely useless, while ours could be used for a kingside attack.  For example, playing Qd2, Bd3-c2, and Qd3, setting up a battery on the b1-h7 diagonal, seems like a very logical idea. Additionally, we could try to prepare f2-f4-f5, grabbing even more space and looking to activate the f1-rook. All in all, Black is facing a passive and unpleasant defense, which is something we're very happy about! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "7) McCutcheon Variation 4.Bg5 Bb4 5.Nge2"]
[Black "McCutcheon Variation 4.Bg5 Bb4 5.Nge2 c5 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6
{ This move, followed by ...d7-d5, defines something called the French Defense. This opening is about fighting for the center rather ambitiously while avoiding direct piece play. As you will see, the first two moves only feature pawn play. The downside for Black is the locked-up light-squared bishop, and very often, this piece tends to be a large issue for quite a long time. }
2. d4 d5
{ Here, we arrive at massive crossroads. White can lock up the center with e4-e5, take Black's pawn and open up the position, or defend the pawn with some knight move − either to c3 or to d2. }
3. Nc3
{ After a long thought, I decided to suggest this move, which is the most critical and ambitious one. Why did I do that and what's the point of this move? As we can see, we are simply protecting the e4-pawn while keeping the center flexible for now. It's important to do so for the following practical reason: most Black players who play the French @@StartBracket@@and I am one of them, I just wrote a course on French that I'm in love with!@@EndBracket@@ love positions with pawn chains. Our goal is to try to avoid creating one!  However, don't worry: while the move  3.Nc3  is known for being a very principled and theoretically heavy one, we won't need loads of theory − instead, I am opting for practical, easy-to-learn sidelines, which still carry quite a bit of punch, as always!  In this position, we'll need to consider quite a lot of moves. Black can try to pin the knight with  3...Bb4  , which is known as the Winawer Variation − the most forcing and sharp one. Black can also try to force us to lock up the center with the move  3...Nf6  , which is another major theoretical move. The passive yet solid decision is to play  3...dxe4  − the Rubinstein Variation. Black is hoping to avoid the pawn chain situation and trade down, liquidating White's hopes to get a spatial advantage or long-term pressure.  And, of course, there are quite a few sidelines, such as  3...Nc6  ,  3...Be7  − the move I suggested in my Black French course,  3...h6  ,  3...a6  , and so on. Let's tackle them all one by one! }
3... Nf6
{ The Classical Variation − one of the two best theoretical ways for Black to continue. Black is putting pressure on the e4-pawn, seeking to provoke the move e4-e5, which would lock up the center and create a position with pawn chains. This is exactly what most French Defense players live for! }
4. Bg5
{ This, along with e4-e5, is one of White's two most popular moves. I prefer it because it seems to be giving us more choices than the opponent. Instead, after  4.e5  , Black can choose among a dozen decent lines, which means it's not only difficult to analyze all of them and try to get an advantage of any kind. You will also be at a practical disadvantage since the opponent is the one dictating how the game will go.  Here, we need to investigate 4 moves. The most popular continuation is @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp2ppp/4pn2/3p2B1/3PP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R2QKBNR b KQkq - 3 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Be7  , which is a quiet way to play. A rather passive continuation, which is also quite frequent, is  4...dxe4  − we can call it a slightly improved version of the Rubinstein Variation, and that is because  we have already committed to playing Bg5, which somewhat narrows down our options.   Then, there is, of course, a pretty sharp move:  4...Bb4  . It can, if both parties are willing, very rapidly result in really murky positions. However, it doesn't have to, as we will see − we will politely decline the invitation for a carnage. Finally, the move  4...h6  , which people hadn't thought was possible in the past, is starting to gain some traction, and is not nearly as bad as one might think, so we will also investigate that one! }
4... Bb4
{ Instead of dealing with the seemingly scary threat of e4-e5, Black is pinning our knight, threatening to win the e4-pawn! This move somewhat reminds me of the sharp counter-attacking Winawer Variation and is considered the most principled and ambitious way for Black to meet the 4.Bg5 line. }
5. Ne2
{ This is an interesting way of dealing with the pin. We are getting ready to recapture on c3 with the knight, avoiding having to double our pawns. On the next turn, we are ready to play a2-a3, kicking the annoying bishop away. As you might expect if you know my writing style already, I also like this move because it's quite rare − it's been seen in only about 600 games out of 17 000 after 4...Bb4!   Here, Black sits at a crossroads and has two logical options available. Most frequently, Black captures on e4; however, sometimes, Black also plays  5...h6  , challenging our bishop and getting rid of the pin. }
5... c5
{ An attempt to blow up the center, but it's a very bad idea. Black is by no means ready, which is something White can easily prove. }
6. a3 Ba5 { This is just awful, as it lets us win material. } 7. dxc5
{ We gladly grab the pawn and plan on pushing b2-b4 next. } 7... dxe4
{ Black seems to be able to maintain material equality for now, as the c3-knight is pinned. But, of course, this is just a temporary situation. }
8. b4 { First, we solve the pin problem. } 8... Bc7 9. Qxd8+
{ Then we trade the queens. } 9... Bxd8 10. O-O-O
{ Now we also make sure the rook gets in the game. At this point, Black has to be aware of two threats: Ng3, winning the e4-pawn on the next turn, and Nb5, looking to invade on d6. Of course, these threats, especially the first one, cannot be stopped. }
10... O-O 11. Ng3
{ Next, we win the pawn on e4 and get a completely winning position. We will not only be a pawn up, but our pieces will be more active and we will dominate the only open file. }
*

