5. Ne2
{ This is an interesting way of dealing with the pin. We are getting ready to recapture on c3 with the knight, avoiding having to double our pawns. On the next turn, we are ready to play a2-a3, kicking the annoying bishop away. As you might expect if you know my writing style already, I also like this move because it's quite rare − it's been seen in only about 600 games out of 17 000 after 4...Bb4!   Here, Black sits at a crossroads and has two logical options available. Most frequently, Black captures on e4; however, sometimes, Black also plays  5...h6  , challenging our bishop and getting rid of the pin. }
5... c5
{ An attempt to blow up the center, but it's a very bad idea. Black is by no means ready, which is something White can easily prove. }
6. a3 Bxc3+ { Black has to give up the bishop pair and help us develop. } 7.
Nxc3
{ Now, the threat is to simply win the c5-pawn. It seems logical for Black to take on d4. }
7... cxd4 8. Qxd4
{ Of course, our queen is perfectly safe in the center. We'd like to capture on d5, then castle long, and likely win the d5-pawn. Also, of course, we have ideas like Bb5+, developing the bishop with a tempo, and then Rhe1, quickly getting all the pieces to perfect positions. }
8... Nc6
{ It seems natural that Black would want to develop a piece and win a tempo by attacking our queen. }
9. Bb5
{ However, that's not an issue for us. We are pinning the knight, threatening to play e4-e5 and take advantage of the pinned f6-knight. And, of course, there are still ideas of exd5 followed by queenside castling, trying to win the d5-pawn. }
9... dxe4 { This move gives Black a lost position. } 10. Qc5
{ Now, Black cannot castle. And, of course, we are threatening to capture on c6. }
10... Bd7 { Black at least has to stop the threat of Bxc6. } 11. Bxf6 Qxf6 12.
Nxe4
{ On the next turn, our knight will invade on d6, causing decisive damage. } *

