{ We are getting ready to castle queenside. Our queen would prefer to be here, rather than on d2, because from d3, it can go to multiple squares on the third rank in the future. This move has been chosen by a number of strong players, such as Jeffery Xiong, who used this variation last year, and Susan Polgar, among others. }
9... e5
{ Black can also try to open up the center right away, taking advantage of the fact we haven't yet played something like f2-f4, which would discourage this pawn break. }
10. O-O-O
{ Of course, we don't have much to think about, we just continue development. It's crucial to point out that, since the position is opening up, having developed active pieces is becoming more important than ever. }
10... exd4 { We have several choices, but the easiest one would be: } 11. Nxf6+
Qxf6 12. Qxd4
{ And we get a considerable amount of initiative in this endgame since our pieces are much more active. }
12... Qxd4 13. Nxd4
{ Now, Nb5 is a threat, so Black cannot just keep developing and has to react. }
13... c6 14. Bc4
{ Black cannot play ...Be6 or ...Bf5. Next, we're about to get the last piece in the game with Rhe1 and invade on the 7th rank with Re7, at which point Black will be stuck protecting the f7-pawn. Soon enough, White went on to convert his advantage rather easily in Mamedov-Tepelenis, Kavala 2011. }
