5. a3 { As usual, we gladly get rid of the pin. } 5... Ba5
{ This time, Black can  (and should!)  try to keep the bishop. } 6. b4
{ This variation will, most likely, transpose to the lines after @@StartFEN@@rnbqk1nr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/1b1PP3/2N5/PPP1NPPP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 3 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Nc6  , if Black chooses to develop the knight there soon in order to put pressure on the d4-pawn. However, Black does not have to. What can be tried instead is to play  ...c7-c6  at some point, in order to free up the passive bishop on  b6  , which is very restricted by our pawns, via  c7  . }
6... Bb6 7. e5
{ By locking up the center, we achieve a couple of things. What are they?  We secure a considerable amount of spatial advantage on the kingside. We prevent Black from ever obtaining a considerable amount of pressure on the e4-pawn, which could be done by playing ...dxe4 and then ...Nf5. We make sure the e4-pawn won't ever be taken, so that our knight on c3 can start doing other stuff, such as going to a4, and chasing the dark-squared bishop. }
7... a5
{ Most Black players who arrived at this position chose to make this move, which is aimed at opening up the a-file. }
8. Na4 { Of course, we still pursue the plan of going after the bishop. } 8...
axb4 9. axb4
{ Now, Black has managed to open up the a-file, which means we cannot capture the bishop on b6 since doing that would leave our rook unprotected. }
9... Bd7
{ Black uses this pin to trade off our a4-knight for the supposedly bad French light-squared bishop.   9...Ba7??  is an absolutely pointless idea. Black not only makes a useless move with the restricted bishop but also blocks the a-file.  10.c3+-  and I'd say White is completely winning here. We have successfully stabilized our center, while Black failed to get any counterplay against it. Within the next few moves, we will play Nf4, Qg4, and likely Bd3, and Nh5. So many attackers should, of course, easily help us do a decisive amount of damage to the black king. }
10. c3 { We don't have much choice here, so we just protect the knight. } 10...
O-O 11. Bg5
{ With this move, we not only develop the bishop but also protect the rook on a1, creating a threat of capturing the bishop on b6 and ruining the pawn structure. This little positional threat forces Black to act. In all fairness, the 'acting' is what Black wanted to do anyway − trade off the bad light-squared bishop! }
11... Bxa4 12. Rxa4 Rxa4 13. Qxa4
{ In the arising position, Black is by no means doing terribly. However, with the considerable spatial advantage, the bishop pair, and a stable center, we are clearly better. In the next moves, our task will be to simply finish development. Once we do that, we'll start enjoying the long-lasting advantages we have, which I have just described above.  For example, I'd find it logical to play g2-g3 and Bh3!? here, in order to discourage any possible ...f7-f6 related pawn breaks and avoid having to move the e2-knight. That knight seems to be blocking the bishop, but as we see, the bishop can get out in a different way. The knight, on the other hand, is great at protecting the d4-pawn. Later, it can of course come to g3 or f4 and support the f2-f4-f5 push, or come to h5 and put pressure on Black's kingside.  In the long run, we'd love to start slowly building up pressure on the kingside with f2-f4-f5, Qd1-g4, etc. As usual, Black has no counterplay, so we are very happy. :@@EndBracket@@ }
