4... c5
{ Just like in another line we've seen in one of the previous chapters, with the inclusion of Bg5 and ...Nf6, this pawn break turns out an absolutely awful premature idea. }
5. a3 { Black cannot keep the pin alive, as retreating loses a pawn to dxc5. }
5... Bxc3+ 6. Nxc3 { Now, we have a ton of pressure on the center. } 6... dxe4
7. Bb5+
{ It's nice to get one more piece out with tempo before releasing the tension. }
7... Nc6 8. d5
{ Of course, Black is already somewhat struggling because of the pin, and has to capture. }
8... exd5 9. Qxd5
{ Now, there are multiple threats, such as:  Bxc6, ruining Black's pawn structure; Qxd8, depriving the opponent of castling rights; Qxe4, winning back the pawn; Qxc5, taking the other pawn first and hoping to prevent Black from ever being able to castle.  
There are a few moves the opponent can make, but the position is hopeless, regardless of what Black does next. }
9... Qxd5 10. Nxd5 Kd8 11. Bf4
{ White followed up with queenside castling, and the combination of threats on the d-file, to the c7-square, the black king, and the much higher piece activity overall turned out too much for Black to handle. White won a lovely game! 1-0 Saunders-Labat, France 2009. }
