6... Nge7
{ The only other logical possibility would be to keep the tension and develop without placing the knight on f6, where it runs into e4-e5 with a tempo.  6...dxe4  transposes to the main 4...dxe4 lines that we are analyzing in another chapter. }
7. Be3
{ We just keep developing. So far so good. It makes sense to put the bishop on f4 in many of these positions, but e3 is also a good square − especially right here since Black could potentially take on e4 at some point and then play ...Nf5, trying to attack our d4-pawn. }
7... O-O 8. Qd2
{ Next, we'll just finish development. If Black doesn't do anything special, the result will be a bad version of many typical positions we analyze elsewhere: there is no counterplay! So, the only logical idea, that is somehow connected to having the knight on c6, would be a central pawn break. }
8... e5
{ However, opening up the position doesn't work out that brilliantly for our opponent. }
9. O-O-O
{ We not only finish development and tuck the king away in the corner, but also get the rook on the d-file, which is super helpful in this case since it's about to open up! }
9... exd4
{ Black has to start releasing the tension, as there is too much pressure on the center and we were threatening to capture the e5-pawn. The key point of queenside castling is that we control the d4-square one more time, which means Black could no longer hope to meet dxe5 with ...d5-d4, either. }
10. Bxd4
{ We don't mind giving up the bishop pair in exchange for the much more active pieces in a pretty open position. }
10... dxe4 11. Nxe4 { Simplifications are about to begin. } 11... Nxd4 12. Qxd4
Qxd4 13. Rxd4
{ The arising position is still very unpleasant for Black, despite looking fairly simple at a first glance. Why so?   We will dominate the only open d-file after Rhd1. Black is not in time to challenge it. Our king is better placed to help us fight for the d-file, and better placed for the endgame overall, as it's easier to bring it to the center fast. If Black develops the light-squared bishop, it's very easy to run into annoying ideas like Nc5, and the queenside could wind up under pressure. There can be a lot of pressure on the f7-pawn after Bc4, Ng5, and so on. Black will need to spend some time figuring out a defense to that. }
