6. b4
{ We are glad to unpin, while also grabbing more space on the queenside and forcing the opponent's bishop on the passive square b6, where it will find itself extremely restricted. }
6... Bb6 7. Bb2
{ I like this odd way of developing the dark-squared bishop a lot. Why is it going there, and what are our ideas? Just like in many other positions with a considerable amount of extra space early on, the goal is to just sustain this center. If we don't allow for any pawn breaks or tactics, we'll keep a large advantage due to this space!  Next, we'd like to protect the e4-pawn once more with Qd3 and go Na4, looking to create tension with the b6-bishop. It's restricted, so we are in no rush to capture it. But at some point, we might do just that!  Also, if Black ever plays ...dxe4, then after Nxe4, the opportunity of d4-d5 arises. We likely won't make this move for a long time, but if we ever do, the b2-bishop would be very happy! That's something Black has to constantly keep in mind. }
7... Nf6 { No one develops the knight here and for a good reason. } 8. e5
{ We just grab more space, while also winning a tempo. And, the knight is forced into a really poor position. }
8... Nd7 9. Na4
{ We have all the same ideas as in the main line. Black just wasted a move and ended up with a knight on d7 − a very passive square, from where it has nowhere to go. }
9... O-O 10. Nf4
{ We are ready to start unfolding an easy kingside attack with Qg4, Nh5, Bd3, etc. Black has no counterplay! }
