{ Here, we arrive at massive crossroads. White can lock up the center with e4-e5, take Black's pawn and open up the position, or defend the pawn with some knight move − either to c3 or to d2. }
3. Nc3
{ After a long thought, I decided to suggest this move, which is the most critical and ambitious one. Why did I do that and what's the point of this move? As we can see, we are simply protecting the e4-pawn while keeping the center flexible for now. It's important to do so for the following practical reason: most Black players who play the French @@StartBracket@@and I am one of them, I just wrote a course on French that I'm in love with!@@EndBracket@@ love positions with pawn chains. Our goal is to try to avoid creating one!  However, don't worry: while the move  3.Nc3  is known for being a very principled and theoretically heavy one, we won't need loads of theory − instead, I am opting for practical, easy-to-learn sidelines, which still carry quite a bit of punch, as always!  In this position, we'll need to consider quite a lot of moves. Black can try to pin the knight with  3...Bb4  , which is known as the Winawer Variation − the most forcing and sharp one. Black can also try to force us to lock up the center with the move  3...Nf6  , which is another major theoretical move. The passive yet solid decision is to play  3...dxe4  − the Rubinstein Variation. Black is hoping to avoid the pawn chain situation and trade down, liquidating White's hopes to get a spatial advantage or long-term pressure.  And, of course, there are quite a few sidelines, such as  3...Nc6  ,  3...Be7  − the move I suggested in my Black French course,  3...h6  ,  3...a6  , and so on. Let's tackle them all one by one! }
3... Bb4
{ The famous Winawer Variation. Black develops in the most active way possible, immediately pinning the knight and threatening the e4-pawn. The downside of this move is that it weakens the g7-pawn. Plus, if Black ever goes ...Ne7, the bishop often ends up short on squares and unable to return to the kingside. }
4. Ne2
{ I like this rare move, played 13@@StartBracket@@!@@EndBracket@@ times less often than the main move  4.e5  . But, when I say 'sideline', don't worry − this is not a bad move! It's a variation that has been tried by such outstanding players as MVL, Firouzja, Ivanchuk, Xiong, and many others when they were looking to avoid the mainstream theory and get a bit more creative.    We make sure the structure remains very flexible by overprotecting the c3-knight with our other knight, so that if Black ever takes it, we can take back with the knight, avoiding doubled pawns. On the next turn, we are planning on continuing with a2-a3, kicking out the annoying bishop and neutralizing the pin. Once we do that, Black will have a hard time finding a good square for the bishop, and we'll continue to develop. But, of course, just as any line  (especially a sideline)  , this move has a few downsides, namely:  It blocks the development of our kingside, even if just temporarily. It leaves the e4-pawn hanging.   Black mostly captures the hanging pawn with @@StartFEN@@rnbqk1nr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/1b1PP3/2N5/PPP1NPPP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 3 4@@EndFEN@@  4...dxe4  , however, some players have tried such moves as  4...Nf6  ,  4...Nc6  , and  4...Ne7  . In this chapter, we'll be focusing our attention on the sidelines. }
4... Nc6
{ The idea of this move is to put pressure on the d4-pawn, which is something Black could benefit from at some point, after playing ...dxe4. Black thinks that our e2-knight will need to move, or else how would we develop our kingside pieces?  And once it does, Black would take on e4, starting to attack the d4-pawn with the queen and knight. This move also helps Black potentially prepare the ...e6-e5 break. It's not a common break in the French, but it is still a bit of a typical idea. We need to be careful about making sure Black doesn't free up the position too easily! }
5. a3
{ Of course, we immediately chase the bishop away, breaking the pin. That was the whole point of Nge2 − now, if Black captured on c3, we'd gladly take back with the knight! }
5... Ba5
{ Keeping the pin alive is more ambitious and logical, to my mind. It's also a much more frequent move, which doesn't come as a surprise. }
6. b4
{ We are glad to unpin, while also grabbing more space on the queenside and forcing the opponent's bishop on the passive square b6, where it will find itself extremely restricted. }
6... Bb6 7. Bb2
{ I like this odd way of developing the dark-squared bishop a lot. Why is it going there, and what are our ideas? Just like in many other positions with a considerable amount of extra space early on, the goal is to just sustain this center. If we don't allow for any pawn breaks or tactics, we'll keep a large advantage due to this space!  Next, we'd like to protect the e4-pawn once more with Qd3 and go Na4, looking to create tension with the b6-bishop. It's restricted, so we are in no rush to capture it. But at some point, we might do just that!  Also, if Black ever plays ...dxe4, then after Nxe4, the opportunity of d4-d5 arises. We likely won't make this move for a long time, but if we ever do, the b2-bishop would be very happy! That's something Black has to constantly keep in mind. }
7... Nge7
{ It only makes sense to develop the knight here. From this square, it can jump to f5 after ...dxe4, to put pressure on the d4-pawn. It also isn't running into e4-e5 with a tempo. }
8. Qd3
{ This is a rare idea, but a very interesting one. Is White preparing long castling? Probably not this time since the move b2-b4 made it a bit too easy for Black to start opening up some files with ...a7-a5. However, what we are doing is protecting the e4-pawn, while also intending to play g2-g3 and Bg2 next, or maybe Na4, going after the bishop. Crucially, this move prevents the ...e6-e5 break, unlike the main line with 8.g3. Let's see why!   8.g3  is the most popular move by far. However, I don't really like it, as it leads to some rather forcing play.  8...e5!  Black immediately blows up the center, activating all the pieces −  the c8-bishop, the c6-knight, and even that poor b6-bishop all of a sudden springs to life!  9.dxe5  Nxe5  .  Now, we need to make sure the black knight doesn't:   checkmate us in one move after ...Nf3; land on c4, harassing our bishop; do a lot of harm to the f2-pawn after ...Ng4.    10.Nf4  Ng4  . This position is very complicated and interesting. But, given it's a sideline where we can easily get a very pleasant position without any counterplay for our opponent, I'll pass, thanks! }
8... O-O
{ Since opening up the center right away doesn't work for Black, it makes sense to simply continue developing. }
9. Na4
{ This move is designed to achieve a few things. What are they?  It creates tension with the black bishop. We don't really need to take it, but we would in a few scenarios. For example, if Black ever goes ...e6-e5, then taking that bishop would greatly help us decrease the control of the d4-square. And, overall, as the position opens up, the bishop will prove more valuable!  It opens up the path for our c-pawn so that at some point we can consider playing c2-c4-c5! It is not obvious to me what Black should do here. And there are just 4 games in the database. However, two strong players @@StartBracket@@2300+ and 2500+@@EndBracket@@ chose to just go ...Bd7, keeping the tension. It allows us to use a really interesting idea, so we need to look at this one! }
9... Bd7 10. c4
{ We are very happy to be able to place even more pawns in the center and control it even better! }
10... dxc4 11. Qxc4
{ Black managed to hold a correspondence game, however it seems fairly obvious that we have a considerably more pleasant position due to our center. And, of course, Black still has a bunch of other problems. For example, the b6-bishop is very restricted and the d7-bishop is passive. Black also lacks space.  All in all, a very pleasant outcome for us. And, which is something I appreciate a lot, a fairly easy outcome to arrive at − remember, we've dodged all the forcing lines and got here purely with logic and positional understanding! ½-½ Cruzado Duenas-Mercky, ICCF email 2008. }
