{ Black offers a knight trade, which is a logical thing to do, as it decreases the spatial disadvantage: the fewer pieces left, the less it matters that you don't have much space. }
7. Nxf6+
{ This move is quite rare, but it's been used in recent years by such strong young players as Xiong, Abdusattorov, Niemann, and others, and White scored really well: 58%. We are happy to force the bishop to go to f6 without having to determine or commit to placing our pieces on weird squares, such as after  7.Qd3  . }
7... Bxf6 8. Be3
{ Now, the goal is obviously to get the queen out and castle. In most cases, we will probably settle for Qd2, followed by queenside castling. However, in many positions, the queen can come to g4 after we play Nf4 and create a lot of threats on the kingside! }
8... O-O
{ This, of course, has been the most popular continuation − for now, Black just castles. }
9. Qd2
{ And we also continue to develop. The plan is to castle and then play Nf4, intending to either open the center with d4-d5! and install the knight on d5, when the time is right, or play g2-g3 and Bg2, increasing pressure on the long diagonal. Of course, the plan of Nf4, O-O-O and g2-g4, h2-h4, etc, can also be very strong and logical! }
9... c5
{ An attempt to simplify the position and liquidate some pawns in the center. It seems logical, but as we've seen in many other chapters by now, it hardly ever works! Of course, we don't want to take the c5-pawn before castling, as that would leave the one on b2 hanging. }
10. O-O-O
{ We get the d4-square under better control and also protect the b2-pawn, creating a simple threat of winning the c5-pawn on the next turn. }
10... cxd4 11. Nxd4
{ Black's main issues involve:  the undeveloped queenside; the fact the d6-square is weak and easily accessible to our pieces − for example, after Nb5-d6, our knight will obviously put a ton of pressure on the position; the fact we can easily develop a kingside attack, both because the bishop is going to run into tempi-winning moves like g4-g5! soon, and because the kingside lacks defenders. }
11... Bd7
{ Black needs this move to be able to develop the knight to c6 and recapture back with the bishop, avoiding the situation where the pawn structure gets ruined. }
12. g4
{ While Black is trying to crawl out of bed, we are instead building the kingside attack without any obstacles. }
12... Nc6 13. Nb5
{ The knight is about to land on d6, and the kingside attack is developing rather easily. Plus, of course, at this very moment, we are threatening to win the bishop on d7. This position isn't nice for Black! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "9) Winawer 3.Nc3 Bb4 4.Nge2 − Main Lines"]
[Black "Winawer 4.Nge2 dxe4 5.a3 Be7 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6
{ This move, followed by ...d7-d5, defines something called the French Defense. This opening is about fighting for the center rather ambitiously while avoiding direct piece play. As you will see, the first two moves only feature pawn play. The downside for Black is the locked-up light-squared bishop, and very often, this piece tends to be a large issue for quite a long time. }
2. d4 d5
{ Here, we arrive at massive crossroads. White can lock up the center with e4-e5, take Black's pawn and open up the position, or defend the pawn with some knight move − either to c3 or to d2. }
3. Nc3
{ After a long thought, I decided to suggest this move, which is the most critical and ambitious one. Why did I do that and what's the point of this move? As we can see, we are simply protecting the e4-pawn while keeping the center flexible for now. It's important to do so for the following practical reason: most Black players who play the French @@StartBracket@@and I am one of them, I just wrote a course on French that I'm in love with!@@EndBracket@@ love positions with pawn chains. Our goal is to try to avoid creating one!  However, don't worry: while the move  3.Nc3  is known for being a very principled and theoretically heavy one, we won't need loads of theory − instead, I am opting for practical, easy-to-learn sidelines, which still carry quite a bit of punch, as always!  In this position, we'll need to consider quite a lot of moves. Black can try to pin the knight with  3...Bb4  , which is known as the Winawer Variation − the most forcing and sharp one. Black can also try to force us to lock up the center with the move  3...Nf6  , which is another major theoretical move. The passive yet solid decision is to play  3...dxe4  − the Rubinstein Variation. Black is hoping to avoid the pawn chain situation and trade down, liquidating White's hopes to get a spatial advantage or long-term pressure.  And, of course, there are quite a few sidelines, such as  3...Nc6  ,  3...Be7  − the move I suggested in my Black French course,  3...h6  ,  3...a6  , and so on. Let's tackle them all one by one! }
3... Bb4
{ The famous Winawer Variation. Black develops in the most active way possible, immediately pinning the knight and threatening the e4-pawn. The downside of this move is that it weakens the g7-pawn. Plus, if Black ever goes ...Ne7, the bishop often ends up short on squares and unable to return to the kingside. }
4. Ne2
{ I like this rare move, played 13@@StartBracket@@!@@EndBracket@@ times less often than the main move  4.e5  . But, when I say 'sideline', don't worry − this is not a bad move! It's a variation that has been tried by such outstanding players as MVL, Firouzja, Ivanchuk, Xiong, and many others when they were looking to avoid the mainstream theory and get a bit more creative.    We make sure the structure remains very flexible by overprotecting the c3-knight with our other knight, so that if Black ever takes it, we can take back with the knight, avoiding doubled pawns. On the next turn, we are planning on continuing with a2-a3, kicking out the annoying bishop and neutralizing the pin. Once we do that, Black will have a hard time finding a good square for the bishop, and we'll continue the flexible nice development. But, of course, just as any line  (especially a sideline)  , this move has a few downsides, namely:  It blocks the development of our kingside, even if just temporarily. It leaves the e4-pawn hanging.   Black mostly captures the hanging pawn with @@StartFEN@@rnbqk1nr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/1b1PP3/2N5/PPP1NPPP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 3 4@@EndFEN@@  4...dxe4  , however, some players have tried such moves as  4...Nf6  ,  4...Nc6  , and  4...Ne7  . In this chapter, we'll focus on the main line  4...dxe4  . Of course, the sidelines are considered in great detail in the corresponding chapter. }
4... dxe4
{ Black is just capturing the free pawn. Later on, Black might return it and focus on rapid comfortable development, or instead try to hold on to it with ...f7-f5. }
5. a3
{ We, of course, follow up with our plan of kicking out the opponent's bishop and breaking the pin. At this point, Black needs to decide whether to hold on to the pawn by taking the knight and then doing something about the hanging pawn or to retreat, returning it right away. }
5... Be7
{ The more popular move, but, due to the recent discoveries I've made in this line, I don't have much faith in it. }
6. Nxe4
{ We get the pawn back. Because of the extra space and more active pieces, it seems obvious White should be better. However, there is one problem: the knight on e2 is really passive! That's the only thing that gives Black hope for equality, I believe. }
6... Nf6
{ Black offers a knight trade, which is a logical thing to do, as it decreases the spatial disadvantage: the fewer pieces left, the less it matters that you don't have much space. }
7. Nxf6+
{ This move is quite rare, but it's been used in recent years by such strong young players as Xiong, Abdusattorov, Niemann, and others, and White scored really well: 58%. We are happy to force the bishop to go to f6 without having to determine or commit to placing our pieces on weird squares, such as after  7.Qd3  . }
7... Bxf6 8. Be3
{ Now, the goal is obviously to get the queen out and castle. In most cases, we will probably settle for Qd2, followed by queenside castling. However, in many positions, the queen can come to g4 after we play Nf4 and create a lot of threats on the kingside! }
8... O-O
{ This, of course, has been the most popular continuation − for now, Black just castles. }
9. Qd2
{ And we also continue to develop. The plan is to castle and then play Nf4, intending to either open the center with d4-d5! and install the knight on d5, when the time is right, or play g2-g3 and Bg2, increasing pressure on the long diagonal. Of course, the plan of Nf4, O-O-O and g2-g4, h2-h4, etc, can also be very strong and logical! }
9... b6
{ Black wants to develop the bishop to the long diagonal, where it will be rather active. Fair enough! }
10. O-O-O { We also just continue our development for now. } 10... Bb7 11. Nf4
{ This move is a very important one for us. Why so?  The knight can jump to h5, disturbing the bishop, helping us seek the bishop pair advantage, and helping us build up the kingside attack. It can support the d4-d5 break, which can at times @@StartBracket@@provided our pieces are more active@@EndBracket@@ help us favorably open up the center. It gets out of the bishop's way, which enables us to finish development easily. }
11... Nd7
{ Black keeps developing too. And this is when we need to make a decision about the direction of the game from now on. Do we attack on the kingside? Do we open the center? }
12. d5
{ The decision to open up the center is justified by the awkward placement of two of Black's minor pieces:  the bishop on f6 − we can easily hit it and hope to get the bishop pair; the knight on d7 − the pin on the d-file can prove really awkward for Black to deal with. }
12... exd5 { This leads to a very difficult endgame after a natural sequence. }
13. Nxd5 { Now, we'd like to take the f6-bishop. } 13... Bxd5 14. Qxd5
{ Black gave up the bishop pair and now struggles because of the pinned d7-knight. }
14... Ne5
{ It's logical to activate the pinned knight, but this move enables a queen trade, which is, of course, good for us. Why so? Easy! The bishop pair is a long-term advantage that manifests itself best in endgames with no major pieces, so swapping the queens and rooks is typically good for the side that has the bishop pair − in this case, it's us! }
15. Be2
{ But instead of begging for a trade  (taking the queen and helping Black activate the rook)  , we just keep developing. Let Black take instead! }
15... Qxd5 16. Rxd5
{ The upcoming endgame is going to be extremely difficult for Black. Why so? Isn't the pawn structure symmetrical?   The position is open enough for the bishop pair to prove very strong. The move ...b7-b6 has weakened the a6-square, the c6-square, and the h1-a8 diagonal. Our bishops can easily target the queenside pawns. For example, imagine if we trade rooks and play Bf4-b8. Wouldn't all the pawns just fall? The weakened queenside makes it easy for our king, once we trade the rooks, to invade and help us win their pawns. All in all, Black is nearly lost. }
*

