4... dxe4
{ Black is just capturing the free pawn. Later on, Black might return it and focus on rapid comfortable development, or instead try to hold on to it with ...f7-f5. }
5. a3
{ We, of course, follow up with our plan of kicking out the opponent's bishop and breaking the pin. At this point, Black needs to decide whether to hold on to the pawn by taking the knight and then doing something about the hanging pawn or to retreat, returning it right away. }
5... Bxc3+ 6. Nxc3
{ If we just get to take the e4-pawn without consequences, we should have a considerable advantage due to the extra space in the center, created by our d4-pawn, the bishop pair, and the fact Black's c8-bishop is inactive, as almost always in the French. Black should hurry to accomplish something right now! }
6... f5
{ An attempt to hold on to the extra pawn. As it often happens, it's not a good idea for Black to be greedy in this opening, just like in many other openings. This move doesn't help develop any pieces, and it weakens a lot of dark squares, such as the h1-b8 diagonal, the e5-square, and the a1-h8 diagonal, of course. Since we have a unique and unmatched dark-squared bishop, that's gonna be a huge problem for our opponent. }
7. Qh5+
{ Our goal is to make Black weaken the dark squares as much as possible, so we dream of forcing ...g7-g6 − and we make the dream come true! }
7... g6 8. Qh3
{ From here, the queen is watching the h7-pawn and the one on e6, potentially. The goal is to quickly develop the dark-squared bishop, likely to f4, castle queenside, and blow up the center with f2-f3! Once that happens, we'll have easy access to all the weaknesses, such as the e6-pawn after Bc4, Rhe1, and so on. How does Black plan on surviving? And why is Black agreeing to go through all these issues? Is it just to be a pawn up?! }
8... Qxd4
{ Unsurprisingly, taking one more pawn in a situation where you already have lots of weaknesses and no development turns out to be a spectacularly bad idea. But also, this variation is extremely beautiful, so I'd absolutely love to show it to you! }
9. Nb5 { First, we win even more time, making Black defend the c7-pawn. } 9...
Qg7
{ It makes sense for the queen to retreat here so that it can control the e5-square and help Black meet Bf4 with ...e6-e5. And, of course, the queen is hoping to make itself useful when it comes to defending the weakened kingside. }
10. Bf4 { The c7-pawn is in danger. } 10... e5
{ But Black seems to be able to block the diagonal and the threat, right? Not exactly... }
11. Qc3
{ This gorgeous move creates a threat to the pawns on c7 and e5, taking advantage of the fact the pawn is pinned. }
11... Nc6
{ Black's only defense, of course, as the c-file has to be blocked while also protecting the e5-pawn. }
12. O-O-O
{ We are not only developing and getting the king out of the way. We are also threatening to have our rook join the attack with Rd5! on the very next turn! }
12... Be6
{ Black must prevent that threat too. How do we keep developing the initiative? After all, Black seems to have a pretty strong center, so if nothing happens, we could see the initiative evaporate and the position would quickly become bad. We'd better hurry! }
13. f3 { Of course, we are now opening a lot of files in the center! } 13...
exf3 14. Re1
{ Now, the e-pawn will finally fall. Black cannot easily get out of the bind. I think it's enough to know up to this point and then think on your own, but I will show you a couple more moves, just to prove the position is beyond awful for our opponent. }
14... Nf6 { Black is trying to prepare kingside castling. What can go wrong? }
15. Rxe5 { Now, the e6-bishop is hanging. } 15... Nxe5 16. Nxc7+ Kf7 17. Nxe6
{ Next, we'll take the e5-knight with check, play Bc4, and get the h1-rook in the attack... you catch the drift. It's time for Black to think about what went wrong in the opening after resigning here. }
