{ Black is just capturing the free pawn. Later on, Black might return it and focus on rapid comfortable development, or instead try to hold on to it with ...f7-f5. }
5. a3
{ We, of course, follow up with our plan of kicking out the opponent's bishop and breaking the pin. At this point, Black needs to decide whether to hold on to the pawn by taking the knight and then doing something about the hanging pawn or to retreat, returning it right away. }
5... Bxc3+ 6. Nxc3
{ If we just get to take the e4-pawn without consequences, we should have a considerable advantage due to the extra space in the center, created by our d4-pawn, the bishop pair, and the fact Black's c8-bishop is inactive, as almost always in the French. Black should hurry to accomplish something right now! }
6... Nc6
{ Black's most principled and sound choice, immediately counterattacking the d4-pawn and making us react. }
7. Bf4
{ This rare move has been seen in just 3% of the games or so, but it's been mostly used in very recent years by top players. There are several ideas:  Potentially, we are looking to harass the c7-pawn with Nb5. We are looking to discourage the ...e6-e5 break. At some point, say if Black takes the d4-pawn, ideas like Be5! become possible, attacking whatever piece is on d4 and the g7-pawn. It's just a developing move. If we reach the consensus there's no need to defend the d4-pawn, then why go to the passive e3-square and not here? Next, we'd like to play Qd2 and castle queenside.   Black can consider accepting the d4-pawn, but the overwhelming majority of players who reached this position with the Black pieces tried  7...Nf6  or  7...Nge7  , looking to castle quickly instead of being greedy. }
7... Nf6
{ This move is aimed at protecting the e4-pawn. The downside is that the knight can get pinned after Bg5, and dealing with that pin might end up rather uncomfortable. Also, the knight isn't helping Black address the idea Bb5-Bxc6, like it could from e7. }
8. Bb5
{ Now, we're certainly interested in doubling Black's pawns on the queenside! }
8... Bd7
{ This move does prevent the structural damage but, surprisingly, brings Black a ton of new difficulties. }
9. d5
{ Opening up the position causes a disaster for Black here, as we will quickly get to castle queenside and put a lot of pressure on the d-file. }
9... exd5 10. Nxd5 { Now, the c7-pawn is hanging! } 10... Nxd5 11. Qxd5
{ Of course, the e4-pawn is hanging. Plus, we just want to castle queenside and attack the d7-bishop with two pieces, which will mean Black won't be able to castle, as that would leave the d7-bishop hanging. }
11... O-O 12. O-O-O
{ Again, that poor d7-bishop is under attack! Of course, the pawn is both untouchable and undesirable:  12.Qxe4  Re8  and we lose the queen. }
12... Bg4
{ Fortunately for Black, disaster can sort of be avoided by counterattacking our rook with tempo. Now, a bit of a forcing line occurs. }
13. Bxc6
{ We take advantage of the fact Black's knight is no longer defended by the bishop and gladly spoil the opponent's pawn structure. }
13... bxc6
{ 13...Bxd1??  is losing, as after  14.Bxb7!  Qxd5  15.Bxd5  ,  Black finds two pieces  (the d1-bishop and the a8-rook)  under attack. Black cannot save both and ends up a few pawns down. }
14. Qxd8 Raxd8 15. Rxd8
{ By trading the rooks, we solve the issue of the hanging rook on d1 without wasting any time. }
15... Rxd8 16. Bxc7
{ Despite the opposite-colored bishops in the endgame, which is something that makes a lot of players think of drawn tendencies, White is much better. The thing is that there are many weak Black pawns: on a7, c6, and even on e4, to an extent.  We'll bring the bishop back to e3, from where it'll keep an eye on the a7-pawn, and cover the d2-square. Once that's done, we'll set our king on a lovely journey: b2-b3, Kb2-c3-c4-c5. Likely, that'll enable us to win a pawn on the queenside, and then we'll run our pawn majority to promotion.  It's important to mention that having a pawn on e4 is bad for Black because it restricts the bishop and weakens the dark squares, such as the a1-h8 diagonal and the h2-b8 diagonal. Black is going to suffer for quite a long time! }
