8. Bb5
{ Now, we're certainly interested in doubling Black's pawns on the queenside! }
8... Nd5
{ This is a logical move that attacks the f4-bishop and the c3-knight and guarantees Black a trade of a pair of pieces, and that's what almost everyone who ever had this position with Black went for. }
9. Bxc6+ { However, now we get to spoil the pawn structure. } 9... bxc6 10. Bd2
{ And we simply retreat. Black is currently a pawn up, but the pawn structure is a mess. The c-pawns are obviously pretty weak, the e4-pawn is hanging, and if Black goes for a position with opposite-colored bishops, the dark squares, such as the a3-f8 diagonal, or the a1-h8 diagonal if Black weakens it with ...f7-f5, will turn out really weak. }
10... Nxc3 11. Bxc3
{ Now, we have a position with opposite-colored bishops only. What matters in such positions? Correct! Initiative! These bishops create drawing tendencies in the endgame, but in the middlegame, they facilitate the attack: when you have a dark-squared bishop and the opponent does not, it's much easier to attack on the dark squares. The extra pawn doesn't matter, and Black's bishop is sort of useless at the moment! }
11... O-O
{ 11...Ba6  can also be played in order to prevent us from castling kingside, but it's a pointless move since we want to castle queenside.  12.Qg4!  The queen can also enjoy itself from here if it cannot come to e2! Now, the e4 and g7-pawns are under double attack, this is not good for Black. }
12. Qe2
{ We are preparing to castle queenside, but first, we're making Black either give up the extra pawn or weaken the dark squares even more! }
12... f5
{ I guess if Black has to suffer, the extra pawn might as well be kept. Black is in a difficult position here, but giving up a pawn will yield a difficult position with even less hope. }
13. O-O-O
{ We have wonderful chances in the arising middlegame. On the next turn, we'll go f2-f3. The goal is to get the pawn back if Black ignores us, which will get us a position with multiple weaknesses on a7, c7, c6, e6, and so on. Most likely, Black will take, but then after gxf3! we open up the g-file.  It would be beyond convenient and beyond easy to bring all of our pieces to attack the g7-square as we double the rooks on the g-file, play Qe5!, maybe h2-h4-h5, and at some point d4-d5!, opening up our dark-squared bishop! I am afraid Black's position is nearly lost, because the king is much weaker, and because Black is kind of playing a piece down − this position is a perfect example of how the opposite-colored bishops can magnify any attack tremendously. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "9) Winawer 3.Nc3 Bb4 4.Nge2 − Main Lines"]
[Black "Winawer 4.Nge2 dxe4 5.a3 Bxc3+ #6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6
{ This move, followed by ...d7-d5, defines something called the French Defense. This opening is about fighting for the center rather ambitiously while avoiding direct piece play. As you will see, the first two moves only feature pawn play. The downside for Black is the locked-up light-squared bishop, and very often, this piece tends to be a large issue for quite a long time. }
2. d4 d5
{ Here, we arrive at massive crossroads. White can lock up the center with e4-e5, take Black's pawn and open up the position, or defend the pawn with some knight move − either to c3 or to d2. }
3. Nc3
{ After a long thought, I decided to suggest this move, which is the most critical and ambitious one. Why did I do that and what's the point of this move? As we can see, we are simply protecting the e4-pawn while keeping the center flexible for now. It's important to do so for the following practical reason: most Black players who play the French @@StartBracket@@and I am one of them, I just wrote a course on French that I'm in love with!@@EndBracket@@ love positions with pawn chains. Our goal is to try to avoid creating one!  However, don't worry: while the move  3.Nc3  is known for being a very principled and theoretically heavy one, we won't need loads of theory − instead, I am opting for practical, easy-to-learn sidelines, which still carry quite a bit of punch, as always!  In this position, we'll need to consider quite a lot of moves. Black can try to pin the knight with  3...Bb4  , which is known as the Winawer Variation − the most forcing and sharp one. Black can also try to force us to lock up the center with the move  3...Nf6  , which is another major theoretical move. The passive yet solid decision is to play  3...dxe4  − the Rubinstein Variation. Black is hoping to avoid the pawn chain situation and trade down, liquidating White's hopes to get a spatial advantage or long-term pressure.  And, of course, there are quite a few sidelines, such as  3...Nc6  ,  3...Be7  − the move I suggested in my Black French course,  3...h6  ,  3...a6  , and so on. Let's tackle them all one by one! }
3... Bb4
{ The famous Winawer Variation. Black develops in the most active way possible, immediately pinning the knight and threatening the e4-pawn. The downside of this move is that it weakens the g7-pawn. Plus, if Black ever goes ...Ne7, the bishop often ends up short on squares and unable to return to the kingside. }
4. Ne2
{ I like this rare move, played 13@@StartBracket@@!@@EndBracket@@ times less often than the main move  4.e5  . But, when I say 'sideline', don't worry − this is not a bad move! It's a variation that has been tried by such outstanding players as MVL, Firouzja, Ivanchuk, Xiong, and many others when they were looking to avoid the mainstream theory and get a bit more creative.    We make sure the structure remains very flexible by overprotecting the c3-knight with our other knight, so that if Black ever takes it, we can take back with the knight, avoiding doubled pawns. On the next turn, we are planning on continuing with a2-a3, kicking out the annoying bishop and neutralizing the pin. Once we do that, Black will have a hard time finding a good square for the bishop, and we'll continue the flexible nice development. But, of course, just as any line  (especially a sideline)  , this move has a few downsides, namely:  It blocks the development of our kingside, even if just temporarily. It leaves the e4-pawn hanging.   Black mostly captures the hanging pawn with @@StartFEN@@rnbqk1nr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/1b1PP3/2N5/PPP1NPPP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 3 4@@EndFEN@@  4...dxe4  , however, some players have tried such moves as  4...Nf6  ,  4...Nc6  , and  4...Ne7  . In this chapter, we'll focus on the main line  4...dxe4  . Of course, the sidelines are considered in great detail in the corresponding chapter. }
4... dxe4
{ Black is just capturing the free pawn. Later on, Black might return it and focus on rapid comfortable development, or instead try to hold on to it with ...f7-f5. }
5. a3
{ We, of course, follow up with our plan of kicking out the opponent's bishop and breaking the pin. At this point, Black needs to decide whether to hold on to the pawn by taking the knight and then doing something about the hanging pawn or to retreat, returning it right away. }
5... Bxc3+ 6. Nxc3
{ If we just get to take the e4-pawn without consequences, we should have a considerable advantage due to the extra space in the center, created by our d4-pawn, the bishop pair, and the fact Black's c8-bishop is inactive, as almost always in the French. Black should hurry to accomplish something right now! }
6... Nc6
{ Black's most principled and sound choice, immediately counterattacking the d4-pawn and making us react. }
7. Bf4
{ This rare move has been seen in just 3% of the games or so, but it's been mostly used in very recent years by top players. There are several ideas:  Potentially, we are looking to harass the c7-pawn with Nb5. We are looking to discourage the ...e6-e5 break. At some point, say if Black takes the d4-pawn, ideas like Be5! become possible, attacking whatever piece is on d4 and the g7-pawn. It's just a developing move. If we reach the consensus there's no need to defend the d4-pawn, then why go to the passive e3-square and not here? Next, we'd like to play Qd2 and castle queenside.   Black can consider accepting the d4-pawn, but the overwhelming majority of players who reached this position with the Black pieces tried  7...Nf6  or  7...Nge7  , looking to castle quickly instead of being greedy. }
7... Nxd4 { An awful blunder. } 8. Be5
{ We double-attack the d4-knight and the g7-pawn. The knight cannot just retreat in a random direction since then we'll win the g7-pawn and the h8-rook. }
8... Nf5 { Black has to protect the g7-pawn, logically. } 9. Nb5
{ However, now trouble comes from the other side! Yeah, just like that. The c7-pawn cannot be saved, and that a8-rook is also in trouble! }
9... Qxd1+ 10. Rxd1
{ Black cannot defend the c7-pawn. The best outcome would be just losing a lot of material. }
10... Ke7 11. Nxc7 { The rook is hanging again. } 11... Rb8 12. Nxe6
{ Again, the rook is under attack! } 12... Ra8 13. Nc7
{ Again, that poor rook! } 13... Rb8 14. Nd5+
{ And the game ends, we just pick up a free rook. } *

