7... Nge7
{ Developing the knight to this square has, of course, certain upsides and downsides.  The bad: The e4-pawn isn't defended. The h5 and g4-squares are not controlled, so our queen could jump there.   The good: Bg5 won't be a pin on the knight. In the event of Bb5-Bxc6 at any moment, Black can take back with the knight and keep the pawn structure intact. }
8. Qd2
{ We ignore the seemingly hanging d4-pawn and continue developing while preparing queenside castling. We've already seen in several lines of this chapter that holding on to the extra e4-pawn with ...f7-f5 is typically a poor idea, so we're in no hurry to win back the pawn, as we're not afraid of Black trying that.   This, by the way, is pretty much a new move − everyone takes the e4-pawn instead, but the correspondence players, who know better, keep developing with  8.Qd2  . Let's follow their ideas! }
8... Qxd4
{ This is a really bad idea. Black will suffer because of poor development and the fact our queenside pressure cannot be easily dealt with. }
9. Qxd4
{ By trading, we lure the knight to a square where it can be easily attacked, which will enable us to win even more time. }
9... Nxd4 10. O-O-O
{ We get our rook in the game by winning a tempo and, of course, the c7-pawn is still hanging! }
10... Nec6
{ It's logical for Black to try to hold on to the centralized knight, while also activating the other one. Black might be able to play ...e6-e5 on the next turn, blocking our bishop, so we'd better capture the pawn right away. }
11. Bxc7
{ We have the bishop pair in a position that is rapidly opening up. Our pieces are also a lot more active, and we are about to win the e4-pawn. Needless to say, if we do so, we'll be nearly winning due to:   the bishop pair; much more active pieces; controlling the only open d-file; having an outpost on d6; Black's queenside still being sort of stuck; the king being either inactive on g8 when Black castles, or blocking the rook from e8.  
So, Black's only logical defense is to try to hold on to the extra pawn. }
11... f5 12. b4
{ However, now we immediately set our queenside majority into motion, while also threatening to win a piece on the very next turn by playing b4-b5 and leaving the knights hanging. }
12... a6
{ Black has to stop that threat. But now, the b6-square becomes a hole. } 13.
Bb6
{ The knight is again being harassed. It has nowhere to go, so Black has only one defense. }
13... e5
{ But this move awfully weakens the central d5-square. That square is a bit too inviting for us to ignore... }
14. Nd5
{ So we don't. Now we are not only threatening the obvious fork Nc7+, but we also want to kick the active knight with c2-c3 whenever the time is right. }
14... Ne6
{ Black logically chooses to retreat in advance, while also stopping the fork. }
15. Bc4
{ However, the arising position is dead lost for Black, and the queenside is completely stuck. Black cannot ever castle kingside, as Nc7! would win since that e6-knight would end up pinned. Our bishop pair and the d5-knight are absolutely dominating the game. Next, we can double on the d-file, or maybe blow up the center with Rhe1 and f2-f3. Poor Black! }
*

