{ So should we. Now, we're ready to win back the e4-pawn without ever wondering if the one on d4 can be recaptured. Of course, if we do get to peacefully win the e4-pawn back, we will be clearly better due to our bishop pair, central control, space advantage, and the fact Black's pieces are pretty passive, especially the c8-bishop.  Then, we'll start building pressure on the kingside with Bd3, h2-h4, g2-g4, Ng5, and so on. I think Black should accept that uncomfortable scenario. However, most people would prefer to at least keep the extra pawn if they have to deal with an uncomfortable position. }
9... f5 { That's the move we should really investigate. } 10. f3
{ However, just as in some other lines with the same structure, we can blow up the center, open up the g-file, and prepare to start taking advantage of the weak backward e6-pawn and the outpost on e5. }
10... exf3 11. gxf3
{ Now, the g-file is open, and we are about to execute a very simple plan. What plan, exactly?  We'll develop the bishop to c4 to put more pressure on the e6-pawn so that our opponent is stuck defending it. We'll double the rooks on the g-file, and maybe bring the queen in there too. We'll advance the h-pawn to help us open up the king's shelter. At some point, the d4-d5! break might prove very powerful as well. }
11... Nd5 { Perhaps Black should try to trade down. } 12. Nxd5
{ We'll gladly do so. } 12... Qxd5
{ Now, we need to be paying some attention to the queen, which could suddenly jump on a2. It's not a big deal, just don't miss Qa1 with checkmate. That's something that can be easily stopped with, say, Qc3, making room for the king on a2. }
13. Rg1
{ We start putting more pressure on Black's kingside. Ideas like Bh6 and Qg5 are right around the corner! }
13... Rf7
{ It's logical for Black to stop that threat, while also defending the c7-pawn, which we could have easily won a move ago. We just choose to focus on developing an even more powerful initiative. }
14. c4
{ It's time to blow up the center, making full use of the bishop pair and our major pieces on the d-file, which are ready to dominate it once it's open! }
14... Qd8 15. d5
{ The poor black pieces are being pushed all the way back. Let me show you one fascinating and gorgeous way the game can go. }
15... Ne7
{ Of course, taking on d5 only helps White, so Black wisely chooses to retreat. }
16. Kb1
{ The point of this move is to avoid running into any checks on the c-file, and to prevent ...Qxd2 from being a check! Once this is no longer a problem, we can start considering forcing ideas like Bxc7 followed by d5-d6, and things of that sort. And, of course, we're creating a huge threat of dxe6, because then we'll take the f7-rook with check!   16.dxe6  doesn't work as well as a move later since after  16...Qxd2+  , Black gives a check, so we cannot take the rook! }
16... exd5 { Black has to capture in order to stop the dxe6 threat. } 17. cxd5
{ Now, d5-d6 is on the agenda, followed by Bc4! Or, of course, we can play Bc4 first and threaten d5-d6! later on. }
17... Ng6
{ For example, Black can try to block the g-file to stop all sorts of dangers. We are already going way above and beyond what's necessary, but I can't help myself. I NEED to show you this beautiful idea! }
18. Rxg6
{ We have such a dominant position that we can easily afford to sacrifice an exchange to just win a tempo and completely stop Black from being able to control any of the dark squares. }
18... hxg6 19. Bc4
{ With d5-d6 coming, as well as Rg1, or Be5 and f3-f4!, reinforcing the bishop on a gorgeous outpost, and Black's queenside pieces completely undeveloped and stuck, it's obvious our position is completely winning. What an example of domination! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "9) Winawer 3.Nc3 Bb4 4.Nge2 − Main Lines"]
[Black "Winawer 4.Nge2 dxe4 5.a3 Bxc3+ − Alternative 7.d5"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6
{ This move, followed by ...d7-d5, defines something called the French Defense. This opening is about fighting for the center rather ambitiously while avoiding direct piece play. As you will see, the first two moves only feature pawn play. The downside for Black is the locked-up light-squared bishop, and very often, this piece tends to be a large issue for quite a long time. }
2. d4 d5
{ Here, we arrive at massive crossroads. White can lock up the center with e4-e5, take Black's pawn and open up the position, or defend the pawn with some knight move − either to c3 or to d2. }
3. Nc3
{ After a long thought, I decided to suggest this move, which is the most critical and ambitious one. Why did I do that and what's the point of this move? As we can see, we are simply protecting the e4-pawn while keeping the center flexible for now. It's important to do so for the following practical reason: most Black players who play the French @@StartBracket@@and I am one of them, I just wrote a course on French that I'm in love with!@@EndBracket@@ love positions with pawn chains. Our goal is to try to avoid creating one!  However, don't worry: while the move  3.Nc3  is known for being a very principled and theoretically heavy one, we won't need loads of theory − instead, I am opting for practical, easy-to-learn sidelines, which still carry quite a bit of punch, as always!  In this position, we'll need to consider quite a lot of moves. Black can try to pin the knight with  3...Bb4  , which is known as the Winawer Variation − the most forcing and sharp one. Black can also try to force us to lock up the center with the move  3...Nf6  , which is another major theoretical move. The passive yet solid decision is to play  3...dxe4  − the Rubinstein Variation. Black is hoping to avoid the pawn chain situation and trade down, liquidating White's hopes to get a spatial advantage or long-term pressure.  And, of course, there are quite a few sidelines, such as  3...Nc6  ,  3...Be7  − the move I suggested in my Black French course,  3...h6  ,  3...a6  , and so on. Let's tackle them all one by one! }
3... Bb4
{ The famous Winawer Variation. Black develops in the most active way possible, immediately pinning the knight and threatening the e4-pawn. The downside of this move is that it weakens the g7-pawn. Plus, if Black ever goes ...Ne7, the bishop often ends up short on squares and unable to return to the kingside. }
4. Ne2
{ I like this rare move, played 13@@StartBracket@@!@@EndBracket@@ times less often than the main move  4.e5  . But, when I say 'sideline', don't worry − this is not a bad move! It's a variation that has been tried by such outstanding players as MVL, Firouzja, Ivanchuk, Xiong, and many others when they were looking to avoid the mainstream theory and get a bit more creative.    We make sure the structure remains very flexible by overprotecting the c3-knight with our other knight, so that if Black ever takes it, we can take back with the knight, avoiding doubled pawns. On the next turn, we are planning on continuing with a2-a3, kicking out the annoying bishop and neutralizing the pin. Once we do that, Black will have a hard time finding a good square for the bishop, and we'll continue the flexible nice development. But, of course, just as any line  (especially a sideline)  , this move has a few downsides, namely:  It blocks the development of our kingside, even if just temporarily. It leaves the e4-pawn hanging.   Black mostly captures the hanging pawn with @@StartFEN@@rnbqk1nr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/1b1PP3/2N5/PPP1NPPP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 3 4@@EndFEN@@  4...dxe4  , however, some players have tried such moves as  4...Nf6  ,  4...Nc6  , and  4...Ne7  . In this chapter, we'll focus on the main line  4...dxe4  . Of course, the sidelines are considered in great detail in the corresponding chapter. }
4... dxe4
{ Black is just capturing the free pawn. Later on, Black might return it and focus on rapid comfortable development, or instead try to hold on to it with ...f7-f5. }
5. a3
{ We, of course, follow up with our plan of kicking out the opponent's bishop and breaking the pin. At this point, Black needs to decide whether to hold on to the pawn by taking the knight and then doing something about the hanging pawn or to retreat, returning it right away. }
5... Bxc3+ 6. Nxc3
{ If we just get to take the e4-pawn without consequences, we should have a considerable advantage due to the extra space in the center, created by our d4-pawn, the bishop pair, and the fact Black's c8-bishop is inactive, as almost always in the French. Black should hurry to accomplish something right now! }
6... Nc6
{ Black's most principled and sound choice, immediately counterattacking the d4-pawn and making us react. }
7. d5
{ This is the move that I was originally hoping to make work. It is aimed at opening up the center, likely trading queens, and achieving a symmetrical endgame where White has the bishop pair. I tried my best to make this variation appealing but didn't exactly succeed.  Let me clarify. I don't mean I was looking for some huge winning advantage, of course! Instead, I just wanted a playable comfortable endgame with the bishop pair, where we'd learn a bunch of ideas and score a lot of points due to the superior understanding. But the problem is that the lines are fairly obvious from Black's perspective, and the game is rather forcing.  You can still use this variation and investigate it in more depth on your own, but if Black is reasonably well prepared, we don't have that much to boast of, I am afraid. At the same time, White still scores a wonderful 58%! So, I decided to offer it as a theory-light alternative variation, which you can play when you are into risk-free lazy chess. }
7... exd5 8. Qxd5
{ We are offering a queen trade. Of course, Black won't trade on d5, as it will drastically activate our knight and threaten the c7-pawn. }
8... Be6
{ Black hopes we take the queen, which will get the rook in the game. Jobava did that in a recent game versus GM Zierk and won, but it's not hard for Black to get equality there. }
9. Qxe4
{ 9.Qxd8+  Rxd8  10.Nxe4?!  Nd4!  Unfortunately, this active move prevents us from just endlessly dreaming of how lovely our bishop pair will be.  11.Bd3  Bc4!⩱  and Black takes away our bishop pair, making use of the fact we cannot take as the c2-pawn and the a1-rook will end up forked. }
9... Nf6
{ Black wins a bit too much time, for my taste, by attacking our queen. } 10.
Qa4
{ This is a less popular move, which again leads to an equal endgame.  10.Qh4  is White's most common move, hoping to  play Bg5 next, pin the knight and potentially double the pawns, damaging the structure.  However, after  10...Qd4!  , which is the precise defense, Black gets to equalize comfortably. For more details, see the next Informational. }
10... Qd4 11. Bb5
{ Again, we do restrain Black's activity and prevent all the ...Nd4 ideas by pinning the knight. Of course, at this very moment, we are threatening to win the queen, as the knight is pinned and cannot take it. }
11... Qxa4 12. Bxa4 O-O-O
{ Black unpins the knight, and on the next turn, would like to jump with it to d4. Sure enough, we have the bishop pair, but as you can see, Black is considerably ahead in development and the pieces are much more active. }
13. Bxc6 { We try to ruin the pawn structure and trade down a bit. } 13... bxc6
14. Be3 Nd5
{ However, now Black forces further simplifications and achieves an equal endgame. }
15. Nxd5
{ After  15...Rxd5  ,  the position might look a bit nicer for us since our structure is just visually prettier, but after ...Kb7 on the next turn, Black's queenside pawns won't ever be a real problem. Black doesn't even have to play that move − we cannot win the a7-pawn, as after ...c6-c5! our bishop will get trapped and lost. So, this is a risk-free way of playing, no doubt. But you won't win much, either. }
*

