Qh4
{ This is White's most common move, hoping to play Bg5 next, pin the knight and potentially double the pawns, damaging the structure. }
10... Qd4
{ However, with this precise defense, Black gets to equalize comfortably by offering a queen trade, but under favorable circumstances: Black wants to activate the knight if we accept! }
11. Bg5
{ This move offers better practical opportunities since there is a good chance Black will fall for a bit of a trap.  11.Qxd4  Nxd4  12.Bd3  seems to take everything under control,  as the c2-pawn is defended. If we had just a couple more moves, we'd be able to push those annoying black pieces back, wouldn't we... Unfortunately, time does matter, and we don't have enough of it.  12...Bf5!=  and Black swaps off the bishop pair, equalizing. }
11... Qe5+
{ Black should take advantage of the fact our king is still stuck in the center, to make our bishop go to a somewhat passive square. }
12. Be2
{ And this is where you hope Black falls for a trap if you choose to play this 7.d5 variation. Should Black castle queenside, or deprive us of the bishop pair with  12...Nd4? }
12... O-O-O
{ The way to go. Sure enough, Black accepts the structural damage but doesn't care.   12...Nd4?!  This natural move is a really suspicious decision. Why so? Because after  13.O-O-O!  , we keep the bishop pair, sort of.  We just want to play Bd3! next, pointing out that Black's last move was pointless. But wait, we left our bishop hanging, didn't we? Not exactly...    13...Nxe2+?  14.Nxe2  Qxe2??  Now, Black's lack of development will make a world of difference.  15.Bxf6!  gxf6  16.Rhe1!  The queen is forced to go away, and the tremendously active white pieces will finish off the king that carelessly chose to stay in the center.  16...Qa6  17.Qxf6+-  ,  the rook is under attack. Rd3, followed by Red1 and Rxd8, is kind of inevitable. Poor Black! 1-0 Zaitsev-Kosyrev, Moscow 1996. }
13. O-O h6 14. Bxf6 gxf6
{ The wrecked pawns are compensated by the open g-file and Black's ability to harass our king by doubling there, playing ...f5-f4-f3, ...Bd5, and ...Nd4. }
