[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "10) French − Typical Structures and Ideas"]
[Black "How White's center collapses without c2-c3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. e5
{ Of course, we don't play the Advance Variation. However, this pawn structure occurs in many French positions  (in most, in fact!)  , so it doesn't matter what the opening sequence is. In this position, the plans of both sides are pretty simple and straightforward.  You see, we have a position with the pawn chains. The white pawns are pointing at the black kingside, and the e5-pawn is taking away the f6 and d6-squares from the black pieces. For that reason, it's very easy for White to bring all the pieces to the kingside with Qh5, Nf3, Ng5, or Bg5, Bd3, and so on.  Black, on the other hand, has less space. The central pawns are pointing at the queenside, and that is where Black will be playing. Black will try to go ...c7-c5, undermining the d4-pawn, and put more pressure on it with ...Nc6, ...Qb6, and so on. }
3... c5 { Black is immediately undermining the center. } 4. Nf3
{ White had to protect the d4-pawn with the pawn. But what happens if White doesn't?   4.c3!  is the only correct move here, White needs to protect the center. We will see and discuss it in the next examples! }
4... cxd4 { Now, the e5-pawn becomes weaker too! } 5. Nxd4 Nc6
{ The e5-pawn is now a problem! } 6. f4
{ White needs to protect the e5-pawn, but this move weakens the g1-a7 diagonal. As you might have seen in the theoretical chapter, we quite often go for this structure as White. Overall, it's a good one, but only if White can stabilize the center with Be3, Qd2, and so on. But here, White is not in time... }
6... Bc5 7. Be3 Qb6
{ As it is easy to see, the knight on d4 and the pawn on b2 are in trouble. }
8. Bb5
{ In order to stop both threats, White has to make this move. However, giving up the powerful light-squared bishop and improving Black's pawn structure isn't attractive either. }
8... Bd7
{ Black unpinned the knight, which leaves White with the only choice. } 9. Bxc6
bxc6
{ The d4-square is no longer an outpost because Black can and will go ...c6-c5, kicking it out! }
10. b3 { The b2-pawn was hanging, so White needed to address that threat. }
10... Be7 11. O-O c5
{ Black has a very powerful center and the bishop pair. On the other hand, White has no active ideas and the pieces are being pushed back. It's extremely important to realize you don't want this to happen, so whenever possible, you need to either protect the d4-pawn with c2-c3, or the e5-pawn with f2-f4, but only if you can make sure the pieces are active enough and things do not fall apart. Now, let's go to the next example! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "10) French − Typical Structures and Ideas"]
[Black "How White loses the d4-pawn"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. e5
{ Of course, we don't play the Advance Variation. However, this pawn structure occurs in many French positions  (in most, in fact!)  , so it doesn't matter what the opening sequence is. In this position, the plans of both sides are pretty simple and straightforward.  You see, we have a position with the pawn chains. The white pawns are pointing at the black kingside, and the e5-pawn is taking away the f6 and d6-squares from the black pieces. For that reason, it's very easy for White to bring all the pieces to the kingside with Qh5, Nf3, Ng5, or Bg5, Bd3, and so on.  Black, on the other hand, has less space. The central pawns are pointing at the queenside, and that is where Black will be playing. Black will try to go ...c7-c5, undermining the d4-pawn, and put more pressure on it with ...Nc6, ...Qb6, and so on. }
3... c5
{ Black undermines the d4-pawn. From the previous example, we know how bad it would be if we don't protect it with the pawn. }
4. c3 { So, this time we do. } 4... Nc6
{ Black is going to play ...Qb6 next, putting more pressure on this pawn. Of course, there were other good theoretical moves − for example, in my Black French course, I recommend a different setup. But that's not the point, of course. }
5. Nf3 Qb6 6. Be2
{ Let's say White just keeps making natural-looking developing moves. } 6...
Nge7 7. O-O
{ White's position wasn't bad until castling kingside, but now it collapses. }
7... cxd4
{ On the other hand, attacking the pawn with  7...Nf5  while keeping the tension in the center is not nearly as good since White can rescue it with  8.dxc5!  Bxc5  and the position might look good, but Black failed to win the pawn. In fact, Black's position isn't good either because after  9.b4!  ,  White grabs space and is about to win even more both space and time by kicking the opponent's pieces out of their active positions. }
8. cxd4 Nf5
{ The d4-pawn cannot be saved, which means White is losing a pawn and the impressive center is collapsing. Of course, White cannot save the pawn with Be3 either because that move would drop the b2-pawn. Overall, as we are about to discover in the next example, Black isn't really interested in trading on d4 too prematurely. However, doing so in order to win the pawn is very appropriate, of course. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "10) French − Typical Structures and Ideas"]
[Black "Why Black shouldn't vs. play ...cxd4 too early"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. e5
{ Of course, we don't play the Advance Variation. However, this pawn structure occurs in many French positions  (in most, in fact!)  , so it doesn't matter what the opening sequence is. In this position, the plans of both sides are pretty simple and straightforward.  You see, we have a position with the pawn chains. The white pawns are pointing at the black kingside, and the e5-pawn is taking away the f6 and d6-squares from the black pieces. For that reason, it's very easy for White to bring all the pieces to the kingside with Qh5, Nf3, Ng5, or Bg5, Bd3, and so on.  Black, on the other hand, has less space. The central pawns are pointing at the queenside, and that is where Black will be playing. Black will try to go ...c7-c5, undermining the d4-pawn, and put more pressure on it with ...Nc6, ...Qb6, and so on. }
3... c5 { Black undermines the d4-pawn. } 4. c3
{ From the previous example, we know how bad it would be if we don't protect it with the pawn. }
4... Nc6 5. Nf3
{ We have seen these moves in the previous example. There, Black played  5...Qb6  , putting pressure on the pawn. But what if instead,  Black traded on d4? Are there any downsides to it? }
5... cxd4
{ This move, unless it results in directly winning the d4-pawn as in the last example, is a considerable mistake. Why so? }
6. cxd4 Qb6 7. Nc3
{ Because now White gets an opportunity to develop the knight to c3! From here, the knight could do two things.   There could be room for a setup Bd3-Ne2, overprotecting the d4-pawn and looking to bring the knight to the kingside to help with kingside pressure. White can do what we are about to see! }
7... Nge7
{ Black seems to be preparing ...Nf5, putting pressure on the d4-pawn. } 8. a3
{ White is covering up the b4-square. Why? } 8... Nf5 9. Na4
{ So that Black never has a check on b4. With this move, White is kicking out the black queen from its annoying attacking position. Once Black's queen leaves, White just finishes development with the center being safe and sound. Remember, White's position is better in the long run due to the space advantage and lack of bad pieces. Black needs to generate counterplay right away, and failed to. }
9... Qc7 10. Be2
{ With O-O, b2-b4, Bb2, Rc1, etc, coming next, it is obvious that Black does not have a single active idea. So, the position is strategically lost. Now you know why it's not good for Black to trade on d4 early on! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "10) French − Typical Structures and Ideas"]
[Black "How White stabilizes the center"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. e5
{ Of course, we don't play the Advance Variation. However, this pawn structure occurs in many French positions  (in most, in fact!)  , so it doesn't matter what the opening sequence is. In this position, the plans of both sides are pretty simple and straightforward.  You see, we have a position with the pawn chains. The white pawns are pointing at the black kingside, and the e5-pawn is taking away the f6 and d6-squares from the black pieces. For that reason, it's very easy for White to bring all the pieces to the kingside with Qh5, Nf3, Ng5, or Bg5, Bd3, and so on.  Black, on the other hand, has less space. The central pawns are pointing at the queenside, and that is where Black will be playing. Black will try to go ...c7-c5, undermining the d4-pawn, and put more pressure on it with ...Nc6, ...Qb6, and so on. }
3... c5 { Black undermines the d4-pawn. } 4. c3
{ From the previous example, we know how bad it would be if we don't protect it with the pawn. }
4... Nc6 5. Nf3 Qb6
{ From the previous example, we know Black should not trade on d4 prematurely because White wants to play Nc3-a4, kicking out the black queen from its active position and stabilizing the center. But we also know from another earlier example that if White just goes Be2 and O-O, ignoring the opponent's pressure on the center, it can easily collapse after ...Ne7-f5 and ideas of that sort.  So, the natural question appears. If White's center is fragile, and if Black knows they shouldn't help us stabilize it by taking on d4, and if we know it can easily collapse unless some action is taken... what action needs to be taken? It's fairly simple, actually. We need to MAKE Black play ...cxd4 somehow! But how can we do that? }
6. a3
{ This slow-looking move would never come to any reasonable player's mind unless they have some experience in the pawn chain positions. Why are we wasting time with a pawn move instead of developing a piece? Because our key priority is stabilizing the center. We want to play b2-b4, putting too much pressure on the c5-pawn. We'll make Black push it @@StartBracket@@more on that later@@EndBracket@@ or take on d4, but in that case, the knight gets the long-awaited c3-square! }
6... Nge7 7. b4 cxd4
{ 7...c4  this is a classic positional mistake and it will be discussed in one of the next examples. }
8. cxd4 Nf5 9. Bb2
{ The center is protected just in time! Success!   9.Be3  also does a good enough job of protecting the center since the b2-pawn is no longer hanging, as it's now on b4. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "10) French − Typical Structures and Ideas"]
[Black "Why playing ...c5-c4 is usually a bad idea"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 c5 4. c3 Nc6 5. Nf3 Bd7 6. Bd3 c4
{ This move could be seen in numerous French positions, and it's almost always a bad one. Why so? Very easy. White is going to be attacking on the kingside and has a large spatial advantage and no bad pieces. Black, on the other hand, has less space and a bad light-squared bishop. Black needs counterplay, NOW! But, once Black locks up the center, all the aspirations for counterplay are gone. }
7. Bc2
{ White is going to start building up a kingside attack without ever having to worry about the fragility of the d4-pawn. Let's see a few more moves to better understand how White's initiative will be developing. }
7... Nge7 8. Nbd2 Ng6 9. h4
{ This move creates a threat of h4-h5, kicking the knight out to a very uncomfortable square. Black needs to prevent that, but at what cost?! }
9... h5 10. Ng5
{ Now, unfortunately for the opponent, there is a huge problem with the g5-square. It's not really possible to kick the knight out with ...f7-f6, and that is for several reasons: it would hang the g6-knight and if it didn't, it would weaken the e6-pawn. Also, the h5-pawn is now rather weak! This means Black cannot easily castle without hanging it. By the way, we see this theme in the Caro-Kann positions. }
10... Be7 11. Ndf3 O-O
{ As I had explained earlier, Black could not castle. The h5-pawn can no longer be protected! }
12. Ng1
{ White will win the h5-pawn and checkmate Black on h7. This is a disaster! } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "10) French − Typical Structures and Ideas"]
[Black "How the e5-pawn gets too weak and lost"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Be7
{ This is the variation I propose for Black in my Black French course. Black is keeping the tension in the center, trying to provoke the move Nf3. Provoking that move would mean White won't be able to play f2-f4 anymore, which means it would be harder to protect the e5-pawn. }
4. Nf3
{ Let's say White does make this move. It's not a mistake yet, of course.  4.Bd3  is the move I suggest for White in the theoretical part. }
4... Nf6 5. e5
{ Although this move has also been played by quite a few strong players, I don't have much confidence in it. This is because White's pawn center might turn out rather difficult to defend!   Keeping the tension in the center with  5.Bd3  is a better idea, I believe. }
5... Nfd7 6. Bd3
{ 6.Ne2!  c5  7.c3  is a better setup for White, I believe, because playing this way allows protecting the d4-pawn with the pawn, which is really valuable! }
6... c5
{ Now, it's no longer possible to protect the d4-pawn with the c-pawn, or the e5-pawn with the f-pawn! This means White can easily get in trouble. }
7. O-O
{ 7.dxc5  Nxc5⇆  gives Black a very pleasant position but at least doesn't result in a complete collapse. }
7... cxd4 8. Nxd4 Nxe5
{ And White's center got destroyed and lost! As you can see, being able to meet ...cxd4 with cxd4, protecting the e5-pawn, or being able to play f2-f4, overprotecting the e5-pawn, is really important for White in these positions. If White fails to do that, White can quickly get in trouble. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "10) French − Typical Structures and Ideas"]
[Black "Why the move f2-f4 is so valuable"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. e5 Nfd7
{ As usual, we have a position with the pawn chains in the center. The problem is that since we played the move Nc3, we can no longer go c2-c3, protecting the d4-pawn. And, as we had seen in the previous example, a big problem is that Black is about to go ...c7-c5, then take the d4-pawn, and try to win the one on e5! We really need to do something about that. Fortunately, the solution is easy. }
5. f4
{ With this move, White not only grabs space on the kingside but also overprotects the e5-pawn.   5.Nf3  c5!  results in a position with a ton of pressure on White's center. This is not fun for White! Although, this is also a somewhat reasonable theoretical line, at a club level; White will see the position fall apart most of the time though. }
5... c5 6. Nf3 cxd4 7. Nxd4
{ Although Black managed to get rid of the d4-pawn, the one on e5 is perfectly safe and healthy since we got that key move f2-f4! in. This is a very important idea to remember! If you have this pawn chain, it's very desirable to be able to play either c2-c3 or f2-f4. Or both! But if none of the two are possible, chances are the center could collapse in no time. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "10) French − Typical Structures and Ideas"]
[Black "How to protect the center with c2-c3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Nc6 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. e5 Nd7
{ This is another interesting key idea. We just seem to have some opening position, what could be so interesting about it? One detail is that the black knight is on c6. This makes it impossible for Black to go ...c7-c5, at least in the near future, which is good news for White's center. However, the idea we are about to see is useful for many reasons − both when Black can and when cannot go ...c7-c5. }
6. Ne2
{ Remember this move! What are the ideas behind it?  The knight wasn't doing anything on c3. Now, it is going to f4 or g3 in order to help White develop play on 'White's' part of the board − the kingside. It could become an instrumental attacking piece by reaching the h5-square or supporting the f4-f5 break at some point.  It frees up the c-pawn, allowing White to meet ...c7-c5 in the future with c2-c3, keeping the d4-pawn safe. This way, even if Black takes ...cxd4, White can take back with the c-pawn, keeping the pawn on e5 safe. That's really important since f2-f4 isn't possible at this point, so if White wasn't able to meet ...cxd4 with cxd4, the e5-pawn could end up really vulnerable. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "10) French − Typical Structures and Ideas"]
[Black "How to keep the d3-bishop safe"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 h6 4. Bd3 Nc6 5. Nf3 Nf6 6. e5 Nd7
{ Now is the time to familiarize ourselves with another valuable idea. This position, which occurred from one of the numerous sidelines, is not important to us at all. What is important is to understand a few key ideas.   The knight on c3 is misplaced. It is not putting any pressure on such squares as e4, d5, or b5. It's not defending anything. So, it needs to be moved away to a better spot. Our light-squared bishop is our most valuable piece. Unlike the other one, it's not restricted by the central pawns. Oftentimes, it's used for what we know as the Greek Gift, or for some other attacking ideas on the kingside. }
7. a3
{ This is a very valuable move. We prevent ...Nb4, making sure the bishop on d3 will be safe forever. Then, we are ready to go Ne2, preparing c2-c3 to make sure the center would be always more than sufficiently protected, and Nf4 or Ng3, continuing to improve the knight's position.   It could be tempting to just start rerouting the knight to the kingside right away. However,  7.Ne2  appears to be a mistake due to  7...Nb4!  Of course, it would be a huge disappointment if Black was able to deprive us of our best minor pieces. However, keeping it isn't that easy and comfy either.  8.Bb5  c6!  9.Ba4  b5!  10.Bb3  c5!  Black keeps winning more and more tempi by taking advantage of this bishop's bad position! Now, Black is threatening to play ...c5-c4, trapping it. For instance, after  11.c3  c4!  ,  Black gets it anyway. You need to be very careful to make sure such a scenario does not occur! }
7... Be7 8. Ne2
{ The knight is on its merry way to the kingside, the center can be always protected with c2-c3, and the light-squared bishop is shielded from all kinds of harassment like ...Nb4. What a great life! }
*

