[White "10) French − Typical Structures and Ideas"]
[Black "Why provoking Nf3 often makes Black's king safe"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Be7 4. Bd3
{ This is one of the theoretical positions that arise in the course. And, actually, in my Black French course too! The reason why we are looking at it again is because it's really useful to know the following idea.   4.Nf3  ,  let's compare the main idea we're seeing to this line.  4...Nf6  5.e5  Nfd7  .  As you can see, the white queen can no longer jump out to g4, so Black is not in danger of any sorts! }
4... Nf6 5. e5 Nfd7 6. Qg4
{ Since Black failed to wait for the move Ng1-f3, the queen is not blocked, it is able to come to the kingside. And this is an extremely valuable detail because now, Black's kingside is going to be in trouble! }
6... O-O
{ 6...g6  7.Bh6  makes Black really regret not being able to castle.   6...Kf8  doesn't lose anything, but just places the king in a very awkward position. There's no telling how to activate the h8-rook! }
7. Bh6 { This just loses an exchange and the game. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "10) French − Typical Structures and Ideas"]
[Black "Why the dark-squared bishop is so dangerous in the Winawer"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "1r1qk2r/pp1b1pp1/4p1n1/3pP3/2pP2B1/P1P3P1/2PQ2P1/1RB2RK1 b k - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

1... Qe7
{ This position is a training exercise that I had found in one of the old Soviet books, which came from the game Stein-Petrosian. This is a typical structure that arises in the Winawer French. Granted, you wouldn't see it that much in the course, if at all. However, it's still instructive to see the point!  See, White's structure might not look that pretty since the c-pawns are doubled and the a-pawn is isolated. However, those pawns cannot be attacked anytime soon. But, White has a huge trump: the dark-squared bishop! This piece has no competitors. So, how would White try to take advantage of this fact? Black fails to restrict the bishop and gets in trouble right away... }
2. a4
{ White is happy to sacrifice a pawn in order to clear up the a3-f8 diagonal! }
2... Bxa4 3. Ra1
{ If the bishop retreats, White can do what happened in the game, or simply take back the sacrificed pawn with Rxa7. }
3... b5
{ Black preserves the extra pawn, but now the light-squared bishop is dead. }
4. Ba3 { As you can see, Black is no longer able to castle. } 4... Qd7 5. Rf2
{ Time to attack a new weakness: the f7-pawn! } 5... Rb7 6. Raf1
{ White got a very powerful attack and ended the game in no time. A very powerful display of the strength of the unique dark-squared bishop! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
