[White "10) French − Typical Structures and Ideas"]
[Black "How to protect the d4-pawn and square"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "rnb1k2r/pppnqppp/4p3/3pP3/3P4/2N5/PPP2PPP/R2QKBNR w KQkq - 0 7"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ This is another position from one of the theoretical chapters. A memory marker, if you will. Black is about to go ...c7-c5 sometime soon, trying to ruin our center. As you hopefully remember by now, the knight on c3 is often misplaced in the long run, because it prevents the white c-pawn from helping protect and reinforce the center. Luckily, White can solve this problem in more than one way. }
7. Qd2
{ It might seem as though White is simply getting ready to castle queenside, but White actually has a different idea in mind!   7.f4  is, of course, another perfectly reasonable way to play, also reinforcing the center. }
7... a6
{ In order to avoid running into this annoying Nb5 idea, Black has to make sure to cover up the b5-square.   7...c5?  is too premature, as after  8.Nb5±  ,  Black is not well-equipped to prevent Nd6+ and Nc7+, which means Black is in deep trouble. }
8. Nd1
{ What is this mysterious move? Very easy: White is getting ready to meet ...c7-c5 with c2-c3, reinforcing the d4-pawn! The knight will find a good place for itself on e3 or f2 later on. The position is rather closed, so the matter of keeping the center stable and solid is much more urgent and relevant than piece play. }
8... c5 9. c3 { The center is under control and White is very happy. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "10) French − Typical Structures and Ideas"]
[Black "How to get counterplay on the f-file"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1b1k2r/1p1nqppp/p1n1p3/2ppP3/3P1P2/2P5/PP1Q2PP/R2NKBNR b KQkq - 0 10"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ As we are seeing throughout the theoretical chapters and model games, often Black ends up in very passive and unpleasant positions with little space and no counterplay. So, let's remind ourselves of  (or learn!)  the best plan that allows Black to get counterplay. And, if the White player is too naive or ignorant, White's center can fall apart in no time! }
10... f6
{ In order to get real counterplay, Black needs to open up the f-file for the rook. }
11. Nf3 cxd4
{ As we are about to discover, it is crucial for our opponent to include this pawn trade in order to weaken our d4-pawn. }
12. cxd4 fxe5 { Black also opens up the f-file. } 13. fxe5 O-O 14. Bd3
{ This move looks logical, as it develops the piece to the most active square. However, it is a bad one, as it completely ignores the opponent's idea.   14.Nf2!  is the correct move. It frees up the d1-square for the rook, so it always can help protect the d4-pawn, and it prevents any checks from the e1-h4 diagonal, therefore keeping everything under control. White is slightly better here, according to our analysis from the theoretical chapter. }
14... Rxf3 { What is this? Black eliminates the defender of the d4-pawn! } 15.
gxf3 Qh4+ { Oops! Now, the d4-pawn is falling. } 16. Qf2 Nxd4
{ It turns out Black has another cute trick up the sleeve. } 17. Qxh4 Nxf3+ 18.
Kf2 Nxh4
{ The white rooks don't have anything useful to do, which means Black, who has two pawns for the exchange, and a weakness on e5 to play against, is clearly in the driver's seat. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "10) French − Typical Structures and Ideas"]
[Black "Martin Gonzales − Sergey Dolmatov, Barcelona 1983"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "rnbq1rk1/ppp3pp/4p3/3pPp1Q/3P2P1/P1P5/2P2P1P/R1B1KB1R b KQ - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ This is one of my favorite positional examples of an exchange sacrifice in the French. It comes from an old game between Gonzales and Dolmatov, which I had first seen in the book of my coach who took me from roughly 1800 to 2200, FM Leonid Nikolaev.  In this position, it seems as though White has been building a rather annoying attack on the kingside. White is about to play Bd3, Rg1, take on f5, maybe throw the bishop on g5 or h6 and seriously challenge the black king's safety. What should Black do about that? }
1... Bd7
{ Black is just improving the bishop, looking to bring it to e8 and g6. } 2.
gxf5 Rxf5 3. Qh3
{ This is the key position. White is about to go Bd3, attacking the rook and x-raying the h7-pawn through the rook. Looks like Black is in trouble, isn't it? }
3... Be8 4. Bd3 Bg6 { Black doesn't care about the hanging rook! } 5. Rg1 Qf8
6. Bxf5 Bxf5
{ What compensation did Black get for the rook?  all the attacking ideas are gone; all the light squares and diagonals, such as b1-h7, are really weak; White's king is now permanently weak. It cannot, obviously, be rescued by kingside castling, as White gave up that right. Staying in the center also looks suspicious.  
Finally, castling queenside is extremely unsafe as well since Black can attack with ideas like ...Nc6-a5-c4, ...c7-c5, ...Rc8-c6-b6, and so on. So, White has no plan, and the extra exchange is sort of useless since there aren't a lot of open files. }
7. Qf3
{ The rest of the game is not relevant to our goals, but I think you would enjoy seeing it. }
7... Nc6
{ 7...Bxc2  8.Qe2  Bg6  9.Qb5  would have complicated things too much. The key piece of advice when you sacrificed an exchange for long-lasting positional compensation is to not hurry to regain the material. Instead, it is worth just improving the positions of your pieces and seeing the opponent's pawns will get lost one by one. }
8. Qe2 Kh8 9. a4 Qf7 10. a5
{ How can Black improve the position considerably? } 10... b6 11. axb6 cxb6
{ Now, Black has a passed pawn on the a-file. } 12. Rg3 Na5 13. f3 Nc4
{ The advantage is obvious, as Black can advance the pawns on the queenside. }
14. Kf2 a5 15. Kg1 a4 16. Ba3 Bg6 17. Kf2 Qf5 18. Ra2 Ra7 19. Bc1 h6 20. Kg1 a3
21. Rg2 Bh5 22. Rg3 Qf8 23. Rh3 Bg6 24. Rg3 Bf5 25. Qg2 b5 26. Qf2 b4 27. Qe1
Bxc2 28. cxb4 Bb1 29. Ra1 a2 30. f4 Qe8 31. Qe2 Qa4 32. Qe1 Rb7 33. Bd2 Nxd2
34. Qxd2 Rxb4 35. Rd3 Bxd3 36. Qxd3 Rb3
{ 0-1 Martin Gonzalez-Dolmatov, Barcelona 1983. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "10) French − Typical Structures and Ideas"]
[Black "The exchange sacrifice ...Rxf3"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1b2rk1/ppq3p1/2nbp2p/3p3n/3P3B/3B1N2/PPQ1NPPP/R4RK1 w - - 0 15"]
[SetUp "1"]

15. Bg6
{ Here is another very common exchange sacrifice in the French positions. This one, of course, occurred from the Tarrasch Variation @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/3PP3/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Nd2  Nf6  , which we do not analyze in the course. However, the idea is worth knowing about no matter what.    White played this move in order to make the black knight move either back to f6, or to f4, asking for a piece trade. But, the opponent didn't seem that willing to cooperate. }
15... Rxf3
{ 15...Nf4  16.Nxf4  Bxf4  17.Bg3  would play into White's hands. The e6-pawn is weak and the c8-bishop is passive, so White would have been happy to just trade off the pieces and liquidate any chances for dynamic counterplay, securing the positional advantage. }
16. gxf3 Bxh2+ 17. Kh1 Nf4
{ In return for the sacrificed exchange, Black had considerably weakened the opponent's pawn shelter, got a pawn, and a lot of active play. Next, Black can follow up with ...Bd7 and ...Rf8. The f3 and d4-pawns are now rather weak and White does not seem to have a lot of threats. So, Black has full compensation. This position is rather famous − it was reached in 117 games. Black scored extremely well. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "10) French − Typical Structures and Ideas"]
[Black "Why ...f7-f5 is often a bad idea"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1b1k2r/1p1nqppp/p1n1p3/3pP3/3P1P2/8/PP1Q2PP/R2NKBNR b KQkq - 0 11"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ In this example, we will see why playing ...f7-f5, locking up the kingside, is not a desirable idea. It will also remind us why the queen trade, although generally bad for White, who is looking to attack on the kingside, is sometimes good − mostly when White had already secured a large positional advantage and made it clear that Black won't be able to accomplish the queenside counterplay goals. }
11... Qb4
{ Black is looking to trade the queens. Why? Mostly, I think because if Black just castled kingside, we could try to set up a slow-developing kingside attack with moves like Bd3, Nf3, maybe Ng5, and so on, taking advantage of our tremendous spatial advantage. Black thinks that in the endgame would at least not run the risk of getting checkmated.   However, I think this endgame is going to be very unpleasant for Black, who will not enjoy any counterplay, especially with ...f7-f6, down the f-file. And what about our spatial advantage? As I point out in many places in this course, minor pieces are much more affected by lack of space than the queens, which is why trading them doesn't really help Black solve the problems related to the lack of space. }
12. Nf3 Qxd2+ 13. Kxd2
{ White doesn't need to do anything special and will just get the rest of the pieces out, for example, with moves like Nf2, Be2, Nd3, and Rac1. Then, White can play a2-a3 and b2-b4, looking to make progress on the queenside. One important thing to point out is that Black can go ...Nb6, looking to activate it by bringing it over to c4. However, we can easily prevent that idea and leave the knight restrained over there by playing b2-b3. }
13... f5
{ Black locks up the kingside. This move is more appropriate in the middlegame because it blocks the b1-h7 diagonal, which typically blunts White's light-squared bishop and prevents White from building a kingside attack. However, with no queens on the board, White was not going to do that anyway. Now, the e6-pawn is weak and requires constant attention, and the ...f7-f6 break is foregone forever. Not a good decision by the Black player! }
14. Nf2
{ Time for the white knight to get active. It would like to go to d3 and then c5. On c5, it will not only be placed nicely, but it would also be putting endless pressure on the e6-pawn. }
14... Nb6 { Black is trying to activate the knight. } 15. b3
{ No, thank you! Nice and simple! } 15... Ke7 16. Nd3 Bd7 17. Nc5
{ Now, the b7-pawn is under pressure, and it would be very difficult to ever remove the knight from c5. The e6-pawn is also a weakness. As you can see, Black has no counterplay related to ...f7-f6, the bishop on d7 is dead, and the e6-pawn requires constant babysitting.  Therefore, we can arrive at a conclusion that the plan with ...f7-f5 is often a bad one, as it results in fairly safe positions, where White cannot easily checkmate Black on the kingside, but very passive ones. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "10) French − Typical Structures and Ideas"]
[Black "Why ...c7-c5 is often bad in the Rubinstein"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1bqkb1r/ppp2ppp/4pn2/8/3P4/5NP1/PPP2P1P/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 0 7"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ This position is a theoretical one from the Rubinstein Variation of the French. In many lines, especially where the white bishop goes to, say, d3 or c4, it's a very natural idea for Black to go ...c7-c5 in order to get rid of our d4-pawn, which provides us with a considerable amount of space in the center. But, when we fianchetto the light-squared bishop, this typical good idea turns into a really bad one. }
7... c5
{ This is a perfect example of how easy it is to misplay this position with Black. Black challenges the d4-pawn but makes our light-squared bishop an absolute beast. }
8. Bg2 { White scored over 77% in this position! } 8... cxd4 9. Qxd4
{ This is an absolutely crucial idea to remember. In many variations of the @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/ppp2ppp/4pn2/8/3P4/5N2/PPP2PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7.g3  system, we desperately crave the queen trade. Why so? Because as a result, we get a very pleasant endgame  where our g2-bishop is exerting powerful pressure on their b7-pawn, and as a result, their queenside is absolutely stuck! Remember: no queens = a lot less counterplay. We are in control, we are dominating, so we dearly welcome that scenario! }
9... Qxd4 10. Nxd4
{ Black's queenside pieces are stuck. There is no telling how to develop the c8-bishop and the a8-rook, and we can develop even more pressure on the queenside with moves like Bf4, then Nb5, looking to jump to d6 or c7, O-O-O, and so on. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "11) Rubinstein French − Model Games"]
[Black "Wesley So − Darwin Yang, Montreal 2012"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ This game is a demonstration of how the young Wesley So  (at that time, already the world's top-100 player, but still a college student at Webster University)  slowly squeezed the opponent in a typical passive Rubinstein position. The main takeaway from this game? Just pay attention to the bishop on c8 and the rook on a8, and once you are done studying the game, those pieces would have hopefully told you a story! }
1... e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 dxe4
{ Black trades off the central pawns, hoping to avoid a position with the pawn chains and lack of space. }
4. Nxe4 Nd7
{ Black is planning on going ...Ngf6 next, looking to trade pieces in order to minimize the value of White's spatial advantage. }
5. g3
{ We typically play Nf3 first, and g2-g3 later, but of course, this move order also deserves attention. }
5... Ngf6 6. Nxf6+ Nxf6
{ Black's c8-bishop is a very passive piece, which is a typical situation in the French Defense. Black would like to activate it with ...b7-b6 and ...Bb7, solving that problem. Of course, Wesley So is interested in preventing that from happening! }
7. Bg2
{ White is playing in a pretty clever way, not developing the knight to f3 in order to keep the g2-bishop's diagonal open. This way, Black cannot ever go ...b7-b6 or ...Bb7, solving the problem of the c8-bishop. But, of course, this move order also comes at a cost, and there is a reason why we don't use it. }
7... c5
{ This move makes it impossible for Black to ever block the long diagonal with ...c7-c6, which considerably increases the potential of our bishop.   7...e5!  is the move I am concerned about. After  8.dxe5?!   8.Qe2!  8...Qxd4  9.Nf3  9...Qd5  10.Qxe5+  Qxe5+  11.Nxe5  Bd6  is objectively equal, although White still retains a bit of pressure.  8...Qxd1+  9.Kxd1  Ng4  ,  Black gets the pawn back and starts taking over since we needed to give up the castling rights. }
8. Nf3 cxd4
{ As we discussed in the theoretical chapter, it is not in Black's interests to open up the center and trade queens. This game will be a perfect example of why! }
9. Qxd4
{ We are very happy to offer a queen trade. Why so? Because in the endgame, Black will have no counterplay. The c8-bishop is stuck, and so is the rook on a8. On the other hand, our bishop on g2 is very powerful, and we have many ways of increasing pressure on the queenside with moves like Nb3-a5, or Nb5, Bf4/e3, and so on. Of course, we will also aggressively fight for the d-file with O-O-O or Rd1, as it is the only open file on the board. }
9... Qxd4 10. Nxd4 a6
{ With this move, Black prevents the knight from coming to b5. However, this move also weakens several squares, such as b6, while also wasting time. }
11. Bf4
{ White keeps developing. It would have also been sensible to place the bishop on e3, or even on b2. However, on f4, it serves a very important purpose. Namely, it takes the b8-square under control, preventing Black from solving the problem of developing the queenside pieces with ...Rb8 and ...Bd7.  If Black ever kicks this bishop out with ...Nd5, it can retreat to d2. In that case, you can argue that what I had just described above isn't happening. However, playing ...Nd5 isn't as simply good as it looks because that knight will be inevitably kicked out with c2-c4. That will enable us to win time, grab space, and the bishop would be able to return to f4 anytime later. }
11... Be7 12. O-O
{ I personally would be also attracted to the idea of castling queenside, immediately getting the rook on the only open d-file. And, of course, the king on c1 would be very useful, as it would be helping us control the d-file. Furthermore, it would be able to join the game very fast, for example via d2-d3-c4, once the pieces come off.   12.O-O-O  seems a lot more logical, getting the rook on the open d-file and placing our king in a spot, from where it could quickly get active. }
12... O-O 13. Rad1
{ White keeps placing pieces on good logical squares. Next, would like to play c2-c4, taking more space and taking the d5-square under control. As you can see, Black is still unable to develop the a8-rook and the c8-bishop without losing material. }
13... Rd8 14. c4
{ Nice and simple. As planned, the d5-square is under control. } 14... Kf8
{ Unable to do much, Black is trying to at least bring the king a bit closer to the center. }
15. Bc7
{ White starts somewhat deviating from the plan. I think it would have been better to keep the opponent stuck.   15.Ne2!  is the improvement I would like to suggest. The idea is to trade one of Black's very few active pieces − the rook on d8. The remaining queenside pieces, on the other hand, would be stuck. Furthermore, the knight can go to c3-a4-b6, putting more pressure on Black's queenside. And, of course, Black cannot free up the position with ...e6-e5 at any moment. }
15... Rd7 16. Bb6 e5
{ Now, Black manages to get some counterplay, the c8-bishop finally gets the hope of coming out. }
17. Nb3
{ The knight is ready to come to c5 or a5, putting more pressure on Black's queenside. }
17... Rxd1 18. Rxd1 e4
{ Black tries to block the g2-bishop, but this move weakens the d4 and f4-squares. }
19. Nc5 { The e4 and b7-pawns are both weak. } 19... Bf5 20. Rd4
{ 20.Nxb7??  Rb8!  would be a problem, as now two pieces would end up hanging. }
20... g6 21. b4
{ As the side variation with Nxe4 shows, White wasn't ready to win the e4-pawn yet. With this move, White is getting ready by removing the b2-pawn from a square where it would be loose. And, of course, is grabbing more space on the queenside. Given enough time, White would also love to play a2-a4-a5, increasing the spatial advantage even more, and restricting the opponent further.   21.Nxe4  Nxe4  22.Bxe4  seems to be winning a pawn, but it's not that simple, as Black has  22...Bf6∞  attacking the rook, which is protecting the e4-bishop. So, things are still complicated! }
21... Re8 22. a4 { The space grab must go on! } 22... Bxc5
{ Black figures no more pressure on the b7-pawn is tolerated and gives up the bishop pair. However, alongside the weak dark squares and the impressive queenside majority, as well as White's control of the d-file, it seems as though the bishop pair makes our advantage decisive. }
23. Bxc5+ Kg8 24. Bd6
{ White is looking to reroute the bishop to f4, and then maybe g5, trying to start bothering the knight, which is guarding the e4-pawn, and the d5 and d7-squares. The latter is rather valuable, as we'd like to use it for our rook, eventually, to invade on the 7th rank.   24.a5  looks like an even better move, completely restricting Black's queenside first. }
24... Nd7 25. h3
{ Time to expand on the kingside as well! We'd love to go g3-g4 next, kicking out the bishop and winning the e4-pawn. Not only would we win a pawn, which is a great thing overall, but we would also tremendously activate the light-squared bishop, which is currently rather restricted by the e4-pawn. }
25... h5 { Black needs to try to prevent that. } 26. g4
{ With this pawn trade, we are finally bringing that beast on g2 to life. }
26... hxg4 27. hxg4 Bxg4 28. Bxe4
{ The b7-pawn is hanging. But actually, the bishop on g4 is also loose, which means we have threats like Bxg6, winning a pawn due to the discovered attack on that bishop. }
28... b6 29. Bb7
{ Now, we have a double attack on the bishop on g4 and the pawn on a6. } 29...
Re1+ 30. Kg2 Bd1
{ Black tries the last trick, hoping White would just trade the a-pawns. However, White has something much better! }
31. b5
{ To force the win, White is using a very cute tactical trick.   31.Bxa6  Bxa4  should still be a winning position, but converting it would certainly take more time and effort. }
31... a5
{ Black blocks the queenside, preventing the Bb4 tactic.   31...axb5??  32.Bb4!  is the point, double attacking the rook on e1 and the knight on d7! }
32. Bc6
{ We'd love to finally break through on the queenside with c4-c5, but the knight on d7 is stopping that. So, we need to kick it away! }
32... Nf6 33. c5
{ Black resigned since after the trade, our b-pawn is queening no matter what. This is a wonderful showcase of how dangerous it can be to end up stuck with the bishop on c8 and the rook on a8 unable to come out. That's why Black needs to be very quick to solve the problem of the queenside pieces in these positions. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "11) Rubinstein French − Model Games"]
[Black "Frode Olav Olsen Urkedal − Benjamin Arvola, Fagernes 2020"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
{ This time, White started with 1.d4, but soon, the game transposed back to the French. }
1... e6 2. e4 d5 3. Nc3 dxe4
{ Again, the solid but passive Rubinstein system. } 4. Nxe4 Nd7 5. g3
{ Just like in that game of Wesley So, White delays the move Nf3 in order to keep the h1-a8 diagonal open for as long as possible. }
5... Ngf6 6. Nxf6+ Nxf6 7. Bg2 c5
{ Black makes the same mistake just like in Wesley So's game. Black is opening up the h1-a8 diagonal, making the g2-bishop much more powerful.   7...e5!  Again, Black needs to urgently solve the problem with the c8-bishop by opening the h3-c8 diagonal, or by getting it out to the h1-a8 diagonal. The latter isn't possible, so the former should be tried! }
8. Nf3 Be7 9. O-O
{ White is getting ready to take on c5. The key was to castle first so that if Black trades the queens, we can take back with our rook.   9.dxc5?  We aren't ready to do this yet, as after  9...Qxd1+  ,  we lose castling rights and our king ends up stuck in a weird position. }
9... O-O
{ As we had seen in the previous example, trading doesn't help Black either, as after  9...cxd4  10.Qxd4  Qxd4  11.Nxd4±  ,  the queenside pieces are stuck. Next, we go c2-c4, taking away the d5-square from the black knight, then Bf4, Rfd1, at some point Nb5-d6, and develop a tremendously strong initiative on the queenside. }
10. a4
{ An interesting idea. Instead of releasing the tension, White is waiting for the opponent to do that. What's the idea of this move? If allowed, White is going to play a4-a5, and maybe even a5-a6, advancing the pawn all the way up to put pressure on the b7-pawn and down the long diagonal. On the other hand, if Black ever responds with ...a7-a5, then the b5-square becomes weak, and the white knight will gladly take advantage of that with Nd4-b5.   10.dxc5  seems like a more logical continuation to me. We are hoping Black would trade the queens, giving us the favorable endgame we are discussing in detail in the theoretical chapter, and in these model games. Instead, after  10...Bxc5  11.Qe2!  ,  we discourage any ...e6-e5 ideas, which could help Black free up the light-squared bishop and occupy space in the center. Next, we will install our knight on a dominant position on e5 and follow up with c2-c4, grabbing more space in the center and taking the d5-square away from the knight. }
10... cxd4
{ Black decides to release the tension, after all, not finding anything better to do.   10...Bd7  would not have solved any problems, and that is for a few reasons. We could choose between two very strong continuations.  11.Ne5!  We attack the b7-pawn and are about to get the bishop pair.   11.dxc5  Bxc5  12.Ne5  also looks very strong. The point is that the bishop on c5 is a bit misplaced, as it could run into moves like Nd3, or b2-b4. Also, we can play Bg5 next, creating a very annoying pin, since the black bishop is no longer on e7.  11...Qc7  12.Nxd7  Nxd7  13.Bf4±  ,  we have the bishop pair and a strong initiative. Next, we can choose between taking on c5, opening up the center, and getting a queenside majority, or d4-d5, also opening the position up but keeping the pawn structure symmetrical. }
11. Qxd4 Qxd4 12. Nxd4 { Again, Black got to this very unpleasant endgame. }
12... e5
{ At least, Black gets to make this freeing up, which allows the activation of the bishop on c8 and grabs space. However, the position is still by no means a piece of cake, as there is still strong pressure on the h1-a8 diagonal. }
13. Re1
{ Instead of moving the knight away, White is capitalizing on the pin down the e-file, putting pressure on the e5-pawn.   13.Nb5  is also very strong, of course. The knight is putting pressure on the a7-pawn. If Black ever kicks it out, ideas like Nc7, followed maybe by Bg5 and Nd5 at some point, taking advantage of the fact that the d5-square has gotten weakened by the move ...e6-e5, become very tempting. But if not, we can always consider playing Rd1 and Nd6, placing the knight on a wonderful square, where it would be putting pressure on the b7 and f7-pawns. }
13... Ng4
{ Black sort of has to defend the pawn in this awkward manner. It's awkward because the knight is by no means stable here, it can be always kicked out with h2-h3.   13...Bd6  doesn't fix any problems either. Sure enough, the bishop defends the pawn but ends up in a very loose position.  14.Nb5!  The bishop needs to keep protecting the e5-pawn, so it ends up in a very ugly spot.  14...Bb8  15.Be3±  and Black's queenside is absolutely stuck. }
14. Nb3
{ Here, the knight might seem to be placed somewhat awkwardly. However, that's not exactly true because it does several important things.  It prevents the black bishop from coming to c5, putting pressure on the f2-pawn. It can always go to a5 to put pressure on the b7-pawn. In the future, after we kick out the knight with h2-h3 and play Be3, the bishop or the knight can invade on c5. }
14... Bd6
{ Black was about to lose the e5-pawn after h2-h3, so the pawn gets protected by the bishop. }
15. h3 { Time to get rid of that annoying knight. } 15... Nf6 16. Na5
{ White is choosing to immediately put pressure on the b7-pawn.   16.Be3  is also looked very logical. This move allows us to prepare Bc5 or Nc5 on the next turn. And, it does one more thing, which is not as obvious, but very important. Black's bishop on c8 is stuck. How to unravel the kingside?  You need to play ...Rb8, protecting the b7-pawn, then develop the bishop and play ...b7-b6. If Black could do that, all the problems would be solved. So, the move Be3 is a very important prophylactic decision, which prevents that plan by attacking the a7-pawn. It's not obvious to me what Black should be doing here! }
16... e4
{ With this move, Black sort of takes care of the threats to the e5-pawn, which was about to be lost after Nc4. Very importantly, Black also blocks the g2-bishop, preparing to go ...b7-b6 and get the light-squared bishop out.   16...Bb4  double attacks the rook and the knight, but that's not a problem.  17.Rxe5+-  and White wins the pawn, keeping everything under control. }
17. Nc4
{ The knight did its job on a5, now it is moving back. The idea is to take the squares on d6 and e5 under control and see where the bishop will go. For example, if it goes to c5, we can always play c2-c3 and b2-b4, seizing more space on the queenside, while also winning time. Additionally, we could play b2-b3 and Bb2, developing the bishop to the powerful long diagonal. Not only would it be placed very well there, but also, at some point we could capture the knight on f6, which is currently defending the e4-pawn, and win the e4-pawn.   17.Bxe4?  It would be wrong to capture this pawn, even if it was free because our light-squared bishop has so much promise! So, I'd rather not get it traded off. Plus, the h3-pawn would end up hanging at the end. However, an even bigger problem is that Black gets to take advantage of the pin on the e-file with  17...Re8  18.f3  Bb4-+  and White is losing a decisive amount of material. }
17... Rd8 18. Rd1
{ White is looking to trade Black's only developed rook, which is a good idea because Black's remaining pieces would be stuck.   18.Nxd6  ,  it is rather surprising for me that White didn't want to take the bishop pair!  18...Rxd6  19.Bg5  and White has a few large threats: to take on f6 and then win the e4-pawn, or simply trade off the rooks with Rd1 on the next turn and occupy the d-file. }
18... Be7 19. Rxd8+ Bxd8 20. Nd6
{ Having distracted the black bishop, White is able to attack the weak e4-pawn with one more piece and finally win it. This is an example of what happens when you advance the pawns far without offering them piece support. }
20... Bb6 21. a5
{ Before capturing the pawn, White grabs even more space on the queenside. At some point, especially when the g2-bishop is open, the a5-a6! idea would become very powerful. }
21... Bc5 22. Nxe4 Nxe4 23. Bxe4
{ We are threatening with that annoying move a5-a6, and Black needs to stop that. }
23... a6 24. Kg2
{ We are overprotecting the h3-pawn. Black could not afford to take it anyway since the b7-pawn would end up hanging. But, it doesn't hurt to defend it. Next, we'd love to develop the dark-squared bishop and play Rd1, starting to threaten to occupy the d-file. Black would need to either resign, as the rook and bishop cannot move  (you cannot successfully defend with one piece versus three!)  , or start giving up more material. }
24... Bd7
{ Black decides to throw in more material, which is a logical but desperate thing to do. }
25. Bxb7 Re8 26. Be3
{ White is happy to return one pawn  (or at least pretend to do so!)  to trade down. Crucially, Black's pawn on a6 is hanging, so it's not a real pawn sacrifice. }
26... Bxe3 27. fxe3 Bb5
{ Black needs to protect the a6-pawn, but now White consolidates the position.   27...Rxe3  28.Bxa6+-  is completely winning, of course. White will just move the bishop back and promote the a-pawn. }
28. e4
{ White solves the problem of the hanging e3-pawn in the easiest way possible, while also creating an outpost on d5 for the bishop. Next, White can play Bd5 and c2-c4!, supporting the advance of the queenside pawns. }
28... f5 29. Bd5+ Kf8 30. c4 { Finally, the pawns start moving forward. } 30...
Bd7 31. Rf1 { The f-pawn is pinned, so Black is losing even more material. }
31... Rb8 32. Rf2 Rb4 33. exf5
{ Time to win another pawn! In a few moves, Black had to resign due to three pawns down and no counterplay. }
