[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "11) Rubinstein French − Model Games"]
[Black "Ian Nepomniachtchi − Georg Meier, Hersonissos 2017"]
[Result "*"]

{ In this game, we will see how the most famous Rubinstein Variation proponent  (GM Georg Meier)  gets outplayed in our favorite variation with the fianchetto. }
1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 dxe4 4. Nxe4 Nd7 5. Nf3
{ 5.g3  is the move order we had seen in the past few model games, but it's not the one I recommend, as after  5...Ngf6  6.Nxf6+  Nxf6  7.Bg2  e5!  Black equalizes. Of course, such a strong and knowledgeable player as Meier would know that, so Nepo plays the more principled line. }
5... Ngf6 6. Nxf6+ Nxf6 7. g3 b6
{ Of course, Meier chooses the best setup available to Black: the bishop is going to the long diagonal. }
8. Bb5+
{ White tries to stop that, making the opponent respond in an inconvenient way. }
8... Bd7
{ 8...Nd7??  not only is very awkward but also, leads to a lost position right away.  9.Ne5+-  .  Black cannot develop the light-squared bishop, and we create a few very powerful tactical threats:   Qf3, double-attacking the rook on a8 and the f7-pawn; Nxf7 followed by Qf3+, forking the king on f7 and the rook on a8; If Black ever goes ...Be7, after Nc6!, the queen gets trapped. }
9. a4
{ As I explain in the theoretical chapter, this is a very valuable move. If Black trades the bishops, then after axb5, we create an outpost on c6, that we can use with Ne5-c6. Furthermore, the a-file opens up and the pawn on a7 becomes very weak. Otherwise, Black cannot go ...Bc6, activating the bishop. So, Black needs to chase our bishop away. }
9... a6 10. Be2
{ The downside of forcing the move ...a7-a6 is that now that pawn is weak. It would require constant babysitting. Or, if Black goes ...a6-a5, that wastes another tempo, and again weakens the b5-square. }
10... Bc6 11. O-O
{ Having unpinned the knight on f3 by castling  (the rook on h1 is no longer hanging)  , we are ready to jump on e5 with the knight. }
11... Be7
{ Black develops in a more conservative way, avoiding the popular endgame variation.   11...Bd6  is another major variation, where Black gives up the bishop pair, hoping to build an unbreakable fortress in the endgame.  12.Ne5  12...Bxe5  13.dxe5  Qd5  14.Qxd5  Nxd5  .  This endgame offers Black good chances to hold the game, and very pleasant, risk-free chances to win for us. We analyze it in another model game of this chapter. }
12. Ne5
{ However, now, White is able to make this enjoyable move, activating the knight and pushing the opponent's bishop away. The c6-square is weak, so soon White will try to trade the light-squared bishops and invade on c6. }
12... Bb7 13. c4
{ Before trading the light-squared bishops, White is trying to occupy even more space in the center, taking the d5-square. }
13... Nd7
{ Black is immediately challenging this annoying centralized knight, not letting the opponent have enough time to trade the light-squared bishops with Bf3 and install the knight on c6.   13...O-O  14.Bf3!  seems to lead to serious positional problems for Black. For instance, after  14...Bxf3  ,  we can even consider a pawn sacrifice!  15.Qxf3!  Qxd4  16.Nc6!  The black queen and bishop are forked.  16...Qd7  17.Rd1!  White keeps winning more and more time.  17...Bd6  18.Bg5!  Black is dominated and hardly has any moves at all! For instance, after  18...Ne8!!  19.Be7+-  ,  we win an exchange and the game. }
14. Bf3
{ We are trying to fight for the c6-square anyway. Now, a few trades will happen, but the pawn structure is also about to change, which would give White a considerable amount of extra space on the kingside. }
14... Bxf3 15. Qxf3
{ Black is facing two large threats: Nc6, installing the knight on the dominating square and forcing the queen to go in the middle of nowhere, and Qxf7, with checkmate. So, Black needs to trade. }
15... Nxe5 16. dxe5
{ The pawn on e5 is very helpful. Why so? It takes the d6 and f6-squares away from Black. The one on f6 is especially valuable because we can try to start a kingside attack with Rd1-d4-g4, Qh5, Bh6, and so on, and it's great that Black cannot bring the defender in. }
16... O-O 17. Rd1 Qe8
{ As you can see, although Black is by no means losing, the pieces are incredibly passive. }
18. Be3
{ White can consider bringing the rook on d4-g4, or even invading on the queenside with moves like Qb7!, trying to pinpoint the fact that the c7 and a6-pawns are a bit loose. }
18... Bb4 19. h4
{ Time to start making progress on the kingside! The idea is to play h4-h5 and h5-h6, making Black considerably weaken the kingside pawn structure. }
19... h6 20. Rd4 { The rook is finally joining the attack. } 20... Bc5 21. Rg4
{ White is already creating numerous threats, such as Bxh6, winning a pawn and destroying the opponent's king, and Bxc5, spoiling the pawn structure on the queenside. }
21... Bxe3
{ By trading the bishops, Black eliminates both threats, but still, the position remains very passive. }
22. Qxe3 { Now, of course, we are threatening to win the h6-pawn. } 22... Kh8
23. c5
{ And now, White is looking to make progress on the queenside, trying to ruin the opponent's pawn structure! }
23... Qc6
{ I am not sure about this defense.  23...b5  would have likely been the better way of defending. But, Black's position still looks very suspicious. For instance, we can go  24.Rd4  ,  returning the rook in the game, and looking to play b2-b4, and maybe a4-a5, grabbing even more space on the queenside. Then, we can double the rooks on the only open d-file, and try to invade on d7.  Black can trade down a bit more, but that does not seem to be fully resolving the problems.  24...Rd8  25.Rxd8  Qxd8  26.axb5  axb5  27.Ra7  and although Black should be definitely able to survive, White is certainly still pressing. }
24. cxb6 Qxb6
{ 24...cxb6  keeps the pawn structure intact, but White gets a strong initiative on the c-file.  25.Rc1  Qb7  26.Rd4⩲  .  The d-rook is about to invade on d6. Our queen can join by coming to b3 to attack the b6-pawn, or to d3 to help us dominate the d-file. }
25. Qc3
{ Now, Black has the rather weak pawn structure on the queenside. The a6 and the c7-pawns are going to be a problem! }
25... Rfd8 26. Rc4 { Time to attack the c7-pawn! } 26... Rd7 27. Rc1
{ More trouble coming Black's way! } 27... Rb8
{ Black tries counterattacking the b2-pawn first, but that's an easy problem to solve.   27...Rc8?  would defend the pawn, but all of Black's pieces would be tied put and in extremely passive positions.  28.Rb4  Qa7  29.Qc6±  and Black literally doesn't have a single move! }
28. b4
{ I have decided to cut off the rest of the game, because it lasted more than 80 moves, and the rook endgames, although extremely interesting, aren't a part of this course. :@@EndBracket@@ But, I think it's obvious by now, how unpleasant Black's position has been the entire time! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "11) Rubinstein French − Model Games"]
[Black "S. Rohit − Bhattacherjee Aayush, Budapest 2021"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ In this game, we will see a wonderful show case of how White converted the bishop pair in the line that is supposedly Black's most solid and reputable defense against our setup. }
1... e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 dxe4
{ Black chooses the solid but passive Rubinstein system, opening the center and hoping to trade down. }
4. Nxe4 Nd7 5. Nf3
{ This time, unlike in the previous games, White immediately develops the knight, which is what I suggest in our theoretical section.   5.g3  is the line we have seen in the previous model games. The upside of this variation is that we are going to keep the light-squared bishop open and active, preventing Black from activating the c8-bishop. However, the downside is that Black is able to play ...e6-e5, activating the bishop that way.  5...Ngf6  6.Nxf6+  Nxf6  7.Bg2  e5!  This is the problem with this move order, just as I explain in the previous examples. }
5... Ngf6 6. Nxf6+ Nxf6 7. g3 b6
{ This time, Black chooses the most solid and reliable defense. Knowing that if White's bishop gets to the long diagonal, life will be hard, Black is immediately trying to improve the worst piece − the light-squared bishop. }
8. Bb5+
{ I hope you remember this idea from the theoretical part − we are looking to make the black bishop go to the awkward square on d7. }
8... Bd7 9. a4
{ If Black wants to capture on b5, is very welcome to do so. Doing that would create a weak pawn on a7 and an outpost on c6 that our knight would love to go to. So, Black cannot do that. }
9... a6
{ Black makes our bishop leave. However, the last move has a downside. It's not a very obvious one, but an important one. Namely, now the a6-pawn becomes a bit of a liability! Black needs to either keep a rook on a8 to protect it or go ...a6-a5 at some point, wasting a tempo and weakening the b5-square!   After  9...Bxb5?  10.axb5  ,  the c6-square is an outpost, and we are about to play Ne5-c6, installing the knight on a wonderful position. Also, the a7-pawn is weak for the rest of the game, which makes it difficult, if not impossible, to move the a8-rook away. }
10. Be2
{ We are about to play Ne5, preventing Black from ever going ...Bc6 and activating the bishop. }
10... Bc6
{ So, Black needs to activate the bishop right away. Unfortunately, the knight is pinned, so we cannot go Ne5 yet. }
11. O-O { We unpin it, preparing to go Ne5 on the next turn. } 11... Bd6 12.
Ne5
{ Black could retreat, which is another major theoretical move that we discuss in detail in the theoretical chapter. But, the most solid theoretical path, suggested in notable sources, such as Vitiugov's book, and Langrock's book, is trading the queens. That's exactly what Black does in this game! }
12... Bxe5 13. dxe5 Qd5
{ Black gives up the bishop, but forces a queen trade by threatening checkmate, while also attacking the e5-pawn at the same time. }
14. Qxd5 Nxd5
{ Black is hoping this position would turn out very solid and unbreakable. Sure enough, we have the bishop pair, but the position is currently rather closed. The knight on d5 is also blocking the d-file and the diagonals. If we kick it out with c2-c4, it would go to b4, and that square would be another outpost. }
15. a5
{ First, we are grabbing more space on the queenside, threatening to trade on b6 and open up the position. Black needs to do something about that. }
15... b5
{ Black manages to keep the position closed. However, the dark squares, such as c5, are becoming much weaker. Furthermore, now the b5 and a6-pawns are now fixed on the light squares. For example, if we ever manage to play c2-c4, our light-squared bishop would suddenly start attacking the weak a6-pawn. }
16. Bd2 O-O-O
{ Black connects the rooks, keeping the king close to the weak a6-pawn, and controlling the d-file. }
17. Rfd1
{ In this position, we have a few very simple goals. As usual, the side with the bishop pair, in this case, White, wants to trade all the rooks. Once that happens, there will be no counterplay @@StartBracket@@ever!@@EndBracket@@ and we would be able to slowly start grabbing space on both parts of the board. Also, we want to start activating the king. }
17... Rd7 18. f3
{ The king is coming over to f2, to begin with. Then, hopefully, further! }
18... Rhd8 19. Kf2 Ne7 20. Bb4
{ With this move, we are forcing trades of all rooks. } 20... Rxd1 21. Rxd1
Rxd1 22. Bxd1
{ Now, Black has a difficult decision to make: either move the knight, allowing the wolf in the shipyard, or approve the trade on e7. But hold on, why would we give up the bishop pair, going for the endgame with light-squared bishops only? The problem is that Black had played ...b6-b5, weakening the dark squares and placing all the pawns on the light ones! As a result, our king can invade on c5, and all the pawns will be easy targets for our bishop. }
22... Kd7
{ Black's position would have been difficult no matter what, but the trade should have been avoided.   22...Nf5  ,  like it or not, Black had to keep the knight alive.  23.g4  ,  the knight is being kicked out to some really awkward square.  23...Nh4  24.Bf8!  Black starts losing material. Or at least gets very close to that! For instance, after  24...g5  25.Be7  Ng6  ,  Black manages to get our e5-pawn, but this trade is by no means favorable.  26.Bxg5  Nxe5  27.Bf6±  .  With the board opening up considerably, the bishops are becoming more and more powerful. Soon, we'll go c2-c3 and Bc2, including our other bishop into the hunt on the kingside pawns, and Black is falling apart. }
23. Bxe7 Kxe7 24. Ke3
{ The king is ready to invade on d4 and c5! Please observe how our e5-pawn is restricting not only the kingside pawns but also the king, preventing it from going to d6! }
24... Kd7 25. Kd4 Kc8 26. Be2
{ White also activates the bishop, potentially looking to play c2-c4 at some point, or Bd3, starting to attack Black's kingside pawns. First, of course, White will make sure to remove the f3-pawn from a square where it could be hanging. }
26... Kb7 27. f4
{ This move, as I had explained above, makes sure the pawn won't ever hang. White is ready to install the king on c5, maybe at some point blow up Black's queenside pawns with c2-c4, looking to get to that weakness on a6, and, of course, slowly grab space on the kingside with h2-h4, g3-g4-g5, and so on. Black cannot do anything about any of these ideas, so the position is dead lost. }
27... g6
{ It's not obvious why Black made this move, as it weakens the dark squares even more. And creates even more targets! At least, Black should have tried to hold with ...h7-h6, placing pawns on squares where our bishop couldn't attack them. Black would have been lost anyway, but this move makes things even worse. }
28. Kc5 Be4 29. c4
{ Finally, it's time to break through and expose the weak pawn on a6. } 29...
bxc4
{ 29...c6?  leads to a disaster, as it allows the white king to infiltrate.  30.Kd6+-  and the king would inevitably come to e7 and scoop up all the kingside pawns. }
30. Bxc4
{ Now, White has many ways to win. But the easiest plan is to go b2-b4-b5, get an outside passed pawn, run it, distract the black king, and then invade on the kingside with our king, or with our bishop − say, via b5-e8. }
30... Bf3 31. Bb3
{ Instead, White takes the time and waits. We could go Ba4-e8 next, attacking the kingside pawns!   31.b4!  seems like the easiest plan to me, looking to push b4-b5 and execute the aforementioned plan. }
31... Bc6 { So, Black prevents that threat. } 32. Bc2
{ On top of the other problems, Black is sort of in zugzwang. If the bishop leaves the a4-e8 diagonal, our bishop would go to a4 and then e8! But if the bishop goes to, say, b5, then we can give a check from e4, forcing the king away! Of course, Black can make a few moves with the kingside pawns, but that would only weaken the position further. }
32... Bd5 33. Ba4
{ Finally, the bishop gets in! Now, decisive material gains are right around the corner. }
33... Kc8 { 33...c6?  34.Kd6  isn't helping Black, of course. } 34. h4
{ 34.Be8  would also win on the spot, of course. But, White chooses not to hurry, for some reason. }
34... Kd8 35. Bc6
{ Black managed to cover the e8-square, but now, the invasion happens from the other side. The a6-pawn is very weak. }
35... Bb3
{ 35...Bxc6  36.Kxc6  is, of course, an entirely lost pawn endgame.  36...Kc8  and Black is able to prevent our king from invading, for now. But, such endgames get lost because of zugzwang. We just need to make the opponent run out of the pawn moves!  37.g4  h6  38.b3+-  .  Time for the black king to move, and ours invades decisively to b7 or d7. }
36. Bb7 { And now it falls. } 36... Bc2 37. Bxa6 Be4 38. Bb5 Ba8 39. Bc6
{ Black resigned since not only is our a-pawn queening, but we are also forcing a completely winning pawn endgame. As you can see, even though Black swapped the queens very soon, reaching a supposedly solid position, it was by no means easy to play it. Black never managed to make a single active move in the entire game. And, once White was allowed to trade off the bishop pair, going for the same-colored bishop endgame, Black was completely lost all of a sudden! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "12) Classical French − Model Games"]
[Black "Ernesto Inarkiev − Alexander Riazantsev, Krasnoyarsk 2003"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ In this game, Inarkiev  (a future 2700+ super-GM)  went on to win another future super-GM in our variation of the Classical French. Black created weak squares on e5 and d4, and White skillfully took advantage of that. Let's see how! }
1... e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Nf6
{ The Classical Variation. Black keeps the tension, hoping that White would lock the position up with e4-e5. In that case, Black gets the standard French theme − a position with pawn chains, which most, if not all, French players absolutely adore. }
4. Bg5
{ But, as we discussed in the theoretical chapter, we keep the tension for now. The f6-knight is pinned, so Black has to worry about e4-e5 coming up, taking advantage of that pin. }
4... Be7 { Black unpins the knight, continuing to develop. } 5. e5
{ We grab space, locking the center up. } 5... Nfd7 6. Bxe7
{ As I explain in the theoretical chapter, this trade is not necessarily the most trivial one. White exchanges the supposedly 'bad' bishop, which was restricted by the pawn chain. That's a good piece of news, of course. But, there is also a bad one. Namely, the problem is that we have more space, so trading pieces is not very beneficial in that regard, as when the pieces come off the board, the value of our spatial advantage vanishes. }
6... Qxe7 7. f4
{ This is a very important idea that you absolutely need to remember − and, even more importantly, understand! Why do we need it? You see, in the French positions, White typically grabs a lot of space in the center. But when that happens, the pawns become vulnerable to the pawn breaks − ...c7-c5 and ...f7-f6. We cannot defend the d4-pawn with c2-c3 since our knight is on that square. So, we need to make sure that when Black goes ...c7-c5 and trades on d4, our e5-pawn stays well-protected!   7.Nf3  isn't as good, since after  7...c5  ,  not the d4-pawn, but the one on e5 is in danger: Black wants to take on d4 and then start attacking the e5-pawn! }
7... O-O 8. Nf3 c5
{ Black tries undermining the center, but White isn't particularly worried about that. }
9. dxc5
{ We could have waited until Black takes on d4, but there is no need for that. }
9... Nc6 10. Qd2 { White is getting ready to castle queenside. } 10... Nxc5 11.
O-O-O f6
{ Black tries undermining the central pawn, opening up the f-file for the rook. That's totally okay with us! }
12. exf6 Qxf6 13. g3
{ The f4-pawn is hanging, but it's not difficult to protect it. Now, the e5-square is an outpost White can use for the knight or even a rook in the future. And, of course, the pawn on e6 is now a clear weakness. It might not be easy to win it yet, but we are certainly going to enjoy putting a lot of pressure on it, always keeping the opponent restrained. }
13... Rd8
{ Black is trying to activate the rook. Potentially, at some point, will be able to play ...Ne4, which would be an awkward thing for us to deal with since we won't be able to take it. }
14. Qe1
{ White prevents the aforementioned positional threat of ...Ne4 by taking that square under better control, while also removing the queen from its sketchy position on the d-file, and taking the e5-square under control as well.   14.h3?  If we were to make a random move, suddenly  14...Ne4!  is a problem. Now, we need to allow the opponent to trade the knights on c3, which would ruin our pawn structure because  15.Nxe4??  dxe4-+  loses, as it's a double attack on the queen and the f3-knight.   14.Qe3??  would be a great square for the queen, but this move doesn't work for tactical reasons, as we lose a piece due to  14...d4! }
14... Bd7 15. Qe3
{ Now that the d-file is blocked and ...d5-d4 is no longer possible, White is happy to activate the queen further, attacking the knight. }
15... b6 16. Bg2
{ White is about to play Rhe1 and Nd4, looking to trade a pair of pieces and put pressure on the e6-pawn. }
16... Be8 17. Nd4
{ Time to trade the knights! This trade helps us weaken the e5-square and decrease the number of pieces on the board, which helps kill any possible counterplay. }
17... Nxd4 18. Rxd4
{ Next, we are going to play Rhe1 and Qe5, offering a queen trade as well. }
18... Rac8 19. Re1 b5
{ Black tries to get some activity on the queenside with ...b5-b4. We need to be very careful because there is already a tactical threat! }
20. Bh3
{ A very interesting move, which puts pressure on the e6-pawn and prepares for the creation of material imbalance.   20.h3?!  b4  21.Rxb4??  d4!  wins Black a piece! }
20... b4 { Black needs to play in a principled way! } 21. Nxd5
{ White is initiating a tactical sequence, which results in trades and material gains. }
21... exd5 22. Bxc8 Rxc8 23. Rxd5
{ Now, White has a rook and two pawns for two minor pieces. But more importantly, Black's king is vulnerable, which allows us to either attack it or force a queen trade, which means the white king won't ever run into any problems on the c-file. }
23... Na4 24. Qd4
{ With this lovely move, White prevents the threats to the b2-pawn and offers a queen trade. Of course, is also attacking the b4-pawn, and is potentially preparing Rd8, creating threats on the 8th rank.   24.Qe6+??  would be a move with a great idea, but awful execution.  24...Qxe6  25.Rxe6  Bf7∓  and our rooks end up forked. }
24... Qc6
{ Of course, Black is desperate to keep the queens on the board in order to have at least some counterplay.   24...Qxd4  25.Rxd4  results in a completely lost endgame for Black because on an open board, the rook and pawns are way stronger than the minor pieces. Plus, Black is about to lose the queenside pawns.  25...a5  26.Re5  Nc5??  27.Rc4+-  and everything collapses! }
25. Qd2
{ White is preventing counterplay against the c2-pawn, preparing to play, for example, Rde5, attacking the bishop, and offering to trade the queens with Qd5+. }
25... Qf6 26. Qxb4
{ White is slowly but surely collecting more and more harvest! } 26... Qc6 27.
Qd2 { The c2-pawn is safe and sound! } 27... Qb6 28. Qd4
{ White keeps insisting on the trade. } 28... Qc7
{ And now, of course, a move like c2-c3 would do the job of covering the king up. But, I want you to find an instant win for White! Look at all the forcing moves. }
29. Rxe8+ Rxe8 30. Rd7
{ Black is losing right away since we are threatening the queen and checkmate on g7! }
30... Re1+ 31. Kd2 { No worries. One check doesn't do anyone any harm. } 31...
Re2+ 32. Kxe2 Qxc2+ 33. Kf3
{ The king will easily hide from checks, but Black cannot stop the mating threats like Qd5+, Rd8+, and so on. If Black goes ...Qc6+, we can either hide from checks or trade queens with Qd5+ and get a completely winning endgame. So, Black resigned! This game shows us the power of long-lasting pressure on the weak e6-pawn and the power of the outposts on d4 and e5. And, of course, the creative use of material imbalance! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "12) Classical French − Model Games"]
[Black "Dejan Stojanovski − Ljupco Radicevski, Skopje 2009"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ This game is a showcase of how to use large spatial advantage in the endgames, which arise from the French Defense positions. }
1... e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Nf6
{ The Classical Variation. Black keeps the tension, hoping that White would lock the position up with e4-e5. In that case, Black gets the standard French theme − a position with pawn chains, which most, if not all, French players absolutely adore. }
4. Bg5
{ But, as we discussed in the theoretical chapter, we keep the tension for now. The f6-knight is pinned, so Black has to worry about e4-e5 coming up, taking advantage of that pin. }
4... Be7 { Black unpins the knight, continuing to develop. } 5. e5
{ We grab space, locking the center up. } 5... Nfd7 6. Bxe7
{ As I explain in the theoretical chapter, this trade is not necessarily the most trivial one. White exchanges the supposedly 'bad' bishop, which was restricted by the pawn chain. That's a good piece of news, of course. But, there is also a bad one. Namely, the problem is that we have more space, so trading pieces is not very beneficial in that regard, as when the pieces come off the board, the value of our spatial advantage vanishes. }
6... Qxe7 7. Qd2
{ We are continuing natural development. It might seem as though White is only interested in castling queenside next, but actually, there is one more very cool idea coming up. As you hopefully remember, a typical fear of any White player, while facing the French, is that their big beautiful center will get destroyed with ...c7-c5 or ...f7-f6. We are able to meet the latter with f2-f4, but what about the former?  For now, as we'll see, Black is unable to play this move. But in the future, Black will! That's why our mini-plan is to go Nd1!, rerouting the knight to e3, where it is likely to prove useful in the upcoming kingside play, while also preparing to meet ...c7-c5 with c2-c3! Even in the opening, it's crucial to think of prophylaxis. }
7... a6
{ Black covers up the b5-square. That is done in order to prepare ...c7-c5, undermining White's center, without allowing the annoying Nb5-d6 jump. }
8. Nd1
{ Just on time! Black was ready to play ...c7-c5 and blow up our center, so it's very important that we can meet that move with c2-c3.   8.Nf3?  would be an ignorant move, which would allow Black to ruin our center.  8...c5!  And once the d4-pawn disappears, the one on e5 would become very difficult to defend! }
8... c5 9. c3 { The center is safe and sound, just as planned. } 9... Nc6 10.
f4
{ White is getting ready to develop with Nf3, Be2/d3, and so on. It was definitely very valuable and beneficial to insert the move f2-f4, as it helps us reinforce the e5-pawn. }
10... cxd4 11. cxd4 Qb4
{ Black is looking to trade the queens. Why is that? Mostly, I think because if Black just castled kingside, we could try to set up a slow-developing kingside attack with moves like Bd3, Nf3, maybe Ng5, and so on, taking advantage of our tremendous spatial advantage. Black thinks that in the endgame, the risk of getting checkmated is eliminated.  However, I think this endgame is going to be very unpleasant for Black, in the absence of any counterplay, especially without ...f7-f6, down the f-file. And what about our spatial advantage? As I point out in many places in this course, minor pieces are much more affected by lack of space than the queens, which is why trading them doesn't really help Black solve the problems related to the lack of space. }
12. Nf3 Qxd2+ 13. Kxd2
{ White doesn't need to do anything special; we will just get the rest of the pieces out, for example with moves like Nf2, Be2, Nd3, and Rac1. Then, a2-a3 and b2-b4 can be played, looking to make progress on the queenside. One important thing to point out is that Black can go ...Nb6, looking to activate it by bringing it over to c4. However, we can easily prevent that idea and leave the knight restrained over there by playing b2-b3. }
13... f5
{ Black locks up the kingside. This move is more appropriate in the middlegame because it blocks the b1-h7 diagonal, which typically blunts White's light-squared bishop and prevents White from building a kingside attack. However, with no queens on the board, White was not going to do that anyway. Now, the e6-pawn is weak and requires constant attention, and the ...f7-f6 break is foregone forever. Not a good decision by the Black player! }
14. Nf2
{ Time for the knight to get active. It would like to go to d3 and then c5. On c5, it will not only be placed nicely, but it would also be putting endless pressure on the e6-pawn. }
14... Nb6 { Black is trying to activate the knight. } 15. b3
{ No, thank you! Nice and simple! } 15... Ke7 16. Nd3 Bd7 17. Nc5
{ Now, the b7-pawn is under pressure, and it would be very difficult to ever remove the knight from c5. }
17... Nd8 18. Rc1
{ White keeps improving the position with nice natural moves. Please note how passive Black's pieces are! In particular, that rook on h8 seems useless. }
18... Bc6 19. Be2
{ White connects the rooks. Next, I think it would make sense to play Rc2 and Rhc1, doubling up on the only open file. Then, I would consider the following idea: White can play a2-a4, looking to go a4-a5, grabbing more space, kicking the knight out, and fixing the pawns on the light squares, so that the bishop is even more passive, and so that the white minor pieces could easily attack them. If Black goes ...a6-a5 to stop that, then the b5-square becomes weak. Also, White can always consider making progress with the kingside expansion, such as h2-h3 and g2-g4. }
19... Nd7 20. Nd3
{ White isn't agreeing to the trades, which is very logical: the opponent has less space, and the pieces are restricted. Why facilitate that? }
20... Bb5 21. Rc7
{ The rook is invading. Please note Black's pieces  (the king and the knights)  are placed so awkwardly, that there is no way to chase the white rook away. }
21... Bxd3
{ This is an interesting decision, which I consider rather questionable, after all. Black gets rid of the traditionally 'bad' French bishop, which was also restricted by the black pawns. So what's the downside of it? The thing is that Black could keep it on c6, which would help block the c-file.  Now, there is no way to block the c-file, so White is about to invade. And the a4-a5 ideas make even more sense, because if Black ever goes ...a6-a5, then our bishop would be able to come to b5, adding more pressure. This is an interesting example, which allows making an important observation: sometimes, even the traditionally 'bad' piece can be an important defender, and getting rid of it means the defense becomes unbearable. }
22. Bxd3 Rb8 23. Rhc1
{ As planned, White just keeps making the most logical moves! Next, we should go b3-b4, a2-a4, and a4-a5, restricting the opponent even more. }
23... Rg8
{ Black is hoping to get some counterplay by preparing the pawn break ...g7-g5. That's a logical thought, but it's not something Black is likely to pull off. }
24. b4 h6 25. b5
{ This move is not actively preventing Black's counterplay on the kingside, but it still works, because White is creating a threat of winning the a6-pawn.   25.h4+-  seems like the easiest solution to me. Why not just prevent any ...g7-g5 related ideas and then improve the queenside pieces and pawns all you want? }
25... a5
{ 25...axb5  26.Bxb5  is a disaster for Black, who needs to give up a pawn.  26...Nc6  27.Bxc6  bxc6  28.R1xc6+-  .  Not only does White have a very powerful extra a-pawn, which is about to run, but also, the knight on d7 is in a dangerous position. Ideas like Rd6 or Ne1-d3-c5 are about to win that piece! }
26. b6
{ Black's pieces are beyond stuck, and there is a huge threat of Bb5!, putting more pressure on that knight on d7 and forcing material gains! }
26... Nc6 27. Bb5 { Black cannot avoid material losses. } 27... Rgc8 28. Bxc6
bxc6 29. R1xc6 Rxc7 30. bxc7
{ Of course, the c7-pawn is extremely strong! As we can see, Black is not just a pawn down but also has extremely passive pieces, and the a5 and e6-pawns are weak. }
30... Rc8 31. Ne1
{ The knight wasn't doing much on f3, so it is coming over to the queenside − for example, to c5. }
31... Nf8
{ Black is preparing the move ...Kd7, which would win the c7-pawn. But that's okay! }
32. Nd3 Kd7 33. Ra6
{ In return, we get the a-pawn, and will soon run it all the way up the board. }
33... Kxc7 34. Rxa5 Kb6 35. Ra4
{ White needs a few moves to consolidate and improve the rook's position. }
35... Nd7 36. Rb4+ Kc6 37. Rb1
{ 37.Kc2!  seems like an easier way to win. The point of this move is to bring the king to b3 to easily protect the a-pawn and support its advance! }
37... Nb6 38. Nc5 Re8 39. a4 { Finally, it's time for the pawn to run! } 39...
g5
{ 39...Ra8  isn't possible, of course, as that move loses Black's key pawn, which is holding up the entire pawn chain.  40.Nxe6+-  Rxa4  41.Nxg7+-  and the f5-pawn is falling too! }
40. fxg5
{ I am not sure about this decision. Sure enough, White is still winning, but why weaken the pawn structure and open the h-file for the black rook?   40.g3  would have been even easier, to my mind. The point is that even though Black can open up the g-file by trading pawns on f4, Black won't be EVER able to activate the rook since the e6-pawn would fall. So, we can just focus on advancing our a-pawn by playing Kd3 first, avoiding the ...Nc4+ fork, then a4-a5-a6, and so on. }
40... hxg5 41. h3 Nc4+ 42. Kc3
{ White is still winning, fortunately.  Converting this position would take a bit of work, but one interesting idea would be to play g2-g3 and h3-h4, creating a passed pawn on the kingside as well. However, Black makes a big mistake. }
42... Nxe5
{ Black tries to take advantage of the fact that we cannot take back, as that would leave the knight on c5 hanging, but this capture enters a forcing sequence, which is very favorable for White. }
43. Re1
{ The pawn on e6 is falling, and together with it, Black's entire position. }
43... Nc4 44. Rxe6+ Rxe6 45. Nxe6
{ Black is losing right away since not only do we have a passed pawn on the a-file, but we are about to create one on the other flank with g2-g3 and h3-h4 too. Also, Black's kingside pawns are hard to defend. }
45... g4 46. h4
{ Black resigned since it is impossible to stop both of our pawns. As you can see, it was very difficult to play without any space! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "12) Classical French − Model Games"]
[Black "Zoltan Varga − Christopher Repka, Slovakia 2015"]
[Result "*"]

{ This game is another example of White slowly but surely using spatial advantage in the typical French endgame. }
1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Nf6
{ The Classical Variation. Black keeps the tension, hoping that White would lock the position up with e4-e5. In that case, Black gets the standard French theme − a position with pawn chains, which most, if not all, French players absolutely adore. }
4. Bg5
{ But, as we discussed in the theoretical chapter, we keep the tension for now. The f6-knight is pinned, so Black has to worry about e4-e5 coming up, taking advantage of that pin. }
4... Be7 { Black unpins the knight, continuing to develop. } 5. e5
{ We grab space, locking the center up. } 5... Nfd7 6. Bxe7
{ As I explain in the theoretical chapter, this trade is not necessarily the most trivial one. White exchanges the supposedly 'bad' bishop, which was restricted by the pawn chain. That's a good piece of news, of course. But, there is also a bad one. Namely, the problem is that we have more space, so trading pieces is not very beneficial in that regard, as when the pieces come off the board, the value of our spatial advantage vanishes. }
6... Qxe7 7. Qd2
{ We are continuing natural development. It might seem as though White is only interested in castling queenside next, but actually, there is one more very cool idea coming up. As you hopefully remember, a typical fear of any White player, while facing the French, is that their big beautiful center will get destroyed with ...c7-c5 or ...f7-f6. We are able to meet the latter with f2-f4, but what about the former?  For now, as we'll see, Black is unable to play this move. But in the future, Black will! That's why our mini-plan is to go Nd1!, rerouting the knight to e3, where it is likely to prove useful in the upcoming kingside play, while also preparing to meet ...c7-c5 with c2-c3! Even in the opening, it's crucial to think of prophylaxis. }
7... a6
{ Black covers up the b5-square. That is done in order to prepare ...c7-c5, undermining White's center, without allowing the annoying Nb5-d6 jump. }
8. Nd1
{ Just on time! Black was ready to play ...c7-c5 and blow up our center, so it's very important that we can meet that move with c2-c3.   8.Nf3?  would be an ignorant move, which would allow Black to ruin our center.  8...c5!  And once the d4-pawn disappears, the one on e5 would become very difficult to defend! }
8... c5 9. c3 { The center is safe and sound, just as planned. } 9... Nc6 10.
f4
{ White is getting ready to develop with Nf3, Be2/d3, and so on. It was definitely very valuable and beneficial to insert the move f2-f4, as it helps us reinforce the e5-pawn. }
10... f6
{ In this game, Black tries the most ambitious and objectively strongest plan: to open up the f-file in order to get some counterplay, instead of just passively waiting and suffering! }
11. Nf3 cxd4
{ As we are about to see, and as you hopefully remember from the theoretical chapter, it is very valuable for Black to trade on d4 first, in order to make our d-pawn weaker and create a few threats against it. }
12. cxd4 fxe5 13. fxe5 O-O
{ So, what threats to the d4-pawn am I talking about? The exchange sacrifice ...Rxf3, aimed at eliminating its defender! Let's take a look at what happens if White plays an ignorant move. }
14. Nf2
{ This is a very important move. White is not only improving the passive knight, but is also stopping the ...Qh4+ idea, which we are discussing in a sideline.   14.a3?  If White isn't paying attention, the center will, all of a sudden, just fall apart.  14...Rxf3!  15.gxf3  Qh4+!  The d4-pawn cannot be saved.  16.Qf2  Nxd4!!  Black also has this cute little trick, justified by the fork ...Nxf3. The e5-pawn is also in a bad shape, and there are a couple more annoying things for White to deal with, such as ...Nc2+.  For instance, after  17.Qxh4  Nxf3+  18.Kf2  Nxh4-+  ,  the endgame is lost for White because the e5-pawn is also falling, and Black will have three @@StartBracket@@!@@EndBracket@@ pawns for the missing exchange. Also, our rooks won't be able to do that much yet, which makes our problems even larger. }
14... Qb4
{ So, Black again offers a queen trade, just as in the previous game. However, this time the position does not seem as bad because the f-file is open, which means Black can get some counterplay there. And the absence of the f-pawns means Black has less of a spatial disadvantage.   14...Rxf3?  no longer makes sense, since after  15.gxf3  Qh4  16.O-O-O+-  ,  we easily protect the d4-pawn. White is a clear exchange up. And, in fact, will be able to take advantage of the structural changes by placing at least one rook on the g-file and launching an attack on the black king!   14...Nb6!  followed by the classical ...Bd7-e8-h5! idea, improving the light-squared bishop, would have been a lot better. We discuss this plan in the theoretical chapter, of course! }
15. Qxb4 Nxb4
{ Black's knight is seemingly placed quite actively, and is currently threatening a fork on c2. But, of course, this is only a temporary thing. It's getting kicked out. }
16. Kd2
{ However, the endgame still seems unpleasant for Black. Not as unpleasant as in the previous game, but still really uncomfortable. Again, the knight on d7 has nothing useful to do. If it goes to b6, we just restrict it with b2-b3. Then, we'd love to kick out the knight on b4, then improve our f2-knight by placing it on d3 and maybe c5, and try to take advantage of the open c-file by invading on c7. }
16... Nb6
{ The knight is looking to come to a4 or c4, while also unblocking the black bishop. }
17. b3
{ Of course, this simple prophylactic move does a great job of restricting the knight. }
17... Bd7 18. Nd3
{ With this move, White improves the knight. The knight trade would ensure the safety of White's center − see the sideline to understand what the problem with keeping the knights by means of 18.a3 could be.   18.a3  ,  kicking out the knight might look like a good idea, but actually, it doesn't turn out to be one. Why so?  18...Nc6  .  Because now, Black is able to get counterplay by putting pressure on the d4-pawn! For instance, after  19.Nd3  ,  Black can again try the exchange sacrifice, aimed at ruining our center.  19...Rxf3!?  20.gxf3  Nxd4∞  .  The pawns on b3, f3, and e5 are weak, while the rooks don't have that much to do. So, it would be much more prudent to not allow that to happen. }
18... Nxd3
{ After  18...Nc6  19.Nc5  ,  Black has no time to get any counterplay with ...Rxf3, as there is a lot of pressure on the b7 and e6-pawns, and the d7-bishop.  19...Rxf3?  This time, Black doesn't have the time to get any counterplay.  20.gxf3  Nxd4  21.Bh3!  The e6-pawn is a target, which means Black will either need to allow us to play f3-f4 and protect the e5-pawn or enter the forcing line  21...Nxf3+  22.Ke3  Nxe5  23.Nxd7  Nbxd7  24.Bxe6++-  when the position quickly opens up and falls apart since now the white rooks become incredibly powerful! }
19. Bxd3 Bb5
{ Black is offering a bishop trade, which is fair because the bishop was very restricted. However, this move spoils Black's pawn structure. There is one more problem. As the pieces come off, each remaining piece becomes much more important. Unfortunately, the only remaining black piece is the extremely passive knight on b6! So, it almost feels  (at least, for quite a while)  that Black is a piece down! And, of course, many of the black pawns: b5, b7, and e6, are very weak. }
20. Bxb5 axb5 21. Rhc1
{ Black is facing such threats as Rc5 and Rc7, and it's not easy to deal with them. You might wonder why am I saying that given that Black can simply go ...Rc8 with either rook, offering a trade. The problem is that if all the rooks come off, White can simply go Kc3-b4, winning the queenside pawns, as the king is much more active! }
21... Rac8 22. Rxc8 Rxc8 23. Ng5 { The e6-pawn is also a huge problem! } 23...
Re8
{ 23...Rc6  24.Rc1+-  is a disaster for Black. The rook will get traded, and the pawn on e6 won't be able to survive.  24...Rxc1  25.Kxc1  and the e6-pawn cannot be defended. Actually, it's hard to imagine the b5-pawn surviving either, as our king is much closer, and it can go to c2-c3-b4 in no time. }
24. Rc1
{ Finally, things are starting to fall apart. It's not possible for Black to prevent Rc5 or Rc7. }
24... h6 { At least, Black can kick the knight away. For now. } 25. Nf3
{ 25.Nh3!  seems like a better idea to me because the knight can easily come to f4 if Black doesn't go ...g7-g5. And if that happens, Black weakens even more squares!  25...g5  26.Rc7!  Rb8  27.Nf2  .  The maneuver Ng4-f6 cannot be stopped, and Black is about to suffer decisive losses. }
25... Ra8 26. Rc2
{ Black is not going to get any counterplay. However, the ideas like Kc3-b4 or Ne1-d3-c5 cannot be stopped. }
26... Kf8 27. Ne1 { Time for the knight to find new targets! } 27... Ke7 28.
Kc3 Nc8 29. Kb4
{ This is what decisive progress looks like. It might seem as though White is just winning a pawn. However, an extra queenside pawn is very valuable because by playing a2-a4, b3-b4, a4-a5, b4-b5, and so on, we would create a passed pawn and queen it in no time. }
29... Kd7 30. Nd3 b6 31. Kxb5
{ Besides having to protect the weak b6-pawn, the one on e6, and the c-file, Black also needs to watch the f-file since White is now able to play Rf2-f7, trying to invade there as well. A classic principle of two weaknesses! }
31... Ra7 32. a4
{ These pawns are starting to advance. Please note the c8-knight can never move! }
32... Ra8 33. g4 Ra5+ 34. Kb4
{ Black resigned. The pieces are stuck on the queenside, protecting the b6-pawn and stopping our a-pawn. That's why, being completely tied up, Black cannot stop ideas like Rf2, Nf4-h5, and protect the kingside. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "12) Classical French − Model Games"]
[Black "Emil Sutovsky − Markus Schaefer, Solingen 2011"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Nf6
{ The Classical Variation. Black keeps the tension, hoping that White would lock the position up with e4-e5. In that case, Black gets the standard French theme − a position with pawn chains, which most, if not all, French players absolutely adore. }
4. Bg5
{ But, as we discussed in the theoretical chapter, we keep the tension for now. The f6-knight is pinned, so Black has to worry about e4-e5 coming up, taking advantage of that pin. }
4... Be7 { Black unpins the knight, continuing to develop. } 5. e5
{ We grab space, locking the center up. } 5... Nfd7 6. Bxe7
{ As I explain in the theoretical chapter, this trade is not necessarily the most trivial one. White exchanges the supposedly 'bad' bishop, which was restricted by the pawn chain. That's a good piece of news, of course. But, there is also a bad one. Namely, the problem is that we have more space, so trading pieces is not very beneficial in that regard, as when the pieces come off the board, the value of our spatial advantage vanishes. }
6... Qxe7 7. f4
{ White overprotects the e5-pawn, grabbing more space on the kingside. As we know by now, it's a very typical idea in these positions. However, we prefer a different theoretical move.   7.Qd2  is the move order I suggest, the key idea being to be on time with the Nd1 and c2-c3! plan.  7...a6  8.Nd1!  c5  9.c3!  and we have successfully managed to use the c-pawn as well to make our center even more secure. }
7... O-O 8. Nf3 c5
{ Black has castled and is now undermining our center. As I had pointed out several times in the theoretical chapter, and in other model games, castling first is very important for Black because playing ...c7-c5 prematurely runs into Nb5! with a very unpleasant double threat of Nd6+ and Nc7+, which typically causes Black tremendous difficulties. }
9. Qd2 Nc6 10. dxc5
{ In order to make sure Black can never lock up the queenside with ...c5-c4, creating favorable conditions for an easy pawn storm, White releases the tension.   10.O-O-O  is also possible, but here, Black gets an extra opportunity.  10...c4  ,  and Black can choose to lock up the queenside and try to rapidly attack the white king with ...b7-b5-b4. While this doesn't have to be a disaster, things get too complicated and too scary for no reason.  11.g4  Rb8  12.f5  b5∞  .  It's certainly better to avoid such a scenario. }
10... Nxc5
{ Of course, it is much better for Black to take with the knight in these positions. This is because this recapture helps prepare ...Bd7 followed by ...Rfc8, activating all the pieces. Instead, taking with the queen would leave the queenside pieces stuck. }
11. O-O-O a6
{ This move achieves several things. Most importantly, Black is getting ready to advance the queenside pawns with ...b7-b5-b4. It's not likely that this pawn storm can lead to a checkmate, especially because the center of the board is fairly open. However, it's still the right plan for Black. By pushing those pawns, Black would kick our pieces back, win time, and make room for the pieces to come to the active queenside squares. Ideally, Black would love to play ...b5-b4, then ...a5-a4, and ... b4-b3 at some point, forcing the files to open. }
12. Bd3
{ White is preparing to go Ne2-d4, taking advantage of the outpost, and evacuating the knight from inevitable ...b7-b5-b4 related danger. }
12... b5 13. Qe3
{ It was also possible to play Ne2 right away, but first, White takes the d4-square under more control, while also starting to stare at the c5-knight. It's a potentially valuable thing because if Black ever wanted to play ...f7-f6 and then take with the queen, Black would hang that knight! And, of course, if Black ever wanted to make a move like ...Qc7 or ...Qb7, that'd leave the knight hanging as well. }
13... Nxd3+ 14. Rxd3
{ It's a bit of a bummer to allow Black to trade off our light-squared bishop, but there are several bright things about that trade.  Now, we have an extra knight, which means when we go Ne2-d4, looking to occupy that wonderful outpost, Black can trade off a pair of knights, but won't be able to ever make our other knight leave. Black's bishop on c8 is a pretty bad piece. Potentially, Black can make it look good with ...b5-b4, ...a6-a5, and ...Ba6, but that's a bit of an optical illusion, as it still won't be doing much on the f1-a6 diagonal. The rook could be useful on the third rank! For example, we can go Nd4, then Qh3 and Rg3, bringing the rook to attack the opponent's king! }
14... f5
{ Black chooses to block the kingside. At least, Black should have gone ...f7-f6, hoping to undermine the e5-pawn and sort of force White to take, because here, White had two attractive options: the one chosen in the game, and simply keeping the tension with Ne2-d4! }
15. exf6
{ Just like in the first game of this chapter, White is very happy to go for this pawn structure, where the e6-pawn and the e5-squares are weak. }
15... Qxf6 16. g3
{ The f4-pawn was under pressure, but it's easy to defend it, of course. Now, White needs to start taking advantage of the weak dark squares. That would be best achieved with Ne2-d4, trading a pair of knights, followed by pressure on the e6-pawn with moves like Re1. Of course, swapping the queens would also be good for White since the opponent has long-term weaknesses, and the queen trade would kill all the possible counterplay. }
16... Bd7 17. Re1 { As planned, the rook is coming to the e-file. } 17... a5
{ Black is trying to tempt White with the loose b5-pawn. But, of course, White's goal here is to switch to restrictive positional play. Strategically, White almost won already, so why complicate matters? }
18. Qc5
{ A pretty interesting move. White is activating the queen, potentially looking to disturb Black with moves like Qd6. Also, now the d3-rook can use the e3-square. And, as it turns out, White is preparing a little tactical escalation.   18.Nxb5?  would be a big mistake due to  18...Nb4!  Black double attacks the rook on d3 and the knight on b5, making the position rather unclear. }
18... b4 { Black falls right into this one. } 19. Nxd5
{ The loose position of this bishop on d7 allows White to make this move work. }
19... exd5 20. Qxd5+
{ Of course, this is a double attack on the king and the bishop. Unless Black wants to be two pawns down, the check needs to be blocked. }
20... Rf7 21. Ng5
{ However, now White is able to force a transition into a position with a rook and two pawns for two minor pieces. Does that remind you of Inarkiev's game from this chapter? }
21... Rf8 22. Nxf7 Rxf7 23. Qc5
{ The rook is ready to invade on d6. And, White has an even bigger threat! }
23... Qf5
{ Black offers a queen trade. Frankly, the endgame after the trade should be lost as well, but White is claiming that the opponent's king is so weak that it's worth keeping the queens on the board.   23...a4??  Let's say Black skips a move, doing something ignorant. Can you find a forced win for White?  24.Rxd7!!  Rxd7  25.Re8+  Kf7  26.Rf8+  and we win the opponent's queen, and then the c6-knight. The game ends right away. }
24. Rd5 Qh3 25. f5
{ With this move, White creates a tactical threat. White takes the g6 and e6-squares under control, creating a mating threat! }
25... h6
{ Black makes room for the king, stopping the mating threats. However, the problem is that the move f4-f5 has also cut the connection between the black queen and bishop, which allows for another little tactical.   25...a4??  26.Rxd7!  Rxd7  27.Re8+  Kf7  28.Qf8  with checkmate. That was the point of the move f4-f5! }
26. Rxd7 Rxd7 27. Qxc6
{ Now, White is just a pawn up in a simple position with no more material imbalance. }
27... Qxf5 28. Qe6+
{ White offers a queen trade. It seems to me that the rook endgame should be easily won because the a5-pawn is pretty vulnerable, the white king is much@@StartBracket@@!@@EndBracket@@ more active, and White's c-pawn can start running in no time. }
28... Rf7 29. b3
{ White makes a somewhat surprising, but very logical and ambitious decision. Given that there is this scary pin on the a2-g8 diagonal, White is in no rush to trade queens. If Black avoids a trade, White is going to try to take advantage of the pinned rook by means of Rd1-d7, for instance. }
29... Qf2
{ Black keeps the queen, hoping to get some counterplay. But, unfortunately, that's not going to happen.   29...Qxe6  30.Rxe6  Rf2  would lead to a lost rook endgame.  31.Re5  31...Rxh2  32.Rxa5  Rg2  33.Rb5  Rxg3  34.Rxb4  and the white pawns, supported by the king, will run much more easily. }
30. Rd1
{ The rook is about to come to d7, in which case White would be able to liquidate into a pawn up winning endgame. }
30... Kh7 { So, Black rushes to unpin. } 31. Qe4+
{ However, White reminds the opponent that the king isn't safe at all. Black needs to either go back to the 8th rank, which seems very scary, or weaken the 7th rank with ...g7-g6. }
31... g6 { 31...Kg8?  32.Rd8+  doesn't look great either! } 32. Qe5
{ The problem of not having a pawn on g7 is that the a1-h8 diagonal is much weaker now. So, White is preparing ideas like Rd8-Qh8, which can result in a very quick checkmate. }
32... Qb6 33. Rd5
{ The a5-pawn is also a target, which White is happy to remind the opponent about! }
33... Rc7
{ Black chooses to give up another pawn to at least keep the pieces somewhat active, but that isn't helping.   33...Ra7  would keep the pawn alive, but wouldn't help Black survive.  34.Rc5!?  The rook is on its merry way to c8, from where it would create mating threats. Black is dead lost, for instance  34...Ra8??  35.Rc7++-  with checkmate on g7. }
34. Rxa5 Qc6 35. Qe2
{ Of course, it's easy to stop Black's threats. All White needs to do now is to bring the rook back to a good position, such as e5, and force trades, since any endgame two pawns up should be winning extremely easily. Of course, it would be best to swap the queens, not the rooks, since although the queen endgame would be easily winning, there are always some checks to worry about. }
35... Qf6 36. Re5
{ White blocks the a1-h8 diagonal, preventing the annoying check on a1. It would be useful to go Kb1 next, covering up the a1-square, so the rook can move freely. }
36... Ra7 37. Kb1
{ As you can see, White is very happy to take the time to make all the prophylactic and defensive moves. One of the most difficult things for club players to fully acknowledge is that the goal is to win reliably and convincingly, not fast! }
37... Rd7 38. Re4 { The b4-pawn is also a problem! } 38... Qd6 39. Qe1
{ All of Black's pieces are getting tied up protecting the b4-pawn. } 39... Rb7
40. Re6 Qc5 41. Qe4
{ Time to start focusing on other targets! As you can see, by now any minimal activity Black had has evaporated. Black is stuck dealing with various weaknesses, which enables White to activate the pieces even more, and shortly force trades. As Nimzowitch said, while looking for piece trades, don't beg by chasing the opponent's pieces. Instead, just improve your pieces relentlessly until the opponent is dreaming of trades! }
41... Rg7 42. h4
{ h4-h5! is on the radar, taking advantage of the pinned g6-pawn. Of course, first White will go g3-g4, preparing that move. }
42... h5 43. Re5
{ Now, the threat is Rxh5+. Things are finally coming to an end! } 43... Qg1+
44. Kb2
{ Black resigned, as it's not possible to prevent the threats of Rxh5 and Qxb4. Two pawns down and without counterplay, with multiple weaknesses, Black figured there wasn't much to fight for. As you could hopefully observe, White's conversion technique was brilliant. White did things pretty slowly, but without ever allowing even for the slightest bit of counterplay! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "13)  Winawer French − Model Games"]
[Black "Jean Marc Degraeve − Christian Maier, Cappelle la Grande 2001"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ This game is a showcase of how a 2350+ level player ended up collapsing without ever getting the slightest bit of counterplay versus our 4.Nge2 system. }
1... e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Bb4
{ The famous Winawer Variation. Black develops in the most active way possible, immediately pinning the knight and threatening the e4-pawn. The downside of this move is that leaving the kingside with the bishop weakens the g7-pawn. Plus, if Black ever goes ...Ne7, the bishop often ends up short on squares and unable to return to the kingside. }
4. Ne2
{ With this rare and flexible move, we make sure the structure remains very flexible by overprotecting the c3-knight with our knight, so that if Black ever takes it, we can take back with the knight, avoiding doubled pawns. On the next turn, we are planning on continuing with a2-a3, kicking out the annoying bishop and neutralizing the pin.   Once we do that, Black will have a hard time finding a good square for the bishop, and we'll continue the flexible nice development. But, of course, just as any line, especially a sideline, this move has a few downsides, namely: it blocks the development of our kingside, even if just temporarily, and it leaves the e4-pawn hanging. }
4... Ne7
{ Black keeps developing, ignoring the possibility of capturing our central pawn.   4...dxe4  is the main move, which we are about to discuss in another model game. }
5. a3
{ We are immediately kicking out the bishop. Of course, we would be beyond thrilled to see Black trade on c3, as that would give up the bishop pair, and help us solve the slightly awkward situation with our kingside pieces − the knight on e2, although it's useful for protecting the c3-knight, is blocking in our f1-bishop. }
5... Ba5 6. b4 { Now, we grab more space, pushing the bishop further away. }
6... Bb6 7. e5
{ Black could try to capture on e4 and then put pressure on our d4-pawn with moves like ...Nf5, and we definitely don't need that to happen. Now, the b6-bishop is extremely restricted, as you can easily see. }
7... a5
{ Black is trying to open up the a-file and trade a pair of pawns in order to facilitate the defense. }
8. Na4
{ It's important for us to be careful: Black was threatening to capture on b4, taking advantage of the pin on the a-file. With the last move, White not only solves that problem but also attacks the bishop on b6. It's possible to trade on b6 at any moment, getting the bishop pair and making Black's pawn structure look a bit funky.  However, perhaps it's best to delay that trade: the b6-bishop is very restricted, so there is no need to trade it off. Plus, after ...cxb6, the c-file would open up and our c-pawn might wind up a bit backward and weak. }
8... Ba7
{ Black moves the bishop away in order to prevent any Nxb6 ideas. However, by doing so, that also blocks the rook on a8. And, of course, the bishop is still very inactive.   8...c6  ,  however, if Black tried to activate the bishop by playing ...Bc7 and ...f7-f6, we would immediately trade it off.  9.Nxb6  Qxb6  10.Rb1  and the beauty of this trade this time is that Black couldn't take with the c-pawn, opening up the c-file for the rook. Now, of course, Black is clearly worse due to lack of space, lack of counterplay, and the fact that we have the bishop pair. }
9. c3
{ White overprotects the d4 and b4-pawns, making sure the center is super secure. }
9... Bd7
{ Black is looking to trade off a pair of pieces on a4, giving up the bishop pair, but also getting rid of the bad French bishop. }
10. Ng3
{ White is unblocking the kingside pieces. Now, the light-squared bishop is ready to go to d3, starting to stare at the h7-pawn and the black kingside overall. Then, at some point, White could play Qg4, Nh5, Bg5/h6, and create a very powerful attack. Of course, don't forget about the loose knight on a4 while bringing the queen over to the kingside! }
10... Nf5
{ Black is offering a knight trade, which in a way is logical enough because of lack of space. However, this move spoils Black's pawn structure and therefore is a considerable mistake. }
11. Nxf5 exf5 12. Nc5
{ The knight is now very active. If Black trades it, we would play bxc5, opening up the b-file and creating a weak pawn on b7 that can be easily attacked. If not, then Black will need to tolerate it or go ...b7-b6, which would just bury the a7-bishop alive. }
12... b6
{ That's the route Black chooses. Now, the bishop on a7 is just dead! } 13.
Nxd7 Qxd7 14. b5
{ A wonderful positional move! Now, the knight on b8 is also dead! Black cannot ever go ...Nc6 or ...Na6, as you can see. Sure enough, at some point, Black could move the queen away and go ...Nd7, but that is not an easy solution to all the problems either. Why so? Because:  on d7, the knight is doing nothing, and cannot go anywhere further − the squares on c5, e5, and f6 are controlled by the white pawns; the queen isn't easy to move away since it needs to be protecting the d5 and f5-pawns. }
14... O-O 15. Bd3
{ The f5-pawn isn't likely to get lost anytime soon, however by attacking it with moves like Qc2 or Qf3, White can provoke another weakening move ...g7-g6, which would leave the dark squares around the black king, such as f6 and h6, much weaker. }
15... c6
{ Black is hoping to get rid of White's crucial pawn, which is currently doing such a wonderful job restricting the black bishop and knight. }
16. a4
{ No, thank you! Of course, White would rather not play chess ever again than let go of that wonderful pawn! }
16... f6
{ Black is trying to undermine the center. Of course, that's a logical idea, but it doesn't help much, either. }
17. f4
{ As we can see, the center is also very easy to defend. Next, White is ready to go O-O, Qf3, and maybe h2-h3 and g2-g4 at some point, opening up the kingside, and the diagonals for the bishops. }
17... Qe6 18. O-O g6 19. Qb3
{ White finds another target: c3-c4!, blowing up the center and opening the position for the bishops. It's very important to point out that the diagonals around the black king, such as a3-f8, a2-g8, and a1-h8, are rather weak, so if White's bishops spring to life, the consequences might end up rather severe. }
19... cxb5 20. axb5 Rc8
{ Black is trying to stop the move c3-c4, but is bound to fail. How should White improve the position further? }
21. Ra4
{ Of course! White can easily take the c4-square under even more control. The pawn break is inevitable. }
21... fxe5 22. fxe5 Nd7
{ Finally, the knight gets out. Just in time to see the collapse of Black's position! }
23. c4
{ The center opens up, after all. Decisive material losses are inevitable. }
23... Bb8 { 23...dxc4?  24.Bxc4  doesn't help either, of course. } 24. cxd5 Qf7
25. e6
{ Black is losing a piece, on top of the other problems, and resigned. As you can see, this was an extremely easy, one-sided game. But, don't forget: it's not easy to make things look this easy versus a 2370-rated player!  Black had no idea how to deal with this variation, ended up with a passive bishop on a7, failed to get any counterplay, got the queenside pieces stuck, and things collapsed in no time. A great showcase of how difficult it could be to handle a position that doesn't look like the typical Winawer ones! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "13)  Winawer French − Model Games"]
[Black "Parimarjan Negi − Anish Giri, Spanish League 2011"]
[Result "*"]

{ This game is the one between the highest-rated players we've seen so far. The Black player, Anish Gir, is a super-GM, and the author of the Lifetime Repertoire on the French Defense! Let's see how he got in trouble versus Negi's tricky opening choice. }
1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Bb4
{ The famous Winawer Variation. Black develops in the most active way possible, immediately pinning the knight and threatening the e4-pawn. The downside of this move is that leaving the kingside with the bishop weakens the g7-pawn. Plus, if Black ever goes ...Ne7, the bishop often ends up short on squares and unable to return to the kingside. }
4. Ne2
{ With this rare and flexible move, we make sure the structure remains very flexible by overprotecting the c3-knight with our knight, so that if Black ever takes it, we can take back with the knight, avoiding doubled pawns. On the next turn, we are planning on continuing with a2-a3, kicking out the annoying bishop and neutralizing the pin.   Once we do that, Black will have a hard time finding a good square for the bishop, and we'll continue the flexible nice development. But, of course, just as any line, especially a sideline, this move has a few downsides, namely: it blocks the development of our kingside, even if just temporarily, and it leaves the e4-pawn hanging. }
4... dxe4
{ Black is just capturing the free pawn. Later on, Black might return it and focus on rapid comfortable development, or instead try to hold on to it with ...f7-f5. }
5. a3
{ We, of course, follow up with our plan of kicking out the opponent's bishop and breaking the pin. At this point, Black needs to decide whether to hold on to the pawn by taking the knight and then doing something about the hanging pawn, or to retreat, returning it right away. }
5... Be7
{ This is Black's more popular move. Black is happy to return the pawn to keep the bishop pair for now and hopefully trade a few pieces. Essentially, our opponent is hoping to play a somewhat improved version of the Rubinstein Variation, where our knight on e2 is sort of misplaced. However, as I explain in the theoretical chapter, I do not have much belief in the soundness or appeal of this variation, as opposed to the one with 5...Bxc3.   5...Bxc3+!  is the more reliable choice, as we discuss in the theoretical chapter and other model games. }
6. Nxe4
{ We get the pawn back. Because of the extra space and more active pieces, it seems obvious White should be better. However, there is one problem: the knight on e2 is really passive! That's the only thing that gives Black hope for equality, I believe. }
6... Nf6
{ Black offers a knight trade, which is a logical thing to do, as it decreases the spatial disadvantage: the fewer pieces left, the less it matters that you don't have much space. }
7. Nxf6+
{ This move is quite rare, but it's been used in recent years by such strong young players as Xiong, Abdusattorov, Niemann, and others, and White scored really well. We are happy to force the bishop to go to f6 without having to determine or commit to placing our pieces on weird squares, such as after  7.Qd3  . }
7... Bxf6 8. Be3
{ Now, the goal is obviously to get the queen out and castle. In most cases, we will probably settle for Qd2, followed by queenside castling. However, in many positions, the queen can come to g4 after we play Nf4 and create a lot of threats on the kingside! }
8... O-O 9. Qd2
{ We are getting ready to castle queenside, then activate the knight with Nf4, unblocking the f1-bishop, and then see what to do next. We can consider opening up the center with d4-d5, as the game shows, or launch a kingside attack with moves like g2-g4, h2-h4, g4-g5, and so on. }
9... b6
{ Black wants to develop the bishop to the long diagonal, where it will be rather active. Fair enough! }
10. O-O-O Bb7 11. Nf4
{ This move is very valuable, not only because it unblocks the bishop on f1, which was starting to feel a bit claustrophobic, but also because it potentially helps prepare the d4-d5 push. Why would White even consider playing d4-d5, trading the d4-pawn, which occupies way more space, for the passive pawn on e6?  Mostly because it would open up the position, which benefits the side with the more active pieces − in this case, definitely White! This plan is particularly effective versus the setups where Black fianchettoes the light-squared bishop because doing that is rather time-consuming. }
11... Nd7 12. d5
{ The decision to open up the center is justified by the awkward placement of two of Black's minor pieces:  the bishop on f6 − we can easily hit it and hope to get the bishop pair; the knight on d7 − the pin on the d-file can prove really awkward for Black to deal with. }
12... e5
{ Black chooses to avoid the simplifications and close the center. This way, the aforementioned highly unpleasant endgame gets sidestepped. However, that lands in a middlegame where Black can easily run into a very powerful attack on the kingside. Remember another rule of thumb: it's much easier to attack on a flank when the center is closed and there is no counterplay there!   12...exd5  leads to a very difficult endgame after the natural sequence  13.Nxd5  13...Bxd5  14.Qxd5  Ne5  15.Be2  Qxd5  16.Rxd5±  .  Black didn't have to make all of these moves, but it's logical to do so. Now, White just has the bishop pair on an open board. The plan is to trade the rooks, get the king active, and go after the queenside pawns with Bf4, or Kd2-c3-b4-b5-a6! }
13. Nh5
{ Negi places the knight in a perfect spot, from where it can both help get the bishop pair and build a kingside attack. }
13... Be7 14. f4
{ This is a very interesting decision. White wants to go f4-f5, occupying space on the kingside, and hoping that pawn would help open things up after g2-g4-g5 and f5-f6! at a right time. To be honest, given that the f5-f6 pawn break completely tears the black king apart, any time would be the right one.   14.Bc4  is the theoretical continuation that I recommend instead. }
14... exf4
{ Black tries to avoid that outcome, however, now the white bishop becomes enormously active. }
15. Bxf4
{ It is worth pointing out that the b7-bishop is just dead. It's staring at a wall and won't ever be useful, it seems. White is ready to start enjoying the position in many ways: for example, we can launch a kingside pawn storm with g2-g4-g5, or play Ng3-f5, using the knight to not only put pressure on the g7-pawn but also on the e7-bishop. The only thing which should be remembered is that if White ever goes Bd3, that could hang the d5-pawn, so care is needed. }
15... Bd6
{ Black tries to find some relief via trades, which is a very logical line of thought. However, the Indian star had something absolutely brilliant planned against that.   After  15...Nf6  ,  it seems as though Black should immediately bring more defenders to the king, right? Well, this move doesn't work out as well as Black would like, and for more than one reason!  16.Nxg7!!  This gorgeous sacrifice completely opens up the poor black king.   16.Bxc7  is lazy, yet also a very effective way to get a large advantage. But, in the endgame, which might not feel enough to the ambitious White players.  16...Qxc7  17.d6!  Qxd6  18.Qxd6  Bxd6  19.Nxf6+!  A nice intermezzo! The black pawn structure gets ruined.  19...gxf6  20.Rxd6±  and White is certainly much better, although it would take a fair bit of work to convert the better pawn structure.  16...Kxg7  17.Be5!  With Bd3, then Qg5+ and Qh6 coming, Black is about to get destroyed. For instance, after  17...h6  18.Qf4+-  ,  White is also ready to have the rook join the attack with Rd3-g3. Unfortunately, Black is dead lost, as the king is helplessly weak. }
16. Bh6
{ The king is so weak that all the immediate sacrifices are extremely tempting! The g7-square is a huge problem. }
16... gxh6
{ Giri decides to accept the sacrifice, which seems Black's only decent choice.   16...Be5  ,  Black could also refuse to accept the sacrifice but after  17.Re1  ,  White would either make the opponent transpose into the game if Black takes, or after  17...Bf6  18.Nxf6+!?  Nxf6  19.Qg5±  ,  keep a powerful attack, while also acquiring the bishop pair without having to sacrifice anything. }
17. Qxh6 { Now, White is, of course, threatening checkmate in one move: Qg7. }
17... Be5 18. Bb5
{ What's so impressive about this attack is that White just keeps improving the position of the pieces! Okay, White is also creating threats, of course. Now, the threat is to take the knight on d7, then go Qg5+ and win the bishop on e5. But still, White isn't attacking by capturing or checking!  It's sort of amazing that we can just keep making developing, logical-looking moves. Plus, of course, there are ideas like Rg3-h3, joining the attack via the third rank. And if the bishop on e5 were to go somewhere, the rook would also gain access to the valuable g3-square. }
18... Kh8
{ Black avoids the aforementioned threat by making sure Qg5 won't ever be a check. }
19. Rhe1
{ White just keeps bringing the pieces in! Again, the threat is to eliminate the knight and win the undefended bishop on e5. }
19... Rg8 { This is Black's only chance, the extra piece must be returned. }
20. Bxd7
{ Of course, Black cannot have the opponent take the e5-bishop while the queens are still on the board. }
20... Qg5+
{ Black is fortunate to be able to trade queens and liquidate into a bad endgame!   20...Qxd7??  21.Rxe5+-  is a completely resignable position. The king is beyond weak. Nf6 is coming, so is Rh5. Funnily enough, that b7-bishop is just dead too! }
21. Qxg5 Rxg5 22. g4
{ White is very interested in keeping the knight in its annoying position on h5. From here, by controlling the g7-square, the knight helps create a mating net. }
22... Bxh2 23. Bf5
{ Black's defense was incredibly difficult, and immediately goes wrong. } 23...
Bd6
{ 23...Bc8□  .  In order to survive, Black needed to challenge the g4-pawn by offering a bishop trade. For instance, after  24.Re8+  Rg8!  ,  the position looks awkward, but Black seems to be surviving, as White is forced to trade some of the pieces.  25.Rxc8  Rgxc8  26.Bxc8  Rxc8  27.Rf1⩲  .   With c2-c4 and Kd2-d3 coming next, it's obvious that White is considerably better since the pawn structure is superior: the f7 and h7-pawns are weak, while the one on d5 is considerably restricting the opponent. Also, the white king is much more active. However, Black can keep defending, and rather successfully! }
24. Nf6
{ Black failed to force the trade of the light-squared bishops, and now it's too late: there is too much pressure on the h7-pawn! }
24... Rg7
{ 24...Bc8??  is, of course, no longer possible due to  25.Re8+  and now White controls the g8-square, so Black cannot block with the rook. Therefore, the king is dragged into the war zone.  25...Kg7  26.Nh5+  Kh6  .  First of all, moves like Rh1 seem to be creating strong threats. But, more importantly, White can just win a piece in one move.  27.Rxc8+-  . }
25. Rh1
{ The h7-pawn cannot be kept alive. With the loss of this pawn, the entire position collapses: despite the fact the queens are gone, the black king is still extremely weak! }
25... Be5 26. Nxh7 Kg8
{ Black manages to evacuate the king from a discovered check on the h-file. However, on g8, it's still in a very dangerous situation. }
27. Rde1
{ Black's bishop cannot really retreat, as it needs to keep guarding the f6-square: the opponent's position is collapsing! }
27... Bxd5
{ Black's last hope: the rook on h1 is hanging, which means White doesn't have the tempo to spare to capture the bishop on e5.   27...Bd6??  28.Nf6+  Kf8  29.Rh8+  is, of course, a checkmate.   27...f6??  doesn't help either. How does White win by force? Find a tactic!  28.Be6+!  Of course! Easy enough. :@@EndBracket@@  28...Rf7  and now, White could either just win the exchange, or do even better with  29.Rxe5!  fxe5  30.Ng5+-  ,  when White would be at least a piece up. }
28. Rh5
{ But, since that bishop needs to keep guarding the f6-square, it's not escaping! }
28... f6 { How to win by force? } 29. Rxe5
{ White needs to deprive the f6-square of a defender to set up a major fork. }
29... fxe5 30. Nf6+ Kf7 31. Nxd5
{ With two pieces for the rook, White is completely winning. The e-pawn won't go anywhere because White can easily block it by installing the knight on e4. Then, we can always advance the pawn with g5-g6. Also, the white king can easily come to e3-e4, helping collect the weak e5-pawn. And, of course, Black is still dealing with some annoying one-move threats. }
31... c6 32. Nb4 { White keeps winning time by attacking the weak pawns. }
32... c5 33. Nc6 Kf6
{ 33...Re8  34.Bd7!  is a cute move that makes the rook leave and abandon the e5-pawn. Of course, it's not the only way to win, but it's the nicest one. }
34. Rh6+ Kg5 35. Re6
{ Black resigned since the e5-pawn is also lost. An absolutely brilliant win by Negi, if you ask me. It would be a huge honor to play such a powerful attacking game versus anyone, but once you also remember the sky-high level of his opponent, it becomes a true masterpiece! As you can see, it's not safe for Black to have the bishop on b7 completely cut off and restricted by the powerful pawn on d5! Overall, these positions look really difficult to play with Black. }
