[White "13)  Winawer French − Model Games"]
[Black "Vassily Ivanchuk − Espen Forsaa, Gibraltar 2013"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Bb4
{ The famous Winawer Variation. Black develops in the most active way possible, immediately pinning the knight and threatening the e4-pawn. The downside of this move is that leaving the kingside with the bishop weakens the g7-pawn. Plus, if Black ever goes ...Ne7, the bishop often ends up short on squares and unable to return to the kingside. }
4. Ne2
{ With this rare and flexible move, we make sure the structure remains very flexible by overprotecting the c3-knight with our knight, so that if Black ever takes it, we can take back with the knight, avoiding doubled pawns. On the next turn, we are planning on continuing with a2-a3, kicking out the annoying bishop and neutralizing the pin.   Once we do that, Black will have a hard time finding a good square for his bishop, and we'll continue the flexible nice development. But, of course, just as any line, especially a sideline, this move has a few downsides, namely: it blocks the development of our kingside, even if just temporarily, and it leaves the e4-pawn hanging. }
4... dxe4
{ Black takes the temporarily hanging pawn, which is the best way of meeting our variation. }
5. a3
{ However, now Black is facing a choice: should the bishop move away, keeping the bishop pair but returning the pawn, or take on c3, trying to avoid wasting time? }
5... Bxc3+
{ 5...Be7  6.Nxe4  is another major variation, of course, which we discuss in the game Negi-Giri. }
6. Nxc3
{ Now, Black is facing a choice. If we just get the pawn back, we will have a noticeable advantage due to our bishop pair and extra space in the center. The best move is  6...Nc6  , trying to keep disturbing White's center. However, it might seem as though Black can just protect the pawn, right? }
6... Nf6 7. Bg5
{ Not exactly! The knight is pinned, and it's not possible to hold on to the extra pawn anymore. }
7... h6 8. Bh4
{ White chooses to keep the bishop pair and the pin, which is the more ambitious way of handling the position.   8.Bxf6  Qxf6  9.Nxe4  also leads to a clear advantage. White gives up the bishop pair but keeps the better position due to the superior activity, lead in development @@StartBracket@@caused by Black's queen being forced to keep moving around@@EndBracket@@, and Black's bad bishop on c8. }
8... Nc6
{ Black tries to put pressure on the d4-pawn, but this is an easy concern to address.   8...g5?  Black can, of course, unpin this way, but it's a really bad idea, as it considerably weakens the king.  9.Bg3  ,  it's too unsafe to castle kingside since h2-h4! would tear the kingside apart. However, after something like  9...Nbd7  ,  we are still happily going to play  10.h4!  ,  opening up the h-file and making Black deal with the annoying pin on the h-file!  10...Rg8  11.Qe2+-  and the e4-pawn cannot be defended, so Black will just suffer in an awful position with no place for the king to go, and equal material. }
9. Bb5
{ White develops a piece to a good square, threatening to spoil Black's pawn structure, while also pinning the knight, which stops the threats to the d4-pawn. }
9... Bd7 10. O-O
{ White chooses to keep the tension, continuing development and ignoring the e4-pawn for now.   10.Nxe4  ,  of course, it was also possible to take the pawn back. However, that would require a bit of calculation.  10...g5  Black unpins the f6-knight, threatening to take ours on e4.  11.Nxf6+  Qxf6  12.Bg3  Qxd4??  It seems as though this pawn is hanging, but that's not true!  13.Qxd4  Nxd4  14.Bxd7+  Kxd7  .  Black's pieces carelessly walked onto the d-file and will now die because of the pin.  15.O-O-O  ,  with c2-c3 coming next, Black is losing a knight. }
10... a6 11. Bc4 g5
{ Black dares to unpin the knight at a cost of a horribly weakened kingside. Sure, Black does keep the e4-pawn for the time being, but this is too weakening. }
12. Bg3 Ne7 13. f3
{ Of course, White is immediately opening up the game as much as possible! When you are ahead in development, you need to open the files and diagonals very quickly! Plus, Black cannot even afford to take. }
13... e3
{ Understandably, Black tries to keep the position closed. However, now the e3-pawn is very weak, it's going to get lost in no time. So, why did Black weaken the position if the extra pawn cannot be kept anyway?   13...exf3??  14.Qxf3  ,  Black's knight on f6 is in trouble.  14...Nf5  15.Be5+-  .  With threats like g2-g4, kicking the piece that blocks the f-file away, d4-d5, opening up the position, and the simple Qxb7, taking the free pawn, Black is dead lost. }
14. Ne4
{ White keeps making very active moves, preparing new threats like Be5, taking advantage of the weakened knight on f6 and the loose a1-h8 diagonal. Not a minute of a break for Black!   14.Qd3  was also simple and strong to just win the pawn back. Of course, Black cannot hold on to it with  14...Nf5  as after  15.Be5  ,  the knight is pinned, and there is a huge threat of Ne4. And, of course, White is ready to kick out the f5-knight with g2-g4, getting rid of the defender of the e3-pawn. }
14... Ng6
{ With this move, Black not only protects the f6-knight with the queen but also takes the e5-square under control, preventing the threat of Be5! }
15. Re1 { The e3-pawn is falling, after all. } 15... Bc6 16. Rxe3
{ Now, it turns out White has a new threat. What is it? Well, the black queen is protecting the knight on f6. But it also needs to protect the pawn on c7, which is attacked by our bishop. With too many responsibilities, the black queen is overloaded! }
16... Qe7
{ 16...Nxe4  was a way to avoid losing material but after  17.fxe4±  ,  White achieves a dominant position with the powerful center and the bishop pair. And, on top of Black's other problems, the f-file also opens up! }
17. Nxf6+ Qxf6 18. Bxc7
{ The first and already decisive material gain! White is not only a pawn up but still keeps a dominating position. Black's king is the biggest problem: the center can open with c2-c4 and d4-d5, so keeping it in the center isn't safe. Of course, you cannot castle queenside either. However, kingside castling is also dangerous, as we are about to discover! }
18... Rc8
{ After  18...O-O  ,  it looks as though the king escaped all the dangers, but that's a delusion. The moves ...h7-h6 and ...g7-g5 weakened it tremendously, and White can keep building a slow attack, for example after  19.Be5  Nxe5  20.Rxe5±  .   Next, White can consider playing c2-c3, Bd3-c2, and Qd3, setting up a battery against the king. Additionally, there are always ideas like Rf1 and f3-f4, or h2-h4, opening it up even more. And, of course, White is still a pawn up! But, in all fairness, perhaps this would have been Black's best chance since the alternatives are way worse. }
19. Bd6 { Now, Black won't even be able to castle! } 19... Qd8 20. Bb4
{ White is seriously threatening ideas like d4-d5!, taking advantage of the pin on the e-file, or even Bxe6!, tearing the king's shelter apart. }
20... Nf4
{ Black makes the only move that keeps the position afloat − taking the d5 and e6-squares under control, avoiding the d4-d5 break, and preventing the very immediate disaster.   20...b6??  If Black were to skip a turn and do something silly, the position would be lost right away. For example, because of  21.d5!  Bd7  22.dxe6  Bxe6  23.Bxe6  Qxd1+  24.Rxd1  fxe6  25.Rxe6+  ,  White is winning all the pawns in the world. Of course, if it wasn't the case, White would also keep a decisive attack, even in the endgame, because of ideas like R1d6, Bc3, and so on. The 6th and 7th ranks, as well as the a1-h8 diagonal, are too weak. }
21. Bf1
{ But, of course, the idea of opening up the center doesn't disappear; it is just getting a bit delayed. White is about to play c2-c4! and d4-d5!, tearing it apart just a few moves later. }
21... a5
{ Black is desperate to kick the bishop away in order to acquire the ability to castle kingside. Black would manage to do that, but that won't help. }
22. Be1 O-O 23. c4
{ The problem is that the move ...g7-g5 made the king chronically weak. Therefore, White is about to win by installing the bishop on c3, opening up the long diagonal with d4-d5! and following up with Qd4!, setting up a deadly battery against the black king. }
23... a4 24. Bb4
{ First, White chooses to win a tempo against the rook. This inclusion is valuable because when the rook is no longer on f8, it becomes much harder to play ...f7-f6 at some point, hoping to keep the long diagonal closed at all costs. }
24... Re8 25. Qd2
{ Ivanchuk takes his sweet time. Before going for the d4-d5 break, he improves the rest of the pieces. }
25... Qd7 26. Rae1 Ng6 27. Bc3 { Everything is ready for the pawn break! }
27... b5 28. d5 exd5 29. Qd4
{ Black resigned, as checkmate is unstoppable. Hopefully, this game taught us how dangerous it is to weaken the kingside with ...g7-g5! }
