3. e5
{ Sorry, I couldn't help myself with the exclamation mark. While there are many other interesting variations that White can choose, this one is the most strategically interesting one. You won't ever run out of new ideas to explore, or alternative ways to play. We are closing the center, preventing Black from exchanging the central pawns, and are grabbing a lot of space while doing so.  Here, Black has two main moves:  3...Bf5  , developing the light-squared bishop, which has been the most popular move historically, and  3...c5  , which is an attempt to play the French a tempo down, but without blocking the  bishop on c8.  The  3...c5  line has become very popular in 2010-2015, and its popularity has only been increasing. It leads to more forcing play. }
3... Bf5
{ In this chapter, we'll focus on this move, which seems to be more ideologically aligned with the Caro-Kann. Why am I saying that? Because I think of the Caro as an opening chosen for slow positional play, not for forcing variations. @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp2pppp/2p5/3pP3/3P4/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3...c5  is the other main line, which we investigate in another chapter.   Here, White has a ton of moves. By saying a ton, I mean it: people have been seriously trying  4.h4  ,  4.c4  ,  4.Be3  ,  4.Nd2  ,  4.g4  , and, of course, the main move  4.Nf3  . We'll go for an interesting strategic idea. }
4. c4
{ What is the point of this move, its advantages, and cons?  We are ambitiously fighting for the center and space, placing another pawn in the center. By doing so, we make room for our pieces: for example, now it makes sense to have a knight on c3. Potentially, we can release the tension with cxd5, opening up the c-file when we'd like, or push c4-c5, grabbing a lot of space on the queenside. The most obvious visual downside of this move is that Black can seemingly take ...dxc4, and when that happens, we get a 'hole' on d5 − this central square becomes an outpost for Black's pieces.  
So, how come our move is one of White's most promising weapons in the Advance Variation? Why isn't it a large positional mistake? How poorly do you need to misunderstand chess to voluntarily provide wonderful outposts in the center for your opponents? Actually, there is no problem here, and here is why. To explain this, I'd use Dvoretsky's phrase: 'redundant pieces'.  What did the greatest chess coach of all time mean by that? Well, here's the deal. Imagine you have 3 pieces that want to use this wonderful outpost on d5. But only one piece can be there at a time! So, what are the other two doing? Exactly − nothing! So, the idea is that as long as we keep a lot of pieces on the board, our e5-pawn will provide us a considerable spatial advantage, and Black would be restricted.  Black would be able to place one of the pieces  (likely a knight)  on the d5-square, but the rest of the pieces will be passive. Also, importantly, the d5-outpost, while lovely, isn't threatening to us. The knight just looks good there, but it's not deep enough in our territory for it to be threatening in any way! To summarize, we are fighting for space, and in return are happy to let ONE black piece feel good.   There is a similar line  4.h4  h5  5.c4  , but I chose to not include the h-pawn moves to avoid the sharp @@StartFEN@@rn1qkbnr/pp2pppp/2p5/3pPb2/3P4/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 1 4@@EndFEN@@  4.h4  h6  , which requires a lot more theoretical knowledge. We don't mind strategic complexity, but aren't purposefully looking for sharp play! So, we ditch that.  There are also some  4...h5  lines I do not like.  In general, having pawns on h4 and h5 leads to a slightly different type of play. For example, castling kingside becomes more difficult because the h-pawn may become weak without the support of the rook. }
4... dxc4
{ However, in some games, roughly in 15% of all games that reached this position, Black also chose to immediately release the tension, 'securing' positional gain − the d5-outpost. Of course, by doing so, Black also lets us rapidly get the bishop out, which we are very happy about. In this position, White scores a lovely 56%, which isn't bad at all! }
5. Bxc4
{ By the way, a similar position, most likely, a transposition, would occur after @@StartFEN@@rn1qkbnr/pp2pppp/2p5/3pPb2/2PP4/8/PP3PPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq c3 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...e6  5.Nc3  dxc4  , but I'll also mention that via that exact move order. }
5... e6
{ Of course, Black would always make this move in order to start developing the kingside pieces. And, without a doubt, Black also likes the idea of preventing e5-e6, as well as blocking our light-squared bishop! }
6. Nc3
{ The knight is coming out to the most natural and active square. Our next moves will, most likely, be Nge2 and Ng3, harassing the black light-squared bishop. We would typically prefer to have a knight on e2 and then g3, rather than on f3, and that's for a few reasons. What are they?  The knight is able to jump to e4. It doesn't block the f-pawn, and in fact, can easily support the f2-f4-f5 push. It controls the h5-square, which could be valuable to restrict the black light-squared bishop's mobility and to attack Black's h-pawn if it ever moves to h5. On the other hand, the knight on f3 is blocking the f-pawn. It can also get pinned with ...Bg4, so I'd rather not place it there.    Here, Black can make several moves, but most people, logically enough, chose  6...Nd7  . Black develops a knight, preparing  the ...Nb6-d5 maneuver, which wins a tempo and gets the knight on the outpost on d5.  Some people have also tried  6...Ne7  , which isn't too bad, but it seems a bit premature: why not wait? What if that knight could  go to h6 instead? Or what if Black's dark-squared bishop could come out first? }
6... Nd7
{ Of course,  6...Ne7  7.Nge2  Nd7  results in the same positions as the lines analyzed via @@StartFEN@@rn1qkbnr/pp3ppp/2p1p3/4Pb2/2BP4/2N5/PP3PPP/R1BQK1NR b KQkq - 1 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Nd7  . }
7. Nge2
{ 90% of the players chose to develop the knight here for the reasons we discussed above, and I completely agree with their choice! Ne2-g3, harassing the bishop, is underway. }
7... Nb6
{ Black attacks our bishop, winning a tempo. The knight is ready to jump to d5, or just remain on b6 for now and play ...Ne7-d5, placing another knight on d5. }
8. Bb3
{ We have no choice but to retreat here, as  8.Bd3  would allow Black to swap a pair of pieces. We have a lot of hope for our bishop's future.  We also have more space, so we aren't big fans of trades. And, of course, Black's bishop is supposed to be a target after Ng3, so why trade it off? But, we are happy to keep the bishop on b3, because the aspiration is that after f2-f4-f5, the a2-g8 diagonal will open up, and the bishop would shine like a diamond! }
8... Ne7
{ Black keeps developing. It wasn't obvious what to do with the dark-squared bishop yet, and playing ...Be7 would have gotten the knight stuck on g8. So, Black prepares ...Ned5 and ...Be7, followed by castling. Here, most people castle with White, but I'd like to immediately attack the black bishop. }
9. Ng3
{ 9.O-O  Qd7  10.Nf4!?  is also a very interesting line for White, which some of you might want to investigate as an alternative. The idea is to  meet ...Nd5 by simply capturing it. This way of playing has been pointed out by GM Lars Schandorff in his book Playing the Caro-Kann published by Quality Chess as a reason why he won't recommend that variation for Black.   For example, after  10...h6  11.Be3  Bh7  12.Rc1  Ned5  13.Ncxd5  Nxd5  14.Nxd5  exd5  , White achieved a much more active position and won a convincing game in Morozevich-Sasikiran, Moscow 2001. }
9... Bg6
{ Of course, Black has no desire to let us capture it, especially because Black wants to play ...Ned5. In that case, after Nxf5, Black would have to take with the pawn, which would double the pawns and open the position for our bishop pair. Of course, Black could also wait and not touch the e7-knight yet with the idea to recapture on f5 with the knight. But in that case, the knight would stay on e7, blocking the development of the kingside! }
10. h4
{ Only 18 games have been played like this so far − about 20% of the games that reached this position. However, it started catching up in popularity as of late and was recently chosen by MVL. Instead of rushing to castle, we are hoping to provoke Black to weaken the position on the kingside!  At this point, the opponent has to decide whether to play ...h7-h5 or ...h7-h6. Here are my thoughts on both: ...h7-h5 is good because it stops our h-pawn from advancing, thus preventing us from grabbing even more space on the kingside. At the same time, ...h7-h5 is bad because that pawn becomes an easy target. Essentially, as long as we have a knight and a queen on their current positions, Black won't be ever able to castle short without hanging their h-pawn! Also, ... h7-h5 is bad because it weakens the g5-square.   ...h7-h6 is good because it doesn't create a pawn target, but ...h7-h6 is bad because it enables us to grab even more space on the kingside. However, it seems universal conclusion among the Black players that  10...h6  is a better move. At least, it's been chosen in 13 games, versus  10...h5  , which has been only played 5 times. }
10... h5 { Now, this pawn is a real target! } 11. Bg5
{ Another perk of provoking ...h7-h5 is that the g5-square becomes really weak. It's very easy to plant a piece there without ever worrying that Black would kick it out with ...h7-h6! Now, Black has a problem unraveling the kingside and has to move the queen. }
11... Qd7 12. O-O
{ We keep developing. Now, we have a couple of ideas, here they are:  Play Bc2, trading off the light-squared bishops. Sure enough, we aren't interested in trades overall, but now that Black had played ...h7-h5, their h5-pawn has become weak, which means after the bishop trade, it might simply get lost.  Play a2-a4, trying to grab space on the queenside. Provoke ... a7-a5 and then install the knight on e4 and c5! Of course, we could also install the knight there without including the a-pawn moves, but making Black move the a-pawn weakens the queenside.  Just keep improving the position with a2-a3 to prevent ...Bb4, then Qd2, then Rad1, and see what Black is up to.  Consider Nce2-f4, increasing pressure on the g6-bishop. As we see, Black has a lot of ideas to reckon with, and no active play yet! }
12... Nf5
{ Everyone has overwhelmingly preferred this move, which trades a pair of knights and somewhat alleviates two issues: Black's lack of space, and our ability to put pressure on the h5-pawn. }
13. Nxf5 Bxf5 14. Qd2
{ We just keep developing. With our last move, we've connected the rooks. }
14... Be7
{ Of course, it doesn't look as though Black can come up with any other developing move. Placing the bishop on b4 would be silly, as ...Bxc3 would only improve our structure and take away the d5-square as an outpost from Black after we play bxc3. }
15. Rad1
{ We keep centralizing the pieces. Our last move is an example of combining development with prophylaxis: if Black ever captures on g5, we can take with the queen without leaving the d4-pawn hanging!   This position has been reached in three games so far, and Black tried three moves:  15...f6  ,  15...O-O-O  and  15...Bxg5  . It does not look to me as though we need to spend a lot of time memorizing things in this position, which can be explained by words and logic, but let's see a few more lines. }
15... O-O { No one has tried this move, and rightly so. } 16. Qe2
{ A large problem with the h5-pawn arises. } 16... Bxg5 17. hxg5 Bg6
{ This doesn't get the bishop trapped, but enables a very powerful attack. }
18. g4 hxg4 19. Qxg4
{ Next, we'll proceed with Kg2, Qh4, Rh1, and checkmate on h8! } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "14) Caro-Kann 3.e5 Bf5"]
[Black "Caro-Kann 3.e5 Bf5 4.c4 dxc4 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6
{ This move, followed by  2.--  d5  , defines the Caro-Kann Defense − one of the most solid openings for Black out there. Black is preparing to fight for the  center with ...d7-d5, just like in the French Defense. So, these two openings are sort of siblings, if you would like a bit of a figure of speech.  The main difference is that in the French, Black blocks the light-squared bishop, but gets to attack White's center with ...c7-c5 in one move − rather fast! On the other hand, in the Caro, Black cannot attack the center nearly as fast, since ...c7-c6, followed by ...c7-c5, would cost an extra tempo. But on the bright side, Black doesn't block the light-squared bishop! So, the Caro-Kann players want a solid game without a typical bad bishop. They hope to develop it or trade it off and then still eventually undermine the center with ...c6-c5, hoping the tempo won't make much of a difference. }
2. d4
{ This, of course, is White's most ambitious move.  2.Nf3  d5  3.d3!?  is another variation, which is a recent discovery − it's been actively played at the top level only since 2018. It's one of my all-time favorites, and I had written about it in the past.  Unfortunately, even though it would have been a good fit for this course, and I know many people were hoping I'd cover exactly this variation, I decided to go for something else, and that's for a few reasons.   The theory isn't changing very fast in this Nf3-d3 system, so I didn't feel as though I had a lot of new ideas to offer.  In the main system, the Advance Variation, which is what I'm recommending, the game is much more complex. I thought we'd get a nice mix of the ability to discover more about interesting strategic chess and a relatively simple line to learn too!    3...dxe4  4.dxe4  Qxd1+  5.Kxd1  . If you like endgames, and variations that don't require much theory, make sure to pay attention to this one as well! }
2... d5
{ Black follows up in the most logical way, fighting for the center with the d-pawn. Now, we arrive at massive crossroads. In the second part of the 20th century, everyone used to play  3.Nd2  or  3.Nc3  − these two moves are just a transposition. No one used to believe  3.e5  was dangerous.  However, nowadays, the opinion most players hold is exactly the opposite:  3.Nd2  and  3.Nc3  have been neutralized in numerous ways, while  3.e5  is known to offer the most interesting complex play! }
3. e5
{ Sorry, I couldn't help myself with the exclamation mark. While there are many other interesting variations that White can choose, this one is the most strategically interesting one. You won't ever run out of new ideas to explore, or alternative ways to play. We are closing the center, preventing Black from exchanging the central pawns, and are grabbing a lot of space while doing so.  Here, Black has two main moves:  3...Bf5  , developing the light-squared bishop, which has been the most popular move historically, and  3...c5  , which is an attempt to play the French a tempo down, but without blocking the  bishop on c8.  The  3...c5  line has become very popular in 2010-2015, and its popularity has only been increasing. It leads to more forcing play. }
