{ This is the move Black overwhelmingly chooses, reinforcing the d5-pawn and starting to prepare kingside development − now the bishop can come out, the knight gets the e7-square, and so on. }
5. Nc3 Bb4
{ This move has been played in about 200 games  (roughly 13% of all games played in this position)  , but it's been suggested in one of my favorite Chessable courses that weren't written by myself. :@@EndBracket@@ That course, of course, is Erwin L'Ami's LTR on the Caro-Kann from Black's perspective. Here is what he says about the move: 'I like this move, preparing for smooth development with ...Ne7 and ...O-O.' }
6. cxd5
{ This is more promising than  6.Qb3  ,  which is covered in a separate Informational. We are immediately releasing the tension, hoping to prove the bishop is somewhat misplaced on b4. }
6... Qxd5
{ Technically speaking, taking with the queen is possible. It was even played by the ever-creative Russian GM Fedoseev versus Carlsen! But, it's hard to see the merits of this move. }
7. Ne2
{ Next, White will just go a2-a3, winning a tempo or getting the bishop pair. }
7... Qd8
{ Black essentially forced a typical structure of these @@StartFEN@@rn1qkbnr/pp2pppp/2p5/3pPb2/3P4/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 1 4@@EndFEN@@  4.c4  lines,  where Black has an outpost on d5, but no space and a passive position. }
8. a3 { First, White unpinned. } 8... Ba5 9. Ng3
{ Then White won a tempo by attacking the bishop. As we know, the knight is placed perfectly on that square, as it helps prepare the f2-f4-f5 play. }
9... Ne7 10. Bc4 { White keeps developing. } 10... Bg6 11. h4
{ White got a standard initiative on the kingside and then convincingly won. We study this type of position in great detail in the @@StartFEN@@rn1qkbnr/pp2pppp/2p5/3pPb2/2PP4/8/PP3PPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq c3 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...dxc4  variations, please look at them for more explanations on why White is doing so well here!  1-0 Carlsen-Fedoseev, Krasnaya Polyana 2021. }
*

