{ This is Black's second most popular move. It is fairly natural, isn't it? Black is just developing a knight, for now, keeping the tension in the center alive. However, even though a number of very strong GMs, such as Esipenko, Kobalia, and many others have used this move order, I believe it is suspicious and hardly correct!  Why would I make such a claim? See, this move creates a problem, which is more typical of openings like the Slav or London: often, one side can open up the c-file @@StartBracket@@in this case, we can do that by playing cxd5@@EndBracket@@, but doesn't want to, because doing so surrenders the spatial advantage @@StartBracket@@our pawn on c4 is more useful than the Black one on c6@@EndBracket@@.  However, the idea of opening up that file becomes A LOT more tempting after ...Nd7, because now the Black knight cannot go to c6 anymore to block it! Of course, Black could try to play ...Ne7-c6, but in that case, the knight on d7 would be extremely passive. It seems to me that this variation's popularity has been declining, and that is exactly because of the c-file opening up fast, and only in White's favor. }
6. cxd5 { We are very glad to be able to immediately open up the c-file! } 6...
cxd5 7. h4
{ We are threatening to trap the black bishop with g2-g4 and h4-h5, of course. }
7... h5
{ This is too much, as it creates a weak pawn on h5 and a weak square on g5. }
8. Bd3
{ Another downside of ...h7-h5 is that Black cannot react to this move with ...Bg6. Black is forced to trade! }
8... Bxd3 9. Qxd3 Ne7 10. Bg5
{ Now, Black's kingside is rather stuck. The Black players always tried counterattacking our queenside here. }
10... Qb6 { But that can be easily ignored. } 11. Nf3
{ Taking on b2 only helps us activate even more pieces and open even more files by means of Rb1-Rxb7. }
11... Nc6
{ Black should try to unblock the kingside pieces, preparing to develop the dark-squared bishop. But, I am afraid, Black won't be ever able to safely castle, as Ne2-f4/g3 would cause a lot of damage to the h5-pawn. For example, if we play Ne2-f4, and Black responds with ...g7-g6, we would likely crush the kingside with a knight sacrifice on g6! }
12. O-O Be7
{ Another downside of offering this bishop trade is that the d6-square becomes weak, making the ideas of Nb5-d6 a lot more appealing. }
13. Rac1
{ For now, we keep improving the pieces. If Black takes on g5, the standard idea of hxg5!, which we've seen in another line of this chapter, would be very powerful. The point is to meet kingside castling with a well-timed g2-g4, Kg2, Rh1, and Qe3-f4-h4, with a decisive mating attack. And, of course, to restrict Black's kingside even more. }
13... a6 { Black must prevent the Nb5-d6 idea for good. } 14. Ne2
{ With Nf4 coming on the next turn, Black is in a very rough shape. Castling kingside is not possible, as the h5-pawn would fall. But without a castle, then how would the rooks come into the game? At some point, we can proceed with Bxe7 and then Ng5, followed by f2-f4-f5, looking to open up the f-file. Poor Black! How to deal with all that? I have no idea. }
*

