{ This is Black's second most popular move. It is fairly natural, isn't it? Black is just developing a knight, for now, keeping the tension in the center alive. However, even though a number of very strong GMs, such as Esipenko, Kobalia, and many others have used this move order, I believe it is suspicious and hardly correct!  Why would I make such a claim? See, this move creates a problem, which is more typical of openings like the Slav or London: often, one side can open up the c-file @@StartBracket@@in this case, we can do that by playing cxd5@@EndBracket@@, but doesn't want to, because doing so surrenders the spatial advantage @@StartBracket@@our pawn on c4 is more useful than the Black one on c6@@EndBracket@@.  However, the idea of opening up that file becomes A LOT more tempting after ...Nd7, because now the Black knight cannot go to c6 anymore to block it! Of course, Black could try to play ...Ne7-c6, but in that case, the knight on d7 would be extremely passive. It seems to me that this variation's popularity has been declining, and that is exactly because of the c-file opening up fast, and only in White's favor. }
6. cxd5 { We are very glad to be able to immediately open up the c-file! } 6...
cxd5 7. h4
{ We are threatening to trap the black bishop with g2-g4 and h4-h5, of course. }
7... h6
{ Black must make room for this bishop exactly this way since  7...h5?  would weaken the kingside too much. }
8. g4
{ But now, we can grab even more space, while also continuing to win time! }
8... Bh7 9. Bd3
{ Now, we force Black to trade and help us develop the queen, which wins another tempo. }
9... Bxd3 10. Qxd3
{ Black's main problem is that it seems very difficult to find good squares for all the pieces. A few setups that come to mind include ...Bb4 and ...Ne7, or ...Ne7-c6 followed by ...Be7. It's also not obvious if it's safe to castle kingside. Logically, you'd think it shouldn't be! }
10... h5
{ This is the move that was chosen in the only game that reached this position so far. Black undermines our pawn structure, getting an outpost on f5 no matter what we do next, as our g-pawn has to move or take. For some reason, White didn't capture. But, this move seems most logical to me, that's what I would be recommending. }
11. gxh5
{ It might seem as though we ruin our pawn structure, but there is nothing to worry about. Those of you who have a wide range of opening interests might have seen this idea elsewhere − for example, in the Bayonet Attack of the King's Indian, where White plays bxa5 and then goes a4-a5, restricting Black's queenside.  Here, we plan on installing the bishop on g5, then playing Nf3, Nce2, Nf4, and h4-h5, grabbing a ton of space on the kingside. Alternatively, of course, we could also achieve that with Nge2-g3, and then h4-h5. }
11... Rxh5 12. Nf3
{ Now, Black needs to figure out how to develop the kingside pieces. If you play ...Be7, the knight on g8 feels very unhappy. But after ...Ne7, so does the Black bishop. And, of course, another problem is that Black had already conceded castling rights. I mean, Black can still castle queenside, but that's not something that is ever done in these positions. }
12... Ne7
{ This is a brand-new position, so it's not possible to analyze every single move, but we'll look at this one: Black is trying to take advantage of the outpost on f5 that has just been created with this cheeky ...h6-h5 move. }
13. Bg5
{ We pin the knight and prevent Black's kingside from coming out. Also, the rook is completely out of business on h5. Why is it there?! }
13... Qb6
{ To unpin, Black can make this typical move and sets eyesight on the b2-pawn. But, we don't care: Black wouldn't ever want to capture it, as then Rb1-Rxb7 would tremendously activate our rook and help us − the side with the better coordination and development. }
14. Ne2
{ We continue with the plan of preparing Nf4 and h4-h5. Of course, we can also always choose to castle kingside: despite the lacking g-pawn, our king is super safe, since we have way more pieces on the kingside. Let's make a few more logical moves to see how the game can go. }
14... Nf5 { Black prepares ...Be7 and activates the knight. } 15. Ng3
{ We force the knight trade, which fixes our pawn structure, enables us to play g3-g4 whenever we want, and opens the f-file. }
15... Bb4+
{ Black can develop with a tempo and deprive us of castling rights, but we don't care. }
16. Kf1 Nxg3+ 17. fxg3
{ Next, we'll go Kg2 and start thinking how to invade on the open c-file and the semi-open f-file. The rook on h5 is absolutely out of play. The black king is in an awkward situation. It seems that Black is just lost because of all these factors: lack of development, coordination, the pieces being all over the place not doing anything useful, and our pieces having so many promising options. }
*

