4. c4
{ What is the point of this move, its advantages, and cons?  We are ambitiously fighting for the center and space, placing another pawn in the center. By doing so, we make room for our pieces: for example, now it makes sense to have a knight on c3. Potentially, we can release the tension with cxd5, opening up the c-file when we'd like, or push c4-c5, grabbing a lot of space on the queenside. The most obvious visual downside of this move is that Black can seemingly take ...dxc4, and when that happens, we get a 'hole' on d5 − this central square becomes an outpost for Black's pieces.  
So, how come our move is one of White's most promising weapons in the Advance Variation? Why isn't it a large positional mistake? How poorly do you need to misunderstand chess to voluntarily provide wonderful outposts in the center for your opponents? Actually, there is no problem here, and here is why. To explain this, I'd use Dvoretsky's phrase: 'redundant pieces'.  What did the greatest chess coach of all time mean by that? Well, here's the deal. Imagine you have 3 pieces that want to use this wonderful outpost on d5. But only one piece can be there at a time! So, what are the other two doing? Exactly − nothing! So, the idea is that as long as we keep a lot of pieces on the board, our e5-pawn will provide us a considerable spatial advantage, and Black would be restricted.  Black would be able to place one of the pieces  (likely a knight)  on the d5-square, but the rest of the pieces will be passive. Also, importantly, the d5-outpost, while lovely, isn't threatening to us. The knight just looks good there, but it's not deep enough in our territory for it to be threatening in any way! To summarize, we are fighting for space, and in return are happy to let ONE black piece feel good.   There is a similar line  4.h4  h5  5.c4  , but I chose to not include the h-pawn moves to avoid the sharp @@StartFEN@@rn1qkbnr/pp2pppp/2p5/3pPb2/3P4/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 1 4@@EndFEN@@  4.h4  h6  , which requires a lot more theoretical knowledge. We don't mind strategic complexity, but aren't purposefully looking for sharp play! So, we ditch that.  There are also some  4...h5  lines I do not like.  In general, having pawns on h4 and h5 leads to a slightly different type of play. For example, castling kingside becomes more difficult because the h-pawn may become weak without the support of the rook. }
4... e6
{ This is the move Black overwhelmingly chooses, reinforcing the d5-pawn and starting to prepare kingside development − now the bishop can come out, the knight gets the e7-square, and so on. }
5. Nc3 Ne7
{ This is Black's very main move, keeping the tension in the center while also developing a knight to the most logical square. Keeping the b8-knight in its current position is also important to not run into cxd5 at a bad time @@StartBracket@@as the line 5...Nd7 demonstrates@@EndBracket@@. }
6. Nge2
{ One of the very main lines. White wants to bring the knight to g3 and pursue the typical plan of harassing the bishop with h2-h4-h5, and so on. However, I won't be recommending this variation, and this is for a particular reason. But, if you don't mind trying the arising positions, feel free to consider this an interesting alternative!   6.Nf3  is also popular, but I don't like this move, primarily because  Black can pin the knight with ...Bg4 at any moment.   6.a3  is the main line. White is waiting, keeping the tension in the center.  This move has a few potential benefits:  It cuts out all the ...Bb4-related ideas. It potentially prepares c4-c5, followed by b2-b4 − a plan related to the attempt of grabbing infinite amounts of space on the kingside. However, I don't really like the extremely closed nature of these positions.    For example, after  6...Nd7  7.c5  Bg6  8.f4  Nf5  9.Nf3  Bh5  10.Be2  Be7  , Black achieved very good control of the light squares and comfortably finished development. Soon enough, after White got careless for a moment, the center suddenly collapsed. This is not a terrible way of playing, I just dislike it! 0-1 Luther-Hera, Triesen 2007. }
6... dxc4
{ Black can also keep the tension with  6...Nd7  , but I am only concerned about this move. Black is capturing the unprotected pawn, potentially hoping to hold on to it! }
7. Ng3
{ We attack the bishop, hoping it retreats because in that case, we'll be able to capture the c4-pawn and get the exact position that we analyze via the move order @@StartFEN@@rn1qkbnr/pp2pppp/2p5/3pPb2/2PP4/8/PP3PPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq c3 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...dxc4  5.Bxc4  e6  . We couldn't be happier in any other line! This is, actually, what most Black players went for! However, you shouldn't count on that, as Black has a better idea. }
7... b5 { Black isn't letting us have the pawn back. } 8. a4
{ We undermine the pawn structure on the queenside. } 8... b4
{ Black cannot sustain that pawn chain, so the b-pawn must move forward. Now, the c4-pawn looks weak, but our knight is hanging. }
9. Nce4
{ We are threatening to play Nd6+. Of course, that knight invasion would be absolutely devastating and the pawn on c4 is hanging. So, Black's reaction is fairly straightforward and forced. }
9... Bxe4 10. Nxe4
{ Again, we are threatening the same things: invading on d6 with the knight and taking back the c4-pawn. There is only one reasonable move the opponent can try. }
10... Nf5 { The issue is that now our d4-pawn is also under attack! } 11. Bxc4
{ If we were to play this line, the only logical move, to my mind, would be this pawn sacrifice. We are letting Black have our d4-pawn!   11.Be3  has been tried twice by one of the strongest Greek players, GM Mastrovasilis. However, I don't really fancy the position after  11...Qd5  since we'll have to keep wasting time moving our pieces around, and Black seems to enjoy a fairly comfortable development. ½–½ Mastrovasilis-Svetushkin, Subotica 2008. }
11... Qxd4
{ Black is forcing a queen trade, as the queen is attacking two of our pieces and the e5-pawn. }
12. Qxd4 Nxd4
{ Now, Black is threatening with a fork on c2, so we need to react. } 13. O-O
{ In this position, if White had a bit more time, there could have tremendous compensation for the missing pawn. What makes us excited about this position?  Many of the Black pawns, for example, the ones on b4 and c6, are really weak. Black has a lot of weak squares, such as c4, c5, and d6. We are ahead in development. Given enough time, we'd get the bishop out to e3, the rooks to the semi-open c and d-files, and it seems we should be able to generate quite a lot of pressure, and likely win some of the pawns back.  
However, somehow we are not on time. Black keeps gaining time by attacking the e5-pawn and by offering trades! }
13... Nd7 { Now, the e5-pawn is hanging. } 14. Rd1
{ We get the rook in the game with a tempo, making the knight leave. } 14...
Nf5
{ This is a fairly interesting position to analyze. The problem is that we don't want to ever play f2-f4, as that would kill our dark-squared bishop, while also weakening the g1-a7 diagonal, allowing for ideas like Bc5+, then maybe some of Black's pieces could invade on e3, and so on.  If you're interested, you can analyze this position deeper, searching for some initiative. But, I feel this is not the most interesting direction. Plus, it's a bit too forcing. }
*

