6. h3
{ In a position with nearly 600 games after 5 moves, I'd like to recommend a very rare idea, which has been only seen in 15 games so far. But, two of them have been recently played by Carlsen. He convincingly beat Firouzja and MVL! The idea is very simple. We'll try to play Nf3 on the next turn, but won't ever allow Black to pin the knight with ...Bg4 and trade down this way! }
6... Nd7 { Most Black players just chose to keep the tension. Fair enough! } 7.
Nf3
{ Now, I don't mind placing the knight here: the idea of ...Bg4 is no longer there! }
7... Bg6
{ This is also possible − Firouzja chose this move versus Magnus in order to keep the tension and at some point prepare ...Nf5. However, our response is both typical and strong. }
8. cxd5
{ As we discuss throughout the chapter − say, after @@StartFEN@@rn1qkbnr/pp3ppp/2p1p3/3pPb2/2PP4/2N5/PP3PPP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq - 1 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Nd7  , or after @@StartFEN@@r2qkb1r/pp1nnppp/2p1p3/3pPb2/2PP4/2N2N1P/PP3PP1/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 2 7@@EndFEN@@  7...h6  in this variation, this move is often a tempting idea when Black's knight is  already on d7, and this is because opening up the c-file with the knight there is great for us − that piece should be on c6! }
8... Nxd5 9. Bd3
{ We enjoy the standard spatial advantage. Please see more explanations of this type of position in the 7...h6 variations! }
