4... e6
{ This is the move Black overwhelmingly chooses, reinforcing the d5-pawn and starting to prepare kingside development − now the bishop can come out, the knight gets the e7-square, and so on. }
5. Nc3 Ne7
{ This is Black's very main move, keeping the tension in the center while also developing a knight to the most logical square. Keeping the b8-knight in its current position is also important to not run into cxd5 at a bad time @@StartBracket@@as the line 5...Nd7 demonstrates@@EndBracket@@. }
6. h3
{ In a position with nearly 600 games after 5 moves, I'd like to recommend a very rare idea, which has been only seen in 15 games so far. But, two of them have been recently played by Carlsen. He convincingly beat Firouzja and MVL! The idea is very simple. We'll try to play Nf3 on the next turn, but won't ever allow Black to pin the knight with ...Bg4 and trade down this way! }
6... c5
{ Given that the move h2-h3 doesn't seem to contribute much to our ability to control the center, it's not a surprise Black can consider blowing up our center right away. That's a typical Caro-Kann idea for Black anyway, so why not do it right now, when we still cannot control the center that well with our pieces? Fair enough! }
7. Nf3
{ We protect the d4-pawn, creating a threat of capturing the pawn with dxc5 on the next turn since the very annoying ...d5-d4 push has been successfully prevented.   7.dxc5?  won't be a good idea, as after  7...d4  , Black ends up winning a ton of time and space. Crucially, we cannot benefit from the tempting-looking  8.Nb5  Nec6  9.Nd6+?  since after  9...Bxd6  10.exd6  Nb4!-+  , it's not obvious how to stop  big trouble related to the c2-square. I would assure you right away − it simply isn't possible to do so, which means we are already dead lost. Not a good start! }
7... dxc4
{ Black can also choose to start releasing tension in the center right away. We don't mind that at all − it only helps our pieces get more active even faster. }
8. Bxc4
{ It seems as though Black needs to worry about quite a few ideas here: dxc5 is always worth keeping an eye on, but it would be even better for White to capture that pawn if Black couldn't take on d1 and make us take back in some awkward manner.  So, For example, after we castle kingside, dxc5 might become a huge threat, since the queen trade would only help us activate our rook. Also, there could be ideas like Qb3!, winning a tempo by attacking the loose b7-pawn, and then dxc5. And, of course, the ever-annoying Nb5-d6 is something Black always needs to be on the lookout for. }
8... a6
{ That's why it seems very natural for our opponent to take the b5-square under control once and for good. Possibly, ...b7-b5 can be played at some point, but most importantly, Black is preventing all the Nb5 and Bb5-related ideas. }
9. O-O
{ Now that we've castled, we are ready to capture on c5 and then try to hold on to that extra pawn. }
9... cxd4
{ It seems very logical for Black to capture. Why so, would you ask? Shouldn't be a problem to open up the center, given that development isn't exactly very impressive at the moment? Well, the issue is that Black always had to reckon with two dangerous ideas:  Taking on c5, and then holding on to the pawn. Playing d4-d5! when appropriate, opening up the center very rapidly. By exchanging, Black eliminates both.    9...b5?  Playing this way is a really bad idea, I won't even make this a trainable variation. What's the problem? Black is developed very poorly, and it's not easy to rapidly finish the kingside development,  as the e7-knight is blocking all the pieces. That's why advancing aggressively isn't ambitious, it's only over-optimistic and creates targets for us to attack!    10.Be2  c4  , Black needs to avoid  the dxc5 threat.  11.a4!  It's very appropriate to attack the weaknesses right away!  11...b4  12.Na2!+-  . At this point, it becomes obvious that the  threats of Nxb4 and Bxc4 cannot be prevented properly.  For example,  12...b3  13.Nc3  Qc7  is well met by  14.d5  when Black is just lost. }
10. Ne2
{ I really like this move, because the knight wasn't doing much on c3. So, why don't we use this piece to recapture the pawn? }
10... Nbc6
{ Black isn't able to hold on to the pawn but is hoping that taking it back will at least enable the trade of a pair of knights. Fewer pieces = less of an initiative for White, and less spatial issues for the opponent.   10...d3?  won't save the pawn, of course. After  11.Ned4  , we win a tempo by attacking the bishop and just recapture it a move later.  11...Bg6  12.Bxd3  , with a similar type of position, except Black lost time moving the bishop back, and helped us activate the knight faster. }
11. Nexd4
{ The good news for us is that by taking back, we are also attacking the bishop on f5, making Black waste another tempo to preserve it − no matter if right now or on the next turn. }
11... Nxd4
{ 11...Be4  would result in a very similar position, for example after  12.Be3  ,  with Qe2, Rfd1, and Rac1 coming up next. }
12. Nxd4
{ Black has many reasons to move the bishop right now.  Of course, the most obvious one is that Black would like to preserve the bishop pair, if possible. Another major one might be less obvious, but still very important: taking on f5 now is kind of acceptable for Black, as taking back with the knight is possible, keeping the pawn structure intact.  
However, what if we wait for the black knight to move, and capture later? Then Black would need to spoil the structure! And if Black doesn't move the knight, developing the kingside pieces becomes problematic! }
12... Be4 13. Be3
{ We just keep developing. Next, we'll activate the queen and the rooks, for example by means of Qe2, Rac1, and Rfd1, starting to set up some x-rays, such as on the d-file versus the black queen. }
13... Nc6 { A fairly natural, but a very bad move. } 14. Qg4
{ Black is completely lost, all of a sudden. If the bishop goes to g6, we capture the knight and ruin the pawn structure. But if it doesn't, our queen is placed incredibly well on g4, because it prevents Black from ever developing the f8-bishop since doing that would leave the g7-pawn hanging! With two central files being open, Black won't survive with the king stuck in the center. }
14... Bd5 15. Bxd5 Qxd5
{ Wasting time moving the queen around is a must if Black is hell-bent on keeping the pawn structure intact. }
16. Nxc6 Qxc6 { More time wasted. } 17. Rac1 Qd7 { And more. } 18. Rfd1
{ And more! Next, we'll play Rc7, at which point it's obvious the game is over. How is Black's development looking here? This is a rhetorical question, of course. :@@EndBracket@@ }
