8. Bxc4
{ It seems as though Black needs to worry about quite a few ideas here: dxc5 is always worth keeping an eye on, but it would be even better for White to capture that pawn if Black couldn't take on d1 and make us take back in some awkward manner.  So, For example, after we castle kingside, dxc5 might become a huge threat, since the queen trade would only help us activate our rook. Also, there could be ideas like Qb3!, winning a tempo by attacking the loose b7-pawn, and then dxc5. And, of course, the ever-annoying Nb5-d6 is something Black always needs to be on the lookout for. }
8... a6
{ That's why it seems very natural for our opponent to take the b5-square under control once and for good. Possibly, ...b7-b5 can be played at some point, but most importantly, Black is preventing all the Nb5 and Bb5-related ideas. }
9. O-O
{ Now that we've castled, we are ready to capture on c5 and then try to hold on to that extra pawn. }
9... cxd4
{ It seems very logical for Black to capture. Why so, would you ask? Shouldn't be a problem to open up the center, given that development isn't exactly very impressive at the moment? Well, the issue is that Black always had to reckon with two dangerous ideas:  Taking on c5, and then holding on to the pawn. Playing d4-d5! when appropriate, opening up the center very rapidly. By exchanging, Black eliminates both.    9...b5?  Playing this way is a really bad idea, I won't even make this a trainable variation. What's the problem? Black is developed very poorly, and it's not easy to rapidly finish the kingside development,  as the e7-knight is blocking all the pieces. That's why advancing aggressively isn't ambitious, it's only over-optimistic and creates targets for us to attack!    10.Be2  c4  , Black needs to avoid  the dxc5 threat.  11.a4!  It's very appropriate to attack the weaknesses right away!  11...b4  12.Na2!+-  . At this point, it becomes obvious that the  threats of Nxb4 and Bxc4 cannot be prevented properly.  For example,  12...b3  13.Nc3  Qc7  is well met by  14.d5  when Black is just lost. }
10. Ne2
{ I really like this move, because the knight wasn't doing much on c3. So, why don't we use this piece to recapture the pawn? }
10... Nbc6
{ Black isn't able to hold on to the pawn but is hoping that taking it back will at least enable the trade of a pair of knights. Fewer pieces = less of an initiative for White, and less spatial issues for the opponent.   10...d3?  won't save the pawn, of course. After  11.Ned4  , we win a tempo by attacking the bishop and just recapture it a move later.  11...Bg6  12.Bxd3  , with a similar type of position, except Black lost time moving the bishop back, and helped us activate the knight faster. }
11. Nexd4
{ The good news for us is that by taking back, we are also attacking the bishop on f5, making Black waste another tempo to preserve it − no matter if right now or on the next turn. }
11... Nxd4
{ 11...Be4  would result in a very similar position, for example after  12.Be3  ,  with Qe2, Rfd1, and Rac1 coming up next. }
12. Nxd4
{ Black has many reasons to move the bishop right now.  Of course, the most obvious one is that Black would like to preserve the bishop pair, if possible. Another major one might be less obvious, but still very important: taking on f5 now is kind of acceptable for Black, as taking back with the knight is possible, keeping the pawn structure intact.  
However, what if we wait for the black knight to move, and capture later? Then Black would need to spoil the structure! And if Black doesn't move the knight, developing the kingside pieces becomes problematic! }
12... Be4 13. Be3
{ We just keep developing. Next, we'll activate the queen and the rooks, for example by means of Qe2, Rac1, and Rfd1, starting to set up some x-rays, such as on the d-file versus the black queen. }
13... Bd5
{ Black needs to offer more trades, as space is a luxury. And, as the line with  13...Nc6  shows, it's not easy to finish development by conventional means! }
14. Rc1
{ We don't even mind trades that much. But, we want them to happen on our terms: each trade should help us activate more pieces! }
14... Bxc4 15. Rxc4
{ Now, the rook is incredibly active. We'd like to move the queen somewhere. In fact, there are many attractive spots to choose from, such as g4, f3, b3, maybe a4, and then get the last rook in the game. The idea of placing it on d1, setting up an x-ray versus the black queen, looks great to me, as well as the idea of going Rfc1, preparing to double up on the c-file. }
15... Nd5
{ Black absolutely needs to urgently get the king castled. Of course, blocking the d-file, which could cause Black lots of trouble, while also installing his knight on a great outpost, seems like a good way of accomplishing this objective. }
16. Qg4
{ But, the position still remains very difficult for Black. Why so?  Black cannot develop the bishop, as the g7-pawn would end up hanging.  Solving that problem with ...g7-g6 sounds scary. For example, ...Be7 after ...g7-g6 could be answered with Bh6, preventing castling anyway.  Black already needs to be on the lookout for forcing solutions on our end, such as a knight sacrifice on e6, or the f2-f4-f5 play. Black is not developed, so sacrifices could be a fast and correct way to a convincing victory.  Even if Black does manage to castle, we'd still be better because of the spatial advantage and our control of the c-file.  Another attacking idea could be playing Ne2, moving the queen, and then bringing the c4-rook to g4 or h4!  
And, of course, we are not afraid of Black capturing on e3, since doing so would open up the f-file for our f1-rook, while also depriving the opponent of the only developed piece. That's another way to easily understand why Black is in so much trouble: there is only ONE@@StartBracket@@!@@EndBracket@@ piece in the game 15 moves after it started! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "14) Caro-Kann 3.e5 Bf5"]
[Black "Caro-Kann 5.Nc3 Ne7 6.h3 c5 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6
{ This move, followed by  2.--  d5  , defines the Caro-Kann Defense − one of the most solid openings for Black out there. Black is preparing to fight for the  center with ...d7-d5, just like in the French Defense. So, these two openings are sort of siblings, if you would like a bit of a figure of speech.  The main difference is that in the French, Black blocks the light-squared bishop, but gets to attack White's center with ...c7-c5 in one move − rather fast! On the other hand, in the Caro, Black cannot attack the center nearly as fast, since ...c7-c6, followed by ...c7-c5, would cost an extra tempo. But on the bright side, Black doesn't block the light-squared bishop! So, the Caro-Kann players want a solid game without a typical bad bishop. They hope to develop it or trade it off and then still eventually undermine the center with ...c6-c5, hoping the tempo won't make much of a difference. }
2. d4
{ This, of course, is White's most ambitious move.  2.Nf3  d5  3.d3!?  is another variation, which is a recent discovery − it's been actively played at the top level only since 2018. It's one of my all-time favorites, and I had written about it in the past.  Unfortunately, even though it would have been a good fit for this course, and I know many people were hoping I'd cover exactly this variation, I decided to go for something else, and that's for a few reasons.   The theory isn't changing very fast in this Nf3-d3 system, so I didn't feel as though I had a lot of new ideas to offer.  In the main system, the Advance Variation, which is what I'm recommending, the game is much more complex. I thought we'd get a nice mix of the ability to discover more about interesting strategic chess and a relatively simple line to learn too!    3...dxe4  4.dxe4  Qxd1+  5.Kxd1  . If you like endgames, and variations that don't require much theory, make sure to pay attention to this one as well! }
2... d5
{ Black follows up in the most logical way, fighting for the center with the d-pawn. Now, we arrive at massive crossroads. In the second part of the 20th century, everyone used to play  3.Nd2  or  3.Nc3  − these two moves are just a transposition. No one used to believe  3.e5  was dangerous.  However, nowadays, the opinion most players hold is exactly the opposite:  3.Nd2  and  3.Nc3  have been neutralized in numerous ways, while  3.e5  is known to offer the most interesting complex play! }
3. e5
{ Sorry, I couldn't help myself with the exclamation mark. While there are many other interesting variations that White can choose, this one is the most strategically interesting one. You won't ever run out of new ideas to explore, or alternative ways to play. We are closing the center, preventing Black from exchanging the central pawns, and are grabbing a lot of space while doing so.  Here, Black has two main moves:  3...Bf5  , developing the light-squared bishop, which has been the most popular move historically, and  3...c5  , which is an attempt to play the French a tempo down, but without blocking the  bishop on c8.  The  3...c5  line has become very popular in 2010-2015, and its popularity has only been increasing. It leads to more forcing play. }
3... Bf5
{ In this chapter, we'll focus on this move, which seems to be more ideologically aligned with the Caro-Kann. Why am I saying that? Because I think of the Caro as an opening chosen for slow positional play, not for forcing variations. @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp2pppp/2p5/3pP3/3P4/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3...c5  is the other main line, which we investigate in another chapter.   Here, White has a ton of moves. By saying a ton, I mean it: people have been seriously trying  4.h4  ,  4.c4  ,  4.Be3  ,  4.Nd2  ,  4.g4  , and, of course, the main move  4.Nf3  . We'll go for an interesting strategic idea. }
4. c4
{ What is the point of this move, its advantages, and cons?  We are ambitiously fighting for the center and space, placing another pawn in the center. By doing so, we make room for our pieces: for example, now it makes sense to have a knight on c3. Potentially, we can release the tension with cxd5, opening up the c-file when we'd like, or push c4-c5, grabbing a lot of space on the queenside. The most obvious visual downside of this move is that Black can seemingly take ...dxc4, and when that happens, we get a 'hole' on d5 − this central square becomes an outpost for Black's pieces.  
So, how come our move is one of White's most promising weapons in the Advance Variation? Why isn't it a large positional mistake? How poorly do you need to misunderstand chess to voluntarily provide wonderful outposts in the center for your opponents? Actually, there is no problem here, and here is why. To explain this, I'd use Dvoretsky's phrase: 'redundant pieces'.  What did the greatest chess coach of all time mean by that? Well, here's the deal. Imagine you have 3 pieces that want to use this wonderful outpost on d5. But only one piece can be there at a time! So, what are the other two doing? Exactly − nothing! So, the idea is that as long as we keep a lot of pieces on the board, our e5-pawn will provide us a considerable spatial advantage, and Black would be restricted.  Black would be able to place one of the pieces  (likely a knight)  on the d5-square, but the rest of the pieces will be passive. Also, importantly, the d5-outpost, while lovely, isn't threatening to us. The knight just looks good there, but it's not deep enough in our territory for it to be threatening in any way! To summarize, we are fighting for space, and in return are happy to let ONE black piece feel good.   There is a similar line  4.h4  h5  5.c4  , but I chose to not include the h-pawn moves to avoid the sharp @@StartFEN@@rn1qkbnr/pp2pppp/2p5/3pPb2/3P4/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 1 4@@EndFEN@@  4.h4  h6  , which requires a lot more theoretical knowledge. We don't mind strategic complexity, but aren't purposefully looking for sharp play! So, we ditch that.  There are also some  4...h5  lines I do not like.  In general, having pawns on h4 and h5 leads to a slightly different type of play. For example, castling kingside becomes more difficult because the h-pawn may become weak without the support of the rook. }
4... e6
{ This is the move Black overwhelmingly chooses, reinforcing the d5-pawn and starting to prepare kingside development − now the bishop can come out, the knight gets the e7-square, and so on. }
5. Nc3 Ne7
{ This is Black's very main move, keeping the tension in the center while also developing a knight to the most logical square. Keeping the b8-knight in its current position is also important to not run into cxd5 at a bad time @@StartBracket@@as the line 5...Nd7 demonstrates@@EndBracket@@. }
6. h3
{ In a position with nearly 600 games after 5 moves, I'd like to recommend a very rare idea, which has been only seen in 15 games so far. But, two of them have been recently played by Carlsen. He convincingly beat Firouzja and MVL! The idea is very simple. We'll try to play Nf3 on the next turn, but won't ever allow Black to pin the knight with ...Bg4 and trade down this way! }
6... c5
{ Given that the move h2-h3 doesn't seem to contribute much to our ability to control the center, it's not a surprise Black can consider blowing up our center right away. That's a typical Caro-Kann idea for Black anyway, so why not do it right now, when we still cannot control the center that well with our pieces? Fair enough! }
7. Nf3
{ We protect the d4-pawn, creating a threat of capturing the pawn with dxc5 on the next turn since the very annoying ...d5-d4 push has been successfully prevented.   7.dxc5?  won't be a good idea, as after  7...d4  , Black ends up winning a ton of time and space. Crucially, we cannot benefit from the tempting-looking  8.Nb5  Nec6  9.Nd6+?  since after  9...Bxd6  10.exd6  Nb4!-+  , it's not obvious how to stop  big trouble related to the c2-square. I would assure you right away − it simply isn't possible to do so, which means we are already dead lost. Not a good start! }
7... Nbc6
{ Black keeps the tension and puts more pressure on our center. At this point, we need to be aware of such potential dangers as ...cxd4, intending to meet Nxd4 with ...Nxe5, winning our unprotected e5-pawn. }
8. dxc5 { So, we release the tension ourselves. } 8... d4
{ This is not a good idea anymore. What's the key difference? } 9. Nb5 Ng6
{ We don't need to jump on d6 with the knight, allowing for that ...Nb4-c2+ stuff. Instead, we'll simply play the text move. }
10. Nfxd4
{ And Black's f5-bishop is trapped! By the way, it is important to take  10.Nfxd4  in order to have the check on d6:  10...Bxc5  11.Nd6+  Bxd6  12.Nxc6  . After @@StartFEN@@r2qkb1r/pp3ppp/2n1p1n1/1NP1Pb2/2Pp4/5N1P/PP3PP1/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 2 10@@EndFEN@@  10.Nbxd4  Bxc5  11.Nxf5  doesn't work in view of  11...Bxf2+  and Black is better. }
10... Nxd4 11. Nxd4 Bxc5 12. Qa4+
{ We force a winning endgame with the bishop pair and an extra pawn. } 12...
Qd7
{ Black must accept the queen trade since giving up the castling rights is even worse. }
13. Qxd7+ Kxd7 14. Nxf5 exf5 15. f4
{ As a result of this unforced, yet logical line, we ended up with an extra pawn, the bishop pair, and a perfectly safe position. Of course, this means we should be winning after some careful moves. }
*

