9. Qxd8+
{ We trade queens. Unfortunately, that helps activate the black rook, but we need to do that anyway.  9.Bxc4?!  doesn't make sense, as after  9...Qxd1+  , we need to recapture in some awkward manner, which causes us to lose coordination and waste time. }
9... Rxd8
{ This is a very interesting position, which is a bit of a crossroads. You are extremely unlikely to ever encounter it in the game − there are no games like this in the database, since the entire @@StartFEN@@rn1qkb1r/pp2nppp/2p1p3/3pPb2/2PP4/2N5/PP3PPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 2 6@@EndFEN@@  6.h3  idea is very rare, and the response  6...c5  is even less common.   However, it's still worth analyzing this line, not only to be theoretically prepared but also to understand the typical ideas in positions which arise after Black breaks up the center with ...c6-c5. We need to be careful about a few ideas, which are available to our opponent:  ...Ng6, trying to win the e5-pawn; ...Nb4, threatening to invade the c2 or d3 squares, oftentimes with a fork and material gains of some kind. }
10. Bxc4
{ This is another interesting variation for you to investigate on your own. }
10... Ng6 { Black is attacking the e5 and c5-pawns, as originally intended. }
11. Bb5 { We pin the knight to prevent the e5-pawn from getting lost. } 11...
Bxc5 12. Be3
{ This is an interesting idea. The point is not to voluntarily create doubled pawns on the e-file, but to create an idea of e3-e4!, looking to trap Black's dark-squared bishop. Of course, we also want to use the semi-open f-file, and so on. }
12... Bb6 13. Bxc6+
{ We can ruin Black's pawn structure at a cost of the bishop pair. } 13... bxc6
14. O-O
{ Our pawn structure is slightly better and we can try to take advantage of the weak c6 and a7-pawns, as well as the outpost on c5. For example, we can proceed with Rac1, Na4-c5, and so on. This is an interesting, seemingly risk-free endgame to play. But, again, Black seems objectively fine. }
