[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "15) Caro-Kann 3.e5 c5 and 3...g6"]
[Black "Caro-Kann 3.e5 g6 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6
{ This move, followed by  2.--  d5  , defines the Caro-Kann Defense − one of the most solid openings for Black out there. Black is preparing to fight for the  center with ...d7-d5, just like in the French Defense. So, these two openings are sort of siblings, if you would like a bit of a figure of speech.  The main difference is that in the French, Black blocks the light-squared bishop, but gets to attack White's center with ...c7-c5 in one move − rather fast! On the other hand, in the Caro, Black cannot attack the center nearly as fast, since ...c7-c6, followed by ...c7-c5, would cost an extra tempo. But on the bright side, Black doesn't block the light-squared bishop! So, the Caro-Kann players want a solid game without a typical bad bishop. They hope to develop it or trade it off and then still eventually undermine the center with ...c6-c5, hoping the tempo won't make much of a difference. }
2. d4
{ This, of course, is White's most ambitious move.  2.Nf3  d5  3.d3!?  is another variation, which is a recent discovery − it's been actively played at the top level only since 2018. It's one of my all-time favorites, and I had written about it in the past.  Unfortunately, even though it would have been a good fit for this course, and I know many people were hoping I'd cover exactly this variation, I decided to go for something else, and that's for a few reasons.   The theory isn't changing very fast in this Nf3-d3 system, so I didn't feel as though I had a lot of new ideas to offer.  In the main system, the Advance Variation, which is what I'm recommending, the game is much more complex. I thought we'd get a nice mix of the ability to discover more about interesting strategic chess and a relatively simple line to learn too!    3...dxe4  4.dxe4  Qxd1+  5.Kxd1  . If you like endgames, and variations that don't require much theory, make sure to pay attention to this one as well! }
2... d5
{ Black follows up in the most logical way, fighting for the center with the d-pawn. Now, we arrive at massive crossroads. In the second part of the 20th century, everyone used to play  3.Nd2  or  3.Nc3  − these two moves are just a transposition. No one used to believe  3.e5  was dangerous.  However, nowadays, the opinion most players hold is exactly the opposite:  3.Nd2  and  3.Nc3  have been neutralized in numerous ways, while  3.e5  is known to offer the most interesting complex play! }
3. e5
{ Sorry, I couldn't help myself with the exclamation mark. While there are many other interesting variations that White can choose, this one is the most strategically interesting one. You won't ever run out of new ideas to explore, or alternative ways to play. We are closing the center, preventing Black from exchanging the central pawns, and are grabbing a lot of space while doing so.  Here, Black has two main moves:  3...Bf5  , developing the light-squared bishop, which has been the most popular move historically, and  3...c5  , which is an attempt to play the French a tempo down, but without blocking the  bishop on c8.  The  3...c5  line has become very popular in 2010-2015, and its popularity has only been increasing. It leads to more forcing play. }
3... g6
{ This is also a possible way of playing. This position sometimes arises via @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  g6  2.d4  c6  ,  followed by ...d7-d5, and is usually referred to as the Gurgenidze Variation of the Caro-Kann, named after the Georgian @@StartBracket@@as in a country, not a state!@@EndBracket@@ Grandmaster, who was known for his passion for offbeat sidelines.  What is Black's plan? Why is the bishop developed to g7? In brief, the claim is that the king would be safer this way. Later on, Black would consider such ideas as ...f7-f6, ...Nh6-f7, and will do the very best to create a lot of pressure on the e5-pawn, hoping to provoke exf6 exf6.  If that happens, Black would claim we have been deprived of our trump: the e5-pawn. Then a symmetrical position would arise, which would typically look only marginally worse for Black, mostly because ...f7-f6 makes the king a bit weaker and the e-file a bit looser. However, as theory has firmly established, this setup has several considerable disadvantages. Mostly, it's very passive. Black is short on space and doesn't have any activity or threats. }
4. c4
{ Just like in the main variation, I like the idea of occupying even more space in the center. }
4... Bg7 5. Nc3
{ We just keep developing, of course. Now, Black is facing a somewhat difficult situation: how to develop the pieces? Black could play ...Nh6, but the knight might end up stuck on the edge of the board in a very passive position. Black could go ...e7-e6, but that's just a very poor version of the standard main line since the combination of ...e7-e6 and ...g7-g6 only creates weak dark squares, and the g7-bishop is blocked by our center. }
5... Be6
{ Some people have tried this weird-looking move. The idea is to put pressure on our c4-pawn and force White to make a decision regarding the central tension. }
6. Qb3
{ As a very typical consequence of the c8-bishop leaving its nest early, the b7-pawn starts lacking protection, which often backfires. This is the case here too: we are putting more pressure on the d5-pawn, while also attacking the one on b7! }
6... Qb6
{ Black would typically block the b-file with the queen, hoping to force an endgame. }
7. cxd5 { No problem! We are happy to play along. } 7... Qxb3
{ Black finds an opportunity to trade the queens in between. } 8. axb3 Bxd5
{ The only game that reached this position saw Black try to install the bishop on d5, probably hoping for a trade. That's a natural idea: had Black played ...cxd5, the bishop on e6 would have looked very silly, stuck behind the pawn. }
9. b4
{ We can take on d5 at any moment − and at some point, we probably will, obtaining the lovely bishop pair. But in the meantime, we'd also love to put more pressure on Black's queenside with b4-b5. It's important to understand that our opponent is nearly lost here, mostly because of the lack of space, and the g7-bishop being blocked by our center.   And, of course, Black will have a very hard time developing the pieces − say, the g8-knight. If Black ever tries to free up the bishop and deprive us of our powerful center with ...f7-f6, we can simply respond with f2-f4, reinforcing it, keeping all the aforementioned advantages. }
