{ By pinning our knight, Black is creating a lot of pressure on the d4 and e5-pawns, forcing us to react. After  5...cxd4  6.Nxd4  , we just transpose to the lines analyzed via @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp2pppp/8/2ppP3/3P4/5N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 4@@EndFEN@@  4...cxd4  5.Nxd4  Nc6  6.c4  . }
6. cxd5
{ Unfortunately, Black's last move also has a considerable downside. Namely, it failed to protect the center. Now, Black is forced to take back with the queen, which will then run into a lot of tempi. }
6... Qxd5 7. Nc3
{ Of course, retreating with the queen seems pointless. And, it runs into d4-d5! }
7... Bxf3
{ There is one forced variation here that we'll need to learn. This is the one! By capturing, Black is leaving the queen hanging, while also attacking ours, and putting a lot of pressure on the d4-pawn. We have no choice but to engage in the complications. Fortunately, they are very favorable for us.   7...Qd8??  loses after  8.d5!  Nxe5??  9.Nxe5  Bxd1  10.Bb5++-  and the game is over. }
8. Nxd5 Bxd1 9. Nc7+ { Now, Black is losing the rook. } 9... Kd8 10. Nxa8
{ We are currently an exchange up, but the knight is stuck in the corner. So, we need to be very precise during the next few moves. }
10... Bh5
{ Black's bishop has to leave. It could go anywhere, but it won't affect our plans. }
11. d5
{ The knight is forced to leave. If Black takes the e5-pawn, which we are deliberately leaving hanging, we'll go Bf4, developing with tempo, and most importantly, starting to x-ray the c7-square in order to allow our knight to escape! }
11... Nb4
{ So, it's logical to see what happens if Black wants to fork our king and rook! }
12. Be3
{ We don't mind that at all! The knight would get stuck in the corner, while ours would escape. }
12... Nc2+ 13. Kd2 Nxa1 14. Bxc5
{ The a7-pawn is under attack. If it falls, the knight escapes via b6. If instead, Black goes ...b7-b6, then we can rescue it with Rc1 and Nc7, or with Bb5-c6, protecting it and making it invulnerable. Black is completely lost, despite the fact that is currently a piece up. Why so?  We are a pawn up and are threatening to win one more. The knight on a1 will be captured within two moves − we just need to move the bishop out and then take the knight with our rook. Our gorgeous d5 and e5-pawns are making it absolutely impossible for Black's kingside pieces to come out! }
