{ With this ambitious check, we manage to develop our kingside very quickly. Of course, blocking with ...Bd7 seems ridiculous, while ...Nd7 is passive. That move would surrender control of the d5-pawn and allow us to blow up the center very easily with the typical c2-c4! }
5... Nc6 6. Bxc6+
{ We won't be able to benefit from the standard doubled pawns, as Black can take on d4 on any turn, undoubling them. So why are we giving up the bishop pair so easily? To try to hold on to the extra pawn! }
6... bxc6 { Which extra pawn? } 7. dxc5
{ This one! The plan is c2-c3, Be3, Nbd2, b2-b4!, holding on to the c5-pawn forever. }
7... e6
{ The most natural move for Black is this one, of course, attacking the c5-pawn and hoping to recapture it in the most logical way − with the bishop. }
8. Be3
{ Of course, we won't allow the opponent to take the c5-pawn back, that was the whole point! }
8... Ne7
{ 8...Nh6  would result in something very similar, for instance,  9.Nbd2  Nf5  10.b4  with a transposition. }
9. Nbd2
{ We just keep developing. The plan is c2-c3, b2-b4, and Nb3, reinforcing the c5-pawn, and planning to occupy the outpost on d4. }
9... Nf5
{ Black is threatening to take on e3 and win back the c5-pawn. What do we think of the idea of letting the opponent double our e-pawns? We don't mind that at all, as long as we keep the extra pawn. How come? Well, the position would stay rather closed, so the bishops won't be useful. The e-pawns won't be easily attacked by the black pieces. And, by taking on e3, Black is opening up the f-file for our rook! What's there not to like? }
10. b4 a5
{ Black could also take on e3, but it makes sense to try to blow up the queenside. Or, at least, you should know this idea exists and not be afraid of it! }
11. a3 { No worries, the b4-pawn is easy to defend. } 11... Nxe3 12. fxe3
{ These doubled pawns, as I had explained above, are not a source of worries or problems. No one can attack them, and the d4-outpost will prove very useful. }
12... Be7 { So, Black should just keep developing. } 13. O-O
{ And so would we. } 13... O-O 14. Nb3
{ By putting more pressure on the a5-pawn, we are making Black trade on b4. Next, we'll install the knight on d4, putting pressure on the c6-pawn. The open a-file would be rather useful for us because it would enable us to trade off the major pieces. Once we do that, it would be easier to put pressure on the c6-pawn, and maybe get a passed pawn on the queenside with b4-b5. All in all, Black is just a pawn down for no reason. They shouldn't be playing this way! }
*

