ce on the queenside and gaining time.  5...Bxc5  6.b4  Bb6  7.Nf3  Ne7  8.Bd3  a5  9.b5  Nd7  10.O-O  Ng6  11.Bb2  O-O  .   A position like this is really interesting to play, without a doubt. Black would try to undermine our e5-pawn with ...f7-f6, and take advantage of the weakened c5-square by playing ...Nc5, ...a5-a4, etc. We, instead, often try to push c2-c4, looking to recapture on c4 with the knight and then install it on d6. Interesting play, without a doubt, but not something I'd prefer. }
4... cxd4
{ Releasing the tension immediately is Black's best, safest, and easiest choice, since it prevents us from being able to capture on c5. }
5. Nxd4 Nc6
{ Now, the e5-pawn seems to be hanging. But, as we will soon find out, it's not true. So, we continue our plan of blowing up Black's center in order to open up the position and tremendously activate our pieces. }
6. c4 { Everything according to the plan. } 6... dxc4
{ This results in a one-sided endgame, where we will be having all the fun! }
7. Nxc6 Qxd1+
{ It's natural that Black wants to trade queens and deprive us of castling rights, as opposed to allowing us to do that by taking on d8! }
8. Kxd1 bxc6 9. Bxc4
{ The king is perfectly safe on d1. Next, we'll just proceed with Nc3, Be3, then Kc2 or Ke2. I would prefer to avoid a check with ...Bf5, which is why I would play Ke2 if Black can give that check. But, if Black locks up the bishop with ...e7-e6, I'd rather go to c2, in order to help protect the queenside.  For example, if Black ever wants to put pressure down the b-file with ...Rb8, it's no big deal, as b2-b3 can easily prevent all the counterplay; however, having a king on c2 could be nice. On the other hand, having a king on e2 means we aren't blocking the c-file, which allows us to play Rac1 and start attacking the weak c6-pawn.  I went into a bit too much detail discussing where the king is going, but the simple conclusion is that Black got a bad pawn structure for no reason whatsoever, and we are comfortably better! All you need to do is get the rest of your pieces out and slowly start pressuring that c6-pawn. The one on a7 is also a bit of a weakness, as moves like Be3 will either make the rook stuck on a8 or will cause Black to make more weakening pawn moves, such as ...a7-a6 or ...a7-a5. }
