{ This variation has started to become fairly popular @@StartBracket@@and then extremely popular!@@EndBracket@@ in the last decade. Since Black is immediately provoking conflict in the center, it is only natural that play here is quickly becoming pretty forcing, unlike after  3...Bf5  , where the strategic understanding and knowledge of plans can often nearly completely eliminate one's need to know the forcing lines.   3...Bf5  is the historical main line. It is still the most popular continuation nowadays, but the difference is that back in the day, only  3...Bf5  was considered reputable, while now  3...c5  gets a fair share of respect as well. }
4. Nf3
{ We just protect the d4-pawn, getting ready to blow up the center with our favorite move c2-c4! This move might be 4 times less common than the main line  4.dxc5  , but it is the most critical theoretical attempt to challenge Black's setup.  Here, Black has three main continuations. The most popular move is @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp2pppp/8/2ppP3/3P4/5N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Nc6  , which is not as good as  4...cxd4  unless it is played with the intention of transposing to the 4...cxd4 lines with  4...Nc6  5.c4  cxd4!  6.Nxd4  .  Also, very importantly, @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp2pppp/8/2ppP3/3P4/5N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Nc6  gives White the additional option of  5.dxc5  , which is not the same as the @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp2pppp/8/2ppP3/3P4/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.dxc5  lines. This is because when the  black knight is on c6, it can run into the Bb5 pin, and can no longer go to d7, attacking the c5-pawn. So, the move  order @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp2pppp/8/2ppP3/3P4/5N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Nc6  has several drawbacks, no upside, and at best just transposes to the correct  4...cxd4  5.Nxd4  Nc6  lines.  Finally, there is @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp2pppp/8/2ppP3/3P4/5N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Bg4  , after which play can get really sharp.  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp2pppp/8/2ppP3/3P4/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.dxc5  is the main line. I don't mind the arising positions, but I am afraid the theoretical workload will be a bit too large here. Typically, what you get is a position like this one.  4...e6   4...Nc6  is also a fairly popular move, but I actually don't have much faith in this one! And that's an important piece of knowledge for our theoretical variations, as in some lines, we might try to transpose here!  5.a3  ,  White isn't holding on to the c5-pawn, as that's not really possible yet. Instead, White wants to meet ...Bxc5 with b2-b4, grabbing space on the queenside and gaining time.  5...Bxc5  6.b4  Bb6  7.Nf3  Ne7  8.Bd3  a5  9.b5  Nd7  10.O-O  Ng6  11.Bb2  O-O  .   A position like this is really interesting to play, without a doubt. Black would try to undermine our e5-pawn with ...f7-f6, and take advantage of the weakened c5-square by playing ...Nc5, ...a5-a4, etc. We, instead, often try to push c2-c4, looking to recapture on c4 with the knight and then install it on d6. Interesting play, without a doubt, but not something I'd prefer. }
4... cxd4
{ Releasing the tension immediately is Black's best, safest, and easiest choice, since it prevents us from being able to capture on c5. }
5. Nxd4 Nc6
{ Now, the e5-pawn seems to be hanging. But, as we will soon find out, it's not true. So, we continue our plan of blowing up Black's center in order to open up the position and tremendously activate our pieces. }
6. c4 { Everything according to the plan. } 6... Nxe5
{ This greedy capture is a very poor idea. Unsurprisingly, it hasn't been played much at the master level, in 1-2% of the games. However, you are very likely to encounter this move at a club level, so we need to discuss it. And, of course, discussing it would be very helpful for better understanding the dynamic resources available to White in this type of position. }
7. cxd5
{ As usual, it's best to take advantage of the development lead by opening up the position. The d5-pawn is really restricting Black, preventing ...e7-e6, so Black needs to bite the bullet and take it. }
7... Qxd5 8. Nc3
{ We keep winning time by making the most natural developing moves. } 8... Qd8
9. Bf4 { Black is forced to keep retreating. } 9... Ng6
{ Here, after the simple Bg3, we have a tremendous lead in development. However, there is another move, a much better one. I cannot help but show it to you since it's so unexpected and cool! }
10. Ndb5
{ This has been played in one game only so far, but White is just winning. The main threat is, of course, Nc7+. But, we are also threatening to trade queens, depriving Black of castling rights. But wait, aren't we hanging our bishop? }
10... Nxf4
{ 10...Qxd1+?  loses even faster, as after  11.Rxd1  Nxf4  12.Nc7+  is not a threat of winning a rook − it's a threat of mate in one! So, Black has to give up the rook and accept a lost position. }
11. Qa4
{ We are threatening two checkmates in one move: Nc7 and Nd6! The problem is that it would be a double check − with our knight and our queen, which would make it a checkmate. }
11... Bd7 { Of course, Black needs to prevent that. } 12. Qxf4
{ But now, White gets the missing piece back, renewing the threat of Nc7+. }
12... Rc8 13. Nxa7
{ The easiest move is this one, just winning the pawn back. Next, we can play Nb5 or Bb5, castle queenside, and win in no time since we have a tremendous lead in development. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "15) Caro-Kann 3.e5 c5 and 3...g6"]
[Black "Caro-Kann 3.e5 c5 4.Nf3 cxd4 #5"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6
{ This move, followed by  2.--  d5  , defines the Caro-Kann Defense − one of the most solid openings for Black out there. Black is preparing to fight for the  center with ...d7-d5, just like in the French Defense. So, these two openings are sort of siblings, if you would like a bit of a figure of speech.  The main difference is that in the French, Black blocks the light-squared bishop, but gets to attack White's center with ...c7-c5 in one move − rather fast! On the other hand, in the Caro, Black cannot attack the center nearly as fast, since ...c7-c6, followed by ...c7-c5, would cost an extra tempo. But on the bright side, Black doesn't block the light-squared bishop! So, the Caro-Kann players want a solid game without a typical bad bishop. They hope to develop it or trade it off and then still eventually undermine the center with ...c6-c5, hoping the tempo won't make much of a difference. }
2. d4
{ This, of course, is White's most ambitious move.  2.Nf3  d5  3.d3!?  is another variation, which is a recent discovery − it's been actively played at the top level only since 2018. It's one of my all-time favorites, and I had written about it in the past.  Unfortunately, even though it would have been a good fit for this course, and I know many people were hoping I'd cover exactly this variation, I decided to go for something else, and that's for a few reasons.   The theory isn't changing very fast in this Nf3-d3 system, so I didn't feel as though I had a lot of new ideas to offer.  In the main system, the Advance Variation, which is what I'm recommending, the game is much more complex. I thought we'd get a nice mix of the ability to discover more about interesting strategic chess and a relatively simple line to learn too!    3...dxe4  4.dxe4  Qxd1+  5.Kxd1  . If you like endgames, and variations that don't require much theory, make sure to pay attention to this one as well! }
2... d5
{ Black follows up in the most logical way, fighting for the center with the d-pawn. Now, we arrive at massive crossroads. In the second part of the 20th century, everyone used to play  3.Nd2  or  3.Nc3  − these two moves are just a transposition. No one used to believe  3.e5  was dangerous.  However, nowadays, the opinion most players hold is exactly the opposite:  3.Nd2  and  3.Nc3  have been neutralized in numerous ways, while  3.e5  is known to offer the most interesting complex play! }
3. e5
{ Sorry, I couldn't help myself with the exclamation mark. While there are many other interesting variations that White can choose, this one is the most strategically interesting one. You won't ever run out of new ideas to explore, or alternative ways to play. We are closing the center, preventing Black from exchanging the central pawns, and are grabbing a lot of space while doing so.  Here, Black has two main moves:  3...Bf5  , developing the light-squared bishop, which has been the most popular move historically, and  3...c5  , which is an attempt to play the French a tempo down, but without blocking the  bishop on c8.  The  3...c5  line has become very popular in 2010-2015, and its popularity has only been increasing. It leads to more forcing play. }
3... c5
{ This variation has started to become fairly popular @@StartBracket@@and then extremely popular!@@EndBracket@@ in the last decade. Since Black is immediately provoking conflict in the center, it is only natural that play here is quickly becoming pretty forcing, unlike after  3...Bf5  , where the strategic understanding and knowledge of plans can often nearly completely eliminate one's need to know the forcing lines.   3...Bf5  is the historical main line. It is still the most popular continuation nowadays, but the difference is that back in the day, only  3...Bf5  was considered reputable, while now  3...c5  gets a fair share of respect as well. }
4. Nf3
{ We just protect the d4-pawn, getting ready to blow up the center with our favorite move c2-c4! This move might be 4 times less common than the main line  4.dxc5  , but it is the most critical theoretical attempt to challenge Black's setup.  Here, Black has three main continuations. The most popular move is @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp2pppp/8/2ppP3/3P4/5N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Nc6  , which is not as good as  4...cxd4  unless it is played with the intention of transposing to the 4...cxd4 lines with  4...Nc6  5.c4  cxd4!  6.Nxd4  .  Also, very importantly, @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp2pppp/8/2ppP3/3P4/5N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Nc6  gives White the additional option of  5.dxc5  , which is not the same as the @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp2pppp/8/2ppP3/3P4/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.dxc5  lines. This is because when the  black knight is on c6, it can run into the Bb5 pin, and can no longer go to d7, attacking the c5-pawn. So, the move  order @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp2pppp/8/2ppP3/3P4/5N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Nc6  has several drawbacks, no upside, and at best just transposes to the correct  4...cxd4  5.Nxd4  Nc6  lines.  Finally, there is @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp2pppp/8/2ppP3/3P4/5N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Bg4  , after which play can get really sharp.  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp2pppp/8/2ppP3/3P4/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.dxc5  is the main line. I don't mind the arising positions, but I am afraid the theoretical workload will be a bit too large here. Typically, what you get is a position like this one.  4...e6   4...Nc6  is also a fairly popular move, but I actually don't have much faith in this one! And that's an important piece of knowledge for our theoretical variations, as in some lines, we might try to transpose here!  5.a3  ,  White isn't holding on to the c5-pawn, as that's not really possible yet. Instead, White wants to meet ...Bxc5 with b2-b4, grabbing space on the queenside and gaining time.  5...Bxc5  6.b4  Bb6  7.Nf3  Ne7  8.Bd3  a5  9.b5  Nd7  10.O-O  Ng6  11.Bb2  O-O  .   A position like this is really interesting to play, without a doubt. Black would try to undermine our e5-pawn with ...f7-f6, and take advantage of the weakened c5-square by playing ...Nc5, ...a5-a4, etc. We, instead, often try to push c2-c4, looking to recapture on c4 with the knight and then install it on d6. Interesting play, without a doubt, but not something I'd prefer. }
4... cxd4
{ Releasing the tension immediately is Black's best, safest, and easiest choice, since it prevents us from being able to capture on c5. }
5. Nxd4 Nc6
{ Now, the e5-pawn seems to be hanging. But, as we will soon find out, it's not true. So, we continue our plan of blowing up Black's center in order to open up the position and tremendously activate our pieces. }
6. c4 { Everything according to the plan. } 6... e6
{ Black must protect the d5-pawn. } 7. Nc3 Bc5
{ This is the second most popular move, which has been tried by such famous Caro-Kann experts as Navara and Movsesian. Black isn't interested in pinning the c3-knight. Instead, Black wants to immediately put pressure on the d4-knight, forcing White to do something about this issue. We don't have a lot of choices − taking the knight on c6 is the only reasonable way to continue. }
8. Nxc6
{ 8.Nb3  is possible, but after  8...Bb4  , Black seems to have a lot of counterplay:  the e5-pawn is hanging, and ...d5-d4 is a bit of a threat too. I think the position after  9.cxd5  exd5  10.Bb5!?  is fairly interesting to explore, but I would rather stick to the main line, which offers us a lot of promise.   8.Be3?!  is very suspicious, since after  8...Qb6!  ,  Black develops pressure on the d4-knight, the b2-pawn, and the e5-pawn is still under attack. It seems we are forced to ask for a draw after  9.Na4  Bb4+  10.Nc3=  .  Black can choose to retreat to c5 and force a draw, or keep playing. In either case, we are not interested in this outcome! }
8... bxc6
{ Now, Black seems to have a pretty solid pawn structure − at least, the d5-pawn is very well-protected. However, Black is still facing several problems, namely:  We can trade on d5, either forcing Black to open up the a4-e8 diagonal, or forcing ...exd5, getting a somewhat dicey structure with the hanging pawns.  The pawn on e5 is restricting the kingside access − the knight cannot go to f6. Since the bishop has already gotten developed, the g7-pawn is loose, and the typical Qg4-related ideas can considerably challenge the kingside.   We can just keep developing with Bd3, O-O, and try to slowly build kingside pressure after Qh5, Bg5, Rad1-d3-g3, and so on. As you can see, White is choosing among several attractive plans! }
9. cxd5
{ As always, whenever possible, I prefer the positional and logical path, as opposed to the sharp one. Now, Black is choosing between two logical ways of recapturing.  The more popular move is ...cxd5, keeping the structure intact. However, most recent games saw Black take with the e-pawn, going for the hanging pawns. Why is that? Let's analyze both moves and discover the answer!   9.Qg4  is a good way of playing as well, but the positions after  9...Ne7  10.Qxg7  Ng6  get too sharp to my taste. }
9... exd5
{ This has become a more popular choice in recent years since Black is keen on avoiding the positions after  9...cxd5  10.b4!  But in order to do so, Black must accept the structure with the somewhat weak doubled pawns. And some weak  squares, such as c5 and d4.  In this structure, our dream would be to play a2-a3, b2-b4, Na4, Rc1, Nc5, and install the bishop on d4. If we achieve that, Black's queenside pawns will become clearly weak, and our pieces will be enjoying dominant positions. At the same time, we have an extra pawn in the center. This means at some point ideas like f2-f4-f5-f6 could become interesting, building an attack on the kingside.  But, to be fair, I don't think this plan is likely to be carried out since the center is fairly open. You typically only attack a flank, especially if that includes pawn play, with a closed center. }
10. Bd3 { For now, we just continue our development. } 10... Ne7 11. O-O Bf5
12. Na4
{ Our goal is to try to take advantage of the weak c5-square. If possible, we'd like to develop the dark-squared bishop, then play Rc1 and install the knight on c5. Or, we could play b2-b3, Ba3, and then install a piece on c5! However, if you do the latter, be careful: at times, b2-b3 would run into ...Bd4! with a double attack on the a1-rook and the e5-pawn. }
12... Bd4
{ Black has also tried this move. The idea, of course, is to attack the e5-pawn. }
13. Bc2
{ This cute idea has never been tried, but it seems very logical. We are attacking the d4-bishop. Black is being tempted to take the e5-pawn − doing that would lose on the spot. If instead, Black takes the c2-bishop, we'll take the one on d4, reaching a very pleasant position with the opposite-colored bishop and plenty of weak dark squares to take advantage of! }
13... Bxc2
{ 13...Bxe5??  loses on the spot. Black cannot afford to take up the e-file, as after  14.Bxf5  Nxf5  15.Re1+-  ,  f2-f4 comes next, winning a piece. }
14. Qxd4
{ We want to install the knight on c5. Then, we can consider playing b2-b3, Bb2, or maybe Ba3, enjoying the a3-f8 diagonal. Alternatively, we could consider going for some kingside play with f2-f4-f5-f6. If that succeeds, we would be extremely happy, of course.  However, I would be a bit hesitant to recommend this plan at all times since playing f2-f4 weakens the light squares, such as e4 and f5. Black has better control of them, so we need to be careful while doing that. }
14... Bxa4
{ Instead of retreating, which allows for the aforementioned annoying plans, Black can also choose to capture the knight. This way, Black just gets a slightly worse position due to the somewhat inferior pawn structure and weak dark squares. }
15. Qxa4 O-O 16. Be3
{ Next, we'll install the bishop on c5. We can easily protect the e5-pawn with f2-f4. Black needs to be on the lookout for the queenside pressure  (the a7 and c6-pawns could become easy targets)  and for the f2-f4-f5 kingside-type play, of course. It seems White is clearly dictating the way the game would be going! }
