ce on the queenside and gaining time.  5...Bxc5  6.b4  Bb6  7.Nf3  Ne7  8.Bd3  a5  9.b5  Nd7  10.O-O  Ng6  11.Bb2  O-O  .   A position like this is really interesting to play, without a doubt. Black would try to undermine our e5-pawn with ...f7-f6, and take advantage of the weakened c5-square by playing ...Nc5, ...a5-a4, etc. We, instead, often try to push c2-c4, looking to recapture on c4 with the knight and then install it on d6. Interesting play, without a doubt, but not something I'd prefer. }
4... cxd4
{ Releasing the tension immediately is Black's best, safest, and easiest choice, since it prevents us from being able to capture on c5. }
5. Nxd4 Nc6
{ Now, the e5-pawn seems to be hanging. But, as we will soon find out, it's not true. So, we continue our plan of blowing up Black's center in order to open up the position and tremendously activate our pieces. }
6. c4 { Everything according to the plan. } 6... e6
{ Black must protect the d5-pawn. } 7. Nc3 Bb4
{ Black's best choice, pinning the knight. This way Black also decreases pressure on the d5-pawn. Then, Black just wants to go ...Nge7 and castle, finishing development. }
8. Nxc6
{ This knight trade isn't just a trade − it's an introduction to a forcing line, which leads to... an endgame! }
8... bxc6 9. Qa4
{ The black bishop is hanging, and so is the c6-pawn.   9.Bd3  is the less forcing move, which leads to more complex positions. If you don't like the objective equality of the main line, give it a shot! For example, after  9...Ne7  10.cxd5  Qxd5  11.O-O!?  is an interesting pawn sacrifice. The queen is now hanging, of course. But if Black were to retreat,  say with ...Qa5, we'd keep a large advantage by playing Qe2, f2-f4, Ne4, and so on. We'd have a much better pawn structure, and our pieces would be more active too. So, Black has to bite the bullet.    11...Qxe5  12.Re1  Qd6!  It's important for Black to retreat exactly here. Why so? Because White wants to attack with  moves like Qg4 or Qh5, and by retreating to d6, Black prevents that since the d3-bishop would be left hanging.  13.Qf3  O-O  14.Bf4  .  White's pieces are much more active. Next, we can play Be4, Qe4, maybe Rad1, Re3-g3/h3, and so on. We have a lot of compensation for the missing pawn, without a doubt! So, if you prefer messy positions, where the game cannot dry up too fast, explore this gambit! }
9... Rb8
{ This has also been played in quite a few games. However, I don't fully trust it. }
10. cxd5 exd5
{ This weird variation, which offers a pawn sacrifice, somehow makes a bit of sense. I still find this fact somewhat unbelievable! }
11. Qxc6+ { We gladly pick up the free pawn. } 11... Kf8
{ Black couldn't block with ...Bd7, as that would have hung the d5-pawn as well. }
12. a3
{ Black was threatening with some ...d5-d4 pushes, so we want to unpin the knight.  12.Qxd5??  isn't possible, of course, since after  12...Qxd5  , we just lose the queen − our knight is pinned! }
12... Ne7
{ The opponent, unfortunately, finds a way to win a tempo against our queen. }
13. Qa4 Ba5
{ The pin is still alive, and we're really interested in solving that issue. }
14. b4 Qc7
{ This is the key reason why the weird pawn sacrifice makes sense: Black is able to set up a double attack on the knight and the e5-pawn and get the material back. However, as a result, we get to simplify the game and force a very pleasant endgame. }
15. Bb2
{ The knight needs to be protected, and the bishop dreams of a wonderful future on the a1-h8 diagonal, especially when the e5-pawn falls. }
15... Qxe5+ 16. Be2 Bb6
{ Castling seems suspicious since that leaves the e2-bishop somewhat loose, which can be taken advantage of by means of ...d5-d4. That's why we'll do something else. }
17. Qd1
{ This prophylactical, slow-looking move helps us protect the bishop and prepare kingside castling. We might also be interested in going Na4, setting up a discovered attack on the queen, and trading off the b6-bishop to get the bishop pair and a wonderfully active bishop on the long dark diagonal. Please remember the opponent's king is still stuck in the corner, and so is the h8-rook! }
17... Ba6
{ Black can take advantage of the pinned bishop and force some trades. } 18.
O-O { That's okay. We are now threatening to win the hanging bishop on a6. }
18... Bxe2 { Logically, the opponent initiates a series of exchanges. } 19.
Qxe2
{ We have to trade queens, as taking with the knight would have lost the b2-bishop. }
19... Qxe2 20. Nxe2
{ The arising endgame is clearly much better for White. Why so?  The king is stuck on f8. The rook is stuck in the corner. Of course, achieving coordination and decent piece activity will take the opponent a lot of effort and time. Black has an isolated pawn and no activity in return, so it's just a weakness. We have an outside passed pawn. The open c-file seems easy to take over. The b2-bishop is incredibly active. Not a fun endgame for Black, by any means! Next, we'll go Rfd1, Rac1, maybe Nd4, or maybe even Nf4/c3 to try to win the isolated pawn. }
*

