{ Black follows up in the most logical way, fighting for the center with the d-pawn. Now, we arrive at massive crossroads. In the second part of the 20th century, everyone used to play  3.Nd2  or  3.Nc3  − these two moves are just a transposition. No one used to believe  3.e5  was dangerous.  However, nowadays, the opinion most players hold is exactly the opposite:  3.Nd2  and  3.Nc3  have been neutralized in numerous ways, while  3.e5  is known to offer the most interesting complex play! }
3. e5
{ Sorry, I couldn't help myself with the exclamation mark. While there are many other interesting variations that White can choose, this one is the most strategically interesting one. You won't ever run out of new ideas to explore, or alternative ways to play. We are closing the center, preventing Black from exchanging the central pawns, and are grabbing a lot of space while doing so.  Here, Black has two main moves:  3...Bf5  , developing the light-squared bishop, which has been the most popular move historically, and  3...c5  , which is an attempt to play the French a tempo down, but without blocking the  bishop on c8.  The  3...c5  line has become very popular in 2010-2015, and its popularity has only been increasing. It leads to more forcing play. }
3... c5
{ This variation has started to become fairly popular @@StartBracket@@and then extremely popular!@@EndBracket@@ in the last decade. Since Black is immediately provoking conflict in the center, it is only natural that play here is quickly becoming pretty forcing, unlike after  3...Bf5  , where the strategic understanding and knowledge of plans can often nearly completely eliminate one's need to know the forcing lines.   3...Bf5  is the historical main line. It is still the most popular continuation nowadays, but the difference is that back in the day, only  3...Bf5  was considered reputable, while now  3...c5  gets a fair share of respect as well. }
4. Nf3
{ We just protect the d4-pawn, getting ready to blow up the center with our favorite move c2-c4! This move might be 4 times less common than the main line  4.dxc5  , but it is the most critical theoretical attempt to challenge Black's setup.  Here, Black has three main continuations. The most popular move is @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp2pppp/8/2ppP3/3P4/5N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Nc6  , which is not as good as  4...cxd4  unless it is played with the intention of transposing to the 4...cxd4 lines with  4...Nc6  5.c4  cxd4!  6.Nxd4  .  Also, very importantly, @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp2pppp/8/2ppP3/3P4/5N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Nc6  gives White the additional option of  5.dxc5  , which is not the same as the @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp2pppp/8/2ppP3/3P4/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.dxc5  lines. This is because when the  black knight is on c6, it can run into the Bb5 pin, and can no longer go to d7, attacking the c5-pawn. So, the move  order @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp2pppp/8/2ppP3/3P4/5N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Nc6  has several drawbacks, no upside, and at best just transposes to the correct  4...cxd4  5.Nxd4  Nc6  lines.  Finally, there is @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp2pppp/8/2ppP3/3P4/5N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Bg4  , after which play can get really sharp.  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp2pppp/8/2ppP3/3P4/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.dxc5  is the main line. I don't mind the arising positions, but I am afraid the theoretical workload will be a bit too large here. Typically, what you get is a position like this one.  4...e6   4...Nc6  is also a fairly popular move, but I actually don't have much faith in this one! And that's an important piece of knowledge for our theoretical variations, as in some lines, we might try to transpose here!  5.a3  ,  White isn't holding on to the c5-pawn, as that's not really possible yet. Instead, White wants to meet ...Bxc5 with b2-b4, grabbing space on the queenside and gaining time.  5...Bxc5  6.b4  Bb6  7.Nf3  Ne7  8.Bd3  a5  9.b5  Nd7  10.O-O  Ng6  11.Bb2  O-O  .   A position like this is really interesting to play, without a doubt. Black would try to undermine our e5-pawn with ...f7-f6, and take advantage of the weakened c5-square by playing ...Nc5, ...a5-a4, etc. We, instead, often try to push c2-c4, looking to recapture on c4 with the knight and then install it on d6. Interesting play, without a doubt, but not something I'd prefer. }
4... cxd4
{ Releasing the tension immediately is Black's best, safest, and easiest choice, since it prevents us from being able to capture on c5. }
5. Nxd4 Nc6
{ Now, the e5-pawn seems to be hanging. But, as we will soon find out, it's not true. So, we continue our plan of blowing up Black's center in order to open up the position and tremendously activate our pieces. }
6. c4 { Everything according to the plan. } 6... e6
{ Black must protect the d5-pawn. } 7. Nc3 Bb4
{ Black's best choice, pinning the knight. This way Black also decreases pressure on the d5-pawn. Then, Black just wants to go ...Nge7 and castle, finishing development. }
8. Nxc6
{ This knight trade isn't just a trade − it's an introduction to a forcing line, which leads to... an endgame! }
8... bxc6 9. Qa4
{ The black bishop is hanging, and so is the c6-pawn.   9.Bd3  is the less forcing move, which leads to more complex positions. If you don't like the objective equality of the main line, give it a shot! For example, after  9...Ne7  10.cxd5  Qxd5  11.O-O!?  is an interesting pawn sacrifice. The queen is now hanging, of course. But if Black were to retreat,  say with ...Qa5, we'd keep a large advantage by playing Qe2, f2-f4, Ne4, and so on. We'd have a much better pawn structure, and our pieces would be more active too. So, Black has to bite the bullet.    11...Qxe5  12.Re1  Qd6!  It's important for Black to retreat exactly here. Why so? Because White wants to attack with  moves like Qg4 or Qh5, and by retreating to d6, Black prevents that since the d3-bishop would be left hanging.  13.Qf3  O-O  14.Bf4  .  White's pieces are much more active. Next, we can play Be4, Qe4, maybe Rad1, Re3-g3/h3, and so on. We have a lot of compensation for the missing pawn, without a doubt! So, if you prefer messy positions, where the game cannot dry up too fast, explore this gambit! }
9... a5
{ Black hopes to keep the pin alive, which is why the bishop gets protected. Fair enough! }
10. cxd5
{ We immediately trade, taking advantage of the pinned c3-pawn. Black is forced to enter a pretty forcing line.   10.Qxc6+?  is a bad idea since after  10...Bd7  11.Qb7  d4!  , we run into a lot of threats. White isn't losing, by sheer miracle, but I don't want to be a part of this! }
10... Qxd5
{ A bit of tactical equilibristics. Black is taking advantage of the fact our knight is pinned, making a bold move. The queen not only ensures the safety of the c6-pawn, but it's also attacking the one on d5! Now, our queen looks a bit silly on a4, and we certainly don't want to feel forced to start defending.   10...exd5?  This time, we can just win a pawn!  11.Qxc6+  Bd7  −  the difference is that the d5-pawn is hanging too!  12.Qxd5±  and Black just lost material for no reason.   Black can also give up the bishop pair with  10...Bxc3+  , but after the simple  11.bxc3  Qxd5  12.Be3±  , we follow  up with f2-f4, Rd1, and get a dominant position without much effort. }
11. Qxb4
{ The queen is not that safe on d5, after all! By capturing the bishop, we unpin the knight and get ready to take the queen. }
11... axb4
{ 11...Qxe5+??  isn't a good intermediate move, as after  12.Qe4  , we keep the extra piece. }
12. Nxd5 exd5
{ Black must take this way in order to keep the queenside pawns connected. If we try Bd2, Black will simply protect the b4-pawn with ...c6-c5. This is the variation that GM Erwin L'Ami and IM Christof Sielecki recommended for Black in their Caro-Kann courses. Both courses are great, and the line is objectively very sound. I do believe Black should be doing okay here, but the problems certainly aren't over yet. And, this position has been seen in only 48 games so far, so it's not as though this 'solution' is well-known. }
13. Be3
{ The bishop is going to c5. This way, we achieve several things:  Get ready to attack the b4-pawn. Prevent Black from connecting the pawns with ...c6-c5. Prevent Black from castling. If Black blocks the a3-f8 diagonal with ...Ne7, Black won't be able to castle anyway since the knight would be left hanging. A very useful move, as you can see! }
13... f6
{ Black should immediately undermine the e5-pawn. This way, Black will either get rid of our main space-grabbing asset or will force us to play f2-f4, when Black can exchange a pair of pawns and claim the isolated e-pawn could wind up weak.   13...Ne7  is not as good since the knight loses the option of coming out to f6 after exf6 Nxf6.  14.f4  with a much better version of the positions in the main line in the text. }
14. f4 { We protect the pawn, of course. } 14... Bf5
{ Typically, Black would keep the tension and develop the bishop. This is the move Sielecki and L'Ami propose in their courses. }
15. Bc5 { Of course, we continue with our plan of attacking the b4-pawn. }
15... Kd7
{ Black gives it up, hoping to activate the kingside pieces quickly and get counterplay against the weak e5-pawn and on the a and b-files. As we saw in many other lines, the natural reaction of playing ...b4-b3 hardly ever turns out good in these positions, since White just plays a2-a4 and goes after the b3-pawn with Ra3 later on. }
16. Bxb4 fxe5 17. fxe5 Nh6
{ We cannot hold on to the e5-pawn, Black will get that one back. However, that's fine! }
18. a3
{ We are not only protecting the bishop, avoiding ...Rb8 with a tempo in the future, but we are also enabling the a-rook to move freely since it will be no longer tied up protecting the a2-pawn. }
18... Rhe8 { Black attacks the e5-pawn. It cannot be saved. } 19. Kd2
{ Time to get the king in action! Of course, there is no point in castling. In the endgame, the king can often safely be in the center. Here, it's certainly the case, since the d-file is closed. }
19... Rxe5 20. Be2
{ Objectively speaking, Black has enough activity to hold equality. However, I would still pick White for a very simple reason. We have the bishop pair and outside passed pawn! What does this mean? Typically, in positions with the bishop pair, you want to trade all the rooks.  Why so? Because the bishops are better at cutting off the opponent's king and controlling the entire board, than other minor pieces. As a result, once the rooks are gone, it's much easier for the side with the bishop pair to use their king as an active piece. Combine that with an outside passed a-pawn, and you will quickly see that if all the rooks come off, Black could easily land in a lost endgame!   So, while Black is okay, has to be careful, and we have a very clear plan − just trade the rooks off! But, objectively, this is Black's very best theoretical defense in the @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp2pppp/2p5/3pP3/3P4/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3...c5  4.Nf3  system. If Black knows this far, the positions should be okay − that's a fair outcome. But, very few games saw these variations, and those were mostly GM games or correspondence chess games. I wouldn't worry about your opponents being aware of this way of defending Black's position! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "16) Caro-Kann 3.e5 Bf5 − Model Games"]
[Black "Alexis Cabrera Pino − Rufino Camarena Gimenez, Albacete 2005"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ The educational goal of this game is to showcase the value of obtaining a kingside majority after Black plays ...exd5, giving White an extra e-pawn, and how one-sided the game can quickly become in those cases. }
1... c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. c4
{ Let me remind you what is the point of this move, its advantages and cons.  We are ambitiously fighting for the center and space, placing another pawn in the center. By doing so, we make room for our pieces: for example, now it makes sense to have a knight on c3. Potentially, we can release the tension with cxd5, opening up the c-file when we'd like, or push c4-c5, grabbing a lot of space on the kingside. The most obvious visual downside of this move is that Black can seemingly take ...dxc4, and when that happens, we get a 'hole' on d5 − this central square becomes an outpost for Black's pieces.  
So, how come our move is one of White's most promising weapons in the Advance Variation? Why isn't it a large positional mistake? How poorly do you need to misunderstand chess to voluntarily provide wonderful outposts in the center for your opponents? Actually, there is no problem here, and here is why.  To explain this, I'd use Dvoretsky's phrase 'redundant pieces'. What did the greatest chess coach of all time mean by that? Well, here's the deal. Imagine you have 3 pieces that want to use this wonderful outpost on d5. But only one piece can be there at a time! So, what are the other two doing? Exactly − nothing!   The idea is that as long as we keep a lot of pieces on the board, our e5-pawn will provide us a considerable spatial advantage, and Black would be restricted. Black would be able to place one of the pieces  (likely a knight)  on the d5-square, but the rest of the pieces will be passive. Also, importantly, the d5-outpost, while lovely, isn't threatening to us. The knight just looks good there, but it's not deep enough in our territory for it to be threatening in any way! To summarize, we are fighting for space, and in return are happy to let ONE Black piece feel good. }
4... e6
{ Black reinforces the d5-pawn, getting ready to develop the kingside pieces. }
5. Nc3 dxc4
{ And Black decides to release the tension, giving up the center, but obtaining an outpost on d5. As you likely already know from the theoretical part of the repertoire, I am very skeptical about this type of setup for Black, who gets an outpost on d5, and a whole lot of problems with space in return. }
6. Bxc4 Nd7
{ Black is looking to play ...Nb6-d5. The other knight can go to e7 and f5. Or, Black can play ...Nb6 and then ...Ne7-d5, because the kingside pieces lack space. }
7. Nge2
{ A very important idea to remember: the knight prefers being exactly here, not on f3, because it can go to g3 and support the f2-f4-f5 and h2-h4-h5 pawn pushes. }
7... Nb6 8. Bb3
{ Of course, White keeps the bishop on the board. It's important to remember that:  we have more space, so trades aren't good overall; the light-squared bishop is our 'better' one, as unlike the dark-squared one, it's not restricted by the pawns; Black's bishop on f5 is a target for all kinds of harassments, such as f2-f4-f5, h2-h4-h5, Ng3, maybe g2-g4, and so on. }
8... Ne7 9. Nf4
{ This is another interesting plan. But, as you know, I prefer playing a bit differently. White's idea is to control the d5-square, so that if Black wants to go ...Nd5, White can surprisingly trade, making the opponent change the pawn structure in a very unfavorable way.   9.Ng3  Bg6  10.h4!  is the theoretical recommendation. }
9... Ned5
{ Quite a lot of strong players, including Le Quang Liem and Daniil Dubov, continued this way as Black. However, I consider it a very suspicious idea exactly because of what White did in this game. }
10. Ncxd5 Nxd5 11. Nxd5
{ Black is forced to give us a strong pawn majority on the kingside. } 11...
exd5
{ Now, White can easily make a ton of progress on the kingside with f2-f4, Bc2, f4-f5!, and then Qh5, f5-f6, Rf3-g3, etc, whenever ready.   11...cxd5?  12.Ba4+!  is, of course, a disaster! }
12. O-O h5
{ I am not sure if I understand this move. Black is making room for the bishop, while also preventing the move g2-g4. But, White had no desire to play g2-g4! Instead, White just wanted to trade bishops and push f2-f4-f5, grabbing a decisive amount of space on the kingside. So, Black seems to have simply weakened the position, making it harder to safely afford kingside castling. }
13. Bc2 { Of course, White keeps pursuing the aforementioned plan! } 13... Qd7
{ Although Black's position is already very bad, there are always faster and slower ways of losing these bad positions. And Black finds a great resilient move, showing White that in order to trade bishops, White will need to capture on f5, helping Black activate the queen and control the f5-square!   13...Bxc2  14.Qxc2  would greatly help White, as it would 'unblock' the f5-square, making the f2-f4-f5 push much easier to accomplish.  14...Be7  15.f4  O-O ?  16.f5+-  leads to a dead lost position for Black. How would Rf3-h3, Qe2, etc, be stopped? Of course, that isn't possible. Playing ...g7-g6 is not good, as it hangs the g6-pawn. But even if that move wasn't hanging a pawn, we could always meet it f5-f6!, reaching a dominant position. }
14. Bg5
{ White finds a very clever move. The thing is that the f8-bishop doesn't have a lot of squares to go to. And if it goes to e7, White will take it, creating circumstances where Black doesn't really have a single pleasant way of recapturing back! }
14... Be7 { This move is rather awkard to make, but what else can Black do? }
15. Bxf5 { Black has to give up castling rights! } 15... Qxf5 16. Bxe7 Kxe7
{ Of course, the king on e7 doesn't feel comfortable at all. } 17. Qb3
{ Black isn't getting a single minute of a break. If Black managed to get the rook away from h8 and play ...Kf8-g8, the position would be somewhat awkward, but still playable. However, that's not going to happen! }
17... Qd7
{ Black brings the queen back, trying to avoid the weakening pawn moves.   ➢  17...Rab8?  just blunders a pawn.  18.Qa3+  and the a7-pawn falls, giving White a winning position.   ➢  17...Rhb8  doesn't lose any material on the spot but after  18.Qb4+!  ,  preventing the king from escaping via f8-g8,  18...Ke8  19.Rae1+-  ,  with Re3, Rfe1 and e5-e6! coming up, and the black king stuck in the center, the position is by no means acceptable! }
18. Rae1
{ White gets the last piece in the game. Next, White is ready to follow up with f2-f4-f5 and f5-f6 or e5-e6, tearing the black king's shelter apart. }
18... h4 19. f4 g6
{ Black needs to somehow slow down, if not completely prevent, White's kingside advance. However, that's not exactly possible. }
20. Qd3
{ As you can see, f4-f5! cannot be prevented, at least not without huge material damage. }
20... Qe6
{ This move doesn't help stop White's plan, and now things are starting to collapse.   20...Qf5  stops the f4-f5 break but accepts the endgame with a bad pawn structure. However, White doesn't even have to take. Instead, I'd prefer to go  21.Qa3+!  Ke8  22.Rf3!  The rook on h8 is stuck, and the queenside is about to be attacked more with Rb3, Qd6, and so on. The position isn't literally falling apart on the spot, but it definitely remains very dangerous! }
21. f5 gxf5 22. Rxf5
{ White has several threats, such as:  putting more pressure on the f7-pawn with Ref1 and Qf3; bringing the rook to f6 in order to kick the Black queen @@StartBracket@@and important defender!@@EndBracket@@ out; bringing the queen to the attack via a3-d6. }
22... Rag8
{ 22...Rhf8  ,  Black can try defending with this rook, the point being to keep the other one on a8 to avoid losing a pawn to Qa3+. However, given how weak the king is, it doesn't seem as though the pawn is particularly important.  23.Rf6  Qg4  24.Ref1+-  .  With Qa3-d6 coming next, Black is totally paralyzed. }
23. Ref1
{ White is ready to pick the a7-pawn with Qa3+ on the next turn, but, of course, White can also choose to just continue creating threats against the black king. }
23... Rg7 24. Qb3
{ Before winning a pawn, White chooses to create another tiny threat − this time, to the b7-pawn.   24.Qa3+  would have been the easiest way to win.  24...Ke8  25.Qxa7  and it's not just an extra pawn. Black's main problem is that we keep creating threats, such as Qxb7, or Qb8+, winning the h8-rook, or even Rf6, Qa3, Rd6, or e5-e6 when the time is right. }
24... b6
{ 24...Rb8  would only make things worse, as after  25.Qa3+  Ke8  26.Qxa7  ,  White wins not only a pawn but also a tempo by attacking the black rook. }
25. Qa3+
{ Finally, it's time to convert the dominant attacking position into a material advantage. }
25... Ke8 26. Qxa7 Rhg8 27. Kh1
{ No need to run into a check!   27.a3??  is an example of what happens if you stop paying attention in a winning position, even for just one move!  27...Rxg2+  28.Kh1  Qxf5!!  and White cannot take the queen due to checkmate in one move with ...Rg1+, so White is lucky to still be able to bail out with a perpetual check! Be careful out there! }
27... f6
{ Black tries the last trick, sneakily attacking the queen on a7 with the rook!   27...Rxg2??  doesn't work, of course, due to the simple  28.Qb8+!  Ke7  29.Rxf7+  Qxf7  30.Qc7+  and White takes the queen on the next turn. But not the rook, as that would blunder checkmate in one move with ...Rxg1! }
28. Qxb6
{ 28.exf6??  Rxa7  is another example of having to pay attention until the very end! }
28... Rxg2 29. Rxf6
{ And Black resigned since he cannot stop all the attacking threats, such as Qb8+, or Qc5 and Rf8+, or Qxc6+, or e5-e6-e7. Of course, the white king is perfectly safe − Black doesn't have a single check. As you can see, once White forced the opponent to capture ...exd5 and got an impressive pawn majority on the kingside, the position became incredible, and the rest of the game was really one-sided! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "16) Caro-Kann 3.e5 Bf5 − Model Games"]
[Black "Ivan Cheparinov − Ervin Ozkan, Skopje 2013"]
[Result "*"]

{ This game is a showcase of why it's dangerous to go ...Nd7 and allow White to open up the c-file with cxd5, forcing ...cxd5 when the knight can no longer go to c6, helping block the c-file, and occupying an active position at the same time. }
1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. h4
{ White chooses a slightly different theoretical variation, but the position is very similar to the one we are studying in the theoretical chapter. In fact, soon enough, the game just transposes to our theory! }
4... h5 5. c4 e6 6. Nc3 Nd7
{ As you know from the theoretical chapter, although this is a rather frequent move, I am quite the opposite of a big fan of it. I think it's very suspicious for Black to develop the knight here when there is still tension in the center, and White's next move, as well as the entire game overall, show why. }
7. cxd5
{ The timing of this exchange is literally perfect. Black's problem is that going ...exd5, giving White the pawn majority in the center, is typically very bad − see the previous model game to understand why. However, after ...cxd5, the knight on d7 is extremely misplaced, as it cannot help block the c-file, and it cannot put pressure on the d4-pawn, or do anything else remotely useful. }
7... cxd5
{ 7...exd5  8.Bd3  Bxd3  9.Qxd3  will be followed with f2-f4-f5, which would cause Black a lot of problems. See the previous game for convincing proof of that! }
8. Bd3
{ White trades the bishops in order to speed up development − after all, the game has opened up quite a bit! Also, with Black's pawn already on h5, White can try to use it as a target with moves like Ne2-f4, making it difficult for Black to ever dare to castle kingside. }
8... Bxd3 9. Qxd3 Ne7
{ Black's kingside pieces don't have a lot of room, as you can see. For example, a natural question is, where should the e7-knight go? To c6 to block the c-file, but abandoning the kingside? Or to f5, helping put some pressure on h4 and shielding the kingside, but abandoning the other flank? }
10. Nf3
{ White just keeps developing. One of Black's problems is that the h5-pawn and the g5-square are both extremely weak. For example, if Black castles kingside, we can go Ne2-f4, attacking the h5-pawn, and it's not obvious how Black would be dealing with that.   10.Bg5!  seems like an even better move to me because now, Black cannot easily move the kingside pieces again!  10...Qb6  is the only move that could have potentially dissuaded White from developing the dark-squared bishop since now the b2-pawn appears to be hanging. However, that pawn can be easily ignored.    11.Nf3!  Qxb2?  This is a very bad capture. Not only Black is not going to keep the extra pawn, but he is also helping White open up the files, which is very beneficial only to White, as development is much more impressive.  12.Rb1  Qa3  13.Rxb7+-  .  Black is in a dead bind. Next, White can go O-O, involve the other rook via b1, maybe at some point unpin the c3-knight with Rb3 and play Nd5, looking to jump into d6 or c7. Poor Black! }
10... Nb6
{ Black is trying to make room on d7 for the queen, but I find this plan to be very suspicious since the knight already moved twice, but it won't be doing much here either: if it ever comes to c4, it would just get kicked out with b2-b3!   10...Nf5  seems like a better path, focusing on developing the kingside pieces. However, this move allows a little cute tactic, made possible by the fact the knight on f5 is a bit loose.  11.Bg5  Be7  12.Nxd5!  The knight on f5 would hang if Black takes back! So, Black needs to settle for  12...Nxe5□  13.dxe5  Qxd5  14.Qxd5  exd5⩲  when White gets a very pleasant endgame with a weak isolated pawn on d5. At the same time, this is by no means a disaster for Black, the position is just somewhat worse. }
11. Bg5
{ Of course, White's bishop is very glad to go to this square, which I call 'semi-outpost': technically speaking, Black could at some point kick it out with ...f7-f6, but realistically, that's not happening any time soon. And, of course, White creates a rather annoying pin. It can be dealt with, but it's still fairly irritating that Black needs to waste time doing that. }
11... Qd7 12. O-O
{ Having castled, White can start toying with ideas such as Rc1 and Nb5, looking to invade to d6 or c7. }
12... a6 { Black prevents that. } 13. Rac1
{ The rook still wants to come to the only open file, of course. } 13... Nf5
14. Ne2
{ And the knight is on its merry way too. First of all, with this move, White opens up the c-file for the rook. Secondly, the knight can either go to f4, putting pressure on the h5-pawn or maybe even to g3, getting rid of Black's only semi-active piece: the f5-knight! }
14... Be7
{ Black, of course, is very willing to trade down and finally finish development. However, although it is likely that some pieces will be traded, Black won't be able to castle, all because of that h5-pawn, which requires constant babysitting! }
15. Ng3
{ White tries to take advantage of the fact that Black is very passive on the kingside by opening up the files. }
15... g6
{ Black tries to keep the knight on f5 alive. But, now the pawn structure gets changed in an unfavorable way.   15...Nxg3  16.fxg3+-  is a completely lost position for Black, because next, we will play Rc2-f2, trade the bishops, install the knight on g5, and the f7 and h7-squares will collapse. }
16. Nxf5
{ If Black takes with the e-pawn, the one on d5 becomes much weaker. Also, if Black ever plays ...exf5, then we can play Rfe1 and try to push e5-e6! at some point, tearing the position apart. Instead, in the event of ...gxf5, the pawn on h5 becomes much weaker. }
16... gxf5 17. Bxe7 Qxe7 18. Ng5
{ This knight is greatly enjoying being on an outpost, of course. Next, White can double the rooks on the c-file and invade on c7. Black's problem is that castling kingside is a luxury since the h5-pawn is too weak, and after Qf3-Qxh5, White would simply checkmate! So, the rook on h8 is not able to participate in the game, which means Black won't challenge our plan of dominating the c-file. }
18... Kf8 19. Rc3 Rc8 20. Rfc1
{ Nice and simple. The fight for the c-file is inevitably going to be won by White and in no time. }
20... Rc4 21. b3
{ Of course, we don't need to capture the rook, allowing the opponent to favorably change the pawn structure with ...dxc4, winning an outpost on d5 for the knight. }
21... Rxc3 22. Rxc3 Ke8 23. Qc2
{ White is getting ready to make decisive progress by invading on c7. } 23...
Kd8
{ This temporarily addresses the threat of invasion, but of course, doesn't solve all of Black's problems. }
24. a4
{ This is also a great path. White is threatening to kick the knight out with a4-a5 and then invade on c8 with the rook.   24.Rc5!  ,  with a huge threat of Qc3 and Qa5!, pinning the poor loose knight on b6 and winning it, would have been even more convincing. }
24... Rf8 25. a5 Na8 26. Nh7
{ Black resigned since on top of the other problems, White's knight will invade on f6. For example, now the threat is Rc8+ followed by Nf6+, and Black cannot really stop that. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "16) Caro-Kann 3.e5 Bf5 − Model Games"]
[Black "Julian Radulski − Robert Hafner, Lienz 2011"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ In this game, we will see how a strong Bulgarian Grandmaster kept slowly improving his pieces' positions in a standard closed Caro structure, until the opponent gave him an opportunity to swiftly switch to pressuring Black's kingside. Once that happened, the collapse occurred in no time! }
1... c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. c4
{ Let me remind you what is the point of this move, its advantages and cons.  We are ambitiously fighting for the center and space, placing another pawn in the center. By doing so, we make room for our pieces: for example, now it makes sense to have a knight on c3. Potentially, we can release the tension with cxd5, opening up the c-file when we'd like, or push c4-c5, grabbing a lot of space on the kingside. The most obvious visual downside of this move is that Black can seemingly take ...dxc4, and when that happens, we get a 'hole' on d5 − this central square becomes an outpost for Black's pieces.  
So, how come our move is one of White's most promising weapons in the Advance Variation? Why isn't it a large positional mistake? How poorly do you need to misunderstand chess to voluntarily provide wonderful outposts in the center for your opponents? Actually, there is no problem here, and here is why.  To explain this, I'd use Dvoretsky's phrase 'redundant pieces'. What did the greatest chess coach of all time mean by that? Well, here's the deal. Imagine you have 3 pieces that want to use this wonderful outpost on d5. But only one piece can be there at a time! So, what are the other two doing? Exactly − nothing!   The idea is that as long as we keep a lot of pieces on the board, our e5-pawn will provide us a considerable spatial advantage, and Black would be restricted. Black would be able to place one of the pieces  (likely a knight)  on the d5-square, but the rest of the pieces will be passive. Also, importantly, the d5-outpost, while lovely, isn't threatening to us. The knight just looks good there, but it's not deep enough in our territory for it to be threatening in any way! To summarize, we are fighting for space, and in return are happy to let ONE Black piece feel good. }
4... e6 5. Nc3 Ne7
{ Black is choosing the most popular and solid line. He is keeping the tension in the center, getting ready to take on d5 with the knight if possible. }
6. Nf3 Nd7 7. h3
{ As I explain in the theoretical chapter, I find this a very interesting and promising theoretical path. Actually, I recommend making this move before Nf3, in order to never allow the pin ...Bg4, but White got to the same place via a slightly different move order. The idea is that the black bishop can never go to g4, annoyingly pinning the knight, and making room on f5 for the knight.   7.cxd5  ,  unlike in the position without a knight on e7, it doesn't really make sense to trade on d5 soon, as after  7...Nxd5  8.Nxd5  cxd5  ,  although the knight on d7 seems a bit passive, Black managed to trade a pair of pieces and is about to trade more with ...Bb4+ and ...Qa5+, solving the space shortage problems. }
7... Bg6
{ With this move, Black is making room on f5 for the knight since the kingside pieces need to somehow get out! }
8. Be2 dxc4
{ If Black were to ever trade on c4, that should be done exactly now: by delaying this move, Black made White capture on c4 by wasting two bishop moves @@StartBracket@@Bf1-e2-xc4@@EndBracket@@, not one! As we know, this trade helps White activate the bishop and get a considerable amount of extra space. However, one of the reasons why Black feels tempted to give up the most useful central pawn is not just because Black gets an outpost on d5, but also, because it's hard to get the kingside pieces out without that trade. }
9. Bxc4 Nd5
{ Black is happy to occupy this outpost, preparing to go ...Be7 and castle kingside. }
10. O-O Be7
{ Unfortunately, since our knight is on f3 and not on e2, it's not possible anymore to play for the f2-f4-f5 pawn advance, aimed at removing Black's e6-pawn, which helps stabilize the center. However, that's okay. White has other plans in mind, such as using the squares on c5, d6, and g5 to place the knights and bishop very nicely! }
11. Re1
{ With this move, which might at first seem a bit mysterious, White achieves a few things: it discourages any ...f7-f6 related pawn breaks; White makes it possible to install the knight on e4. }
11... O-O 12. Ne4 h6
{ Black takes the g5-square under control, while also making room for the bishop.   12...Bxe4?  Black has less space, which makes trades attractive overall. But not this attractive! The problem is that after  13.Rxe4  ,  White is ready to swing the rook over to g4, then go Bd3, Bc2, Qd3, h3-h4, Ng5, and so on, bringing every single piece to attack the opponent's king! Additionally, after Rg4, White could also choose a faster path − Ng5 and Qh5! }
13. Bd2
{ The bishop doesn't seem very active here, but it didn't have many other places to go to. Next, White can play Rc1, and potentially a2-a3, b2-b4, and Nc5, installing the knight on a wonderful square. Of course, one of White's dreams in this position would be to trade the dark-squared bishops and install the knight on d6. }
13... N5b6
{ It's not exactly obvious to me, what is the point of this move, besides the obvious attack on the white bishop. If it retreats, what would the black knight do on b6? Going there with the other knight, the passive one, would have made way more sense.   13...N7b6  would have kept the d5-knight on an active position, which is more logical. }
14. Ba5
{ White could just retreat, but it's even better to pin the knight this way. While the pin itself is not particularly dangerous, the upside of having a bishop on a5 is that Black can no longer try grabbing space on the queenside with ...a7-a5-a4. }
14... Qb8
{ Black wants to unpin, and the queen did not have a lot of attractive squares to go to. }
15. Bd3
{ Of course, the bishop was actually hanging now, so it retreats. Next, White should try to go Rc1 and eventually install the knight on c5. But, it would be better to do that while keeping the light-squared bishops on the board, of course. }
15... Nd5 16. Rc1
{ The knight is ready to jump on c5. If Black ever takes it, after dxc5, we'd have a gorgeous outpost on d6, which we will be able to make use of with Nd2-c4-d6, for example. Although it might seem as though making progress isn't very easy, I want you to pay close attention to how the black queen and rooks are positioned. The opponent is literally completely stuck! Of course, it is also worth reminding that with the last move, White discourages the ...c6-c5 break. }
16... b6
{ Black cannot tolerate this stuck-up back-rank situation any longer and tries to make room for the queen on b7, which would allow coordinating the rooks. That's a logical and fair decision. However, it comes at a cost of weakening the c6-pawn. }
17. Bd2 Qb7 18. Qe2
{ White tries to get to the a6-square from another angle.   18.Qa4!  looks like a potential improvement to me. Black's huge problem is not the weakness of the c6-pawn. It's the fact that White is about to go Ba6!, taking advantage of the weak square, and making the move ...Rc8 impossible. For instance, after  18...b5  19.Qd1  ,  Black does manage to prevent that threat; however in order to do that, is forced to weaken the c5-square and the c6-pawn even more. }
18... a6 19. Ng3
{ Now that Black had weakened all the queenside pawns, and even more importantly, drove the queen so far away from the kingside, White figures it's time to try to do damage elsewhere: White wants to trade the light-squared bishops, go Qe4-g4, Nh5, and launch a kingside attack! It might seem like a very unexpected direction for the game to take, but it's a really logical one: all of White's pieces, even including the rook on e1, can easily join the attack, while Black cannot easily  (or at all!)  get any defenders to the kingside. }
19... Bxd3 20. Qxd3 c5
{ The opponent tries getting counterplay by breaking up the center, which is very logical. However, it might not be fast enough! }
21. Nh5
{ With Qe4-g4, or Re4-g4 knocking at the king's door, Black definitely isn't feeling safe here. }
21... cxd4 22. Nxd4 Kh8
{ Black tries to walk the king away from dangers on the g-file, eliminating the threat.   22...b5??  If Black were to skip a turn, White would have an instant win! How so?  23.Qg3!  g6  24.Nxe6!  The position collapses, since  24...fxe6??  25.Qxg6+  Kh8  26.Qg7  is a checkmate, of course. }
23. Nxe6
{ White goes for the most ambitious and principled continuation, trying to deprive Black of any ability to control the g6-square so that the queen can jump in there.   23.Qf3  was also possible, continuing the attack in a slower manner, preparing Qg4, and putting pressure on the kingside in a standard way. }
23... fxe6 24. Qg6
{ Not only is there a threat of checkmate on g7, but also, a bishop sacrifice on h6 is coming up! }
24... Rg8 { Of course, Black has no choice but to stop checkmate in one move. }
25. Bxh6
{ However, the g7-square is still under so much pressure! White keeps attacking and already has two pawns for the sacrificed piece. For all this activity, and given how vulnerable the black king is, seems like a ton of compensation! }
25... Bf8
{ Again, the g7-square needed to be protected.  25...gxh6??  26.Qxh6  is, of course, also a checkmate. }
26. Bg5
{ Here, Black still could somehow survive, according to the engine, by going ...Bc5 and preparing the odd move ...Nf8!, which kicks the white queen out. But, of course, that's a very difficult idea to find − and even if you see it, it's not obvious if Black is surviving there. However, in the game, things go downhill right away. }
26... Be7
{ A fatal mistake. Black was still in time to defend with  26...Bc5  , when the same line as in the game:  27.Nf6  N7xf6  28.exf6  is not working due to  28...gxf6  and the queen  on b7 is no longer obstructed by the bishop on e7. }
27. Nf6
{ Unfortunately, Black can hardly stop the threat of mate in one with Qh7 or Qh5. }
27... N7xf6 28. exf6
{ Again, there is a mating threat of Qh5. There is no stopping it − taking on f6 with the knight only delays it by one move, as White would simply trade that defender off. So, Black resigned.  It's a very interesting game because it shows a rather unusual plan: White was in no rush to build a kingside attack. Instead, he kept improving the pieces, caused the opponent to weaken the queenside and move all the pieces over there, and then, all of a sudden, quickly developed a powerful initiative on the other flank! }
