[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "16) Caro-Kann 3.e5 Bf5 − Model Games"]
[Black "Marian Petrov − Mario Schachinger, Vienna 2011"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. c4 e6 5. Nc3 Ne7 6. h3
{ Again, White uses the rare variation that I am suggesting. By making this move, White covers up the g4-square, making it possible to go Nf3 without ever running into an annoying pin ...Bg4, which would help Black free up the f5-square for the knight and put more pressure on our center.  Overall, of course, it's best to play Nge2-g3 in these positions, however, it's hard to do that when the c4-pawn is still under attack, since Black tends to always meet Nge2 with ...dxc4!, trying to then hold on to that pawn. But, if Black ever captures on c4, or we don't need to deal with ...dxc4 anymore for some other reason, then we want to go Nge2-g3, chasing the bishop away, winning time, and keeping the options of f2-f4-f5, or h2-h4-h5 open.   6.Nf3  Bg4  is the idea we need to worry about if we skip the prophylactic move h2-h3. }
6... dxc4
{ Black chooses to release the tension in the center, which is a fair plan. By the way, of 4 games that arrived at this position, 3 of them have been played by the same player: the Bulgarian GM Marian Petrov. As you can see, he really likes the subtle 6.h3 system, so make sure to check out his games! }
7. Bxc4 Nd7 8. Nge2
{ As I had explained earlier, the knight would always prefer this square if White no longer needs to worry about ...dxc4. }
8... Nb6 9. Bb3
{ As I explain in the theoretical chapter and previous model games, we do not want to trade the light-squared bishops since we have more space, and because the opponent's bishop on f5 is going to run into multiple harassing moves, such as Ng3, h4-h5, and so on. }
9... Ned5
{ By bringing exactly this knight to d5, Black unblocks the f8-bishop, getting ready to play ...Be7 and castle kingside, finishing development.   9...Nbd5  ,  it might be natural to place this knight on d5, but what to do with the one on e7?! }
10. O-O Be7 11. Ng3
{ The bishop is being tucked away, which allows White to win even more time. }
11... Bg6 12. Nce4
{ Instead of trying to make progress on the kingside by using the f-pawn, which is a plan we discuss in the 12.f4 sideline, White prefers bringing more pieces to that part of the board.   12.f4  seems like another very attractive plan to me. White, naturally, wants to go f4-f5 and open up the f-file for the pieces. How should Black handle that? Let's explore!  12...O-O   12...Qd7!  Black should absolutely try to discourage the f4-f5 push at almost any cost.  13.Qf3  ,  let's see what happens if we insist.  13...f5!  With this move, Black achieves and gives up several things.  Black prevents f4-f5; Black leaves the knight on g3 very misplaced. However, this moves also comes at a large cost: the g6-bishop is killed, the e6-pawn becomes much weaker, and Black gives up the option of undermining the center with ...f7-f6.  
I think this position is also playable and interesting, but the fact that Black can play ...f7-f5 shows that it might be a bit useless to try to make f2-f4-f5 work just yet.  13.f5!  exf5  14.Nxf5↑  .  This position, where the rook on f1 is beyond happy, and the g6-bishop is so restricted, looks great to me. Next, we can play Qg4, h3-h4-h5, Nce4, and improve our pieces even more, creating unpleasant tension on the kingside. Black should definitely avoid this outcome by all means! }
12... O-O 13. Qg4
{ The queen is also coming over! With h3-h4-h5, Bg5, or Nh5 coming next, it seems as though Black should be rather worried about the safety of the kingside. }
13... Qc8
{ It is not obvious to me what the black queen is doing here. In hindsight, it turned out Black made this move in order to prepare the ...f7-f6 or ...f7-f5 break, and was trying to make sure the e6-pawn won't end up hanging. However, I consider this move suspicious, as it drives the queen further away from the kingside. }
14. Nh5
{ 14.h4!  seems even stronger. The problem is that since the black queen is no longer on d8, the h4-square is no longer sufficiently controlled by Black! ...h7-h5 cannot be played either. Of course, the threat is h4-h5, nearly trapping the bishop, followed by h5-h6!, making the opponent tremendously weaken the dark squares.    14...Bxe4  15.Nxe4  Kh8!  Black needs to prevent Bh6 by unpinning the h-pawn, however, this position looks very bad.  16.h5  ,  White is threatening h5-h6, obviously. If Black stops that, we can keep improving the position with f2-f4, Rf3-g3, maybe Bc2 at some point, and so on. The opponent had to give up the bishop pair, has no space, and not a single piece is doing anything useful. This clearly looks wonderful! }
14... f5
{ Black weakens the pawn structure but makes room on the 7th rank for the pieces − for example, now the rook can come to f7 and protect the g7-square. }
15. exf6 gxf6 16. Qe2
{ First of all, Black wanted to go ...f6-f5 and fork our queen and knight. But more importantly, by weakening the pawn structure, Black managed to get rid of the powerful e5-pawn, which was making it difficult to bring the pieces over to the kingside, for example via the f6-square. So, we no longer have hopes of getting a powerful kingside attack. However, what we can easily do is start putting pressure on the position by using the weak squares, such as h6, and weak pawns, such as f6 and e6. }
16... Qe8 17. Nhg3
{ 17.Nf4!  seems even better. The point is to put pressure on the e6-pawn. Next, White can follow up with Nc5, attacking the e6-pawn with that knight and the e2-queen as well. On the other hand, if Black trades the knights, the e6-pawn still remains very weak.  17...Nxf4  18.Bxf4  Nd5?  19.Bh6±  and after Nc5 coming next, it seems as though Black's position is close to collapsing. }
17... Kh8
{ Black tries to walk the king away, so that the e6-pawn won't ever be taken with check, and so that the rook could come to g8 at some point if needed. }
18. Bh6 Rg8 19. Nc5
{ White is changing the pawn structure. Attacking the e6 and b7-pawns is forcing Black to give up the bishop pair. }
19... Bxc5 20. dxc5 Nd7
{ What can we say about this pawn structure? Now, there is again an outpost on d6; Black's e6-pawn might not seem that weak anymore, as it seems as though Black can always go ...e6-e5, preventing any attacks on the e-file.  However, if Black ever does go ...e6-e5, the f5-square will become much weaker. And, of course, if Black ever went ...f6-f5, the e5-square would also become really weak. So, for the time being, Black needs to keep dealing with weak-ish pawns. }
21. Rac1 { Of course, the c5-pawn needs to be protected. } 21... Qe7 22. Be3
{ White doesn't mind letting go of the bishop pair because doing that means Black has to get rid of the best piece − the centralized knight on an outpost. Also, once that knight disappears, the e6-pawn becomes much weaker. }
22... Nxe3
{ Black had to keep the knight alive, as it was helping restrict the b3-bishop. The white dark-squared bishop, on the other hand, wasn't doing much. Now, the e6-pawn is just extremely weak. }
23. Qxe3 Rge8 24. Rfd1
{ The rook could attack the pawn from e1, but it's much better to do that from a lovely outpost on d6, where it also helps fight for the d-file! }
24... Nf8
{ The poor black pieces need to keep retreating, which isn't fun at all. } 25.
Rd6 Qg7 26. h4
{ The bishop is about to get chased away with h4-h5 too. Also, at some point, the pawn could go all the way to h6, creating a mating net and taking the g7-square away from the black pieces. }
26... h6 27. Re1 { The e6-pawn doesn't get a break even for a second. } 27...
Bf7 28. Bc2
{ White decides it's not possible to actually win the e6-pawn and is trying to find a better place for the light-squared bishop. }
28... Bg6 29. Bd1
{ No trades are going to happen! The black pieces are so passive, they lack purpose, so why trade? }
29... Re7 30. b4 a6 31. a4 { Time to make progress on the queenside too! }
31... f5
{ Black tries improving the queen by opening up the a1-h8 diagonal, but this decision only weakens the position further: now, the e5 and f4-squares are outposts for the white pieces, and the g6-bishop is very restricted. }
32. Ne2 Rae8 33. Nf4
{ Black is absolutely paralyzed. Later on, as both parties got in a bit of time trouble, things got messy, and White won 20 moves later. I have decided to cut the game off here, as the rest is not particularly relevant to our interests. The key takeaways?  White can build up kingside play without any hurry. Playing ...f7-f6, asking for exf6 gxf6, helps Black stop an immediate kingside attack, but results in a rather sad position with long-term weaknesses on e6 and f6, and therefore is not a particularly appealing plan − rather one Black uses out of despair. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "17) Caro 3.e5 c5 and 3...g6 − Model Games"]
[Black "Vladimir Potkin − Xavier Alanic, Barcelona 2013"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ In this game, we will see how an experienced Russian GM demonstrates why the ...g7-g6 setups in the Caro-Kann are not a good idea, especially against the Advance Variation. }
1... c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 g6
{ This position sometimes arises via @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  g6  2.d4  c6  ,  followed by ...d7-d5, and is usually referred to as the Gurgenidze variation of the Caro-Kann, named after the Georgian @@StartBracket@@as in a country, not a state!@@EndBracket@@ Grandmaster, who was known for his passion for offbeat sidelines.  What is Black's plan and why is Black developing the bishop on g7? In brief, the claim is that the king would be safer this way. Later on, Black would consider ideas such as ...f7-f6, ...Nh6-f7, and will do the very best to create a lot of pressure on the e5-pawn, hoping to provoke exf6 exf6. If that happens, Black would claim we got deprived of our trump: the e5-pawn.  Then a symmetrical position would arise, which would normally look only marginally worse for Black, mostly because ...f7-f6 makes the king a bit weaker and the e-file a bit looser. However, as theory has firmly established, this setup has several considerable disadvantages. Mostly, it's very passive, Black is short on space, and doesn't have any activity or threats. }
4. c4
{ Just like in the main variation, I like the idea of occupying even more space in the center. }
4... Nh6
{ Most often, Black chooses to just develop the knight, keeping the tension in the center, and avoiding any committal decisions, such as ...f7-f6. }
5. Nc3 Bg7 { Unfortunately, Black's bishop is going to be very passive on g7. }
6. Bf4
{ This, of course, is also a perfectly reasonable way of playing. It's important to remember that the knight on h6 doesn't have a lot of squares, and especially if we go h2-h3 and g2-g4, after Qd2, it could end up trapped.   6.cxd5!  is the path I suggest in the theoretical chapter. The point is that this way, Black can never choose to take on c4 and play ...Nf5, attacking the d4-pawn. Black is also deprived of the ..c6-c5 break, and given how little space there is on the kingside, and how restricted the h6-knight and the g7-bishop are, Black clearly won't be having that much fun.  6...cxd5  7.Bf4±  .  Black has no way to put any pressure on our center, the kingside pieces are very restricted, and Black has no space. }
6... dxc4
{ As usual in all the Caro-Kann positions we study, this capture is helping White activate the bishop. And, of course, Black has to concede space. }
7. Bxc4 Nf5
{ Black tries to make at least one active move and is now attacking the d4-pawn. However, that threat is very easy to neutralize. And, as you can see, because of that knight on f5, the c8-bishop cannot get out. }
8. Nf3 O-O 9. Qd2
{ This is a natural move and a very good one. But, somewhat surprisingly, I believe White could have nearly finished the opponent off right away, had he played more energetically!   9.g4!?  looks even stronger to me. The point is that after  9...Nh6  10.h3  ,  Qd2, trapping and winning the black knight, is a huge threat. I am having a hard time understanding how Black will be stopping that! For instance, after the only  10...Kh8  11.Qd2  Ng8  12.O-O-O+-  ,  it seems as though Rdg1, followed by h3-h4-h5, should easily checkmate the black king in no time.  Of course, White has plenty of other attractive ideas as well, such as Ng5, attacking the f7-pawn and provoking the extremely weakening move ...e7-e6, which makes the d6 and f6-squares wonderful outposts for the white knights. Black is done! }
9... h5
{ This move is tremendously weakening the black king overall, and the g5-square, to be more specific, but Black felt desperate to prevent the g2-g4 ideas. }
10. h3
{ However, White isn't giving up on the plan of making that pawn break work! Of course, g2-g4 is about to win the knight on the very next move. }
10... c5
{ Black is desperately trying to solve the problems of the f5-knight by making it possible for it to jump to d4.   10...h4?  stops the threat of g2-g4, but still results in a lost position since that pawn will soon get lost.  11.Rd1  ,  first, White overprotects the d4-pawn and then can choose among many attractive options. The simplest plan would be to go Bg5 and just snatch that free pawn on h4! }
11. d5
{ However, White gets a decisive amount of center. Black is already completely lost! }
11... e6 12. d6
{ Of course, the protected passed pawn on d6 alone is enough for a decisive positional advantage. The good news for Black is that he now can access the c6-square, which enables him to try to go ...Nc6 and ...Nd4. }
12... Nd4
{ In order to get at least some play, Black decides to sacrifice a pawn.   12...Nc6  ,  however, this move doesn't help much. For instance, White can go  13.Ne4  and attack the c5-pawn. After  13...b6  14.Bg5!  ,  the f6-square turns out a huge problem.  14...Qe8  15.Nf6+  Bxf6  16.Bxf6+-  and with g2-g4 and Qh6 coming next, the black king, unsurprisingly, gets mated in no time. }
13. Nxd4 cxd4 14. Qxd4
{ White is, of course, happy to accept. The problem for the opponent is that he doesn't have any pieces on active squares. The only thing we need to be very careful about is the health and safety of our e5-pawn. With a combination of moves ...Nc6 and ...Qa5, we could accidentally lose it. }
14... Qa5 15. Qe4
{ White retreats in advance, so ...Nc6 doesn't win a tempo and that e-pawn. }
15... Nc6 16. Bb5
{ With this move, White blocks the 5th rank, preventing the opponent's queen from attacking the e5-pawn. If needed, White would gladly trade on c6. Please note that keeping this pawn alive is important for several reasons:  Just like any extra pawn, we don't want to lose it. It keeps the d6-pawn so strong. The g7-bishop will be dead, as long as the e5-pawn is alive. }
16... Bd7 17. O-O a6
{ Black is forcing the trade on c6, but Potkin isn't bothered by that, of course. }
18. Bxc6 Bxc6 19. Qe3
{ The e5-pawn is perfectly safe. Next, White should overprotect it with Re1, and maybe trade the dark-squared bishops. Although the bishop on g7 is very passive, which means any conversation about the bishop pair is sort of pointless, it does one valuable thing: it protects the f6-square! If that bishop disappears, White could actually develop a powerful kingside attack with Ne4-f6 and Qg5 or Qh6! }
19... Qb4
{ Black creates at least one threat, after all: to take the b2-pawn. } 20. a3
{ White could have easily addressed that threat, but determines there is nothing to worry about.   20.Rab1  was also good and simple enough to just protect the b2-pawn, but White isn't bothered. }
20... Qxb2 21. Ra2
{ Now, the queen is trapped, on top of Black's other problems! Game over. }
21... Qb3 22. Rb1 Qc4 23. Rb4
{ As you can see, Black has not managed to make a single active move in this game. The bishop on g7 never managed to spring to life. And the struggle of that knight on h6 caused Black to start giving up the material very early on, which immediately resulted in a lost position. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "17) Caro 3.e5 c5 and 3...g6 − Model Games"]
[Black "Andrey Zhigalko − Manuel Jose Reales Murto, Spanish League 2013 "]
[Result "*"]

{ This game starts as the English but soon transposes into our line of the Caro-Kann. }
1. c4
{ 1.e4  c6  2.d4  d5  3.e5  c5  4.Nf3  Nc6  5.c4  e6  is the way we get this position, of course. }
1... c6 2. e4 e6 3. d4 d5 4. e5 c5 5. Nf3
{ With a somewhat weird move order, White got to the Caro-Kann with @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp2pppp/2p5/3p4/3PP3/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq d6 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.e5  c5  , which is the more recent and trendy direction, as opposed to the @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp2pppp/2p5/3p4/3PP3/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq d6 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.e5  Bf5  main lines.  However, the system where Black has to play ...e7-e6 doesn't seem particularly appealing. The point of playing  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp2pppp/2p5/3p4/3PP3/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq d6 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.e5  c5  , after all, is all about getting the French-type position without  locking in the bishop on c8, at least just yet. Here, Black already did that! }
5... Nc6
{ The white center is a bit fragile. We always need to keep in mind the option of ...cxd4 followed by ...Nxe5. In the theoretical chapter, we discuss in detail why it's often very dangerous to accept that pawn. Typically, it's not just dangerous, but outright awful. However, another good direction White can take, instead of keeping the tension in the center, is to release it and likely create an isolated queen's pawn in the opponent's camp. }
6. cxd5 exd5 7. Bb5
{ By pinning this knight, White not only prevents the opponent from pressuring the d4 and e5-pawns but is also developing rapidly. And, White is potentially ready to put pressure on the pinned knight with Nxd4 at some point, or Qa4. }
7... a6
{ With this move, Black gets the bishop pair but takes too much time to do that. What about developing the kingside pieces? After all, it's not a typical position with pawn chains. The center is pretty open! }
8. Bxc6+ bxc6 9. O-O
{ Now, White is ready to put pressure on the c-file, for example by playing dxc5, forcing the bishop to go to c5, and then Qc2, x-raying the bishop and the c6-pawn! }
9... c4
{ Understandably, Black tries to keep the position closed, preventing the dxc5-related ideas, which I had mentioned earlier. However, this move doesn't contribute to development, and in fact, provides another target that will help us open up the position.   9...cxd4  ,  of course, opening up the center is also very scary for Black, who is completely undeveloped.  10.Nxd4  Bd7  11.Re1  .  We can go e5-e6 whenever we want. Black's kingside pieces are sort of stuck: the knight cannot go to f6. But if it goes to e7, the bishop will be blocked inside. If the bishop goes to e7, the knight will be blocked.  So, Black's only way of developing is ...Bc5 or ...Bb4, but that doesn't help block the e-file and control the squares on the kingside, such as g5 and h4, which White can use to attack the opponent. For instance, after  11...Bb4  12.Bd2  Bxd2  13.Nxd2  Ne7  ,  White can choose between breaking through with e5-e6, which looks very powerful as well, or simply securing a strategically dominant position with  14.N2b3  O-O  15.Rc1±  .   White owns the dark squares and can proceed with Nc5, Rc3, Qd2, Rec1 and put pressure on the a6 and c6-pawns. Black has no counterplay, and the light-squared bishop is absolutely useless. }
10. b3 cxb3 11. axb3
{ Now, White also has a target on the a-file. It's going to be very easy to carry out a powerful and simple positional plan of trading the dark-squared bishops with Ba3, depriving Black not only of the bishop pair but of the ability to control the dark squares, such as c5 and d6.  Once that happens, White can easily play, for example, b3-b4, Nd2-b3-c5, double the rooks on the a-file or c-file, and slowly but surely build up pressure against the weak pawns on a6 and c6. Given the Black's light-squared bishop will be absolutely useless in that scenario, I would say that if White manages to do those things, White would have a completely winning position. }
11... Nh6
{ It seems really awkward and unfortunate that Black needs to develop the knight here since White could easily take it, making the kingside a very unsafe place for the black king to be. But, of course, going to e7 didn't seem very appealing either, because doing that would have blocked Black's f8-bishop in, forcing Black to move the knight even more, continuing to waste time.   11...Ne7  ,  although this is a slow plan, it would have arguably been the lesser evil.  12.Ba3!  I think the most logical thing for White is just swapping off the dark-squared bishops, following the plan I had described above.  12...Ng6  13.Bxf8  Nxf8  ,  Black needs to take with the knight to avoid losing castling rights.  We have spent a lifetime discussing the downsides of his position, but actually, the knight will really be well-placed on e6, where it would help control the c5-square, while also putting some pressure on the d4-pawn.  14.Qd3  ,  we put more pressure on the a6-pawn, while also making sure Black cannot ever go ...Bg4 and pin our knight.  14...Ne6  15.Rc1  Bd7  16.Nc3±  .  With Na4-c5 coming, I think it's clear that Black's position is very unappealing, however, this is the best outcome. }
12. h3
{ I feel it would have been even stronger to just ruin the opponent's pawn structure, however, restricting the black pieces, preventing ...Bg4 and ...Ng4, also looks like a good path to take.   12.Bxh6  looks like a great choice to me as well. For instance, after  12...gxh6  13.Qc2!  Bd7  14.Nc3+-  ,  with Na4-c5 coming, White could consider not only attacking the weak a6 and c6-pawns but also playing Rfe1 and trying to push e5-e6!, opening up the center. Where would Black's king escape? There isn't a single place on the board that seems to be a safe long-term haven! }
12... Nf5 13. Nc3 h5 14. Na4
{ Although it would be great to eventually trade the dark-squared bishops, White takes time to do so. The point is that it would be much nicer to go Ba3 once the black bishop had already moved − say, to e7, so that Black wastes a full tempo. }
14... Be7 15. Qc2 { The c6-pawn is a bit awkward to defend. } 15... g5
{ Desperation. Understanding that this long-term weakness makes the position strategically lost, Black tries an unexpected kingside storm. Of course, Black doesn't have enough pieces there to make it a serious attempt at anything, so White is winning in more than one way.   15...Bd7  16.Ba3  finally, White should trade the bishops, then go Nc5, and achieve an absolutely dominant position.  16...Bxa3  17.Rxa3  O-O  18.Nc5+-  .  I don't believe it's possible to save the a6-pawn. }
16. Bxg5
{ This move also works, but I am a bit surprised White didn't choose the easier path.   16.Qxc6+  seems like the laziest and easiest way to win.  16...Bd7  17.Qxd5  and White is about to capture the g5-pawn twice, looking to distract the queen from defending the rook on a8. Also, White is ready to play Qe4, taking the g4-square under control, and preparing the decisive advance of the central pawns with d4-d5-d6, or d4-d5 and e5-e6. For instance, after  17...Rc8  18.Qe4  ,  d4-d5 and d5-d6 or e5-e6 cannot be stopped, and Black cannot do a thing on the kingside, so the position is completely lost. }
16... Bxg5 17. Nxg5 Nxd4
{ Black is able to get our central pawn, protecting the c6-pawn and attacking our queen at the same time. However, that doesn't seem to help much.   17...Qxg5??  18.Qxc6+  is, of course, the point. The rook on a8 is going to be lost, and the c8-bishop won't survive for too long either. }
18. Qd2 { The black knight cannot stay in its current active position. } 18...
Ne6
{ 18...Nxb3??  seems like a lovely fork, but this move just loses.  After  19.Qf4  ,  White is threatening mate on f7, so the opponent has no time to capture the rook.  19...O-O  20.Ra3+-  ,  the rook comes to g3 on the next turn, and Black is just going to get mated. }
19. f4
{ White is happy to take fxg5 if possible, opening up the f-file for the rook. }
19... d4
{ Probably, Black was hoping that the opponent would focus on winning this pawn, which could give Black a bit of a break, and maybe allow Black to escape into some bad endgame after multiple eventual trades on d4. But, of course, White isn't going to do that. Instead, White is happy to continue attacking the opponent's king, taking advantage of the new outpost on e4!   19...O-O  is not very helpful, because the g-pawn is absent, which means Black's king is going to be permanently weak. For example, White can go  20.Rac1  Bd7  21.Rc3+-  and bring the rook on g3 on the next turn, developing a decisive attack. }
20. Ne4
{ The knight is coming to d6 or f6, which brings the game to its logical end. }
20... Ng7 21. Nd6+ Kf8 22. f5
{ The d4-pawn is falling. Our other knight can come to c5. Next, we can go f5-f6 or e5-e6 when the time is right, opening up the f-file and finally checkmating that king. }
22... Rb8 23. Nc5 Qh4 24. Ra4
{ It's sort of funny how White brings another piece in the decisive attack. The rook was meant to take the a6-pawn, or maybe go to the f-file at some point. But instead, it joins the attack via the 4th rank! }
24... Qg3 25. Nxc8 { Black resigned, as everything is collapsing. } 25... Rxc8
26. Nd7+ Ke7 27. Qxd4
{ Black cannot stop Qd6+ with a checkmate in a couple of moves. And, of course, if there wasn't an immediate checkmate, White would still be completely winning since Black's pieces are lacking any coordination whatsoever, and Black is already losing all the pawns one by one. Another awful game for Black, who hasn't managed to make a single active move, having gotten a strategically lost position by move 10! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "17) Caro 3.e5 c5 and 3...g6 − Model Games"]
[Black "Carlos Daniel Albornoz Cabrera − Marco Antonio Fernandez Gil, Maia 2022"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ This game demonstrates how White should handle the flexible structure after Nxc6 bxc6, and the typical attacking ideas. }
1... c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 c5 4. Nf3 cxd4 5. Nxd4 Nc6 6. Nxc6
{ As you know from the theoretical chapter, this is not the path I prefer. However, this position, or something similar to what happened in the game, can arise in our lines after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp2pppp/8/3pP3/3N4/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...e6  6.Nd2  , and understanding these structures with a flexible center is very valuable overall. }
6... bxc6 7. Bd3 e6 8. O-O Ne7 9. Nd2
{ The knight wasn't needed on c3 or anywhere else, of course. White wants to bring it to f3, and then either d4, trying to control the center, or g5, in order to build a kingside attack and put pressure on the h7 and f7-pawns. }
9... Ng6
{ The knight on this square is in a very interesting position. The good news for Black is that it attacks the e5-pawn, while also blocking the b1-h7 diagonal and our light-squared bishop, making any sort of Greek Gifts impossible. However, it doesn't have a lot of squares to go to and can be easily attacked with h2-h4-h5. Overall, I do not find its position very reliable! }
10. Nf3 Be7
{ After  10...a5  , looking to trade the light-squared bishops quickly, we can react in a standard way:  11.c4!  Ba6  12.Qa4  , getting a similar position to the one here. }
11. c3
{ This is another key idea that you need to remember. This move achieves several important things:  If Black ever tries swapping the restricted bishop for our active one with ...Ba6, we can just retreat to c2, keeping our most valuable attacking piece on the board. Now, White can go Qa4-g4, bringing the queen over to the kingside in a very effective manner, without having to move the knight. }
11... a5
{ This move indicates Black wants to trade the light-squared bishops with ...Ba6. However, as my explanation above indicates, we have no interest or need of allowing that! }
12. Qa4 { First, White attacks the c6-pawn. } 12... Qd7 13. Re1
{ This move is valuable for two reasons: if Black tries swapping the bishops with ...Ba6, we can just retreat with Bc2, without losing the rook on f1; the rook helps protect the e5-pawn and discourage any ...f7-f6-related pawn breaks. }
13... Ba6 14. Bc2 { Of course, no trades! } 14... h5
{ With this move, Black must have wanted to prevent our queen from coming to g4. However, it's a very suspicious decision since now the g5-square and the g6-knight become much looser. }
15. Bxg6
{ And, of course, White is able to immediately take advantage of that! } 15...
fxg6
{ The problem with this pawn structure is not the mere fact that Black had to play ...fxg6. Doing that is fine since Black gets a semi-open f-file. The real problem is that now the g5-square is weak. }
16. Qc2
{ First, White makes the opponent place the king in a very awkward position. }
16... Kf7 17. Bg5
{ And then, White offers a trade of Black's best minor piece. The one on a6 is not restricted by anything, but it's rather useless! }
17... h4
{ Black tries making room on h5 for the rook. A pretty creative idea, but it's not helping that much.   17...Bxg5?  18.Nxg5++-  is not just a bad trade for Black for positional reasons, but also a blunder. The king is forced to retreat, which means the g6-pawn is getting lost. }
18. Rad1
{ The white rook is not just coming to the center. It is headed to d4 and f4, where it would help develop a decisive attack! }
18... Rh5 19. Bxe7 Qxe7 20. Rd4
{ Now, the direct threats include Rf4+, pushing the king away and winning the g6-pawn, and Rg4, attacking that pawn. The former isn't going to win on the spot since Black can block with ...Rf5, but Black always has to reckon with it anyway. }
20... Rah8
{ 20...g5  was a better idea, preventing Rf4, and potentially making room on g6 for the black king.  21.Qd2  ,  the g5-pawn should not be able to survive, for instance, after  21...Kg6  22.Rg4  ,  Black is somehow surviving for the time being but doesn't have a single move! The rook on h5 is completely stuck, and so is the queen. Next, White can play h2-h3, and maybe even b2-b3 and c3-c4!?, looking to make progress on the other flank, which has been nearly completely abandoned. }
21. Rg4 R8h6 22. h3
{ White is in no hurry and prevents any ...h4-h3 related ideas, planning to go Ng5 and Re3-f3, bringing the last uninvolved piece in. Also, since Black had abandoned the queenside, it's possible and logical to consider attacking a5-pawn at some point with Qa4. The queen, from that square, will be also attacking the h4-pawn, making the black queen a bit torn apart between both flanks. }
22... c5 23. Qa4 { The a5-pawn is falling. } 23... Bb7 24. Qxa5 d4
{ Black is hoping to ruin our pawn structure by taking on f3, but that doesn't bother us even a bit since Black cannot attack our king with any pieces. }
25. cxd4 { So, we are just collecting more free pawns. } 25... Bxf3 26. gxf3
cxd4 27. Rc1
{ The rook is joining the attack from the queenside! This is perfectly logical since Black's rooks are stuck on the h-file. Beautiful use of the idea of two weaknesses! Black was holding up the h4-pawn, but once the queenside opened up, everything is collapsing. }
27... Kg8 28. Rc8+ Kh7 29. Qa8
{ The king escaped dangers on the 7th rank, but not on the 8th! } 29... g5
{ Black has to make room on g6 for the king, of course. } 30. Rxd4
{ Black resigned since two pawns got lost, the rooks are trapped on the kingside, and White is still continuing the attack, for example with Rd6, and then Re8. }
