[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "17) Caro 3.e5 c5 and 3...g6 − Model Games"]
[Black "Gawain Jones − Ivan Cheparinov, Hengshui IMSA Blitz 2019"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 c5 4. Nf3 cxd4 5. Nxd4 Nc6 6. c4 e6 7. Nc3 Bb4
{ As we discuss in the theoretical chapter, this is Black's best move. By pinning the knight, Black is reducing the pressure we have on the center, specifically on the d5-square. }
8. Nxc6 bxc6 9. Qa4
{ This, as the theoretical chapter explains, is a forcing path to an endgame! }
9... a5
{ Black needs to defend the bishop.   9...Bxc3+?  10.bxc3  leads to a very bad position with weak dark squares. Specifically, the a3-f8 diagonal is going to be a big issue for Black. Plus, the c8-bishop is a bad piece. }
10. cxd5
{ Black cannot afford to take on d5 with the e-pawn, as the pawn on c6 would be lost with a check. Instead, ...cxd5 isn't possible as that pawn is pinned.   10.Qxc6+  Bd7!  offers a ton of initiative because Black is threatening to play ...d5-d4 next, taking advantage of our pinned knight. }
10... Qxd5 11. Qxb4
{ By eliminating the bishop, we unpin the knight on c3, getting ready to take the queen. }
11... axb4 12. Nxd5 exd5
{ 12...cxd5  13.Bd2!  results in huge problems with the b-pawn, as I explain in the theoretical chapter. For instance, after  13...b3  14.a4!  ,  White's a-pawn will run up the board very quickly, supported by the bishops. However, the b3-pawn still isn't safe. After Ra3 and Be2-d1, White will inevitably pick it up. }
13. Be3
{ White's bishop is coming to c5 to attack the weak pawn. It's important to go Be3 quickly in order to take the c5-square under control and make sure Black cannot connect the pawns with ...c6-c5. }
13... f6 14. Rc1
{ With this move, White lets the opponent capture the central pawn and is also abandoning the one on a2! Why? In exchange, White wants to capture the pawn on c6 and open up the position as much as possible. I am not entirely sure about the amount of theoretical challenge this move provides, but it was enough to confuse one of the world's best theoreticians and Topalov's former second!   14.f4  is the main move, protecting the e5-pawn. }
14... Rxa2
{ I am not entirely sure how good of a strategy for Black it is to open the position for the white pieces.   14...Kd7!  I think it would have been better for Black to keep the tension, refusing to take any of the white pawns, but keeping the one on c6 alive, and keeping the position closed overall. }
15. Rxc6 { The bishop is under attack, of course. } 15... Bd7 16. Rd6
{ The rook is occupying a perfect position here since it is helping create a threat of e5-e6!, forcing the black bishop away and obtaining a dominant position. }
16... Rxb2
{ Black couldn't afford to capture the pawn. Dealing with the threat of our pawn advancing should be been a huge priority!   16...Ne7!  was Black's only move. The point is to prepare ...Nf5!, looking to kick the white rook away, and hopefully trade off White's bishop on e3. For instance, after  17.exf6  gxf6  18.Rxf6  Nf5  ,  Black is a pawn down but is counterattacking the b2-pawn, our bishop, and has ideas like ...Ra1+ or ...Kd8 followed by ...Re8, dramatically activating all the pieces. This should provide Black with a fair amount of compensation. }
17. e6
{ This is a very big accomplishment for White. The point is that this pawn won't queen but it's taking the d7 and f7-squares away from Black's pieces, including the king. This means that if White also goes Bc5, taking the e7-square away, White would construct a perfect mating net! }
17... Ba4 18. Ra6
{ The rook wants to come to a8 after the bishop arrives at c5. That, of course, would be checkmate. But, unfortunately for Black, the bishop hardly has any good squares to retreat to! The problem is that going into White's territory with ...Bb3 or something along those lines doesn't help stop a powerful attack on the king. }
18... Rb1+ 19. Kd2
{ Of course, White no longer cares about the check. Now, Black also needs to worry about Bb5+ at some point, which would set up a discovered attack on the black rook and win it. }
19... Rd1+ 20. Ke2
{ The game is coming to an end. White is not only threatening Bc5 and Ra8+ but is also attacking the bishop on a4, which cannot really retreat, leaving the d1-rook unprotected. }
20... Ra1
{ Now, Black is threatening a discovered attack on the rook on a6 by means of ...Bb5+ or ...Bd1+, which means White needs to address that threat.   20...Rxf1  ,  this cheeky move might look good at a first glance, as it seems Black is about to follow up with ...Bb5+, winning the rook on a6. However, that's not gonna happen due to the lovely intermediate move.  21.Ra8+!  Ke7  22.Kxf1+-  .  Not only is White an exchange up but also the g8-knight and the h8-rook are stuck! }
21. Kf3
{ The rook is now protected by the bishop on f1. And, White has a threat: Rxa4 followed by Bb5+, winning that rook on a4! }
21... Bd1+ 22. Kg3 { The king is finally out of annoying checks. } 22... Rxa6
23. Bxa6
{ Now, the black bishop is hanging. Of course, it's very easy to see why Black's position is a minute or two away from collapsing: the kingside pieces are still in their original positions! }
23... Bc2 24. Bc5 { The black king is in a mating net. } 24... b3
{ The pawn is quite close to promoting, but it's not going to be on time, of course.   24...Ne7  ,  it would be lovely to get the kingside pieces out, but Black is not in time.  25.Ra1  and with Bb5+ and Ra8 coming next, there isn't much for Black to do!  25...b3  26.Bb5+  Kd8  27.Ra8+  .  White picks up all of the opponent's pieces. }
25. Bb5+ Kd8 26. Ra1 { The king is in a mating net. } 26... Ne7 27. Ra8+ Nc8
28. Bd6
{ Black resigned, as it's not possible to stop the threats of mate in one move with e7, and Bd7, followed by taking the knight. Although the opening was by no means played perfectly  (White definitely went for a bit of a gamble!)  , I think it's extremely valuable to see how powerful the white bishops got once the position opened up! This is exactly the problem Black should extremely wary of in this variation. }
