[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "18) Caro-Kann − Typical Structures and Ideas"]
[Black "The Advance ...dxc4 structure − plans and ideas"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "4k3/pp3ppp/2p1p3/4P3/3P4/8/PP3PPP/4K3 w - - 0 6"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ This is the pawn structure that you will be seeing really often in the Advance Caro-Kann with @@StartFEN@@rn1qkbnr/pp2pppp/2p5/3pPb2/3P4/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 1 4@@EndFEN@@  4.c4  . What are the main things  worth knowing about it? The most obvious visual downside of this pawn structure is that, since Black played ...dxc4, we got a 'hole' on d5 − this central square can now be used as an outpost for Black's pieces. What does White have in return? Since when is it good to help the opponent create outposts?  To explain this, I'd use Dvoretsky's phrase 'redundant pieces'. What did the greatest chess coach of all time mean by that? Well, here's the deal. Imagine you have three pieces that want to use this wonderful outpost on d5. But only one piece can be there at a time! So, what are the other two doing? Exactly − nothing!  The idea is that as long as we keep a lot of pieces on the board, our e5-pawn will provide us a considerable spatial advantage, and Black would be restricted. Black would be able to place one of the pieces  (likely a knight)  on the d5-square, but the rest of the pieces will be passive. Also, importantly, the d5-outpost, while lovely, isn't threatening to us. The knight just looks good there, but it's not deep enough in our territory for it to be threatening in any way!  To summarize, we are fighting for space, and in return are happy to let ONE black piece feel good. As you can see, it is very important for White to keep the pieces on the board in this structure. Also, it is important to point out that White enjoys an outpost on d6! It will be most useful if the dark-squared bishops disappear. In the next few examples, we will see what a dream position for Black and for White can look like in this structure. }
6. -- *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "18) Caro-Kann − Typical Structures and Ideas"]
[Black "The Advance ...dxc4 Structure − Black's dream position"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "4k3/pp3ppp/2p1p3/3nP3/3P4/8/PP1B1PPP/4K3 w - - 0 6"]
[SetUp "1"]

6. Ke2
{ This is Black's dream position in this structure. White's dark-squared bishop is his worst piece because the central pawns are heavily restricting it. Black's knight, on the other hand, is the best piece: it's sitting on a lovely outpost. And, Black has no shortage of space.   But, here is what's interesting. Although Black is undoubtedly better, it is by no means easy to not only win this game but also, make any progress! This proves a very interesting point: in a way, the @@StartFEN@@rn1qkbnr/pp2pppp/2p5/3pPb2/3P4/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 1 4@@EndFEN@@  4.c4  variation and this structure is sort of risk-free for White! Even if you play badly and get literally the worst endgame possible, you don't seem to be risking that much. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "18) Caro-Kann − Typical Structures and Ideas"]
[Black "The Advance ...dxc4 structure − White's dream position"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1bq1rk1/pp3ppp/1npNp3/3nP3/3PN1Q1/8/PP3PPP/1BRR2K1 w - - 0 6"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ Here is the same pawn structure as in the two last examples, but with a lot more pieces. As you can see, the dark-squared bishops are gone, which means White can put the d6-outpost to full use. The other knight is ready to support that one, or maybe jump to g5 or f6 to help the kingside attack.  The white queen is enjoying itself on g4 and could go to h5, playing an instrumental role in the attack on the black king. The white rooks are also able to join very easily, for example with Rd3-g3/h3. Black, on the other hand, does not have the slightest bit of counterplay. Here is a sample variation of how we can make progress. }
6. Rd3 Qe7 7. Rh3 g6
{ Black needs to weaken the kingside and the dark squares even more, but that looks awful.   7...a6??  8.Rxh7!  Kxh7  9.Nf6+!  Double check! That bishop on b1 is so proud of itself!  9...Kh8  10.Qh3  .  This was quite a lovely mate, wasn't it? }
8. Ng5 { Black is forced to weaken the kingside even more. } 8... h5 9. Qg3
{ Black is absolutely paralyzed! Next, we can start calculating sacrifices like Rxh5 or Ngxf7, and it's not obvious what Black would do about this. What a disaster! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "18) Caro-Kann − Typical Structures and Ideas"]
[Black "Why playing ...Nd7 is often bad for Black"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "rn1qkbnr/pp3ppp/2p1p3/3pPb2/2PP4/2N5/PP3PPP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq - 0 5"]
[SetUp "1"]

5... Nd7
{ This is the basic theoretical tabiya on move 5. Why are we looking at it here again, instead of seeing it once only in the theoretical chapter? Because a lot of people make the ...Nd7 decision, which I consider a mistake despite its popularity. }
6. cxd5 cxd5
{ The black knight has nothing useful to do on d7. Bad knight!   6...exd5?  is a wrong and a very dangerous move for Black because it provides us with a pawn majority on the kingside. Essentially, we'll just develop with Bd3, and Ne2, and then will overrun Black on the kingside with f2-f4-f5.  7.Bd3  Bxd3  8.Qxd3  ,  with f2-f4-f5 coming, I am not sure if there is much to add. We don't even need to play Nge2; instead, f2-f4 followed by Nf3 would be just fine too! Black is nearly lost. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "18) Caro-Kann − Typical Structures and Ideas"]
[Black "How the inclusion of h2-h4 and ...h7-h5 matters"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r3k2r/1p1nbpp1/pqn1p3/3pP1Bp/3P3P/2NQ1N2/PP3PP1/2R2RK1 w kq - 0 14"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ This is another position that we have seen in the theoretical chapter. One key thing that I would like to teach you by showing you this position is how the inclusion of moves h2-h4 and ...h7-h5 impacts the evaluation. I believe this inclusion tends to clearly favor White in an overwhelming majority of cases. Primarily, this is because of two reasons:  The g5 and g4-squares, naturally, get weaker. However, White can easily use the g5-square by installing the knight or the bishop there, while Black cannot use the one on g4. The h5-pawn becomes very weak. That makes it much harder for Black to castle kingside since doing so would make it nearly impossible to protect the pawn. }
14. Ne2
{ With Nf4 coming on the next turn, Black is in a very rough shape. Black cannot castle kingside, as the h5-pawn would fall, as we had learned earlier. But if Black doesn't do that, then how would the rooks come into the game? At some point, we can proceed with Bxe7 and then Ng5, followed by f2-f4-f5, looking to open up the f-file. Poor Black! How to deal with all that? I have no idea. }
14... O-O { Here, White wins in many ways. } 15. Nf4
{ 15.Rxc6  Qxc6  16.Bxe7+-  but this tactic, although cute, is not really relevant to the standard themes of the position. }
15... g6 16. Nxg6 { This is, however, a tactic you absolutely need to know! }
16... fxg6 17. Qxg6+ Kh8 18. Qxh5+
{ White gets a decisive attack. As you can see, that h5-pawn was a real liability and trying to defend it only made things a lot worse for Black. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "18) Caro-Kann − Typical Structures and Ideas"]
[Black "The hanging pawns structure"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "4k3/p4ppp/2p5/3pP3/8/8/PP3PPP/4K3 w - - 0 10"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ This pawn structure arises fairly often in the @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp2pppp/2p5/3p4/3PP3/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq d6 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.e5  c5  Caro-Kann positions. What are the ideas here? Black has the rather weak hanging pawns because  they failed to both advance @@StartBracket@@to c5 and d5@@EndBracket@@. As a result, Black has some weak squares, such as c5 and d4.  Therefore, White's dream would be to play a2-a3, b2-b4, Na4, Rc1, Nc5, and install the bishop on d4. If we achieve that, the black queenside pawns will become clearly weak, and our pieces will be enjoying dominant positions. At the same time, we have an extra pawn in the center. This means at some point ideas like f2-f4-f5-f6 could become interesting, building an attack on the kingside.  But, to be fair, I don't think this plan is likely to be carried out since the center is fairly open. You typically only attack on a flank, especially if that includes pawn play, with a closed center. }
10. -- *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "18) Caro-Kann − Typical Structures and Ideas"]
[Black "The flexible center − How to attack as White"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1bqk2r/p3bppp/2p1p1n1/3pP3/8/3B1N2/PPP2PPP/R1BQ1RK1 w kq - 0 11"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ We see this theoretical position in the @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp2pppp/2p5/3p4/3PP3/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq d6 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.e5  c5  chapter.  How can we describe it?  White's e5-pawn is taking away the f6 and d6-squares from the black pieces, gaining a lot of space on the kingside and facilitating the kingside attack ideas.  Therefore, Black had to play ...Ne7-g6, which is very slow, but in a way rather attractive, because the knight covers up the b1-h7 diagonal, which limits our light-squared bishop, and potentially helps put pressure on the e5-pawn. White needs to be careful about not losing it to some ...Qc7 at some point, or not having it undermined with ...f7-f6 in circumstances where Black can afford that.  Black's light-squared bishop is still a bad piece. Most importantly, how can White build a kingside attack here? I want to remind you of the following brilliant idea. }
11. c3 O-O 12. Qa4
{ The queen is finding its way to the kingside, after all! The c6-pawn is under attack too, of course. }
12... c5 13. Qg4
{ White has many annoying threats and ideas, such as:  h2-h4-h5, kicking out the knight @@StartBracket@@where would it go?!@@EndBracket@@ and grabbing space on the kingside; Bxg6!, followed by Bg5, Qh4, and hopefully Nxg5 and Qh7 with checkmate; Qh5, Ng5 and f2-f4, maybe followed by Rf3-h3. All in all, we seem to have a very easy kingside attack and no weaknesses. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "19) Sicilian − Sidelines"]
[Black "Sicilian Sidelines 2.Nf3 a6 − Informational 3.d4"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5
{ This move initiates what we know as the Sicilian Defense, the queen of the @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  Black openings. Alongside  1.e4  e5  , it's one of the two most sound ways of meeting 1.e4  from the theoretical standpoint. Black is fighting for the center, the d4-square, without creating a symmetrical position. This opening is extremely popular with players who want sharp, creative and fighting chess, and those who don't want to settle for symmetry, less space, or any other concessions. }
2. Nf3
{ In this chapter, we'll be discussing several sidelines Black can try in the Sicilian. To be honest, I don't necessarily have a very negative or dismissing opinion about most of them. Black isn't going to lose by force or anything like that.  Black is trying to avoid the known theory, especially because in the Sicilian main lines, it often tends to be fairly forcing and demanding memorization-wise, and tries to just get a playable position. Naturally, it comes at a cost: we are usually able to secure a stable and enjoyable advantage by simple means.  But, remember my motto from the first part of the course: while facing the sidelines, be thankful for the easy comfortable advantage! Don't think your opponent is disrespecting you! Don't try to win immediately! Don't go crazy! This is the way the sidelines bring a lot of points to your opponents. Instead, stay calm and happy you got a pleasant position without needing to prove your knowledge or be very precise. }
2... a6
{ This is a so-called O'Kelly Sicilian. A pretty interesting line, which contains a funny positional trap! In fact, I was hoping to write a course about it one day, and almost decided to do so, but then I got very focused on working on this repertoire, and IM Christof Sielecki quickly published a course on the O'Kelly before I could write one. :@@EndBracket@@ Black's last move is useful for many reasons in various Sicilian positions:  It prepares the ...b7-b5 advance. The queenside expansion is a typical plan for Black! It prevents the pin Bb5, which is also useful in many Moscow or Rossolimo-type positions. And, as we will see, it invites White to fall for a very natural positional trap. }
3. d4
{ This very natural move, which is the main way of playing against almost any Sicilian variation, the so-called Open Sicilian, turns out to be a bad idea here! }
3... cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 { The e4-pawn is hanging. } 5. Nc3
{ 5.e5?  Qa5+  is, of course, not a good idea for White since that just loses the precious e-pawn for nothing. }
5... e5
{ Hold on, isn't this a bit similar to the Sveshnikov Variation? That main line Sicilian, which so many super GMs use, for example, Carlsen in his World Championship match versus Caruana? That Sicilian where Black weakens the d5-square and the d-pawn? Yeah, whatever. The problem is that we cannot play Nb5! This is when the move ...a7-a6 is paying off so well! So, White has to play passively. }
6. Nb3 Bb4
{ Black immediately gets extremely active and is threatening to take the e4-pawn since the knight on c3 is pinned. }
7. Bd3 d5
{ The center opens up, the c3-knight is pinned, and Black is already taking over the initiative! This is absolutely not the way we want the game to go, especially versus a rare sideline. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "19) Sicilian − Sidelines"]
[Black "Sicilian Sidelines 2.Nf3 a6 3.c4 Nc6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5
{ This move initiates what we know as the Sicilian Defense, the queen of the @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  Black openings. Alongside  1.e4  e5  , it's one of the two most sound ways of meeting 1.e4  from the theoretical standpoint. Black is fighting for the center, the d4-square, without creating a symmetrical position. This opening is extremely popular with players who want sharp, creative and fighting chess, and those who don't want to settle for symmetry, less space, or any other concessions. }
2. Nf3
{ In this chapter, we'll be discussing several sidelines Black can try in the Sicilian. To be honest, I don't necessarily have a very negative or dismissing opinion about most of them. Black isn't going to lose by force or anything like that.  Black is trying to avoid the known theory, especially because in the Sicilian main lines, it often tends to be fairly forcing and demanding memorization-wise, and tries to just get a playable position. Naturally, it comes at a cost: we are usually able to secure a stable and enjoyable advantage by simple means.  But, remember my motto from the first part of the course: while facing the sidelines, be thankful for the easy comfortable advantage! Don't think your opponent is disrespecting you! Don't try to win immediately! Don't go crazy! This is the way the sidelines bring a lot of points to your opponents. Instead, stay calm and happy you got a pleasant position without needing to prove your knowledge or be very precise. }
2... a6
{ This is a so-called O'Kelly Sicilian. A pretty interesting line, which contains a funny positional trap! In fact, I was hoping to write a course about it one day, and almost decided to do so, but then I got very focused on working on this repertoire, and IM Christof Sielecki quickly published a course on the O'Kelly before I could write one. :@@EndBracket@@ Black's last move is useful for many reasons in various Sicilian positions:  It prepares the ...b7-b5 advance. The queenside expansion is a typical plan for Black! It prevents the pin Bb5, which is also useful in many Moscow or Rossolimo-type positions. And, as we will see, it invites White to fall for a very natural positional trap. }
3. c4
{ This move, alongside  3.c3  , is a known solution to the O'Kelly. We don't need a large advantage. We would just happily settle for a well-known typical Maroczy Bind position. In fact, we usually get such positions a tempo down in our @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq c6 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.Nf3  e6  3.c4  Sicilian lines! }
3... Nc6
{ Black is looking to play ...e7-e5, locking up the center, so we need to open it up. }
4. d4 cxd4 5. Nxd4
{ Now, we have the standard Maroczy Bind-type spatial advantage. Left to our own devices, we'd love to just finish our development with Nc3, Be3, Be2, O-O, and so on. So, Black needs to do something very specific − right now, or a move later. }
5... e5
{ 5...Nf6  6.Nc3  e5  transposes to the @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/1p1ppppp/p1n5/8/2PNP3/8/PP3PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...e5  lines. }
6. Nf5
{ This time, we need to dive into some complications. We are threatening a check on d6, forcing Black to either play ...d7-d6, which results in worse positions than the ones after  6.Nc2  , since after @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/1p1p1ppp/p1n5/4pN2/2P1P3/8/PP3PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 6@@EndFEN@@  6...d6  ,  the f8-bishop is stuck inside, or play the sharp lines after  6...d5  .   6.Nc2  is possible but doesn't give us much.  6...Bc5!  7.Nc3  d6  8.Be3  . We can trade off the bishops, but with an  outpost on d4 and a somewhat weak pawn on d6, Black doesn't have much to worry about.  8...Be6  9.Be2  Nf6  10.O-O  O-O=  .  Sure enough, the d6-pawn is a bit backward, but Black will just go ...Qe7 and ...Rfd8, protecting it, and we cannot do that much. }
6... d6
{ This is possible but very passive. Now, the f8-bishop is stuck behind the pawn. }
7. Ne3 { We don't allow Black to ever consider capturing on f5. } 7... Nf6
{ Black develops, attacking the e4-pawn. } 8. Nc3
{ The goal is to just calmly finish development. } 8... Be7 9. Bd3
{ I like placing the bishop here, and that is for a few reasons:   Black can never go ...Nd4 and take it, which would be the case if the bishop had been on e2. If Black goes ...Nd4, we can play Ne2! and trade the knight off. If we ever play Nd5 and after ...Nxd5 recapture exd5 @@StartBracket@@which isn't likely@@EndBracket@@, then the bishop would be staring at the h7-pawn! }
9... O-O 10. O-O
{ We'd like to play Ned5, f2-f3, and Be3, developing all the pieces harmoniously and starting to point pieces at the weak b6-square. }
10... Be6 11. Ned5
{ Black has no counterplay, a bad bishop on e7, and a weak pawn on d6. Please note this position would not be nearly as good had Black managed to play ...Bc5 and swap off the dark-squared bishops. If that had happened, Black would not have:  nearly as many spatial problems; bad bishop; problems with the dark squares, such as b6; a harder time accessing the d4-outpost. }
