2. Nf3
{ In this chapter, we'll be discussing several sidelines Black can try in the Sicilian. To be honest, I don't necessarily have a very negative or dismissing opinion about most of them. Black isn't going to lose by force or anything like that.  Black is trying to avoid the known theory, especially because in the Sicilian main lines, it often tends to be fairly forcing and demanding memorization-wise, and tries to just get a playable position. Naturally, it comes at a cost: we are usually able to secure a stable and enjoyable advantage by simple means.  But, remember my motto from the first part of the course: while facing the sidelines, be thankful for the easy comfortable advantage! Don't think your opponent is disrespecting you! Don't try to win immediately! Don't go crazy! This is the way the sidelines bring a lot of points to your opponents. Instead, stay calm and happy you got a pleasant position without needing to prove your knowledge or be very precise. }
2... a6
{ This is a so-called O'Kelly Sicilian. A pretty interesting line, which contains a funny positional trap! In fact, I was hoping to write a course about it one day, and almost decided to do so, but then I got very focused on working on this repertoire, and IM Christof Sielecki quickly published a course on the O'Kelly before I could write one. :@@EndBracket@@ Black's last move is useful for many reasons in various Sicilian positions:  It prepares the ...b7-b5 advance. The queenside expansion is a typical plan for Black! It prevents the pin Bb5, which is also useful in many Moscow or Rossolimo-type positions. And, as we will see, it invites White to fall for a very natural positional trap. }
3. c4
{ This move, alongside  3.c3  , is a known solution to the O'Kelly. We don't need a large advantage. We would just happily settle for a well-known typical Maroczy Bind position. In fact, we usually get such positions a tempo down in our @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq c6 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.Nf3  e6  3.c4  Sicilian lines! }
3... Nc6
{ Black is looking to play ...e7-e5, locking up the center, so we need to open it up. }
4. d4 cxd4 5. Nxd4
{ Now, we have the standard Maroczy Bind-type spatial advantage. Left to our own devices, we'd love to just finish our development with Nc3, Be3, Be2, O-O, and so on. So, Black needs to do something very specific − right now, or a move later. }
5... e5
{ 5...Nf6  6.Nc3  e5  transposes to the @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/1p1ppppp/p1n5/8/2PNP3/8/PP3PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...e5  lines. }
6. Nf5
{ This time, we need to dive into some complications. We are threatening a check on d6, forcing Black to either play ...d7-d6, which results in worse positions than the ones after  6.Nc2  , since after @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/1p1p1ppp/p1n5/4pN2/2P1P3/8/PP3PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 6@@EndFEN@@  6...d6  ,  the f8-bishop is stuck inside, or play the sharp lines after  6...d5  .   6.Nc2  is possible but doesn't give us much.  6...Bc5!  7.Nc3  d6  8.Be3  . We can trade off the bishops, but with an  outpost on d4 and a somewhat weak pawn on d6, Black doesn't have much to worry about.  8...Be6  9.Be2  Nf6  10.O-O  O-O=  .  Sure enough, the d6-pawn is a bit backward, but Black will just go ...Qe7 and ...Rfd8, protecting it, and we cannot do that much. }
6... d5
{ Black is breaking up the center, trying to take advantage of the loose knight on f5. }
7. cxd5
{ Now, the c6-knight is hanging, so Black needs to enter a pretty forcing line. }
7... Bxf5 8. exf5 Nd4
{ Black lost a pawn and gave up the bishop pair, but obtained a powerful outpost on d4 for the knight, and is attacking the d5-pawn. }
9. Nc3 { Of course, we make the most logical move, protecting the d5-pawn. }
9... Nf6 { Black keeps putting pressure on the d5-pawn. } 10. Bd3
{ I am happy to return the extra pawn in order to keep the bishop pair in an open position. Black can go  10...Nxd5  , or delay the capture with  10...Be7  . Both moves are likely to transpose into each other, so we'll focus on  10...Nxd5  , which has been played 5 times more often.   10.Bg5  allows us to keep the extra pawn but does not seem to promise much of an advantage. After  10...Be7  11.Bxf6  Bxf6  12.Bd3  O-O  , the problem is that our light-squared bishop is rather restricted, and we have opposite-colored bishops, so converting this pawn won't be very easy. But we are definitely somewhat better risk-free! }
10... Nxd5 11. Be4
{ We are immediately putting pressure on the knight. It cannot easily leave, as that would lose the b7-pawn. }
11... Nxc3 { This is a clear mistake. } 12. bxc3 Nb5 13. Qf3
{ We protect the c-pawn, avoid a queen trade, and are about to win the b7-pawn. Very importantly, we are not just winning a pawn. Once we take the b7-pawn, we gain an important tempo by attacking the rook, and on the next turn, will give a check with Bc6+, depriving the opponent of castling rights! So, White is winning. }
