1. e4 c5
{ This move initiates what we know as the Sicilian Defense, the queen of the @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  Black openings. Alongside  1.e4  e5  , it's one of the two most sound ways of meeting 1.e4  from the theoretical standpoint. Black is fighting for the center, the d4-square, without creating a symmetrical position. This opening is extremely popular with players who want sharp, creative and fighting chess, and those who don't want to settle for symmetry, less space, or any other concessions. }
2. Nf3
{ In this chapter, we'll be discussing several sidelines Black can try in the Sicilian. To be honest, I don't necessarily have a very negative or dismissing opinion about most of them. Black isn't going to lose by force or anything like that.  Black is trying to avoid the known theory, especially because in the Sicilian main lines, it often tends to be fairly forcing and demanding memorization-wise, and tries to just get a playable position. Naturally, it comes at a cost: we are usually able to secure a stable and enjoyable advantage by simple means.  But, remember my motto from the first part of the course: while facing the sidelines, be thankful for the easy comfortable advantage! Don't think your opponent is disrespecting you! Don't try to win immediately! Don't go crazy! This is the way the sidelines bring a lot of points to your opponents. Instead, stay calm and happy you got a pleasant position without needing to prove your knowledge or be very precise. }
2... Nf6
{ This is the so-called Nimzowitch Variation of the Sicilian. A pretty rare one − only 15  000  games in the database, compared to 750  000  after  2...d6  .  Black is hoping to play ...d7-d5 in the event of Nc3.  And, just like in the Alapin @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq c6 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.c3  Nf6  ,  Black doesn't seem to mind allowing us to push e4-e5, grabbing space with tempo.  This variation is fairly unsound, in terms of White being able to get an opening advantage. However, it's been used by a lot of strong players, including Duda, Mamedyarov, Dreev, Rakhmanov, and others, mostly in blitz and rapid. The reason they play it is to avoid theory and get a murky complex position, where White could get overambitious and expand the pawns too much, weakening them. We won't do that! }
3. e5 { We gladly kick the knight out. } 3... Nd5 4. g3
{ Black would need to undermine our powerful e5-pawn with ...d7-d6 or ...e7-e6 eventually. So, we are preparing to deploy the bishop on the long diagonal, making the king safer, and hoping to take advantage of the position opening up. Then, we'd love to go d2-d4 at some point, opening the center up quickly! }
4... Nc6
{ Black could also start with  4...d6  or  4...e6  , but it will be the same thing. }
5. Bg2 d6
{ Black is immediately undermining the e5-pawn, which occupies so much space in the center. This is clearly the best choice!  5...e6  leads to similar positions that will be discussed after ...e7-e6 on the next turn. }
6. exd6
{ Now, Black is facing a choice. To play ...exd6 seems unreasonable, as that opens the e-file, and after d2-d4, the d5-knight will turn out rather loose. So, Black needs to either take with the queen, keeping the c8-bishop open, and keeping the options of playing ...g7-g6 and ...Bg7, or ...e7-e6, or ...e7-e5 available, but placing the queen in an awkward position, or play ...e7-e6, blocking the c8-bishop but preparing to take on d6 with the f8-bishop and castle shortly. }
6... e6
{ A safe choice, but now we easily get a clearly better position risk-free. }
7. d4
{ We are immediately opening up the center, hoping Black captures, activating the g2-bishop. Of course, c2-c4 will be available at some point as well, grabbing space with tempo. }
7... Bxd6 8. c4 { We are continuing to aggressively occupy a lot of space. }
8... Nf6 9. Nc3
{ And we follow with the logical development. Black needs to be mindful of Nb5 coming at some point, so it makes sense to unload the tension in the center − now, or a move later. }
9... O-O 10. O-O cxd4 11. Nxd4
{ Finally, the g2-bishop is starting to shine bright! Black cannot just develop with ...Bd7, both because we can trade on c6, ruining the pawn structure, and because of Nb5-d6 coming with tempo, likely grabbing the bishop pair. So, Black needs to trade a pair of knights. }
11... Nxd4 12. Qxd4
{ However, in this position, the c8-bishop is clearly a big problem, just like in the Rubinstein French with g2-g3, which is a part of this repertoire. We'd love to keep making normal developing moves like Be3 or Bg5, Rfd1, then at some point Nb5-d6. Black really needs to do something urgent about the queenside. }
12... e5
{ I believe it's urgent that Black makes this move, hoping to follow up with ...Qe7 and any move with the light-squared bishop. In this position, a strong Latvian GM and a fellow Chessable author chose to retreat with the queen to h4, which wasn't bad. He went on to easily win in 29 moves, but I think we can do even better. 1-0 Neiksans-Aldokhin, chess.com 2022. }
13. Qd1
{ The idea is to play Bg5, pinning the knight, and then take advantage of the pin and the outpost on d5 with moves like Ne4 or Nd5. Black needs to develop the light-squared bishop, I believe. }
13... Bg4 14. Qb3
{ However, now the b7-pawn is under pressure, and it seems pretty difficult to save it. With Qxb7 threatened, as well as Bg5, Nd5, Ne4, or even Nb5, Black seems to be in a very rough shape! }
