{ Now, Black is facing a choice. To play ...exd6 seems unreasonable, as that opens the e-file, and after d2-d4, the d5-knight will turn out rather loose. So, Black needs to either take with the queen, keeping the c8-bishop open, and keeping the options of playing ...g7-g6 and ...Bg7, or ...e7-e6, or ...e7-e5 available, but placing the queen in an awkward position, or play ...e7-e6, blocking the c8-bishop but preparing to take on d6 with the f8-bishop and castle shortly. }
6... Qxd6
{ Black can also temporarily sacrifice a pawn with  6...Bg4  , in which case it’s wiser to focus on development rather than on capturing more pawns with  7.dxe7  , helping Black develop. Instead, we will just play  7.h3  Bh5  8.d4!  , transposing to the positions discussed later in the chapter. }
7. O-O
{ Now, we are ready to start opening the game up with d2-d4 since Black's development is clearly far from impressive. }
7... e5
{ This is possible, but it seems too ambitious and too dangerous. Black is trying to control all the space in the world, but the lack of development does not seem to support this ambition. }
8. Na3
{ A bit surprisingly, the knight is placed best on this square, since from here, it can come not only to b5 but also to c4, pressuring the e5-pawn! }
8... Be7
{ Black, who already has a lot of space, needs to focus on castling quickly, and preserving the center safely. }
9. Re1
{ If we had one more tempo, we'd proceed with Nc4, winning the e5-pawn, so Black needs to defend it. }
9... f6 10. c3
{ However, now we are opening up the center with d2-d4, trying to take advantage of the weakened a2-g8 diagonal. Of course, the g2-bishop will become a lot more powerful too! }
10... Be6 11. d4 { The center is collapsing. } 11... cxd4 12. cxd4 exd4 13.
Nxd4 Nxd4 14. Qxd4
{ Right now, we have a very direct threat of Rxe6 followed by capturing a loose piece on d5. Also, there are a ton of threats related to the c7-square, such as Nb5, followed by trading on d5 multiple times and forking on c7. Black is about to run into Nc4, Nb5, Qe4, or Rd1. Black is in so much trouble! Objectively, the position is lost. }
