{ Black would need to undermine our powerful e5-pawn with ...d7-d6 or ...e7-e6 eventually. So, we are preparing to deploy the bishop on the long diagonal, making the king safer, and hoping to take advantage of the position opening up. Then, we'd love to go d2-d4 at some point, opening the center up quickly! }
4... Nc6
{ Black could also start with  4...d6  or  4...e6  , but it will be the same thing. }
5. Bg2 d6
{ Black is immediately undermining the e5-pawn, which occupies so much space in the center. This is clearly the best choice!  5...e6  leads to similar positions that will be discussed after ...e7-e6 on the next turn. }
6. exd6
{ Now, Black is facing a choice. To play ...exd6 seems unreasonable, as that opens the e-file, and after d2-d4, the d5-knight will turn out rather loose. So, Black needs to either take with the queen, keeping the c8-bishop open, and keeping the options of playing ...g7-g6 and ...Bg7, or ...e7-e6, or ...e7-e5 available, but placing the queen in an awkward position, or play ...e7-e6, blocking the c8-bishop but preparing to take on d6 with the f8-bishop and castle shortly. }
6... Qxd6
{ Black can also temporarily sacrifice a pawn with  6...Bg4  , in which case it’s wiser to focus on development rather than on capturing more pawns with  7.dxe7  , helping Black develop. Instead, we will just play  7.h3  Bh5  8.d4!  , transposing to the positions discussed later in the chapter. }
7. O-O
{ Now, we are ready to start opening the game up with d2-d4 since Black's development is clearly far from impressive. }
7... Bg4
{ In order to prevent us from tearing the center apart with d2-d4, Black needs to pin our knight. }
8. h3
{ However, this immediately causes another problem. Will Black give up the bishop pair, or will try to keep the pin, risking a situation where the bishop ends up passive and useless on g6 after the possible g3-g4? }
8... Bh5
{ Black should keep the pin alive. In this position, you need to remember a very important nuance.  8...Bxf3  is passive and spineless.  9.Qxf3  e6  10.Nc3  and with the bishop pair, and a wonderful unmatched g2-bishop, we are clearly better.  Black would likely need to retreat with ...Nf6, but then we can even consider rerouting the knight to c4 with Nb5-a3-c4, looking to play c2-c3 and d2-d4, blowing up the center. Or just continue playing d2-d3, Ne4, Bg5, etc. }
9. d4
{ This move is aimed at opening up the position as much as possible, and it is not a real pawn sacrifice, as we are about to discover.   9.g4  isn't as good of a move order since after  9...Bg6  10.d4  , Black doesn't need to take and can just castle,  10...O-O-O  preparing to take advantage of our weakened kingside  with ...h7-h5! So, make sure to NOT play this way! }
9... cxd4
{ 9...Nxd4  doesn't win a pawn, as after  10.g4  Nxf3+??  11.Bxf3+-  ,  we are attacking the h5-bishop and the d5-knight at the same time, winning a piece.   9...O-O-O?  isn't a good idea either, as after  10.c4  Nb6  11.Nc3!  cxd4  12.Nb5!  and with c4-c5, a2-a4-a5, Bf4, Rc1 coming next, Black's position is very dangerous. }
10. g4
{ Now, we unpin, getting ready to capture the d4-pawn, opening up the g2-bishop. }
10... Bg6 11. Nxd4
{ Black shouldn't want to help us develop even more by trading on d4. } 11...
e6 12. Nxc6
{ We either force the opponent to ruin the pawn structure or voluntarily walk into a dangerous pin. }
12... Qxc6 13. Nc3
{ Black, of course, cannot capture on c3, attacking our queen, because we will take the queen on c6 with a check. So, we are guaranteed to be able to capture on d5 on the next turn, creating a weak isolated pawn for Black and opening up the e-file, getting a strong initiative there as well. }
