{ This move order, where Black keeps the central tension, is also referred to as 'The Sniper Defense' − a funny name, but it doesn't make a bad variation any better. By the way, it's also important to point out that this position can arise via, say, @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  g6  2.d4  Bg7  3.Nf3  c5  , which coincides with what we do against the Modern Defense. }
4. dxc5
{ We don't plan on holding on to the extra pawn. The idea is that Black will need to waste quite a bit of time in order to get it back. }
4... Qa5+ 5. c3
{ Now, b2-b4 is a threat, holding on to the extra pawn. So, Black must take it right away. }
5... Qxc5 6. Na3
{ This is a very common idea in these positions. The knight is going to b5. Then, we'll play Be3, kicking the black queen away, and asking the opponent if it's easy to defend the c7-square. }
6... Nf6
{ Black wants to castle as soon as possible, so developing the kingside pieces is necessary.   6...Bxc3+  is not something to fear. Following  7.bxc3  Qxc3+  8.Qd2  Qxa1  9.Nb5  Na6  , White can trap the queen with  10.Nc3  . }
7. Nb5
{ Black has to be very careful, as Be3 seems to be quite a large threat. Not only will the queen have just the c6-square, but also the a7-pawn might end up hanging! }
7... b6
{ Black needs to block the g1-a7 diagonal, while also making room for the queen on b7. }
8. b4
{ Again, the queen is short on squares. The next few moves are pretty forced. }
8... Qc6 9. e5 { Black keeps wasting time moving the knight around. } 9... Ne4
{ 9...Nd5??  is an awful blunder, which loses on the spot.  10.Qxd5  Qxd5  11.Nc7++-  and we are a piece up. }
10. Nfd4 { Again, Black is forced to make the only moves. } 10... Qb7 11. Bd3
{ We are about to play f2-f3 and trap the poor knight. } 11... d5
{ Black needs to protect the knight this way. } 12. exd6
{ We happily capture, pointing out that Black cannot take back without ruining the pawn structure.  12.f3!?  isn't bad either.  The knight on e4 has nowhere to retreat, correct? But, unfortunately, this move doesn't win immediately, since the opponent  can go  12...a6!  and our knight cannot retreat  as then the c3-pawn would be lost. So, the position remains murky − let's not go down this route. }
12... O-O
{ Instead of taking back right away, it's wiser to castle first, in order to avoid pins on the e-file, such as Qe2! We can, but don't want to be greedy and capture another pawn. Prioritizing development seems wiser. }
13. O-O
{ Now, we are ready to play Bxe4. The opponent would capture back without a check and we'll trap the rook with Nc7! So, Black needs to take the pawn, finally. }
13... Nxd6 14. Nxd6 exd6 15. Bf4
{ As a result, we got a large positional advantage due to the weak isolated d6-pawn and a gorgeous knight on d4. Also, playing ...d6-d5 isn't that safe because we can potentially seriously annoy the opponent with some Nb5-d6 or Nb5-c7 ideas. Those dark squares are pretty weak!  The only somewhat unusual thing about this position with an IQP is that our pawn is on b4. It's fair to claim the c3-pawn is a bit weaker, as a result. But the weakness is rather optical − no one can attack that pawn. Next, we'll play Re1, Qd2, or Qb3, and will gladly jump to b5 with the knight. Black is in a very rough shape, not just because of an isolani, but also because the coordination isn't exactly the best. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "20) Sicilian 2...g6"]
[Black "Sicilian 2.Nf3 g6 3.d4 cxd4 − Informational 4.Nxd4"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5
{ This move initiates what we know as the Sicilian Defense, the queen of the @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  Black openings. Alongside  1.e4  e5  , it's one of the two most sound ways of meeting 1.e4  from the theoretical standpoint. Black is fighting for the center, the d4-square, without creating a symmetrical position. This opening is extremely popular with players who want sharp, creative and fighting chess, and those who don't want to settle for symmetry, less space, or any other concessions. }
2. Nf3
{ In this Lifetime Repertoire, I have decided to go for the most ambitious way of playing versus the Sicilian Defense − the so-called Open Sicilian. Why would I do that? Isn't this a positional repertoire, and isn't the Open Sicilian known to be sharp and principled? Well, here is the deal.  It's a Lifetime Repertoire. I want this course to carry a theoretical punch, which most sidelines cannot offer. I was considering the Alapin, 2.c3, as well, but decided to not go down that route, because the isolated pawn positions, which often arise there, aren't to everyone's taste.  Interestingly enough, in many sharp-looking positions, there is a path to simplifications, which means that with sufficient theoretical knowledge, we are playing risk-free. It's not possible to get an advantage in every single theoretical variation of the Sicilian as White, and maybe not even in most.  
What we are doing instead is something different. We are striving to test our opponent's knowledge of typical ideas and forcing lines, and if Black is prepared brilliantly, we accept the fact Black should be able to defend. However, we want to play risk-free, looking to get the better endgames or positions with pleasant positional pressure in the middlegame! }
2... g6
{ The so-called Hyper Accelerated Dragon. Black wants to keep the pawn on d7 for the time being, which is an important nuance: the option of playing ...d7-d5 remains open, thus discouraging White from ever going for the sharpest lines with queenside castling.   Another detail is that Black avoids the Rossolimo Variation, which arises after  2...Nc6  3.Bb5  ,  but allows for the Maroczy Bind @@StartBracket@@where White plays c2-c4@@EndBracket@@, and for the variation that I have chosen to suggest. }
3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 5. c4
{ This results in what is known as the Maroczy Bind − a system with the pawns on c4 and e4. This position can arise from a number of openings: Sicilian, English, and even King's Indian. To be honest, this is one of my favorite positions ever to play with White, but I won't be suggesting it in the course. Why so?   1. It's a very complex system, where you'd want to learn dozens of ideas. It would make sense if we also played @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 2@@EndFEN@@  2...Nc6  3.d4  , hoping for the Maroczy Bind, or the Prince Variation @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 2@@EndFEN@@  2...d6  3.d4  cxd4  4.Nxd4  Nf6  5.f3  . However, as a standalone system, it's too much for White to learn.  2. Everyone knows the Maroczy Bind is a very dangerous setup for Black. So, every reasonable Black player is expecting this. There isn't much of a surprise effect − a big shortcoming in my book.  3.  Black is the one choosing the variations, which can vary from very slow positional play to lengthy, 25-move-long forcing lines. As you can see, this isn't the most practical thing for us to learn as a part of this repertoire. However, I also believe these positions are important to understand. I deeply encourage you to spend some time researching them! But a better way to do so would be to read a book on this structure and middlegame. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "20) Sicilian 2...g6"]
[Black "Sicilian 4.Qxd4 Nf6 5.Nc3 Bg7 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5
{ This move initiates what we know as the Sicilian Defense, the queen of the @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  Black openings. Alongside  1.e4  e5  , it's one of the two most sound ways of meeting 1.e4  from the theoretical standpoint. Black is fighting for the center, the d4-square, without creating a symmetrical position. This opening is extremely popular with players who want sharp, creative and fighting chess, and those who don't want to settle for symmetry, less space, or any other concessions. }
2. Nf3
{ In this Lifetime Repertoire, I have decided to go for the most ambitious way of playing versus the Sicilian Defense − the so-called Open Sicilian. Why would I do that? Isn't this a positional repertoire, and isn't the Open Sicilian known to be sharp and principled? Well, here is the deal.  It's a Lifetime Repertoire. I want this course to carry a theoretical punch, which most sidelines cannot offer. I was considering the Alapin, 2.c3, as well, but decided to not go down that route, because the isolated pawn positions, which often arise there, aren't to everyone's taste.  Interestingly enough, in many sharp-looking positions, there is a path to simplifications, which means that with sufficient theoretical knowledge, we are playing risk-free. It's not possible to get an advantage in every single theoretical variation of the Sicilian as White, and maybe not even in most.  
What we are doing instead is something different. We are striving to test our opponent's knowledge of typical ideas and forcing lines, and if Black is prepared brilliantly, we accept the fact Black should be able to defend. However, we want to play risk-free, looking to get the better endgames or positions with pleasant positional pressure in the middlegame! }
2... g6
{ The so-called Hyper Accelerated Dragon. Black wants to keep the pawn on d7 for the time being, which is an important nuance: the option of playing ...d7-d5 remains open, thus discouraging White from ever going for the sharpest lines with queenside castling.   Another detail is that Black avoids the Rossolimo Variation, which arises after  2...Nc6  3.Bb5  ,  but allows for the Maroczy Bind @@StartBracket@@where White plays c2-c4@@EndBracket@@, and for the variation that I have chosen to suggest. }
3. d4 cxd4 4. Qxd4
{ This is one of the most principled lines versus the Hyper Accelerated Dragon, which requires Black to be knowledgeable and precise. Now, you might be surprised: am I not known for sidelines and practical choices? Why go for the main line, or one of those?  Well, here is what's interesting about chess. To people who are seeing some complex-looking line for the first time in their life, it might seem as though the positions are messy and unclear. However, especially as theory has gotten more advanced in recent years, people have understood that often forcing lines are simply a way to kill all the counterplay and get a pleasant endgame, for example.  Here, we would need to know a couple of specific sequences, sure. But the reward is endgames a pawn up or endgames with the bishop pair. These positions are NOT complex if we just know a few ideas, including the ones that allow us to simplify the game! Now, of course, Black's rook is hanging. }
4... Nf6 5. Nc3
{ We just keep developing. The knight protects the e4-pawn now, and we are getting ready to play e4-e5.   After  5.e5?!  Nc6  6.Qa4  Nd5  ,  Black's knight can easily retreat to c7 if needed. Unfortunately, the e5-pawn will be attacked with ...Bg7 and undermined with ...d7-d6. It's currently restricting Black's pieces quite considerably, so it would be very advantageous for Black to undermine it and get rid of it. We shouldn't be allowing this to happen! }
5... Bg7 { An ignorant move order since it neglects our big threat. } 6. e5
{ Of course, we are immediately harassing the knight. } 6... Nc6 7. Qa4
{ The knight hardly has any squares. If it goes to h5, the move g2-g4 will trap and win it. There is no choice but to retreat all the way back to g8. }
7... Ng8 { The e5-pawn is hanging, but that's an easy problem to solve. } 8.
Bf4
{ White's task is very simple. As you can see, this gorgeous e5-pawn is restricting Black considerably. All we need to do is keep it safe and protected, thus preventing Black from unraveling and getting the pieces out to good squares.  Next, we'd love to castle queenside, maybe play h2-h3 to restrict the opponent even more and prevent any ...Ng4 or ...Bg4 ideas. Then, we'll develop the bishop to c4; maybe the queen can come over to the kingside, and eventually, our centralized pieces will find a way to break through. Here, Black would typically either try to prepare kingside castling with the awkward move ...Nh6, or undermine the powerful e5-pawn with ...f7-f6. }
8... f6
{ Black can also choose to immediately undermine the e5-pawn, getting rid of our main asset, which takes so much space in the center. But to do that, Black needs to weaken the king. }
9. exf6 Nxf6 10. O-O-O
{ Now, Black is the one with the central pawns! But, of course, it won't be easy to advance them as castling has to happen first. }
10... O-O 11. Bc4+
{ Problems are starting to come around. Black cannot block with ...e7-e6 due to the x-ray on the d-file: we'd just take that pawn. }
11... Kh8 12. Rhe1
{ Black cannot go ...e7-e6 because the pawn would hang.  12...d6  is possible, technically speaking, but it creates a  hole on e6, which we will exploit with Be6, or with Ng5-e6. }
12... a6
{ That's why it's logical to try playing on the queenside. But the problem is that Black cannot push ...b7-b5 either, as the a8-rook would hang! We'll just take that pawn! Look at his position: all the pieces, especially the queenside ones, are paralyzed. }
13. Ng5
{ We are starting to create serious threats. Not only is the obvious fork on f7 coming, but also, there is a threat of Ne6, forking the queen and the rook and taking advantage of the pin of the d-file. }
13... Qe8 14. Qa3
{ Next, we can even play Bd6, putting more pressure on the e7-pawn and completely restricting Black.   14...d6  is not possible as that hangs a pawn, while  14...b5  isn't possible either. I have no idea what Black should do here. Black is stuck, paralyzed, and probably just lost. }
