Bf4
{ White's task is very simple. As you can see, this gorgeous e5-pawn is restricting Black considerably. All we need to do is keep it safe and protected, thus preventing Black from unraveling and getting the pieces out to good squares.  Next, we'd love to castle queenside, maybe play h2-h3 to restrict the opponent even more and prevent any ...Ng4 or ...Bg4 ideas. Then, we'll develop the bishop to c4; maybe the queen can come over to the kingside, and eventually, our centralized pieces will find a way to break through. Here, Black would typically either try to prepare kingside castling with the awkward move ...Nh6, or undermine the powerful e5-pawn with ...f7-f6. }
8... Nh6
{ This move is the more popular one, but I consider it very suspicious on account of a lovely positional idea. }
9. h3
{ The knight can no longer go to g4. This is a huge problem because, at some point, a simple move like Qd2 or Qe3 would nearly trap it. Going to f5 isn't a solution due to g2-g4! }
9... O-O
{ The strongest Black player who ever got here is IM Padmini, who authored a book on the Hyper Accelerated Dragon. That must have been an experiment because Black's position is nearly lost. }
10. O-O-O
{ As you can see, the opponent cannot afford to play ...d7-d6 without dropping a pawn. The plan is to bring the queen back to the center with Qe4, then go g2-g4 to restrict the opponent's knight and threaten to trap with it Qe3. We can also develop the bishop to c4. Finally, perhaps the way to break through would be simply h3-h4-h5, obtaining a decisive initiative on the kingside, while the opponent is just watching. }
10... Qa5
{ Some Black players offered a queen trade, hoping to avoid running into a strong kingside attack. That's a fair idea, but the endgame is just as bad for Black as the middlegame. }
11. Qxa5 Nxa5 12. Nd5
{ The e7-pawn is a target. Of course, the move ...e7-e6 would be awful, as it would create a massive outpost on d6 for our pieces. }
12... Nc6 13. Bb5
{ We are threatening to take on c6 and then win the e7-pawn. The move ...e7-e6, again, is an awful positional idea. The pawn cannot be protected with ...Re8 either since Nc7 will fork both rooks. And, on top of all those things, that knight on h6 is terribly inactive. I am really not sure what to recommend − Black is on the verge of a disaster. }
