{ This move initiates what we know as the Sicilian Defense, the queen of the @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  Black openings. Alongside  1.e4  e5  , it's one of the two most sound ways of meeting 1.e4  from the theoretical standpoint. Black is fighting for the center, the d4-square, without creating a symmetrical position. This opening is extremely popular with players who want sharp, creative and fighting chess, and those who don't want to settle for symmetry, less space, or any other concessions. }
2. Nf3
{ In this Lifetime Repertoire, I have decided to go for the most ambitious way of playing versus the Sicilian Defense − the so-called Open Sicilian. Why would I do that? Isn't this a positional repertoire, and isn't the Open Sicilian known to be sharp and principled? Well, here is the deal.  It's a Lifetime Repertoire. I want this course to carry a theoretical punch, which most sidelines cannot offer. I was considering the Alapin, 2.c3, as well, but decided to not go down that route, because the isolated pawn positions, which often arise there, aren't to everyone's taste.  Interestingly enough, in many sharp-looking positions, there is a path to simplifications, which means that with sufficient theoretical knowledge, we are playing risk-free. It's not possible to get an advantage in every single theoretical variation of the Sicilian as White, and maybe not even in most.  
What we are doing instead is something different. We are striving to test our opponent's knowledge of typical ideas and forcing lines, and if Black is prepared brilliantly, we accept the fact Black should be able to defend. However, we want to play risk-free, looking to get the better endgames or positions with pleasant positional pressure in the middlegame! }
2... g6
{ The so-called Hyper Accelerated Dragon. Black wants to keep the pawn on d7 for the time being, which is an important nuance: the option of playing ...d7-d5 remains open, thus discouraging White from ever going for the sharpest lines with queenside castling.   Another detail is that Black avoids the Rossolimo Variation, which arises after  2...Nc6  3.Bb5  ,  but allows for the Maroczy Bind @@StartBracket@@where White plays c2-c4@@EndBracket@@, and for the variation that I have chosen to suggest. }
3. d4 cxd4 4. Qxd4
{ This is one of the most principled lines versus the Hyper Accelerated Dragon, which requires Black to be knowledgeable and precise. Now, you might be surprised: am I not known for sidelines and practical choices? Why go for the main line, or one of those?  Well, here is what's interesting about chess. To people who are seeing some complex-looking line for the first time in their life, it might seem as though the positions are messy and unclear. However, especially as theory has gotten more advanced in recent years, people have understood that often forcing lines are simply a way to kill all the counterplay and get a pleasant endgame, for example.  Here, we would need to know a couple of specific sequences, sure. But the reward is endgames a pawn up or endgames with the bishop pair. These positions are NOT complex if we just know a few ideas, including the ones that allow us to simplify the game! Now, of course, Black's rook is hanging. }
4... Nf6 5. Nc3
{ We just keep developing. The knight protects the e4-pawn now, and we are getting ready to play e4-e5.   After  5.e5?!  Nc6  6.Qa4  Nd5  ,  Black's knight can easily retreat to c7 if needed. Unfortunately, the e5-pawn will be attacked with ...Bg7 and undermined with ...d7-d6. It's currently restricting Black's pieces quite considerably, so it would be very advantageous for Black to undermine it and get rid of it. We shouldn't be allowing this to happen! }
5... Nc6
{ The most logical move  (and the best one)  is to develop the knight with tempo. Where should the queen retreat? }
6. Qa4
{ The queen retreats exactly here, and that is in order to pin the c6-knight, especially after Black goes ...d7-d6. Remember this move! Now, e4-e5 is a considerable positional threat, so ...d7-d6 is sort of forced. }
6... d6
{ 6...Bg7?!  As usual, ignoring the threat  of e4-e5 isn't a good idea.  7.e5!  Ng8  8.Bf4±  and we transpose to the positions discussed after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pp1ppp1p/5np1/8/3QP3/2N2N2/PPP2PPP/R1B1KB1R b KQkq - 2 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Bg7  . }
7. e5
{ However, the move ...d7-d6, which is logical and nearly forced, has a downside. It makes the c6-knight pinned and allows us to start opening up the center to our benefit, trying to take advantage of that pin. }
7... Ng4
{ Some Black players also tried this move. The idea is to attack the f2-pawn and prepare ...Qb6, which would prove rather annoying to deal with. }
8. Bf4 { We overprotect the e5-pawn, preparing to castle queenside. } 8... Qb6
{ It seems as though this move is a wonderful one: after all, it's a double attack on the f2 and b2-pawns! But, unfortunately for Black, this is losing because it's not acceptable to be this aggressive with the king still stuck in the center, unable to castle. }
9. O-O-O
{ We are gladly offering Black not just the f2-pawn but even a fork on both of our rooks! }
9... Nxf2 10. Nd5
{ The queen needs to leave while keeping the c7-square defended. } 10... Qd8
11. exd6 { Again, Nc7+ is a huge threat. } 11... exd6
{ We could easily avoid losing a rook with Re1+, but we don't care to bother. }
12. Bb5 Nxh1 { Black could take either rook and lose in the exact same way. }
13. Bxc6+ bxc6 14. Qxc6+
{ With Re1+ coming next, and the fork on f6 always being a possibility, Black is dead lost. You cannot afford to leave the king on e8 like that, can you? }
*

