{ We just continue our development. Now, we are sort of threatening to bother Black with the move Rd1 on the next turn, making Black waste time moving the queen around. }
10... Bg7 11. Rd1
{ Where should the queen retreat? Of course, Black needs to remember about the pinned c6-knight. If it were to go too far, the Bb5 ideas could prove really annoying. }
11... Qg4
{ Black can also offer a queen trade in this weird way. It's an unusual position: we'd normally welcome this trade in these positions, since we have the long-term assets, such as the bishop pair and the extra queenside pawn. But here, taking would help Black activate the f6-knight and the g7-bishop. So, we won't take the opponent's queen just yet. }
12. Qb3
{ Now, the b7-pawn is under attack. Black needs to do something about this threat... or maybe ignore it? }
12... O-O
{ 12...Rb8?!  is a slow move. After the simple  13.h3!  , kicking the black queen away  so the g2-pawn is no longer hanging,  13...Qc8  14.Be2  O-O  15.O-O⩲  , we reach a standard position with a clear advantage due to our bishop pair and the more active pieces. }
13. h3
{ Instead of being greedy, we are kicking the black queen out. Going to c8 is very passive and results in positions similar to the ones where the queen goes to c8 right away, instead of g4. That's why everyone who got here tried  13...Qb4  .   13.Qxb7  is too greedy, so we won't do this. The black knight is under attack, so Black doesn't have the time for moves like ...Rb8. However,  13...Nb4!  can be played and  the c2-pawn turns out awkward to defend. For instance,  after  14.Rd2  Rab8!  , the queen also ends up kicked around. Black gets too much initiative if you ask me! }
13... Qb4 14. Be2 { A simple developing move. } 14... Qxb3 15. axb3
{ The endgame is considerably better for White. Same old stuff: the bishop pair, an extra pawn on the queenside, and the ability to put pressure on Black's queenside with Bf3. Importantly, there is no need to castle. Next, we'll play Bf3 and Ke2!, keeping the king in the center. The goal, as usual, is to trade off the rooks and win the endgame with the bishop pair. A wonderful opening outcome, if you ask me! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "20) Sicilian 2...g6"]
[Black "Sicilian 4.Qxd4 Nf6 5.Nc3 Nc6 #9"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5
{ This move initiates what we know as the Sicilian Defense, the queen of the @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  Black openings. Alongside  1.e4  e5  , it's one of the two most sound ways of meeting 1.e4  from the theoretical standpoint. Black is fighting for the center, the d4-square, without creating a symmetrical position. This opening is extremely popular with players who want sharp, creative and fighting chess, and those who don't want to settle for symmetry, less space, or any other concessions. }
2. Nf3
{ In this Lifetime Repertoire, I have decided to go for the most ambitious way of playing versus the Sicilian Defense − the so-called Open Sicilian. Why would I do that? Isn't this a positional repertoire, and isn't the Open Sicilian known to be sharp and principled? Well, here is the deal.  It's a Lifetime Repertoire. I want this course to carry a theoretical punch, which most sidelines cannot offer. I was considering the Alapin, 2.c3, as well, but decided to not go down that route, because the isolated pawn positions, which often arise there, aren't to everyone's taste.  Interestingly enough, in many sharp-looking positions, there is a path to simplifications, which means that with sufficient theoretical knowledge, we are playing risk-free. It's not possible to get an advantage in every single theoretical variation of the Sicilian as White, and maybe not even in most.  
What we are doing instead is something different. We are striving to test our opponent's knowledge of typical ideas and forcing lines, and if Black is prepared brilliantly, we accept the fact Black should be able to defend. However, we want to play risk-free, looking to get the better endgames or positions with pleasant positional pressure in the middlegame! }
2... g6
{ The so-called Hyper Accelerated Dragon. Black wants to keep the pawn on d7 for the time being, which is an important nuance: the option of playing ...d7-d5 remains open, thus discouraging White from ever going for the sharpest lines with queenside castling.   Another detail is that Black avoids the Rossolimo Variation, which arises after  2...Nc6  3.Bb5  ,  but allows for the Maroczy Bind @@StartBracket@@where White plays c2-c4@@EndBracket@@, and for the variation that I have chosen to suggest. }
3. d4 cxd4 4. Qxd4
{ This is one of the most principled lines versus the Hyper Accelerated Dragon, which requires Black to be knowledgeable and precise. Now, you might be surprised: am I not known for sidelines and practical choices? Why go for the main line, or one of those?  Well, here is what's interesting about chess. To people who are seeing some complex-looking line for the first time in their life, it might seem as though the positions are messy and unclear. However, especially as theory has gotten more advanced in recent years, people have understood that often forcing lines are simply a way to kill all the counterplay and get a pleasant endgame, for example.  Here, we would need to know a couple of specific sequences, sure. But the reward is endgames a pawn up or endgames with the bishop pair. These positions are NOT complex if we just know a few ideas, including the ones that allow us to simplify the game! Now, of course, Black's rook is hanging. }
4... Nf6 5. Nc3
{ We just keep developing. The knight protects the e4-pawn now, and we are getting ready to play e4-e5.   After  5.e5?!  Nc6  6.Qa4  Nd5  ,  Black's knight can easily retreat to c7 if needed. Unfortunately, the e5-pawn will be attacked with ...Bg7 and undermined with ...d7-d6. It's currently restricting Black's pieces quite considerably, so it would be very advantageous for Black to undermine it and get rid of it. We shouldn't be allowing this to happen! }
5... Nc6
{ The most logical move  (and the best one)  is to develop the knight with tempo. Where should the queen retreat? }
6. Qa4
{ The queen retreats exactly here, and that is in order to pin the c6-knight, especially after Black goes ...d7-d6. Remember this move! Now, e4-e5 is a considerable positional threat, so ...d7-d6 is sort of forced. }
6... d6
{ 6...Bg7?!  As usual, ignoring the threat  of e4-e5 isn't a good idea.  7.e5!  Ng8  8.Bf4±  and we transpose to the positions discussed after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pp1ppp1p/5np1/8/3QP3/2N2N2/PPP2PPP/R1B1KB1R b KQkq - 2 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Bg7  . }
7. e5
{ However, the move ...d7-d6, which is logical and nearly forced, has a downside. It makes the c6-knight pinned and allows us to start opening up the center to our benefit, trying to take advantage of that pin. }
7... dxe5 8. Nxe5
{ At this point, Black arrives at important crossroads and can choose between three logical continuations. The most popular one is  8...Bd7  , surrendering the bishop pair. The second one is  8...Qd4  , going for an inferior endgame with a bad pawn structure. The third one @@StartBracket@@and the best one!@@EndBracket@@ is the daring  8...Bg7  , ignoring the threat and sacrificing the pawn in exchange for rapid development and open b and c-files.  As I had promised, the lines we are about to see, while seemingly complicated at first, actually simply result in endgames with a slight advantage to White, in most cases. }
8... Bd7
{ Most often, the Black players would try this move, not sacrificing material or ruining the structure. But, Black is conceding the bishop pair. }
9. Nxd7 { And, of course, we gladly take it. } 9... Qxd7
{ Typically, Black would capture with the queen, which is logical: why remove the f6-knight from an active position, where it controls the d5 and e4-squares, and go backwards? }
10. Be3
{ We just continue our development. Now, we are sort of threatening to bother Black with the move Rd1 on the next turn, making Black waste time moving the queen around. }
10... Bg7 11. Rd1
{ Where should the queen retreat? Of course, Black needs to remember about the pinned c6-knight. If it were to go too far, the Bb5 ideas could prove really annoying. }
11... Qc7
{ Black isn't afraid of Nb5 − the queen will just move away. Also, Black keeps the 8th rank open, this way the rooks are not disconnected. However, there is also a downside: the queen can end up vulnerable on this square after all as we are about to see. }
12. g3 O-O 13. Bg2
{ The bishop is placed brilliantly on the long diagonal. The reason why I am saying Black's queen can end up vulnerable is because it can get hit with Bf4! at any moment, which would be rather annoying to deal with. }
13... a6
{ In most games, Black chose to make this move, which prevents Nb5 forever, and Qb5, which could be an idea. For example, if we went Bf4 and Black retreated to b6, then Qb5, offering a queen trade, could be an interesting thought to consider. }
14. O-O
{ Now, we'd like to play Qb3, taking the b-file under control, and then start disturbing Black with Bf4, Nd5, and ideas of that kind. Even more importantly, here is one more idea: the d-file is the only open file. Both sides are interested in controlling it. By playing the move ...a7-a6, Black had achieved some goals but weakened the b6-square. Our idea behind playing Qb3 is to prepare Bb6!, taking the d8-square under control and winning the d-file! }
14... Rfd8 15. Qb3 { Now, Bb6 is a threat. } 15... Rxd1 16. Rxd1 Rd8 17. Rxd8+
Nxd8 { Taking with the queen would have left the b7-pawn hanging. } 18. Bb6
{ Black is absolutely paralyzed. Next, we can either keep the pressure, or take the knight on d8 and win the b7-pawn, giving up the bishop pair, but finally obtaining material advantage. }
*

