8... Qd4
{ This move helps Black avoid forcing lines and memorization. However, it also comes at a cost: Black needs to accept the inferior pawn structure. }
9. Nxc6 Qxa4 10. Nxa4 bxc6
{ As you can see, the a7 and c6-pawns are now isolated, and can be targeted pretty easily. Plus, we get some lovely outposts for our pieces, such as the c4 and c5-squares. }
11. Bd2
{ The bishop goes here in order not to be hurt by some ...Nd5 or ...Ng4. We are getting ready to castle queenside. }
11... Bg7 12. O-O-O
{ Black needs to somehow get the rook in the game, so everyone who got to this position chose to castle. But, as we can see, our king is much more active on c1 than the black one would be on g8! }
12... O-O 13. Bc4
{ Next, we'll play f2-f3, restricting the black knight and preventing it from going to e4 or g4. Then, we'll place the rook on e1, looking to provoke ...e7-e6, which would weaken the dark squares, such as the one on d6, and limit the c8-bishop. }
13... Nd5
{ Black, logically, chooses to improve the knight. And here, I'd like to suggest a logical novelty. }
14. f3
{ The idea of this move is not just about controlling the e4 and g4-squares. The problem is that Black cannot find a good square for the bishop! d7 and e6 are passive, and going there isn't safe, as it runs into Nc5.   On the other hand,  14...Bf5  now runs into  15.g4!  , grabbing more space on the kingside and winning time. So, Black ends up in a passive position with an inferior pawn structure without any counterplay.   Next, we'll keep improving our position with Rhe1, Nc5, and will eventually play Bb3 and c2-c4, kicking out Black's best piece  (the d5-knight)  from the center. White is clearly enjoying this risk-free superior endgame! }
