7. e5
{ However, the move ...d7-d6, which is logical and nearly forced, has a downside. It makes the c6-knight pinned and allows us to start opening up the center to our benefit, trying to take advantage of that pin. }
7... dxe5 8. Nxe5
{ At this point, Black arrives at important crossroads and can choose between three logical continuations. The most popular one is  8...Bd7  , surrendering the bishop pair. The second one is  8...Qd4  , going for an inferior endgame with a bad pawn structure. The third one @@StartBracket@@and the best one!@@EndBracket@@ is the daring  8...Bg7  , ignoring the threat and sacrificing the pawn in exchange for rapid development and open b and c-files.  As I had promised, the lines we are about to see, while seemingly complicated at first, actually simply result in endgames with a slight advantage to White, in most cases. }
8... Bg7
{ Black ignores the threat to the knight, instead focusing on development and sacrificing a pawn. Of the three main moves, this is the least popular one. But, I expect it to pick up in popularity, as it seems to be Black's best idea. }
9. Bb5
{ We are about to capture on c6 on the next turn. Having a bishop on c6 at the end would be great, and that is for a few reasons:  Maybe we could trade the bishops. Trading is almost always good when we are a pawn up! If not, the bishop would retreat to f3. On the h1-a8 diagonal, it will be placed perfectly.    Taking immediately  9.Nxc6?!  won't be as good since after  9...bxc6  10.Qxc6+  Bd7  , we need to move the queen again, wasting time, and we didn't trade as many pieces as we'd liked. }
9... O-O 10. Nxc6 bxc6 11. Bxc6
{ Now, White is a pawn up. In return, Black got the open b-file and is hoping that, alongside the g7-bishop, the rook on b8 would generate enough pressure on White's queenside to make up for the material deficit and prevent us from easily consolidating and converting the extra pawn.   Here, Black can try one of the two moves:  11...Bd7  , or  11...Rb8  . Those two moves are equally popular, but  11...Bd7  seems to be chosen by the stronger players, and it seems to be a better move too. }
11... Rb8
{ The rook goes to the open file, making it difficult for us to develop the c1-bishop. }
12. O-O
{ We are hoping to play Rb1, protecting the b2-pawn, and the Be3 or Bf4, developing the bishop. All we need is a couple of tempi to consolidate the queenside. }
12... Bf5
{ Black can also try to develop the bishop first, intending to put pressure on the c2-pawn and to free up the c-file for the rook. }
13. Bb5
{ We, however, get a break for a moment. And we use that break to block the b-file. Now, we are ready to get out the queenside pieces with Be3 and Rad1, which would be wonderful news. If that happens, we will be nearly winning, as we are a pawn up for not much compensation. }
13... Nd5
{ Black has to open up the a1-h8 diagonal and activate the bishop, looking to put pressure on our queenside as soon as possible. }
14. Nxd5 Qxd5 15. Bc4
{ We are getting ready to play Bb3 and block the b-file. Next, we'll restrict the black bishop with c2-c3 and will get the queenside pieces out. If that happens, we will have a winning position. }
15... Bd7
{ Black has to find this weird move, which is possible because our queen has to be protecting the c4-bishop. Black trades queens, which is a bit illogical when you are a pawn down. But, there are certain exceptions to this rule, the Benko Gambit being the most obvious and famous one. By trading the queens, Black isn't wasting valuable time retreating and is hoping to retain pressure on our queenside, created by the b8-rook and the g7-bishop, even in the endgame. }
16. Bxd5 Bxa4 17. Bb3
{ We block the b-file, of course, making the b2-pawn safer. } 17... Bc6 18. Rb1
{ And here comes another odd, but very precise and important move that we need to remember. Now, the b2-pawn is protected, which means we are getting very close to the long-term dream of managing to get the queenside pieces out. }
18... a5
{ Black has to keep making active threatening moves on the queenside, or else will slowly lose all the initiative. }
19. Re1
{ We place the rook on a semi-open file, attacking the e7-pawn, and even more importantly, preventing ...Be4, which could turn out a really annoying move to deal with. }
19... a4 20. Bc4
{ With b2-b3 coming next, and ...Be4 prevented, we seem to have successfully anticipated all the counterplay. Being a pawn up, we will slowly start advancing the queenside pawns, playing for a win risk-free and getting closer to the full point each move, as Black's initiative is fading away. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "20) Sicilian 2...g6"]
[Black "Sicilian 4.Qxd4 Nf6 5.Nc3 Nc6 #16"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5
{ This move initiates what we know as the Sicilian Defense, the queen of the @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  Black openings. Alongside  1.e4  e5  , it's one of the two most sound ways of meeting 1.e4  from the theoretical standpoint. Black is fighting for the center, the d4-square, without creating a symmetrical position. This opening is extremely popular with players who want sharp, creative and fighting chess, and those who don't want to settle for symmetry, less space, or any other concessions. }
2. Nf3
{ In this Lifetime Repertoire, I have decided to go for the most ambitious way of playing versus the Sicilian Defense − the so-called Open Sicilian. Why would I do that? Isn't this a positional repertoire, and isn't the Open Sicilian known to be sharp and principled? Well, here is the deal.  It's a Lifetime Repertoire. I want this course to carry a theoretical punch, which most sidelines cannot offer. I was considering the Alapin, 2.c3, as well, but decided to not go down that route, because the isolated pawn positions, which often arise there, aren't to everyone's taste.  Interestingly enough, in many sharp-looking positions, there is a path to simplifications, which means that with sufficient theoretical knowledge, we are playing risk-free. It's not possible to get an advantage in every single theoretical variation of the Sicilian as White, and maybe not even in most.  
What we are doing instead is something different. We are striving to test our opponent's knowledge of typical ideas and forcing lines, and if Black is prepared brilliantly, we accept the fact Black should be able to defend. However, we want to play risk-free, looking to get the better endgames or positions with pleasant positional pressure in the middlegame! }
2... g6
{ The so-called Hyper Accelerated Dragon. Black wants to keep the pawn on d7 for the time being, which is an important nuance: the option of playing ...d7-d5 remains open, thus discouraging White from ever going for the sharpest lines with queenside castling.   Another detail is that Black avoids the Rossolimo Variation, which arises after  2...Nc6  3.Bb5  ,  but allows for the Maroczy Bind @@StartBracket@@where White plays c2-c4@@EndBracket@@, and for the variation that I have chosen to suggest. }
3. d4 cxd4 4. Qxd4
{ This is one of the most principled lines versus the Hyper Accelerated Dragon, which requires Black to be knowledgeable and precise. Now, you might be surprised: am I not known for sidelines and practical choices? Why go for the main line, or one of those?  Well, here is what's interesting about chess. To people who are seeing some complex-looking line for the first time in their life, it might seem as though the positions are messy and unclear. However, especially as theory has gotten more advanced in recent years, people have understood that often forcing lines are simply a way to kill all the counterplay and get a pleasant endgame, for example.  Here, we would need to know a couple of specific sequences, sure. But the reward is endgames a pawn up or endgames with the bishop pair. These positions are NOT complex if we just know a few ideas, including the ones that allow us to simplify the game! Now, of course, Black's rook is hanging. }
4... Nf6 5. Nc3
{ We just keep developing. The knight protects the e4-pawn now, and we are getting ready to play e4-e5.   After  5.e5?!  Nc6  6.Qa4  Nd5  ,  Black's knight can easily retreat to c7 if needed. Unfortunately, the e5-pawn will be attacked with ...Bg7 and undermined with ...d7-d6. It's currently restricting Black's pieces quite considerably, so it would be very advantageous for Black to undermine it and get rid of it. We shouldn't be allowing this to happen! }
5... Nc6
{ The most logical move  (and the best one)  is to develop the knight with tempo. Where should the queen retreat? }
6. Qa4
{ The queen retreats exactly here, and that is in order to pin the c6-knight, especially after Black goes ...d7-d6. Remember this move! Now, e4-e5 is a considerable positional threat, so ...d7-d6 is sort of forced. }
6... d6
{ 6...Bg7?!  As usual, ignoring the threat  of e4-e5 isn't a good idea.  7.e5!  Ng8  8.Bf4±  and we transpose to the positions discussed after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pp1ppp1p/5np1/8/3QP3/2N2N2/PPP2PPP/R1B1KB1R b KQkq - 2 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Bg7  . }
7. e5
{ However, the move ...d7-d6, which is logical and nearly forced, has a downside. It makes the c6-knight pinned and allows us to start opening up the center to our benefit, trying to take advantage of that pin. }
7... dxe5 8. Nxe5
{ At this point, Black arrives at important crossroads and can choose between three logical continuations. The most popular one is  8...Bd7  , surrendering the bishop pair. The second one is  8...Qd4  , going for an inferior endgame with a bad pawn structure. The third one @@StartBracket@@and the best one!@@EndBracket@@ is the daring  8...Bg7  , ignoring the threat and sacrificing the pawn in exchange for rapid development and open b and c-files.  As I had promised, the lines we are about to see, while seemingly complicated at first, actually simply result in endgames with a slight advantage to White, in most cases. }
8... Bg7
{ Black ignores the threat to the knight, instead focusing on development and sacrificing a pawn. Of the three main moves, this is the least popular one. But, I expect it to pick up in popularity, as it seems to be Black's best idea. }
9. Bb5
{ We are about to capture on c6 on the next turn. Having a bishop on c6 at the end would be great, and that is for a few reasons:  Maybe we could trade the bishops. Trading is almost always good when we are a pawn up! If not, the bishop would retreat to f3. On the h1-a8 diagonal, it will be placed perfectly.    Taking immediately  9.Nxc6?!  won't be as good since after  9...bxc6  10.Qxc6+  Bd7  , we need to move the queen again, wasting time, and we didn't trade as many pieces as we'd liked. }
9... O-O 10. Nxc6 bxc6 11. Bxc6
{ Now, White is a pawn up. In return, Black got the open b-file and is hoping that, alongside the g7-bishop, the rook on b8 would generate enough pressure on White's queenside to make up for the material deficit and prevent us from easily consolidating and converting the extra pawn.   Here, Black can try one of the two moves:  11...Bd7  , or  11...Rb8  . Those two moves are equally popular, but  11...Bd7  seems to be chosen by the stronger players, and it seems to be a better move too. }
11... Rb8
{ The rook goes to the open file, making it difficult for us to develop the c1-bishop. }
12. O-O
{ We are hoping to play Rb1, protecting the b2-pawn, and the Be3 or Bf4, developing the bishop. All we need is a couple of tempi to consolidate the queenside. }
12... Qc7
{ Black can also place the queen on the c-file, putting pressure on the c6-bishop. }
13. Bf3
{ We move the bishop away, making sure our queen doesn't wind up overloaded with defensive tasks. Next, we plan on going Rb1 and getting the c1-bishop out, consolidating the queenside. }
13... Bd7 14. Qh4
{ The queen could be a bit vulnerable on the queenside; for example, on a6 it would be hit with ...Ra6, on a3 it could be bothered with ...Nc4 at some point, so White just moves it far away. The goal is to play Rb1, protecting the b2-pawn, and then Be3 or Bf4, finishing development. }
14... Rfc8
{ Logically enough, Black gets the other rook on an active position, where it can x-ray the c-file. }
15. Re1
{ With this move, we attack the e7-pawn, looking to play Bf4 without allowing for ... e7-e5. }
15... Qa5 { Black moves the queen away from the upcoming skewer. } 16. Bd2
{ In the only game that reached this position, White found this lovely move, which might seem impossible at a first glance, as it is leaving the b2-pawn unprotected. The goal is to prepare some trades with moves like Ne4 or Nd5. Potentially, we could also consider playing Bc3, blocking the a1-h8 diagonal and protecting the b2-pawn, once the knight moved away.  Here, Black can move the queen away from the x-ray, but in that case, we can also play Nd1, preparing Bc3. In the only game that I had mentioned, which got here, Black chose to take the b2-pawn. I am not sure if they saw what was coming − the decision isn't terrible, though.   16.Rxe7??  is a terrible blunder due to  16...Rxc3  17.bxc3  Qxc3-+  and our rook is trapped. }
16... Rxb2
{ 0-1 Kathmale-Cvitan, Zadar 2017.  16...Qd8  runs into  17.Nd1!?  when the idea is to play Bc3 and stabilize the queenside. Crucially, Black won't be happy after  17...Rxc2?  18.Bc3±  ,  as the rook gets trapped, and Ne3 is about to win an exchange. }
17. Nd1
{ Now, we are winning an exchange: the black queen and the b2-rook are both under attack! }
17... Qxd2 18. Nxb2 Qxc2 19. Qb4
{ In the arising position, we are undoubtedly playing for two results − we'll either convert the extra exchange for a pawn, or Black will hold a draw. For example, if the a-pawns get traded, I would think the arising position should be holdable: after all, any endgame 3 vs. 4 an exchange up, such as a rook vs. bishop, or a rook vs. knight, is a fairly easy theoretical draw.  So, we'd like to keep the a-pawns if possible, because the rooks greatly benefit from having targets on both parts of the board. But, again, while I cannot promise a win from here, it is obvious our opening play resulted in a wonderful outcome!  Next, we'll probably want to go Re2, kick out the annoying black queen, then move the a1-rook away from danger on the long dark diagonal, and improve the knight with Nd3. It would be very beneficial to trade the queens and a pair of rooks because if that happens, the a7-pawn will prove rather difficult to defend. }
*

