12. O-O
{ We simply castle, getting ready to develop our rook to d1 and put pressure on the d-file. }
12... Bxc6 13. Qxc6 Rb8
{ This was also tried in a few high-level games, but we have a precise defensive move. }
14. Rb1
{ White protects the b2-pawn in advance and gets ready to develop the bishop. If that happens, we will just be a pawn up, for not much compensation from Black's perspective. }
14... Qc8 15. Qa4
{ White kept the queens, preventing the f8-rook from coming into the game with a tempo. }
15... Ng4
{ Black tries to open up the g7-bishop by threatening to take on c3. } 16. Bf4
Rb7 17. h3 Ne5 18. Nd5
{ White, with a series of surgeon-level precise defensive moves, stabilized the position, kept the extra pawn, and went on to convincingly win the game. This isn't a very easy variation for Black to play, either! 1-0 Harsha-Sychev, chess.com 2022. }
