{ We simply castle, getting ready to develop our rook to d1 and put pressure on the d-file. }
12... Bxc6 13. Qxc6 Rc8
{ Black is immediately getting the rook on the open c-file, hoping to put pressure on the c3-knight and the c2-pawn if the knight ever moves. }
14. Qa6
{ Now, it makes sense for the queen to retreat exactly here because the a7-pawn is under attack. Black won't like the idea of dropping another pawn and has to spend some time defending it, which would hopefully allow us to get the queenside pieces out, solving the main problems of this variation. }
14... Qc7 15. h3
{ One of Black's ideas was to go ...Ng4, threatening mate on h2  (a fairly annoying thing to deal with!)  while also attacking the c3-knight with the bishop. We prevent that and now we are ready to play Be3. }
15... Rfd8
{ Black gets the last rook in the game. Unfortunately, this isn't fast enough or threatening enough. }
16. Be3
{ The a7-pawn is under attack, and you certainly wouldn't want to make a passive move like ...Ra8, would you? }
16... Nd5 17. Nxd5 Rxd5 18. c3
{ All the counterplay has been successfully prevented, and White went on to easily convert the extra pawn. Brilliant defense by the experienced Czech GM! 1-0 Neuman-Malyovanyi, Prague 2020. }
