2... e6
{ This move is a very flexible one. Black is getting ready to develop the light-squared bishop. Later, Black can choose to set up the Hedgehog-style setup with ...a7-a6, ...b7-b6, ...d7-d6, etc, or play more ambitiously on the queenside with ...a7-a6 and ...b7-b5.  Black could consider meeting d2-d4 with ...cxd4 and then ...Bc5 or ...Bb4, trying to deploy the dark-squared bishop actively. In terms of variations, this move is used by people who play the Taimanov Variation, the Kan Variation, the Scheveningen Variation, and some others. But, we have a different idea in mind this time, instead of the Open Sicilian! }
3. c4
{ With this move, we are grabbing space in the center, looking to play d2-d4 at some point, and setting up the so-called Maroczy Bind structure, which we also encounter in the 2...d6 positions. In particular, we'd like to delay d2-d4 in order to wait for Black to play ...Be7, or ...d7-d6, so that once the center opens up, Black can never pin our c3-knight with ...Bb4, or at least would need to do that at a loss of a tempo.   At this point, Black can make more than one move. The main one by far is  3...Nc6  . Some players also went for  3...a6  or  3...d6  , but we'll cover those on move 4 − it will be the same thing! }
3... Nc6
{ Now, we are facing a choice: we can play d2-d4 right now, which isn't a bad move, but it sort of ignores the point I had just made in the comments to our third move, or keep delaying that pawn push. }
4. Nc3
{ This is our main choice. We are waiting for Black to commit to ...Be7 or ...d7-d6, which would motivate us to push d2-d4, getting a wonderful Maroczy Bind or Hedgehog-type position.   Here, Black mostly goes  4...Nf6  . However, a bunch of other moves have been tried as well, such as  4...a6  and  4...d6  , keeping the tension and getting ready for the Hedgehog-type play, or  4...Nd4  , which prevents  the d2-d4 ideas completely, or even  4...e5  , which does the same thing. We'll look at all those moves except  4...e5  , which we'll cover on the next turn − that'd be the same thing. }
4... Nd4
{ A rather radical attempt to prevent us from playing d2-d4. Black would love to take advantage of the weakened square on d4 with ...Ne7-c6, ...g7-g6, ...Bg7, etc. So, we need to somewhat hurry. }
5. Bd3
{ Now, we are ready to capture the d4-knight, doubling Black's pawns and getting an extra pawn on the queenside, and retreat to e2 with the other knight without blocking the light-squared bishop. At this point, Black has many moves, but only two decisions: either take the f3-knight or keep the tension.   5.Nxd4?!  isn't a good idea, as after  5...cxd4  6.Ne2  e5  ,  the f1-bishop is stuck. Otherwise, our setup would be perfect. }
5... Ne7
{ The overwhelming majority of the Black players chose to keep the tension. So did my teammate and top-100 level player GM Gledura in a game versus me! }
6. Nxd4 cxd4 7. Ne2
{ We are very glad to reach this setup. Now, the c5-pawn has been displaced, which gives us an opportunity to not only grab space on the kingside with f2-f4 but also on the queenside with b2-b4! }
7... Nc6
{ Black defends the pawn, getting ready to develop the bishop and castle. } 8.
O-O
{ 8.Bc2  followed by 9.O-O  is nearly the exact same thing. But I find the text move more precise because sometimes we'd wait before playing Bc2. The rule of thumb remains correct − always make the necessary moves, such as castling, before the desirable/useful ones like Bc2! }
8... Be7
{ Black is getting ready to castle.  8...g6  can also be tried, looking to fianchetto the bishop, making the kingside a bit safer. After the logical developing moves  9.Bc2  Bg7  10.d3  O-O  , it might not be so easy to attack on the kingside anymore. However, Black’s bishop would be dearly missed on the queenside, and with  11.Bd2  , we will get ready to expand there. Making the kingside safer came at a cost! }
9. a3
{ We'd love to advance the queenside pawns and grab space with b2-b4 if we can. Black can allow it by castling, or doing almost anything, or prevent it with ...a7-a5. }
9... a5 { Black doesn't need to let us grab all the space, of course. } 10. Bc2
{ The bishop makes way for the d-pawn. The plan is d2-d3 and f2-f4. However, at some point we could consider improving the bishop via a4, possibly to take the opponent's knight and win the d4-pawn! We aren't likely to actually win a pawn, but by creating that threat, we could force ...e6-e5, which would make the d5-square weak, and our f2-f4-related play more useful. }
10... d5
{ Black can try to open up the center too. However, this isn't a great idea! }
11. exd5 exd5 12. d3
{ We are about to put a lot more pressure on the d5-pawn with Nf4, Bb3, and Qf3. So, sooner or later, Black would need to trade on c4. }
12... dxc4 13. dxc4
{ We have good control of the d5 and d3-squares. The d4-pawn is, of course, rather weak. Next, we can proceed with Nf4, Re1, and maybe even Qd3, trying to provoke some weaknesses on the kingside. What a wonderful position for White! }
*

