{ Black defends the pawn, getting ready to develop the bishop and castle. } 8.
O-O
{ 8.Bc2  followed by 9.O-O  is nearly the exact same thing. But I find the text move more precise because sometimes we'd wait before playing Bc2. The rule of thumb remains correct − always make the necessary moves, such as castling, before the desirable/useful ones like Bc2! }
8... Be7
{ Black is getting ready to castle.  8...g6  can also be tried, looking to fianchetto the bishop, making the kingside a bit safer. After the logical developing moves  9.Bc2  Bg7  10.d3  O-O  , it might not be so easy to attack on the kingside anymore. However, Black’s bishop would be dearly missed on the queenside, and with  11.Bd2  , we will get ready to expand there. Making the kingside safer came at a cost! }
9. a3
{ We'd love to advance the queenside pawns and grab space with b2-b4 if we can. Black can allow it by castling, or doing almost anything, or prevent it with ...a7-a5. }
9... a5 { Black doesn't need to let us grab all the space, of course. } 10. Bc2
{ The bishop makes way for the d-pawn. The plan is d2-d3 and f2-f4. However, at some point we could consider improving the bishop via a4, possibly to take the opponent's knight and win the d4-pawn! We aren't likely to actually win a pawn, but by creating that threat, we could force ...e6-e5, which would make the d5-square weak, and our f2-f4-related play more useful. }
10... O-O
{ It seems more prudent for Black to avoid making any decisions about the central pawns, at least for now. }
11. d3
{ We, of course, make this logical move, making room for the c1-bishop and overprotecting the c4 and e4-pawns. }
11... e5
{ Black overprotects the d4-pawn, preparing to play ...d7-d6 and develop the light-squared bishop. Black could also start with ...d7-d6, reaching the same position shortly. }
12. f4 { We are starting to expand on the kingside. } 12... d6 13. f5
{ With Ng3, Qg4, Nh5, Rf3-g3/h3, maybe g2-g4 coming next, we have a clear initiative on the kingside. Potentially, we could improve the bad light-squared bishop either by going Ba4 and taking on c6, or with Bd1-g4. I would be glad to trade it for a knight, but won't like to allow for ...bxc6 and ...d6-d5.  So, if Black ever went ...b7-b6, then the Ba4-xc6 idea gains tremendously in attractiveness! In either case, it seems as though we again enjoy a pleasant position without much counterplay available for our opponent. }
