{ First, we'll finish development, and so will the opponent. In a few moves, once all the pieces came out, we'd discuss the plans. }
7... Be7 8. O-O O-O 9. Be3
{ Now that some basic development moves have been played, let's discuss the plans. White has a lot more space. Black, in the Hedgehog positions, typically strives to play ...a7-a6, ...b7-b6, ...Bb7, ...Nbd7, ...Qc7, ...Rac8 and ...Rfd8, harmoniously setting all the pieces on the last two files, and controlling the 5th rank with the pawns − that's why the opening is called this way, referring to the pawns on the 6th rank as the hedgehog's needles.  However, there is a problem, Black's knight is already on c6. This is bad, because of several reasons:  the b7-bishop would be blocked; the knight on d7 could protect the b6-pawn and the f6-knight, and on c6, it cannot; if Black places the queen on c7, with the knight on c6 would often run into the typical Rc1-Nd5! temporary knight sacrifice.   Black can make several moves here, such as  9...a6  ,  9...Bd7  , or  9...Nxd4  . I suggest we focus on the plans instead of worrying too much about the specific move orders. Another issue Black has is  that ...b7-b6 can't be played now or anytime soon, as that'd hang the knight. We can try to advance on the kingside with f2-f4, Qd2, Kh1, Rg1, g2-g4.  The more positional plan would be playing f2-f3, reinforcing the e4-pawn, and then a2-a3, b2-b4, and Nb3 obtaining a dominant position on the queenside. That's the plan I like better, as this repertoire is not about going crazy. :@@EndBracket@@ }
9... Nxd4 { It's logical for Black to trade a pair of knights. } 10. Bxd4 b6
{ Finally, Black can develop the bishop to the long diagonal. } 11. Qd3
{ The queen belongs here, as it helps defend the e-pawn, coordinate the rooks, and from d3, it is ready to slide to g3 or h3 at some point. }
11... Bb7 12. Rad1
{ We keep centralizing the pieces, of course. Next, we'd love to play f2-f4, grabbing space on the kingside, and then f4-f5, hoping to provoke ...e6-e5, which would create a hole on d5. }
12... a6
{ Black takes the b5-square under control, hoping to prepare ...b6-b5 at some point. }
13. Qg3 { The e4-pawn isn't hanging due to the threat of checkmate on g7. }
13... Rc8
{ Let's imagine the opponent keeps the tension, continuing to develop.  13...e5??  14.Bxe5  just loses Black a pawn. }
14. b3
{ We overprotect the c4-pawn. There is no rush! The kingside play will start when we want! Black is in a very passive and difficult situation, and cannot make any pawn break work. So, it's logical to go ...Qc7 and ...Rfd8, isn't it? }
14... Qc7
{ Now, we could start the aforementioned kingside play with f2-f4, or instead open up the center. }
15. e5
{ Black, surprisingly, cannot at all afford a situation when the center opens up. }
15... dxe5
{ 15...Ne8  16.Na4±  and, finally, the material gains  (the b6-pawn)  follow. We are already winning, a pawn up, and with the more active pieces. }
16. Bxe5 { The queen cannot go to c6 due to Bf3! winning a piece. } 16... Qc5
17. Na4 Qa5 18. Bc3
{ There is nothing better than  18...Qf5  and after  19.Rd7  , Black loses a piece and the game. Amazing! }
