{ We are, of course, happy to open up the center right away, now that Black had wasted a tempo. }
5... cxd4 6. Nxd4
{ Here, Black can try a few moves. The moves like  6...Qc7  or  6...d6  will just get us a Hedgehog structure, which we examine via the 4...d6 move order. So, we'll look at  6...Bb4  ,  6...Bc5  and  6...Nf6?! }
6... Bc5
{ Black develops the bishop to an active square, looking to put pressure on the knight on d4 and control the g1-a7 diagonal. }
7. Nxc6 { Again, Black shouldn't want the endgame. } 7... bxc6 8. Bf4
{ I would like to recommend this really unusual move, which has been played in one game only so far. The goal is to install the bishop on d6, paralyzing Black's position! }
8... d6
{ Black should prevent the aforementioned positional threat, but there is a cost to that: the d6-pawn is now pretty weak. }
9. Qd2 { We are getting ready to play Rd1 and put pressure on the d6-pawn. }
9... Nf6 10. Rd1
{ The d6-pawn is under too much pressure. Black doesn't seem very well equipped for pushing ...d6-d5, opening the center, so it makes sense to go ...e5 instead. }
10... e5 11. Be3
{ We trade the bishops, looking to get rid of a defender of the d6-pawn.   11.Bxe5!?  This wins a pawn but allows for too much counterplay.  11...Bg4!  Now, Black is ready to take the e5-bishop, as his queen is no longer hanging!  After  12.Bxf6  Qxf6  , Black seems to have a lot of activity for the missing pawn − and, of course, the bishop pair. }
11... Bxe3 12. Qxe3
{ Next, we'll finish development with simple natural moves like Be2 and O-O and will simply double on the d-file with Rd2 and Rfd1, starting to attack the weak d6-pawn. At some point, ideas like c4-c5, or Na4-b6 could prove useful and advantageous too. Black is just clearly worse − and, as usual, has no counterplay. }
