{ Time to launch the f-pawn! Next, we'd love to play Nc2-e3, looking to control the f5-square. And, of course, the one on d5, but we are mostly interested in seeing ...exf4, when the f-file opens and we can jump into f5 with the knight, or in taking on e5 and then installing the knight on f5. }
9... exf4
{ A bit surprisingly  (to me, at least!)  , most Black players chose to capture, opening the f-file for our pieces, but getting an outpost on e5 for their knight. }
10. Bxf4
{ Next, we'll play Nc2, maybe Qd2, Rae1, Ne3, at some point we'll move the bishop away from f4 and will jump to f5 with the knight. Black tried a few setups here, such as ...Nd4 right away, looking to meet Nc2 by trading a pair of pieces, or ...Be6, preparing ...Nd7-e5. }
10... Nd4
{ GM L'Ami, a famous Dutch theoretician, made this move versus Carlsen's coach Agdestein. }
11. Nc2 Nxc2 12. Qxc2 Be6
{ Black managed to trade down, but I still consider the position rather passive. We can install the knight on d5 whenever we'd like, or even pursue a different plan, which would likely come off as a bit unexpected. }
13. Rad1 Nd7
{ Black tries to install the knight on an outpost on e5, where it would be placed perfectly. Also, Black could try improving the bishop with ...Bf6-e5 or ...Bf6-d4 at some point. But not now, as that would leave the d6-pawn hanging. }
14. d4
{ Unexpectedly, we are opening up the position, looking to get to the weak d6-pawn! }
14... cxd4 15. Nb5
{ The knight can pressure the d6-pawn, or take the d4-pawn, looking to jump to f5! }
15... Ne5 16. Nxd4
{ Next, we'll play b2-b3, making the c4-pawn feel overprotected and safe, and then will jump to f5 with the knight, creating pressure on the d6-pawn, as well as the e7-bishop and the g7-pawn. Later, we can choose to double the rooks on the f-file to put more pressure on the opponent's king, or the d-file, to put pressure on the d-pawn. Again, we have a clearly better position where the opponent has no counterplay. }
*

