{ This move is a very flexible one. Black is getting ready to develop the light-squared bishop. Later, Black can choose to set up the Hedgehog-style setup with ...a7-a6, ...b7-b6, ...d7-d6, etc, or play more ambitiously on the queenside with ...a7-a6 and ...b7-b5.  Black could consider meeting d2-d4 with ...cxd4 and then ...Bc5 or ...Bb4, trying to deploy the dark-squared bishop actively. In terms of variations, this move is used by people who play the Taimanov Variation, the Kan Variation, the Scheveningen Variation, and some others. But, we have a different idea in mind this time, instead of the Open Sicilian! }
3. c4
{ With this move, we are grabbing space in the center, looking to play d2-d4 at some point, and setting up the so-called Maroczy Bind structure, which we also encounter in the 2...d6 positions. In particular, we'd like to delay d2-d4 in order to wait for Black to play ...Be7, or ...d7-d6, so that once the center opens up, Black can never pin our c3-knight with ...Bb4, or at least would need to do that at a loss of a tempo.   At this point, Black can make more than one move. The main one by far is  3...Nc6  . Some players also went for  3...a6  or  3...d6  , but we'll cover those on move 4 − it will be the same thing! }
3... Nc6
{ Now, we are facing a choice: we can play d2-d4 right now, which isn't a bad move, but it sort of ignores the point I had just made in the comments to our third move, or keep delaying that pawn push. }
4. Nc3
{ This is our main choice. We are waiting for Black to commit to ...Be7 or ...d7-d6, which would motivate us to push d2-d4, getting a wonderful Maroczy Bind or Hedgehog-type position.   Here, Black mostly goes  4...Nf6  . However, a bunch of other moves have been tried as well, such as  4...a6  and  4...d6  , keeping the tension and getting ready for the Hedgehog-type play, or  4...Nd4  , which prevents  the d2-d4 ideas completely, or even  4...e5  , which does the same thing. We'll look at all those moves except  4...e5  , which we'll cover on the next turn − that'd be the same thing. }
4... Nf6
{ Black's main move, keeping the tension and asking us to show our intentions. The move  4...e5  is likely to transpose into the positions covered after  4...Nf6  5.Be2  e5  . However, Black can try a different setup: @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp1p1ppp/2n1p3/2p5/2P1P3/2N2N2/PP1P1PPP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 2 4@@EndFEN@@  4...e5  5.Be2  g6  6.O-O  Bg7  7.d3  Nge7  . The knight seems more flexible on that square, as it is not blocking the f-pawn. Nevertheless, it is not able to go anywhere.  Black could try playing ...Nd4 and ...Nec6 at some point, but I feel our knight will be more useful on c2-e3 than the black one could ever be on d4. So, I wouldn’t worry much about this move order. }
5. Be2
{ And we do it in a very clever way. The point is that, again, we want the opponent to go ...Be7, when we can push d2-d4 without worrying about running into that annoying ...Bb4 pin anymore, as pinning our knight that way would mean Black just wasted a tempo moving the bishop twice.   Now, the overwhelming majority of knowledgeable players go  5...d5  , opening up the center themselves, but some people go  5...Be7  , which we dearly welcome, or  5...e5  ,  preventing the d2-d4 advance. The moves like  5...a6  ,  5...b6  ,  5...d6  and whatnot are also possible, but they are covered on move  4. }
5... e5
{ Black can also choose to make this move, completely locking up the center and preventing any d2-d4 ideas. }
6. d3
{ We are reinforcing the center, making it possible for the dark-squared bishop to come out. }
6... Be7 7. O-O O-O
{ Now that both parties have made a few developing moves and achieved a completely symmetrical position, the natural question is what to do next. It's worth mentioning that we are TWO tempi up − one because we have the white pieces, and the second is because Black went ...e7-e6 and then ...e6-e5.  I suggest making way for the f-pawn, looking to grab space on the kingside. The center is completely locked up, so we have all the rights and reasons in the world to play on a flank. However, going for the queenside play with Rb1, a2-a3, Ne1-c2, b2-b4, and so on, isn't a bad idea, either.   7...d6  8.Ne1  would be a mere transposition. }
8. Ne1
{ Since the center is closed, we should go for the flank play, either with f2-f4 or with a2-a3 and b2-b4. }
8... d6 9. f4
{ Time to launch the f-pawn! Next, we'd love to play Nc2-e3, looking to control the f5-square. And, of course, the one on d5, but we are mostly interested in seeing ...exf4, when the f-file opens and we can jump into f5 with the knight, or in taking on e5 and then installing the knight on f5. }
9... exf4
{ A bit surprisingly  (to me, at least!)  , most Black players chose to capture, opening the f-file for our pieces, but getting an outpost on e5 for their knight. }
10. Bxf4
{ Next, we'll play Nc2, maybe Qd2, Rae1, Ne3, at some point we'll move the bishop away from f4 and will jump to f5 with the knight. Black tried a few setups here, such as ...Nd4 right away, looking to meet Nc2 by trading a pair of pieces, or ...Be6, preparing ...Nd7-e5. }
10... Be6
{ Most players, including very strong ones, such as GM Bu Xiangzhi, preferred to keep developing, looking to go ...Nd7-e5, keeping the option of jumping into d4 with the other knight. }
11. Nc2
{ The knight keeps pursuing its route to e3. We can also follow up with Qd2, then Rf2 and Raf1, doubling the rooks on the f-file. Or, instead, just like in the 10...Nd4 variation, we can try to push d3-d4, looking to put pressure on the d6-pawn. }
11... Nd7
{ Black is looking to use the outpost on e5, while also potentially gaining a possibility of activating the bad dark-squared bishop with ...Bf6-e5/d4. }
12. Qd2 Nde5 13. Nd5 Qd7
{ Black should keep the tension, instead of capturing on d5. However, now we can choose between many good plans.   13...Bxd5?!  14.exd5  is a pretty undesirable outcome for  Black because the c6-knight is being deprived of its wonderful square, and we can play d3-d4, or even b2-b4 next. }
14. b4
{ Hitting Black on the queenside too. We enjoy the semi-open f-file, and Black wouldn't ever want to open it up even more with ...f7-f5, as then we'd take on e7, grabbing the bishop pair in an open position. So, Black would be forced to stay passive, but then we can play Rb1, and either grab space on the queenside with b4-b5 or open the b-file with bxc5, depending on circumstances. We have another position with more space, active plans, and no counterplay for Black, and we are very happy about that. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "21) Sicilian 2...e6"]
[Black "Sicilian 2.Nf3 e6 3.c4 Nc6 4.Nc3 Nf6 #6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5
{ This move initiates what we know as the Sicilian Defense, the queen of the @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  Black openings. Alongside  1.e4  e5  , it's one of the two most sound ways of meeting 1.e4  from the theoretical standpoint. Black is fighting for the center, the d4-square, without creating a symmetrical position. This opening is extremely popular with players who want sharp, creative and fighting chess, and those who don't want to settle for symmetry, less space, or any other concessions. }
2. Nf3
{ In this Lifetime Repertoire, I have decided to go for the most ambitious way of playing versus the Sicilian Defense − the so-called Open Sicilian. Why would I do that? Isn't this a positional repertoire, and isn't the Open Sicilian known to be sharp and principled? Well, here is the deal.  It's a Lifetime Repertoire. I want this course to carry a theoretical punch, which most sidelines cannot offer. I was considering the Alapin, 2.c3, as well, but decided to not go down that route, because the isolated pawn positions, which often arise there, aren't to everyone's taste.  Interestingly enough, in many sharp-looking positions, there is a path to simplifications, which means that with sufficient theoretical knowledge, we are playing risk-free. It's not possible to get an advantage in every single theoretical variation of the Sicilian as White, and maybe not even in most.  
What we are doing instead is something different. We are striving to test our opponent's knowledge of typical ideas and forcing lines, and if Black is prepared brilliantly, we accept the fact Black should be able to defend. However, we want to play risk-free, looking to get the better endgames or positions with pleasant positional pressure in the middlegame! }
2... e6
{ This move is a very flexible one. Black is getting ready to develop the light-squared bishop. Later, Black can choose to set up the Hedgehog-style setup with ...a7-a6, ...b7-b6, ...d7-d6, etc, or play more ambitiously on the queenside with ...a7-a6 and ...b7-b5.  Black could consider meeting d2-d4 with ...cxd4 and then ...Bc5 or ...Bb4, trying to deploy the dark-squared bishop actively. In terms of variations, this move is used by people who play the Taimanov Variation, the Kan Variation, the Scheveningen Variation, and some others. But, we have a different idea in mind this time, instead of the Open Sicilian! }
3. c4
