3... Nc6
{ Now, we are facing a choice: we can play d2-d4 right now, which isn't a bad move, but it sort of ignores the point I had just made in the comments to our third move, or keep delaying that pawn push. }
4. Nc3
{ This is our main choice. We are waiting for Black to commit to ...Be7 or ...d7-d6, which would motivate us to push d2-d4, getting a wonderful Maroczy Bind or Hedgehog-type position.   Here, Black mostly goes  4...Nf6  . However, a bunch of other moves have been tried as well, such as  4...a6  and  4...d6  , keeping the tension and getting ready for the Hedgehog-type play, or  4...Nd4  , which prevents  the d2-d4 ideas completely, or even  4...e5  , which does the same thing. We'll look at all those moves except  4...e5  , which we'll cover on the next turn − that'd be the same thing. }
4... Nf6
{ Black's main move, keeping the tension and asking us to show our intentions. The move  4...e5  is likely to transpose into the positions covered after  4...Nf6  5.Be2  e5  . However, Black can try a different setup: @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp1p1ppp/2n1p3/2p5/2P1P3/2N2N2/PP1P1PPP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 2 4@@EndFEN@@  4...e5  5.Be2  g6  6.O-O  Bg7  7.d3  Nge7  . The knight seems more flexible on that square, as it is not blocking the f-pawn. Nevertheless, it is not able to go anywhere.  Black could try playing ...Nd4 and ...Nec6 at some point, but I feel our knight will be more useful on c2-e3 than the black one could ever be on d4. So, I wouldn’t worry much about this move order. }
5. Be2
{ And we do it in a very clever way. The point is that, again, we want the opponent to go ...Be7, when we can push d2-d4 without worrying about running into that annoying ...Bb4 pin anymore, as pinning our knight that way would mean Black just wasted a tempo moving the bishop twice.   Now, the overwhelming majority of knowledgeable players go  5...d5  , opening up the center themselves, but some people go  5...Be7  , which we dearly welcome, or  5...e5  ,  preventing the d2-d4 advance. The moves like  5...a6  ,  5...b6  ,  5...d6  and whatnot are also possible, but they are covered on move  4. }
5... Qb6
{ Black can also try to take the d4-square under control with this odd-looking move. That's not a bad idea at all: Kramnik tried this move versus Grischuk, and so did Caruana versus Carlsen! }
6. h3
{ The idea of this move is to prevent Black from going ...Ng4-e5, trading off a pair of knights. The knight on f6 isn't doing much, while ours on f3 is helping control the d4-square. And, we have more space. So, avoiding this trade is clearly in our favor.   6.e5?  isn't a good idea yet due to  6...Ng4!∓  and the e5-pawn falls. That's why our move 6.h3 is so useful! }
6... d6
{ Black should take the e5-square under control, preventing e4-e5.  6...Be7?  7.e5!  is again very awkward for Black to deal with, as time must be wasted now. }
7. O-O
{ Our goal will be to play d2-d3 and then start the ambitious queenside play with a2-a3, Rb1, and b2-b4! If needed, that pawn break can also be supported with Ne1-c2, Bd2, and so on. As we can see, the black queen's position is a rather awkward one, because it would become a target of our queenside play! }
7... Be7 8. d3 O-O 9. Rb1
{ We could also start with a2-a3. The plan, as we know, is a2-a3 followed by b2-b4. Importantly, Black does not have much counterplay, and cannot, of course, attack on the kingside in return − there are no pawns or pieces that could do that. Black cannot play for the ...d6-d5 break either, as there aren't enough pieces to make that work; and if Black ever did manage to play ...d6-d5, we'd respond with e4-e5!, locking up the center and grabbing space. }
9... Bd7 10. Be3
{ Now, White has a funny threat of playing b2-b4! Black won't be able to take with the knight, as after a2-a3, the knight would be lost. That's why the Black player tried stopping b2-b4 with ...a7-a5. }
10... a5 { However, now, it's the right time to open up the center! } 11. d4
cxd4 12. Nxd4
{ The pawn absolutely does not belong on a5, as now the b5-square is weak, and ...a7-a6 and ...b7-b5 are no longer an agenda. We just have a better version of any typical Hedgehog position, and are clearly better! ½-½ Kratzmajer-Kovacsy, Balatonlelle 2019. }
