{ Now, we are facing a choice: we can play d2-d4 right now, which isn't a bad move, but it sort of ignores the point I had just made in the comments to our third move, or keep delaying that pawn push. }
4. Nc3
{ This is our main choice. We are waiting for Black to commit to ...Be7 or ...d7-d6, which would motivate us to push d2-d4, getting a wonderful Maroczy Bind or Hedgehog-type position.   Here, Black mostly goes  4...Nf6  . However, a bunch of other moves have been tried as well, such as  4...a6  and  4...d6  , keeping the tension and getting ready for the Hedgehog-type play, or  4...Nd4  , which prevents  the d2-d4 ideas completely, or even  4...e5  , which does the same thing. We'll look at all those moves except  4...e5  , which we'll cover on the next turn − that'd be the same thing. }
4... Nf6
{ Black's main move, keeping the tension and asking us to show our intentions. The move  4...e5  is likely to transpose into the positions covered after  4...Nf6  5.Be2  e5  . However, Black can try a different setup: @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp1p1ppp/2n1p3/2p5/2P1P3/2N2N2/PP1P1PPP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 2 4@@EndFEN@@  4...e5  5.Be2  g6  6.O-O  Bg7  7.d3  Nge7  . The knight seems more flexible on that square, as it is not blocking the f-pawn. Nevertheless, it is not able to go anywhere.  Black could try playing ...Nd4 and ...Nec6 at some point, but I feel our knight will be more useful on c2-e3 than the black one could ever be on d4. So, I wouldn’t worry much about this move order. }
5. Be2
{ And we do it in a very clever way. The point is that, again, we want the opponent to go ...Be7, when we can push d2-d4 without worrying about running into that annoying ...Bb4 pin anymore, as pinning our knight that way would mean Black just wasted a tempo moving the bishop twice.   Now, the overwhelming majority of knowledgeable players go  5...d5  , opening up the center themselves, but some people go  5...Be7  , which we dearly welcome, or  5...e5  ,  preventing the d2-d4 advance. The moves like  5...a6  ,  5...b6  ,  5...d6  and whatnot are also possible, but they are covered on move  4. }
5... d5
{ This is the most forcing and reliable path for Black, who wants to get a solid position by liquidating the center. Realistically, Black cannot play for a win at all in this variation − we'll get a slight edge, which our opponent will need to work hard to neutralize. Why so? Because we are about to open up the center and be a tempo up in a symmetrical position! }
6. exd5 exd5
{ Black is threatening to push ...d5-d4. Of course, we don't want to capture the pawn, getting an isolated d-pawn and helping Black activate the knight. }
7. d4
{ So, we need to push the central pawn. However, we are very happy to do so. Now, we have an absolutely symmetrical position, except we have an extra move Be2, which means we should have some initiative. Of course, we are ready to castle on the next turn. If the position starts opening up, the extra tempo will make a world of difference. Especially if we can play Re1+ quickly at some point, starting to harass the black king! }
7... Be7
{ Black can also choose to develop and keep the tension, maintaining symmetry in the center for the time being. }
8. Be3
{ We are threatening to capture the c5-pawn since now we control the d4-square, which means Black won't be able to meet dxc5 with ...d5-d4. }
8... cxd4 { So, Black needs to release the tension in the center. } 9. Nxd4
{ Black can choose between trading a pair of knights on d4 right away, or castling first. Likely, one variation will transpose into the other. }
9... O-O 10. O-O
{ Both parties have made quite a few logical developing moves. Now, we'd like to capture on c6 and then on d5, creating an isolated pawn in Black's position. For that reason, Black needs to unload the center. }
10... Nxd4 11. Bxd4
{ We have a threat of capturing on d5, luring the knight on that square, and then winning a pawn with the familiar tactic Bxg7, taking advantage of the d5-knight's loose position. That's why an overwhelming majority of the Black players chose to capture on c4 right away, activating our other bishop but stopping that threat. }
11... dxc4 12. Bxc4
{ This position is extremely uncomfortable for Black, in my opinion. Next, we'd love to go Qa4, activating the queen. Don't worry, we are not hanging the d4-bishop − Black cannot take it due to a discovered attack on the queen with Bxf7+.  Then, we'll install the rooks on d1 and e1, and maybe will reroute our light-squared bishop to the h1-a8 diagonal with Be2-f3, putting pressure on the b7-pawn. As you can see, although the position is very symmetrical, we are clearly enjoying a pretty strong initiative because all of our pieces are a lot more active. }
12... b6
{ Black can also try to develop the bishop to the long diagonal, which seems rather logical. However, I don't think this plan leads to equality either. }
13. Re1
{ First, we activate the rook. The advantage of this move is that the queen would be forced to babysit the e7-bishop. }
13... Bb7 14. Qa4
{ As usual, we activate the queen this way. The next move will, of course, be Rad1, setting up x-rays on the d-file. }
14... Qc7
{ The high-level game between the super GM and Russia's Women's Team coach Rublevsky versus Caruana's and Giri's former coach Chuchelov saw the latter try this move, which removes the queen from danger on the d-file and prepares ...Qc6 @@StartBracket@@if not now, then later@@EndBracket@@, threatening checkmate on g2 and a queen trade. We also need to be careful about the idea ...Ng4!, harassing the h2-pawn. }
15. h3
{ That's why the prophylactic move h2-h3 is very logical and desirable. } 15...
Rad8
{ Black, logically enough, keeps getting more pieces in the game, attacking our bishop. It wasn't and still isn't easy to activate the other rook since the f7-pawn is under pressure, and a move like Qb3 could easily create a lot of problems with that square. }
16. Bf1
{ The bishop was no longer needed on c4, so we move it all the way back to overprotect the g2-pawn. This way, we also get to defend the d4-bishop with our queen in the most energy-efficient manner and can plan to place the rook on c1, looking to x-ray the queen with Nb5 or Nd5 at some point. }
16... a6
{ Black doesn't seem to have much to do, so it's logical to try to grab space on the queenside with ...b6-b5. }
17. Be5
{ We kick the queen out, while also making the bishop a bit safer − it won't be hanging, unlike on d4. This move also enables our queen to have access to the 4th rank, and we can consider moving it somewhere to f4, for instance, to put more pressure on Black's kingside, especially as a response to ...b6-b5. }
17... Qd7
{ So Black offers a queen trade, hoping to get rid of some of the pressure. }
18. Qb3 { No, thanks! } 18... b5 19. a4
{ Black managed to grab some space on the queenside, but in order to do that, Black had to overexpand the pawns a bit, making them vulnerable. We immediately take advantage of this fact, undermining them! Please note that our f1-bishop is not only safe, and is not only making the kingside safer, but it's also perfectly positioned to attack the queenside pawns! }
19... bxa4 { 19...b4?!  loses a pawn to  20.Bxf6  Bxf6  21.Qxb4±  . } 20. Rxa4
{ We are clearly better due to the much more active pieces and pressure on a6. Next, we can play Rfa1 and Qa2, putting even more pressure on the a6-pawn, and likely winning it very soon! }
*

