13. Qa4
{ With this cute move, we not only activate the queen, potentially preparing ideas like Rfe1, maybe h2-h3, and Be2-f3, but we also create a tactical threat! See, that g4-bishop is loose? A bit loose − defended just by the f6-knight. See where I am going with this? We are threatening to play Bxf6, eliminating its defender, then Bxf7+, and then Qxg4, winning a pawn!   13.f3  has also been tried, but it weakens  the g1-a7 diagonal. The d4-bishop would be taken with check, for example. So I don't like this move. }
13... Bh5
{ If I had to bet, I'd never bet on your opponents finding this odd prophylactic move, which stops the aforementioned tactical threat. }
14. Bb3
{ The point of this move is to overprotect the d4-bishop, make the ...a7-a6 and ...b7-b5 less harmful and threatening, and potentially prepare a very unexpected maneuver: Bd1!? The point of that idea is to either reroute the bishop to f3 if Black moves the bishop away to g6, obtaining a great deal of pressure on the b7-pawn, or have Black take on d1 and help us activate the rook! }
14... a6
{ Most Black players chose this move, which is aimed at grabbing space on the queenside with ...b7-b5. }
15. Be5
{ This move is a very useful and important one. We are preparing to meet ...b7-b5 with a queen retreat to d4 or f4. So, it helps free up the 4th rank. And, importantly, it also moves the loose d4-bishop away from the square where it was hanging! }
15... Bd6
{ In all three games that got here, Black chose to make this move, which offers a bishop trade, taking advantage of the fact we cannot go Rd1, as the d1-square is under the attack of the h5-bishop.   15...b5  16.Qf4  results in something very similar. }
16. Rae1
{ Any rook could go to e1 to protect the bishop, but I like the idea of using this one, because had we played Rfe1, the one on a1 would have been a bit loose, which could potentially matter in the event of things like ...Qb6-xb2, and so on. Always better to have a protected piece than a loose one! }
16... b5 { Black finally grabs space on the queenside. } 17. Qf4
{ The queen retreats to a safe square, where it puts pressure on the bishop on d6, forcing the trade. }
17... Bxe5 18. Rxe5
{ Now, the h5-bishop is a bit loose. There could always be ideas like Ne4 or Nd5, distracting the f6-knight to capture that bishop. With Rfe1 coming next, as well as Nd5 or Ne4 at any moment, it is obvious that we are enjoying a fair amount of initiative in an otherwise symmetrical position. What are our advantages?  all the pieces are more active; the f7-pawn is under pressure; the bishop on h5 is a bit loose and vulnerable to ideas like Rxh5 at some point, as well as g2-g4, f2-f4-f5, and so on; the queenside pawns are a bit overexpanded, which means they could become a target to ideas like a2-a4, or Bd5-b7 at some point. }
