10. dxc5
{ We are hoping to lure the bishop to c5, where it would be vulnerable to ideas like Qc2, Rc1, or even Ne4. However, in order to do that, we are agreeing to spoil our pawn structure. }
10... Bxc5 { This is a bad move though. } 11. Qc2
{ The threat, of course, is to capture the d5-knight, leaving the c5-bishop hanging. Black can take back with the queen, but that would run into Rd1, when at best, Black would lose a lot of time shuffling the queen around, and at worst, the bishop would be lost. }
11... Nxc3 12. Qxc3
{ Now, the bishop and the g7-pawn are both under attack, so Black is forced to concede the bishop pair. }
12... Bd4 13. Nxd4
{ No matter how Black recaptures back, we will at least have the bishop pair in an open position. Then, it would be beneficial for us to trade off the rooks and the queens, getting a nearly winning minor piece endgame with a powerful bishop pair and no counterplay.  We discuss the reasons why the side with the bishop pair almost always wants to swap off the queens and rooks in many other places in this chapter and the model games/ideas chapters, check those out for more details!   Let’s just see how exactly the game can go.  13...Nxd4  14.Bd1  O-O  15.Be3  Nc6  16.Bf3  and if @@StartFEN@@r2qk2r/pp3ppp/2n1b3/8/3N4/2Q5/PP2BPPP/R1B2RK1 b kq - 0 13@@EndFEN@@  13...Qxd4  14.Qa3  Qb4  15.Qxb4  Nxb4  16.Bd2  . White doesn’t need to worry much about specifics − our goal is very simple. We just need to make sure the opponent doesn’t get any accidental activity. Once Black’s pieces get kicked out, White will enjoy a nearly-winning endgame. }
