11... Bxc5
{ 11...Qxd1  12.Rxd1  Bxc5  transposes to the position discussed via @@StartFEN@@r2qk2r/pp2bppp/2n1b3/2P5/8/2P2N2/P3BPPP/R1BQ1RK1 b kq - 0 11@@EndFEN@@  11...Bxc5  12.Ng5  Qxd1  . }
12. Ng5
{ We are immediately harassing the bishop, hoping to get the bishop pair. }
12... Qxd1
{ Unfortunately, Black needs to trade queens, helping us develop the rook. }
13. Rxd1
{ Here, the Black players tried two moves:  13...O-O  and  13...Rd8  . } 13...
O-O
{ This seems to be a more reliable path, which should eventually lead Black to equality. The point is that Black is forced to give up the bishop pair and worsen the pawn structure, but hopes to open up the f-file and put pressure on the f2-pawn in return! }
14. Bf4
{ Black cannot really move the bishop on e6 away since doing that would allow for Bc4. If we can play that move, the f7-pawn will find itself under a lot of very annoying pressure. So, there is no need to take on e6 yet. Instead, we develop the bishop, potentially looking to take on e6 and meet ...fxe6 with Bg3, protecting the f2-pawn. }
14... Rfe8
{ Most Black players chose this move, which prevents the potential structural damage on the e-file. If we take on e6, Black is hoping to take back with the rook. }
15. Kf1
{ Again, there is no need to take just yet. Let's improve the king and overprotect the bishop on e2! I think in this position Black needs to make some ugly move like ...Nd8, but most people, including Caruana, Dominguez, and Jakovenko, went wrong! }
15... Rad8
{ This natural move gets Black in quite a bit of trouble! Instead,  15...Bc8  can be tried. Nonetheless, after  16.Bc4  Rf8  17.Ne4  , although Black is holding on, the position looks very unpleasant, as our pieces are so incredibly active. }
16. Nxe6
{ Now, Black is facing a tough choice. Trading on d1 means activating our rook, conceding the d-file, and allowing ideas like Rd7 and Bc4. }
16... Rxe6
{ So, Caruana and Dominguez in their games against the German GM Meier @@StartBracket@@By the way, look at that! He used this seemingly innocuous variation to get a nice advantage versus two top GMs!@@EndBracket@@ chose to take on e6 with the rook. }
17. Rxd8+ Nxd8 18. Rd1 Nc6
{ White is considerably better due to the bishop pair, the open d-file, and the ability to control the central squares b4 and d4. Meier tried a few different moves here, but I like his game versus Caruana. }
19. Rd5
{ Next, White can improve the position with c4-c5, grabbing space on the queenside and restricting the b7-pawn, or g2-g3, h4-h5, grabbing space on the kingside as well. We will be looking at the rest of this game in a chapter on model games! 1-0 Meier-Caruana, Porto Carras 2011. }
