{ With this move, we are grabbing space in the center, looking to play d2-d4 at some point, and setting up the so-called Maroczy Bind structure, which we also encounter in the 2...d6 positions. In particular, we'd like to delay d2-d4 in order to wait for Black to play ...Be7, or ...d7-d6, so that once the center opens up, Black can never pin our c3-knight with ...Bb4, or at least would need to do that at a loss of a tempo.   At this point, Black can make more than one move. The main one by far is  3...Nc6  . Some players also went for  3...a6  or  3...d6  , but we'll cover those on move 4 − it will be the same thing! }
3... Nc6
{ Now, we are facing a choice: we can play d2-d4 right now, which isn't a bad move, but it sort of ignores the point I had just made in the comments to our third move, or keep delaying that pawn push. }
4. d4
{ Frankly, this move, especially when associated with the somewhat simplifying plan that we are about to see, is fairly interesting as well. }
4... cxd4 5. Nxd4 Nf6
{ In almost all games, Black chose this move, which develops a piece and puts pressure on our center. }
6. Nc3
{ 6.Nxc6?  bxc6  7.e5?  is a terrible idea due to  7...Qa5+∓  and we are losing our central pawn. }
6... Bb4
{ Of course, this is the most principled continuation. Black pins our knight, threatening to capture the e4-pawn. Black is hopeful to see a passive move like  7.f3  , defending  the e4-pawn, to which Black could respond with  (8 ...d5!, blowing up the center and getting a ton of activity right away.) }
7. Nxc6
{ However, we are simplifying the game, trading off a pair of knights, and hoping to play e4-e5 on the next turn.   Now, Black has a choice: either go for the endgame or keep tension with  7...bxc6  . I would gladly take the endgame each time, but unfortunately, people choose to keep the tension 3 times as often. And I think it's objectively the better choice for Black. }
7... dxc6 8. Qxd8+ Kxd8
{ The king can hide on e7 or c7 − it's not the king that is a problem for Black. The problem is that we can go: }
9. e5
{ We grab a ton of space in the center, while also creating an outpost on d6. Now, the knight can either passively retreat back to d7, or make an active jump to e4, trying to take advantage of the pinned c3-knight. }
9... Nd7 { This results in a very passive position for Black. } 10. Bf4
{ First, we defend the pawn. Next, we'd love to castle queenside, unpinning the knight and activating the rook, and go Ne4-d6, invading on a wonderful outpost. So, it's logical for Black to ruin our pawn structure right away. }
10... Bxc3+ 11. bxc3
{ However, now we have the bishop pair and wonderful control over the center. Plus, the opponent's light-squared bishop is not exactly very impressive at the moment. }
11... b6
{ That's why most players chose to immediately start improving that piece. Black is looking to play ...Bb7 and ...c6-c5, or maybe ...Ba6 and ...Nc5, using the c5-outpost for a piece. }
12. h4
{ White is glad to grab a ton of space on the kingside, while also looking to activate the rook in a somewhat unusual manner  (via h3)  and bring it to g3, disturbing Black's kingside, or to d3, looking to double on the only open file and cause problems over there. }
12... Bb7 { Black keeps developing. } 13. h5
{ Now, if we have another move, we'd gladly play h5-h6!, either opening the h-file and causing structural damage to Black's pawns, or forcing ...g7-g6, when the dark squares become extremely weak, and our h6-pawn has great chances of becoming great in any endgame since if we win the one on h7, it would easily queen! }
13... h6 { Black must stop that. } 14. Rh4
{ The rook is coming over to g4. This is a problem because Black won't be able to protect the g7-pawn by moving it  (our pawn on h5 restricts the kingside greatly)  or by playing ...Rg8 since then Bxh6! would win a pawn, taking advantage of the pin on the g-file.  Even if Black doesn't lose anything, is clearly worse because we have the bishop pair, more space, the much more active pieces, targets on the kingside, and so on. Our c-pawns aren't weak, as Black has no way of attacking them. I'd take this position any time! ½-½ Kapnisis-Postny, Heraklion 2017. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "21) Sicilian 2...e6"]
[Black "Sicilian 2.Nf3 e6 3.c4 Nc6 − Alternative 4.d4 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5
{ This move initiates what we know as the Sicilian Defense, the queen of the @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  Black openings. Alongside  1.e4  e5  , it's one of the two most sound ways of meeting 1.e4  from the theoretical standpoint. Black is fighting for the center, the d4-square, without creating a symmetrical position. This opening is extremely popular with players who want sharp, creative and fighting chess, and those who don't want to settle for symmetry, less space, or any other concessions. }
2. Nf3
{ In this Lifetime Repertoire, I have decided to go for the most ambitious way of playing versus the Sicilian Defense − the so-called Open Sicilian. Why would I do that? Isn't this a positional repertoire, and isn't the Open Sicilian known to be sharp and principled? Well, here is the deal.  It's a Lifetime Repertoire. I want this course to carry a theoretical punch, which most sidelines cannot offer. I was considering the Alapin, 2.c3, as well, but decided to not go down that route, because the isolated pawn positions, which often arise there, aren't to everyone's taste.  Interestingly enough, in many sharp-looking positions, there is a path to simplifications, which means that with sufficient theoretical knowledge, we are playing risk-free. It's not possible to get an advantage in every single theoretical variation of the Sicilian as White, and maybe not even in most.  
What we are doing instead is something different. We are striving to test our opponent's knowledge of typical ideas and forcing lines, and if Black is prepared brilliantly, we accept the fact Black should be able to defend. However, we want to play risk-free, looking to get the better endgames or positions with pleasant positional pressure in the middlegame! }
2... e6
{ This move is a very flexible one. Black is getting ready to develop the light-squared bishop. Later, Black can choose to set up the Hedgehog-style setup with ...a7-a6, ...b7-b6, ...d7-d6, etc, or play more ambitiously on the queenside with ...a7-a6 and ...b7-b5.  Black could consider meeting d2-d4 with ...cxd4 and then ...Bc5 or ...Bb4, trying to deploy the dark-squared bishop actively. In terms of variations, this move is used by people who play the Taimanov Variation, the Kan Variation, the Scheveningen Variation, and some others. But, we have a different idea in mind this time, instead of the Open Sicilian! }
3. c4
{ With this move, we are grabbing space in the center, looking to play d2-d4 at some point, and setting up the so-called Maroczy Bind structure, which we also encounter in the 2...d6 positions. In particular, we'd like to delay d2-d4 in order to wait for Black to play ...Be7, or ...d7-d6, so that once the center opens up, Black can never pin our c3-knight with ...Bb4, or at least would need to do that at a loss of a tempo.   At this point, Black can make more than one move. The main one by far is  3...Nc6  . Some players also went for  3...a6  or  3...d6  , but we'll cover those on move 4 − it will be the same thing! }
3... Nc6
{ Now, we are facing a choice: we can play d2-d4 right now, which isn't a bad move, but it sort of ignores the point I had just made in the comments to our third move, or keep delaying that pawn push. }
4. d4
{ Frankly, this move, especially when associated with the somewhat simplifying plan that we are about to see, is fairly interesting as well. }
4... cxd4 5. Nxd4 Nf6
{ In almost all games, Black chose this move, which develops a piece and puts pressure on our center. }
6. Nc3
{ 6.Nxc6?  bxc6  7.e5?  is a terrible idea due to  7...Qa5+∓  and we are losing our central pawn. }
6... Bb4
{ Of course, this is the most principled continuation. Black pins our knight, threatening to capture the e4-pawn. Black is hopeful to see a passive move like  7.f3  , defending  the e4-pawn, to which Black could respond with  (8 ...d5!, blowing up the center and getting a ton of activity right away.) }
7. Nxc6
{ However, we are simplifying the game, trading off a pair of knights, and hoping to play e4-e5 on the next turn.   Now, Black has a choice: either go for the endgame or keep tension with  7...bxc6  . I would gladly take the endgame each time, but unfortunately, people choose to keep the tension 3 times as often. And I think it's objectively the better choice for Black. }
7... dxc6 8. Qxd8+ Kxd8
{ The king can hide on e7 or c7 − it's not the king that is a problem for Black. The problem is that we can go: }
9. e5
{ We grab a ton of space in the center, while also creating an outpost on d6. Now, the knight can either passively retreat back to d7, or make an active jump to e4, trying to take advantage of the pinned c3-knight. }
9... Ne4
{ The knight is pinned. Will we have to play the passive and awkward move  10.Bd2  , which allows Black to trade everything off, spoiling our structure, and getting rid of spatial disadvantage problems, as there will be no pieces left? No way! }
10. a3
{ We are offering a pawn sacrifice!  10.Bd2?  is very passive. After  10...Bxc3!  11.Bxc3  Nxc3  12.bxc3  c5⩱  , we have an inferior structure and nothing in return. }
10... Bxc3+
{ Black needs to capture the knight this way in order to ruin our structure.  10...Ba5?  is a bad idea, as after  11.b4  , we threaten to win a knight since we have unpinned. After the forced  11...Nxc3  12.bxa5±  , we are dominating the board due to the bishop pair, the open b-file, and the  powerful a5-pawn, which is considerably restricting Black's queenside. }
11. bxc3 { Now, Black can dare to take the pawn, or ignore it. } 11... Nxc3
{ This is too greedy and now, we get a powerful initiative. } 12. a4
{ This move achieves several things:  We cut off the path to escape via a4 for the black knight. We open up the a3-f8 diagonal for our unmatched dark-squared bishop. We are preparing a4-a5 in order to squeeze Black's queenside further. We are threatening to play Bd3, cutting off the black knight, and then winning it with Bb2 or Bd2. That's why the knight needs to try escaping immediately. }
12... Ne4 13. Be3
{ We prevent ...Nc5, threatening to win the knight with f2-f3. } 13... b6
{ Black needs to stop the threat of f2-f3 by preparing an escape square on c5 for the knight. }
14. a5
{ However, our initiative on the queenside is only getting started. Black is very uncomfortable here! Now, we are threatening to win the b6-pawn, as Black won't be able to take back due to the pin on the a-file. }
14... Rb8 15. axb6 axb6 16. Ra7
{ White is clearly pressing. The f7-pawn is hanging, the rook on h8 is passive, and Black lacks coordination. This is not a fun position for Black to play! Next, we can continue with Be2-f3, improving the other bishop and increasing pressure on the c6-pawn and down the h1-a8 diagonal. 1-0 Orev-Janakiev, Sofia 2009. }
*

