7... bxc6
{ This is a much more combative and ambitious continuation for Black, keeping the queens as well as the options of setting the pawns in several ways, such as playing for ...d7-d5, or ...d7-d6 and ...e6-e5, fighting for space in the center and for the d4-square. }
8. Bd3 { The e4-pawn was hanging, so we protect it. } 8... d5
{ Possible, but not very tempting. It turns out that opening up the center isn't something Black is ready for just yet. }
9. exd5 { The e4-pawn was hanging, so we take with it to address that issue. }
9... exd5 { 9...cxd5??  isn't possible, as  10.Qa4+  wins the bishop. } 10. O-O
{ By castling, we are not just making the king safe, while also getting ready to play Re1+, but we also unpin the c3-knight, getting ready to capture on d5. }
10... O-O
{ Black needs to escape the danger zone  (the e-file)  with the king as well. }
11. cxd5
{ However, now we are changing the pawn structure in the center, making Black accept an isolated pawn. }
11... cxd5 12. Be3
{ The bishop is getting ready to come to d4 − a wonderful outpost, from where it would control the entire board. Of course, Black cannot play ...d5-d4 due to the well-known tactical theme. So, we just enjoy the long-lasting positional advantage in a risk-free position. }
12... d4 13. Bxd4 Qxd4 14. Bxh7+ { Winning the queen. } *

