{ 6.Nxc6?  bxc6  7.e5?  is a terrible idea due to  7...Qa5+∓  and we are losing our central pawn. }
6... Bb4
{ Of course, this is the most principled continuation. Black pins our knight, threatening to capture the e4-pawn. Black is hopeful to see a passive move like  7.f3  , defending  the e4-pawn, to which Black could respond with  (8 ...d5!, blowing up the center and getting a ton of activity right away.) }
7. Nxc6
{ However, we are simplifying the game, trading off a pair of knights, and hoping to play e4-e5 on the next turn.   Now, Black has a choice: either go for the endgame or keep tension with  7...bxc6  . I would gladly take the endgame each time, but unfortunately, people choose to keep the tension 3 times as often. And I think it's objectively the better choice for Black. }
7... bxc6
{ This is a much more combative and ambitious continuation for Black, keeping the queens as well as the options of setting the pawns in several ways, such as playing for ...d7-d5, or ...d7-d6 and ...e6-e5, fighting for space in the center and for the d4-square. }
8. Bd3 { The e4-pawn was hanging, so we protect it. } 8... e5
{ This setup is the reason why I don't feel like recommending this entire variation as my main choice. Next, Black will play ...d7-d6, getting a flexible center, and achieving good control of many valuable squares, without going for any forcing lines, or having to accept a bad pawn structure. }
9. O-O O-O
{ Here, White has tried multiple moves, such as  10.Bg5  , pinning the knight, or  10.Be3  , simply developing and taking the g1-a7 diagonal under control. }
10. Qe2
{ This rare move was used on several occasions by Carlsen vs. Anand, by Nepo vs. Jakovenko, by Karjakin vs. MVL, and so on. White protects the e4-pawn one more time and is also getting ready to place the rook on the d-file, discouraging any ...d7-d5 ideas. Next, we can also consider such an idea as Na4 and c4-c5!, looking to cut out the bishop on b4, and prevent Black from playing ...d7-d6, making the pawn structure flexible and self-sufficient.  Importantly, exchanging on c3 is hardly ever a good idea for Black in these positions, as it only helps us get the d4-square under control, while also depriving Black of a powerful defender of the dark squares. That means that playing for Bg5 and f2-f4, for example, would be a much easier aspiration to accomplish. }
10... d6
{ So, Black connects the pawns, preventing any c4-c5 ideas and getting ready to develop the light-squared bishop. }
11. Na4
{ We are looking to play a2-a3 and b2-b4, grabbing space on the queenside. Black can try several moves here. But, for example, the most popular one fails to help Black get a good position. }
11... c5 12. a3
{ First, we kick the bishop out, preparing b2-b4 to grab space on the queenside. }
12... Ba5 13. Bd2
{ Now, the d5-square seems to be an outpost for our pieces, while d4 is one for the black ones. So why would we trade the dark-squared bishops, if it seems we need it to control d4? Plus, the black one looks restricted. And wouldn't we end up with a weird blocked light-squared bishop?  It's quite simple, actually. By trading the bishops, we are making b2-b4 much easier to accomplish. And then, once we push b2-b4, we'll make Black trade, which will open up the a-file, give us a few strong pawns on the queenside that control a lot of squares, and deprive Black of the strong outpost on d4: Black would still control that square with the e5-pawn, but that's not solid enough since we can always meet a move like ...Nd4 with f2-f4, or with Ne2/c2, trading it off. White is definitely pressing here! 0-1 Krysa-Quparadze, chess.com 2021. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "22) Sicilian 2...d6"]
[Black "Sicilian 2.Nf3 d6 3.d4 Nf6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5
{ This move initiates what we know as the Sicilian Defense, the queen of the @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  Black openings. Alongside  1.e4  e5  , it's one of the two most sound ways of meeting 1.e4  from the theoretical standpoint. Black is fighting for the center, the d4-square, without creating a symmetrical position. This opening is extremely popular with players who want sharp, creative and fighting chess, and those who don't want to settle for symmetry, less space, or any other concessions. }
2. Nf3
{ In this Lifetime Repertoire, I have decided to go for the most ambitious way of playing versus the Sicilian Defense − the so-called Open Sicilian. Why would I do that? Isn't this a positional repertoire, and isn't the Open Sicilian known to be sharp and principled? Well, here is the deal.  It's a Lifetime Repertoire. I want this course to carry a theoretical punch, which most sidelines cannot offer. I was considering the Alapin, 2.c3, as well, but decided to not go down that route, because the isolated pawn positions, which often arise there, aren't to everyone's taste.  Interestingly enough, in many sharp-looking positions, there is a path to simplifications, which means that with sufficient theoretical knowledge, we are playing risk-free. It's not possible to get an advantage in every single theoretical variation of the Sicilian as White, and maybe not even in most.  
What we are doing instead is something different. We are striving to test our opponent's knowledge of typical ideas and forcing lines, and if Black is prepared brilliantly, we accept the fact Black should be able to defend. However, we want to play risk-free, looking to get the better endgames or positions with pleasant positional pressure in the middlegame! }
2... d6
{ This is Black's most common move by far. What is the idea? By moving the pawn to d6, Black takes the e5-square under control. As a result, the knight can be developed to f6 on the next turn without running into the annoying e4-e5. Also, of course, Black makes it possible for the light-squared bishop to come out in the future, as well as the b8-knight, which at times goes to d7.   This move is used by the players who like the Najdorf Variation − the most complex and sound Sicilian line, objectively; the Dragon Variation − a sharp, uncompromising opening; and, sometimes, the Classical Sicilian, which can be played via  2...d6  or  2...Nc6  . If  2...d6  is chosen, it's because they want to avoid the Rossolimo. }
3. d4
{ We immediately open up the center. With this move, we are getting rid of Black's c5-pawn, which was controlling the central d4-square. We are also activating one of our pieces, which will take on d4. And, we are making it possible for the dark-squared bishop to come out in the future. Now, most Black players take the pawn, but in a very few games, the cheeky  3...Nf6  move order has been tried. }
3... Nf6
{ Some Black players use this cheeky move order to force our knight to go to c3. By doing so, they would get to play their favorite Open Sicilian positions while preventing any c2-c4 related plans, such as the @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pp2pppp/3p1n2/8/3NP3/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  5.f3  variation of the Open Sicilian, or our setups after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp2pppp/3p4/8/3pP3/5N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.Qxd4  followed by 5.c4. Of course, if you play the regular Open Sicilian as White, then @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pp2pppp/3p1n2/2p5/3PP3/5N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 1 4@@EndFEN@@  4.Nc3  is the easiest response. But we cannot afford to make that move. So, we'll go down the most principled forcing variation. }
4. dxc5
{ This is considered to be the reason why the otherwise practical and cunning 3...Nf6 isn't more popular. Now, Black is forced to enter a somewhat forced and somewhat unpleasant variation. }
4... Qa5+ { Possible, but not very good. } 5. c3 Qxc5 6. Bd3
{ We will simply transpose to the main lines we are used to, where we get to set up the Maroczy Bind, by playing h2-h3, O-O, Be3, c3-c4, Nc3, and so on. }
6... g6 { The only logical and ambitious place for the black bishop is here. }
7. h3
{ As usual, we are very happy to make this prophylactical move, which achieves a few goals:  It prevents Black from trading down with ...Bg4-Bxf3. If we ever play Be3, which we will, the Black knight won't be able to ever go to g4. So, we'll just have the standard Maroczy-style positions. }
7... Bg7 8. O-O O-O 9. Be3
{ We are glad that this natural developing move also wins a tempo. } 9... Qc7
10. c4
{ With Nc3, Qd2, Rfd1, a2-a3, b2-b4, etc coming next, or maybe Nd4 and f2-f4, we are enjoying the standard Maroczy-style spatial advantage in a position where the opponent doesn't have any counterplay. }
