3... cxd4 4. Qxd4
{ This variation is 20 times@@StartBracket@@!@@EndBracket@@ less popular than the main move  4.Nxd4  . This, of course, appeals a lot to an author like me, who prefers steering off the well-researched paths, preferring to look for new ideas.  Why is the queen going to d4? Isn't it dangerous to be in the center? Didn't we learn as beginners that the queen shouldn't come out too early? Well, let's see.  The queen can be attacked with ...e7-e5, but that move weakens the d6-pawn, creates a hole on d5, and doesn't help Black develop. We aren't afraid of that. Or, it can be attacked with ...Nc6. This is a bit annoying, but we can pin the knight with Bb5, or retreat to e3. So why are we taking with the queen, after all? This move contains several ideas, such as:  Protecting the e4-pawn. In some lines, making it possible to castle queenside faster. By protecting the e4-pawn, we might be able to avoid playing Nc3, which means the c-pawn is free to advance to c4, forming the Maroczy Bind − a strong pawn formation, which occupies the entire center, preventing counterplay.    Here, Black chooses between several moves. The most popular one is @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp2pppp/3p4/8/3QP3/5N2/PPP2PPP/RNB1KB1R b KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Nc6  . They also tried  4...a6  and  4...Bd7  −  both of those are aimed at preventing Bb5. However, the strongest move nowadays is  considered  4...Nf6  . Luckily, it's been played in only about 7% of the games or so, so most people still haven't caught on! }
4... Nc6
{ This logical move, which attacks the queen and develops a piece to a central square with a tempo, is Black's most popular one by far. Now, White is at large crossroads. Most people, nearly 95% of the players, have chosen to pin the knight with  5.Bb5  .  That move results in pretty complex positions, where White often castles queenside. That's an interesting choice, and it's a choice we will make, as an alternative option, if Black chooses the more cunning move order, which has been discovered recently: @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp2pppp/3p4/8/3QP3/5N2/PPP2PPP/RNB1KB1R b KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Nf6  . However, this is not what I'd like to go for if given a choice. }
5. Qe3
{ As usual, we retreat to this square, where the queen is protecting the e4-pawn. The plan is the same: we'd like to install the pawn on c4, develop with Be2, O-O, play h2-h3 to restrict Black even more, and develop the knight to c3. Black will likely fianchetto the dark-squared bishop, so we'll want to make sure the long diagonal is safe and play Rb1, b2-b3, Bb2, and Rfd1. If we achieve that standard setup, we would have a somewhat more pleasant position due to our spatial advantage.   However, there is a problem. The issue is that compared to the @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp2pppp/3p4/8/3QP3/5N2/PPP2PPP/RNB1KB1R b KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...a6  and  4...Bd7  lines, Black is literally a tempo up since no move has been spent defending against an idea we have no intention of using anyway. So, we might not be able to accomplish everything we want. }
5... Nf6 { 5...g6  6.Be2  is the same thing. } 6. Be2 g6
{ As usual, the long diagonal is where the black bishop belongs. } 7. O-O Bg7
8. h3
{ This slow prophylactic move is the move most people have made, and for a good reason. I would like to save a tempo and focus on development, but it doesn't seem possible to do so. Check the Informational on  8.Rd1  for more details. }
8... O-O 9. Rd1
{ Now, we are ready to proceed with e4-e5, so Black has to do something about that. Here is an important detail. Since we are a full tempo down, compared to the 4...a6 positions, we might need to save this tempo on something else. We might choose to forego the move c2-c4.  Yes, I know, this sounds barbarian, since I had said this variation is all about reaching some kind of a Maroczy Bind. But, such is life. We don't always get the structure we want! However, the good news is that if we choose to play Nc3 without c2-c4, we speed up our development and can still keep fighting for the opening advantage and posing problems to Black! }
9... Be6
{ Another popular continuation. Black wants to meet e4-e5? with ...Nd5!, blocking the d-file and winning a pawn. And, of course, Black keeps developing the pieces, preparing the move ...Rc8.  Here, I think it's reasonable to consider both Nc3 and c2-c4. I feel like we have enough time for the pawn expansion since the move ...Be6 was a bit slow. But, we can also just develop instead. Let's do that so that we don't get confused: in all the main line setups, we'll be playing without c2-c4. }
10. Nc3
{ 10.c4  is another interesting move to explore, and I think it's a rather promising direction as well! }
10... Rc8
{ Black, logically enough, follows up with another developing move, which places the rook on the c-file. Next, Black would probably like to play ...a7-a6 and ...b7-b5. }
11. Rb1
{ This move looks really weird, doesn't it? The idea can be seen in the  11.Nd5  clickable variation: we'd like to install the knight  on d5, but cannot do that for tactical reasons − in particular, because of ...Nb4-c2! coming with a fork. So, we are removing the rook from danger in advance.    11.Nd5  doesn't work at this moment, because after  11...Bxd5  12.exd5  Nb4  , there are threats  to the d5-pawn and to the c2-pawn − and the latter comes with a fork on the a1-rook! That's why we remove it in advance! }
11... Qc7
{ In all the games that reached this position, Black chose this move, which connects the rooks, potentially preparing ...Rfd8, while also increasing pressure on the c-file and avoiding x-ray problems on the d-file.   11...Nb4  would only drop a pawn:  12.Qxa7  and now  12...Nxc2  runs into  13.Qa4  , while @@StartFEN@@2rq1rk1/Qp2ppbp/3pbnp1/8/1n2P3/2N2N1P/PPP1BPP1/1RBR2K1 b - - 0 12@@EndFEN@@  12...Nxa2  13.Nxa2  Ra8  14.Qxb7  gives White a significant advantage as well. }
12. a3
{ Another subtle prophylactic move. The idea, again, is to make sure ...Nb4 doesn't ever happen.  12.Nd5  is possible now but isn't that great.  12...Bxd5  13.exd5  Nb4  is still a fork − this time a triple one, including on  the a2-pawn! }
12... a6 { Black is preparing ...b7-b5. } 13. Nd5
{ Finally, the knight is gladly going to the central square. If Black were to retreat, we'd love to grab space with b2-b4, c2-c4, etc. By the way, here we can see another benefit of the subtle move Rb1: the long a1-h8 diagonal is safe from any tactical tricks, which wouldn't be the case had the rook stayed on a1! }
13... Bxd5
{ Black needs to take with the bishop, of course, as the other capture would have lost a piece to a fork. }
14. exd5 Na5 { Another mandatory move. The knight is looking to come to c4. }
15. c3 { The c2-pawn was under attack, so we deal with that problem. } 15... b5
{ This position has occurred in two games. Let's describe it, and understand what are the good and bad things about it.  We have more space thanks to the d5-pawn.  We have the bishop pair, which would be useful as the position opens up, but isn't that useful now.   The d5-pawn's position is reinforcing the fact that Black's e7-pawn is backward and a bit weak. At the same time, Black enjoys the wonderful c4-square for the knight and doesn't really have any noticeable weaknesses yet. Sure, the e7-pawn is backward, and in some situations, Black's queenside pawns could get undermined with a3-a4, but for now, this doesn't seem to be a problem.  
So, realistically, a complex balanced game is ahead. I somewhat prefer White because of the aforementioned factors, however. Next, I think we should consider improving our knight and bishops. If you can play Nd4, that'd be great. It's a bit difficult to do so, however, because of the d5-pawn.   We can consider the Ne1-c4-b4 idea, increasing pressure on the queenside. Our bishop could go to f1 in order to not be in the way, or to f3 in order to protect the d5-pawn. Black can make one active move − ...Nc4, but besides that, doesn't seem to be able to threaten us somehow. So, we'll improve the knight and the bishops, and hopefully blow up the queenside with a3-a4 someday. It's a very promising position! }
16. Ne1
{ The knight is starting its maneuver, which I had described above. Have fun exploring this position! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "22) Sicilian 2...d6"]
[Black "Sicilian 3.d4 cxd4 4.Qxd4 Nc6 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5
{ This move initiates what we know as the Sicilian Defense, the queen of the @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  Black openings. Alongside  1.e4  e5  , it's one of the two most sound ways of meeting 1.e4  from the theoretical standpoint. Black is fighting for the center, the d4-square, without creating a symmetrical position. This opening is extremely popular with players who want sharp, creative and fighting chess, and those who don't want to settle for symmetry, less space, or any other concessions. }
2. Nf3
{ In this Lifetime Repertoire, I have decided to go for the most ambitious way of playing versus the Sicilian Defense − the so-called Open Sicilian. Why would I do that? Isn't this a positional repertoire, and isn't the Open Sicilian known to be sharp and principled? Well, here is the deal.  It's a Lifetime Repertoire. I want this course to carry a theoretical punch, which most sidelines cannot offer. I was considering the Alapin, 2.c3, as well, but decided to not go down that route, because the isolated pawn positions, which often arise there, aren't to everyone's taste.  Interestingly enough, in many sharp-looking positions, there is a path to simplifications, which means that with sufficient theoretical knowledge, we are playing risk-free. It's not possible to get an advantage in every single theoretical variation of the Sicilian as White, and maybe not even in most.  
What we are doing instead is something different. We are striving to test our opponent's knowledge of typical ideas and forcing lines, and if Black is prepared brilliantly, we accept the fact Black should be able to defend. However, we want to play risk-free, looking to get the better endgames or positions with pleasant positional pressure in the middlegame! }
2... d6
{ This is Black's most common move by far. What is the idea? By moving the pawn to d6, Black takes the e5-square under control. As a result, the knight can be developed to f6 on the next turn without running into the annoying e4-e5. Also, of course, Black makes it possible for the light-squared bishop to come out in the future, as well as the b8-knight, which at times goes to d7.   This move is used by the players who like the Najdorf Variation − the most complex and sound Sicilian line, objectively; the Dragon Variation − a sharp, uncompromising opening; and, sometimes, the Classical Sicilian, which can be played via  2...d6  or  2...Nc6  . If  2...d6  is chosen, it's because they want to avoid the Rossolimo. }
3. d4
{ We immediately open up the center. With this move, we are getting rid of Black's c5-pawn, which was controlling the central d4-square. We are also activating one of our pieces, which will take on d4. And, we are making it possible for the dark-squared bishop to come out in the future. Now, most Black players take the pawn, but in a very few games, the cheeky  3...Nf6  move order has been tried. }
3... cxd4 4. Qxd4
{ This variation is 20 times@@StartBracket@@!@@EndBracket@@ less popular than the main move  4.Nxd4  . This, of course, appeals a lot to an author like me, who prefers steering off the well-researched paths, preferring to look for new ideas.  Why is the queen going to d4? Isn't it dangerous to be in the center? Didn't we learn as beginners that the queen shouldn't come out too early? Well, let's see.  The queen can be attacked with ...e7-e5, but that move weakens the d6-pawn, creates a hole on d5, and doesn't help Black develop. We aren't afraid of that. Or, it can be attacked with ...Nc6. This is a bit annoying, but we can pin the knight with Bb5, or retreat to e3. So why are we taking with the queen, after all? This move contains several ideas, such as:  Protecting the e4-pawn. In some lines, making it possible to castle queenside faster. By protecting the e4-pawn, we might be able to avoid playing Nc3, which means the c-pawn is free to advance to c4, forming the Maroczy Bind − a strong pawn formation, which occupies the entire center, preventing counterplay.    Here, Black chooses between several moves. The most popular one is @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp2pppp/3p4/8/3QP3/5N2/PPP2PPP/RNB1KB1R b KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Nc6  . They also tried  4...a6  and  4...Bd7  −  both of those are aimed at preventing Bb5. However, the strongest move nowadays is  considered  4...Nf6  . Luckily, it's been played in only about 7% of the games or so, so most people still haven't caught on! }
4... Nc6
{ This logical move, which attacks the queen and develops a piece to a central square with a tempo, is Black's most popular one by far. Now, White is at large crossroads. Most people, nearly 95% of the players, have chosen to pin the knight with  5.Bb5  .  That move results in pretty complex positions, where White often castles queenside. That's an interesting choice, and it's a choice we will make, as an alternative option, if Black chooses the more cunning move order, which has been discovered recently: @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp2pppp/3p4/8/3QP3/5N2/PPP2PPP/RNB1KB1R b KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Nf6  . However, this is not what I'd like to go for if given a choice. }
5. Qe3
{ As usual, we retreat to this square, where the queen is protecting the e4-pawn. The plan is the same: we'd like to install the pawn on c4, develop with Be2, O-O, play h2-h3 to restrict Black even more, and develop the knight to c3. Black will likely fianchetto the dark-squared bishop, so we'll want to make sure the long diagonal is safe and play Rb1, b2-b3, Bb2, and Rfd1. If we achieve that standard setup, we would have a somewhat more pleasant position due to our spatial advantage.   However, there is a problem. The issue is that compared to the @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp2pppp/3p4/8/3QP3/5N2/PPP2PPP/RNB1KB1R b KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...a6  and  4...Bd7  lines, Black is literally a tempo up since no move has been spent defending against an idea we have no intention of using anyway. So, we might not be able to accomplish everything we want. }
5... Nf6 { 5...g6  6.Be2  is the same thing. } 6. Be2 g6
{ As usual, the long diagonal is where the black bishop belongs. } 7. O-O Bg7
8. h3
{ This slow prophylactic move is the move most people have made, and for a good reason. I would like to save a tempo and focus on development, but it doesn't seem possible to do so. Check the Informational on  8.Rd1  for more details. }
8... O-O 9. Rd1
{ Now, we are ready to proceed with e4-e5, so Black has to do something about that. Here is an important detail. Since we are a full tempo down, compared to the 4...a6 positions, we might need to save this tempo on something else. We might choose to forego the move c2-c4.  Yes, I know, this sounds barbarian, since I had said this variation is all about reaching some kind of a Maroczy Bind. But, such is life. We don't always get the structure we want! However, the good news is that if we choose to play Nc3 without c2-c4, we speed up our development and can still keep fighting for the opening advantage and posing problems to Black! }
9... Qc7
{ Black can also try making some other developing move, such as this one. Again, we choose between Nc3 and c2-c4. }
10. c4
{ Generally, I lean towards c2-c4 being more attractive when the black queen had already moved because I am more afraid of it coming to b6 or a5, while on c7, it seems misplaced. But,  10.Nc3  is also good, of course, and will likely simply transpose to the positions analyzed via @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/pp2ppbp/2np1np1/8/4P3/4QN1P/PPP1BPP1/RNBR2K1 b - - 2 9@@EndFEN@@  9...Nd7  or  9...Be6  . }
*

