{ As usual, the long diagonal is where the black bishop belongs. } 7. O-O Bg7
8. h3
{ This slow prophylactic move is the move most people have made, and for a good reason. I would like to save a tempo and focus on development, but it doesn't seem possible to do so. Check the Informational on  8.Rd1  for more details. }
8... O-O 9. Rd1
{ Now, we are ready to proceed with e4-e5, so Black has to do something about that. Here is an important detail. Since we are a full tempo down, compared to the 4...a6 positions, we might need to save this tempo on something else. We might choose to forego the move c2-c4.  Yes, I know, this sounds barbarian, since I had said this variation is all about reaching some kind of a Maroczy Bind. But, such is life. We don't always get the structure we want! However, the good news is that if we choose to play Nc3 without c2-c4, we speed up our development and can still keep fighting for the opening advantage and posing problems to Black! }
9... Nd7
{ Logically enough, most Black players have chosen to make this prophylactic move, which blocks the d-file, and opens up the g7-bishop. }
10. Nc3
{ Given that Black has just made a fairly passive move ...Nd7, we are asking, what's next? Of course, going ...Nc5 seems rather logical, but a bit dangerous, as the knight can always run into b2-b4, and since the e4-e5 ideas start to appear again.   10.c4?!  has been played in some games, but I don't think it is fast enough. In particular, I don't like the fact that Black can play  10...Qb6!  offering a queen trade and attacking  the b2-pawn. If we take, ...axb6! followed by ...Nb4! will give the opponent a lot of counterplay on the queenside, which is not nice. On the other hand, after  11.Qd2  Nc5!  ,  the e4-pawn is hanging. We'll need to offer a pawn sacrifice after  12.Nc3  Bxc3  13.Qxc3  Nxe4  , and I am not sure if I want to do that, as Black's pieces are very active too. }
10... b6
{ Most players choose to make this quiet developing move, which is just preparing ...Bb7 followed by ...Rc8. That's fair enough, but now the queen can no longer go to a5, which means Black won't have a lot of counterplay or threats, and the kingside doesn't have a lot of defenders. So, we can try doing something exciting over there! }
11. Qg5
{ Technically speaking, this cheeky move isn't a novelty, as it's been tried in one game. But, since there are quite a few 2700-level games and this move has been played once by an FM, I think it almost qualifies as a new idea. :@@EndBracket@@ Our goal is to take advantage of the fact that the black knight, which could defend the king from f6, has gone away. We want to proceed with Qh4 and Bh6 followed by Ng5, trying to set up a powerful and annoying attack on the opponent's king. And without making any positional concessions or sacrificing material! }
11... Bb7 12. Qh4
{ We are ready to play Bh6 and Ng5. If we are allowed to do that, the position would become really unpleasant! So, Black needs to hurry and offer some piece trades. }
12... Nce5
{ And here, I would like to suggest an improvement. White went  13.Ng5  , but got the knight kicked out of there, and did not accomplish much. Instead, it seems more promising to simply keep the tension. ½-½ Gheorghiu-Nevednichy, Alba Iulia 2021. }
13. Nd4
{ Next, we can consider Bg5, followed by Nd5, putting pressure on the e7-pawn. Alternatively, we can play f2-f4 at some point, kicking the opponent's knight out of its lovely centralized position. }
13... Rc8
{ It seems logical that Black would want to get some counterplay on the semi-open c-file. Next, Black would probably want to continue with ...a7-a6, ...b6-b5, ...Nb6-c4, and get counterplay in that manner. }
14. Bh6
{ We should offer a bishop trade. Now, we might be ready to follow up with f2-f4. I did not want to make this move with the bishop still on c1, as it would have gotten blocked. It's a brand-new position, so it's not exactly obvious what Black would do. }
14... a6 { Preparing counterplay with ...b6-b5. } 15. a4
{ And we prevent that idea quite easily and effortlessly! } 15... Nc4
{ Just as in many other Sicilian positions, it seems natural to jump here with the knight, putting pressure on the b2-pawn. }
16. Nd5
{ Now, the e7-pawn is under quite a lot of pressure. And, it turns out, one more threat is around the corner. Black should probably trade bishops on h6 and play ...e7-e6, somewhat weakening the pawn structure, but solving the king-related problems. Nonetheless, it's natural to just defend the pawn, isn't it? }
16... Re8 17. Nf5
{ Wow! Suddenly, there is a very powerful kingside attack! Black cannot capture the knight, as after Qg5! the king will just get checkmated on the next turn. However, the e7-pawn is hanging, and so is the dark-squared bishop! All of a sudden, Black is nearly lost. }
*

