[White "22) Sicilian 2...d6"]
[Black "Sicilian 3.d4 cxd4 4.Qxd4 a6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5
{ This move initiates what we know as the Sicilian Defense, the queen of the @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  Black openings. Alongside  1.e4  e5  , it's one of the two most sound ways of meeting 1.e4  from the theoretical standpoint. Black is fighting for the center, the d4-square, without creating a symmetrical position. This opening is extremely popular with players who want sharp, creative and fighting chess, and those who don't want to settle for symmetry, less space, or any other concessions. }
2. Nf3
{ In this Lifetime Repertoire, I have decided to go for the most ambitious way of playing versus the Sicilian Defense − the so-called Open Sicilian. Why would I do that? Isn't this a positional repertoire, and isn't the Open Sicilian known to be sharp and principled? Well, here is the deal.  It's a Lifetime Repertoire. I want this course to carry a theoretical punch, which most sidelines cannot offer. I was considering the Alapin, 2.c3, as well, but decided to not go down that route, because the isolated pawn positions, which often arise there, aren't to everyone's taste.  Interestingly enough, in many sharp-looking positions, there is a path to simplifications, which means that with sufficient theoretical knowledge, we are playing risk-free. It's not possible to get an advantage in every single theoretical variation of the Sicilian as White, and maybe not even in most.  
What we are doing instead is something different. We are striving to test our opponent's knowledge of typical ideas and forcing lines, and if Black is prepared brilliantly, we accept the fact Black should be able to defend. However, we want to play risk-free, looking to get the better endgames or positions with pleasant positional pressure in the middlegame! }
2... d6
{ This is Black's most common move by far. What is the idea? By moving the pawn to d6, Black takes the e5-square under control. As a result, the knight can be developed to f6 on the next turn without running into the annoying e4-e5. Also, of course, Black makes it possible for the light-squared bishop to come out in the future, as well as the b8-knight, which at times goes to d7.   This move is used by the players who like the Najdorf Variation − the most complex and sound Sicilian line, objectively; the Dragon Variation − a sharp, uncompromising opening; and, sometimes, the Classical Sicilian, which can be played via  2...d6  or  2...Nc6  . If  2...d6  is chosen, it's because they want to avoid the Rossolimo. }
3. d4
{ We immediately open up the center. With this move, we are getting rid of Black's c5-pawn, which was controlling the central d4-square. We are also activating one of our pieces, which will take on d4. And, we are making it possible for the dark-squared bishop to come out in the future. Now, most Black players take the pawn, but in a very few games, the cheeky  3...Nf6  move order has been tried. }
3... cxd4 4. Qxd4
{ This variation is 20 times@@StartBracket@@!@@EndBracket@@ less popular than the main move  4.Nxd4  . This, of course, appeals a lot to an author like me, who prefers steering off the well-researched paths, preferring to look for new ideas.  Why is the queen going to d4? Isn't it dangerous to be in the center? Didn't we learn as beginners that the queen shouldn't come out too early? Well, let's see.  The queen can be attacked with ...e7-e5, but that move weakens the d6-pawn, creates a hole on d5, and doesn't help Black develop. We aren't afraid of that. Or, it can be attacked with ...Nc6. This is a bit annoying, but we can pin the knight with Bb5, or retreat to e3. So why are we taking with the queen, after all? This move contains several ideas, such as:  Protecting the e4-pawn. In some lines, making it possible to castle queenside faster. By protecting the e4-pawn, we might be able to avoid playing Nc3, which means the c-pawn is free to advance to c4, forming the Maroczy Bind − a strong pawn formation, which occupies the entire center, preventing counterplay.    Here, Black chooses between several moves. The most popular one is @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp2pppp/3p4/8/3QP3/5N2/PPP2PPP/RNB1KB1R b KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Nc6  . They also tried  4...a6  and  4...Bd7  −  both of those are aimed at preventing Bb5. However, the strongest move nowadays is  considered  4...Nf6  . Luckily, it's been played in only about 7% of the games or so, so most people still haven't caught on! }
4... a6
{ This has been played by a number of strong GMs, such as Nepo, Artemiev, Edouard, and many others. However, I believe it's not a great variation for Black because we are able to easily take all the space we want. }
5. c4
{ By playing this move, we acquire much better control of the b5 and d5-squares. That's a very helpful thing because Black often wants to grab space on the queenside with ...b7-b5 or free up the center with ...d6-d5, getting rid of our powerful e4-pawn. Furthermore, our last move helps prevent counterplay on the c-file: for example, if the black rook goes to c8, it won't ever be able to capture the c3-knight, and so on. }
5... Nc6 { In most games, Black started by attacking the queen. } 6. Qe3
{ I like the idea of placing the queen on e3. Why here?  It protects the e4-pawn. It doesn't block the d-file. We can castle and place the rook there, preparing to bother the opponent with e4-e5 or c4-c5 at some point. The c1-bishop gets blocked, unfortunately. However, this is not a problem, because we want to develop it to b2.   Black mostly played  6...g6  ,  6...Nf6  and  6...Bg4  . The two first moves typically just result in a transposition. The third one, though, results in slightly different positions. Fortunately, since this position is not tactical or concrete, the specific move orders don't tend to matter to us as much as understanding does. }
6... Bg4
{ Since h2-h3 hasn't been played yet, Black is making this move right away. Why?  Black has less space, so trading pieces is a common strategy that decreases space-related problems. By trading off the f3-knight, Black gets a better ability to control the d4-square. Black doesn't need this bishop. One of our dream scenarios in this pawn structure is ending up with a knight versus Black's light-squared bishop because that piece won't have anything useful to do. }
7. Be2
{ We keep developing. While the trade on f3 has certain merits for Black, we get a few things, too: the bishop pair and in order to trade, Black would need to waste quite a lot of time. }
7... g6 { It's logical to develop the bishop to the long diagonal, of course. }
8. O-O Bg7 9. Rd1
{ This cunning move sets up a small trap. Black would like to play ...Nf6 and castle, but doing so here would be a pretty terrible idea. }
9... Bxf3
{ Black has to surrender the bishop pair. The downside is that two moves have been spent to trade our knight, which moved only once. And, by doing so, Black helped us bring the bishop to f3. It's not that useful here, but if we were to go e4-e5 or c4-c5, opening up the center, the bishop could suddenly turn out very useful on the h1-a8 diagonal.   9...Nf6?  is a poor idea, as after  10.e5!  , we take advantage of the x-ray on the d-file and destroy Black's pawn structure. }
10. Bxf3 Nf6 11. Nc3 { For now, we keep developing. } 11... Nd7
{ Black plays this move in order to block the d-file, discouraging any x-ray problems, like the c4-c5 or e4-e5 breaks, while also opening up the g7-bishop, and preparing to install the knight on e5 or c5.   After  11...O-O  , Black has to be very careful. For example, we could continue playing as usual, or we can try playing  12.c5!?  ruining Black's pawn structure. That should better be prevented! }
12. Rb1
{ This move is rather important. We'd like to play b2-b3 and develop the bishop to b2, to the long diagonal. For that reason, we want to remove the rook off the long diagonal before weakening it with b2-b3. Or, we could consider playing b2-b4, grabbing space on the queenside. }
12... O-O 13. Be2
{ Given Black played ...Nd7, the e4-e5 and c4-c5 ideas became less likely to happen, so we move the bishop back. This is done in order to protect the c4-pawn, and potentially free up the path for our f-pawn. It could go to f3, overprotecting the e4-pawn, or to f4, grabbing space on the kingside. But, most likely, first, we will just get the c1-bishop out. }
13... Rc8
{ One of the few games that reached this position saw Black continue making natural developing moves. The rook is going to the c-file, potentially x-raying the c3-knight and hinting at some ...b7-b5 along the line. }
14. b3
{ We follow up with the intended plan of preparing Bb2. Black doesn't have any counterplay at the moment, of course. }
14... Qa5
{ Black gets the queen out, connecting the rooks. This queen placement is very standard in the Maroczy Bind type positions. It wouldn't want to go to c7, because it runs into Nd5. Going to b6 isn't very attractive for the same reason. }
15. Bb2 Qc5
{ In the game we are following, Black offered a queen trade. 1-0 Stoyanov-Antova, Sofia 2020. }
16. Qd2
{ I would like to suggest this move, which keeps the queens on the board and the d4-square under better control. Next, we can play a2-a3 and b3-b4, expanding on the queenside, and kicking the black queen out. Black doesn't have the ...b7-b5 or ...d6-d5 break, and the position is just very unpleasant and passive.   16.Qxc5  isn't a bad idea, as trading queens is often good for the party with a long-term advantage because, without the queens, there is a lot less counterplay. However, this move fails because of dynamic reasons. Black gets so much counterplay!  16...Nxc5  and now, there is a threat  of ...Bxc3 followed by ...Nxe4.  17.f3  Bd4+!  18.Kf1  e5!  Black weakens the d5-square but wins the one on d4. Now, the control of the dark squares is nearly perfect, while the light-squared bishop on e2 is sort of dead. I wouldn't like this position! }
