3... cxd4 4. Qxd4
{ This variation is 20 times@@StartBracket@@!@@EndBracket@@ less popular than the main move  4.Nxd4  . This, of course, appeals a lot to an author like me, who prefers steering off the well-researched paths, preferring to look for new ideas.  Why is the queen going to d4? Isn't it dangerous to be in the center? Didn't we learn as beginners that the queen shouldn't come out too early? Well, let's see.  The queen can be attacked with ...e7-e5, but that move weakens the d6-pawn, creates a hole on d5, and doesn't help Black develop. We aren't afraid of that. Or, it can be attacked with ...Nc6. This is a bit annoying, but we can pin the knight with Bb5, or retreat to e3. So why are we taking with the queen, after all? This move contains several ideas, such as:  Protecting the e4-pawn. In some lines, making it possible to castle queenside faster. By protecting the e4-pawn, we might be able to avoid playing Nc3, which means the c-pawn is free to advance to c4, forming the Maroczy Bind − a strong pawn formation, which occupies the entire center, preventing counterplay.    Here, Black chooses between several moves. The most popular one is @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp2pppp/3p4/8/3QP3/5N2/PPP2PPP/RNB1KB1R b KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Nc6  . They also tried  4...a6  and  4...Bd7  −  both of those are aimed at preventing Bb5. However, the strongest move nowadays is  considered  4...Nf6  . Luckily, it's been played in only about 7% of the games or so, so most people still haven't caught on! }
