5... Nc6 6. Bb5
{ We are pinning the opponent's knight, refusing to waste time moving our queen around. }
6... Bd7 { And Black unpins it, threatening to take the queen. } 7. Bxc6
{ The only logical thing would be to trade that knight off − again, we'll do anything to save some time! }
7... Bxc6
{ Let's talk a bit about this position. Black has the bishop pair and a rather solid setup. No weaknesses, we don't have threats yet. So why did we give up the bishop pair, what is our plan? Well, our development is much easier to finish.  Black needs to either spend the time playing ...g7-g6 and ...Bg7 − we can make that setup impossible to achieve, actually! − or go ...e7-e6. The latter is what most people opt for. However, playing ...e7-e6 means weakening the d6-pawn, and this is exactly what we will try to take advantage of! }
8. Bg5
{ This is an important part of our setup to remember. The bishop belongs here because it does several important things. We are somewhat threatening to take on f6 on the very next turn, giving Black an ugly pawn structure. If ...exf6, the d6-pawn, and the d5-square will be weak. If ...gxf6, it would be unsafe for Black to castle kingside. In that structure, typical of the Classical Sicilian, the black bishops are very passive and we can play Nd4, f2-f4, and then either f4-f5, killing the bishops, or e4-e5, taking advantage of the opponent's king, which is typically stuck in the center. }
8... e6
{ Black needs to make this move in order to prepare ...Be7 and kingside castling. Black also needs to prevent Bxf6 in a situation where he cannot take with a piece.   8...g6?  is obviously wrong, as after  9.Bxf6+-  ,  we ruin Black's pawn structure, creating a weak pawn on d6 and a weak square on d5. }
9. O-O-O { We castle, getting ready to open things up with e4-e5. } 9... Be7
{ This is another major crossroads. More than 6000 games have been played in this position. White tried all sorts of moves: the tension-keeping  10.Rhe1  and  10.Kb1  , the aggressive  10.h4  , and the most forcing  10.e5  . All of these moves are very logical and interesting. And you are very welcome to explore them on your own! But, we need to pick one. :@@EndBracket@@ }
10. Rhe1
{ Just as most players have, we are keeping the tension, making the ideas of e4-e5 more dangerous. In this position, most people, 80% or so, chose to castle.   Black can also try other moves, such as  10...Qa5  or  10...Qc7  , but I don't believe they are particularly challenging, or that they change the character of the position that much. For this reason, and since the whole 5.Nc3 variation is our alternative option, I will only focus on the main line. }
10... O-O 11. e5
{ This principled move is immediately opening up the center. Now, the problems related to Black's c6-bishop's active position are not nearly as relevant as in the 10.e5 variation because there are still queens on the board, and the king is already on g8, which creates a few extra tactical possibilities. }
11... dxe5
{ 99% of the strongest players that represented Black in this position made this choice, opening up the d-file and getting ready for a queen trade. }
12. Nxe5 Qxd4 13. Rxd4 Rac8
{ Crucially, this natural move, which also seems to be solving the problem with the pawn structure, as Black is getting ready to take on c6 with the rook, is not as good as the move with the other rook. }
14. Nxc6 Rxc6 15. Ne4 e5
{ Unlike in the other line after @@StartFEN@@r4rk1/pp2bppp/2b1pn2/4N1B1/3R4/2N5/PPP2PPP/2K1R3 b - - 0 13@@EndFEN@@  13...Rfc8  instead of  13...Rac8  , this move doesn't work, since the f8-rook would end up hanging at the end. @@StartFEN@@5rk1/pp2bppp/2r1pn2/6B1/3RN3/8/PPP2PPP/2K1R3 b - - 1 15@@EndFEN@@  15...Rfc8  16.Re2⩲  transposes to the 13...Rfc8 line, which is not the best one for Black! }
16. Bxf6
{ Now, taking on f6 with the pawn or bishop is bad, as we play Rd7, invading on the 7th rank, with a nearly decisive positional advantage. }
16... exd4 17. Bxe7
{ We have two pieces for a rook and a nearly winning position. Unlike in the other line, Black cannot go ...Re6 followed by ...f7-f5, since the f8-rook is hanging. }
17... Re8 18. Ng3
{ Next, we will go Kd2 to protect the rook and move the bishop away. A winning endgame it is! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "22) Sicilian 2...d6"]
[Black "Sicilian 4.Qxd4 Nf6 − Alternative 5.Nc3 #8"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5
{ This move initiates what we know as the Sicilian Defense, the queen of the @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  Black openings. Alongside  1.e4  e5  , it's one of the two most sound ways of meeting 1.e4  from the theoretical standpoint. Black is fighting for the center, the d4-square, without creating a symmetrical position. This opening is extremely popular with players who want sharp, creative and fighting chess, and those who don't want to settle for symmetry, less space, or any other concessions. }
2. Nf3
{ In this Lifetime Repertoire, I have decided to go for the most ambitious way of playing versus the Sicilian Defense − the so-called Open Sicilian. Why would I do that? Isn't this a positional repertoire, and isn't the Open Sicilian known to be sharp and principled? Well, here is the deal.  It's a Lifetime Repertoire. I want this course to carry a theoretical punch, which most sidelines cannot offer. I was considering the Alapin, 2.c3, as well, but decided to not go down that route, because the isolated pawn positions, which often arise there, aren't to everyone's taste.  Interestingly enough, in many sharp-looking positions, there is a path to simplifications, which means that with sufficient theoretical knowledge, we are playing risk-free. It's not possible to get an advantage in every single theoretical variation of the Sicilian as White, and maybe not even in most.  
What we are doing instead is something different. We are striving to test our opponent's knowledge of typical ideas and forcing lines, and if Black is prepared brilliantly, we accept the fact Black should be able to defend. However, we want to play risk-free, looking to get the better endgames or positions with pleasant positional pressure in the middlegame! }
2... d6
{ This is Black's most common move by far. What is the idea? By moving the pawn to d6, Black takes the e5-square under control. As a result, the knight can be developed to f6 on the next turn without running into the annoying e4-e5. Also, of course, Black makes it possible for the light-squared bishop to come out in the future, as well as the b8-knight, which at times goes to d7.   This move is used by the players who like the Najdorf Variation − the most complex and sound Sicilian line, objectively; the Dragon Variation − a sharp, uncompromising opening; and, sometimes, the Classical Sicilian, which can be played via  2...d6  or  2...Nc6  . If  2...d6  is chosen, it's because they want to avoid the Rossolimo. }
3. d4
{ We immediately open up the center. With this move, we are getting rid of Black's c5-pawn, which was controlling the central d4-square. We are also activating one of our pieces, which will take on d4. And, we are making it possible for the dark-squared bishop to come out in the future. Now, most Black players take the pawn, but in a very few games, the cheeky  3...Nf6  move order has been tried. }
3... cxd4 4. Qxd4
{ This variation is 20 times@@StartBracket@@!@@EndBracket@@ less popular than the main move  4.Nxd4  . This, of course, appeals a lot to an author like me, who prefers steering off the well-researched paths, preferring to look for new ideas.  Why is the queen going to d4? Isn't it dangerous to be in the center? Didn't we learn as beginners that the queen shouldn't come out too early? Well, let's see.  The queen can be attacked with ...e7-e5, but that move weakens the d6-pawn, creates a hole on d5, and doesn't help Black develop. We aren't afraid of that. Or, it can be attacked with ...Nc6. This is a bit annoying, but we can pin the knight with Bb5, or retreat to e3. So why are we taking with the queen, after all? This move contains several ideas, such as:  Protecting the e4-pawn. In some lines, making it possible to castle queenside faster. By protecting the e4-pawn, we might be able to avoid playing Nc3, which means the c-pawn is free to advance to c4, forming the Maroczy Bind − a strong pawn formation, which occupies the entire center, preventing counterplay.    Here, Black chooses between several moves. The most popular one is @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp2pppp/3p4/8/3QP3/5N2/PPP2PPP/RNB1KB1R b KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Nc6  . They also tried  4...a6  and  4...Bd7  −  both of those are aimed at preventing Bb5. However, the strongest move nowadays is  considered  4...Nf6  . Luckily, it's been played in only about 7% of the games or so, so most people still haven't caught on! }
4... Nf6 5. Nc3
{ I will give this option as an alternative, and we will go into quite a bit of detail here. That is for a few reasons:  Many of you might like variety.  Many of you might like the idea of playing the somewhat more forcing chess, where we use moves that open up the game in order to simplify and strive for a somewhat better endgame, rather than a fight on a board full of pieces, which is the case in those Be2, Qe3 lines, where we are going for the Maroczy Bind.  Objectively, as I am pointing out, Black is able to reach a playable balanced position in those lines. In this one, however, while he should be able to equalize, the type of equality will be different: Black would often make the only moves to get a drawn or equal endgame, rather than a playable rich middlegame.   This makes 5.Nc3 a good choice for those situations where you want to check your @@StartBracket@@possibly higher-rated@@EndBracket@@ opponent's knowledge without taking any risks. Now, e4-e5! is quite an annoying threat, and Black should address that. }
5... Nc6 6. Bb5
{ We are pinning the opponent's knight, refusing to waste time moving our queen around. }
6... Bd7 { And Black unpins it, threatening to take the queen. } 7. Bxc6
{ The only logical thing would be to trade that knight off − again, we'll do anything to save some time! }
7... Bxc6
{ Let's talk a bit about this position. Black has the bishop pair and a rather solid setup. No weaknesses, we don't have threats yet. So why did we give up the bishop pair, what is our plan? Well, our development is much easier to finish.  Black needs to either spend the time playing ...g7-g6 and ...Bg7 − we can make that setup impossible to achieve, actually! − or go ...e7-e6. The latter is what most people opt for. However, playing ...e7-e6 means weakening the d6-pawn, and this is exactly what we will try to take advantage of! }
8. Bg5
{ This is an important part of our setup to remember. The bishop belongs here because it does several important things. We are somewhat threatening to take on f6 on the very next turn, giving Black an ugly pawn structure. If ...exf6, the d6-pawn, and the d5-square will be weak. If ...gxf6, it would be unsafe for Black to castle kingside. In that structure, typical of the Classical Sicilian, the black bishops are very passive and we can play Nd4, f2-f4, and then either f4-f5, killing the bishops, or e4-e5, taking advantage of the opponent's king, which is typically stuck in the center. }
8... e6
{ Black needs to make this move in order to prepare ...Be7 and kingside castling. Black also needs to prevent Bxf6 in a situation where he cannot take with a piece.   8...g6?  is obviously wrong, as after  9.Bxf6+-  ,  we ruin Black's pawn structure, creating a weak pawn on d6 and a weak square on d5. }
9. O-O-O { We castle, getting ready to open things up with e4-e5. } 9... Be7
{ This is another major crossroads. More than 6000 games have been played in this position. White tried all sorts of moves: the tension-keeping  10.Rhe1  and  10.Kb1  , the aggressive  10.h4  , and the most forcing  10.e5  . All of these moves are very logical and interesting. And you are very welcome to explore them on your own! But, we need to pick one. :@@EndBracket@@ }
10. Rhe1
{ Just as most players have, we are keeping the tension, making the ideas of e4-e5 more dangerous. In this position, most people, 80% or so, chose to castle.   Black can also try other moves, such as  10...Qa5  or  10...Qc7  , but I don't believe they are particularly challenging, or that they change the character of the position that much. For this reason, and since the whole 5.Nc3 variation is our alternative option, I will only focus on the main line. }
10... O-O 11. e5
{ This principled move is immediately opening up the center. Now, the problems related to Black's c6-bishop's active position are not nearly as relevant as in the 10.e5 variation because there are still queens on the board, and the king is already on g8, which creates a few extra tactical possibilities. }
11... dxe5
{ 99% of the strongest players that represented Black in this position made this choice, opening up the d-file and getting ready for a queen trade. }
12. Nxe5 Qxd4 13. Rxd4 Rfc8
{ Black needs to make sure to avoid the upcoming structural damage after Nxc6 and must go here EXACTLY with the f8-rook because otherwise, it could end up hanging on f8 in some lines − see the 13...Rac8?! variation to understand better what I am referring to. }
14. Nxc6 Rxc6 15. Ne4
{ We are hoping to capture the knight on f6 to double the pawns and get a more pleasant endgame. Also, it would be beneficial for us to make the f6-knight disappear because in that case, our rook will be able to invade on d7 in the future. }
15... Rac8
{ In most games, Black made this natural move. After all, isn't it logical to threaten the c2-pawn, win a tempo, and get the last piece in the game? However, this move isn't great. }
16. Re2
{ Now, not only the c2-pawn but also the f2-pawn is protected. As you can see in the @@StartFEN@@r5k1/pp2bppp/2r1pn2/6B1/3RN3/8/PPP2PPP/2K1R3 b - - 1 15@@EndFEN@@  15...e5  main line,  that is an important detail since Black no longer has this ...Nxe4 and ...Nxf2 trick. So, we are about to spoil the pawn structure by taking on f6 on the next turn, and there isn't much Black can do about that. }
16... Rc4
{ In a few high-level games, Black managed to defend with this move. Black is forcing even more trades, going straight for a somewhat inferior rook endgame. }
17. Nxf6+ Bxf6
{ This move is not great, as it doesn't win a tempo against our bishop. Now, we get just a wonderful rook endgame. }
18. Bxf6 gxf6 19. Red2
{ White is much better in this position. Why so?  We have an extra pawn on the queenside. This is a very dangerous pawn structure in the endgame since it's much easier to create a passed pawn on the queenside, as the Black king would have a hard time stopping it.  We own the d-file. This means the black king is cut off from the queenside, which reinforces the previous point, and that we are about to trade a pair of rooks and invade on the 7th rank.  Our king is much better suited for the upcoming endgame activity. Once we trade the rooks, we can go b2-b3, c2-c4, Kc2-c3, and so on, using the monarch to help support the pawn advance.  Black's pawn structure on the kingside isn't great. You can immediately recall the famous game of Rubinstein, where he brought the king to h3 and a recent example Salem-Kramnik.  
If you don't know what I am referring to, make sure to look these examples up − they are fascinating! It likely won't matter in this position, as the structure isn't symmetrical, but the h-pawn can easily become a target for our rook as well if the black king walks too far away from it, say to e7. White went on to win a very instructive game. 1-0 Boiarintsev-Nukin, Aksu Pavlodar 2019. }
*

