2. Nf3
{ In this Lifetime Repertoire, I have decided to go for the most ambitious way of playing versus the Sicilian Defense − the so-called Open Sicilian. Why would I do that? Isn't this a positional repertoire, and isn't the Open Sicilian known to be sharp and principled? Well, here is the deal.  It's a Lifetime Repertoire. I want this course to carry a theoretical punch, which most sidelines cannot offer. I was considering the Alapin, 2.c3, as well, but decided to not go down that route, because the isolated pawn positions, which often arise there, aren't to everyone's taste.  Interestingly enough, in many sharp-looking positions, there is a path to simplifications, which means that with sufficient theoretical knowledge, we are playing risk-free. It's not possible to get an advantage in every single theoretical variation of the Sicilian as White, and maybe not even in most.  
What we are doing instead is something different. We are striving to test our opponent's knowledge of typical ideas and forcing lines, and if Black is prepared brilliantly, we accept the fact Black should be able to defend. However, we want to play risk-free, looking to get the better endgames or positions with pleasant positional pressure in the middlegame! }
2... Nc6 3. Bb5
{ Unlike after every other move, like @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 2@@EndFEN@@  2...d6  or  2...g6  , this time, we would not want to open up the center. I know it might sound confusing since I just said 'We are going for the Open Sicilian'. Well, we are, but not this time. :@@EndBracket@@  The move @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp1ppppp/2n5/2p5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 2 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Bb5  initiates something known as the Rossolimo Variation, which used to be an interesting sideline. There is a story that in the 80s, Kasparov told one of the students of the Botvinnik school 'Kid, you cannot just give up your bishop on c6, this is not Ruy Lopez'. But, of course, a few years later, he would play  3.Bb5  himself.  Over the course of the years, especially as people realized that the Sveshnikov Variation was so good, the desire for an ambitious Anti-Open Sicilian kept growing, and as a result, the move  3.Bb5  has become one of the two main lines, alongside  3.d4  . We are looking to capture on c6 and ruin Black's pawn structure. However, we are not forced to, and in some setups, we would prefer to avoid the trade!  The two main moves for Black are  3...e6  and  3...g6  , but in this chapter, we will see what happens if Black tries other @@StartBracket@@mostly bad@@EndBracket@@ ones, such as  3...a6  ,  3...Qb6  ,  3...Qc7  ,  3...g5?  , and so on. The reputable sidelines are  3...d6  ,  3...Nf6  , and  3...e5!?  , and we'll cover those as well, of course, in another chapter. }
3... Na5
{ In quite a few games, Black tried this odd move, aimed at preventing White from taking on c6 and doubling the pawns. Of course, Black is wasting time. However, Black is hoping to be able to play ...a7-a6, kicking the bishop out, and then ...Nc6, returning back.  Black is claiming that wasting two tempi with ...Nc6-a5-c6 isn't that bad, as White will also waste a tempo with Bb5-e2. But, we are clearly gaining a move, at least! And, likely one more, as Black needs to go ...a7-a6, which is sort of useful, but not necessarily the most useful thing Black can do so early in the game. }
4. O-O { We, of course, just continue developing. } 4... a6 5. Be2 e6
{ Black could also start with ...d7-d6 or some other move. We'll stick to the same setup no matter what. }
6. c4
{ I like the idea of making this move, looking to build the standard Maroczy Bind-type setup. Next, of course, we'll play Nc3 and d2-d4, obtaining the standard spatial advantage. }
6... Qc7
{ All other moves are harmless, but this one requires us to be a bit careful because Black is preparing to x-ray our c-pawn. }
7. d4 { We follow up as planned. } 7... cxd4 8. Qxd4
{ This was the key idea that I wanted to show to you. Taking with the knight instead would have lost the c4-pawn. While we would have had compensation, there is no need to make things sharper than necessary. }
8... Nc6 9. Qe3
{ The queen is perfectly safe here. Next, we'll play Nc3, b2-b3, and Bb2. The bishop would go to b2 no matter what, but actually, we might have an even better idea than b2-b3! }
9... Nf6 10. Nc3 Be7 { Both parties continue developing. } 11. a3
{ With this move, we are preparing to grab more space on the queenside with b2-b4. Black cannot  (or at least, should not!)  stop that plan with ...a6-a5, because that would weaken the b5-square, giving our knights a wonderful outpost.   11.e5?  is not possible at this point, or likely any other, due to  11...Ng4∓  and we lose the e5-pawn. }
11... O-O 12. b4
{ Of course, due to the typical spatial advantage, we are clearly better. We are discussing these positions in detail in the @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq c6 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.Nf3  e6  and @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq c6 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.Nf3  d6  chapters, but in this case, we are just a tempo or two up.  Next, we go Bb2, Rfd1, Rac1, start threatening with the typical Nd5 tactic, and so on. Ideas like h2-h3, Nd4, and f2-f4 can also be considered! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "23) Rossolimo − Bad Sidelines"]
[Black "Rossolimo Bad Sidelines 3.Bb5 Qc7 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5
{ This move initiates what we know as the Sicilian Defense, the queen of the @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  Black openings. Alongside  1.e4  e5  , it's one of the two most sound ways of meeting 1.e4  from the theoretical standpoint. Black is fighting for the center, the d4-square, without creating a symmetrical position. This opening is extremely popular with players who want sharp, creative and fighting chess, and those who don't want to settle for symmetry, less space, or any other concessions. }
2. Nf3
{ In this Lifetime Repertoire, I have decided to go for the most ambitious way of playing versus the Sicilian Defense − the so-called Open Sicilian. Why would I do that? Isn't this a positional repertoire, and isn't the Open Sicilian known to be sharp and principled? Well, here is the deal.  It's a Lifetime Repertoire. I want this course to carry a theoretical punch, which most sidelines cannot offer. I was considering the Alapin, 2.c3, as well, but decided to not go down that route, because the isolated pawn positions, which often arise there, aren't to everyone's taste.  Interestingly enough, in many sharp-looking positions, there is a path to simplifications, which means that with sufficient theoretical knowledge, we are playing risk-free. It's not possible to get an advantage in every single theoretical variation of the Sicilian as White, and maybe not even in most.  
What we are doing instead is something different. We are striving to test our opponent's knowledge of typical ideas and forcing lines, and if Black is prepared brilliantly, we accept the fact Black should be able to defend. However, we want to play risk-free, looking to get the better endgames or positions with pleasant positional pressure in the middlegame! }
2... Nc6 3. Bb5
{ Unlike after every other move, like @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 2@@EndFEN@@  2...d6  or  2...g6  , this time, we would not want to open up the center. I know it might sound confusing since I just said 'We are going for the Open Sicilian'. Well, we are, but not this time. :@@EndBracket@@  The move @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp1ppppp/2n5/2p5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 2 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Bb5  initiates something known as the Rossolimo Variation, which used to be an interesting sideline. There is a story that in the 80s, Kasparov told one of the students of the Botvinnik school 'Kid, you cannot just give up your bishop on c6, this is not Ruy Lopez'. But, of course, a few years later, he would play  3.Bb5  himself.  Over the course of the years, especially as people realized that the Sveshnikov Variation was so good, the desire for an ambitious Anti-Open Sicilian kept growing, and as a result, the move  3.Bb5  has become one of the two main lines, alongside  3.d4  . We are looking to capture on c6 and ruin Black's pawn structure. However, we are not forced to, and in some setups, we would prefer to avoid the trade!  The two main moves for Black are  3...e6  and  3...g6  , but in this chapter, we will see what happens if Black tries other @@StartBracket@@mostly bad@@EndBracket@@ ones, such as  3...a6  ,  3...Qb6  ,  3...Qc7  ,  3...g5?  , and so on. The reputable sidelines are  3...d6  ,  3...Nf6  , and  3...e5!?  , and we'll cover those as well, of course, in another chapter. }
3... Qc7
{ This move has been also tried by numerous players, alongside its superior sibling  3...Qb6  . Black is hoping to avoid the doubled pawns.  Next, Black would like to play ...a7-a6 and kick out the bishop. If we were to retreat, Black's setup doesn't look that silly.  Instead, if we take on c6, Black is hoping to capture with the queen, keeping the pawn structure flexible and good. However, there is a clear downside to this thought process. Namely, Black is wasting a lot of time! Just count − going ...Qc7, then ...a7-a6, and then ...Qc6 costs Black three tempi. And that is within the first 5-6 moves! }
4. O-O { Of course, we just continue developing our pieces. } 4... a6
{ Now, it's the time for us to decide what to do with the bishop. } 5. Bxc6
{ We are happy to give up the bishop pair in return for a tremendous lead in development. }
5... Qxc6 6. Re1
{ With this move, we are not only defending the e4-pawn @@StartBracket@@which, frankly, could have been sacrificed@@EndBracket@@, but we are also developing the rook on the e-file. As we are about to discover, that would prove very useful in no time! }
6... d6
{ Black is preventing e4-e5, getting ready to play ...Nf6. Of course, Black is also getting ready to play ...e7-e5, locking up the center. }
7. d4
{ However, we are the first ones to strike in the center. We are considerably ahead in development, and Black is nowhere close to castling, so we need to open up the position as much as possible! }
7... cxd4 8. Nxd4
{ The queen needs to leave, which means Black is wasting even more time. } 8...
Qc7
{ In every but one game that reached this position, Black chose to retreat here. Black wants to avoid blocking the bishop, which would be the case after ...Qd7. And, of course, Black is hoping to keep it closer to the king, not somewhere on c4, where it would be far away. }
9. Nc3 { Our job is easy, we just keep developing. } 9... e6
{ This seems to be Black's only decent move. Black is taking the d5-square under control, getting ready to play ...Nf6 and meet Bg5 with ...Be7, avoiding damage to the pawn structure. In this position, I am sure we could make a lot of great moves, but I would like to suggest a wonderful idea.   9...Nf6?  only makes things worse, as after  10.Bg5±  , we are about  to take on f6 and spoil Black's structure, as there is no time for ...e7-e6 and ...Be7 to stop that. }
10. Bf4
{ Yes, exactly here! We are voluntarily@@StartBracket@@!@@EndBracket@@ walking our bishop into a pawn fork that seems to be winning a piece. }
10... Nf6 11. e5
{ This results in immediate disaster for Black because of development lag, which means Black is not able to handle a situation where the position opens up. }
11... dxe5 12. Bxe5
{ Next, we plan on capturing on f6, and then harassing Black's kingside with moves like Ne4 and Qf3, which create threats, while also winning time. }
12... Qd8 13. Bxf6 Qxf6 14. Nd5
{ We are threatening a fork on c7, besides the obvious attack on the queen. }
14... Qd8 15. Qh5
{ Make sure to remember this move, it will serve you very well in these open positions, where we are ahead in development. The point is that we are pinning the f7-pawn, creating a threat of taking on e6! Of course, this move also protects the knight on d5. There is nothing Black can do to stop us from capturing on e6 on the next turn, except for ...g6, which loses even faster. }
15... g6 16. Qe5
{ With a double threat of taking the rook on h8 and forking Black on c7. Oh, and, of course, there is a very annoying Nf6+, which has become available, but I think we don't need that one − winning one of the rooks is more than good enough. :@@EndBracket@@ }
*

