{ Yes, exactly here! We are voluntarily@@StartBracket@@!@@EndBracket@@ walking our bishop into a pawn fork that seems to be winning a piece. }
10... e5 { Black needs to bite the bullet and accept the piece sacrifice. } 11.
Nd5
{ First, we take advantage of the new outpost on d5, immediately installing the knight on a wonderful position, while also winning a tempo. }
11... Qd8 12. Nf5
{ If Black doesn't take the bishop, then will just have a strategically lost position with a ton of weak squares and extremely poor development. For example, right now we have a huge threat of Be3 and Bb6, winning even more time and following up with a fork Nc7+. }
12... exf4 13. Qd4
{ More threats are piling up! We are about to go Nb6, attacking the rook. It doesn't seem to be able to retreat to b8, and that is for a few reasons.  If we ever play e4-e5 @@StartBracket@@and we will most likely do so immediately!@@EndBracket@@, then after ...dxe5 Qxe5+, that rook would end up hanging. In many positions, there is no time to retreat, as Black needs to be very afraid of Qa4+ since the b-pawn is now blocked. }
13... Nf6
{ This is an instructive variation to see. However, more stubborn is  13...Ne7  14.Nxg7+  Bxg7  15.Qxg7  Kd7  16.Qxf7  Qf8  17.Qxf8  Rxf8  18.Nb6+  , when Black can try to set up a defense in the endgame since the knight on  a8  will be lost. Still, it is not a picnic and White can play for a win. }
14. Nb6 Rb8
{ Black should have given up the rook, but that won't be principled, would it? }
15. e5
{ We seem to be sacrificing the f5-knight as well, but that's an optical illusion. }
15... Bxf5 16. exf6+
{ Now, the e-file opens up, which proves too much for the undeveloped opponent to deal with. }
16... Be6 17. Qa4+ { With checkmate! } *

