4... Qxc6 5. O-O
{ I am happy to sacrifice the e4-pawn! We are already ahead in development, and taking the pawn would only make Black fall even further behind. }
5... d6 { This is a wiser move. } 6. d4 cxd4 7. Nxd4 Qc7 8. Nc3
{ We get a clear initiative, as we are considerably ahead in development. There are several typical attacking ideas we can try next, such as:  Meeting ...Nf6 with Bg5 to take on f6 and double Black's pawns, forcing a bad structure. Playing Re1 and meeting ...e7-e6 with Nd5! or Nf5!, offering a piece sacrifice to open up the e-file. Sometimes, meeting ...e7-e6 with Ndb5 and Bf4, attacking the d6-pawn, looking to provoke the move ...e6-e5, which would make the d6-pawn backward and the d5-square an outpost for our pieces. If Black goes ...a7-a6 here, it's a direct transposition into the lines covered after 3...Qc7. }
8... Nf6 9. Bg5
{ We are threatening to capture on f6, giving Black a very rigid pawn structure, where it won't be obvious what to do with the king. Additionally, we could always consider opening the center with f2-f4, Qf3, Re1 @@StartBracket@@maybe even the a-rook to keep the other one on the f-file!@@EndBracket@@ and e4-e5. All in all, Black just fell too far behind in development and is barely surviving. }
