2... Nc6 3. Bb5
{ Unlike after every other move, like @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 2@@EndFEN@@  2...d6  or  2...g6  , this time, we would not want to open up the center. I know it might sound confusing since I just said 'We are going for the Open Sicilian'. Well, we are, but not this time. :@@EndBracket@@  The move @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp1ppppp/2n5/2p5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 2 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Bb5  initiates something known as the Rossolimo Variation, which used to be an interesting sideline. There is a story that in the 80s, Kasparov told one of the students of the Botvinnik school 'Kid, you cannot just give up your bishop on c6, this is not Ruy Lopez'. But, of course, a few years later, he would play  3.Bb5  himself.  Over the course of the years, especially as people realized that the Sveshnikov Variation was so good, the desire for an ambitious Anti-Open Sicilian kept growing, and as a result, the move  3.Bb5  has become one of the two main lines, alongside  3.d4  . We are looking to capture on c6 and ruin Black's pawn structure. However, we are not forced to, and in some setups, we would prefer to avoid the trade!  The two main moves for Black are  3...e6  and  3...g6  , but in this chapter, we will see what happens if Black tries other @@StartBracket@@mostly bad@@EndBracket@@ ones, such as  3...a6  ,  3...Qb6  ,  3...Qc7  ,  3...g5?  , and so on. The reputable sidelines are  3...d6  ,  3...Nf6  , and  3...e5!?  , and we'll cover those as well, of course, in another chapter. }
3... g5
{ I cannot believe I am mentioning such a dubious move, which is just giving up a pawn, in an opening course. Black's idea is to sacrifice a pawn to open up the g-file. Black also claims that if we take, moves like ...Nd4 might make more sense.  This move has been tried by GM Ivanisevic once, and two dozen@@StartBracket@@!@@EndBracket@@ times by an FM from Kazakhstan. Of course, in blitz games. It sounds funny, but I don't like getting confused or losing by accident to silly sidelines, so I thought I'd cover this. }
4. Bxc6
{ In the spirit of the Rossolimo, we eliminate the knight, doubling the pawns. A big perk in this specific variation, which we get by taking, is that we don't ever have to deal with ...Nd4. }
4... dxc6
{ Of course, Black should only consider capturing with this pawn, as doing that opens up the light-squared bishop. When you sacrifice material, you at least want to develop fast! }
5. Nxg5 { Time to take the daring pawn. } 5... Nf6
{ Now, the e4-pawn is under attack. Sure enough, for now, it's not hanging, but Black wants to go ...h7-h6, kick the knight out, and win the pawn. }
6. d3 { So, we just protect it. } 6... Rg8
{ And now, Black gets the rook on the semi-open file. Of course, it doesn't mean anything, there are no threats. }
7. O-O
{ I would just castle, as Black has no threats on the g-file. Next, we'd love to play Nc3, f2-f4, and maybe walk the king away with Kh1, just in case. On another note, the move Kh1 is often useful in the Rossolimo, especially in combination with Be3. Why so? Because when we go Be3, Black often responds with ...Ng4, harassing the bishop, and it's nice to be able to retreat to g1! }
7... h6 { Black kicks out the knight to open the g-file for the rook. } 8. Nf3
Bh3
{ Black seems to have created one threat in a row, but that doesn't do anything. }
9. Ne1
{ We are ready to play Kh1 on the next turn, unpinning the g2-pawn and attacking the bishop. }
9... Qc7 10. Kh1
{ White failed to beat his IM-level opponent, who decided to try a silly gambit, but at this point, he is just a pawn up for nothing. Next, we'll go f2-f4, Nc3, Be3, and so on, getting the rest of the pieces out. Black also lost the right to castle kingside.  Castling queenside, on the other hand, doesn't seem safe. That pawn on c5 is a target, and if Black ever defends it with ...b7-b6, it'd allow us to consider several ways of attacking the queenside, such as a2-a4-a5, or a2-a3 followed by b2-b4. The black king won't feel safe there. It wasn't too hard to refute this gambit, as you can see! ½-½ Vatter-Vidonyak, Germany 2010. }
