{ The main idea of the Rossolimo is to capture on c6 and double Black's pawns. However, it seems Black doesn't trust the soundness of our plan, saying to us: take the knight! Give me the bishop pair! Black is happy to insist even at a cost of a tempo. }
4. Bxc6
{ No problem, we will happily oblige! Just like in the main lines with, say, @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp1ppppp/2n5/2p5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 2 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Bb5  g6  4.Bxc6  , Black can choose between two logical-looking ways to take back. }
4... dxc6 { Black is opening up the light-squared bishop. } 5. d3
{ We are getting ready to develop. In this position, a very attractive positional accomplishment would be to play a2-a4-a5, creating an outpost on b6 and separating the c5-pawn from the rest of the pack, and then Nb1-d2-c4, looking to come to b6. The bishop would sit very comfortably on e3, always keeping an eye on that weak c5-pawn. }
5... Qc7
{ Black is preparing to go ...e7-e5, fighting for space in the center.  5...Bg4  is going to look very similar to  5...Qc7  , the main line. }
6. e5
{ We won't let that happen! Now, Black can no longer develop the knight to f6. If Black ever goes ...e7-e6, the d6-square becomes weak, of course, and we'd love to take advantage of that with Nbd2-e4-d6 at some point. That mini-plan would be particularly effective if the dark-squared bishops get traded, as Black would lack the ability to control the d6-square. }
6... Bg4
{ Before playing ...e7-e6, Black needs to develop the bishop to make sure it doesn't get locked inside the pawn chain. }
7. Bf4
{ Black was threatening to take our knight and then win the e5-pawn, so we make this somewhat unusual-looking bishop move, protecting the pawn. Remember, Black really wishes to develop the knight to f6. But that cannot be done, so Black needs to get the kingside pieces out in a very awkward manner. }
7... e6
{ Black is getting ready to play ...Ne7-g6, or ...Ne7-d5, and then ...Be7. However, the d6-square becomes really weak as a result. }
8. h3
{ This move is aimed not only at hoping to deprive the opponent of the bishop pair but also at making room on h2 for our bishop, which, as we are about to see, will prove pretty useful. }
8... Bh5
{ Of course, trading on f3 would have been lame. If Black did that, Black would end up with a clearly inferior position, with less space, a hole on d6, and no development, for nothing in return. }
9. Nbd2 { The knight comes out, hoping to hop to e4 and d6 at some point. }
9... Ne7 10. O-O Nd5
{ This isn't a great square for the knight. How come, you would ask? Aren't central squares a good place to park the knight? Well, not if it gets kicked out! }
11. Bh2 Be7 12. Ne4 O-O 13. c4
{ And the knight is being pushed away to b6, where it would be very restricted, doing absolutely nothing for ages. }
