2... Nc6 3. Bb5
{ Unlike after every other move, like @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 2@@EndFEN@@  2...d6  or  2...g6  , this time, we would not want to open up the center. I know it might sound confusing since I just said 'We are going for the Open Sicilian'. Well, we are, but not this time. :@@EndBracket@@  The move @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp1ppppp/2n5/2p5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 2 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Bb5  initiates something known as the Rossolimo Variation, which used to be an interesting sideline. There is a story that in the 80s, Kasparov told one of the students of the Botvinnik school 'Kid, you cannot just give up your bishop on c6, this is not Ruy Lopez'. But, of course, a few years later, he would play  3.Bb5  himself.  Over the course of the years, especially as people realized that the Sveshnikov Variation was so good, the desire for an ambitious Anti-Open Sicilian kept growing, and as a result, the move  3.Bb5  has become one of the two main lines, alongside  3.d4  . We are looking to capture on c6 and ruin Black's pawn structure. However, we are not forced to, and in some setups, we would prefer to avoid the trade!  The two main moves for Black are  3...e6  and  3...g6  , but in this chapter, we will see what happens if Black tries other @@StartBracket@@mostly bad@@EndBracket@@ ones, such as  3...a6  ,  3...Qb6  ,  3...Qc7  ,  3...g5?  , and so on. The reputable sidelines are  3...d6  ,  3...Nf6  , and  3...e5!?  , and we'll cover those as well, of course, in another chapter. }
