{ No problem, we will happily oblige! Just like in the main lines with, say, @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp1ppppp/2n5/2p5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 2 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Bb5  g6  4.Bxc6  , Black can choose between two logical-looking ways to take back. }
4... bxc6
{ This move is somewhat more popular. Black takes towards the center, getting a pretty flexible pawn mass. Black can either play ...d7-d6, hoping to go ...e7-e5 next, or push ...d7-d5. }
5. O-O { We just continue development. } 5... d6
{ Black hopes to go ...e7-e5, keeping the center closed, the c5-pawn protected by the one on d6, and taking up a lot of space. We need to prevent that! }
6. e5
{ We are preventing the opponent from going ...e7-e5. Now, Black faces a few challenges.  If Black ever goes ...dxe5 or ...d7-d6, allowing for exd6, the doubled isolated c-pawns will become very weak. If Black ever goes ...d6-d5, the pawn on c5 becomes much weaker. If Black doesn't do one of those things, Black can hardly develop since our e5-pawn is preventing the move ...Nf6. We'll just go Re1, and exd6 at some point, opening up the e-file.   6.Re1  e5  7.c3!  is also a very good path. Black has spent every single@@StartBracket@@!@@EndBracket@@ move on pawn play, so opening up the center  with d2-d4 is likely to yield great results. When you are ahead in development, open up the position! }
6... d5 7. h3
{ Black is prevented from going ...Bg4. Now, our focus switches to that weak c5-pawn, which can no longer be defended by Black's d-pawn, as the latter advanced too far. :@@EndBracket@@ }
7... e6 8. Nc3 Ne7 9. Na4
{ The c5-pawn is extremely vulnerable. Black could go ...c5-c4 at some point, but that allows for b2-b3. Sure enough, after the potential ...cxb3 axb3, Black gets rid of the doubled pawn but opens the a-file for our rook. Then, we can play Ba3, looking to trade off the bishops, get rid of Black's bishop pair, and take advantage of the weak c5-square. It's great for us to trade the dark-squared bishops since Black's other bishop is very passive and restricted. }
9... Ng6 10. b3
{ Now, the ...c5-c4 ideas are definitely discouraged. Next, we'll play Ba3, attacking the c5-pawn, then d2-d3 and c2-c4, preventing ...c5-c4 forever. The c5-pawn is weak, the c8-bishop is dead, and Black has no counterplay. Not a good outcome! }
