[Black "Rossolimo Decent Sidelines 3.Bb5 e5 #9"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5
{ This move initiates what we know as the Sicilian Defense, the queen of the @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  Black openings. Alongside  1.e4  e5  , it's one of the two most sound ways of meeting 1.e4  from the theoretical standpoint. Black is fighting for the center, the d4-square, without creating a symmetrical position. This opening is extremely popular with players who want sharp, creative and fighting chess, and those who don't want to settle for symmetry, less space, or any other concessions. }
2. Nf3
{ In this Lifetime Repertoire, I have decided to go for the most ambitious way of playing versus the Sicilian Defense − the so-called Open Sicilian. Why would I do that? Isn't this a positional repertoire, and isn't the Open Sicilian known to be sharp and principled? Well, here is the deal.  It's a Lifetime Repertoire. I want this course to carry a theoretical punch, which most sidelines cannot offer. I was considering the Alapin, 2.c3, as well, but decided to not go down that route, because the isolated pawn positions, which often arise there, aren't to everyone's taste.  Interestingly enough, in many sharp-looking positions, there is a path to simplifications, which means that with sufficient theoretical knowledge, we are playing risk-free. It's not possible to get an advantage in every single theoretical variation of the Sicilian as White, and maybe not even in most.  
What we are doing instead is something different. We are striving to test our opponent's knowledge of typical ideas and forcing lines, and if Black is prepared brilliantly, we accept the fact Black should be able to defend. However, we want to play risk-free, looking to get the better endgames or positions with pleasant positional pressure in the middlegame! }
2... Nc6 3. Bb5
{ Unlike after every other move, like @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 2@@EndFEN@@  2...d6  or  2...g6  , this time, we would not want to open up the center. I know it might sound confusing since I just said 'We are going for the Open Sicilian'. Well, we are, but not this time. :@@EndBracket@@  The move @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp1ppppp/2n5/2p5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 2 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Bb5  initiates something known as the Rossolimo Variation, which used to be an interesting sideline. There is a story that in the 80s, Kasparov told one of the students of the Botvinnik school 'Kid, you cannot just give up your bishop on c6, this is not Ruy Lopez'. But, of course, a few years later, he would play  3.Bb5  himself.  Over the course of the years, especially as people realized that the Sveshnikov Variation was so good, the desire for an ambitious Anti-Open Sicilian kept growing, and as a result, the move  3.Bb5  has become one of the two main lines, alongside  3.d4  . We are looking to capture on c6 and ruin Black's pawn structure. However, we are not forced to, and in some setups, we would prefer to avoid the trade!  The two main moves for Black are @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp1ppppp/2n5/1Bp5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...e6  and  3...g6  , but Black can also try a ton of other @@StartBracket@@mostly bad ones@@EndBracket@@, such as  3...a6  ,  3...Qb6  ,  3...Qc7  ,  3...g5?  , and so on. The reputable sidelines are  3...d6  and  3...e5!?  , and we'll cover those as well, of course. }
3... e5
{ This move, which used to be a funny sideline, has emerged out of nowhere in the few recent years to become one of Black's most solid choices! It is played with a weird idea: Black wants to go ...Bd6, seemingly blocking the queenside pieces, then ...Nge7, making sure that recapturing on c6 with the knight is always possible, then ...Bc7, unblocking the d-pawn, and ...d7-d5, occupying the entire center!  Quite an ambitious and cheeky plan, if you ask me. And, surprisingly, as people found out, it's a good plan for Black! It has been recently recommended by FM Plichta in his Black Dragon Sicilian repertoire on Chessable. This variation is especially effective versus the White Rossolimo players who love trading on c6 because this idea hardly works this time. }
4. O-O
{ We keep the tension. The goal is to play c2-c3 and d2-d4, opening up the center rapidly to take advantage of Black's somewhat awkward setup.   4.Bxc6?!  doesn't make sense this time.  4...dxc6  ,  Black will go ...Bd6, ...Ne7, ...O-O, and maybe ...f7-f5 at some point, reaching an extremely flexible and comfortable setup. Of course, just like in the Ruy Lopez, you cannot win the pawn with  5.Nxe5?!  due to  5...Qd4  6.Nf3  Qxe4+  with a perfectly decent position for Black. }
4... Bd6
{ Black doesn't mind blocking the d-pawn since Black claims it's only a temporary thing: the plan is to go ...Nge7 and ...Bc7, following up with ...d7-d5, fighting for the center. }
5. c3
{ So, we start fighting for the center ourselves, preparing to go d2-d4 and take all of it. }
5... a6
{ It's very important for Black to kick our bishop out first as we are about to discover. The point is that if it goes to c4, it ends up tactically vulnerable as the Informational variation shows us. Instead, if it goes to a4, Black can kick it out with ...b7-b5, developing the queenside very quickly, while also grabbing space. }
6. Ba4
{ The bishop needs to go exactly here. Why so? Because:  We keep an eye on the c6-knight. While we don't want to take it, helping Black's queenside come out faster after ...dxc6, this fact creates tactical ideas. For example, if we have a pawn on d4 and Black's knight is on c6, then Bxc6 eliminates the defender of the e5-pawn, and then dxe5 wins a piece.  If attacked, the bishop can retreat to the safe and comfortable c2-square, where it would protect the e4-pawn.   Unlike on c4, it won't be tactically vulnerable, making our plan of grabbing the center with d2-d4 more likely to succeed. }
6... b5
{ Black is taking space on the queenside first, kicking our bishop away. This makes perfect sense since now Black can easily develop the queenside with ...Bb7 and ...Rc8. }
7. Bc2
{ I prefer having the bishop here rather than on b3, as it's not running into ...c5-c4, while is also helping us protect the e4-pawn. }
7... Nge7
{ Black is getting ready to castle.  7...Nf6?  is, as almost always in this variation, a bad idea, since it leaves the e-file open.  8.d4!  cxd4  9.cxd4  exd4?  10.e5!±  and Black is facing considerable problems on the e-file with Re1 and f2-f4 coming. In fact, it's even worse than that, Black is just losing a piece. }
8. a4
{ Before opening up the center, I want to either make Black concede the a-file with ...Rb8, or weaken the c4-square with ...b5-b4. }
8... b4 { Every Black player chose the latter. } 9. d4
{ We are about to play d4-d5, taking all the center and restricting Black. Of course, there is also a huge positional threat of dxe5, since this move would allow our queen to attack the d6-bishop. That would force Black to give up the bishop pair by taking on e5 with the bishop, which would also run into f2-f4, causing a disaster. }
9... cxd4
{ Black needs to unload the center.  9...O-O??  10.dxe5  Bxe5  11.Nxe5  Nxe5  12.f4±  is awful for Black! }
10. cxd4
{ Here, Black can take on d4 with either the knight or the pawn. Generally, the way the game would go would look extremely similar. The d4-pawn would get lost very soon, and Black would end up with an isolated d-pawn and weak squares on d5 and d6 in front of it. Black is okay with such an outcome since Black is claiming that would yield enough piece activity to make up for the structural weaknesses.   Overall, the @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp1ppppp/2n5/1Bp5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...e5  variation is a very good one for Black, and this statement isn't far from the truth. But, I still prefer White in the arising positions, because, as we are about to see, we get to play somewhat better positions without any risk. }
10... Nxd4
{ I would give this as the main line since FM Plichta recommends it in his LTR. Black trades off a pair of knights, opening up the h1-a8 diagonal so that the bishop can immediately start staring at the e4-pawn. }
11. Nxd4 exd4 12. Nd2
{ As usual, we are hoping to conveniently recapture the d4-pawn with our knight, not the queen!  12.Qxd4?!  Qc7!  is rather annoying since it's a double attack on the  bishop and the h2-pawn. }
12... O-O 13. Nf3
{ We are getting ready to just recapture the pawn and play logical developing moves, such as Be3, Bb3, Qd3, Rac1, Rfd1, and so on. }
13... Qc7
{ This move, which targets the h2-pawn and the c2-bishop, is Plichta's suggestion. }
14. Bg5
{ I like the idea of freeing up the c1-square for our rook so that we can target Black's queen with Rc1 on the next turn, proving it's rather misplaced there. And, of course, it's helpful to go Bg5, starting to attack the knight, since now tactical threats like e4-e5!, distracting the knight's only defender, are starting to appear, which makes Black move the knight away. }
14... Ng6
{ The knight needs to go exactly here in order to block the b1-h7 diagonal and help the king feel safer. }
15. Rc1
{ We are starting to set up some x-rays on the c-file, while also simply protecting the bishop. Now, we are ready to take the d4-pawn back. }
15... Bb7 16. Bb1
{ I like the idea of making Black either go with the queen to a silly passive square like b8, or self-pin the bishop with ...Bc6. }
16... Bc6 17. Qxd4
{ Admittedly, it seems as though Black should be okay here, as it's not that easy for us to do much damage to the d7-pawn. However, I would still definitely pick White, as we have no weaknesses, but the opponent does. Next, I'd probably want to play g2-g3, blocking the diagonal the black queen and bishop are on, and follow up with Rfd1. Then, we can consider moving the queen away to d2 to keep an eye on the b4-pawn and follow with Nd4, activating the knight, looking to threaten the pinned bishop, or coming to f5.  Please note we couldn't move the knight earlier, as that would have blundered the h2-pawn, but once the h2-b8 diagonal is blocked, we can and will improve that piece! While objectively Black should be fine, it seems clearly more enjoyable to be White here. Given that this is one of the very sound theoretical variations for Black, I am more than happy with such an outcome! }
