[Black "Rossolimo Decent Sidelines 3.Bb5 Nf6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5
{ This move initiates what we know as the Sicilian Defense, the queen of the @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  Black openings. Alongside  1.e4  e5  , it's one of the two most sound ways of meeting 1.e4  from the theoretical standpoint. Black is fighting for the center, the d4-square, without creating a symmetrical position. This opening is extremely popular with players who want sharp, creative and fighting chess, and those who don't want to settle for symmetry, less space, or any other concessions. }
2. Nf3
{ In this Lifetime Repertoire, I have decided to go for the most ambitious way of playing versus the Sicilian Defense − the so-called Open Sicilian. Why would I do that? Isn't this a positional repertoire, and isn't the Open Sicilian known to be sharp and principled? Well, here is the deal.  It's a Lifetime Repertoire. I want this course to carry a theoretical punch, which most sidelines cannot offer. I was considering the Alapin, 2.c3, as well, but decided to not go down that route, because the isolated pawn positions, which often arise there, aren't to everyone's taste.  Interestingly enough, in many sharp-looking positions, there is a path to simplifications, which means that with sufficient theoretical knowledge, we are playing risk-free. It's not possible to get an advantage in every single theoretical variation of the Sicilian as White, and maybe not even in most.  
What we are doing instead is something different. We are striving to test our opponent's knowledge of typical ideas and forcing lines, and if Black is prepared brilliantly, we accept the fact Black should be able to defend. However, we want to play risk-free, looking to get the better endgames or positions with pleasant positional pressure in the middlegame! }
2... Nc6 3. Bb5
{ Unlike after every other move, like @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 2@@EndFEN@@  2...d6  or  2...g6  , this time, we would not want to open up the center. I know it might sound confusing since I just said 'We are going for the Open Sicilian'. Well, we are, but not this time. :@@EndBracket@@  The move @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp1ppppp/2n5/2p5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 2 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Bb5  initiates something known as the Rossolimo Variation, which used to be an interesting sideline. There is a story that in the 80s, Kasparov told one of the students of the Botvinnik school 'Kid, you cannot just give up your bishop on c6, this is not Ruy Lopez'. But, of course, a few years later, he would play  3.Bb5  himself.  Over the course of the years, especially as people realized that the Sveshnikov Variation was so good, the desire for an ambitious Anti-Open Sicilian kept growing, and as a result, the move  3.Bb5  has become one of the two main lines, alongside  3.d4  . We are looking to capture on c6 and ruin Black's pawn structure. However, we are not forced to, and in some setups, we would prefer to avoid the trade!  The two main moves for Black are @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp1ppppp/2n5/1Bp5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...e6  and  3...g6  , but Black can also try a ton of other @@StartBracket@@mostly bad ones@@EndBracket@@, such as  3...a6  ,  3...Qb6  ,  3...Qc7  ,  3...g5?  , and so on. The reputable sidelines are  3...d6  and  3...e5!?  , and we'll cover those as well, of course. }
3... Nf6
{ This move is a pretty interesting one. It's sound, but I don't see a lot of value to it, and here is why. Typically, after  3...g6  , White can either  take on c6, or keep tension with Re1, c2-c3, d2-d4, and so on. We, of course, do the latter.  After  3...Nf6  , White  can either choose to take on c6, forcing ...dxc6, when Black has to develop the bishop to g7 anyway − there isn't anything else to do, or White can go e4-e5, O-O, Re1, and get similar positions to the ones in the  3...g6  line.  So, it's not obvious what exactly Black achieves with this move order, while also cutting down the options: in some  3...g6  lines, Black could  go ...Ne7, or ...Nh6-f7. Unfortunately, our setup  vs.  3...g6  is literally the only one that cannot be blindly copied after  3...Nf6  , as we strive to avoid  playing e4-e5, instead hoping to occupy the center after c2-c3 and d2-d4. So, we'll need to learn a couple of specific lines, but no worries, they are pretty straightforward and easy. }
4. Nc3
{ We protect the e4-pawn. This move, however, isn't just a defensive move. It already contains a positional threat. We are threatening to play e4-e5, kicking the knight out. The reason why it's a threat now, although it wasn't a move ago, is because we now control the d5-square, preventing Black from being able to play ...Nd5, and forcing an awkward ugly move like ...Ng4 or something.   Here, Black has three logical continuations, namely  4...Qc7  , the main move and the most decent one;  4...g6  , which a lot of people went for, but I consider this to be a hard sound gamble, and  4...Nd4  , which is also a bit risky. }
4... g6
{ This move has been tried by Abdusattorov, Li Chao, Korobov, and several other strong GMs, but I consider it very suspicious because Black ends up wasting a lot of time, getting a clearly inferior version of the 3...g6 lines.   4...e5  isn’t a great move because after the typical  5.Bxc6  ,  Black gets an awkward position. It is no longer possible to develop easily with ...g7-g6 and ...Bg7 because the e5-pawn would be hanging. }
5. e5
{ First, we kick out the opponent's knight. It is forced to go to g4, which definitely doesn't look like the safest or most optimal square. }
5... Ng4
{ The e5-pawn is in danger, and we don't want to make moves like Qe2, spending time protecting it. }
6. Bxc6
{ So, we eliminate one of the attackers, while also doubling Black's pawns, which is something we enjoy doing in most Rossolimo positions. }
6... dxc6
{ 6...bxc6?  makes no sense since Black cannot build a strong center  with ...d7-d6 and ...e7-e5, and now the c8-bishop is locked inside.  7.h3  Nh6  8.O-O±  with a much better version of the standard positions. }
7. h3
{ The knight wasn't threatening us, but it is still nice to push it out to a passive position on h6. }
7... Nh6 8. Ne4
{ We are attacking the c5-pawn, forcing Black to spend time defending it, which allows us to activate the knight for free. }
8... b6 9. d3
{ The knight on h6 is in a very suspicious situation. For example, if we go Bg5 on the next turn, pinning the e7-pawn and threatening Nd6+, making Black waste time defending, and then following up with g2-g4, restricting the knight, there would be a threat of trapping it with Qd2. So, Black needs to activate it − now, or on the next turn. }
9... Nf5 10. a4
{ I like the idea of making this move, trying to create tension on the queenside with a4-a5. The thing is, if our pawn gets on a5, we'll enjoy something called 'one-sided tension'. Black won't be able to push ...b6-b5 without losing, or at least considerably weakening the c5-pawn. If Black takes on a5, that would terribly weaken or lose the c5-pawn, and make the a5-pawn extremely weak. }
10... a5
{ Black needs to stop that plan. However, now the b6-pawn becomes much weaker. If we ever install the knight on c4, some black piece would be forced to babysit that pawn forever, and it would be hardly possible to kick the knight out with ...b6-b5 without making the a5 and c5-pawns terminally weak. }
11. O-O Bg7
{ Several games arrived at this position. It's not exactly a typical Rossolimo position, because Black failed to solve the problem of the light-squared bishop with ...Bg4, and now it's locked inside, having nothing to do. Black would like to play ...Nd4, swapping the knights and facilitating the defense, so we should prevent that. }
12. c3 O-O 13. Re1
{ Next, we can play Bg5 or Bf4, then Qd2, threatening to trap Black's knight with g2-g4. The opponent, unfortunately, has no counterplay. }
13... Ba6 { Attacking the d3-pawn, but this isn't a problem. } 14. g4
{ First, we kick out the knight to a very passive position. } 14... Nh6 15. d4
{ And open the center. } 15... cxd4 16. Nxd4
{ We are threatening the c6-pawn, while also getting ready to simply play Bf4, overprotecting the e5-pawn and looking to trap the knight with Qd2/c1. Once we go Bf4, we can also consider developing the queen to b3 to put pressure on Black's queenside, following up with Rad1, maybe at some point threatening e5-e6, or simply absolutely restricting Black. }
16... c5 17. Nb5 Qxd1 18. Rxd1 Bb7 19. f3
{ Black doesn't have the slightest bit of counterplay. The knight is placed perfectly on b5. Of course, Black can never capture the e5-pawn, as that would lose the knight on h6. Next, we can play Bf4 or Bg5, double on the d-file, and at some point consider Nc7-d5. White went on to convincingly win both games that got here. 1-0 Nemchenko-Dzenis, ICCF email 2011. }
