{ Black needs to kick our knight out, hoping we would go to c3, so that Black could trade down, decreasing the space disadvantage and dangers in the position. }
8. c4
{ However, we have very different plans! We are forcing the knight to retreat, winning a lot of space in the center and restricting the opponent even more. }
8... Nb4
{ The knight needs to go here so that in the future, it can retreat to c6.  8...axb5?  leads to horrible consequences after  9.cxd5+-  , as our central pawns are making it absolutely impossible for Black to develop in any possible way. }
9. Nc3 d6
{ Black needs to fight for some space in the center and challenge our e5-pawn, or else, how would Black develop? }
10. exd6 Qxd6
{ Of course, taking with the pawn, creating a hole on d5, and opening the e-file for our developed pieces to attack the king, would be too reckless. }
11. Ne4
{ However, now Black is forced to waste even more time, moving the queen around and protecting the c5-pawn. }
11... Qc7 12. d4
{ Of course, being considerably ahead in development, we are looking to open up the position as much as we can. The c5-pawn is hanging, so Black has no choice but to take. }
12... cxd4 13. Re1
{ We could have made a ton of other moves, but I really like this one, which improves the rook, setting Black up for some unpleasant surprises down the e-file. }
13... Bg4 14. Qa4+
{ Black is forced to block with the knight, which leads to an extremely dangerous position by force. }
14... Nc6 15. Nxd4
{ We have a tremendous lead in development, and Black's kingside pieces still haven't made a single move. So, Black needs to evacuate the king elsewhere − at least, in the two high-level games that got here, Black thought so. }
15... O-O-O 16. Nxc6 Qxc6
{ In this position, the strong GM Tukmakov decided to trade queens on c6, achieving a very pleasant endgame, where Black has weak queenside pawns and weak dark squares, such as c5. }
17. Qa5
{ Black's king is very unsafe. Next, we'll go Bf4, b2-b4-b5, and will tear the king apart.   17.Qxc6+  bxc6  18.Be3  also led to a very pleasant and risk-free position. ½-½ Tukmakov-Sveshnikov, Ashkhabad 1978. }
17... e6 18. Bf4
{ With b2-b4-b5 coming, I am not exactly sure what's the defense plan. Black is in dire straits. }
