4. Nc3
{ We protect the e4-pawn. This move, however, isn't just a defensive move. It already contains a positional threat. We are threatening to play e4-e5, kicking the knight out. The reason why it's a threat now, although it wasn't a move ago, is because we now control the d5-square, preventing Black from being able to play ...Nd5, and forcing an awkward ugly move like ...Ng4 or something.   Here, Black has three logical continuations, namely  4...Qc7  , the main move and the most decent one;  4...g6  , which a lot of people went for, but I consider this to be a hard sound gamble, and  4...Nd4  , which is also a bit risky. }
4... Qc7
{ Black takes the e5-square under control, preventing e4-e5, while also protecting the c6-knight, making it possible to recapture with the queen at times, keeping the structure intact. This is the best and most popular move, tried on numerous occasions by such strong GMs as Zhigalko, Zvjaginsev, Rakhmanov, and many others. }
5. O-O
{ First, we just castle. The plan is to go Re1 and prepare e4-e5, pushing the knight out. }
5... Nd4 6. Re1
{ We are happy to let Black have the bishop pair since taking that bishop only continues to waste time. Black is already so behind in development! }
6... a6
{ Black should kick out the bishop in order to unpin the d-pawn. This is the move GM Zhigalko has tried more than a dozen times with Black versus such strong players as So, Nepo, Grischuk, Xiong, and many others. }
7. Bf1 { The bishop gets out of the way. Now, e4-e5 is a huge threat. } 7... e5
{ Black can also try locking the position up. However, this plan doesn't seem to be fully succeeding. }
8. Nd5
{ Black has to capture the knight since retreating with the queen either results in a terrible pawn structure after any queen move met with Nxf6+ gxf6, or loses the e5-pawn if the black queen goes to d8. }
8... Nxd5 { 8...Qd8?  9.Nxe5+-  just loses a pawn. } 9. exd5
{ White is going to relentlessly tear the center apart with c2-c3 and d2-d4 in order to take advantage of the lead in development. }
9... d6 { The e5-pawn was hanging, so Black needed to protect it. } 10. Nxd4
cxd4 11. c3
{ While ahead in development, open the position up! Black has no choice but to follow along. }
11... dxc3 12. bxc3
{ This move is a much better one because it enables us to play d2-d4 next, taking advantage of the powerful and useful rook on e1, which is x-raying the black king. }
12... Be7 13. d4
{ We are offering a pawn sacrifice. In three games that reached this position, Black never dared to accept, instead preferring to castle as soon as possible. }
13... Qxc3 14. dxe5
{ Black cannot take the rook, as after exd6, will get destroyed on the e-file. }
14... dxe5 15. Rb1 O-O 16. Bb2
{ White wins the e5-pawn and gets a dominant, nearly winning position. That's for several reasons: the passed d-pawn is very strong; White can easily and quickly create a very powerful attack on the kingside with ideas like Qh5, Rb3-g3, and Bd3, aiming all the pieces there. }
