{ Black takes the e5-square under control, preventing e4-e5, while also protecting the c6-knight, making it possible to recapture with the queen at times, keeping the structure intact. This is the best and most popular move, tried on numerous occasions by such strong GMs as Zhigalko, Zvjaginsev, Rakhmanov, and many others. }
5. O-O
{ First, we just castle. The plan is to go Re1 and prepare e4-e5, pushing the knight out. }
5... Nd4 6. Re1
{ We are happy to let Black have the bishop pair since taking that bishop only continues to waste time. Black is already so behind in development! }
6... a6
{ Black should kick out the bishop in order to unpin the d-pawn. This is the move GM Zhigalko has tried more than a dozen times with Black versus such strong players as So, Nepo, Grischuk, Xiong, and many others. }
7. Bf1 { The bishop gets out of the way. Now, e4-e5 is a huge threat. } 7...
Ng4
{ This seems to be Black's best variation, threatening to take our f3-knight and checkmate us with Qxh2! Don't blunder this! }
8. g3
{ We stop the threat, preparing to place the bishop on g2. Now, we are threatening to capture the knight on d4 and then win the one on g4, as it is hanging.   8.h3??  Nxf3+  9.Qxf3  Qh2#  is an instant loss! Don't do this!! }
8... Nxf3+ 9. Qxf3 { The knight is under attack and is forced to leave. } 9...
Ne5 10. Qe2
{ The good news for our opponent is that Black managed to swap a pair of pieces, which decreased any future space disadvantage problems. The bad one is that Black spent a lot of time doing that. Now, we have a very simple plan.   We'll go Bg2, then b2-b3 and Bb2, deploying the other bishop to the long diagonal as well, where it hopefully would prove very useful. Then, we'll remove the knight from c3, as it wasn't doing much there. We'll go Nd1-e3, and then c2-c3 followed by d2-d4, occupying the entire center! }
10... e6 11. b3 { The bishop is getting ready to go to b2. } 11... d6 12. Bb2
Be7 13. Nd1
{ We are getting ready to play c2-c3 and d2-d4, occupying the entire center. It's worth pointing out that now there is a threat of f2-f4, kicking out the e5-knight and winning the hanging g7-pawn. }
13... O-O
{ Castling is not just a generally useful chess move, but in this case, it also defends the g7-pawn against the aforementioned threat. }
14. c3 { We are getting ready to occupy the center anyway. } 14... b5
{ Black couldn't stop that, so at least is grabbing space on the queenside, preparing to play ...Bb7, and developing the bishop to the long diagonal. }
15. d4 { We are taking the center, as intended. } 15... Nd7 16. Ne3
{ Now, it's time to activate the knight. } 16... Bb7 17. Bg2
{ We are threatening to play d4-d5, restricting the b7-bishop. We can follow up with c3-c4, taking the entire center and activating the b2-bishop. If Black ever removes the e6-pawn with ...exd5 or ...e6-e5, it would enable our knight to come to f5 and the queen on g4, starting a kingside attack. Again, Black has a passive and unpleasant position. }
