{ Unlike after every other move, like @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 2@@EndFEN@@  2...d6  or  2...g6  , this time, we would not want to open up the center. I know it might sound confusing since I just said 'We are going for the Open Sicilian'. Well, we are, but not this time. :@@EndBracket@@  The move @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp1ppppp/2n5/2p5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 2 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Bb5  initiates something known as the Rossolimo Variation, which used to be an interesting sideline. There is a story that in the 80s, Kasparov told one of the students of the Botvinnik school 'Kid, you cannot just give up your bishop on c6, this is not Ruy Lopez'. But, of course, a few years later, he would play  3.Bb5  himself.  Over the course of the years, especially as people realized that the Sveshnikov Variation was so good, the desire for an ambitious Anti-Open Sicilian kept growing, and as a result, the move  3.Bb5  has become one of the two main lines, alongside  3.d4  . We are looking to capture on c6 and ruin Black's pawn structure. However, we are not forced to, and in some setups, we would prefer to avoid the trade!  The two main moves for Black are @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp1ppppp/2n5/1Bp5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...e6  and  3...g6  , but Black can also try a ton of other @@StartBracket@@mostly bad ones@@EndBracket@@, such as  3...a6  ,  3...Qb6  ,  3...Qc7  ,  3...g5?  , and so on. The reputable sidelines are  3...d6  and  3...e5!?  , and we'll cover those as well, of course. }
3... d6
{ This is Black's 3rd most common move, right after  3...g6  and  3...e6  .  Black is taking the e5-square under control, preparing to play ...Nf6 at some point without running into e4-e5. By playing ...d7-d6, Black also makes it possible to go ...Bd7 next, unpinning the knight, and preventing any damage to the pawn structure. Then, Black would like to develop with ...Nf6, ...g7-g6, ...Bg7, and so on.  In this position, I will offer you two choices, one related to this specific position, and the other  (a very simple one)  will be just a transposition to the lines we play  via @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq c6 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.Nf3  d6!  White mostly plays @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp2pppp/2np4/1Bp5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.O-O  − there are more than 13  000  games in the database. But my main suggestion,  4.Bxc6  , is four times less popular. However, I consider it to be very dangerous, especially for the non-suspecting Black players! }
4. Bxc6+
{ In the true spirit of the Rossolimo, we immediately double Black's pawns, hoping to play against the weak pawn structure. }
4... bxc6
{ Black would love to play ...e7-e5 to get great control of the center, fight for the space, and prevent any d2-d4 or e4-e5 related ideas. If Black manages to do so, development can be done comfortably with ...Be6, ...Be7, ...Nf6, and maybe even ...f7-f5 at some point. }
5. e5
{ This is the key move that you should remember. We are preventing ...e7-e5, making it difficult for Black to fight for space in the center. Crucially, Black is now facing serious problems, both in terms of finishing development, and in terms of understanding what to do with the pawns in the center. Why is that happening?  Black cannot play ...Nf6, because our pawn on e5 is restrictive.  Black can go ...e7-e6, but that would lock in the bishop on c8, and allow us to capture exd6, leaving Black with two isolated doubled c-pawns, which will be very weak for the rest of the game. And, of course, we'll have the outpost on c4.  If Black goes ...d6-d5, that creates fewer problems, but it still leaves the c5-pawn pretty weak, because there is no d-pawn left to defend it. Our goal, in that case, will be to play d2-d3 and c2-c4 to fix the c5-pawn on its current position, and then start attacking it, for example with Nc3-a4, b2-b3, Ba3, and so on. So, Black needs to make a difficult choice. }
5... Bg4
{ Black can also try playing this way. The idea, of course, is to set up his pawns on d5 and e6, keeping the center closed, while not locking the bishop on c8. }
6. h3 { We are immediately kicking the bishop out. } 6... Bh5
{ 6...Bxf3  7.Qxf3  with a very pleasant position,  where the e5-pawn provides a spatial advantage, and Black's structure is inferior. Of course, Black cannot win the e5-pawn, as the one on c6 is hanging with check, followed by a rook on a8. }
7. d3
{ We just keep developing. Now, Black is facing a pretty unpleasant choice: take on f3, which is completely illogical because Black could have done that without wasting time; play ...e7-e6, allowing for exd6, which also looks bad, as in other positions we discuss; go ...d6-d5, locking the center out, but with the light-squared bishop outside. No one has ever done that, and for a good reason, as we are about to discover. Finally, Black can play ...dxe5, trying to take advantage of the pin. }
7... d5
{ This is a mistake, as now we can completely block the opponent's kingside. }
8. g4 Bg6 9. e6
{ This is a typical idea from the Caro-Kann. Black cannot really take. } 9...
fxe6 10. Qe2 Qd6 11. Ne5
{ Black is absolutely stuck. What moves can be played next?! Black can go ...Nf6, but we'll just continue developing with Bf4, Nd2-f3, and so on. On the other hand, the dark-squared bishop and the rook on h8 cannot get out. And, once we play Bf4, there will be a threat of Nxg6, with a discovered attack on the queen. It's not obvious to me what Black should be doing here. The position is lost! }
