5... f6
{ This odd-looking move has been only played in 9 games so far, but surprisingly, I think this is Black's best shot at equality. Not mathematical equality, but dynamic balance, with weaknesses and counterplay. Black wants to make us get rid of the powerful e5-pawn and then occupy the center with ...e7-e5. }
6. exd6 e5
{ The c-pawns are ugly and weak, but Black is about to get a ton of space in the center. }
7. d3
{ We just continue developing. The plan is to install the knight on the gorgeous outpost on c4. }
7... Bxd6 8. Nbd2 Ne7 9. Nc4 { We want to deprive Black of the bishop pair. }
9... Bc7 10. Nfd2
{ Black was potentially hoping to pin the knight with ...Bg4, which wouldn't have been a big deal, but it's nice that it is no longer possible. The knight might come to e4 or to b3, then we'll follow with Be3, or b2-b3 and Ba3, attacking the weak c5-pawn. }
10... O-O 11. b3
{ It's very convenient to develop the bishop to a3 this way, as we don't need to move the knight on d2 first, which would be the case if we tried going for the Be3 setup. }
11... Nd5 12. Ba3
{ Objectively speaking, I think Black should have enough piece activity and space to make up for the structural weaknesses. However, I would still prefer White, and I definitely have great confidence in White's chances in this variation, because no one knows about the move @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/p3pppp/2pp4/2p1P3/8/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...f6  , really.   Plus, even here, Black needs to make some choices, which aren't obvious: do you give up the pawn? Go ...Bd6, letting White deprive you of the bishop pair, ending up with a bad structure? Or ...Bb6, hoping White trades and improves your pawns, but accepting the fact the bishop will be very passive there if White doesn't? We can play O-O, Ne4, Qe2, or Qf3, and keep harassing the c5-pawn forever.   Probably you won’t ever see this position in your games, so it’s not relevant. But, just to show you another idea: the ever-creative engine wants to just ignore the hanging c5-pawn with  12...f5  .  Black wants to go ...Rf6 and bring the pieces over to the kingside. In that case, it makes sense to point out that the e5-pawn gets much weaker. We’ll focus on attacking it now. For example,  13.O-O  Rf6  14.Bb2!  Qe7  15.Qf3!  ,  intending Rae1. Black should be quite uncomfortable, as it’s so difficult to keep protecting endlessly that weak pawn. }
