6... d6
{ I think that this rare and timid-looking move is Black's best choice, getting ready to play ...e6-e5, while still keeping the knight on a very flexible square. I believe this is the way to go if Black wants to equalize. }
7. e5
{ We are preventing Black from playing ...e6-e5, while also getting ready to create doubled isolated pawns by trading on d6. Here, Black needs to show a terrific understanding of the imbalance between piece activity and pawn structure, and... allow that to happen! That's why this has hardly been tried. It's a very illogical, counterintuitive decision! }
7... d5
{ A typical positional mistake. We can either lock up the center with c2-c4 or go h2-h4. }
8. h4
{ Achieving a standard position, where Black lacks space. The move ...h7-h5 results in typical positions where a tempo was wasted by going ...d7-d6 and then ...d6-d5, and otherwise, ...Ng6 always runs into h4-h5. }
8... Nf5 9. h5
{ We grab even more space, preparing an interesting structural transformation. }
9... Be7 { Let's say Black keeps developing. } 10. g4 Nd4
{ Black gets to undouble the c-pawns, which is something our opponent should be supposedly happy about. }
11. Nxd4 cxd4 12. h6
{ However, we make Black weaken the dark squares very considerably. } 12... g6
13. Nd2
{ Next, we'd love to play Nf3 and g4-g5!, completely locking up the kingside. The king would go to f1-g2, or we can castle kingside. Remember, if the position is completely locked up, nothing can happen on the kingside. Next, we'd love to slowly prepare some undermining moves on the queenside, such as c2-c3, b2-b4, or a2-a3 followed by b2-b4. Black has no counterplay and the light-squared bishop is very restricted. Let's be honest, both bishops are! }
