8. exd6
{ This is the more obvious choice, immediately forcing the beneficial pawn structure. }
8... Bxd6 9. Nbd2 { The knight is on its merry way to the outpost on c4. } 9...
O-O 10. c3
{ This move weakens the d3-pawn, so it might not come across as an obvious decision. However, we cover up the d4-square, preventing the black knight from jumping there.   10.O-O  isn't as good, because Black can use the d4-square for the knight.  10...Nd4!  Black hopes to kick our queen  back to d1, take space with ...e6-e5, activate the bishop on c8, and so on. We cannot have that happen.  11.Nxd4!  So, we trade.  Black undoubles the c-pawns,  but we still have an outpost on c4.  11...cxd4  12.Qe4!  With this move, we are attacking  the c6-pawn, hoping to trade off the bishops with Bf4 at some point. Importantly, the d4-pawn isn't hanging. Taking it would be a game-losing mistake due to ...Bxh2+, picking up the loose queen on d4.  12...Bb7  13.Nc4  and we install the knight on a wonderful square. It's not obvious if we would do that, but we could certainly consider taking on d6, going for a somewhat better position with opposite-colored bishops, where our pawn structure is better.   After  13...Bc7  , it seems wise for Black to retreat, not giving  us an option of trading on d6.  14.Bf4  and now we get to trade the bishops, getting rid of the opponent's bishop pair.  14...Bxf4  15.Qxf4  c5  .  Black's structure is worse and we have an outpost on c4, but the bishop is very active. We also cannot easily attack the c5-pawn. Obviously, this is a playable interesting position. But, objectively, it is balanced. }
10... e5
{ Two games reached this position. In one, Black tried ...f7-f6 followed by ...e6-e5, and in the more recent one, Black chose to immediately take more space in the center. }
11. Ne4
{ White gladly activates the knight and is by no means obligated to capture on d6, but it's certainly nice to have that option, as well as pressure on the c5-pawn. }
11... Re8 12. g4
{ And now, White made a pretty ambitious decision. It seems as though the move is a bit risky because it weakens our kingside. But White had no intention of castling kingside! Instead, this move simply grabs space and secures the position of the e4-knight, making it impossible for Black to kick it out with ...f7-f5. }
12... Ne7 13. Nfd2
{ This move, first of all, addresses the threat of the hanging g4-pawn. Secondly, the knight is on its way to the outpost on c4. }
13... Nd5 14. Nc4 Bf8 15. h4
{ White is smoothly developing the initiative on the kingside, continuing to occupy even more space, while the opponent has no activity. }
15... Qd7 16. Rg1 { The g4-pawn isn't hard to defend. } 16... Ba6 17. Be3
{ Now, the c5-pawn is under a lot of pressure. } 17... Nf4
{ The hanging c5-pawn forced Black to seek structural changes. } 18. Bxf4 Bxc4
19. dxc4 exf4 20. f3 { 1-0 Demchenko-Samunenkov, Piestany 2022. } *

