7... Ng6
{ They don't seem to have any other plan, besides this typical one, which we are seeing all the time throughout the entire chapter. }
8. h4
{ As usual, we challenge the knight, preparing h4-h5, and trying to provoke ...h7-h5, which weakens the g5-square, and makes that knight on g6 loose. }
8... h5 9. e5 f6
{ This doesn't make much sense here since the e5-pawn is very easy to defend. }
10. Bb2 Qc7 11. Nbd2
{ We are threatening to win the pawn on f6. Of course, moves like ...Nf4 don't yield anything besides a moment of pleasure. We'd simply retreat with Qf1, then kick out the knight with g2-g3, and return to where we started. So, Black should just develop. }
11... Be7 12. O-O-O
{ Our king is perfectly safe here. Black cannot use the b-file, of course, as it is blocked by our b3-pawn. If Black ever goes ...a7-a5, we immediately answer with a2-a4, preventing any attempts to get counterplay.  No matter if Black castles kingside or not, on the next move, we'd like to play Rdg1, and then prepare g2-g4, opening up the g-file, looking to take advantage of the loose knight on g6 and the loose pawn on g7.  Of course, castling kingside would only make matters worse, as then the black king would also run into this fire. All in all, this is another extremely unpleasant position for Black! }
