{ Now, the knight is less protected than a move ago, which means if Black ever decides to play ...f7-f6, it would end up completely undefended and vulnerable. Additionally, the g5-square has become weaker. However, Black wants to go ...e6-e5, taking more space in the center, and we need to prevent that. }
8. e5
{ With this move, we achieve several things: we prevent ...e6-e5, grab more space, and gain access to the e4-square, which could be used by our queen to attack that loose g6-knight, or by our knight. From there, the knight would attack the c5-pawn, and keep an eye on that weak square on d6. }
8... f6
{ It seems as though most Black players agree on the conclusion that getting rid of our powerful e5-pawn is needed immediately.  8...d5  transposes into  8...d6  , of course, after  9.exd6  . }
9. Nbd2
{ Most people choose to immediately attack the knight with  9.Qe4  , but I prefer developing. We'd love to overprotect  the e5-pawn with Nc4 on the next turn, and then see if Qe4 is still called for. }
9... Qc7 { Black needs to put more pressure on the e5-pawn. } 10. Nc4
{ Of course, we keep defending the pawn too. } 10... Ba6
{ Black needs to put more pressure on the knight, which is the pawn's key defender. }
11. Qe4
{ This is a key move to remember. We are attacking Black's knight, making the opponent take on e5, defend the knight with an awkward king move, or release the tension with ...f6-f5, making that pawn on e5 safe. }
11... Nxe5 { An awful idea. } 12. Ncxe5 fxe5 13. Qg6+
{ Black loses castling rights and is dead lost.  13.Nxe5  should also be winning. }
13... Kd8 14. Ng5
{ The massive fork Nf7+ seems impossible to stop. This isn't acceptable for Black! }
14... Kc8 { The king can try running away, but that doesn't help either. } 15.
Nf7 Rg8 16. Qh7 { And the rook just gets lost for nothing. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "25) Rossolimo 3...e6"]
[Black "Rossolimo 3.Bb5 e6 − 6.Qe2 Ng6 #5"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5
{ This move initiates what we know as the Sicilian Defense, the queen of the @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  Black openings. Alongside  1.e4  e5  , it's one of the two most sound ways of meeting 1.e4  from the theoretical standpoint. Black is fighting for the center, the d4-square, without creating a symmetrical position. This opening is extremely popular with players who want sharp, creative and fighting chess, and those who don't want to settle for symmetry, less space, or any other concessions. }
2. Nf3
{ In this Lifetime Repertoire, I have decided to go for the most ambitious way of playing versus the Sicilian Defense − the so-called Open Sicilian. Why would I do that? Isn't this a positional repertoire, and isn't the Open Sicilian known to be sharp and principled? Well, here is the deal.  It's a Lifetime Repertoire. I want this course to carry a theoretical punch, which most sidelines cannot offer. I was considering the Alapin, 2.c3, as well, but decided to not go down that route, because the isolated pawn positions, which often arise there, aren't to everyone's taste.  Interestingly enough, in many sharp-looking positions, there is a path to simplifications, which means that with sufficient theoretical knowledge, we are playing risk-free. It's not possible to get an advantage in every single theoretical variation of the Sicilian as White, and maybe not even in most.  
What we are doing instead is something different. We are striving to test our opponent's knowledge of typical ideas and forcing lines, and if Black is prepared brilliantly, we accept the fact Black should be able to defend. However, we want to play risk-free, looking to get the better endgames or positions with pleasant positional pressure in the middlegame! }
2... Nc6 3. Bb5
{ Unlike after every other move, like @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 2@@EndFEN@@  2...d6  or  2...g6  , this time, we would not want to open up the center. I know it might sound confusing since I just said 'We are going for the Open Sicilian'. Well, we are, but not this time. :@@EndBracket@@  The move @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp1ppppp/2n5/2p5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 2 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Bb5  initiates something known as the Rossolimo Variation, which used to be an interesting sideline. There is a story that in the 80s, Kasparov told one of the students of the Botvinnik school 'Kid, you cannot just give up your bishop on c6, this is not Ruy Lopez'. But, of course, a few years later, he would play  3.Bb5  himself.  Over the course of the years, especially as people realized that the Sveshnikov Variation was so good, the desire for an ambitious Anti-Open Sicilian kept growing, and as a result, the move  3.Bb5  has become one of the two main lines, alongside  3.d4  . We are looking to capture on c6 and ruin Black's pawn structure. However, we are not forced to, and in some setups, we would prefer to avoid the trade!  The two main moves for Black are @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp1ppppp/2n5/1Bp5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...e6  and  3...g6  , but Black can also try a ton of other @@StartBracket@@mostly bad ones@@EndBracket@@, such as  3...a6  ,  3...Qb6  ,  3...Qc7  ,  3...g5?  , and so on. The reputable sidelines are  3...d6  and  3...e5!?  , and we'll cover those as well, of course. }
3... e6
{ This, alongside with  3...g6  ,  is one of Black's main choices, which became especially popular after Gelfand used it in his World Championship match versus Anand in 2012, having equalized convincingly in several games. Black's idea is  to play ...Nge7, preventing White from doubling the pawns by capturing on c6. Then, Black would like to play ...a7-a6, kicking the bishop out, and ...d7-d5, grabbing space in the center.  If White does take on c6, Black has to @@StartBracket@@we will see why@@EndBracket@@ take with the b-pawn. Then, Black tries to build a big center with ...d7-d5, or with ...d7-d6 and ...e6-e5. All in all, a very good variation for Black.   Luckily, after quite a bit of looking around, I found a very attractive, and somewhat surprising way of challenging this line. This discovery, because of its simplicity, is one of my favorite choices in this entire 1.e4 repertoire.   In this position, the two main choices White has have been  4.Bxc6  , doubling Black's pawns, and  4.O-O  . The former used to be the most popular move, but faded away 7-8 years ago. Instead,  4.O-O  picked up as the more frequent choice. Then, people discovered that after  4.O-O  Nge7  , instead of moves like  5.c3  or  5.Re1  , there was an interesting idea to play  5.d4  . That was very trendy for a while but also declined in popularity a bit. Our main choice will be @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp1p1ppp/2n1p3/1Bp5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.Bxc6  , but I will briefly mention  4.O-O  as well. }
4. Bxc6
{ I consider this move to be White's most promising option. We are immediately in the very spirit of the Rossolimo Variation, doubling Black's pawns. }
4... bxc6
{ Black takes towards the center, getting a semi-open b-file and better control over the center. Now, it's easier to control the d5-square, which makes the plan of ...d7-d6 and ...e6-e5, building a strong center without weakening any squares, a lot more logical.   In this position, White has several good choices, such as  5.d3  , the main move,  5.O-O  ,  5.b3  , and even  5.e5  . }
5. d3
{ Here is the kicker. As you likely know, my reputation as an author has been built on interesting, unexplored, and creative sideline choices. I tend to not go for the most research theoretical stuff because I believe the main lines do not offer a lot of room for creativity. However, this is hard to believe, but it's true.   After  5.d3  , the very main line, and especially after  5.d3  Ne7  6.Qe2  , White's most popular move, Black, in MOST games, chose the wrong continuations, after which is clearly worse!  The better moves are starting to become more known, but are still very infrequently used, so I think we are killing two rabbits with one shot: we are playing the main line, not giving up the fight for theoretical advantage, and... we don't need to deal with a lot of theory, because most people somehow don't play this position correctly!  As for the essence of the move  5.d3  , it's very simple:  we are just overprotecting the e4-pawn, while also making room for the dark-squared bishop, and the b1-knight − it can now come to d2. }
5... Ne7
{ In the overwhelming number of games, Black has chosen this move, keeping the tension and not deciding yet to open up the center with ...d7-d5. As a result, depending on what we do, Black could go ...d7-d5, or ...d7-d6, preparing ...e6-e5. The knight will need to go to g6 in order to unblock the f8-bishop. And this is our hope. Once it does, it will most likely get hit with h2-h4-h5!  In these positions, we are often interested in playing e4-e5. This is done in order to prevent Black's d-pawn from moving: if Black meets e4-e5 with ...d7-d6 or ...d7-d5, we take en passant, creating the weak doubled isolated c-pawns. So, Black often meets e4-e5 with ...Ne7-g6 and ...f7-f6, undermining that pawn.  However, in those cases, the g6-knight is both powerful, as it attacks our center, and vulnerable, as it runs into h2-h4-h5. Black can stop h2-h4-h5 with ...h7-h5, but combining the moves ...f7-f6 and ...h7-h5 is not a very safe idea because it makes the g6-knight very loose, just like the kingside overall. These, in brief, are the main explanations for this position. Now, let's dive in and see some more details! }
6. Qe2
{ This flexible move achieves several things:  The queen will be able to help defend the e-pawn, be it on e4, or on e5 if we advance it. Black might, especially in order to free up the c8-bishop, try the ...c5-c4 pawn break at some point. The queen helps prevent it. Once we play e4-e5, in many cases, especially when Black's knight is loose on g6, the idea Qe4!, attacking the knight, turns out very promising.    The statistics in this position amaze me. In the master database, we see 744 games. Of those, 264 saw the move  6...Ng6  , 173 saw the move  6...Qc7  , and the move  6...d5  has been played in 154 games. However, in my understanding, there are only  two decent moves here, namely ...f7-f6 and ...d7-d6. But, only 104 players have made the correct move  6...d6  . The move  6...f6  is not as good but is also okay, and it's been seen in 48 games. So, you will be seeing the suboptimal variations in 80% of the games, unless my understanding of the position is completely incorrect!  It seems as though top players have been catching up lately, as most recent games saw those two continuations. But, it's still definitely a conclusion most Black players have not reached, so we have a good chance of surprising them! }
6... Ng6
{ This move, which prepares ...e6-e5, as well as ...Be7 followed by kingside castling, has been seen in most games. But, due to White's standard and frequent response, I consider it a bad choice. }
7. h4
{ We are immediately starting to harass the knight, looking to kick it away with h4-h5. Black can prevent us with  7...h5  , or go  7...Qc7  ,  looking to control the f4-square and jump there with the knight. }
7... h5
{ Now, the knight is less protected than a move ago, which means if Black ever decides to play ...f7-f6, it would end up completely undefended and vulnerable. Additionally, the g5-square has become weaker. However, Black wants to go ...e6-e5, taking more space in the center, and we need to prevent that. }
8. e5
{ With this move, we achieve several things: we prevent ...e6-e5, grab more space, and gain access to the e4-square, which could be used by our queen to attack that loose g6-knight, or by our knight. From there, the knight would attack the c5-pawn, and keep an eye on that weak square on d6. }
8... f6
{ It seems as though most Black players agree on the conclusion that getting rid of our powerful e5-pawn is needed immediately.  8...d5  transposes into  8...d6  , of course, after  9.exd6  . }
9. Nbd2
{ Most people choose to immediately attack the knight with  9.Qe4  , but I prefer developing. We'd love to overprotect  the e5-pawn with Nc4 on the next turn, and then see if Qe4 is still called for. }
9... Qc7 { Black needs to put more pressure on the e5-pawn. } 10. Nc4
{ Of course, we keep defending the pawn too. } 10... Ba6
{ Black needs to put more pressure on the knight, which is the pawn's key defender. }
11. Qe4
{ This is a key move to remember. We are attacking Black's knight, making the opponent take on e5, defend the knight with an awkward king move, or release the tension with ...f6-f5, making that pawn on e5 safe. }
11... f5
{ Black can lock up the center, stopping attacking the e5-pawn. But in that case, Black has no counterplay, the knight on g6 is extremely passive, and the g5 and d6-squares are weak. }
12. Qe2
{ It's not obvious to me, what should Black do next. Let's say, Black tries to develop. }
12... Be7 13. Bd2
{ We are preparing to castle queenside because the king is entirely safe: if Black tries to do anything on the b-file, we can just go b2-b3, shutting all that play down. Our last move was important because it took the a5-square under control − see the clickable with 13.Bg5 to understand why it's relevant.   13.Bg5  , it would be great to trade off  the dark-squared bishops, looking to invade on d6 with our knight. But, I'd rather not play this way  (just yet!)  due to  13...Bxc4!  14.dxc4  Bxg5  . Now, we cannot take with the knight, as that would leave  the e5-pawn hanging, while after  15.hxg5  Qa5+  , it seems a bit awkward to deal with the check. Black gets some activity, and I'd rather not give even that! }
13... O-O 14. O-O-O Rab8 15. g3
{ Having taken all the squares under control, we are threatening to go Ng5, attacking the h5-pawn, and likely just winning on the spot. Additionally, the Bg5! idea that we neglected earlier is now more dangerous. Black, of course, has no counterplay. The a6-bishop is passive. Trading on c4 only helps us, as it opens up the d-file and creates a weakness on d7. The g6-knight has no moves, while the e7-bishop is stuck too. The h5-pawn is weak and Black is just lost! }
*

