3... e6
{ This, alongside with  3...g6  ,  is one of Black's main choices, which became especially popular after Gelfand used it in his World Championship match versus Anand in 2012, having equalized convincingly in several games. Black's idea is  to play ...Nge7, preventing White from doubling the pawns by capturing on c6. Then, Black would like to play ...a7-a6, kicking the bishop out, and ...d7-d5, grabbing space in the center.  If White does take on c6, Black has to @@StartBracket@@we will see why@@EndBracket@@ take with the b-pawn. Then, Black tries to build a big center with ...d7-d5, or with ...d7-d6 and ...e6-e5. All in all, a very good variation for Black.   Luckily, after quite a bit of looking around, I found a very attractive, and somewhat surprising way of challenging this line. This discovery, because of its simplicity, is one of my favorite choices in this entire 1.e4 repertoire.   In this position, the two main choices White has have been  4.Bxc6  , doubling Black's pawns, and  4.O-O  . The former used to be the most popular move, but faded away 7-8 years ago. Instead,  4.O-O  picked up as the more frequent choice. Then, people discovered that after  4.O-O  Nge7  , instead of moves like  5.c3  or  5.Re1  , there was an interesting idea to play  5.d4  . That was very trendy for a while but also declined in popularity a bit. Our main choice will be @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp1p1ppp/2n1p3/1Bp5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.Bxc6  , but I will briefly mention  4.O-O  as well. }
4. O-O
{ This is the other major choice. White keeps the tension, continuing to make useful developing moves. }
4... Nge7
{ With this move, Black is preventing the doubled pawns for good. Next, would love to play ...a7-a6, kicking the bishop away. Here, most people try  5.Re1  and  5.c3  , but I would rather suggest a more forcing path. }
5. d4
{ This move has become popular about 4 years ago, and it is an interesting alternative variation for you to explore. White is trying to take advantage of the fact Black's development isn't great by opening up the center. White claims that with the knight on e7, which is blocking the kingside, Black won't be able to develop fast and comfortably.  Or, if that will happen, White will be able to use the time given to gain space or obtain some other advantages. The good news is that this variation is rather straightforward and easy to understand. Since it's an alternative suggestion, I hope you forgive me for annotating it pretty briefly. }
5... cxd4
{ Of course, Black needs to capture since d4-d5 was knocking on the door. } 6.
Nxd4
{ We take back. Now, Black needs to somehow get the kingside pieces out. Most people, by far, have chosen to do that with  6...Qb6  . However,  6...Ng6  has also been played a lot, especially by Gelfand in a ton of blitz and rapid games. }
6... Ng6
{ Black prepares ...Be7 and ...O-O, looking to finally finish development. } 7.
Be2
{ We retreat with the bishop in advance in order to prepare c2-c4 and prevent the bishop from getting stuck on the weird b5-square. }
7... Be7 8. c4 { We are very excited to grab more space in the center. } 8...
O-O 9. Nc3
{ This is a pretty standard Heghehog-style position, where Black's knight on g6 seems a bit misplaced. However, we have wasted a bit of time moving the bishop around to b5 and then back to e2. }
9... Nxd4
{ I think this immediate exchange, aimed at provoking the white queen to come out to the center of the board, is Black's best choice. If Black waits, you'll go Be3, getting ready to take on d4 with the bishop instead, which is a lot less awkward. }
10. Qxd4 b6
{ Black is getting ready to develop the bishop to the long diagonal. By doing that, Black is putting pressure on the e4-pawn, looking to make ideas like ...Bf6, ...Bxc3, and ...Bxe4 possible one day. Of course, we could always overprotect the e4-pawn with f2-f3, but doing that in this very position would lose a queen to ...Bc5. }
11. Be3 Bf6 12. Qd2 Bb7
{ Black creates a threat of taking on c3 and then on e4, giving up the bishop pair, but winning a pawn. }
13. f3
{ We reach a rather pleasant position. Black will go ...Qe7, ...Rfd8, and ...Rac8, claiming that although the position is slightly worse, the only weakness on d7 is pretty easy to defend and that Black doesn't have much of a space problem, since a pair of pieces have been traded already, and since the rest of the pieces are pretty well-placed.  I think both arguments  (ours and Black's)  are not contradicting each other in any way. We are slightly better, Black is solid, and doesn't have counterplay. This is a pleasant, easy, and risk-free outcome, so if you are after such a position, make sure to use this variation! I am, however, personally more drawn to the strategic complexity of the main line. }
*

