{ We take exactly with the knight, in order to either keep the bishop pair, or win a lot of time if Black takes our bishop. }
7... bxc6
{ Black is opening up the b-file, while also reinforcing the center. } 8. Be2
{ The bishop goes here in order to not block the d-file. } 8... d5
{ Black is by no means ready to start fighting for the center this way because the kingside pieces are very far from being developed. }
9. exd5 { Of course, we are immediately blowing the center apart! } 9... cxd5
10. c4
{ Black cannot keep the position under control, it's opening up too much. }
10... dxc4 11. Na3
{ Next, we'll take on c4 with the knight, winning a tempo, and will try to invade on d6 with Bf4 and Nd6. Also, ideas like Bf3 are about to prove rather annoying to deal with since the h1-a8 diagonal is weak. Additionally, the check from a4 could be hard to address too. All in all, Black is in dire straits, which is a fair outcome, given the opening was played very passively and Black failed to develop! }
