{ Of course, Black needs to capture since d4-d5 was knocking on the door. } 6.
Nxd4
{ We take back. Now, Black needs to somehow get the kingside pieces out. Most people, by far, have chosen to do that with  6...Qb6  . However,  6...Ng6  has also been played a lot, especially by Gelfand in a ton of blitz and rapid games. }
6... Qb6
{ Black is attacking the knight on d4, making us release the tension in the center. }
7. Nxc6
{ We take exactly with the knight, in order to either keep the bishop pair, or win a lot of time if Black takes our bishop. }
7... bxc6
{ Black is opening up the b-file, while also reinforcing the center. } 8. Be2
{ The bishop goes here in order to not block the d-file. } 8... Ng6
{ Black needs to get the kingside pieces out, of course, so this move, which unblocks the dark-squared bishop, makes perfect sense. }
9. c4
{ The position is fairly closed. For that reason, we'd love to take the time to grab more space in the center, taking the d5-square under more control, and preventing any future ...d7-d5 ideas. }
9... Be7 10. Nc3 O-O
{ White enjoys having more space, of course. And, the knight on g6 seems rather misplaced. However, we can hardly develop the queenside since the b2-pawn is under a fair bit of pressure. How do we address that problem? }
11. Rb1
{ We are overprotecting the b2-pawn so that the bishop can come out. Next, we'd love to develop it to e3 and play f2-f4, starting to develop an initiative on the kingside, and grabbing even more space. }
11... Qc7
{ Black could also start with  11...c5  ,  opening up the h1-a8 diagonal a bit and taking the d4-square under control. }
12. Be3 c5
{ Or, Black can do that here. The queen, of course, should have retreated, now or a move earlier, to avoid being in trouble on the g1-a7 diagonal, which could materialize with b2-b4, or Na4, or something else. }
13. f4
{ Time to grab space on the kingside, taking the e5 and g5-squares away from the black pieces. }
13... Bb7 { Black just keeps getting the pieces out. } 14. g3
{ Black doesn't have any counterplay since we firmly control the d5 and e5-squares. Black cannot ever make ...d7-d5 work. The move ...e6-e5 will only help us, allowing us to play f4-f5 and grab more space on the kingside. Black also cannot do anything on the queenside, for example on the b-file, because we can easily block that one with b2-b3.  I think White is somewhat better in this position, and this opinion seems to have some theoretical backing − for example, Caruana recently beat Swiercz from here, and many other strong players also used this variation. However, I do not necessarily think that it's extremely easy for White to make a lot of progress, and overall, I prefer the more complex strategic play. So, let's go back to our main line! But, this one is a very good alternative. 1-0  Caruana-Swiercz, Saint Louis 2021. }
