{ This is another interesting setup. It may seem as though White's play is very slow, but there is a fine point to it, which will be revealed soon. }
6... Nge7 { Black continues with the aforementioned plan. } 7. Be3 d6 8. d4
{ White did not get to play d2-d4 in one go, and had to lose a tempo. However, now White is not sacrificing the d4-pawn, which is good news for many players who prefer the more cautious and conservative approach to the opening play. }
8... exd4
{ This is the right reaction, but it has been played in less than one-third of the games that reached this position. }
9. cxd4 O-O 10. Nc3 Qb6
{ White has several interesting moves, but it's hard to claim an objective edge. }
11. dxc5 dxc5 12. Qd6 Nd4 13. Qxb6 Nxf3+ 14. gxf3 axb6
{ I believe, Black should be able to equalize here, even though the position is still not that simple, and White definitely can consider going here to play for a win. Black's queenside pawns are quite weak. The b6-pawn can at some point get attacked with Na4, and White also has an interesting idea of a2-a4-a5!, sacrificing the a-pawn but getting the c5-pawn, and reaching a position where the pieces would be tremendously active. }
15. a4 Be6 16. a5 Rxa5 17. Rxa5 bxa5 18. Bxc5 Bf6 19. Rd1
{ I could not prove to my computer that White is better, but I still don't think Black is doing great. It is, perhaps, one of those positions which Nigel Short described by saying 'It's not possible to claim that White is better, but it's also unfair to claim that Black had equalized'.  I decided to not elaborate too much on the possible deviations on our way to this line. I think you would easily refute all the other Black tries yourself, while it is also possible to discover several alternatives for White. This could be a very good practical choice for those who don't feel comfortable with the long-term pawn sacrifice in the main line, and I by no means think that Black's life is easy in this position, either. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "26) Rossolimo 3...g6"]
[Black "Rossolimo 3.Bb5 g6 − 5.c3 e5 Alternative 6.d3 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5
{ This move initiates what we know as the Sicilian Defense, the queen of the @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  Black openings. Alongside  1.e4  e5  , it's one of the two most sound ways of meeting 1.e4  from the theoretical standpoint. Black is fighting for the center, the d4-square, without creating a symmetrical position. This opening is extremely popular with players who want sharp, creative and fighting chess, and those who don't want to settle for symmetry, less space, or any other concessions. }
2. Nf3
{ In this Lifetime Repertoire, I have decided to go for the most ambitious way of playing versus the Sicilian Defense − the so-called Open Sicilian. Why would I do that? Isn't this a positional repertoire, and isn't the Open Sicilian known to be sharp and principled? Well, here is the deal.  It's a Lifetime Repertoire. I want this course to carry a theoretical punch, which most sidelines cannot offer. I was considering the Alapin, 2.c3, as well, but decided to not go down that route, because the isolated pawn positions, which often arise there, aren't to everyone's taste.  Interestingly enough, in many sharp-looking positions, there is a path to simplifications, which means that with sufficient theoretical knowledge, we are playing risk-free. It's not possible to get an advantage in every single theoretical variation of the Sicilian as White, and maybe not even in most.  
What we are doing instead is something different. We are striving to test our opponent's knowledge of typical ideas and forcing lines, and if Black is prepared brilliantly, we accept the fact Black should be able to defend. However, we want to play risk-free, looking to get the better endgames or positions with pleasant positional pressure in the middlegame! }
2... Nc6 3. Bb5
{ Unlike after every other move, like @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 2@@EndFEN@@  2...d6  or  2...g6  , this time, we would not want to open up the center. I know it might sound confusing since I just said 'We are going for the Open Sicilian'. Well, we are, but not this time. :@@EndBracket@@  The move @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp1ppppp/2n5/2p5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 2 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Bb5  initiates something known as the Rossolimo Variation, which used to be an interesting sideline. There is a story that in the 80s, Kasparov told one of the students of the Botvinnik school 'Kid, you cannot just give up your bishop on c6, this is not Ruy Lopez'. But, of course, a few years later, he would play  3.Bb5  himself.  Over the course of the years, especially as people realized that the Sveshnikov Variation was so good, the desire for an ambitious Anti-Open Sicilian kept growing, and as a result, the move  3.Bb5  has become one of the two main lines, alongside  3.d4  . We are looking to capture on c6 and ruin Black's pawn structure. However, we are not forced to, and in some setups, we would prefer to avoid the trade! In this chapter, we will be investigating Black's main move − @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp1ppppp/2n5/1Bp5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...g6  . }
3... g6
{ Black is fianchettoing the bishop, hoping it would be very useful on the long diagonal. Then Black will finish the kingside development with ...Nf6, or with ...e7-e5 and ...Nge7, blocking the bishop, but grabbing a fair share of space in the center. }
4. O-O
{ We are castling, preparing to play c2-c3, and d2-d4, occupying the center. Here is an important disclosure: back in 2020, I wrote a Yearbook article about this line, specifically @@StartFEN@@r1bqk1nr/pp1pppbp/2n3p1/1Bp5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQ1RK1 w kq - 2 5@@EndFEN@@  5.c3  . I am still a huge fan of this line, and of course, for the sake of the course, I'd focus on something very different than in the article: more sideline and idea discussions, and so on. However, I just want to disclose this chapter is to a large extent based on the article I had written at that time! }
4... Bg7
{ In this position, White has a large choice. Here is what's really interesting. Of course, the  5.Bxc6  positions are very popular. And so are the lines with  5.Re1  , which rose greatly in popularity after famous games like Mamedov-Dubov, and many others.  So what about the most natural way of playing, which is c2-c3 followed by d2-d4, occupying the center?  If you look at the database, you will see it's White's most popular continuation. However, this observation itself is a bit meaningless. This is because,  before 2019 or so, no top players liked using the  5.c3  line, as everyone thought  5.c3  Nf6!  is easy equality. But, around that time, the perception changed. So, 5.c3 is a very old, well-known amateur-level move, but a recent occurrence at the top level, and most findings and suggestions of this chapter are based on very recent games. }
5. c3
{ We are looking to take the entire center with d2-d4. Black can try to prevent that with ...e7-e5, or attack our pawn with ...Nf6. Some Black players also went ...a7-a6, provoking the exchange on c6, claiming that the inclusion of the move c2-c3 helps them, and not us, since it makes the d-pawn backward, forcing White to either exist with the weak pawn or to push d2-d4, which opens the position, supposedly helping the side with the bishop pair − Black. However, I doubt the soundness of that move, and the top players have mostly abandoned it after toying with it for a bit. }
5... e5
{ Obviously, it does not make sense to play  5...Nf6  if Black can resolve the opening problems with  5...e5  . Indeed, this move is extremely logical, as it seems to be  stopping d2-d4, which is White's main idea. Next, Black would love to develop the knight to e7, making sure to meet the trade on c6 by taking with the knight.  And if White goes Bxc6 now, after ...dxc6 the d-file will open up. As a result, the d3-square and/or White's d-pawn would become weak. All these things don't sound too great for us, do they? Fortunately, we have a very powerful solution here, which really questions Black's setup. }
6. d3
{ This is another interesting setup. It may seem as though White's play is very slow, but there is a fine point to it, which will be revealed soon. }
6... Nge7 { Black continues with the aforementioned plan. } 7. Be3 d6 8. d4
{ White did not get to play d2-d4 in one go, and had to lose a tempo. However, now White is not sacrificing the d4-pawn, which is good news for many players who prefer the more cautious and conservative approach to the opening play. }
8... cxd4 { This has been the main move by far, but it is simply wrong. } 9.
cxd4 O-O 10. d5
{ We are locking up the center, while also taking up all the space. } 10... Nb8
{ Now, we have a typical King's Indian type structure. However, without the c-pawns! That is, of course, a TREMENDOUS advantage for White, who always wants to play on the queenside, and open up the c-file with c2-c4-c5. Now, the c-file is open and the d6-pawn is weak.  This means White should be able to achieve the goals on the queenside much quicker than the opponent on the kingside with ...f7-f5-f4. But, at this very moment, Black is threatening to play ...f7-f5, ruining our pawn structure. We need to make sure we can meet that move with f2-f3! }
11. Nfd2
{ White's advantage is huge and undeniable and has scored a whopping 85% from this position, which is some classical King's Indian where White has got several extra tempi, as White has already opened up the c-file and won a few moves by kicking the black knight back to b8. }
11... f5 12. f3 { We reinforce the e-pawn. } 12... f4
{ Black's play is too slow. Let's see a few more logical moves. } 13. Bf2 g5
14. Nc3 Ng6 15. Be2
{ The bishop comes back home to make the ...g5-g4 break harder to accomplish, while also freeing up the b5-square for the knight. }
15... Nd7 16. Nb5
{ White is already double attacking the d6 and the a7-pawns, winning material by force and reaching a winning position. }
