5... a6
{ Black kicks out the bishop, claiming is not scared of us taking on c6, as the move c2-c3 weakened the d2-pawn and the d3-square. }
6. Bxc6 { We take anyway, claiming Black had wasted a tempo on ...a7-a6. } 6...
dxc6 7. d3
{ We protect the e4-pawn, while also taking the d3-square under control, preventing moves like ...Qd3. }
7... e5
{ Taking space in the center, while also blocking the bishop, is not a good idea this time. As usual, when the pawn is on a6, the c5-pawn and the b6-square get weaker. }
8. a4
{ The usual threat arises: playing a4-a5 and Na3-c4, looking to occupy the b6-square. And, of course, if we play a4-a5, the c5-pawn will become isolated, weak, and vulnerable to ideas like Be3, and Nfd2-b3. }
8... a5 { Black needs to stop the positional threat of a4-a5. } 9. Na3
{ The knight is coming to c4 exactly this way. Of course, it couldn't go to d2, as that move would have blundered the d3-pawn. }
9... Qc7 10. Be3
{ We keep making active moves, forcing the opponent to keep defending. } 10...
b6 11. Nc4
{ Next, we'll play Nfd2 and f2-f4, activating the f1-rook and the e3-bishop, while also removing Black's most useful central pawn. We are much better! Plus, to make things worse, Black cannot go ...Nf6 without losing the e5-pawn, while after ...Ne7, the knight would be very passive and have nothing to do. }
