dxc6 7. d3
{ We protect the e4-pawn, while also taking the d3-square under control, preventing moves like ...Qd3. }
7... Nf6
{ Black keeps developing. Next, ...Bg4 is on the agenda, trading down a bit. }
8. h3
{ We prevent that idea, taking the g4-square under control. Now, additionally, we can go Be3 without worrying about the ...Ng4 ideas. }
8... O-O 9. Qc2
{ With this move, we are overprotecting the e4-pawn, making any ...c5-c4 related pawn breaks impossible. And, of course, we are connecting the rooks. }
9... Qc7 10. Be3
{ Black is forced to go ...b7-b6, weakening the queenside even more, especially the c6-pawn. }
10... b6 11. d4 cxd4 12. cxd4
{ Now that the c6-pawn has become much weaker, it makes sense to build the center and undouble the black pawns! Next, we'll just go Nc3, Rfd1, and Rac1, continuing to improve our position. }
12... Bb7 13. Nc3 Rac8
{ White got a clear advantage and went on to beat his strong opponent. However, it's possible to improve on White's already impressive play. 1-0 Rohde-Granda Zuniga, New York 1987. }
14. b4
{ Black's c6-pawn is a target, the b7-bishop is stuck, and so is the one on g7. Next, we'll just improve the position with Rac1 and Rfd1, asking what Black wants to do, and it's not really obvious how to answer that! }
