dxc5 Bg4
{ Black needs to try getting counterplay against our center. In particular, the e5-pawn must be really annoying, so Black pins its only defender. Also, our opponent is short on space, so trades would help facilitate the defense. }
12. Nbd2 Nxd2 13. Qxd2
{ This would have been a nice improvement. It's not easy to decide to make this move over the board, as it seems as though we are letting the opponent weaken our king's shelter. We are ready to play Nd4 and f2-f4, reinforcing the center and holding on to the extra pawn. It's a great move! In particular, it's crucial to see that White keeps an extra pawn.   13.Bxd2?!  was chosen by Anand. It wasn't the best idea, and Black managed to survive. ½-½ Anand-Dubov, Wijk aan Zee 2020. }
13... Bxf3 14. gxf3
{ We are about to go f3-f4, holding on to the extra pawn, so Black's only principled idea is to bite the bullet. }
14... Bxe5 15. Bh6 { Now, the f8-rook and the e5-bishop are both hanging. }
15... Bg7 16. Bxg7 Kxg7 17. Rxe7 { White scoops up the e7-pawn! } 17... Qxc5
18. Rxb7
{ In the end, White is just a pawn up and has great chances to win the game. The arising position is totally one-sided, so we have no reasons to avoid it. }
