9... Qb6
{ Black is attacking the b5-bishop, pretty much forcing White to take. } 10.
Bxc6
{ Now, Black has a choice. The pawn recapture has been the main move by far, but Daniil Dubov, the main proponent of this line from the Black side, has also tried the queen recapture against Anand! }
10... bxc6 11. Qc1
{ Now, Black mostly takes on d4, but can try other continuations as well, of course. This is exactly what Dubov did against Caruana, and it's a very important game to study, despite the fact that Fabiano won a nice game, as Daniil is an extremely well-prepared player in the opening stage. }
11... Rb8
{ Daniil Dubov is not trading on d4, thus not letting White develop the knight to c3. Instead, first of all, he activates the rook. }
12. b3
{ We need to make this move in order to parry the threat to the b2-pawn. }
12... Qa5
{ Black puts pressure on the c3-pawn, making it hard for the b1-knight to come out, and is also creating a threat of ...Rxb3! followed by axb3 Qxa1. }
13. dxc5
{ White is entering a forcing sequence, which you will need to remember. The good news is that White scored 6.5/7 from this position, with the most games played in the last 3 years! }
13... Rxb3 { Black needs to take this pawn, or else will just be a pawn down. }
14. axb3 Qxa1 15. b4
{ I believe that everything was quite forced until this point, and now it's time to evaluate the arising position. The computer might be able to find counter chances for Black, but from the human perspective, the situation definitely looks very pleasant for White and extremely alarming for our opponent.  Why am I saying that? Well, the queen is not doing great on a1. Also, the g7-bishop is passive. At the same time, we have a nice outpost on d4, and if we manage to win the c6-pawn, then our pawn majority on the queenside will become incredibly dangerous. I believe that for those reasons, we should be definitely better. 1-0 Caruana-Dubov, Wijk aan Zee 2020. }
