[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "27) Sicilian 2...g6 − Model Games"]
[Black "Dalibor Stojanovic − John Paul Gomez, Tromsø 2014 "]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ In this game, we will see how White got a very pleasant endgame and converted his advantage thanks to a simple plan of trading all the pieces. }
1... c5 2. Nf3 g6
{ The so-called Hyper Accelerated Dragon. Black wants to keep the pawn on d7 for the time being, which is an important nuance: Black keeps the option of playing ...d7-d5 open, thus discouraging White from ever going for the sharpest lines with queenside castling.   Another detail is that Black avoids the Rossolimo Variation, which arises after  2...Nc6  3.Bb5  ,  but allows for the Maroczy Bind @@StartBracket@@where White plays c2-c4@@EndBracket@@, and for the variation that we are analyzing in the theoretical chapter. }
3. d4 cxd4 4. Qxd4
{ This is one of the most principled lines versus the Hyper-Accelerated Dragon, which requires Black to be knowledgeable and precise. Now, of course, Black's rook is hanging. Our queen might seem a bit vulnerable in the center, and to an extent, this is a correct observation: we have to be careful about moving it around. However, it is going to help support aggressive ideas like e4-e5!, kicking out the black knight, which would inevitably come to f6. }
4... Nf6 5. Nc3
{ White just keep developing. The knight now protects the e4-pawn, helping White ready to play e4-e5.   5.e5?!  Nc6  6.Qa4  Nd5  ,  Black's knight can easily retreat to c7 if needed. Unfortunately, the e5-pawn will be attacked with ...Bg7 and undermined with ...d7-d6. It's currently restricting the black pieces quite considerably, so it would be very advantageous for Black to undermine it and get rid of it. We shouldn't be allowing this to happen! }
5... Nc6 { Logically, Black chooses to develop the knight with tempo. } 6. Qa4
{ The queen retreats exactly here, and that is in order to pin the c6-knight, especially after Black goes ...d7-d6. Remember this move! Now, e4-e5 is a considerable positional threat, so ...d7-d6 is sort of forced. }
6... d6 7. e5
{ However, the move ...d7-d6, which is logical and nearly forced, has a downside. It makes the c6-knight pinned and allows us to start opening up the center to our benefit, trying to take advantage of that pin. }
7... dxe5 8. Nxe5
{ At this point, Black arrives at important crossroads and can choose between three logical continuations: the most popular one is  8...Bd7  , surrendering the bishop pair. The second one is  8...Qd4  , going for an inferior endgame with a bad pawn structure. The third one  (and the best one!)  is the daring  8...Bg7  , ignoring the threat and sacrificing the pawn in exchange for rapid development and open b- and c-files.  While seemingly complicated at first, most of the lines actually simply result in endgames with a slight advantage to White, in most cases. This is definitely what we are about to see in this game. }
8... Qd4
{ This move helps Black avoid forcing lines and memorization. However, it also comes at a cost: Black needs to accept the inferior pawn structure. }
9. Nxc6 Qxa4 10. Nxa4 bxc6
{ As you can see, the a7 and c6-pawns are now isolated and can be targeted pretty easily. Plus, we get some lovely outposts for our pieces, such as the c4 and c5-squares. }
11. Bd2
{ The bishop goes here in order not to be hurt by some ...Nd5 or ...Ng4. We are getting ready to castle queenside. }
11... Bg7 12. Be2
{ It seems more logical to me to develop the bishop to c4 in order to take the d5-square under control, and potentially put pressure on f7. But, apparently, White has a different idea. From e2, the bishop can go to f3, attacking Black's queenside pawns.   12.O-O-O  is the theoretical move I recommend. Black needs to somehow get the rook in the game, so everyone who got to this position chose to castle. But, as we can see, our king is much more active on c1 than the black one would be on g8!  12...O-O  13.Bc4  .  Next, we'll play f2-f3, restricting the black knight and preventing it from going to e4 or g4. Then, we'll place the rook on e1, looking to provoke ...e7-e6, which would weaken the dark squares, such as the one on d6, and limit the c8-bishop.    13...Nd5  ,  Black, logically, chose to improve the knight. And here, I'd like to suggest a logical novelty:  14.f3±  .  The idea of this move is not just about controlling the e4 and g4-squares. The problem is that Black cannot find a good square for the bishop! d7 and e6 are passive, and going there isn't safe, as it runs into Nc5. On the other hand, ...Bf5 now runs into g2-g4!, grabbing more space on the kingside and winning time.  So, Black ends up in a passive position with an inferior pawn structure and no counterplay. Next, we'll keep improving our position with Rhe1, Nc5, and will eventually play Bb3 and c2-c4, kicking out the best piece  (the d5-knight)  from the center. White is clearly enjoying life in this risk-free superior endgame! }
12... O-O 13. O-O-O
{ Of course, it's more reasonable to castle queenside than do anything else with the king. The rook is active on the open d-file, the king can easily join the game after some pieces come off, and helps protect the b2-pawn. }
13... Rb8
{ Understandably, Black wants to see the rook work on the semi-open file. However, it's extremely easy to address pressure on the b2-pawn, because the king and the knight are protecting it. At worst, we will just play b2-b3 if needed. }
14. Bf3 { Time to develop pressure on the isolated pawn on c6! } 14... Be6
{ Black is actually threatening to take the a2-pawn. We won't be able to cut the bishop off with b2-b3 and trap it, since Black's dark-squared bishop would e extremely helpful at controlling the b2-square.   14...Bb7?  is, of course, a horrible square for the bishop. For instance, after  15.Rhe1  e6  16.Nc5+-  ,  White's position is already absolutely dominant.  16...Ba8  17.c4!  It's also nice to take away the d5-square for the black knight. Black is literally paralyzed. Next, we go Bc3, and at some point find a good opportunity to invade on d7. }
15. b3 { Fortunately, that's an easy problem to address. } 15... Bd5
{ What you are about to see is a very instructive moment. What should White do? You certainly don't want to take on d5 and help Black fix the pawn structure, do you? Okay, what else? Cannot move the bishop away and lose the g2-pawn, right? Well, White's main advantage is on the queenside.  Not only are Black's pawns weak, but also, White can easily get a passed pawn there. Especially if the rooks get traded. So, although it seems surprising at first, White doesn't mind, at all, the idea of allowing Black to double the f-pawns! }
16. Rhe1 Rfe8 17. c4 Bxf3 18. gxf3
{ The doubled pawns cannot really be attacked. But, they control a lot of squares, such as e4 and g4. Next, White would like to improve the pieces with Kc2, Bc3, Nc5, and at some point, go Nd7, trading knights and invading on the 7th rank. What's interesting is that although Black has an extra pawn on the kingside, Black cannot really get a passed pawn. Our doubled pawns do a great job stopping any pawn advances! }
18... Nd7 19. Bc3
{ White is happy to trade almost any pieces since the pawn endgame will be easily winning. }
19... Rb7 20. Kc2 Bxc3 21. Kxc3
{ Looking at the white king is sheer pleasure! If the knights get traded, it can even come to d4 and c5 and be perfectly safe there! }
21... a5 22. Rd2
{ With this move, White is getting ready to double on the d-file. The goal, of course, would be to trade the knights and eventually invade on d7 or d8, hopefully coming after the weak queenside pawns with Rc8 or Ra8, for example. }
22... Kf8
{ Understandably, Black is hoping to bring the king closer to the center as well. This is a particularly useful idea because Black needs to cover the d7 and d8-squares to prevent the rooks from invading. }
23. Red1 Nf6 24. Nc5
{ Now, the knight is also occupying a wonderful position. } 24... Rc7
{ How would you like to improve White's position further? A small positional assignment! }
25. Nd7+
{ Of course! The knight trade is extremely beneficial because the opponent's knight was preventing the rooks from invading the 7th rank! }
25... Kg7
{ 25...Nxd7?  26.Rxd7  Rxd7  27.Rxd7  makes things even worse for Black since the king is so passive, and Black doesn't have a chance to consider taking ...exf6 to open the e-file and get some counterplay. }
26. Nxf6 exf6
{ Black desperately needs at least some activity. Opening up the e-file helps achieve that! }
27. Rd7 Rxd7
{ It seems to me that the rook trade is Black's critical mistake. The problem is that our king is much more active. So, essentially, the rooks need to fight both our rook and our king, which isn't really doable. And, of course, with fewer rooks on the board, it's much easier to get a passed pawn on the queenside and advance it, supporting it with the king, without fearing making our king too vulnerable.   27...Rcc8!  Actually, Black still had a chance to get some counterplay. To begin with, Black needed to keep both rooks.  28.Ra7  ,  of course, it would be very logical for White to try to attack the a7-pawn.  28...Re5!  However, Black can sustain it alive this way.  29.Rdd7  Rf8  .  The rook on the 5th rank is enormously active: it can defend the a5-pawn, and when the time is right, consider going after the pawns on f3 or h2! So, the position would have remained complex, but Black should be able to hold. }
28. Rxd7 Re2 29. Rd2
{ Of course, we don't need to allow the opponent's rook to harvest our pawns. Remember, due to the more active king and an extra passed pawn on the queenside, the pawn endgame would be easily winning! }
29... Re5
{ 29...Rxd2  30.Kxd2  f5  31.Kc3  Kf6  32.b4!  is an easy way of winning the pawn endgame with White. We get a passed pawn on the a-file that distracts the opponent's king and collects all the other pawns. A textbook example! }
30. b4
{ White easily creates a passed pawn on the a-file, which should allow to win fairly effortlessly. }
30... a4
{ The opponent, of course, tries to make it harder for White to create a passed pawn. But, although the effort is always commendable, it only delays the inevitable.   30...axb4+  31.Kxb4  and the a-pawn is unstoppable. }
31. Rb2 { The b-pawn is ready to run. } 31... Rf5 32. Kd4
{ 32.b5  would be even easier.  32...cxb5  33.cxb5  Rxf3+  34.Kc4  and the b-pawn cannot be stopped. }
32... Rxf3 33. b5 a3 34. Re2
{ The b-pawn, supported by the king, cannot be stopped. Please note the black king never became useful! }
34... Rf4+ 35. Kc5 cxb5 36. cxb5 Rf3 37. Rc2
{ Black resigned since the b-pawn is going to queen. I think the most instructive parts of this game are:  How easy and logical White's plan was. White just needed to trade the pieces! The fact that the doubled f-pawns weren't a problem. How important the difference in king activity turned out to be at the very end! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "27) Sicilian 2...g6 − Model Games"]
[Black "Zoran Jovanovic − Thomas Reich, Schwarzach 2014"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 g6
{ The so-called Hyper Accelerated Dragon. Black wants to keep the pawn on d7 for the time being, which is an important nuance: Black keeps the option of playing ...d7-d5 open, thus discouraging White from ever going for the sharpest lines with queenside castling.   Another detail is that Black avoids the Rossolimo Variation, which arises after  2...Nc6  3.Bb5  ,  but allows for the Maroczy Bind @@StartBracket@@where White plays c2-c4@@EndBracket@@, and for the variation that I have chosen to suggest. }
3. d4 cxd4 4. Qxd4
{ This is one of the most principled lines versus the Hyper-Accelerated Dragon, which requires Black to be knowledgeable and precise. Now, of course, Black's rook is hanging. Our queen might seem a bit vulnerable in the center, and to an extent, this is a correct observation: we have to be careful about moving it around. However, it is going to help support aggressive ideas like e4-e5!, kicking out the black knight, which would inevitably come to f6. }
4... Nf6 5. Nc3
{ White just keeps developing. The knight now protects the e4-pawn, helping White get ready to play e4-e5.   5.e5?!  5...Nc6  6.Qa4  Nd5  ,  Black's knight can easily retreat to c7 if needed. Unfortunately, the e5-pawn will be attacked with ...Bg7 and undermined with ...d7-d6. It's currently restricting the black pieces quite considerably, so it would be very advantageous for Black to undermine it and get rid of it. We shouldn't be allowing this to happen! }
5... Nc6
{ The most logical move  (and the best one)  is to develop the knight with tempo. Where should the queen retreat? }
6. Qa4
{ The queen retreats exactly here, and that is in order to pin the c6-knight, especially after Black goes ...d7-d6. Remember this move! Now, e4-e5 is a considerable positional threat, so ...d7-d6 is sort of forced. }
6... d6 7. e5
{ However, the move ...d7-d6, which is logical and nearly forced, has a downside. It makes the c6-knight pinned and allows us to start opening up the center to our benefit, trying to take advantage of that pin. }
7... dxe5 8. Nxe5
{ At this point, Black arrives at important crossroads and can choose between three logical continuations: the most popular one is  8...Bd7  , surrendering the bishop pair. The second one is  8...Qd4  , going for an inferior endgame with a bad pawn structure. The third one  (and the best one!)  is the daring  8...Bg7  , ignoring the threat and sacrificing the pawn in exchange for rapid development and open b- and c-files.  As I had promised, the lines we are about to see, while seemingly complicated at first, actually simply result in endgames with a slight advantage to White, in most cases. In this game, White gets a very pleasant middlegame. Although the queens stay on the board for a while, the position remains very simple and free of tactics. }
8... Bd7
{ Black solves the pin problem at a cost of giving up the bishop pair. } 9.
Nxd7 Qxd7 10. Be3
{ Now, White's goal is to simply finish development. White's main assets are the bishop pair and the pawn majority on the queenside. So, White wants to position the bishop on the long diagonal h1-a8, where it would be very useful, and hopefully trade the queens and rooks. If White manages to do that, will easily set the queenside majority in motion and get a nearly-winning endgame. }
10... Bg7 11. Rd1
{ Of course, it is very logical to take control of the only open file, while also winning a valuable tempo. }
11... Qc8
{ As we discuss in the theoretical chapter, the queen has several squares to retreat to. However, abandoning the c6-knight isn't a great idea, as we can always go g2-g3 and Bg2, deploying the bishop on a wonderful long diagonal and putting a lot of pressure on the opponent's knight. Secondly, if the queen goes to c7, it often gets hit with Nb5 or Bf4. So, Black's safest bet is to go to this passive-looking square, where the queen is safe at a cost of blocking the rook in the corner. }
12. Be2 O-O 13. O-O
{ White has finished development and is now ready to develop more pressure on the queenside with Bf3 and double the rooks on the d-file, hoping to swap them off. }
13... a6
{ This move is on one hand helpful to Black because it prepares the ...b7-b5 break, which is meant to grab more space on the queenside and somewhat free up Black's position. Also, with this move, Black takes the b5-square under control, preventing ideas like Nb5. However, it comes at a large positional cost.  First of all, Black weakens the b6-square. As a result, White can install the bishop on b6 and take the d8 square under control, which would be extremely beneficial if White wants to fight for the d-file. Secondly, if Black goes ...b7-b5, it would weaken the long diagonal h1-a8, which isn't optimal, because White is the only side with the light-squared bishop.   13...Rd8  was also tried versus the Croatian Grandmaster.  14.Rxd8+  Qxd8  15.Rd1⩲  .  In the arising position, we keep a standard advantage: the bishop pair, an extra pawn on the queenside, and the more active pieces. White went on to win another convincing game. 1-0 Jovanovic-Hujbert, Hungary 2017. }
14. Qh4
{ I prefer retreating to b3 instead. This is because we are playing on the queenside, our goal is to put pressure on the b7-pawn, take advantage of the weak b6-square, and so on. So, I do not believe White should be driving the pieces away from that part of the board. But, let's see how that worked out.   14.Qb3!  is the theoretical improvement I suggest in the course. The queen retreats in advance. Now, the positional threat is Na4-b6! Black has to stop that.  14...b5  ,  logically, Black continues the queenside expansion. However, after  15.a4⩲  ,  it turns out the pawn advance was a bit too optimistic. Now, the queenside pawns become targets for our pieces.  15...b4   15...Na5  leads to a very similar scenario as 15...b4, for example  16.Qb4  Nc6  17.Qc5  b4  18.Nd5  Nxd5  19.Qxd5↑  .  The b2-pawn is untouchable due to Bf3!, attacking the knight. It won't be able to retreat, as in that case, we'll take the a8-rook, winning an exchange. We still keep a lot of pressure on the opponent's queenside.  16.Nd5  ,  there is a threat to the b4-pawn and a threat of a fork on b6.  16...Nxd5  17.Rxd5↑  .  The black b4 and a6-pawns are weak. Our bishops can easily harass them. Plus, we have ideas such as Rc5 and Qc4, increasing pressure on the black knight, which is helping hold the queenside together. Additionally, once the rook goes to c5, the light-squared bishop can go to f3, increasing the pressure even more. I am afraid Black is in a very difficult situation, as it's not obvious how Black should be dealing with our piece activity and the pawn weaknesses. }
14... Qf5
{ Finally, Black activates the queen, attacking the c2-pawn and connecting the rooks. }
15. Rd2
{ Of course, White's goal remains the same: just trade all the rooks and queens, if possible. }
15... Rad8 16. Rfd1 Rxd2 17. Rxd2
{ Everything has been going according to plan! } 17... h5
{ Black takes the g4-square under control, potentially looking to go ...Ng4, harassing our bishop on e3 and opening up the one on g7, while also making an escape square for the king. }
18. h3 { Of course, White is happy to prevent ...Ng4. } 18... Rd8
{ Yes! Black is helping us by trading all the rooks! Thank you! } 19. Rxd8+
Nxd8 { The only important thing now is to not blunder the c2-pawn. } 20. Qb4
{ White doesn't mind giving up the c2-pawn, surprisingly. What is the idea? White is counterattacking the one on e7! }
20... Qd7
{ 20...Qxc2?  21.Qxe7  Ne6  22.Qxb7+-  is a disaster for Black, of course. }
21. Bf3
{ Time for this unopposed bishop to get into the game and become the most powerful piece! }
21... Nc6 22. Qb6
{ 22.Bxc6!?  would also be pretty interesting. Black cannot take with the queen as that hangs the e7-pawn, so Black must go for  22...bxc6  .  Although ruining the opponent's structure, and creating weaknesses on c6 and a6 is always pleasant, I feel that our bishop is worth more than that. }
22... Qc8 23. Nd5
{ A very lovely move. By making it, White unfreezes the queenside pawns, getting ready to set them in motion! }
23... Nxd5 24. Bxd5 e6 25. Bf3
{ As you can see, Black's queenside pieces are stuck since the b7-pawn is so fragile. White is ready to start advancing the queenside pawns, looking to create a passed pawn. For example, a good plan would be to play c2-c4, b2-b4, a2-a4, and then b4-b5. We trade a pair of pawns, take cxb5, so our passed pawn is as close to the edge as possible, and just run it up the board with a4-a5-a6. }
25... Be5 26. c3 { White takes the d4 and b4-squares under control. } 26... Bc7
27. Qb3
{ It's not obvious to me why not just keep the tension with  27.Qc5!  I would have definitely been tempted to do that. }
27... Qd7 28. Qd1
{ Although trading queens is a good thing overall, I feel White's few last moves haven't been the most active ones possible, which is something that allows Black to somewhat get out of the bind. }
28... Qe7
{ Black avoids a queen trade, fearing White's bishops and the pawn majority.  However, this move wastes time, which should have been used to improve the king!   28...Qxd1+  29.Bxd1  Kf8!  would have offered better chances to defend. The king is coming to d7 to help protect the queenside! }
29. Kf1 Bd6 30. Bxc6
{ A very interesting decision. Having enjoyed the bishop pair for a long time, White finally gives it up to ruin the opponent's pawn structure. }
30... bxc6 31. Qd3
{ The weaknesses need to be attacked! Please note the a6-pawn is impossible to defend with some move like ...Qb7, as it would drop the loose bishop on d6. }
31... Qd8 32. Qxa6
{ A free pawn! All White needs to do now is just making sure to not blunder some accidental perpetual or back-rank mate, and then run the pawn with a2-a4-a5, Qb7, a5-a6-a7-a8. :@@EndBracket@@ }
32... Bc5 { Black cheekily threatens checkmate in one with ...Qd1. } 33. Qe2
Bxe3 34. Qxe3
{ White's king is perfectly safe, which is very important in the queen endgames. The game went on for another two dozen moves, but eventually, White convincingly made use of the passed pawn. To me, it's very impressive to see how simple White's plan was: all White needed to do was trade the rooks. Once that happened, the bishops ended up putting so much pressure on the opponent's queenside! }
