[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "28) Sicilian 2...d6 − Model Games"]
[Black "Tsvetan Stoyanov − Gabriela Antova, Sofia 2020 "]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ This game is a showcase of how difficult it is to tolerate the powerful knight on d5. And, it shows that kicking the knight out at a cost of weakening the pawn structure is not very appealing either! }
1... c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Qxd4 Nc6 5. Qe3
{ I like the idea of placing the queen on e3. Why here? It protects the e4-pawn and it doesn't block the d-file. White can castle and place the rook there, preparing to bother the opponent with e4-e5 or c4-c5 at some point. The c1-bishop gets blocked, unfortunately. However, this is not a problem because we want to develop it to b2. }
5... Nf6 6. Be2 g6 7. O-O Bg7 8. c4
{ By playing this move, White acquires much better control of the b5 and d5-squares. That's a very helpful thing because Black often wants to grab space on the queenside with ...b7-b5 or free up the center with ... d6-d5, getting rid of the powerful e4-pawn. Furthermore, White's last move helps prevent counterplay on the c-file: for example, if the black rook goes to c8, it won't ever be able to capture the c3-knight, and so on. }
8... Bg4
{ Since h2-h3 hasn't been played yet, Black is making this move right away. Why?  Black has less space, so trading pieces is a common strategy that decreases space-related problems. By trading off the f3-knight, Black gets a better ability to control the d4-square. Black doesn't need this bishop. One of White's dream scenarios in this pawn structure is ending up with a knight versus Black's light-squared bishop because that piece won't have anything useful to do. }
9. Rd1
{ This cunning move sets up a small trap. Black would like to just castle, but doing so here would be a pretty terrible idea. }
9... Nd7
{ Black plays this move in order to block the d-file, discouraging any x-ray problems, like the c4-c5 or e4-e5 breaks, while also opening up the g7-bishop, and preparing to install the knight on e5 or c5.   9...O-O  10.e5!  creates a ton of problems on the d-file, of course! }
10. Nc3 Bxf3
{ Sooner or later, Black has to surrender the bishop pair. Or else, what is the bishop doing on g4? The downside is that Black has spent two moves to trade off the white knight, which moved once only. And, by doing so, helped the opponent bring the bishop to f3. It's not that useful here, but if White were to go e4-e5 or c4-c5, opening up the center, the bishop could suddenly turn out very useful on the h1-a8 diagonal. }
11. Bxf3 O-O 12. Rb1
{ This move is rather important. White would like to play b2-b3 and develop the bishop to b2, to the long diagonal. For that reason, White wants to remove the rook off the long diagonal before weakening it with b2-b3. Or, White could consider playing b2-b4, grabbing space on the queenside. }
12... a6 13. Be2
{ Given Black played ...Nd7, the e4-e5 and c4-c5 ideas became less likely to happen, so White moves the bishop back. This is done in order to protect the c4-pawn, and potentially free up the path for our f-pawn. It could go to f3, overprotecting the e4-pawn, or to f4, grabbing space on the kingside. But, most likely, first White will just get the c1-bishop out. }
13... Rc8
{ Black continues making natural developing moves. The rook is going to the c-file, potentially x-raying the c3-knight and hinting at some ...b7-b5 along the line. }
14. b3
{ White follows up with the intended plan of preparing Bb2. Black doesn't have any counterplay at the moment, of course. }
14... Qa5
{ Black gets the queen out, connecting the rooks. This queen placement is very standard in the Maroczy Bind-type positions. It wouldn't want to go to c7 because it runs into Nd5. Going to b6 isn't very attractive for the same reason. }
15. Bb2 Qc5 16. Qh3
{ I am not sure if I like this queen's position since besides attacking the knight on d7 and taking a look at the c8-rook, it's not doing much there.   I would like to suggest  16.Qd2  ,  which keeps the queens on the board and the d4-square under better control. Next, we can play a2-a3 and b3-b4, expanding on the queenside, and kicking the queen out. Black doesn't have the ...b7-b5 or ...d6-d5 break, and the position is just very unpleasant and passive. }
16... Nde5
{ This is a very instructive mistake. It might seem as though the knight is now placed actively, however allowing the white knight to effortlessly land on d5 is something Black would greatly regret.   16...Nf6!  was necessary, discouraging the white knight from going to d5 by attacking the e4-pawn. However, White is still better, of course. We could switch to the plan of grabbing space on the queenside by going a2-a3 and b3-b4, for example. }
17. Nd5
{ Now, White is ready to play b3-b4, rapidly advancing the queenside pawns. Of course, there could also be a threat of b3-b4 and b4-b5!, kicking out the c6-knight and winning the pawn on e7! Black could always consider kicking our knight out with ...e7-e6, but that would greatly weaken the d6-pawn and cannot be recommended unless it's an extreme measure. }
17... e6 18. b4 { White is able to justify this move tactically. } 18... Qa7
{ 18...Nxb4??  19.Nxb4  Qxb4  20.Bxe5+-  wins a piece, of course, since now the queen is hanging. }
19. Ne3 { Now, the d6-pawn is a clear target. } 19... b5
{ Black is undermining the c4-pawn, which is typically a desirable plan while fighting the Maroczy Bind since the c4-pawn provides White with a considerable amount of spatial advantage. However, in this position, it just gives White a powerful passed pawn on the queenside and is therefore a wrong idea. }
20. cxb5 axb5 21. a3
{ White chooses to avoid a pawn trade, instead reinforcing the structure on the queenside. Objectively speaking, White is still much better, but I fail to understand why not take the more direct path. But, of course, with the b5 and d6-pawns so weak, and the bishop pair in hand, White retains an obvious positional advantage.   21.Bxb5!  Qxa2  22.Bf1!  was even better, getting ready to simply advance the b-pawn! Of course, it's not hanging.  22...Nxb4??  23.Bxe5  Bxe5  24.Rxb4+-  and White wins a loose piece. }
21... Qb8 22. f4
{ Time to push Black's pieces back! This move is closely associated with White's next one. }
22... Nd7 23. e5
{ The problem is that Black's knight on d7 is loose, so the position must be closed down. }
23... d5
{ However, now there are a few problems. First of all, the position is just bad overall. The b5-pawn is weak, the g7-bishop is dead. White can go Rbc1, then Qf3-f1, start attacking the b5-pawn, trade all the rooks, and likely get a winning endgame. However, secondly, White has a promising tactical sequence! What is it? }
24. Nxd5
{ Yes! White is trying to take advantage of the queen position. Black cannot take back since that'd hang the knight on d7! }
24... Ndxe5
{ Luckily, Black can get the pawn back. However, this exchange has helped considerably open things up, which is great for the side with the bishop pair.   24...exd5  25.Qxd7  is a completely winning position, of course, since White has an extra pawn, the bishop pair, and the much more active pieces. }
25. Ne3
{ Unfortunately for the black knight, it doesn't have too many places to go to. }
25... Nc4
{ So, Black needs to place it on a square that is hardly controlled. Luckily, this doesn't result in a loss of a pawn, however, it changes the position in a manner that heavily favors White. }
26. Bxg7 Kxg7 27. Bxc4 bxc4 28. Nxc4 Qxf4
{ Black managed to keep the material equality, but now White has two connected passed pawns! }
29. Nd6 Rc7 30. Qc3+
{ And, Black is facing a pin on the c-file! Next, White is going to follow up with b4-b5, winning the pinned knight. }
30... Qe5
{ So, Black must offer a queen trade. However, that doesn't help solve the pin problem. }
31. Rbc1 Nd4
{ Black tries the last trick, as the endgame is completely lost. However, that doesn't help much either.   After  31...Qxc3  32.Rxc3  ,  Black is inevitably losing the knight to Rdc1 or to b4-b5. }
32. Qxc7 Ne2+ 33. Kh1
{ Black resigned since after taking on c1, White still keeps the extra piece. As you can see, things escalated a bit too fast and unexpectedly. However, White was better throughout the entire game, and once the knight landed on d5, Black had a very difficult choice between defending a bad passive position, where the knight needed to be tolerated, or weakening the pawn structure with ...e7-e6. }
