[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "28) Sicilian 2...d6 − Model Games"]
[Black "Vitaly Boiarintsev − Tolegen Nukin, Pavlodar 2019"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6
{ Interestingly enough, this game saw a  2...e6  move order, but soon transposed into the line we play after  2...d6!  3.d4  cxd4  4.Qxd4  Nc6  5.Bb5  Bd7  is the way we typically arrive at this position, of course. }
3. Nc3 { 3.c4  is the way we play versus this variation, obviously. } 3... d6
4. d4 cxd4 5. Qxd4
{ I haven't seen a lot of people play this way − neither with Black, combining ...d7-d6 and ...e7-e6 so early, nor with White, playing Qxd4 versus the ...e7-e6 lines! But, of course, now we just transpose to the variation we study in detail after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq c6 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.Nf3  d6  . }
5... Nc6 6. Bb5
{ White could retreat with the queen, but it's even more promising to pin the knight. }
6... Bd7 { Black unpins, forcing White to either retreat or trade on c6. } 7.
Bxc6 Bxc6
{ In exchange for the bishop pair, White gets a powerful centralized queen, rapid development, and an opportunity to put pressure on the d6-pawn/ }
8. Bg5
{ Of course, White dreams of the bishop trade on e7. If that happened, the d6-pawn would become extremely weak and Black would give up one of the advantages − the bishop pair. }
8... Nf6 9. O-O-O
{ Of course, it's very natural to castle queenside. The king is safe on c1. And, very importantly, our rook is getting ready to work on the d-file, either by putting pressure on the weakish d6-pawn or after e4-e5, which will help us open that file! }
9... Be7
{ After  9...h6  ,  the capture on f6 is a much more tempting idea than a move ago.  10.Bxf6  Qxf6  11.e5!  The position is opening up, and Black absolutely isn't ready for that. For instance, after  11...dxe5  12.Nxe5  ,  we are threatening to take on c6 and checkmate Black with Qd7. There is hardly any defense. I mean, Black can avoid getting checkmated, but the position is awful.  12...Qe7  13.f4  ,  we are about to open the central files with Rhe1 and f4-f5, and Black cannot get any pieces out. }
10. Rhe1
{ By keeping the tension and bringing the rook in the center, White is making the ideas of e4-e5 more dangerous.   ➢  10.Bxf6  would be a great move if we could force Black to take with the pawn, weakening the kingside structure. However, Black can offer a temporary pawn sacrifice.  10...Bxf6!  11.Qxd6  Qxd6  12.Rxd6  and White might feel happy for a moment, as we nearly won a pawn, but that's not true, of course.  12...Bxc3!  13.bxc3  Bxe4⩱  .  White just ruined the pawn structure for no reason.   ➢  10.e5  dxe5  11.Nxe5  Qxd4  12.Rxd4  Bxg2!  doesn't give White anything yet, as I explain in the theoretical chapter. We need to wait before opening up the center. }
10... O-O 11. e5
{ This principled move is immediately opening up the center. Now, the problems related to the c6-bishop's active position are not nearly as relevant as in the clickable variation with @@StartFEN@@r2qk2r/pp2bppp/2bppn2/6B1/3QP3/2N2N2/PPP2PPP/2KR3R w kq - 4 10@@EndFEN@@  10.e5  because there are still queens on the board, and the king is already on g8, which creates a few extra tactical possibilities. }
11... dxe5
{ Black has almost no choice but to open up the d-file and trade queens. } 12.
Nxe5 Qxd4
{ 12...Qc7  was also chosen by some strong players, but it doesn't solve Black's structural problems, as after  13.Qc4!  Rac8  14.Nxc6  Qxc6  15.Qxc6  Rxc6  16.Ne4  ,  we get the same position as in the game. }
13. Rxd4
{ The g2-pawn is untouchable, as we have learned in the theoretical chapter. Of course, White is dreaming of capturing the bishop on c6, depriving the opponent of the bishop pair and spoiling the pawn structure, guaranteeing a considerably superior endgame. }
13... Rfc8
{ Black needs to make sure to avoid the upcoming structural damage after Nxc6. And must go here EXACTLY with the f8-rook, because otherwise, it could end up hanging on f8 in some lines − see the  13...Rac8?!  variation in the theoretical chapter to better understand what I am referring to.   ➢  13...Bxg2?  14.Nd7!  is a huge problem for Black, whose rook is under attack. The point is that after  14...Rfd8??  15.Bxf6  Bxf6  16.Nxf6+  gxf6  17.Rxd8+  Rxd8  18.Rg1+-  ,  we are able to win the piece, as the g-file is open. This would not be the case if we didn't wait for Black to castle before opening up the g-file!   ➢  13...Rac8  as I explain in the theoretical chapter, this is a much better move. Please explore theory to understand why, let's not repeat ourselves here. }
14. Nxc6 Rxc6 15. Ne4
{ White is hoping to capture the knight on f6, double Black's pawns, and get a more pleasant endgame. Also, it would be beneficial for us to make the f6-knight disappear because in that case, our rook would be able to invade on d7 in the future. }
15... Rac8
{ In most games, and in this one as well, Black made this natural move. After all, isn't it logical to threaten the c2-pawn, win a tempo, and get the last piece in the game? However, this move isn't great, as we are about to discover.   15...e5!  is the unnatural theoretical improvement. In my opinion, this is Black's only chance to equalize in this variation, as I explain in the theoretical part! }
16. Re2
{ White easily stops the threat to the c2-pawn. Now, the upcoming exchange on f6, which damages Black's pawn structure, is inevitable. }
16... Rc4
{ Black is trying to trade a pair of rooks to facilitate the defense, but this does not seem to be helping. Why so? Because the more pieces we trade, the more valuable our better structure @@StartBracket@@once we take on f6@@EndBracket@@ and the extra pawn on the queenside become! }
17. Nxf6+ Bxf6 18. Bxf6 gxf6 19. Red2
{ White is much better in this position. Why so?  We have an extra pawn on the queenside. This is a very dangerous pawn structure in the endgame since it's much easier to create a passed pawn on the queenside, as the black king would have a hard time stopping it.  We own the d-file. This means the black king is cut off from the queenside, which reinforces the previous point, and that we are about to trade a pair of rooks and invade on the 7th rank.  Our king is much better suited for the upcoming endgame activity. Once we trade the rooks, we can go b2-b3, c2-c4, Kc2-c3, and so on, using the monarch to help support the pawn advance.  The black pawn structure on the kingside isn't great.  
You can immediately recall the famous game of Rubinstein, where he brought the king to h3, and a recent example Salem-Kramnik. If you don't know what I am referring to, make sure to look these examples up, they are fascinating! It likely won't matter in this position, as the structure isn't symmetrical, but the h-pawn can easily become a target for our rook as well, if the black king walks too far away from it, say to e7. }
19... Rxd4 20. Rxd4
{ A pair of rooks is gone. Of course, right now, we have a threat of invading on the 7th rank. Black can easily stop that threat. However, the main nuance of the fact that the rooks are gone is that now the white king can easily get active! }
20... Rc7 21. Kd2
{ As promised, the king is getting in the game. The goal is to start advancing the extra passed pawn on the queenside, using the king to help make that plan happen smoothly and easily. }
21... f5
{ Black made this move in order to make room on f6 for the king, preparing to go ...Kg7-f6, maybe even looking to bring it to e5! The problem is that although the king could go to f8-e7, it would be cut off from the queenside, unable to help stop White's c-pawn advance! }
22. c4 { White is continuing the plan, of course. } 22... Kg7 23. Kd3 Kf6 24.
b4 { Next, White would like to go c4-c5, Kc4, b4-b5, Rd6, and c5-c6! } 24... e5
{ With this move, Black occupies a bit of space in the center, taking the d4-square under control. However, it weakens the d5-square and the 6th rank. White can play Rd6+ and cut off the king not just on the d-file, but on the 6th rank as well! }
25. Rd6+ Ke7 26. c5
{ Black is absolutely helpless and, of course, cannot create a passed pawn on the kingside, as the pawn structure doesn't support that aspiration. If Black waits, White goes Kc4, b4-b5, Kd5, and c5-c6, effortlessly getting a decisively valuable passed pawn. }
26... Rd7
{ Unable to wait, desperate for a change, Black tries going for a pawn endgame. However, it turns out the endgame is completely lost. That's not very surprising, given that White has a passed pawn and that the king is much more active! }
27. Rxd7+ Kxd7 28. Kc4 Ke6
{ Black might be hoping to be able to play ...f5-f4, then ...f7-f5, ...e5-e4, and ...e4-e3, actually making some progress with the kingside pawns. However, that's not meant to happen! }
29. g3
{ If Black goes ...f5-f4, we take, and our f-pawn will easily stop the doubled isolated f-pawns. If Black ever goes ...e5-e4, a passed pawn will never be created. }
29... h5 30. b5
{ White, on the other hand, can easily keep making progress. One problem Black has is that at some point, the king will need to move away, which will enable our king to come to d5 and support our passed pawn, while also starting to hunt the opponent's kingside pawns! }
30... h4 31. gxh4
{ Of course, taking this pawn is an easy decision: Black cannot really get a passed pawn in the center, especially with our king so close to the e- and f-files. However, now White wins easily by running the c- and h-pawns up the board simultaneously. Black is unable to stop both! }
31... f4 32. h5 e4 33. h6 e3 34. fxe3 f3 35. Kd3
{ Black resigned, as it's obvious that either of our passed pawns will queen within a few moves. As you can see, this rook endgame turned out incredibly difficult for Black to defend! And, we are nearly guaranteed to get it straight out of the opening, unless Black is well-prepared. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "28) Sicilian 2...d6 − Model Games"]
[Black "Anton Demchenko − Mikhail Linker, Sochi 2018"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ In this game, we will see how White built the Maroczy Bind and his master-level opponent collapsed within 10 moves! }
1... c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Qxd4 Nc6 5. Qe3
{ As we see throughout the theoretical chapter, the white queen retreats to this square, from where it is protecting the e4-pawn. White would like to install the pawn on c4, develop with Be2, O-O, play h2-h3 to restrict Black even more, and develop the knight to c3.  Black will likely fianchetto the dark-squared bishop, so White will want to make sure the long diagonal is safe and play Rb1, b2-b3, Bb2, and Rfd1. If White achieves that standard setup, would have a somewhat more pleasant position due to the spatial advantage.   However, as I explain in the theoretical chapter, there is a problem. The issue is that compared to the @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp2pppp/3p4/8/3QP3/5N2/PPP2PPP/RNB1KB1R b KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...a6  and  4...Bd7  lines, Black is literally a tempo up, as no move has been spent defending against an idea we have no intention of using anyway. So, we might not be able to accomplish everything we want. }
5... g6
{ Of course, the long diagonal is where the bishop belongs.   5...e6  ,  Black can also develop the bishop to e7, but it won't be doing much from that square. Also, the c8-bishop gets blocked and the d6-pawn becomes weak. White can easily set up the Maroczy Bind and get a very pleasant advantage, for example  6.Be2  Nf6  7.c4  Be7  8.O-O  O-O  9.Nc3±  ,  with a typical pleasant position, where Black has no active play, a passive bishop on e7, a weakish pawn on d6, and a misplaced knight on c6. If Black wanted a Hedgehog setup, the knight needs to be on d7, as I explain in the chapter on structures and ideas. }
6. Be2 Bg7 7. O-O Nf6 8. h3
{ This slow prophylactic move is the move most people have made, and for a good reason. The point is that White needs to always worry about ...Ng4 in some shape or form. For example, it's nice to go Rd1 and threaten x-rays on the d-file with e4-e5, but that move is never possible due to ...Ng4! double attacking the queen and that pawn. Also, at some point, there could be ideas of ...Ng4 followed by ...Qb6, putting pressure on the f2-pawn.   8.Rd1  O-O  9.c4  ,  if White tries playing without h2-h3, will quickly regret it.  9...Ng4!  10.Qd2  Qb6!  and we are forced to make extremely ugly and passive moves like Rf1, which, of course, is not appealing at all. }
8... O-O 9. Rd1
{ By bringing the rook to the d-file, White is not just making a useful positional move but is also creating an x-ray threat of e4-e5!, forcing the opponent to react in some awkward way, such as moving the queen to c7, where it could be attacked with Nb5 or Nd5, or going back with ...Nd7, blocking the queenside pieces. }
9... Qc7
{ On this square, the queen is a bit misplaced because we will inevitably go Nc3 and Rc1 at some point, and then moves like Nd5 would be very unpleasant for Black to deal with. }
10. c4
{ White goes for the Maroczy Bind structure, taking the d5 and b5-square under better control.   10.Nc3  ,  however, unlike situations where Black goes ...a7-a6 or ...Bd7, wasting a tempo, I don't feel as though we have enough time to build the Maroczy Bind convincingly, so I prefer just developing the knight, giving up on the dream of spatial advantage. }
10... Bd7
{ This is a very passive move. White has a long-lasting advantage, created by space, so Black needed to do something urgent − see the  10...Qb6!  suggestion. However, now, White is on time to stabilize the position and get a large positional advantage with very simple moves.   10...Qb6!?  is a very interesting idea, which I am a bit worried about. The point is that Black is not afraid of the queen trade, as after  11.Qxb6  axb6  ,  Black opens up the a-file and threatens the e4-pawn.  12.Nc3  Nd7!  Black is threatening to take on c3, ruining the white pawn structure on the queenside. We can avoid that, but Black still keeps a lot of counterplay.  13.Nd5  Nc5!  The e4-pawn is in danger. I am afraid this is too much counterplay for my taste! }
11. Nc3
{ The a1-h8 diagonal is a bit loose. So, White has to make sure to not play a move like b2-b3, which weakens the diagonal, allowing for a ... Nxe4-type tactic. First, White needs to go Bd2 and Rac1. Or Rb1, walking the rook away from danger, and then b2-b3 and Bb2, deploying the bishop to a great place on a long diagonal without exposing to tactical threats. }
11... Rac8 12. Bd2
{ The Russian Grandmaster chooses to develop this way, which is also fair. At some point, White can consider moving the queen away and deploying the bishop on e3, if he'd like. }
12... b6
{ It's understandable that Black wants to avoid danger on the c-file, so he is making room for the queen on b7. However, this move is a very suspicious one, because it weakens the c6-square. This means White is going to find the idea of playing Nd5, trading knights, capturing cxd5, and getting an outpost on c6 much more beneficial and attractive. }
13. Rac1
{ For now, White keeps making the most logical developing moves. Problems on the c-file are building up! }
13... Qb7 14. b3 { It's always useful to overprotect the c4-pawn. } 14... Rfd8
15. Nd5
{ Time to take action! Black cannot really avoid a trade since White can always go Bc3, putting more pressure on that knight on f6, threatening to ruin the opponent's pawn structure. }
15... Nxd5 { However, now the e7-pawn becomes too much of a problem. } 16. exd5
{ This move is also very strong because the e7-pawn is a considerable weakness.   16.cxd5  would be also very attractive, creating an outpost on c6. However, this path would be even more effective if the light-squared bishops were gone, because in that case, Black wouldn't be able to protect the c6-square nearly as easily. So, White chooses another path. }
16... Ne5 17. Nd4
{ No trades! White is threatening to play f2-f4, all of sudden trapping the opponent's knight in the very center of the board! Even if White couldn't trap the knight, it would still be great to kick it all the way back. }
17... Be8 18. Bc3
{ White isn't rushing with material gains. However, having overprotected the d4-knight, is ready to play f2-f4, winning the e7-pawn after the knight has to leave. There is no defense!   18.f4!  Nd7  19.Nc6!  is also a wonderful idea. White is just winning an exchange actually! }
18... b5
{ Black tries some desperate tricks, but there is no counterplay to be found. }
19. cxb5
{ The knight is now going to be able to enjoy the outpost on c6 forever!   19.Nxb5  Bxb5  20.cxb5  is also completely winning, of course. }
19... Rc5 20. f4
{ The knight is forced to leave, then ours comes to c6, winning the e7-pawn or the rook on d8. The game is already over! Black tried some desperate piece sacrifice, but of course, eventually still lost without ever having any chances. As you can see, although the position after @@StartFEN@@r1b2rk1/ppq1ppbp/2np1np1/8/4P3/4QN1P/PPP1BPP1/RNBR2K1 w - - 3 10@@EndFEN@@  10.c4  was objectively balanced, a strong master-level player was able to turn it into a loss in just 10 moves! }
