[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "29) Sicilian 2...e6 − Model Games"]
[Black "Sergei Rublevsky − Kirill Bryzgalin, Ilyumzhinov Cup Internet 2006"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. c4 Nc6 4. Nc3 d6
{ With this move, Black indicates he doesn't mind the opponent building a Maroczy Bind structure versus the Hedgehog setup. }
5. d4
{ Of course, White is happy to open the center and take space. It's valuable to mention that Black can no longer annoy or bother us by going ...Bb4 at some point, pinning the knight! }
5... cxd4 6. Nxd4 Nf6 7. Be2
{ First, White is focused on finishing development, and so is the opponent. In a few moves, once all the pieces came out, we will discuss the plans. }
7... Be7 8. O-O O-O 9. Be3
{ Now that some basic development moves have been played, let's discuss the plans. White has a lot more space. Black, in the Hedgehog positions, typically strives to play ...a7-a6, ...b7-b6, ...Bb7, ...Nbd7, ...Qc7, ...Rac8 and ...Rfd8, harmoniously setting all the pieces on the last two files, and controlling the 5th rank with the pawns − that's why the opening is called this way, referring to the pawns on the 6th rank as the hedgehog's needles. However, there is a problem: Black's knight is already on c6. This is bad because of several reasons:  the b7-bishop would be blocked; the knight on d7 could protect the b6-pawn and the f6-knight, and on c6, it cannot; if Black places the queen on c7, with the knight on c6, Black would often run into the typical Rc1-Nd5! temporary knight sacrifice; another issue Black has is that ...b7-b6 cannot be played now or anytime soon, as that'd hang the knight.  
We can try to advance on the kingside with f2-f4, Qd2, Kh1, Rg1, and g2-g4. The more positional plan would be playing f2-f3, reinforcing the e4-pawn, and then a2-a3, b2-b4, and Nb3 obtaining a dominant position on the queenside. That's the plan I like better, as this repertoire is not about going crazy. :@@EndBracket@@ }
9... a6
{ This move is useful because it covers up the b5-square. This way, Black achieves a few things:  Black no longer needs to worry about Ndb5 at some point, which could create pressure on the d6-pawn; no longer needs to worry about Ndb5 after ...Qc7, which wins a tempo and harasses the queen; at some point, Black hopes to be able to push ...b7-b5. }
10. Rc1
{ White just keeps developing. One very unfortunate nuance about Black's setup is that the knight is on c6. This is bad for a few reasons, namely:  Black cannot play ...b7-b6 and ...Bb7, as that would obviously hang the knight; if Black does go ...b7-b6 somehow, say after ...Bd7, that pawn might be weak and vulnerable to ideas like Na4, Qb3, and so on. Had the knight been on d7, it wouldn't be the case, as it would be protecting the pawn at all times; from d7, the knight could jump to c5 and attack the e4-pawn. }
10... Nxd4
{ It's logical for Black to trade a pair of knights. First of all, Black has less space, and secondly, as I had explained, the knight was awkwardly placed, causing Black a hard time with the c8-bishop's development. }
11. Bxd4 Bd7
{ 11...b6  seems to make sense as well, reaching the flexible Hedgehog setup, taking the c5-square under better control, and preparing to go ...Bb7. However, the move in the text is a better one because it doesn't weaken the c6-square. In this structure, on the other hand, at some point, White can start dreaming of occupying the weak c6-square with a piece. For instance, if somehow Black's e-pawn disappeared or moved, White went Nd5 and took cxd5, then White would be able to invade on c6. }
12. f3
{ First, White overprotects the e4-pawn, while also making room on f2 for the bishop, just in case. }
12... Bc6 13. a3
{ White is getting ready to play b2-b4, gaining space on the queenside. However, White prefers to slowly prepare it, instead of rushing with b2-b4 right away. The reason is that White wants the b4-pawn to be protected so that Black cannot ever go ...d6-d5 and suddenly attack it with the bishop! }
13... Qd7
{ An ideal setup for Black would be ...Rac8, ...Rfd8, and ...Qc7-b8, but it’s not possible to reach it comfortably. Placing the queen on c7 with a piece on c6 runs into the Nd5 theme. At the same time, going for ...Qb8, ...b7-b6, ...Qb7, ...Rac7 and ...Qb8 again is just extremely slow. }
14. b4
{ White doesn't simply have a lot of space on the kingside and is threatening to play b4-b5, trapping the bishop on c6! }
14... b5
{ Black needs to make this rather drastic and overextending decision in order to save the bishop. Now, however, the b5-pawn would be rather weak.   14...b6?  would be a nice positional move, making room on b7 for the bishop. But of course, it isn't possible as it just hangs a pawn:  15.Bxb6+-  . }
15. cxb5 axb5
{ By capturing with the pawn right away, Black points out the a3-pawn could be a bit weak as well. And, by keeping the bishop alive, Black keeps better control of the d5-square. Let's see how that would prove beneficial if White tried just defending the a3-pawn.   15...Bxb5  would have likely been better. However, after  16.Nxb5  axb5  17.Qd3±  ,  the b5-pawn would have been extremely weak for the rest of the game, which isn't a pleasant situation for Black to deal with. }
16. a4
{ With this creative move, White gets rid of the weakness on a3 and obtains a passed pawn.   16.Ra1  e5!  17.Be3  d5!  allows Black to free up in the center and suddenly feel very comfortable, as is no longer short on space. }
16... bxa4 17. b5
{ This is the whole point. The bishop is being kicked out, and the a4-pawn falls. }
17... Bb7 18. Nxa4
{ Of course, White is threatening to win an exchange with Nb6. But even if that move wasn't winning an exchange, it would still be very annoying to deal with because the knight would be taking away the squares on a8 and c8, making it impossible for Black to fight for the open files. }
18... Bd8
{ Black decides that neutralizing the annoying knight is worth giving up the bishop pair. }
19. Nb6 Bxb6 20. Bxb6 Rfc8
{ Of course, White doesn't mind trading the rooks. If White manages to do that, the bishop pair will become even more powerful, and so would the outside passed pawn! }
21. Qd2
{ On top of other problems, the d6-pawn is still very weak, of course. } 21...
e5
{ Black tries to prepare ...d6-d5, getting rid of the weak pawn and of White's central dominance.   21...d5?  22.e5!  results in an awful position for Black, of course, as the knight is being pushed back, and the b7-bishop is dead. }
22. Rfd1 d5 23. exd5 Nxd5
{ Alright, the good news for the opponent is that Black managed to get rid of the space shortage and the weakish d6-pawn. However, White's b-pawn and the bishop pair are still major factors, which are giving a strategically winning position. }
24. Bf2 h6
{ Black doesn't have a lot of useful things to do, so at least can create an escape square. }
25. Bc4
{ Time for the other bishop to get in the game! The pressure on the a2-g8 diagonal is going to be rather annoying, just like the pin on the d-file. }
25... Rxc4
{ Black chooses to give up an exchange in order to get rid of the opponent's annoying bishop pair and passed pawn. But, is still going to be an exchange down and the position is by no means great.   25...Rd8  26.Qe1  also leaves Black in trouble, as we are ready to put more pressure down the d-file. The e5-pawn is also rather weak, and it won't be easy to solve that problem since playing ...f7-f6 greatly weakens the 7th rank, and the a2-g8 diagonal, while defending the pawn with ...Re8 isn't desirable because the rook is needed on the d-file, or to fight White's passed pawn. }
26. Rxc4 Qxb5 27. Rc5
{ Black is still facing several problems. That is mostly because the e5-pawn is weakish and the 7th rank is a problem. }
27... Qb3 28. Qe1
{ Keeping the queens doesn't look like a good decision because Black is suddenly able to get too much counterplay versus our king.   28.Qc2  ,  in these positions, it's always a question of whether trading queens is worth it. On one hand, Black won't have much counterplay against the white king. However, it's not easy to win with the pawns on one flank only. But, White definitely keeps a large advantage. Let's explore a bit more!  28...Qxc2  29.Rxc2  f6  ,  sooner or later Black would need to make that move to protect the e5-pawn.    30.Rc5  ,  the knight doesn't want to move away, as that allows our rooks to invade on the 7th rank. Also, it doesn't even have anywhere to go: for example, going to e7 or b4 loses a piece to a fork − find how!  30...Rd8  31.Ra1  ,  the rook is about to invade on a7.  31...Kh7  ,  Black wants to go ...Ra8 and offer a rook trade without blundering a check on the 8th rank at the end, such as Rc8+.  32.Ra7  Ra8!  Black is able to afford this move due to back-rank issues.  33.Rxa8   33.Rxb7?!  Ra1+  isn't nice for us. We can get a piece back and not lose, but we didn't gain anything either.  34.Be1  Rxe1+±  .  33...Bxa8  .  To make progress in this position, White would need to find a weakness and coordinate the pieces against it. It looks like g7 is the best target. We can try something like installing the rook on the 7th rank, such as a7. Then the bishop can go to c5, threatening to come to f8, forcing the black king to sit on g8. Then, our king can come in. Objectively, I think Black should be able to hold but keeps struggling. }
28... Ra2
{ Black misses out on a chance to go ...Nf4! and get counterplay.   28...Nf4!  would have been a problem. Can you see what is Black's threat? For instance, after  29.Rxe5??  Nh3+!  30.gxh3  Qxf3  suddenly checkmates the white king! }
29. Rdc1
{ 29.Rb1!  White should have traded a pair of rooks, and maybe even more. For instance, after  29...Rb2  30.Rxb2  Qxb2  31.Qc1±  ,  White is perfectly able to trade everything off, reaching an endgame that still isn't easy to win, but preventing all the counterplay.   Or, even better, White has @@StartFEN@@6k1/1b3pp1/7p/2Rnp3/8/1q3P2/1r3BPP/1R2Q1K1 w - - 0 30@@EndFEN@@  30.Rcc1  instead, with the idea of  taking on b2 and following up with Rb1.  If Black sidesteps that with  30...Ba6  , the line continues  31.Qxe5  Rxb1  32.Qe8+  Kh7  33.Qe4+  winning back the rook and the game. }
29... Qb2
{ Again, Black misses a golden opportunity. Now, the game is ending swiftly!   29...Nf4!  Again, Black had such a powerful counterplay resource. Black was threatening not only with an obvious fork ...Nd3+ but also annoying kingside ideas like ...Nh3+, or ...Bxf3, threatening checkmate on g2 afterwards. }
30. Rb1 { Black is losing material due to problems on the b-file. } 30... Qa3
31. Rxb7 Ra1 32. Rb1
{ And Black resigned, as White is a rook up. Overall, it was a really smooth game, where White kept increasing the positional pressure until the opponent 'cashed out' into a bad one-sided position. However, then Rublevsky missed a chance to trade queens and allowed too much counterplay, which his opponent didn't take advantage of. As they say, all is well that ends well! Hopefully, this game shows why it's very pleasant to play these positions with White. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "29) Sicilian 2...e6 − Model Games"]
[Black "Georg Meier − Fabiano Caruana, Porto Carras 2011"]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3
{ This game, actually, didn't start with  1.e4  , but very soon transposed into our lines.  1.e4  c5  2.Nf3  e6  3.c4  Nc6  4.Nc3  Nf6  5.Be2  d5  6.exd5  exd5  7.d4  is the way we arrive here, of course. }
1... c5 2. c4 Nc6 3. Nc3 e5 4. e3 Nf6 5. Be2 d5 6. d4 exd4 7. exd4
{ Finally, we have a direct transposition into the @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  2.Nf3  e6  lines! The position is entirely symmetrical, except we have an extra  move Be2, which means we should have some initiative. Of course, we are ready to castle on the next turn. If the position starts opening up, the extra tempo will make a world of difference. Especially if we can play Re1+ quickly at some point, starting to harass the black king! }
7... Be6
{ With this move, Black keeps the tension in the center. This way, he avoids helping White activate the pieces, which would be the case in the event of ...dxc4 or ...cxd4. Black is also starting to threaten ...dxc4 since we won't be able to react to that capture with d4-d5 anymore.   7...dxc4  8.d5!  is something Black should avoid by all means since the knight is going to waste a lot of time moving around. Preventing this outcome is the goal of the 7th move! }
8. cxd5
{ We cannot have Black go ...dxc4 in a situation when d4-d5 is no longer possible, so we need to capture that pawn. }
8... Nxd5 9. O-O
{ Now, we'd love to capture the d5-knight and play Be3, developing the bishop and putting pressure on the c5-pawn. Of course, we would be happy if the center opened up as much as possible since we are somewhat ahead in development. }
9... Be7 { For the time being, Black is just developing. Fair enough! } 10.
dxc5
{ We are hoping to lure the black bishop on c5, where it would be vulnerable to ideas like Qc2, Rc1, or even Ne4. However, in order to do that, we are agreeing to spoil our pawn structure. }
10... Nxc3
{ 10...Bxc5?  is a bad move due to  11.Qc2!  The threat, of course, is to capture the d5-knight, leaving the c5-bishop hanging. Black can take back with the queen, but that would run into Rd1, when at best, Black would lose a lot of time shuffling the queen around, and at worst, the bishop would be lost.  11...Nxc3  12.Qxc3  and now, the bishop and the g7-pawn are both under attack, so Black is forced to concede the bishop pair.    12...Bd4  13.Nxd4±  .  No matter how Black recaptures back, we will at least have the bishop pair in an open position. Next, it would be beneficial for us to trade off the rooks and the queens, getting a nearly winning minor piece endgame with a powerful bishop pair and no counterplay. The side with the bishop pair almost always wants to swap off the queens and rooks in order to get a simple endgame without counterplay, where the king can easily get active. }
11. bxc3
{ Why did we voluntarily get a weak-looking pawn structure on the queenside? Well, in return, we get:  the semi-open b-file; an outpost on d4; once we install the knight on d4, we could play Bf3, developing powerful pressure on the h1-a8 diagonal; we are hoping to use our lead in development to harass Black with moves like Ng5, looking to win the bishop pair, or make the bishop move away and become vulnerable to ideas like Re1+, harassing the king, which is still stuck in the center; if Black focuses on development, we might be able to just hold on to the extra pawn with Be3. }
11... Qxd1 12. Rxd1 Bxc5 13. Ng5
{ White is immediately looking to make use of the lead in development and the somewhat awkward position of the black pieces. We want the bishop pair or a lot of time @@StartBracket@@which we would get if Black is forced to move the bishop around@@EndBracket@@. }
13... O-O
{ Black is forced to give up the bishop pair and worsen the pawn structure, but in return, Black hopes to open up the f-file and put pressure on the f2-pawn!   13...Bd7??  14.Nxf7!  Kxf7  15.Rxd7++-  wins us two pawns and the game. }
14. Bf4
{ Black cannot really move the bishop on e6 away since doing that would allow for Bc4. If we can play that move, the f7-pawn will find itself under a lot of very annoying pressure. So, there is no need to take on e6 yet. Instead, we develop the bishop, potentially looking to take on e6 and meet ...fxe6 with Bg3, protecting the f2-pawn. }
14... Rfe8
{ Most Black players chose this move, which prevents the potential structural damage on the e-file. If we take on e6, Black is hoping to take back with the rook.   ➢  14...Bf5??  15.Rd5  loses a piece to a fork.   ➢  14...Bc8?!  I understand the desire to keep the bishop pair, but not to that extent! White can do a lot of tempting things here, such as Bc4 or Bf3. Another one would be  15.Ne4!  winning a tempo.  15...Be7  16.Nd6!  The idea is to follow up with Bf3 and Rb1!, making use of the open b-file and the long diagonal to put pressure on the opponent's queenside.  Black seems forced to give up the bishop pair to avoid this annoying outcome.  16...Bxd6  17.Bxd6  Re8  18.Rd2⩲  .  Next, White can follow up with c4-c5, looking to restrict Black's queenside, then maybe Rb1 or Rd1, trying to put pressure on the b-file or double up on the d-file, then Bf3, increasing pressure on the long diagonal as well. This doesn't look like a fun position for Black, does it? }
15. Kf1
{ Again, there is no need to take just yet. Let's improve the king and overprotect the bishop on e2! Objectively, in this position, Black needs to make some ugly move like ...Nd8, but most people, including Caruana, Dominguez, and Jakovenko, went wrong! }
15... Rad8
{ This natural move gets Black in quite a bit of trouble! But, Caruana wasn't the only one to make it. }
16. Nxe6
{ Now, Black is facing a tough choice. Trading on d1 means activating our rook, conceding the d-file, and allowing ideas like Rd7 and Bc4. }
16... Rxe6
{ Caruana in this game and Dominguez in another game against Meier chose to take on e6 with the rook. However, this move gets Black in a very suspicious position! }
17. Rxd8+ Nxd8 18. Rd1 Nc6
{ White is considerably better due to the bishop pair, the open d-file, and the ability to control the central squares b4 and d4. }
19. Rd5
{ Next, White can improve the position with c4-c5, grabbing space on the queenside and restricting the b7-pawn, or g2-g3, h4-h5, grabbing space on the kingside as well. }
19... Ba3 20. g3 { Time to start occupying more space on the kingside! } 20...
h6 21. h4
{ It's not obvious if Black's last move was just meant to create an escape square, or if Black wanted to go ...g7-g5, grabbing space, but weakening the structure. In either case, White doesn't need to care. White wanted to take more space anyway, and stopping any ...g7-g5 ideas is just a nice bonus. }
21... Kf8 22. h5
{ This move restricts Black's kingside entirely, preventing the g-pawn from ever moving. }
22... Ke8 23. Bg4
{ Time for the light-squared bishop to also come into the game! } 23... Re7 24.
Bc8
{ Black needs to either tolerate this extremely annoying bishop or weaken the light squares. }
24... b6
{ Caruana chooses the latter. This move looks rather logical because it offers Black an outpost on c5, which the bishop would love to use. }
25. Ba6
{ The bishop did its job on the h3-c8 diagonal, now it's time to look for the greener pastures. The threat, of course, is to install it on b5 and pin the black knight, which would be a rather annoying thing to deal with. }
25... Bc5
{ 25...Rd7  was the only way to stay in the game, exchanging rooks in order to relief some of the pressure. }
26. Bb5 Re6
{ Black isn't losing anything, but it's pretty difficult to make the next moves! Black could go ...Ke7 or ...Kf8, but both have a downside: ...Kf8 worsens the king's position, while ...Ke7 makes the king a bit exposed to ideas like Rd7+ once the knight moves away. }
27. Bc7
{ Even stronger is  27.Re5!  Kd7  28.Rxe6  fxe6  29.Be5  Bf8  30.Ke2  when the pin on the c6-knight is very unpleasant, to say the least. If Black tries to disentangle with  30...a6  , after  31.Bxc6+  Kxc6  32.c4  , the bishop endgame is winning for White, as Black's bishop is grounded to the defense of the kingside pawns. }
27... Ke7
{ How to make more progress? The white pieces are already very active. Who else could be more useful? }
28. f4
{ Of course, the pawns! The threat is to play f4-f5. The rook would need to go f6, or else Black would lose the knight. But on that square, after g3-g4, it won't have a single move! }
28... g6
{ Black tries to prevent that move, but sometimes, as they say, the cure is worse than the disease. The problem is that the h6-pawn becomes a lot weaker. }
29. g4 Kf8 30. f5
{ The aforementioned idea couldn't be prevented no matter what. } 30... Rf6
{ Now, the black rook does not have a single move! This is a rather spectacular observation to make, actually, isn't it? }
31. Bg3
{ There is no more need to keep the bishop on c7. White wants to go Bh4 at some point, either trapping the rook or provoking ...g6-g5, which would give up all the tension in the center and keep the rook permanently trapped. }
31... gxf5 32. gxf5
{ It's not possible to prevent Bh4, which is about to win at least an exchange. }
32... Kg7 33. Bh4 Ne7
{ 33...Rd6??  34.Rxd6  Bxd6  35.Bxc6  wins White a piece, of course. } 34.
Bxf6+ { First material gains are there. } 34... Kxf6 35. Rd7 a5 36. Bc4
{ Time to target the f7-pawn. Black either will take the one on f5, trading a pair of pawns, or keep the tension in order to not lose the one on f7. In the latter case, White will just bring the king all the way to e4, protecting the f5-pawn, and will think about what to do next. There aren't many pawns left on the board, and it doesn't look as though Black has that many targets. So, although White should be winning due to the extra exchange, some careful handling is still required. }
36... Nxf5 37. Bxf7 { By capturing this way, White protects the h5-pawn. }
37... Ng3+ 38. Kg2 { Time for the king to get active. } 38... Ne4 39. Be8 Ke5
{ Black decides to not capture the pawn, which is fair enough − activating the king, and avoiding those annoying checks on f7 and g7, which I show in a clickable sideline, is a reasonable desire.   39...Nxc3  40.Rf7+!  is the problem. The goal is to cut the king off from the h6-pawn, winning it.  40...Kg5  41.Rg7+  Kf6  42.Rh7!   42.Rg6+  Ke7  43.Bc6  Nxa2  44.Rxh6±  is not as clear since Black is about to run the two connected passed pawns up the board.  42...Kg5  43.a4!  and Rg7+ followed by Rg6 cannot be stopped, it seems. }
40. Rd3 Kf4 41. Bg6
{ The white bishop is now placed perfectly to both protect the h5-pawn and keep a lot of squares on the queenside under control and cut off the opponent's knight. }
41... Nd6 42. Kf1 { The king starts moving over to the queenside. } 42... Nc8
43. Ke2 Ne7
{ Of course, Black cannot create any threats, so White just continues pursuing the initial plan. }
44. Kd2 Kg5 45. Be8 Nf5 46. Rf3 Kg4 47. Rf1 Ng7 48. Bf7 Kg5 49. Re1 Nf5 50. Bg6
Nd6 51. Rf1 Nc4+ 52. Kd3 Nd6 53. Rf8 Kg4 54. Rf6 Kg5 55. Re6 Kh4 56. Kc2 Kg5
57. Kb3
{ Black's position should be lost here. Let me offer a few thoughts on how to win:  We'll place the pawn on a4 to restrict Black's queenside more and take the b5-square under control. We will wait until the knight moves away, so our king can come to c4. Then, when the time is right, we will sacrifice an exchange on c5 and go Kc4, winning both queenside pawns and the game. Black cannot prevent that plan by using the king somehow, both because the king is cut off, and because going too far with it would abandon the h6-pawn. }
57... Nb5 { How to win by force? } 58. Re5+ Kf4 59. Rxc5 { Yes! } 59... bxc5
60. Kc4 Na3+ 61. Kxc5
{ The a5-pawn is falling, while our c-pawn is queening. The end! } 61... Ke3
62. c4 Kd2 63. Kd4
{ Black resigned, as our c-pawn cannot be stopped. A wonderful win for Meier, who had to spend a lot of time converting at the end, but who played the entire game extremely precisely, without ever allowing the slightest bit of counterplay, and making the most out of the bishop pair and the more active pieces. Don't forget, it's not just a technical win. It's a technical win versus Caruana! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "30) Sicilian 2...Nc6 − Model Games"]
[Black "Antonios Pavlidis − Vasilios Kotronias, Thessaloniki 2017 "]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ This game is going to be a showcase of how White creates a superior pawn structure in the Rossolimo and then slowly but surely takes advantage of it. Here is what's funny about it. Who had Black in this game? The Greek GM Kotronias! What is he known for? Yes, he is a famous theoretician, who wrote... a book on Anti-Sicilians published by Quality Chess in 2016. In this book, he recommends this exact line! And he played it just a year after the book was out. So, it would be very inspiring to see how he got outplayed despite knowing the positions rather deeply. }
1... c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5
{ The move  3.Bb5  initiates something known as the Rossolimo Variation, which used to be an interesting sideline. There  is a story that in the 80s, Kasparov told one of the students of the Botvinnik school 'Kid, you cannot just give up your bishop on c6, this is not Ruy Lopez'. But, of course, a few years later, he would play  3.Bb5  himself. We are  looking to capture on c6 and ruin Black's pawn structure. However, we are not forced to, and in some setups, we would prefer to avoid the trade! }
3... d6
{ This is Black's 3rd most common move, right after  3...g6  and  3...e6  . Black  is taking the e5-square under control, preparing to play ...Nf6 at some point without running into e4-e5. By playing ...d7-d6, Black also makes it possible to go ...Bd7 next, unpinning the knight, and preventing any damage to the pawn structure. Then, our opponents would like to develop with ...Nf6, ...g7-g6, ...Bg7, and so on. }
4. Bxc6+
{ In the true spirit of Rossolimo, White immediately doubles Black's pawns, hoping to play against the weak pawn structure. }
4... bxc6
{ Black would love to play ...e7-e5 to get great control of the center, fight for the space, and prevent any d2-d4 or e4-e5-related ideas. If Black manages to do so, it will be comfortable to develop with ...Be6, ...Be7, ...Nf6, and maybe even ...f7-f5 at some point. }
5. e5
{ This is the key move that every White player should remember. We are preventing ...e7-e5, making it difficult for Black to fight for space in the center. Crucially, Black is now facing serious problems, both in terms of finishing development, and in terms of understanding what to do with the pawns in the center. Why is that happening?   Black cannot play ...Nf6 because our pawn on e5 is restrictive.  Black can go ...e7-e6, but that would block in the bishop on c8, and allow us to capture exd6, leaving Black with two isolated doubled c-pawns, which will be very weak for the rest of the game. And, of course, we'll have the outpost on c4.  If Black goes ...d6-d5, that creates fewer problems, but it still leaves the c5-pawn pretty weak because there is no d-pawn left to defend it. Our goal, in that case, will be to play d2-d3 and c2-c4 to fix the c5-pawn on its current position, and then start attacking it, for example with Nc3-a4, b2-b3, Ba3, and so on. So, Black needs to make a difficult choice. }
5... dxe5
{ This is Black's most popular move, and one of the best ones. While it looks really ugly, since Black voluntarily accepts a very bad pawn structure, this decision can be justified with the next move, which happens to be very concrete. }
6. Nxe5 Qd5
{ This was the entire point of Black's last move. Having ruined the pawn structure, Black is winning a tempo by double attacking the knight and the g2-pawn. }
7. Nf3 Qe4+
{ Fortunately for Black, there is another very precise and specific move. We still haven't had the time to castle, and Black takes advantage of that. We need to either give up castling rights or block the check with Qe2, losing the c2-pawn.   Some Black players also tried pinning the knight with  7...Bg4  .  They are claiming that if they have doubled c-pawns, they can give up the bishop pair and create us a pair of doubled isolated pawns on the f-file as well, sort of evening the situation out. However, I do not believe this is a good path for Black, and here is a simple explanation of why.  The c-pawns are far away from the king. And, they are more advanced. The more advanced the weak pawns are, the easier to attack them. Plus, the king cannot defend the c5-pawn after Nc3-a4 and Be3. Conversely, our f3-pawn won't be easy to attack. And even if Black does, we'll just go Ke2, solving that problem very easily.    8.d3  ,  we want to play Nbd2, preventing Black from doubling the pawns, so that needs to be done right away.  8...Bxf3  9.Qxf3  Qxf3  10.gxf3  .  We got to the aforementioned scenario. Black has a very bad position: the isolated doubled c-pawns, especially the one on c5, are weak, but ours are not.  10...e6  11.Be3!  Of course, we are developing in the most logical way, not only placing the pieces on good squares but also immediately starting to target the pawns.    11...Nf6  12.Nd2!  The knight could also go to c3 and then a4 or e4. However, I like this move better: we can still attack the pawn from b3 or e4, but we also keep the option of going to c4 to enjoy the outpost.  12...Be7  13.Rg1!?  I like the idea of including this move. Black wouldn't want to castle and run into some Bh6-related ideas, so will need to weaken the pawn structure with ...g7-g6, making the f6-knight a bit looser, or make the somewhat ugly move ...Rg8. And, of course, the g-file is already semi-open, so even if we don't win anything, our rooks wants to be there anyway.    13...g6  14.Ne4  ,  the c5-pawn is starting to become a problem.  14...Nd7  ,  Black is forced to go back to avoid losing the pawn.  15.f4  − this move is very beneficial to us, because it takes the e5-square under control, preventing any ...Ne5-related ideas, which could help Black get some counterplay by attacking the f3-pawn and preparing the ...c5-c4 break.  15...O-O  16.O-O-O±  .  The c5-pawn is permanently weak. Black could go ...f7-f5, kicking the knight out, to get some relief. However, that only hurts Black since our knight can just walk back to d2-b3, keeping an eye on the c5-pawn, and Black's e-pawn would become another weakness.  Black has no counterplay, the pieces are stuck. Next, we can consider improving the queenside with b2-b3, taking the c4-square under even more control, maybe a2-a4, grabbing space and preventing any ...a7-a5-a4 ideas, maybe Kb2, so that when the rooks get traded, the king can easily come to attack the c5-pawn via c3-c4. Black is very passive here, and we are clearly better. }
8. Kf1
{ It's totally fine to give up the castling rights. Next, we'll play d2-d3, then Nbd2-c4, taking advantage of the outpost. Then, we'll develop the bishop to the long diagonal with b2-b3 and Bb2. After that, we'd love to play Qe2 and offer a queen trade. If we do trade the queens, the uncastled king won't be a problem. It could just sit on e2, or walk to h1-h2. If the queens don't get traded, then we can just walk the king to a safe spot, while also connecting the rooks, with h2-h3, and Kg1-h2. }
8... Nf6
{ It looks like the author forgot his own recommendation. Trust me, this happens way more often than you'd think!   In his book, Kotronias recommends  8...g6  ,  claiming it's an improvement over 8...Nf6. However, I disagree.  9.Nc3  Qf5  10.b3!  It's absolutely crucial to start with this move. If you went d2-d3 first, after ...Bg7, the knight on c3 would be hanging, making b2-b3 impossible.   10.d3  Bg7!  is exactly what Black is hoping for, since now the b2-b3 plan is no longer possible! Don't forget to play b2-b3 early enough!  10...Bg7  11.Bb2  and Black has no other moves than ...Nf6, which just transposes to our main lines.  11...Nf6  12.d3  O-O  13.Qe2±  .  With the positional threat of Qe5, just like in the main lines. White has a clear typical advantage! }
9. d3
{ We are happy to prepare Nbd2-c4, while also kicking out the queen with a tempo. }
9... Qf5 10. Nbd2 g6
{ It makes sense for Black to deploy the bishop on the long diagonal, as opposed to going ...e7-e6 and ...Be7. If Black chose that path, the bishop on e7 would be passive, and the c8-bishop would end up blocked inside. }
11. b3
{ I think it's very useful to place the bishop on the long diagonal. Especially now, so that Black is not on time to go ...Bg7, move the knight, and start harassing us on the a1-h8 diagonal before our bishop gets to b2. }
11... Bg7 12. Bb2 O-O 13. Qe2
{ This move is aimed at controlling the e4 and e5-squares, helping the a1-rook get in the game via e1... and something else! }
13... Ba6 14. Qe5
{ With this move, we are forcing a queen trade because retreating would lose the c5-pawn. Once the queens are gone, our king's position is no longer a concern. We'll install the knight on c4, then go Ke2, or h2-h3, Kg1-h2, then Rfe1, and will start trading down, while also trying to attack Black's weak pawns with moves like Ba3, or Ne5, or Nc4-a5. Black has no counterplay, no active ideas, and weak pawns, so the position is very unpleasant. }
14... Rfd8
{ Black cannot really prevent the queen trade, but doesn't see any need to take first, helping White position the bishop on a great central square, where it would help control several squares, such as d6, b8, and so on. }
15. Re1
{ White just keeps improving the pieces and is, of course, interested in the queen trade. However, the black queen cannot really ever retreat, as that would drop the c5-pawn. So, why hurry? Now, White is threatening to trade the queens and win the e7-pawn. }
15... e6 16. h3
{ The point of this move is to cover up the g4-square, preventing any ...Ng4 ideas in the future. And, at some point, White wants to go Kg1-h2, connecting the rooks. But, White needs to be very careful because the move Kh2?? in this position, two or three moves later, would blunder the queen to ...Ng4+. }
16... Ne8 { Finally, Black forces the queen trade. } 17. Qxf5 exf5
{ Now, Black has another pair of doubled pawns. These ones on the f-file are completely fine, they are not weak by any means.  However, now White gets an open e-file for the rook, and can always consider opening up the files on the kingside with g2-g4.   17...gxf5  would be even worse, as it would create a weakish pawn on h7.  18.Bxg7  Kxg7  .  Here, I am sure any move is fine, but I'd like to show you a particularly interesting idea.  19.g4!  White opens up the h-file for the rook to make a point about the weak h7-pawn and get the king on g2 in no time, connecting the rooks!  19...fxg4  20.hxg4+-  .   Next, we'd love to play g4-g5, taking the f6 and h6-squares away from Black's pieces and restricting the kingside pawns. Then, White can double the rooks on the h-file, attack the h7-pawn, and of course also keep attacking the weak c5-pawn with Re5, Ne4, etc. Black has numerous weaknesses and nothing in return, so the position should be lost. }
18. Ne5
{ I am not sure why White decided to keep the dark-squared bishops on the board. Although Black's one isn't particularly threatening, it would be nice to deprive the opponent of the bishop pair. And, crucially, the other one on a6 would have been so passive! Of course, White is attacking the c6-pawn. That's a bit annoying for the opponent to deal with, but the pawn isn't lost right away.   18.Bxg7  Kxg7  19.Re5!  seems like a more logical path to me. Next, White can get the king out of the way with g2-g3 and Kg2, or Ke1-d1, and then place the other rook on the e-file as well. What's interesting is that the white king can consider going on a lovely little trip: e1-d1-c1-b2-c3, looking to come to c4 when the time is right to win the c5-pawn! }
18... Rac8 19. Ba3
{ If the bishops didn't disappear, at least White should consider attacking the c5-pawn! }
19... Bf8 20. g4
{ This is a very impressive positional decision. Although it might seem weird at a first glance  (why would we undouble the opponent's pawns?!)  , it actually makes perfect sense. White wants to take back with the g-pawn, opening up the h-file for the rook, creating the somewhat backward pawns on h7 and f7. }
20... f6
{ Black kicks the active knight out, making room on f7 for the king.   20...fxg4  21.hxg4±  .  Next, White can consider going g4-g5, Ne4, Ng4, Bb2, and invading on f6 or h6 with a decisive effect. }
21. Nef3 Rd5 22. Nc4
{ The threat is Ne3 followed by gxf5, at least ruining the opponent's pawn structure, and at best, just winning a pawn. This forces Black to finally react. }
22... fxg4 23. hxg4
{ Now, the h-file is open, which means the h7-pawn always requires some protection. }
23... Rd7 24. Nfd2
{ The knight is coming to e4 to put more pressure on the c5-pawn. Plus, once it's there, White could always consider going Bb2, attacking the f6-pawn. }
24... Bxc4 25. bxc4
{ A very interesting decision. Taking with the knight seems more intuitive, of course, as it keeps the pawn structure intact. And that would have been a great move too! However, White chooses to double the pawns. Why?  This way, White opens up the b-file, which is for our use only: White can always choose to block it with Nb3. Plus, even without that, White controls all the invasion squares, such as b4, b3, b2, and b1, making it useless for the black rooks. And, of course, the knight would enjoy itself on b3, since it would be attacking the c5-pawn from there. The point is that the e4-square might become unavailable one day, so White is looking for a useful alternative in advance. }
25... Re7 26. Kg2
{ 26.Rxe7  Bxe7  27.Nb3+-  seems to win the c5-pawn on the spot. White either missed this, or he just figured the pawn is so weak that it's not going anywhere. :@@EndBracket@@ }
26... Rxe1 27. Rxe1
{ Now, White also controls the e-file. Admittedly, there aren't many ways to use it yet. However, it's still useful to have it, and that is because:  if the black bishop goes away or gets traded, the rook can invade on e7; the loose black knight makes the rook stuck protecting it; if the rook somehow walked away, there is always an idea of Re6, attacking the c6-pawn. }
27... Rb8
{ It might seem useful to take several potential invasion squares under control, while also improving the king, but  27...Kf7  doesn't achieve much. Remember I mentioned the h7-pawn might end up weak?  28.Rh1!  Kg8  29.Ne4+-  .  Finally, it's time to win material. White is picking up the c5-pawn, and of course, the opponent still doesn't have any counterplay. }
28. Re6
{ As I had explained earlier, the black rook is not supposed to get any activity. It's being forced back! }
28... Rc8 29. Nb3 { Finally, the c5-pawn is falling. } 29... Kf7 30. Re1 Rb8
31. Bxc5 Bxc5 32. Nxc5 Rb2
{ Black seems to be getting some counterplay, but it's not something White is bothered by, as White is going to win more pawns. }
33. Re6 Rxc2 34. a4
{ A very classy move! There is no need to give up that pawn. On the other hand, the one on c6 is not going anywhere! }
34... Ng7 35. Rxc6 h5
{ Understandably, Black wants to trade more pawns, and hopefully get some counterplay on the kingside. The position is lost no matter what, so I would call this move a mistake − it's a logical attempt. }
36. Rc7+ Kg8 37. gxh5 Nxh5 38. Rxa7
{ White collects even more pawns. Of course, since White has several passed pawns on the queenside, and the black king is cut off, queening one of them is a matter of very easy technique. }
38... g5 39. a5 g4 40. a6 g3
{ Black seems to be getting some counterplay. Right? Not really. } 41. Ne4
{ Everything is under control. } 41... gxf2 42. Nxf2 Ra2 43. Kf3 f5 44. c5
{ The a-pawn might have been slowed down, but the c-pawn is queening. So, time to resign. As you can see, even such an experienced GM, coach, and author as Kotronias didn't have much of an idea of how to handle this position, and things quickly went downhill. It's not a critique in his address − it just shows these positions are by no means easy to play! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "30) Sicilian 2...Nc6 − Model Games"]
[Black "Evgeny Prokopchuk − Georgy Arzumanian, Nefteyugansk 2002"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ This game will be another instructive example of how White got a noticeable structural advantage and the opponent kept struggling the entire game without ever managing to get a bit of counterplay. }
1... c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5
{ The move  3.Bb5  initiates something known as the Rossolimo Variation, which used to be an interesting sideline.  There is a story that in the 80s, Kasparov told one of the students of the Botvinnik school 'Kid, you cannot just give up your bishop on c6, this is not Ruy Lopez'. But, of course, a few years later, he would play  3.Bb5  himself.  We are looking to capture on c6 and ruin Black's pawn structure. However, we are not forced to, and in some setups, we would prefer to avoid the trade! }
3... e6
{ This move became especially popular after Gelfand used it in his World Championship match versus Anand in 2012, having equalized convincingly in several games. Black's idea is to play ...Nge7, preventing White from doubling the pawns by capturing on c6. Then, Black would like to play ...a7-a6, kicking the bishop out, and ...d7-d5, grabbing space in the center. If White does take on c6, Black takes with the b-pawn. Then, Black tries to build a big center with ...d7-d5, or with ...d7-d6 and ...e6-e5. }
4. Bxc6
{ As I explain in the theoretical chapter, I consider this move to be White's most promising option. White is immediately doubling Black's pawns, in the very spirit of the Rossolimo Variation. }
4... bxc6
{ Black takes towards the center, getting a semi-open b-file and better control over the center. Now, it's easier to control the d5-square, which makes the plan of ...d7-d6 and ...e6-e5, building a strong center without weakening any squares, a lot more logical. }
5. d3
{ White's last move is very simple and logical, overprotecting the e4-pawn, while also making room for the dark-squared bishop, and the b1-knight − it can now come to d2. }
5... Ne7
{ With this move, Black is keeping the tension, not deciding yet to open up the center with ...d7-d5. As a result, depending on what we do, Black could go ...d7-d5, or ...d7-d6, preparing ...e6-e5. The knight will need to go to g6 in order to unblock the f8-bishop. And this is our hope. Once it does, it will most likely get hit with h2-h4-h5!  In these positions, we are often interested in playing e4-e5. This is done in order to prevent Black's d-pawn from moving: if Black meets e4-e5 with ...d7-d6 or ...d7-d5, we take en passant, creating the weak doubled isolated c-pawns. So, Black often meets e4-e5 with ...Ne7-g6 and ...f7-f6, undermining that pawn.  However, in those cases, the g6-knight is both powerful, as it attacks our center, and vulnerable, as it runs into h2-h4-h5. Black can stop h2-h4-h5 with ...h7-h5, but combining the moves ...f7-f6 and ...h7-h5 is not a very safe idea because it makes the g6-knight very loose, just like the kingside overall. }
6. Qe2
{ This flexible move achieves several things:  The queen will be able to help defend the e-pawn, be it on e4, or on e5 if we advance it. Black might, especially in order to free up the c8-bishop, try the ...c5-c4 pawn break at some point. The queen helps prevent it. Once we play e4-e5, in many cases, especially when Black's knight is loose on g6, the idea Qe4!, attacking the knight, turns out very promising. }
6... Ng6
{ This move, which prepares ...e6-e5, as well as ...Be7 followed by kingside castling, has been seen in most games, and, of course, in this one too. But, due to White's standard and frequent response, I consider it a bad choice. }
7. h4
{ White is immediately starting to harass the knight, looking to kick it away with h4-h5. Black can prevent us with  7...h5  , or go  7...Qc7  , looking  to control the f4-square and jump there with the knight. }
7... h5
{ Now, the knight is less protected than a move ago, which means if Black ever decides to play ...f7-f6, it would end up completely undefended and vulnerable.  Additionally, the g5-square has become weaker. However, Black wants to go ...e6-e5, taking more space in the center, and White needs to prevent that. }
8. e5
{ With this move, White achieves several things: prevents ...e6-e5; grabs more space; gains access to the e4-square, which could be used by the queen to attack that loose g6-knight, or by the knight. From there, the knight would attack the c5-pawn, and keep an eye on that weak square on d6. }
8... f6 { Black needs to immediately get rid of our powerful e5-pawn. } 9. Qe4
Kf7 10. Na3 { The knight is coming to c4 to help sustain the e5-pawn. } 10...
Qc7 11. Nc4 Ba6
{ Black must defend the knight, keeping the e5-pawn under fire. } 12. Bf4
{ Of course, White should keep protecting the pawn. Next, White would love to castle queenside and potentially invade on d6 with the knight, or maybe even consider such a creative and unexpected attacking idea as Rh3-g3. For that reason, Black is forced to start swapping off the pieces. }
12... Bxc4 13. dxc4 f5
{ Black chooses to lock up the kingside. In my opinion, this is a very suspicious decision, because it gives up all the tension in the center. Furthermore, it weakens the g5 and the d6-squares. Now, the e5-pawn is incredibly strong, while Black has no counterplay and numerous weaknesses: the g5-square, the d6-square, the c5-pawn, and the d7-pawn.   13...Nxf4  is the better theoretical decision.  14.Qxf4  ,  again, we are ready to castle queenside, starting to attack that backward d7-pawn, and maybe consider this Rh3-g3 idea.  14...d5  .  In both games that reached this position, Black chose to make this move, which is aimed at grabbing space and getting rid of the backward d7-pawn.    15.Rh3±  ,  with the rook coming to g3, we are starting to create a lot of annoying attacking ideas on the kingside, such as Ng5, and so on. We can always keep our king safe, for example by simply going Kf1-g1, if necessary. Alternatively, we could castle queenside. Black won't be able to do much on the b-file. But, I would personally prefer to keep the king on f1, as that is even safer.  We could get the other rook in the game with Rd1-d3, and see where to use it. Maybe even on the kingside with Rf3 at some point! I am not sure how Black will handle this position, since the g6-square, the f6-pawn, the h5-pawn, and even the g7-pawn are always under a bit  (or a lot!)  of pressure. But, it doesn't matter, as we have a clear plan and are much better. Let the opponent figure out how to defend! }
14. Qxf5+
{ A very creative solution! I think that White loses some advantage this way, but gets a risk-free pleasant endgame, which was probably an attractive enough reason to decide to go this way. I'd rather play for a bigger advantage with the queens on, though.   14.Qe3  ,  of course, it would have been simple  (and extremely strong!)  to just retreat, keeping the aforementioned positional advantages. }
14... exf5 15. e6+ dxe6
{ This is a decision that I find very hard to explain. Why voluntarily create doubled isolated pawns on the c-file and a hole on e5?!   15...Kxe6!  would have been a much better way to defend. The rather obvious point is that Black doesn't get isolated weak c-pawns. After  16.Bxc7  d6⩲  ,  the queenside pawns are perfectly safe and easy to defend. Sure enough, White is still better. White can move the bishop over to c3, castle queenside, develop some light pressure on the d6-pawn, and down the long a1-h8 diagonal, but choosing this position over the one in the game still seems a no-brainer. }
16. Bxc7 Be7 17. O-O-O
{ Now, White's position should be winning. White is always threatening to invade on the 7th rank, the e5-square is weak, and so is the one on g5. And, of course, all the queenside pawns are incredibly weak too. White just needs to go g2-g3, overprotecting the h4-pawn and freeing up the rook, install the bishop on a dominant e5-square, and bring the king in, say with b2-b3, Kb2-a3-a4-a5-a6! Of course, swapping the rooks in the middle of that process would be good as well. }
17... Rhc8 18. Ba5 { The bishop is headed to c3. } 18... Bf6
{ Black stops that idea, but now, White can invade on the 7th rank. } 19. Rd7+
{ 19.Ng5+!  also seems very annoying to deal with.  19...Bxg5+?  20.hxg5  gives up a powerful bishop, leaving the white one unopposed, and creates a weak h-pawn.  20...h4?!  21.Rd7+  Kg8  22.Bc3  e5  23.Rhd1+-  ,  Black is entirely paralyzed. With R1d6 coming next, or Rb7 followed by doubling on the 7th rank, it seems obvious Black is dead. }
19... Ke8 20. Rd2
{ The rook didn't really have to retreat. But, remember, White's advantage is long-lasting and does not need to use it immediately. The c-pawns are still weak, and so are the e6-pawn and the e5 and g5-squares. And, White's bishop is placed in an excellent position where it prevents the opponent's rooks from ever fighting for the d-file.   20.Rhd1!  would have been stronger and easier. White doesn't need to worry about the h4-pawn, as Black has no time to take it.  20...Nxh4?  21.Nxh4  Bxh4  22.Rxg7  Bxf2  23.Rdd7+-  leads to an absolute disaster. }
20... Rab8 21. b3
{ Of course, stopping the threats to the b2-pawn wasn't too hard. } 21... Rb7
{ Black acknowledges that the d8-square is never going to be available for the rooks and tries fighting for the d-file this way. }
22. g3
{ This move is a lovely one because it protects the h4-pawn and takes the f4-square under control. Now, the h1-rook is free to move wherever it wants. }
22... Rd7 23. Re1 Nf8
{ The knight is forced to move back, which isn't enjoyable for Black at all.   23...e5  could be played, technically speaking. But, it would only create more weaknesses.  24.Bc3!  The e5-pawn is now under a lot of pressure. Remember, the further the pawns advance, the harder it becomes to defend them!  24...e4  25.Bxf6  gxf6  26.Ng1±  ,  Black's pawn structure on the kingside doesn't look nice at all! What White needs to do now is to go Ne2, and if the black knight ever moves, the white one can come to f4 and attack the h5-pawn, which is a weakness forever. }
24. Rde2
{ White avoids a rook trade, getting ready to install the knight on e5. } 24...
Kf7 25. Ne5+ Bxe5 26. Rxe5
{ Finally, Black is reminded that the c5-pawn is a weakness! } 26... Re7 27.
Bc3
{ 27.Rxc5?  wasn't possible yet, as after  27...Nd7  ,  the rook gets trapped! }
27... Nd7
{ Due to this little tactical trick, Black was able to avoid losing a pawn. However, the position is still very bad, since the pawn is going to be weak forever, which would make the knight stuck defending it. }
28. R5e2 Rce8 29. Be5
{ The bishop is on its way to d6, where it would help White permanently attack the c5-pawn and cause discoordination of the black rooks. }
29... Rc8
{ 29...Nxe5  30.Rxe5  doesn't help Black, since the c5-pawn finally falls on the next move. }
30. Kb2
{ Which piece hasn't been working? The king! Where could White use it? Of course, for picking the queenside weaknesses! }
30... Ree8 31. Rd1 Nf6 32. f3
{ Another very classy move − White takes the e4 and g4-squares under control. }
32... Red8 33. Red2 Rxd2 34. Rxd2
{ Now that a pair of rooks has been traded, it is even easier to activate the king and use it for attacking the weak queenside pawns without fearing any counterplay. }
34... Ke8 35. Ka3 Rd8 36. Rd3
{ A funny move. White doesn't mind the rook trade overall, but on top of that, White also wants the pawn structure straightened out!   36.Rxd8+  Kxd8  37.Ka4  also seems like a pretty straightforward win. For instance, after  37...Kc8  38.Ka5  Kb7  39.Bb2  ,  Black's king cannot move without allowing ours to come further  (to a6)  and the black knight is nearly in zugzwang too.  39...Ne8  40.Ba3+-  and finally White starts winning the weak pawns. }
36... Ke7 37. Ka4
{ The king's invasion is unstoppable. The position is finally collapsing. }
37... Nd7 38. Bd6+ Ke8 39. Ka5
{ The queenside pawns will fall within a few next moves. } 39... e5 40. Bc7 Rc8
{ How to win material? } 41. Bxe5
{ Yep! The pin on the e-file is breaking Black's position. } 41... Nxe5 42. Re3
Kd7 43. Rxe5
{ The c5 and f5-pawns are both hanging, so even more material is going to be lost. }
43... g6 44. Ka6
{ 44.Rxc5  Re8!  would be still completely winning for White, but the opponent would get some counterplay, so Black understandably chooses to not yet capture this pawn. }
44... Kd6 45. f4 Rc7 46. Re8
{ The rook is coming to g8 or a8 to collect all the weak pawns. } 46... Rd7 47.
Rg8 Kc7 48. Kxa7 Rd2 49. Rg7+ Kc8 50. Kb6
{ Black understandably resigned, since all the pawns will get lost, and taking the ones on c2 and a2 is not nearly enough to escape. As you can see, Black never got the slightest bit of counterplay in this game either! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "30) Sicilian 2...Nc6 − Model Games"]
[Black "Fabiano Caruana − Vladimir Fedoseev, Douglas 2019 "]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ In this game, we will see how Caruana absolutely dominated a very strong opponent after sacrificing the pawn in one of the major 3...g6 Rossolimo variations. }
1... c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 g6 4. O-O Bg7 5. c3
{ White is hoping to take the entire center with d2-d4 on the next turn. As I explain in the theoretical chapter, this move has always been incredibly popular with club players, but never with the elite GMs. However, in recent years, the trend has changed! }
5... e5
{ Black's move is extremely logical, as it seems to be stopping d2-d4, which is White's main idea. Besides that, Black wants to develop the knight to e7, making it possible to recapture on c6 with the knight in the future, avoiding positions with doubled pawns. And if White takes on c6 right now, then after ...dxc6, the d-file will open up and the d3-square and/or White's d-pawn would become weak. All these things don't sound too great for White, do they? Fortunately, there is a very powerful solution here, which really questions Black's setup. }
6. d4
{ White is sacrificing a pawn in order to open up the position and take advantage of the considerable lead in development. }
6... cxd4
{ 6...exd4  is going to transpose to the main line with 6...cxd4 after  7.cxd4  .  Now if Black takes with the pawn, we transpose. On the other hand, it's not a good idea to try and take with the pieces on d4, as after  7...Nxd4  8.Nxd4  Bxd4?  9.Nc3!  ,  White is quickly developing an overwhelming initiative, for instance  9...Ne7  10.Bg5  O-O  11.Bc4  d6  12.Nd5±  and White is already winning at least an exchange, as  12...f6??  loses to the obvious  13.Nxf6+  Kg7  14.Nd5+-  . }
7. cxd4 exd4 8. Bf4
{ This is the point of White's pawn sacrifice. Now White wants to install the bishop on d6 to block the black queenside pieces. On the other hand, the extra doubled d-pawn does not matter too much, as this extra pawn is not going anywhere, and it is not helping Black control any important squares.  Black, actually, kind of wishes the d7-pawn did not exist! If that was the case, Black could easily develop the queenside pieces. At this point, Black has several possibilities, and a few decisions to make. Should the kingside pieces develop first? Or does Black try to somehow unravel the queenside with ...a7-a6 and ...b7-b5? }
8... Nge7
{ In this game, Black chose to develop the kingside pieces first, which is very logical. }
9. Bd6
{ The bishop is placed brilliantly here, as it is blocking Black's entire queenside! }
9... O-O 10. Nbd2
{ One important point to mention here is that since Black's bishop cannot be developed over the h3-c8 diagonal, the only choice is to play ...a7-a6 and ...b7-b5. That's why, if White had another tempo, would have made a very powerful positional move a2-a4!, stopping the ...b7-b5 ideas altogether. }
10... a6
{ Black needs to make ...b7-b5 and ...Bb7 happen somehow, or how else would the queenside pieces get out? }
11. Qa4
{ This is a funny-looking move. White takes advantage of the pin on the a-file, making the opponent realize that unraveling the queenside would be a bit more complicated than Black was hoping!   11.Bd3!?  While Fabi's move is fine, I think there's nothing wrong with the simple retreat either. For example, after  11...b5  12.a4!  ,  Black just weakened the queenside and created a hook, so we are jumping at that hook immediately!  12...bxa4  13.Qxa4±  White is exercising incredibly strong pressure on the queenside and has very obvious ways of improving the position.   For example, if given a few tempi, White would go b2-b4!, Nd2-b3-c5, Rfc1, etc, when Black would nearly have to resign, as he would be absolutely stuck on the last ranks. That is why Black absolutely has to go  13...a5!  ,  but then follows the obvious  14.b4!  Bb7  15.bxa5±  and White is winning the pawn back with a huge advantage.  White is about to follow with Nc4, making it impossible for Black to even ever think of winning the a5-pawn. Black cannot take it now, either, as after  15...Rxa5?  16.Qb3  Rxa1  17.Rxa1  Ba8  18.Nc4+-  ,  White's pieces are incredibly active, and there is no way to stop threats like Nb6-d5, Bc4 followed by Ng5, etc. The game is about to be over in a few moves! }
11... Ra7 { Now, Black is actually threatening to take the bishop. } 12. Bd3
{ So it needs to retreat. } 12... b5 13. Qc2
{ The problem is that the rook on a7 is very misplaced. Where would it go?! For example, from a8, it could go to c8, fighting for the open file. }
13... Bb7
{ Black had finally developed the bishop, but the pieces are still very passive, and now Caruana takes advantage of the overextended queenside pawns to develop more pressure there. First, he creates a weakness on the a-file. }
14. a4 bxa4
{ 14...b4  is possible, of course, too. However, this move makes the c4-square very weak. For instance, White can continue  15.Qb3  .  The idea is to go e4-e5 next, and possibly Ng5 and Bc4, targeting the f7-pawn!  15...a5  ,  let's say Black overprotects the b4-pawn, while also getting ready to trade the bishops with ...Ba6.  16.e5!  Ba6  17.Bxa6  Rxa6  18.Ne4!  The knight can jump to c5 or f6. Black literally has no moves! Right now, the threat is Nf6, since Black won't be able to take it, as after exf6, the pinned e7-knight is in trouble.  18...Re8?  19.Nfg5+-  and the position is falling apart! }
15. Rxa4 a5
{ At this point, many ideas were possible, but Fabiano decides to gain some space on the kingside first, possibly preparing h4-h5 or Ng5. }
16. h4
{ 16.b4!?  also looks very attractive to me. It doesn't look like a good idea, as the queenside pawns get traded, which seems to decrease White's opportunities to play for a win. However, if we calculate a bit further, that doesn't turn out to be a correct observation.  16...axb4?  17.Rxa7  Nxa7  18.Bxe7  Qxe7  19.Qc7!  Black suddenly loses a piece! }
16... Ba6
{ Black's position was already difficult but had to somehow wait, say with ...Ra8, hoping that White wouldn't be able to find a decisive breakthrough. }
17. Bxa6 Rxa6 18. b4
{ The pin on the a-file just causes Black to lose the a-pawn. As a result, White restores the material balance, while keeping a huge positional advantage. }
18... Na7 19. Qc5
{ Caruana chooses to keep pressing instead of winning the pawn.   19.Bc5±  would have been even stronger. Now the black knight is protected by the rook only, so the rook has no moves, and White threatens Qd3!, attacking the rook and winning at least a piece. Black has no way of stopping this threat without giving up the a-pawn, but then White obtains an incredibly strong passer on the a-file, which would quickly win him the game. }
19... Nac8 20. Bc7
{ If anything, looking at these types of moves is an absolute pleasure. Black is forced to tuck all the pieces into the corner! }
20... Qe8 21. b5
{ It's very important to stay tactically alert and prevent ...Rc6!   21.Rxa5??  Rc6!  would be an awful blunder, as all of a sudden White would lose the bishop! }
21... d6
{ In order to have at least a slight hope to survive, Black needs to kick the queen out and activate his own.  21...Ra8  22.b6!  is, of course, a disaster for Black, who cannot stop the b-pawn. }
22. Qc4 d5
{ It may look as though the position got somewhat murkier, but White keeps everything under control. }
23. Qc5 { The queen really enjoys sitting on this square! } 23... dxe4 24. Nxe4
d3
{ Black is able to avoid moving the rook for now, since White's one on a4 is being x-rayed. }
25. Ra3
{ The rook finally walks away from the pin, setting the passed b-pawn free to do amazing things.  25.bxa6  25...Qxa4  doesn't offer White anything special. }
25... Re6 26. Nfg5
{ This wonderful move protects the e4-knight, while also winning a tempo. And, all of a sudden, it turns out the black rook is trapped in the middle of the board! }
26... Nf5 27. Nxe6
{ Finally White's overwhelming positional advantage resulted in material gains! Soon, Fabiano went on to win. In my opinion, he played a brilliant game. As you can see, his talented and incredibly strong opponent wasn't able to do literally anything! At no point in the game could Black create any threats or counterplay at all.  In my opinion, this game is a huge theoretical success for White, and hopefully, a good enough reason to give the pawn sacrifice a try! 1-0 Caruana-Fedoseev, Douglas 2019. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "31) Sicilian − Typical Structures and Ideas"]
[Black "Maroczy Bind − general plans and ideas"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "4k3/pp2pp1p/3p2p1/8/2P1P3/8/PP3PPP/4K3 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ What you are seeing here is the famous structure called the Maroczy Bind. Is it determined by White's pawns on e4 and c4 versus Black's d6 and e7-pawns. This structure can occur in a number of openings − of course, in our case, it arises in various Sicilian positions, however, it can also arise in the English, King's Indian, or many other places.   White's c4 and e4-pawns create more space in the center. Please note I did not say 'spatial advantage'! We will see the reason for that in the next examples. Here are some of the plans for both sides:  White has more space, so White wants to keep pieces on the board. Black, on the other hand, has less space and wants to trade pieces.   White can try to expand on the queenside with a2-a3 and b2-b4, or on the kingside with f2-f4. Even though these plans could be combined @@StartBracket@@especially if the opponent plays extremely passively!@@EndBracket@@ it's typically better to focus on playing on just one part of the board. As they say, you can be anywhere, but not everywhere.   Black often tries making the pawn breaks ...b7-b5 or ...f7-f5 work. Some people also try going ...e7-e6 and ...d6-d5, hoping to liquidate the center, but that hardly ever works.   Often, Black would try the dark-squared strategy, which involves going ...a7-a5-a4, grabbing space on the queenside, then ...Nd7-c5, and ...Qa5, installing the pieces on active positions on that part of the board and blockading it.   White's light-squared bishop tends to be the most useless piece. Black would often like to trade off all the pieces and leave White with that bad bishop versus the knight. Let's now see a few more examples that show those points more concretely. }
1. -- *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "31) Sicilian − Typical Structures and Ideas"]
[Black "What to avoid as White in the Maroczy Bind"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "5k2/5p1p/1p1p2p1/p1n1p3/P1P1P3/1P3P1P/2B3P1/6K1 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ This is White's nightmare and Black's pipe dream in the Maroczy Bind. To get here, Black played ...a7-a5 early on. White panicked enough about the opponent's expansion that chose to stop it with a2-a4, killing the light-squared bishop. Now, it's aggressively fighting for the title of one of the worst bishops to ever exist on planet Earth.   Black's position has no targets and the knight is perfect. Next, Black can go ...Ke7-e6 and try to play ...f7-f5-f4, grabbing more space on the kingside. Black could also reroute the knight to d4 via e6 and bring the king to c5 and b4, taking advantage of the weak dark squares and trying to win the b3-pawn. All in all, White is looking at an awful endgame. Maybe it's lost, or maybe White could somehow miraculously save it, but in either case, you should avoid this position by all means! }
1. -- *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "31) Sicilian − Typical Structures and Ideas"]
[Black "White has spatial advantage"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r2q1rk1/pb1nppbp/1pnp2p1/3N4/1PP1P3/PN3P2/3Q1BPP/2RR1BK1 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ This example, alongside the next one, will be a perfect way to understand something that a lot of chess players really struggle with. Before we go on, can you please slow down, and answer one question? The question is: if you hear the phrase 'White has more space' and a phrase 'White has spatial advantage', do you think it's the same thing or not? Why or why not?  Okay, hopefully, you gave it some thought. Here is a very simple explanation. Having spatial advantage, which means the opponent has a disadvantage, is something that occurs when the pieces lack good squares to go to. They are restricted and uncomfortable. Think of a life comparison: what if we place 15 people in a 2-bedroom apartment? That is a lack of space! On the other hand, having a lot of space, although rarely a disadvantage, might not be an advantage either. It will absolutely not be an advantage if your opponent has ENOUGH space.  It's perfectly possible to have quite little of something, but just enough. Life comparison − many people are happy with a modest residence and don't need more room. So, in chess, this observation is a really important one, because it enables you to understand if one of the sides actually has a problem.  In this position, it seems to be as though White has a real spatial advantage because Black's pieces are very restricted.  The knight cannot go to c5. If one of the knights goes to e5, it will likely get kicked out, immediately, or a bit later, with f3-f4. The black queen cannot use such squares as c7, b6, or a5. This also greatly inconveniences the f8-rook, which cannot come out to some good square like c8. All in all, Black really wishes to have more space!  But, what if you have too little space? Think of that life example above. 15 people in a small house? Have some of them leave! Therefore, Black should actively seek and accept the piece trades. Every piece trade is good for Black. White, on the other hand, should keep the pieces on the board. Please note there is no room for 'style' or 'preferences' of any sort. If you have more space, you MUST keep the pieces on; if you have less, you MUST trade. Doing anything else just means making a mistake! }
1. -- *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "31) Sicilian − Typical Structures and Ideas"]
[Black "White has more space − but no spatial advantage!"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r4rk1/p3ppbp/1p1p2p1/8/1PP1P3/P4P2/5BPP/2RR2K1 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ We have the exact same position as in the previous example, where I spent a lot of effort explaining how White should be on cloud nine because the opponent's pieces are so restricted. However, here the situation is completely different. Hopefully, comparing the two will really help us understand this notion of space versus spatial advantage.  Although White still has more space − the advanced pawns are definitely making that claim hard to argue with − Black is no longer at a disadvantage. Black only has a few pieces left, and all of them feel perfectly comfortable. The g7-bishop is not restricted by any means, and neither are the rooks. So, the position is simply equal! White's extra space is useless. }
1. -- *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "31) Sicilian − Typical Structures and Ideas"]
[Black "Why ...b7-b6 and ...Bxd5? are huge mistakes for Black"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "2rq1rk1/3nppbp/ppbp2p1/8/1PP1P3/2N1BP2/P2QB1PP/2RR2K1 b - - 0 16"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ This position occurred in a tournament game I played in 2018 versus a talented junior from Belarus. This example's objective is to show you two concepts:  Why it's bad to play the move ...b7-b6 in these positions. Why it's bad to trade the knight off with ...Bxd5. Also, I guess it's fair to say that while each of these two decisions is bad on its own, combining the two makes things much worse. }
16... Qc7
{ Black lacks room for the pieces and decides to get the queen out, at least somewhere. }
17. Nd5
{ Now, the e7-pawn is hanging. So, Black needs to either retreat back to d8 or trade the annoying knight off. }
17... Bxd5
{ Well, trades are good for the side with less space, right?  Sure, overall that's true. However, the reason why this decision screams HUGE MISTAKE at me is because now the c6-square is extremely weak. Black first weakened it with ...b7-b6, and now made things much worse by playing ...Bxd5. }
18. cxd5
{ All White needs to do is to trade off all the major pieces on the c-file, then invade on c6 with the queen, or simply pick up the queenside pawns by using the powerful bishops. }
18... Qb7 19. Rxc8 Rxc8 20. Rc1
{ The rooks are inevitably coming off, then the white queen is going to c6, and Black is in deep trouble. The game went on for a bit longer, but it was won fairly easily. }
20... b5
{ Black is trying to shut down the queenside and restrict our light-squared bishop.   20...Rxc1+  21.Qxc1  makes things worse for Black by giving up the c-file. }
21. Rc2
{ With this move, I am taking over the c-file. Next, I am ready to go Qc1 and make Black give it up. }
21... Kf8
{ At the exact moment when I relaxed and figured the position was completely winning, my opponent had found the only chance to try to defend. He wants to go ...Ke8-d8, bringing the king closer to the queenside. The position is still lost, but it's a good try. }
22. Qc1 Rxc2 23. Qxc2 Ke8 24. a4
{ Black wishes he could go ...Kd8 and ...Qc7, trading queens and achieving a rather locked-up position, which he should be able to hold. However, Black is not in time. }
24... bxa4 25. Qxa4 { The a6-pawn is in trouble. } 25... Bc3
{ Black seems to be counterattacking the one on c3, but this move fails for tactical reasons. }
26. Qc6
{ The bishop on c3 is hanging, and Black cannot take on b4 with the queen as Qc8 is a checkmate in one. }
26... Qxc6 27. dxc6 Ne5 28. c7 Kd7 29. Bb6 Bxb4 30. Bxa6 Bc5+ 31. Kf1
{ And the opponent had to resign, as my c-pawn was inevitably going to queen. As you can see, the endgame with the bishop pair and an outpost on c6 turned out absolutely horrible for Black! 1-0 Krykun-Strybuk, Vilnius Open 2018. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "31) Sicilian − Typical Structures and Ideas"]
[Black "How Black makes the ...b7-b5 break work"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1r3k1/pp2ppbp/3pbnp1/q7/2P1P3/1PN1BP2/P2QB1PP/2R1K2R b K - 0 13"]
[SetUp "1"]

13... a6
{ This is one of the most popular main lines in the Maroczy Bind. This position does not occur in our repertoire, but it absolutely can help us learn a few key ideas. First of all, Black is trying to prepare the ...b7-b5 break, which would get rid of the c4-pawn and help free up the position. }
14. O-O
{ This move is completely ignorant, as it allows Black to make the desired pawn break work.   14.Na4!  forcing the endgame and trying to take advantage of the weak b6-square is the correct choice here.  14...Qxd2+  15.Kxd2  . }
14... b5 { How does this pawn break work? } 15. cxb5
{ 15.Nd5  is another super important idea to understand. White is attacking the a5-queen and the e7-pawn, so Black must be in trouble, right? Not at all!  15...Qxd2!  16.Bxd2   16.Nxe7+??  Kf8  results in White losing the knight and the game. This is VERY important! If Black had played ...Rac8 instead of ...Rfc8, then the f8-square would have been occupied and this move ...Kf8 would not have been possible, which means Black would have simply lost a pawn!  16...Nxd5  17.cxd5  Bd4+  18.Kh1  Bd7=  .  Please note that although the c6-square has been weakened here, the position is completely equal because Black still kept the light-squared bishop alive! This means White cannot invade on c6 with the rook. However, if the light-squared bishops were gone and White could play Rc6 and Rfc1  (two moves in a row)  , then White would dominate the only open file and the position would be completely winning! }
15... axb5
{ The pawn seems to be hanging, as White can choose to take it with the bishop or the knight. But upon further inspection, this original observation turns out incorrect. }
16. Bxb5
{ 16.Nxb5  Qxd2  17.Bxd2  Rxa2  is not good for White either, because the a2-pawn gets lost, and the one on b3 is now weak. However, please note this whole idea only worked because the f8-rook went to c8! Instead, if Black had played ...Rac8, then the other rook would be on f8 now, and Black would have no rook to take on a2 with! }
16... Rxc3 17. Qxc3 Qxb5
{ This results in a winning position for Black since the two active minor pieces are much more valuable here than a rook and a pawn. }
