[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "31) Sicilian − Typical Structures and Ideas"]
[Black "Hedgehog − main plans and ideas"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1bq1rk1/pp2bppp/2nppn2/8/2PNP3/2N1B3/PP2BPPP/R2Q1RK1 b - - 0 9"]
[SetUp "1"]

9... a6
{ This pawn structure, where Black goes ...d7-d6, ...e7-e6, and ...a7-a6, is often referred to as the Hedgehog. White has a lot more space. Black, in these positions, typically strives to play ...b7-b6, ...Bb7, ...Nbd7, ...Qc7, ...Rac8, and ...Rfd8, harmoniously setting all the pieces on the last two files, and controlling the 5th rank with the pawns − that's why the opening is called this way, referring to the pawns on the 6th rank as the hedgehog's needles. However, there is a problem: Black's knight is already on c6. This is bad because of several reasons:  The b7-bishop would be blocked. The knight on d7 could protect the b6-pawn and the f6-knight, and on c6, it cannot. If Black places the queen on c7, with the knight on c6, that would often run into the typical Rc1-Nd5! temporary knight sacrifice. Another issue Black has is that ...b7-b6 cannot be played now or anytime soon, as that'd hang the knight.  
We can try to advance on the kingside with f2-f4, Qd2, Kh1, Rg1, g2-g4. The more positional plan would be playing f2-f3, reinforcing the e4-pawn, and then a2-a3, b2-b4, and Nb3, obtaining a dominant position on the queenside. That's the plan I like best.  Here is one summarizing thought, which I thought was extremely refreshing, when I heard it for the first time. Unlike in the proper Maroczy Bind position @@StartBracket@@with the pawn on e7 instead of e6@@EndBracket@@, where Black has no weaknesses, here Black does! Specifically, the d6-pawn is a weakness.  For that reason, although Black has less space, Black should be trying to keep the pieces on the board instead of trading them! This is because each piece trade means there is less and less possible counterplay to be created, and therefore, the d6-pawn would be easier and easier for White to attack, as White would not need to worry about the opponent breaking out of a bind! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "31) Sicilian − Typical Structures and Ideas"]
[Black "Hedgehog − the Nd5! tactical shot"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r2q1rk1/1b2bppp/ppnppn2/8/2PNP3/2N1BP2/PP2B1PP/2RQ1RK1 w - - 0 12"]
[SetUp "1"]

12. Qd2
{ Here is the showcase of the idea I had briefly mentioned before. The black knight should be on d7, not on c6! On c6, it creates a tactical liability. What do I mean? Let's see! }
12... Qc7
{ This move is not something the opponent can afford, although it does look fairly natural. If Black is left alone for a few more moves, Black would like to play ...Rac8 and ...Qb8, hiding the queen in a safe spot. However, that's not meant to happen because White can take advantage of the c-file's problems immediately. }
13. Nd5
{ The unexpected  (at least, for the players that are not experienced in these positions!)  temporary sacrifice blows things up and proves Black is in deep trouble. }
13... exd5
{ 13...Qd8  14.Nxc6  Bxc6  15.Bxb6  wins White a pawn, yielding a completely winning position. }
14. cxd5
{ Of course, White is going to get the piece back on the next turn, also obtaining a decisive positional advantage. }
14... Rfe8 15. Nxc6
{ White is absolutely dominating the board. Very importantly, the fact that Black's e-pawn had disappeared made the f5-square much weaker, making ideas like Nd4-f5 and Bd4, starting to uncomfortably stare at the g7-square, a lot more attractive. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "31) Sicilian − Typical Structures and Ideas"]
[Black "How to kill the c8-bishop − and how to prevent that!"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1bqkbnr/p4ppp/2p1p3/2pp4/4PP2/3P1N2/PPP3PP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 0 6"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ This position occurs in the @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.f4  Sicilian, which I wrote a course about back in the day. But, of course, the theoretical part or move order is irrelevant. What matters to us is that this is a very common structure in the Rossolimo, which is a very important part of this repertoire.   Black's c-pawns are rather weak, mostly because Black had already committed to playing ...d7-d5.  The thing is that when you have doubled pawns, you want to make sure your FRONTAL doubled pawn  (the one on c5, in this case)  is easy to defend. This is because it's much easier to attack the more advanced pawn on c5 than the one which is hiding behind it.  Another very important consideration  (likely, a more important one!)  is the future of the c8-bishop. As you can see, this piece seems rather passive. It's restricted by Black's own e6 and c6-pawns.  In this example, we are going to learn about the positional dream of killing this bishop, which White cherishes, and about the way Black can sometimes prevent that. }
6... Nf6
{ Now, White is going to be on time to make the dream come true.   6...c4!  Black is absolutely desperate to get the light-squared bishop out. In order to do that, Black is even happy to sacrifice a pawn!  7.dxc4  Ba6!  Black is a pawn down, but the bishop managed to spring to life. Black has great compensation! And, even if White was better, Black would have to do this anyway since the alternatives mean slow and inevitable death. }
7. e5 { First, White kicks out the knight, grabbing more space in the center. }
7... Nd7 8. c4
{ This move is one of the most important ideas for everyone who plays the Rossolimo to understand and remember. Now, the c5-pawn is stuck. It won't ever run away, and White can attack it endlessly with Nc3-a4, b2-b3, Ba3, and so on. Even more importantly, the c8-bishop is dead! There is no way to activate it on the c8-h3 diagonal, a8-h1, or even a6-f1! It's the worst piece ever! White is strategically winning. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "31) Sicilian − Typical Structures and Ideas"]
[Black "Why ...Ne7 is a mistake in the Rossolimo"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1bqk1nr/pp3pbp/2p3p1/2p1p3/4P3/3P1N1P/PPP2PP1/RNBQ1RK1 b kq - 0 7"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ This is another standard Rossolimo position. It's not a part of our theoretical repertoire, but we see this type of position all the time, so it's important to understand the following idea really well. What should Black do with the knight on g8? Where should it go − specifically right now, and what is the best place for it overall? A lot of your opponents will make this mistake, so be careful!  White wants to prepare the f2-f4 break, which will allow getting rid of the e5-pawn, which takes a lot of space in the center, and open the f-file for the rook. That's why the black knight would be best placed on e6. The way to go is to protect the e5-pawn first with ...Qe7, and then play ...Nf6-d7-f8-e6! This journey might seem a bit lengthy, but it's the best square for the knight. Conversely, it's not a terrible idea either to play ...f7-f6 and ...Nh6-f7.  However, a lot of your opponents will develop it to e7. They will do that because going to f6 seems to be blundering the e5-pawn, while e7 is safe and quick. }
7... Ne7
{ However, as I have learned from Boris Gelfand's great book Positional Decision Making, this is an awful square for the black knight in these positions because it is very restricted! It cannot go to c6, d5, or f5. You could argue it is supporting the ...f7-f5 break, but this argument doesn't hold up because Black could control the f5-square more than enough times anyway. So, now the knight is terribly misplaced. If your opponent ever makes this move in these structures, be happy knowing they have no idea what they are doing!   7...Qe7!  followed by ...Nf6-d7-f8-e6 is the way to go! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "31) Sicilian − Typical Structures and Ideas"]
[Black "Why including h2-h4 and ...h7-h5 is good in the ...bxc6 Rossolimo"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1bqkb1r/p2p1ppp/2p1p1n1/2p5/4P3/3P1N2/PPP1QPPP/RNB1K2R w KQkq - 0 7"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ We arrive at this theoretical position from the @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp1ppppp/2n5/1Bp5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...e6  Rossolimo Variation. Here is one important idea to understand.  If we could do whatever we want without ever considering the opponent's counterplay, we would love to play the move e4-e5. This move would make the c5-pawn much weaker, as ...d7-d6 is harder to play. You can go ...d7-d6, but after exd6, Black gets two isolated doubled c-pawns.  Also, overall, Black wants to go ...d7-d6 and ...e6-e5, grabbing space in the center and organizing the pawns nicely. However, playing the move e4-e5 is often tricky business, as it allows Black to get counterplay with ...f7-f6, undermining this pawn. That's why it's better to first go h2-h4. }
7. h4
{ We want to either kick the knight away, making it harder for Black to control the e5-square, or to provoke ...h7-h5. }
7... h5 8. e5
{ The reason why including h2-h4 and ...h7-h5 is so beneficial for White is fairly simple: now, the g6-knight is much less safe. If Black ever goes ...f7-f6, that knight ends up undefended and we can easily disturb it, for example with Qe4. Also, the h5-pawn is a bit of a weakness. If Black ever castles, we can just move the f3-knight away, asking the opponent a logical question: how would Black defend that pawn? Make sure to keep this idea in mind! }
*

